<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ACQUIRE TIGHT END IN TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys feel they got lucky, in a
couple of ways.
</P>
<P>
   In a trade with Atlanta on Sunday, the Cowboys acquired O.J.
Santiago, a 6-foot-7, 264-pound tight end with 44 NFL career
starts, including Super Bowl XXXIII barely 19 months ago. The
Falcons, in return, will receive Dallas' fourth-round pick in 2001
and seventh-round pick in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   No fewer than seven tight ends had come and gone during a
three-week flurry of auditions with the Cowboys in an unsuccessful
attempt to replace No. 3 tight end Mike Lucky, whoseseason ended
with a knee injury July 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys finally have what they wanted all along: another
Mike Lucky ... and more.
</P>
<P>
   The Santiago trade _ actually initiated by the Falcons _ came
amid the NFL's final cutdown to 53 players, which the Cowboys
reached Sunday by waiving 18 players.
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising cut was fourth-year veteran Tony Hutson, who
went to training camp as one of three players vying with Solomon
Page and Jorge Diaz for the starting job at right guard and ended
up not making the team. Coming off major knee surgery Oct. 12,
Hutson was held out of all but the last two preseason games for
what was described by team officials as ``precautionary'' measures.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones indicated that the Cowboys might not be done
with roster moves. With rookie Kareem Larrimore set to start at
left cornerback, the team is known to be interested in upgrading
that position, if possible.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys put in a waiver claim, they must wait until 3
p.m. Monday to learn if they are awarded the player. Based on 1999
record, similar to draft order, the Cowboys cannot be awarded a
player unless 18 teams pass on him.
</P>
<P>
   If a player clears waivers after 24 hours, he is fair game to be
signed by anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Giants cornerback Phillipi Sparks, who has been
unwilling to sign for the $440,000 veterans minimum, remains
available on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   Jones called it ``quite a swing'' over the past 10 days at the
Cowboys' tight-end position, where David LaFleur has bounced back
from a groin strain to give the Cowboys optimism for him this
season ... and now the addition of Santiago, who can back up both
pass-catching tight end Jackie Harris and blocking tight end
LaFleur.
</P>
<P>
   ``O.J. Santiago definitely can block,'' coach Dave Campo said.
``He's handled our defensive ends at times in the past. Greg Ellis
is a pretty good indicator as to whether a guy can block or not.
O.J. did some good things against Greg a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a nice little package there with LaFleur, Harris and
Santiago because we have a combination of everybody with those
three guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Santiago, 26, looks like a basketball player in shoulder pads.
Surprisingly, he's a better blocker than expected and maybe less of
a receiver because of past signs of inconsistent hands. He can
split the safeties on the deep ball, but can he catch it?
</P>
<P>
   That, along with injuries, was the problem in Atlanta where
Santiago caught only 15 passes for an 11.6-yard average and no
touchdowns last season after catching 27 passes for 15.9-yard
average and five touchdowns during the Falcons' Super Bowl run two
seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta signed Santiago for the lowest of three possible tenders
_ $472,000 _ for a restricted free agent. He will be an
unrestricted free agent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have had Sanitago's successor _ Reggie Kelly _ since
drafting him in the second round in 1999, using a pick from
Baltimore that cost the Falcons their first-round choice in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago underwent surgery this off-season to repair a torn
right pectoral muscle, which was the result of a weight-room
injury. He was to be examined by Cowboys team doctors Sunday night,
then given a playbook because he's being counted on to be ready for
Sunday's season opener against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very comfortable that he will be able to walk out there
and help us immediately,'' said Campo, adding that Santiago will
receive a crash course in a select number of packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to emphasize,'' Jones said, ``that a guy like O.J.
Santiago does more than just (serve as a backup); we can now expand
with him. The potential is there to open up the offense even beyond
what we thought we could do with LaFleur, Harris and Lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have now acquired four players in 2000 who have
started in the past two Super Bowls: Joe Bowden, Barron Wortham and
Harris (Tennessee), and Santiago (Atlanta).
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're probably not through (setting) this 53-man roster,''
said Jones, excusing himself to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   There was a waiver wire to read, possibly claims to be made ...
and most likely a cornerback to be found out there somewhere. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
