<HEADLINE>
PALMER: `I STUNK'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ USC sophomore quarterback Carson Palmer
didn't need anyone to tell him how he played in the Trojans' 29-5
victory over Penn State on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He offered his own analysis moments after he reached the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stunk up the whole game. I stunk,'' Palmer said. ``I felt
very rusty. I came out and played awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer was playing his first game in nearly a year. He broke his
collarbone against Oregon and was forced to sit out the rest of the
season. That was apparent early against Penn State, when his second
pass of the game was intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very rusty. I came out and played awful,'' Palmer said.
``After the first interception, I thought I would bounce back and
get into a rhythm, but I didn't throw one good ball the whole
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Palmer was 10 of 20 for 87 yards and one interception.
He was almost intercepted a couple of other times in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Although Palmer was clearly not at his best, USC was
concentrating on its running game. This after its special teams and
defense spotted the Trojans an early 14-3 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But that did little to calm Palmer's frustration over his
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been over a year. I wish I knew what it was,'' he said.
``I can't play like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony was that Palmer felt he had one of his worst college
games in what he considered the biggest college victory of his
brief career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely (the biggest),'' Palmer said. ``It's a completely
different team. We have a new attitude and it gives us a lot of
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense and the offense had my back. I'm disappointed, but
all that's important is we got the win.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
