<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUMPY RIDE ON VEHICLE SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Aug. 28:
</P>
<P>
   It has been a dismal month for those concerned about motor
vehicle safety, but it brightened just a bit last week when two of
the world's major automobile manufacturers took corrective action
to restore consumer confidence. First the Ford Motor Co. decided to
cut production of its popular Ford Explorer sport utility vehicles
so as to free their tires to help replace those being recalled for
safety reasons on existing vehicles. Some 6.5 million
Bridgestone/Firestone tires are being recalled after being linked
to hundreds of accidents and 46 deaths in the United States alone.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Mitsubishi Motors, Japan's No. 4 automaker, admitted that
it has systematically concealed customer complaints about tens of
thousands of defective automobiles since 1977. Middle-level
officials, anxious to avoid embarrassing recalls, covered up
complaints about fuel tanks, brakes and clutches, simply by
altering or hiding documents. Top management says it never knew
about it. The company expanded a recall of the faulty vehicles,
most of which were sold in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's decision to halt production will be costly. Ford will
suspend Explorer production at its big St. Louis plant, as well as
production of Ford Ranger pickup trucks at two other plants. These
are very profitable vehicles, and Ford estimates its pretax loss at
up to $140 million. The shutdowns will last until Sept. 11, giving
the supply of replacement tires time to begin catching up with
demand.
</P>
<P>
   The decision made good business and legal sense. Ford would have
been vulnerable to lawsuits had it continued to mount tires on new
Explorers at a time when drivers of old Explorers needed
replacements for the tires Firestone recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone has said that, despite the many claims
sent to it by warranty-holders, the company did not detect a
pattern of failure that required special attention. But when Ford
ran the same claims through its own computers, it discovered not
only an unusually high number of complaints but also the source of
most of the problem tires _ a factory in Decatur, Ill., operated
from 1994 to 1996 by replacement workers. Ford says that from now
on it will inspect warranty data on all the tires it installs on
its cars, instead of depending on the tire manufacturer to supply
that information.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford's own performance remained under critical scrutiny. By
week's end, Ford was being rebuked by Transportation Secretary
Rodney Slater for failing to notify regulators promptly last year
when it recalled the Firestone tires on some of its vehicles
overseas. Congress, which will hold hearings next month, may need
to mandate that manufacturers report all lawsuits, recalls and
serious customer complaints to the regulators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
