McCULLOUGH MAKES NAME FOR HIMSELF IN KICKOFF CLASSIC 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In one afternoon USC went from Tailback
Who back to Tailback U.
</P>
<P>
   While USC coach Paul Hackett has insisted that three or maybe
even four tailbacks would play this season, sort of a
tailback-by-committee setup, one emerged Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Sultan McCullough locked up the position by gaining
128 yards in 29 carries in the Trojans' 29-5 victory over Penn
State in the Kickoff Classic. For his efforts, he was named the
game's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready. I've been ready for months,'' McCullough said.
``This is what I wanted. Whatever I need, I'm going to get. I think
I can do it. I'll show them.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough has always been confident, but this is the first time
he has demonstrated consistency in a game, partly because it's the
first time he hasn't been buried on the depth chart. McCullough not
only had a career high in rushing, he did it without the usual
long, breakaway runs that have been characteristic for a back who
is also one of college track's top sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it had to be a power game,'' McCullough said. ``I run
over people too if I have to. That's why we wear pads. I knew I
could do a lot against another team.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just McCullough who believes he can be a power or
breakaway back anymore. After Sunday's game, his teammates were
more than happy to throw compliments his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hitting the hole hard and fast,'' offensive tackle Faasea
Mailo said. ``He's learned to use his speed as a sprinter to be a
devastating back.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, McCullough could give USC another legitimate
weapon for an offense that already includes quarterback Carson
Palmer and wide receiver Kareem Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions seemed determined to shut down Kelly,
double-teaming him about 75 percent of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they keep doubling me, Sultan will keep having the game
that he does,'' Kelly said. ``I didn't have a great game but Sultan
came through. I don't care about stats.''
</P>
<P>
   With Malaefou MacKenzie hurting his hamstring and Petros
Papadakis playing primarily in short-yardage situations, Hackett
seemed ready to crown McCullough as ``the back'' following the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along that we have three backs,'' Hackett said.
``We felt that one of them would separate themselves and Sultan
certainly took a big step today. And it was the way he ran. He had
tough runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got great speed and is one of the fastest in the country,
but he's learning to be a tailback.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough is just thankful he's finally getting the carries he
dreamed about when he signed with USC out of Muir High in Pasadena,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what I would I get today, I'm just glad I got
the ball,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
