<SLUG> BC-RAC-ORDINARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HORSE RACING: AN ORDINARY HORSE? NEVER!
</HEADLINE>
 By JOE DRAPE  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ This time of year, with the glory of
the Triple Crown faded and the stars of the spring series on the
sidelines, there is a tendency to size up the 3-year-olds and hang
the tag of ordinary around their necks. That's too bad.
</P>
<P>
   As the afternoon of the 131st Travers proved here Saturday,
there's no such thing as an ordinary horse _ especially for the
people most intimately involved with them. Ask Nick Zito, the
colorful and competitive New York trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Hoarse and heartbroken after his Albert the Great was run down
by Unshaded 20 yards from the wire, keeping him a neck away from
his first Travers victory, Zito composed himself and distilled the
magic of horse racing. He explained how he had won the Kentucky
Derby with Albert the Great's father, Go For Gin, and how Carl
Nafzger had won the Derby with Unbridled, who is Unshaded's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, racing is such a beautiful sport,'' Zito said with
an appreciative smile. ``Here he is 10 years later, winning the
Travers with his son. So it's a remarkable business we're in and
there's a lot of romance.''
</P>
<P>
   Or ask Jim and Terry Scatuorchio, the owners of More Than Ready,
the victor in the Grade I King's Bishop here, which preceded the
Travers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, the small, black colt was being
mentioned in the same breath as Affirmed and Easy Goer after
topping a perfect five-for-five start with a nearly 10-length
victory here at the Sanford Stakes. When a fever disrupted his
training, two tough losses followed in the fall and the colt was
sent to Kentucky for a complete physical. While veterinarians found
nothing wrong, More Than Ready was laid up and forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   But the Scatuorchios and the trainer Todd Pletcher believed he
was far from an ordinary horse and aimed him for the Triple Crown.
In January, he was a dead heat winner in his return race, the
Hutcheson Stakes in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Then he ran valiantly the next five races against the best
3-year-olds in the nation. But each time, he never quite got to the
finish line first. In the Louisiana Derby, Mighty passed him in the
final jumps; in the Bluegrass Stakes, High Yield nosed him after a
breathtaking stretch duel; in the Kentucky Derby, he took the lead
in the stretch but couldn't hold on and finished fourth, six
lengths behind Fusaichi Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one days ago, More Than Ready was poised to win his first
Grade I race, a coveted designation worth millions when it comes
time to sell a colt for stallion duties. He was among the top
choices in the Haskell Invitational at New Jersey's Monmouth Park,
the track where Jim and Terry Scatuorchio had their first date.
</P>
<P>
   This time, disaster hit the day before the race when the colt's
regular rider, John Velazquez, broke his collarbone in a spill at
Saratoga. With jockey Richard Migliore on him for the first time,
More Than Ready got in traffic trouble and finished fourth, just 2{
lengths from the winner.
</P>
<P>
   So More Than Ready was taken off the Travers trail and entered
in the seven-furlong King's Bishop. It was a Grade I race at a
sprint distance he excelled at. Before the Haskell, Scatuorchio had
already signed a stallion deal for More Than Ready's post-racing
career.
</P>
<P>
   A victory would secure a great deal of bonus money. But for the
Scatuorchios, for Eddie Rosen, the pedigree consultant who helped
pick out More Than Ready, for the dozens of family members and
friends who had followed the colt across the country the past year,
winning the King's Bishop was also about seeing a hard-working
horse finally get the respect he deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an experience of a lifetime,'' Scatuorchio said.
``He's brought a lot of joy into a lot of people's life and you
never know if you'll get an opportunity like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   So when More Than Ready went from last to first to capture the
race, the winner's circle was crowded, exuberant and tearful with
the colt's ardent followers. Even Pletcher, who is as reserved and
measured as Zito is emotional, couldn't help but be touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes this game isn't very sophisticated when you
think here's a horse who has proven himself in Grade I company over
and over again, but hasn't won,'' said Pletcher, who is leading the
trainer standing here. ``If ever there was a horse deserving of a
Grade I race, it's him.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the year, votes will be counted among writers and
racing secretaries, and one 3-year-old will be named champion. It
probably will be the Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus. But don't tell
Nafzger, Zito, Pletcher or the Scatuorchios that their horses are
ordinary. They won't believe you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
