<HEADLINE>
NEWBURY HAS A KICK FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ USC kicker David Newbury was trying to
contain himself Sunday, even though he made all three field goals
in the Trojans' 29-5 victory over Penn State in the Kickoff
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I don't know if you all remember how I started off
last year,'' Newbury said. ``I'm always a fast starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbury made two field goals against Hawaii, including a
48-yarder, before descending into a season-long slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I want to sit back and wait for something to happen
before getting too excited,'' Newbury said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, though, Newbury has noticed one change from a year ago.
After he missed an extra point against Penn State, he came back and
nailed all three of his field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I dwelled too much on a bad kick,'' he said.
``That's the difference. I have a lot more confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbury couldn't play it cool on the field, however, jumping up
and down each time he converted a kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't help it,'' Newbury said. ``I've been waiting for
this game since Nov. 26. I wanted to show my teammates I could do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   FAMILIAR FACE: Former USC strong safety Rashard Cook, who is
playing for the Philadelphia Eagles, was on the Trojans' sideline
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only live an hour away, I had to come,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Cook was a sophomore the last time the Trojans played Penn
State, in the 1996 Kickoff Classic. Penn State won that game 24-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a different Penn State team,'' Cook said. ``And I
think we have a better team than we did back then.''
</P>
<P>
   INJURY REPORT: Tailback Malaefou MacKenzie suffered a hamstring
strain, but it is not considered serious. He was limited to three
carries and gained eight yards.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Trojans emerged from the game healthy.
</P>
<P>
   JUMP START: An otherwise flawless day had one slight hitch when
the truck carrying USC's equipment would not start after the game.
After a delay it was repaired and made it to Newark International
Airport in time to catch the team's chartered flight back to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   DEJA VU: Troy Polamalu's 43-yard interception for a touchdown
was the first Penn State has allowed for a score since USC
defensive back Quincy Harrison returned an interception 68 yards in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   BACK IN FORM: USC tailback Petros Papadakis scored a touchdown _
his first since Dec. 31, 1998 in the Sun Bowl _ on a 2-yard run.
Papadakis sat out last season after breaking his foot in training
camp. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
