<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-LIBERTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY LOOKS FOR SOLACE AS COOPER LEAVES THE STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  By TOM SPOUSTA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The celebration echoed through the Compaq Center and
filtered hauntingly into the loser's locker room. As though being
beaten for the third time by the Houston Comets in the WNBA finals
wasn't enough, the Liberty couldn't shut out the sounds of its
failure.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets' 79-73 overtime victory Saturday was as traumatic as
it was dramatic for the Liberty. Despite the odds against winning
twice on Houston's court, the Liberty players said they truly
believed they could bring down this dynasty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We played them better than anybody else played them this
season,'' guard Becky Hammon said. ``We came in here with a lot of
heart and determination, and fell one basket short again. It's not
a very good feeling.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Center Tari Phillips said, ``I thought if we were able to pull
this one out, we would have won the series.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Liberty became a footnote to a fourth title.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets' four straight WNBA championships are the most
consecutive titles in professional sports since the Islanders won
four National Hockey League Stanley Cups from 1980 to 1983.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The last such run in baseball was put together by the Yankees,
who won five titles from 1949 to 1953. In the NBA, the Boston
Celtics won eight straight titles, from 1959 to 1966. There has
never been a NFL team that won four straight championships,
although the Green Bay Packers won three straight, in the seasons
from 1965 to 1967. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, the Liberty can make a valid argument that it
could have swept the two-of-three-game series from the Comets, who
are scheduled for a victory parade Tuesday in downtown Houston
thanks to Cynthia Cooper's two clutch baskets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1 at Madison Square Garden, Cooper's 3-point play with
26 seconds left clinched the Comets' 59-52 victory. If her shot
with 21.5 seconds to play from beyond the NBA 3-point line had
missed and Game 2 had not gone into overtime, the Liberty most
likely would have won and tied the series. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much like its regular season, which started 4-9, the Liberty
found success to be elusive and victories hard-earned in the
playoffs. The Liberty blew several chances to beat the Comets, but
it also staged impressive comebacks, particularly in Game 2, when
it rallied from 10 points down in the first half and from 9 points
down in the second half. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had a lot of talented players, we just had to find
that chemistry,'' the Liberty's Vickie Johnson said. ``In the
second half of the season, we really put it together. Everybody
doubted us and never thought we would win the East. But we always
fought back.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now the Liberty and the rest of the WNBA can look forward to a
league without Cooper, the four-time finals most valuable player
whose retirement casts a shadow on the Comets' quest for a fifth
straight championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at all the games she has won for them, they would
have to do a lot of adjusting and a lot of regrouping,'' Liberty
coach Rich Adubato said. ``Nobody has the ability to break the
defense down and finish the way she does. Swoopes breaks it down
and scores. Cooper breaks it down and creates opportunities for
everybody.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty's Sue Wicks said, ``When she leaves, it will be a
different game.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even Sheryl Swoopes, the league's most valuable player and
defensive player of the year, admits to wondering about the
post-Cooper era. But she predicts several stars-in-waiting will
emerge to keep the Comets among the WNBA's elite next season.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be foolish to say we're not going to miss Cynthia,''
Swoopes said. ``She's been such a great player. We're going to miss
her, and the basketball world is going to miss her. At the same
time, I don't want to take anything away from this team and say
we're going to be nothing without her. Obviously, we're going to be
different offensively, but other players will have their chance to
shine. We'll be ready for that challenge.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes, who scored 31 points on Saturday, added: ``I'm never
going to think this is my team, this is the way we're going to do
it, etc. This is our team. That's why we've been so successful.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Especially against the Liberty. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
