<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vincent La Selva, the artistic director of the New
York Grand Opera Company, often answers the telephone himself in
the company's Carnegie Hall office. For several years, he's been
noting some of the questions posed about the company's summer
season of free opera in Central Park. Here are a few he especially
enjoyed from this year's batch:
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you get a reserved seat in the unreserved section?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I be sure to get a seat if they are all taken?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I buy a subscription for the free opera?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When do you decide if it's going to rain or not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wrote the music for Verdi's `Don Carlos'?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will I be able to get out of the park when the opera is
over?''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   They're not like us out there!
</P>
<P>
   I was visiting my son in Sacramento, Calif., and joined him on a
trip to his bank. Most of the transactions with the customers
seemed to take some time. Finally it was my son's turn, and the
teller greeted him: ``Hi, Rick, how are the dogs? Last week, Suzie
told me one of them was sick. And by the way, how was that meat
loaf recipe I gave Suzie?''
</P>
<P>
   Rick stood there and chatted with her, oblivious to the line
that continued to form behind him.
</P>
<P>
   I stood there and thought: ``GIVE HIM THE MONEY. JUST GIVE HIM
THE MONEY!''
</P>
<P>
   _ ARLENE COHEN
</P>
<P>
   Ted Hardin telephoned a neighborhood restaurant and ordered a
simple salad of just lettuce and tomatoes to accompany his
spaghetti. He paid for it and discovered when he sat down to eat
that the salad was brimming with olives, mushrooms, onions,
peppers, nuts and carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Incensed, he dialed the restaurant and told them in no uncertain
terms to immediately send the plain lettuce and tomato salad he had
ordered. When it was delivered, he shoved the first salad in the
delivery man's hands and made a snide remark about incompetence. He
noted that the second delivery man was better dressed than the
first one and that the salad came in a different container.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later he realized that he had mistakenly dialed
another neighborhood restaurant, and as confused as they
undoubtedly must have been, they nevertheless sent the salad he
said he had ordered.
</P>
<P>
   REGRETS
</P>
<P>
   We beat ourselves for these _
</P>
<P>
   All the ``should'ves.''
</P>
<P>
   I should've said this.
</P>
<P>
   I should've done that.
</P>
<P>
   And the judgments _
</P>
<P>
   She should've said this.
</P>
<P>
   He should've done that.
</P>
<P>
   I will dwell no longer
</P>
<P>
   in the land of Should'ves.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't the energy.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't the time.
</P>
<P>
   Am I happy with this poem?
</P>
<P>
   I should've written something different.
</P>
<P>
   _ JUDITH NAOMI FISH
</P>
<P>
   Scene: David B. Kriser Dental Center at the New York University
College of Dentistry on East 24th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Elderly couple, brother and sister.
</P>
<P>
   Observer: Rowann Gilman.
</P>
<P>
   Action: Man filling out clipboard questionnaire for his sister.
</P>
<P>
   He: ``Heart disease. I'm putting `no.' Right?''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``Right.''
</P>
<P>
   He: ``Dry mouth? `No,' right?''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``Right.''
</P>
<P>
   He: ``Halitosis. You know, bad breath. No bad breath, right?''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``Well, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   He: ``No, you don't have bad breath.''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``I don't? So where did all my friends go?''
</P>
<P>
   Who remembers the ``Who's on first'' dialogue between Abbott and
Costello, asks Camille Lavington. She was in a new D'Agostino
market that had sent out coupons for complimentary items, when she
heard this exchange between a distinguished-looking older gentleman
and an uninterested checker.
</P>
<P>
   Gentleman: ``I've come for my orange juice.''
</P>
<P>
   Checker: ``What orange juice? We've got lots of orange juice.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentleman: ``The orange juice that D'Agostino invited me to
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Checker: ``What orange juice are you talking about? We stock
orange juice from several places at different prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentleman: ``I don't care where it comes from or what it costs.
D'Agostino invited me to have free freshly squeezed orange juice.''
</P>
<P>
   Checker: ``What do you mean FREE?''
</P>
<P>
   Gentleman: ``Yes, free freshly squeezed orange juice.''
</P>
<P>
   Checker, giving up: ``Somebody get this man some freshly
squeezed orange juice.''
</P>
<P>
   Checker: ``Here's your orange juice.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentleman: ``Where's the straw?''
</P>
<P>
   Checker: ``Somebody bring him a straw. Anything else?''
</P>
<P>
   Gentleman: ``Yes, where's the chair to sit on to enjoy my orange
juice?''
</P>
<P>
   Lavington was leaving the store at this point, obviously amused.
The gentleman winked at her. He knew she remembered Abbott and
Costello.
</P>
<P>
   Masha Wise Woolwich was seated in the front of a Fifth Avenue
bus facing a little girl of perhaps 8 or 9, who was flanked by her
two grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had such a wonderful time at lunch with your lady friends,''
the little girl said. ``And the museum and tea at the Plaza. Thank
you, thank you for such a wonderful day of adultery.''
</P>
<P>
   Cell phone conversations are irritating at least every second
bus passenger, according to an unscientific survey of reactions in
letters and telephone calls. Florrie Chiat was on a 57th Street
crosstown bus when a cell phone rang and the owner, in a loud
voice, proceeded to share her ``business'' conversation with her
unhappy fellow riders. Finally a man, also in a loud voice,
suggested that everyone join him in singing, which they did.
</P>
<P>
   The phone user was oblivious, continuing to share her business
with the rest of the bus. Another passenger then piped up. He
suggested that the Metropolitan Transportation Authority should
have two rates, one for true passengers and another for passengers
using the bus as an office.
</P>
<P>
   That one worked.
</P>
<P>
   The call ended.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   After arriving on the Long Island Rail Road at Pennsylvania
Station, we hailed a taxi and en route mentioned that after the
theater we would be returning to Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The driver told us that he lived in an adjacent town on the
island and that he, too, would be going out there about midnight.
We rejected as too expensive his suggestion that we hire his taxi
for the return trip. He then replied that he hated to drive alone
and offered to meet us outside the theater and drive us home as his
guests.
</P>
<P>
   We agreed to meet him after the curtain fell, but never expected
that he would be there. To our surprise, he was. We were four
passengers, and I sat in front with him and discovered that he was
from Kiev in Ukraine, the same city from which my father had
emigrated almost 100 years ago. We spent a delightful hour singing
Russian and Jewish folk songs, and when we arrived at our
destination tipped him well: what our railroad fare would have
cost.
</P>
<P>
   I thought then that here was an ordinary New Yorker, a man who
defied the cold, abrasive, impersonal image. A man with the same
dreams and ambitions that my father had a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ ARNOLD WEBER
</P>
</TEXT>
