<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3779 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-EXPOS-HNS &LR;      08-28 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-EXPOS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Streaking Elarton, Eusebio lead Astros past Expos
</P>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Scott Elarton never expected to win 15 games this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Eusebio hasn't been keeping tabs on his improbable hitting
streak.
</P>
<P>
   But both players remained on course Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio extended his hitting streak to a club-record-tying 23
consecutive games, and Elarton pitched his second career complete
game as the Astros cruised to a 7-3 victory over the Montreal Expos
at Olympic Stadium. The victory was the Astros' 10th in their last
13 games.
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio doubled twice and hit his seventh homer to match Art
Howe (1981) and Luis Gonzalez (1997) for the longest hitting streak
in club history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the Astros' record streak was 23 games,'' said
Eusebio. ``It hasn't really been on my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Elarton (15-4), who fought off control problems that
resulted in a career-high seven walks, became one of five 15-game
winners in the National League this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even thinking about 20 wins,'' said Elarton, who also
pitched a complete game against Montreal on Aug. 6. ``I would have
been happy with 10 wins this season. I didn't know what to expect
coming back from surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou went 3-for-4 with his 25th homer as the Astros
scored all the runs they would need during a four-run fourth
inning. Alou, who went 6-for-10 during the weekend series, raised
his batting average to .366.
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio, who began his hitting streak July 9, tied the record
with a double down the right-field line off Expos starter Trey
Moore in the fourth inning. He added an RBI double in the fifth and
a solo homer in the eighth that put the Astros ahead 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on fire,'' Elarton said. ``He doesn't waste any time.
When he gets up to the plate, he swings the bat and gets it out of
the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored one run in the first inning, four in the
fourth and one in the fifth to take a 6-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno and Julio Lugo singled to lead off the game, and
both advanced on a balk by Moore. Jeff Bagwell delivered a
run-scoring grounder for his 31st RBI in August, tying the team
record for RBIs in a month.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros failed to produce any more runs in the inning when
Richard Hidalgo's pop to short right field was caught by second
baseman Jose Vidro. Lugo was gunned down attempting to score from
third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised to see Lugo going on the play. I thought he
was faking,'' Expos catcher Brian Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell walked to lead off the fourth, and two batters later,
Alou launched a two-run homer down the left-field line. Eusebio
followed with his record-tying hit, and Cedeno added a two-run
single with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   With a six-run cushion, Elarton had room for error. He walked
six batters through six innings, including two to load the bases in
the fifth. The 6-7 righthander escaped trouble by coaxing Vidro
into an inning-ending fly out to left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to take me out after the sixth inning, but I said
I wanted to go out there,'' Elarton said. ``I felt I could get
things straightened out. I wasn't being aggressive the way I
should.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider broke up Elarton's shutout bid with a two-run double
in the sixth inning. The Expos never put together another serious
threat as Elarton grew stronger late in the game. Following a walk
to Andy Tracy in the sixth, Elarton needed only 23 pitches to
retire the next eight batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a quality of a great pitcher to go through some rough
waters and find a way to smoother sailing on the other side,''
Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``A lot of guys, once they get
into the late innings and have a rough inning or two, that's it.
They can't regroup. Elarton did.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton allowed six hits while striking out six. His two
complete games trail only Chris Holt, who has three, for the team
lead.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
