<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3780 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ROSTER-TE     08-28 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ROSTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANSECO SOUNDING UPBEAT ABOUT FUTURE WITH RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys announced their ``final'' cuts Sunday to meet
the deadline to reduce the number to 53, but this is far from the
team's roster for first game of the season. The Cowboys are looking
for help at cornerback and safety. Look for them to make room by
reducing their numbers at linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   QUARTERBACKS (2)
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman and Randall Cunningham. You didn't think Clint
Stoerner would make the roster, did you? Aikman and Cunningham are
probably the most accomplished 1-2 combo in the league. If both go
down, the season is over anyway. Besides, the Cowboys would have
signed a veteran off the street start before turning the team over
to Stoerner. Look for receiver Joey Galloway to play quarterback in
an emergency situation. RUNNING BACK (3)
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith, Chris Warren and Michael Wiley.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Warren have combined for more yards than any 1-2 combo
in the league. Both are still capable of carrying the load. Wiley
got the nod as the No. 3 back largely because the Cowboys paid him
a $100,000 bonus as a fifth-round pick. He might make his biggest
impact as a returner. FULLBACK (1)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Thomas
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys don't mind having just one fullback because they
will use a lot of two tight end sets. Besides the H-back position
has largely the same responsibility as the fullback, meaning tight
ends Jackie Harris and O.J. Santiago, will be able to supplant
Thomas at times. WIDE RECEIVER (6)
</P>
<P>
   Joey Galloway, Raghib Ismail, James McKnight, Jason Tucker, Wane
McGarity and Chris Brazzell.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Cowboys had only one receiver they could count
on. Now they have six. Speedsters Galloway and Ismail might make up
the most dangerous starting combo in team history. McKnight, Tucker
and McGarity have potential. TIGHT END (3)
</P>
<P>
   David LaFleur, Jackie Harris and O.J. Santiago
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, the Cowboys have gone crazy looking for
a serviceable tight end to replace the injured Mike Lucky. Sunday's
trade for the veteran Santiago gave them someone better than Lucky.
He has the size to block like LaFleur and the speed to make plays
down the field like Harris. This threesome is solid. Harris,
however, remains the biggest addition. He could be Aikman's most
trusted receiver. GUARD (5)
</P>
<P>
   Larry Allen, Solomon Page, Jorge Diaz, Kelvin Garmon and Al
Jackson
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like about this group? The starters could be as
good as any in the league. Diaz is a backup with starters'
experience. Garmon, the camp surprise, is the favorite to start
next year when Page moves to tackle. The Cowboys liked Jackson so
much that they gave him $20,000 to sign as rookie free-agent before
camp. TACKLE (2)
</P>
<P>
   Erik Williams and Flozell Adams
</P>
<P>
   Williams is a four-time Pro Bowl pick. And Adams could achieve
standout status this year. The Cowboys would move either Allen or
Page to guard if Williams or Adams go down. Allen started at tackle
two years ago, and Page is a natural tackle. CENTER (3)
</P>
<P>
   Mark Stepnoski, Ben Fricke and Dale Hellestrae
</P>
<P>
   Stepnoski is no longer considered the best center in the game.
But he is as steady as they come. Fricke can also backup at guard
and is the backup deep snapper. The one-dimensional Hellestrae, the
league's best deep snapper, is the real ``Survivor'' winner.
DEFENSIVE END (4)
</P>
<P>
   Greg Ellis, Ebenezer Ekuban, Peppi Zellner and Dimitrius
Underwood
</P>
<P>
   ``Who''' was never in question. The only surprise here is that
``he'' of the troubled past (Underwood) is being counted on in the
rotation. Ellis must pick up where he left off when he was injured
last year. Ekuban is being counted on to have a breakout year as
well. If not, the Cowboys are in trouble. DEFENSIVE TACKLE (5)
</P>
<P>
   Chad Hennings, Alonzo Spellman, Leon Lett, Brandon Noble and
Michael Myers
</P>
<P>
   This group is solid. However, that will not be good enough. The
Cowboys need Hennings, Spellman and Lett to be dominant if they are
going to become legitimate contenders. Spellman has looked the part
in the practice. But he must do it consistently in games. Ditto for
the still cat-quick Lett. LINEBACKER (7)
</P>
<P>
   Dexter Coakley, Dat Nguyen, Darren Hambrick, Joe Bowden, Barron
Wortham, Orantes Grant and Chris Bordano.
</P>
<P>
   Write this group down in pencil because Bordano is not likely to
stay. The Cowboys don't need seven linebackers. They really don't
need three middle linebackers. Bowden and Wortham give the Cowboys
their best set of backups in of more than a decade. Contrary to the
hype, Coakley is the star, not Nguyen. Not yet. SAFETY (4)
</P>
<P>
   Darren Woodson, George Teague, Izell Reese and Chris Akins.
Woodson and Teague make up the most capable starting position on
defense. Reese has made a successful return from neck surgery.
Akins, a special-teams maven, is the updated version of Kenny Gant
and Bill Bates. CORNERBACK (6)
</P>
<P>
   Ryan McNeil, Kareem Larrimore, Charlie Williams, Duane
Hawthorne, Dwayne Goodrich and Mario Edwards
</P>
<P>
   McNeil is the only sure thing here. The Cowboys are looking for
a cornerback to supplant the rookie Larrimore, whether it's the
result of the trade, a waiver-wire pick up or Williams returning to
help. The latter is not likely to happen in time for the season
opener. SPECIALISTS (2)
</P>
<P>
   Tim Seder (kicker) and Micah Knorr (punter)
</P>
<P>
   Kickers coach Steve Hoffman has seemingly done it again. Seder
and Knorr appear to be the second coming of Richie Cunningham and
Toby Gowin _ or is that Chris Boniol and John Jett? Besides if
Seder doesn't make it, veteran kickers Eddie Murray and Doug
Pelfrey are a phone call away. PRACTICE SQUAD CANDIDATES
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Clint Stoerner, defensive end Bryant Shaw, defensive
end Aaron Fields, receiver Damon Hodge and running back Troy
Hambrick.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys plan to field a full practice squad. These are the
top candidates. Fields and Hambrick are the mostly likely targets
to get picked up by other teams. A cornerback, maybe Sunday cut
Stephen Fisher, could sneak on to the practice squad if a spot
becomes available. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
