<HEADER>
A3782 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-L     08-28 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARL HOPES FOR CHANCE TO STICK IN ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Scott Karl, whom the Angels acquired from the
Colorado Rockies last week, will become the 13th pitcher to start a
game for the Angels this season when he takes the mound Tuesday
against the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Karl averaged 11 wins and 33 starts for four consecutive seasons
with the Brewers from 1996-99 but struggled this season after being
traded to the Rockies, going 2-3 with a 7.68 ERA. He began the
season in the starting rotation but was demoted to the bullpen
before being traded to the Angels for a player to be named.
</P>
<P>
   ``My consistency and the numbers I put up in Milwaukee were a
result of me being out there every fifth day,'' Karl said. ``Over
the course of a season, everybody will have a slump and a hot
streak. It's what you do in the middle that dictates the kind of
season you have.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Milwaukee, I started every five days. In Colorado, I never
got that opportunity. I don't know if they were impatient or just
wanted to go in a different direction. But the routine I was used
to was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   He might not get that routine with the Angels, either, as their
rotation has been a revolving door, shuttling pitchers between the
mound and the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's (manager Mike) Scioscia's call,'' Karl said. ``I've
done my best when they run me out there every five days. I hope for
that opportunity here.''
</P>
<P>
   PERCIVAL READY: Troy Percival returned from his stay on the
disabled list Saturday night and gave up a two-run homer to Travis
Fryman. But Scioscia said Percival is ``ready to get back on the
horse'' and resume his role as the club's closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Troy Percival is our closer,'' Scioscia said. ``He
didn't lose the position because of an injury. The way our bullpen
lines up, we're much better with Percy in the closer's spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Shigetoshi Hasegawa assumed the role in Percival's absence,
saving four of five opportunities. But he will return to his role
as a set-up man.
</P>
<P>
   Percival has been working on a new pitch, a cut fastball, and he
threw it a few times Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's looking for is to have some kind of breaking pitch
he can get into the zone when his curveball is not working for
him,'' Scioscia said. ``It can be an effective pitch for him. It's
another weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE REHAB: Pitcher Tim Belcher made a rehab start for Single-A
Lake Elsinore on Sunday night. Scioscia said Belcher will need one
or two more rehab starts before he'll be considered for the
starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers Jarrod Washburn (stress fracture in shoulder) and Seth
Etherton (tendinitis in shoulder) continue to rehab their injuries.
Washburn is closer to returning than Etherton but is still a week
to two weeks away from beginning a rehab assignment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3783 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-HELTON-HNS &LR;      08-28 2143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HELTON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hits keep coming as Helton chases .400
</P>
<P>
   By RICHARD JUSTICE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Todd Helton's preparation has begun more than five
hours before game time. After catching a cab to Three Rivers
Stadium, he has changed into baseball cleats, gym shorts and a
T-shirt to join a half-dozen other Colorado Rockies for an early
round of batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Moments before stepping into the batting cage, he is casually
chatting with two reporters, but the small talk abruptly stops and
the smile disappears when his workday begins. Over the next few
hours, he will take this early round of batting practice, follow it
with the standard pre-game hitting, and finally have a last-minute
one-on-one session beneath the stands with Rockies hitting
instructor Clint Hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   There also will be a videotape study session and perhaps a
glance at the notebook he keeps on dozens of opposing pitchers.
Once prone to ``beating myself up after every bad at-bat,'' Helton
seems as unflappable as any player in the big leagues, thanks in
part to these long workdays that force him to think only of the
next task or the next at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   His work is paying off. Long touted as one of the game's next
great hitters, Helton, 27, has fulfilled all his potential and then
some in his third full major-league season. He's among the National
League leaders in a host of offensive categories, from RBIs and
hits to doubles and runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a Nintendo machine,'' said Rockies shortstop Neifi
Perez, himself a budding star. ``It's just ping, ping, ping.
Single, double, homer. He's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's that batting average, which is at .394 after
Helton went 2-for-4 in a 9-2 win over the Pittsburgh Pirates on
Sunday afternoon. No major leaguer has carried such a lofty average
this late in a season since George Brett made a run at .400 two
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   That magical barrier hasn't been cracked since Ted Williams hit
.406 in 1941. Helton has consistently downplayed talk of .400,
saying it's not even a goal and he doesn't feel comfortable talking
about it. But on this day, he's relaxed and chatty and confident
enough to discuss the possibility of reaching a milestone that
ranks alongside Joe DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak as one of
baseball's most sacred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's realistic,'' he said. ``There's 30-something
games left, and I have to hit a little over .400 in that stretch. I
think I've done that before. It's realistic when you look at it
that way. I don't like talking about it. When you talk about it,
it's harder to separate yourself from it. You don't want it to
become the focus of the game and why I'm going out there and
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   With a sweet lefthanded swing that reminds some of former
Yankees great Don Mattingly, Helton has spewed hits all over the
place this summer, reaching base in 114 of the 126 games he has
started. He's hitting .413 since the All-Star break, and 10 days
ago he briefly got his average above .400.
</P>
<P>
   Want more? He's hitting .545 with the bases loaded, .432 with
runners on base and .387 after the seventh inning. Best of all,
according to those who know him best, he has done it the
old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works his tail off,'' Rockies manager Buddy Bell said.
``This is a very hard game, and he's making it look easy.''
</P>
<P>
   In these first swings in the batting cage, Helton seems focused
on nothing except the pitcher. He stands upright in the box and
wiggles the barrel of the bat directly over his head as he awaits
the pitch. Then, as it's delivered, he raises his front foot for an
instant, cocks the bat behind his left ear, and explodes toward the
ball in one silky motion of power and grace.
</P>
<P>
   Helton has complained he doesn't have one of those classically
beautiful lefty swings, that his stroke never will be as
picturesque as that of Brett or Rafael Palmeiro. Typically, he's
being too critical of himself, because on this day, his swing is as
graceful and easy to watch as any in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too many people have walked the walk he's walking right
now,'' Hurdle said. ``I told him to enjoy it. It's all that hard
work that has gotten him to this point. He shouldn't let it lock
him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton was hitting .370 on Aug. 4, but he began to make a
serious run at .400 by going 19-for-29 on a road trip to Montreal
and New York and getting his average as high as .400 during one
game. He has not finished a game above .400, but he has stayed in
the .390s despite having back-to-back hitless games last week for
the first time since June 22-23.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Brett went over .400 on Aug. 17 and was above it as
late as Sept. 4. He slipped to .399 on Sept. 5 and finished at 390.
(Tony Gwynn finished at .394 in 1994, but a strike ended the season
Aug. 12.)
</P>
<P>
   Hurdle, who played with Brett in Kansas City and remains a close
friend, has told Helton some of what Brett went through that summer
of '80. He has spoken of the attention and how Brett handled the
stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``George would never let an opposing pitcher see if he was
struggling,'' Hurdle said. ``He'd go back in the tunnel, and we
could hear him letting off steam. We'd go back and check to see if
he'd hurt himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd is different. He's under control all the time. I've
wondered how he lets the steam off. They're similar in that both of
them have the ability to drive the ball from line to line. Whatever
is asked of them to do to help the team win is first and foremost.
They have the ability to have the focus and concentration to just
hit the ball hard somewhere and to not get caught up in any of the
periphery, any of the external environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Both are extremely disciplined at the plate. Brett, who played
in just 117 games in 1980, struck out only 22 times in 449 at-bats
that season. Helton has struck out 43 times in 465 at-bats this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never saw George swing at as many balls outside the strike
zone as Todd will,'' Hurdle said. ``Todd will expand the strike
zone at times. At times, he's more of a slasher. George had
tremendous control of the strike zone. If George took a pitch,
there was a pretty good chance it wasn't a strike. Todd has great
recognition of the strike zone, but he knows what he can get out
after. George didn't venture much outside the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton arrived in the big leagues to stay when first baseman
Andres Galarraga left the Rockies to sign with the Atlanta Braves
after the 1997 season. Wearing jersey No. 17 because of his
admiration for Cubs veteran Mark Grace, Helton immediately reminded
some of Grace with a lefthanded stroke that sprayed line drives
from foul line to foul line.
</P>
<P>
   He hit .315 in his first full season and finished second to Cubs
righthander Kerry Wood in the 1998 National League Rookie of the
Year voting. He got even better in his second season, hitting 320.
Last winter, he went back to Knoxville, Tenn., with three goals: to
start the season hotter, to hit lefties better and to hit better on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   Consider it done. A career .240 hitter in April, he burst from
the gates this season, batting. 367 during the opening month. He's
also hitting .336 against lefties, a 69-point improvement on his
career average against them. And on the road, he's hitting .362,
which is 100 points better than his career average away from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a goal-oriented person,'' he said. ``That's
what's fun about the whole thing. You set goals, and you strive for
them. If you don't have goals, what makes you better?''
</P>
<P>
   His workaholic personality comes through in virtually every
interview as he looks the reporter in the eye, politely answers
each question and even attempts a joke or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind the attention,'' he said, ``but I'm not seeking
it out. Someone told me it was the result of doing well. That's a
good way to look at it. But I'm still not going to be doing any
stand-up routines.''
</P>
<P>
   He married a former University of Tennessee classmate two
winters ago, taking her to a baseball fantasy camp before their
honeymoon began.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to have someone to share your life with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's also close to Hurdle, who was Colorado's minor-league
hitting instructor when Helton began his career. These days, the
two discuss virtually every at-bat. They're also friends off the
field, exchanging advice on a number of subjects, including their
personal reading lists (both recently finished Hannibal and are
making their way through a sampling of James Lee Burke thrillers).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've built a trust in one another over a lot of years,''
Hurdle said. ``I can suggest he try something that maybe someone
who doesn't have the history with him can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton grew up in the heart of Volunteer country, in Knoxville,
Tenn., with an older brother and younger sister. His father Jerry
played briefly in the Minnesota Twins organization but left
baseball when his first son was born.
</P>
<P>
   From his earliest days, Helton recalls the miniature batting
cage in his basement. He was a two-sport star (baseball and
football) at Knox Central High, where his perfectionist nature was
already detectable.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him what kind of grades he got, and he will focus on the
lone B _ the only class in which he didn't receive an A during high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an honors English class,'' he said. ``I was supposed to
read a bunch of books over the summer but was playing baseball and
didn't have time to read them. I tried to alibi through all those
books.''
</P>
<P>
   After high school, Helton had two choices: sign a baseball
contract with the San Diego Padres or accept a football scholarship
from Tennessee. Thanks to some parental persuasion, he accepted the
football scholarship, but after four days of two-a-days, he was
rethinking the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to my family and decided to stay with football,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His heart apparently was never in it. He did start four games
for the Vols between the Heath Shuler and Peyton Manning eras. But
even as he played football, it was his passion for baseball that
bubbled to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``College football wasn't something that excited me,'' he said.
``Don't get me wrong. I tried my best. It wasn't like I didn't
care. But I always felt I was behind. I hadn't been to spring
practice or anything like that. I was hitting in a cage while
others were lifting weights and getting stronger. It's easier to
work at something you like.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he remembered from those days, he said: ``I do
remember certain plays, but you could fit them all on one VCR
tape.''
</P>
<P>
   He makes his offseason home in Knoxville, and there's still a
bit of Tennessee orange running through his blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I can sing Rocky Top,'' he said. ``No, I'm not going
to.''
</P>
<P>
   He got a second chance at baseball when the Rockies made him the
eighth pick of the 1995 draft. He began his career at Class A
Asheville, N.C., and climbed steadily up the organization's ladder.
His batting average climbed each season, from .254 at Asheville in
1995 to .352 at Class AAA Colorado Springs in 1997. He made an
impression in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Helton take a round of batting practice one
spring, former Rockies manager Don Baylor issued the following
order: ``Don't anyone mess with this kid's swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some have suggested Helton's hitting .400 wouldn't be a
legitimate achievement because he plays half his games in the
hitter-friendly confines of Coors Field. It's true Helton is
hitting .425 at home and .362 on the road, but that argument
overlooks the fact most hitters develop a comfort zone in their
home parks. It also overlooks the fact Williams hit .428 at Fenway
Park and .380 on the road in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree it's difficult for guys who play in Denver to hit on
the road,'' Helton said. ``Denver is such a good place to hit, and
when you go on the road, it's such a contrast. What you have to do
is take the same feeling when you step into the box. You have to
take the same feeling you have in Colorado on the road with you.
It's hard to do, but it's something you have to program to do.''
</P>
<P>
   If Helton needs his home-field advantage late in the season,
he's going to have it. The Rockies play 18 of their last 27 games
at home, including nine of their last 12.
</P>
<P>
   Helton knows the next few weeks of his life will be hectic if he
keeps his batting average near .400. He has spoken to Hurdle enough
to know the microscope under which Brett lived in 1980. He also
watched the 1998 Mark McGwire-Sammy Sosa circus from afar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would mean more to him than he lets on,'' teammate
Jeff Cirillo said. ``I mean, he has a chance to do something people
will remember forever. I think he'll do it, too. What will bother
him is if it begins to be a distraction for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
