<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3785 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-EUSEBIO-STREAK-HN     08-28 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-EUSEBIO-STREAK-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eusebio travels slow road to club-record hitting streak
</P>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Tony Eusebio is taking the scenic route into the
Astros' record book.
</P>
<P>
   In a journey that has spanned almost two months, Eusebio tied
the club record by hitting safely in his 23rd consecutive game
during the Astros' 7-3 victory over the Montreal Expos on Sunday at
Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio delivered his record-tying hit with a double down the
right-field line off Expos starter Trey Moore in the fourth inning.
He joined Art Howe (1981) and Luis Gonzalez (1997) for the longest
hitting streak in club history.
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio, a 33-year-old catcher who has been relegated to backup
duties for most of this season, added an RBI double in the fifth
and a solo home run in the eighth to cap a 3-for-4 afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's doing is amazing,'' Astros first baseman Jeff
Bagwell said. ``You don't hear of any supposed `backup catchers' _
guys who don't play a lot _ having 23-game hitting streaks.''
</P>
<P>
   While sharing playing time with rookie Mitch Meluskey, Eusebio
has put together a streak _ the longest active one in the majors _
spanning 50 days and 44 Astros games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to have this long of a streak, especially
since I don't play every day,'' said Eusebio, who had a 24-game
hitting streak while with Class AAA Tucson in 1993. ``My job the
last three or four years has been as a backup, but when they need
me in an emergency, I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio's 23-game hitting streak is the fifth-longest by a
catcher since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio began the streak July 9 _ in the final game before the
All-Star break _ with a single in the fourth inning off Kansas
City's Jeff Suppan. Since then, Eusebio has raised his laverage
from .203 to .285. During the streak, he is batting .405
(34-for-84).
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself I have an opportunity to get my batting average
up,'' said Eusebio, who went 7-for-12 in the three-game series with
the Expos. ``Every time I've gone to play I haven't thought about
the streak just getting a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   So how hard is it to not go hitless in 50 days? Consider that
when Pete Rose set the modern National League record of 44
consecutive games with a hit in 1978, he did it in 47 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he'll probably finish the season with a 24-game
hitting streak since he doesn't play every day,'' Bagwell joked.
``That makes it even more impressive. I can't express to people how
hard it is to maintain a string when you don't see live pitching
every day. I can't go more than one day without facing a pitcher.
Otherwise, I'm all screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Eusebio had two doubles and a home run in his final
three at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Sandy Koufax could get him out right now,''
pitcher Jose Lima said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
