<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3786 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX     08-28 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELIEVE IT OR NOT, STARS, MAVERICKS ARE ONLY RELIEF IN SIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a perfect local August, it would rain twice a week with an
average temp of 75. The sports media would just be returning from
two weeks of Dallas Cowboys training camp in Waikiki. The Texas
Rangers' bullpen would not be returning from a certain isolated
beach property in the Pacific, having been voted ``on'' the island
_ forever. A federal law would ban NFL exhibition games. Lone Star
Park would be offering full refunds on losing wagers.
</P>
<P>
   Reality, of course, has instead given us an August from the
deepest depths of jock-kingdom hell. And worst of all, in a month
of sporting worsts around here, the ongoing boredom has been the
hardest. It makes us crazy. It made one of us open the door naked
when the cops were knocking. It makes some of us talk in tongues,
mumbling to ourselves such gibberish as:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurry, hockey. Hurry, hoops.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be long now, friends. So hang on. August is expiring,
and the Dallas Stars are coming back, then the Dallas Mavericks are
coming back. Rain can't be far behind, and while in this delusional
state, why not wish for a snowstorm before Thanksgiving?
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, when the NHL was a foreign concept, you would
have been given a Hatcher high-stick to the head for thinking
outloud that a hockey season would someday be our salvation from
the August blast furnace. Just 10 months ago, the Mavericks ranked
behind the Pro Bass Tour as a sporting endeavor most likely to wet
your bait.
</P>
<P>
   But in eager anticipation, while also knowing instant relief is
needed from the Rangers and from those five Cowboys exhibition
games, the following is a brief capsule of what's coming on ice and
wood.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, with their established championship pedigree, report
to training camp in Vail, Colo., on Sept. 8. On Oct. 4, camp opens
for the Mavericks, who have wandered our streets, unloved and
ignored for more than a decade. Now, however, there has been a
sudden reversal in public perception. Who says it's impossible to
out-Jerry Jerry? Someday soon will Jerry be trying to out-Cuban
Cuban?
</P>
<P>
   In the category of boredom this summer, the Stars' off-season
activity ranked right up there with the Rangers and the Cowboys. If
you wanted some fun, then you tried to keep up with Mark Cuban, who
has his ownership speedometer stuck on 90 mph. But check his tires
_ are they Firestone?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of meddling, does Cuban dream up all these trade
proposals on his own, like a Fantasy League geek? Where did this
latest thing come from? Who the heck thought the troublesome
Christian Laettner was a fit with the Mavericks? Is it the same guy
who also pursued Shawn Kemp (unsuccessfully, thank goodness)
earlier this summer?
</P>
<P>
   The answer from Cuban:
</P>
<P>
   ``Nellie, Del, Sidney, Keith Grant, etc., all get involved in
the discussions about a player.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Don Nelson, Del Harris, Sidney Moncrief and Grant,
who is the assistant GM to Big Nellie. Cuban is telling us these
are basketball decisions, not Cuban decisions. Does that make
anybody feel better?
</P>
<P>
   But without question, it's the Cuban enthusiasm, and the Cuban
money, fueling a renewed interest level in the Mavericks, combined
with the team's strong finish and strong work ethic that was on
display last season.
</P>
<P>
   Just the opposite is Stars GM Bob Gainey, the steady,
dependable, spotlight-shy mastermind of hockey success at Valley
Ranch. But for those of us who thought it was a bummer summer for
Gainey, along comes Stars coach Ken Hitchcock to disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock was presented the list of local and leaguewide knocks
on the Stars doing nothing to improve in this off-season. Such as:
</P>
<P>
   Lack of overall speed not being addressed. ``Wrong,'' Hitchcock
said. ``We will add speed, but it's green speed. Young players like
Jon Sim, Roman Lyashenko, (Richard) Jackman and others will be
expected to provide this.''
</P>
<P>
   Lack of scoring firepower. ``Better health solves this,'' said
Hitchcock, meaning Jere Lehtinen, Joe Nieuwendyk and Jamie
Langenbrunner opening the season at full speed. Plus, Brett Hull's
regular-season slump appeared to be cured in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of leadership, with the heart and soul of Guy Carbonneau
retired. ``This is a challenge,'' Hitchcock said. ``You don't just
automatically replace what Guy gave us. We do have the people who
can provide the necessary leadership, and now there is no excuse
for them not to step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, a lack of toughness. How in the heck was a Scott
Thornton allowed to walk in free agency? And then Dave Manson, too?
``Well,'' said Hitchcock, who paused on this issue, ``this is why
coaches have to stay the hell out of the money end of the business.
We want to re-sign everybody. As far as toughness, we have some
people who will have to prove themselves in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the plus and minus factors, the welcome sign is out for
the Stars and Mavericks. Hurry, hockey. Hurry, hoops. We need you.
And soon. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
