<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3787 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-USAMATEUR-BOS &LR;      08-28 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRISCOLL RALLIES TO STAY ALIVE IN US AMATEUR 
</HEADLINE>
 AMATEUR-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, N.J. _ Putt after putt had refused to fall,
afternoon had given way to early evening, and it was apparent that
only a miracle could save James Driscoll in Sunday's final match of
the 100th US Amateur Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Hopeless?
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of, yeah,'' said Driscoll. ``But I never really thought
I'd blown it because the match was never over, so . . .''
</P>
<P>
   So why not a miracle? It came in the form of a three-hole
stretch over fabled Baltusrol Golf Club's upper course, a series of
shots that helped erase Jeff Quinney's 3-up lead and propel
Driscoll into overtime in this oldest of US golf championships.
Driscoll, 22, the pride of Brookline, Mass., and Charles River CC
in Newton, won the 34th hole with a conceded birdie, the 35th with
a knee-knocking 8-foot birdie putt, and the 36th with a 4-foot putt
for par after a Houdini escape from the pine trees down the right
fairway.
</P>
<P>
   The stirring finish forced extra holes, but after matching pars
at the first and second, Driscoll and Quinney were defeated by
weather. With lightning in the area, play was halted with Driscoll
and Quinney standing on the 193-yard, par-3 third tee, the 39th
hole of the match. They will return at 9 Monday morning to continue
the sudden death, a reality that met with mixed emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish we could have finished,'' said Driscoll, who lost
the first hole of the 36-hole match and never would get it all
squared until 35 holes later. ``Not because I might have had some
momentum, but just to get it over with tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinney, dejected after his day-long lead had vanished, greeted
the stoppage with open arms. ``I'm trying to keep my head high,''
he said. ``I'm still in there, but I'm tired. It's a fresh day.''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll conceded he, too, was exhausted because it was long day
of putting woes, crucial shots, and situations that you rarely see.
Regardless of how Monday's restart turns out, whether it lasts one
hole or a dozen or even more, it will have a hard time matching the
drama and bizarre turn of events that dominated 38 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we wouldn't be calling it drama if not for Driscoll's
comeback, which started at the par-4 16th, the 34th of the day. And
as it is with most comebacks, this came courtesy of a leader's
tentative swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game left me,'' said Quinney, who was 2 up after the
morning portion but quickly doubled that lead when Driscoll started
the afternoon bogey-bogey. ``I just didn't feel comfortable. I just
didn't finish the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinney was dormie, 3 up with three to play, when he fell apart
and pumped life into Driscoll's fading hopes.
</P>
<P>
   He missed the fairway on the 16th, was short of the green in
two, and chipped long after watching Driscoll knock his approach
within 20 feet. When Quinney fluffed his fourth shot and pitched
long with his fifth, he conceded Driscoll's putt and tried to
regroup at the 566-yard, par-5 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Quinney did, too, slamming a drive left-center and a perfect
layup to get within 100 yards of the pin. Driscoll spoiled a great
drive by pushing his layup right into a bunker 60 yards short of
the pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest shot in golf,'' said Driscoll, who knew he
couldn't treat it like a typical bunker shot. ``Way too long to
blast it. There's really no other way to play it except kind of try
to punch-hook it.''
</P>
<P>
   He pulled it off perfectly, knocking it within 8 feet of the
pin. Quinney was 15 feet away with his third shot, then missed his
birdie putt. The pressure was all on Driscoll, who had been
frustrated hole after hole with a putting stroke that left him
baffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right from the get-go, I missed a short one on the first
hole,'' he said, ``and my putting is very much determined on how I
putt in the beginning of a round.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been but two birdies in the morning and one in the
afternoon _ not counting the conceded one on the 34th hole _ and as
he stared down this 8-footer at the 35th hole he didn't flinch. ``I
didn't have any more or less confidence than I always do over a
putt.''
</P>
<P>
   He saw the left-to-right, downhill break, ``a cup-and-a-half
outside the hole,'' and he knew he had to make it. He probably had
put himself in a similar make-believe situation thousands of times
in all those years since he first started whacking balls around
Charles River CC. But this time, well, it was for real.
</P>
<P>
   It was also dead in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did exactly what I thought it was going to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Needing to win the 36th hole to extend the match, Driscoll tried
to compose himself, but he did too good a job. He threw a relaxed
swing on the ball and pushed it into the pine trees and was jolted
to find his ball resting against a pine cone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure the ball was touching. I wasn't going to risk
a two-shot penalty at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   He had three options _ hit it backward where the opening was
wide; directly sideways where the opening was a little less wide;
or go forward, where the gap was narrow. ``Hey,'' he said to
himself, ``I might as well go as far up as I can,'' and he threw a
punch shot on first the pine cone, then the ball. The pine cone
splattered; the ball ran underneath branches, between small pine
bushes, and came to rest 144 yards from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   Quinney, who had driven poorly and was 135 yards out after his
second shot, watched helplessly as Driscoll lifted a pitching wedge
to 4 feet. He had led the festivities since about 9:35 in the
morning, but now, with darkness falling, he was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   He had a 15-footer for birdie to end it, but missed.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure back to Driscoll, who wasted little time settling over
the 4-footer. ``It caught the right edge and snuck in,'' said
Driscoll, whose enthusiastic gallery roared. His parents, sister,
five brothers, dozens of cousins, and countless friends from
Charles River CC rushed the green, but Driscoll looked at none of
them. He cast his eyes skyward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it went in,'' he said. ``I was just thanking
God at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   He had dodged plenty of obstacles, none more incredible than the
par-5 eighth hole in the afternoon. Already 3 down at that point,
Driscoll had driven well left beneath a tree and for some reason he
chose to gamble. He pulled out a 3-wood and convinced himself that
he had enough room to swing hard.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. The club got caught in a tree branch, and while he knew
he would look silly, Driscoll knew something else _ he could have
been called for a penalty had he stopped his swing. So he followed
through _ and whiffed. That's right, he missed.
</P>
<P>
   But he regrouped with a punched iron that put him in position to
reach the green with his fourth shot. When he missed his par
attempt, he had only one hope _ a three-putt bogey by Quinney, who
obliged, running his 20-foot downhill birdie try a good 15 feet
strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have gone 4 up,'' said Quinney, shaking his head in
disbelief. ``I hit a terrible putt.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a feeling Driscoll could relate to _ at least for the
first 33 holes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
