<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC EARNED VICTORY OVER PENN STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's cardinal-and-gold edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   If you read any of the preseason college football magazines,
then you know Penn State had been downgraded from Nittany Lion to
Pretty Kitty. Joe Paterno may have to wait until 2001 to get the
seven wins he needs to tie Bear Bryant's NCAA Division I win
record.
</P>
<P>
   But it's been so long since USC's defense actually got after an
opponent that no restrictions will be placed on their 29-3 win
Sunday at the Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   USC's defense held Penn State to six rushing yards, and that's a
pretty sweet number even if you concede that Lion quarterback
Rashard Casey played like he was handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   It shines when compared to last season, when USC's defense was
stomped by Arizona (307 yards), Stanford (160) and Arizona State
(213), and allowed 21 or more points in 8 of 12 games. Going back
to mid-1996, USC's defense had allowed 21 points or more in 26 of
42 games, and gone 9-17 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   With Sultan McCullough, Kareem Kelly and Carson Palmer, one has
to believe the Trojans can average 30 points a game, even in spite
of Sunday's modest offensive effort. If Zeke Moreno and ex-Long
Beach City College linebacker Markus Steele can just contain
opponents, then USC has every right to believe it can return to the
Top 10 and Rose Bowl. ...
</P>
<P>
   Penn State returned only two starters on defense, but
McCullough's 137-yard effort still stands out as progress for the
running game. USC netted just 31 yards a year ago against Oregon
and minus 20 yards against Arizona, and neither team had a great
defense. ...
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing about these ``extra'' games in college football
is the glare of the spotlight. Florida State gets bored beating BYU
and people say the Seminoles are down from last season. USC will
undoubtedly jump into the top ten now and leave most everyone
expecting a rout of Colorado in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's a quality program, and I'm guessing Gary Barnett, who
lost to USC in the '96 Rose Bowl when he was at Northwestern, will
be looking to even that score. ...
</P>
<P>
   One can talk all day about the intangibles of the Yankees and
Braves and the pitching depth of the A's and Mariners. But who
makes and misses the playoffs more than likely will come down to
the kind of schedule the contenders have in September.
</P>
<P>
   American League, team by team:
</P>
<P>
   Yankees: They have more road games left than the other AL
contenders except the Angels, but they also have the second-best
road record in the league. The Yankees, four up on Boston in the
East, have just three games left with the Red Sox (Sept. 8-10), and
Toronto could be DOA when they meet for two series inside of a long
week. The Yankees finish with the Tigers, Rays and Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox: The best time to take the Sox temperature is next
week, after this week's games against the A's and Angels.
Thereafter, they have just a three-game series with Cleveland and a
series against Boston the last week. Even with fractured pitching,
they're eight games up on Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners and A's: They almost have identical schedules. Both
have a series coming up with Boston, followed by a run of games
against sub-.500 teams and a AL West round-robin the last 10 days.
The A's play four in Seattle, but they're home to Chicago this week
while the pitching-wracked Mariners are at the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Angels: Mike Scioscia's team is just 2{ games out of the wild
card spot, but they have only 12 home games left and a 27-34 road
record. However, after a three-game series at Chicago this weekend,
the next six series are against sub-.500 teams before ending the
season with the A's and Mariners. Considering the way the Angels
have rebounded from some heartbreaking losses, it would be
shortsighted to say they're done.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox, Blue Jays and Indians: The Blue Jays are done, with six
of their next seven series against the Yankees, White Sox and A.L.
West leaders. Cleveland's rally has been impressive, but they'll
have to do more than split a sequence that includes the White Sox,
Yankees and Red Sox twice in mid-September. Boston needs to step up
during a brief homestand against Seattle and Oakland, what with the
Yankees and Indians still to come. ...
</P>
<P>
   National League, team-by-team:
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals: After next weekend's series at home versus the Mets,
the Cards don't face a team with a winning record the rest of the
season. Who needs Mark McGwire with a slate like this?
</P>
<P>
   Braves and Mets: Their race to decide the N.L. East champ will
likely encompass the wild card as well. The schedule favors the
Mets, what with Atlanta having two series left with Arizona, both
coming before two series with the Mets the last two weeks of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   N.L. West: The Giants next six series are against sub-.500
teams, while Arizona has two series against Atlanta and two more
with the Dodgers. The Giants could have the division padlocked by
the time they play seven games against the Snakes the last 11 days
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers hope to stay within sight of the Giants until they
launch a 13-game homestand. But the Giants would still need to give
back a lot of games, and the Dodgers would have to figure a way to
overcome a 32-30 home record. ...
</P>
<P>
   I've never seen a major-league hitter take more good pitches
than Dodgers center fielder Tom Goodwin. Sometimes you can be too
patient. ...
</P>
<P>
   Don't say Davey Johnson can't play little ball. The winning run
Sunday in the Cubs game came on a walk, sacrifice, ground ball to
advance the runner to third, and wild pitch. Just like the days of
Maury Wills and Jim Gilliam. ...
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing that Ismael Valdes took a huge step in
rehabilitating his reputation in the club house by plunking Mark
Grace on the arm Sunday. It earned him an ejection, but it was the
kind of statement his reputation needed. ...
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball did Tommy Lasorda's U.S. Olympic baseball
team no favors. Several teams refused to allow their top prospects
on the team. Third baseman Joe Crede (White Sox), first baseman
Carlos Pena (Rangers) and pitcher Randy Keisler (Yankees) were
among the top minor leaguers the Olympic team couldn't have.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Trojan Barry Zito (A's), Aubrey Huff (Tampa Bay) and Craig
House (Rockies) were also on the list before they were called them
up to the majors. ...
</P>
<P>
   I'd get excited about the upcoming Fernando Vargas-Felix
Trinidad 154-pound title bout if I didn't already know that Don
King, Trinidad's promoter, will find some way to screw things up. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
