<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS CUT TWO MORE THAN REQUIRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Monday's Patriots roster is different from
Sunday's, and Tuesday's is sure to be different from Monday's as
new coach Bill Belichick attempts to build his team, one that is
still thin at the edges.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick Sunday reduced his roster to 51 players, two fewer
than necessary, clearly believing help will be available from
elsewhere. And help is particularly needed at running back and
tight end, where Belichick has only two players each, and at
linebacker, now down to a rather thin five.
</P>
<P>
   The two extra roster spots mean Belichick will closely peruse
the list of players cut by Sunday's 4 p.m. deadline. The Patriots
certainly will have at least two, if not more, players cut by other
teams in Foxborough by midweek.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what the waiver wire brings,'' said the coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an exact science,'' Belichick added of his first
cutdown with New England. ``I'm sure there'll be some mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But few fans could argue with Belichick's surgery, even if the
final cut included one ``name,'' veteran running back Raymont
Harris, and one of former coach Pete Carroll's 1999 starters,
safety Chris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Not much was expected of the journeyman Harris when he was
signed by New England, and Carter's play ranged from mediocre to
poor last season even though Carroll kept him in the defensive
backfield for virually the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not so much about him but the progress of the other
players,'' Belichick said of Harris, who was released outright. And
the waiving of Carter, who languished on the third team for much of
training camp, came as no surprise. ``We had only so many spots,''
said Belichick, noting that the players he kept in Carter's place
made contributions on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Three local players were waived: wide receiver and fan favorite
Sean Morey of Marshfield and Brown, tight end Chris Eitzmann of
Harvard, and linebacker Marc Megna of Fall River. It is quite
possible that all three could be named to the practice squad;
players who clear waivers by 4 p.m. Monday can be brought back.
</P>
<P>
   One key decision by Belichick was to keep all four of his
quarterbacks, Drew Bledsoe, John Friesz, Michael Bishop, and rookie
Tom Brady, who threw the ball well enough in exhibition games to
suggest he may have a future in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Brady, said Belichick, ``showed us enough where we could keep
him on the roster.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping all four QBs means that the Patriots have 26 offensive
players (4 QBs, 2 TEs, 2 RBs, 3 fullbacks, 6 wide receivers, and 9
offensive linemen) to 22 on the defensive side. Also on the roster
are kicker Adam Vinatieri, punter Lee Johnson, and Lonnie Paxton,
he of the laser beam long snaps. But those numbers could change
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick also placed rookie offensive lineman Adrian Klemm, a
second-round draft choice, on the physically unable to perform
list. This means Klemm (knee) cannot return for at least six weeks.
The coach, though, said he expects Klemm to play this season.
</P>
<P>
   Also, veteran offensive lineman Lance Scott (knee) was placed on
the injured reserve list, meaning that he cannot return this
season. He was the third offensive lineman to be placed on an
injured list in four days, as veteran Todd Rucci (knee) recently
was placed on the non-football injury list. Rucci cannot return for
at least six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Others among the 12 players waived were rookie nose tackle
Maurice Anderson of Virginia; rookie offensive lineman Rob Gatrell
of Fresno State; rookie running back Patrick Pass of Georgia;
rookie defensive lineman Jeff Marriott of Missouri, and rookie
linebacker Maugaula Tuitele of Colorado State.
</P>
<P>
   Also waived were nose tackle Garrett Johnson, linebacker Olrick
Johnson, and cornerback Kelly Malveaux, all of whom have NFL
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said he and his staff were of common mind on most of
the cuts, with fierce debates on only a few players. A determining
factor, beyond the usual factors of special teams play and
versatility, was whether it was believed players were improving.
</P>
<P>
   If the coaches felt two players were equal, said Belichick, a
deciding factor ``was whether one player was gaining ground or
another was leveling off. You try to project where the (improving)
player will be a month from now or a year from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Two players who clearly fit that bill are young wide receivers
Dane Looker and Shockmain Davis, each of whom made the team. The
Patriots obtained Looker in a trade with the Rams three weeks ago,
a condition of which was that the Patriots would give St. Louis a
sixth-round draft choice if he made the team. And Looker was
impressive in making the squad, catching 19 passes in three
exhibition games, four for touchdowns. Davis, also a rookie, was
nearly as impressive.
</P>
<P>
   As most NFL coaches do, Belichick said cutdown day was
difficult. ``It's been a tough couple of days,'' he said. ``It's a
tough day no matter how long you've been in the league. You never
get used to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
