<SLUG> BC-GLF-FLEETBOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NELSON CAPTURES FLEETBOSTON CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ For more than a dozen holes Sunday, the final
round of the FleetBoston Classic at Nashawtuc Country Club was an
all-out hit-me-with-your-best-shot war.
</P>
<P>
   Three shots separated 11 golfers, and a playoff seemed
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   But then Larry Nelson took charge with back-to-back birdies on
holes 14 and 15 to open up some breathing room between himself and
the pack, and suddenly the battle was for second place.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson could cruise after that, aware the tournament was his to
win or lose. He added another birdie at 17 and pocketed $195,000
after a 13-under-par 66_203 and a tough four-shot margin of victory
over Jim Thorpe, who finished 67_207.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood's Allen Doyle (67), Chi Chi Rodriguez (67), and Bruce
Fleisher (68) all finished at 208, and at 209 were two-time
champion Hale Irwin (69) and Leonard Thompson (70).
</P>
<P>
   The win was a milestone for Nelson, 52, who has helped design
more than a dozen golf courses worldwide. It was his third win of
the year and eighth since joining the Senior PGA Tour in 1997. The
$195,000 pushed his 2000 earnings to $1,773,355, third behind
Fleisher and Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, after shooting 70 and falling a stroke behind leader
Kermit Zarley, Nelson felt someone was due for a big round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to be somebody, it had to be,'' said
Nelson. ``I just didn't know it was going to be me. That would be
the only way you could get out of the pack. Either that or we'd be
having an 11-way playoff. It looked like it was going to be that
way for a while. I really didn't feel comfortable out there until
the 10th.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when he slammed a 3-wood 249 yards to within 35 feet of
the pin and two-putted for birdie. That pushed him to 10 under, and
he never surrendered after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``From then on I felt it was mine to win or lose,'' said Nelson,
who used a different putter each round in an effort to help him
cure that ailing part of his game. ``I felt my game was getting
better every day,'' he said, ``and I was just hoping my putting
would kick in, which it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has played the last two Senior PGA stops, but before that
withdrew from the Bell Atlantic and Lightpath Long Island Classics
with an inflamed vertebra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three weeks ago today, I couldn't tie my shoes,'' he said. ``I
stopped lifting weights, stopped running, everything the doctor
said. Now I'm stretching and doing situps and the back feels OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the also-rans gave it a go during the final round.
Thorpe pulled within a stroke of the leader on the ninth with a
3-footer that put him 8 under. He nursed that until the 18th, when
a 2-footer for birdie fell and broke the logjam with Rodriguez,
Doyle, and Fleisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I might have a chance to win if I shot 7 or 8
under,'' said Thorpe, whose best finish this season was a
fifth-place tie at the Lightpath Classic. ``I really didn't give
myself an opportunity to do that on the back nine. I didn't think
I'd be where I am, though, especially after starting 70-70.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Rodriguez, who turned back the hands of time with
a stirring back-nine 31 that featured five birdies, including three
straight at 14, 15, and 16. The birdie on 10 ignited him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 60 feet from the back edge, like a football field,''
said Rodriguez, who recorded his best finish since 1996. ``I felt
the adrenaline pumping. I haven't been nervous in six years and
that is very bad for you because then you don't care. (Sunday) I
was like a roach in a chicken nest.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle, Fleisher, and Irwin made runs at the top spot, but once
Nelson made those back-to-back birdies, they couldn't get over the
hump.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the media area, Nelson had a few parting words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing here. I love the crowds; they're bigger here
than just about anywhere in the country. And they are very nice. I
especially love this course, I just can't pronounce its name.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronouncing it correctly wasn't necessary. Playing it was, and
Nelson played it very well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
