<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYALS OUTLAST RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ROYALS-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ How hot was it?
</P>
<P>
   Check under the collars of Tim Wakefield, Jimy Williams, and
Scott Hatteberg.
</P>
<P>
   On a stifling, 95-degree day when Wakefield's knuckleball
betrayed him again and the Red Sox needed all the help they could
muster, they fell victim in part to an obscure umpire, Pat Spieler,
who fueled a killer Kansas City rally by appearing to make one of
the most abominable calls since the birth of the national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   No one needed laser surgery to see that Wakefield's
second-inning throw to the catcher Hatteberg appeared to force out
Dave McCarty at the plate with enough time left for Hatteberg to
down a lemonade. Spieler's call allowed another run to score when
the next batter, Jermaine Dye, launched a sacrifice fly that
otherwise would have ended the inning.
</P>
<P>
   And the Sox never recovered, as the Royals ran up leads of 9-1
and 11-3 before Boston staged a trademark late charge, which this
time fell short. The fallout was an 11-7 loss, a split in the
four-game series, and a lot of anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a brutal call,'' Hatteberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't good at all,'' Wakefield said. ``He cost me two
runs, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Spieler insisted to Williams that Hatteberg took his foot off
the plate before the throw arrived. But the manager said the ump
may have been influenced by a freak of astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must have been a full sun out there,'' he said. ``He was
out by 30 feet. That's not good, not at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams protested vehemently and said later, ``Why he didn't
throw me out, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their complaining, no one in the Sox clubhouse went so
far as to blame the loss on Spieler, not when poor pitching and a
fielding miscue or two were crucial to the setback.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, the Sox remain a half-game ahead of Cleveland
in the American League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to use it as an excuse,'' Wakefield said of
Spieler's call. ``I didn't pitch very well today, and I haven't
pitched very well in the last three starts.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave up seven earned runs on eight hits and three walks in
five innings. That was an improvement on his last outing, when he
yielded eight runs on nine hits and two walks in 4 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Wakefield's effort Sunday also was better than his
performance two weeks ago in Texas, when he was knocked out in the
fourth inning after walking the bases loaded and giving up a grand
slam to Ricky Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wakefield (6-9) is winless in his last eight starts
since he won his fourth game in a row July 16. His ERA in the eight
starts mushroomed to 7.58, and his dismal stretch is sure to
provide grist for Monday morning managers who want him out of the
starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield said he cannot pinpoint his problem. ``If I had the
answers,'' he said, ``we might have won.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he has no plans to remove Wakefield from his spot.
And Wakefield considers the notion ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make the decisions around here,'' he said. ``I made
something like 10 quality starts. Now I've had three bad ones, and
you're asking me if I'm out of the rotation. Don't ask me that.
That's stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how hot it got afterward. On the field, Hatteberg said,
it was the hottest game he ever has caught, and he played some
minor league ball in Florida and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   It got hotter as the Royals built their lead, thanks to the
second-inning fiasco and two-run homers by Dye in the third inning
and McCarty in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the fifth, the Sox were down, 9-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incredibly hot, tiring game,'' Hatteberg said, ``and
when you get down, it makes it that much more difficult to come
back. You have to mount an attack to put together some big innings,
and when you don't it drags on you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox made it 9-3 in the sixth, after Brian Daubach led off
with his second double of the day and Nomar Garciaparra singled,
sending Daubach to third. After Hatteberg walked, Lou Merloni
brought home Daubach with a sacrifice fly and Trot Nixon singled in
Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Royals scored two more runs off Bryce Florie in
the bottom of the inning, Williams appeared to call it a day.
</P>
<P>
   He yanked Daubach, who was 7 for 14 (.500) in the series with
two homers, four doubles, and four RBIs. Taken out, too, was
Garciaparra, who is leading the league with a .373 average. So was
Troy O'Leary, who was 4 for 12 (.333) in the series with three
doubles.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's replacement, Bernard Gilkey, stroked the first of five
hits in a four-run, eighth-inning rally that closed the KC lead to
11-7.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach's replacement, Rico Brogna, grounded into a force play
to end the rally. The Sox tried to complete the comeback in the
ninth, when Garciaparra's replacement, Manny Alexander, walked to
lead off. But Gilkey struck out and Hatteberg grounded into a
double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you put some new blood in the game and it sparks
you,'' Williams said. ``And it did.''
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes you wish you had not taken out your starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you say, `Damn, why did I do that?' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With little time for second-guessing, the Sox departed for Tampa
for a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games like this are going to happen,'' Hatteberg said. ``We've
just got to put it behind us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
