u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-B     08-28 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIXON'S SLUMP PROVING HARD TO STOMACH 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There are dozens of broken bats, shattered
helmets, and even a battered coffee machine or two in Trot Nixon's
past that could testify to how he has dealt with slumps in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's killing me not to snap here or there,'' Nixon said Sunday
morning. ``We had a punching bag in Pawtucket that I just wore out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thankful for the fact that we're in the thick of things.
If we weren't, I would be going insane right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months into his second major league season, Nixon looked as
if he would become as much of a fixture in right field as the Pesky
Pole. He was hitting .321 by the end of May, was on a pace to drive
in and score more than 100 runs, and had seven home runs in his
first 44 games.
</P>
<P>
   His game-winning, ninth-inning home run in Yankee Stadium off
Roger Clemens on the last weekend in May sent Nixon's popularity
soaring. Remember when the notion that the Sox had a shot at Sammy
Sosa first surfaced, there were plenty of people who didn't want to
do the deal if it meant giving up the homegrown Trot?
</P>
<P>
   But then came June, the hits became scarcer, and in Toronto,
Nixon blew out his right hamstring running out a ground ball in
SkyDome. He wound up missing a month, and hasn't been the same as
he was before he got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The .300 hitter of May has hit just .237 (36 for 152) since
then. He has just one home run in his last 48 games, and his two
RBIs in Sunday's 11-7 loss to the Royals gave him just 15 in that
span.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to explain why I haven't been able to lock in on
things,'' he said Sunday. ``I feel like I've been seeing the ball,
but I'm just not reacting to it like I normally should.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my wife (Kathryn), `This is an absolute battle ever
since I've been back from my injury. I feel like I've swung the bat
at times, closer to where I was before I got hurt. I wasn't
swinging that good then, but I felt like I had a little bit of whip
in my bat, and I felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Nixon said, he probably should have taken a little
more time before coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably should have played a few more rehab games. I had
that choice. I probably should have gone to Pawtucket for a week or
so, to get some at-bats down there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You miss a lot of time, you lose a lot of your timing. It's
tough. You want to come back and help the ball club as much as
possible, and then you're not doing anything at the plate, you just
feel like crap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I care about is winning ballgames. You want
your personal goals, too, but you have to set that stuff aside and
get Ws. But it's frustrating when your team wins and you didn't do
anything. You say, `Geez, what did I do? It was nine on eight
today.' Sometimes, I have to tell myself not to think that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had just two hits in 15 at-bats this weekend in Kansas
City. With a runner on third in the second inning Sunday and one
out, he lined to short. Wendell Kim could have sprinted back and
forth across the diamond a half-dozen times in the time Nixon made
his way back to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   He lined to deep center in the fourth, singled a run home on
another line drive in the sixth, and his sacrifice fly in the
eighth made it 11-6.
</P>
<P>
   It's baffling to Nixon why he hasn't been able to get more
trajectory on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of frustrating that I haven't been able to put up
the power numbers I'd like,'' he said. ``I should have at least 15
home runs by now. I can hit 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why I'm not getting the trajectory. If I knew, I
could probably get the ball in the air more. I don't think it's
mechanics. I think it's more or less where you hit the ball. It's
not like taking a pistol 10 feet from the target, pointing it, and
if the pistol is accurate and you aim and set it, you'll be all
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hit the baseball, you want to hit underneath it, but
you can't hit it wherever you want. Johnny Damon is a perfect
example, what he did with his home run Saturday night. He just took
the bat, drove it through the zone down, and got that the backspin
on the ball. It just took off on a line. I figured the ball was
going to have some topspin, but he got underneath it and got that
backspin.
</P>
<P>
   ``In certain situations, I just missed balls. I either hit 'em
too high or off the end of the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, when he got off to a brutal start as a rookie,
Nixon spent long hours working with manager Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to him last year because of the fact I was absolutely
lost,'' he said. ``I don't feel like I'm really lost now. The more
I take batting practice, the more I'll get in that groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Between them, Nixon (8) and Troy O'Leary (10) have hit as many
home runs in 709 at-bats as Royals left fielder Mark Quinn, a
rookie, has hit in 404 at-bats. Jermaine Dye, the Royals right
fielder who drove in three runs Sunday with a two-run homer and
sacrifice fly, has 99 RBIs, one more than O'Leary and Nixon
combined.
</P>
<P>
   And Damon, the splendid Royals center fielder who wore out Red
Sox pitching (21 for 42, .500) and is leading the major leagues in
hitting since the All-Star break, is the same age as Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ticks me off to the point that there's no return,'' Nixon
said. ``But if I sit here ticked off every time I did that, I'd
find myself out of baseball or down in the minor leagues. I don't
want to do that, but there are so many great players out there, if
you don't put up some good numbers you're not going to be around
very long.''
</P>
<P>
   What sustains him, he said, is the knowledge that he can salvage
his season with a big September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep telling myself we've got another whole month and we're
right in the thick of things,'' he said. ``We're in a great
position. We have a tough month ahead, but nothing comes easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want stuff served on a silver platter. Every now and
then a silver platter is nice, but we're going to have to work for
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
