<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS GOES ON SPIEL ABOUT UMP SPIELER 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-UMPIRE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ His name is Pat Spieler, he is a substitute
umpire in his first season in the major leagues, and after this
weekend, he won't need any introductions to Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would probably recognize him in the mall,'' said Williams,
who had more face time arguing with Spieler than he would have
liked, no more so than in the second inning when Spieler, who was
working behind the plate, ruled Sox catcher Scott Hatteberg did not
have his foot on the plate when Tim Wakefield threw home on a
bases-loaded ground ball by Jeff Reboulet in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a forceout that would have been the second out of the
inning with the score still 1-0, Royals, Kansas City had another
run and would soon make it three when Hector Ortiz scored on a
sacrifice fly by Johnny Damon, which otherwise would have been the
third out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   David McCarty, who scored on the comebacker to Wakefield, would
have been out by 30 feet if Spieler hadn't ruled Hatteberg was off
the plate. No one _ not Williams, not Hatteberg, not Wakefield _
could recall a similar ruling by a plate umpire on a routine
comebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have been a full sun today,'' said Williams, who has
been known to cite a full moon as the explanation for other bizarre
occurrences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe he called that play,'' Williams said. ``Why
I didn't get tossed by him, I don't know. Why I didn't get tossed
by the first-base umpire, I don't know, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg said he didn't see a replay, unlike Channel 25
announcer Sean McDonough, who told the folks back home they'd just
witnessed ``an awful'' call, the worst he'd seen this season. But
there was no question, Hatteberg said, that the runner should have
been out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out and straddled the base and my foot was on the front
of the plate, just where I wanted it,'' Hatteberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who argued vigorously with Spieler after Wakefield
stormed from the mound in protest, in the fifth debated first-base
umpire Tim Timmons, who ruled that Jermaine Dye had beaten Lou
Merloni's attempt to double him off after catching a foul popup by
Mark Quinn behind the third-base bag. Mike Sweeney, who was on
third, scored on the play when first baseman Brian Daubach threw
wildly to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got as much sun as those players today,'' Williams said.
``That's not good. I don't like that. I don't like to be out there.
And I didn't use sunscreen, either. That's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Spieler had an eventful weekend. Friday night, while umpiring at
second base, he called out Jose Offerman at first when he was
doubled off the bag on a fly ball to Dye in right field. Saturday,
he ruled that Royals first baseman Sweeney slid into the bag ahead
of Manny Alexander on Alexander's bid for an infield hit. Williams
argued those calls, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't good, he wasn't good at all,'' was Wakefield's
summation of Spieler's work behind the plate, which may have been
the first time the umpire has been behind the plate for a
knuckleballer this season, no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cost me two runs in the second inning, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   His ball-strike work was also bad, according to both Wakefield
and Hatteberg.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who contended that Spieler also was late in making his
call, muted his criticism by saying that the Sox couldn't blame
this loss on a call made in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what happens,'' he said, ``is your focus goes to the
umpire instead of what you're trying to do in the game. Do you ever
get it back?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
