<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3800 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      08-28 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ANNE STEPHENSON'S ``NEW &AMP; NOTABLE'' BOOK REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``DROWNING RUTH''
</P>
<P>
   By Cristina Schwarz
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   This first novel is soap opera at its best, a story with such
melodrama waiting around every bend that it would seem silly if
Schwarz were not so adept at leading us on through the mire. It is
1919, and Amanda Starkey, a Milwaukee nurse who cares for men sent
home from the Great War, is teetering on the edge of a nervous
breakdown. When the hospital asks her to leave, she goes home to
live on her family's farm overlooking Nagawaukee Lake with her
younger sister, Mattie, and Mattie's 3-year-old daughter, Ruth. A
year later, Mattie is found mysteriously drowned (yes, Mattie,
despite the book's title), her body frozen in the lake ice. What
happened? Schwarz moves masterfully back and forth in time,
switching from third-person narration to the voices of Ruth and
Amanda and introducing characters who are startlingly blind to
their roles in events that cost Mattie her life and threaten
Amanda's sanity. It's a darkly entertaining story of guilt and
grief, told with suspense and meticulous control.
</P>
<P>
   ``TO THE BEST OF MY ABILITY''
</P>
<P>
   Edited by James M. McPherson
</P>
<P>
   (DK, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   John Adams, historian James M. Banner Jr. writes, was
``insecure, volatile, impulsive, irritable, suspicious,
self-pitying, self-righteous and filled with often combustible
rage.'' John F. Kennedy once said to a group of Nobel Prize winners
that they were ``the most extraordinary collection of human talent
ever gathered at the White House, with the possible exception of
when Thomas Jefferson dined alone.'' And was it a critic or an
admirer who asked about Andrew Jackson, ``If (he) wants to go to
heaven, who's to stop him?'' Most of us don't need to know
everything about the 42 men who have been presidents of the United
States, but it's nice to grasp the basics. This handsome book
offers an informative essay about each president, written by a
member of the Society of American Historians (editor McPherson
deals with Abraham Lincoln). Also, here are voting statistics for
each election and the texts of each president's inaugural address.
It's a primer well worth its price.
</P>
<P>
   ``ISN'T THAT A GUN IN YOUR POCKET?''
</P>
<P>
   By Rachel Abramowitz
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $26.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started directing, people said to me the first day,
`Where shall we put the camera?''' Elaine May remembers. ``And I
didn't know what the camera looked like. I thought it was one of
the lights.'' Luckily, she figured it out. This book, which began
as a story about women in the movie business for
(beginitalic)Premiere (enditalic)magazine, is really a rambling
collection of miniprofiles of powerful women in Hollywood,
including Barbra Streisand, Jodie Foster, writer-director Nora
Ephron, director Penny Marshall, studio executive Sherry Lansing
and agent Sue Mengers. Abramowitz actually spends less time on the
subject of women and power than she does telling stories about the
making of such films as (beginitalic)The Accused(enditalic),
(beginitalic)Yentl(enditalic), (beginitalic)Thelma
&AMP;(enditalic)(beginitalic)Louise(enditalic), (beginitalic)Fatal
Attraction (enditalic)and (beginitalic)When Harry Met
Sally(enditalic). In the end, it's more fun that way. After all,
she says, the true measure of success in Hollywood is the ease with
which it's taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE CIVIL WAR: A NEW VIEW IN CLOSE-UP 3-D''
</P>
<P>
   By Marc E. Frey
</P>
<P>
   (Running Press, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   This ``book'' is terrific if you are 8 years old, but Civil War
enthusiasts with more years under their belts will probably find it
wanting. On the first page, a simple tent pops up, much like the
one Lincoln and McClellan met in at Antietam (there are men in this
one, too, but they aren't Lincoln or McClellan and you need a
flashlight to see them). On the next page is something that bears
considerable resemblance to a pit toilet but is really a
stubby-barreled, muzzle-loading cannon (that's the problem with
pop-up books - everything looks like something else, and you don't
get to choose what it is). The third page offers a simple pop-up of
the ironclad warship Monitor; on the fourth are the trenches of the
Petersburg campaign; on the fifth is the city of Columbia, S.C.,
with little flames coming out of it; and finally, a lumpy
topographical map of Gettysburg. That's what you get for the price
of admission - scoff or enjoy, as you will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 0120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0032 </DOCNO>
