<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE MAKING ITS MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ A year ago Adam Eyre, Rustin ``Rusty''
Pierce, and Mauricio Wright were far from the Revolution radar
screen. Eyre and Pierce were playing for collegiate teams in
California and North Carolina, respectively, and Wright was the
captain of the San Jose Clash.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are the Revolution's starting defenders and likely the
key to the team's Major League Soccer playoff prospects as it
prepares to meet D.C. United at Foxboro Stadium Wednesday and in
Washington Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Fernando Clavijo has completely revamped the Revolution
defense, benching Olympic team captain Brian Dunseth and discarding
three former national team players, Mike Burns and Dan Calichman of
the United States and Ivan McKinley of South Africa. The result has
been consecutive 2-1 victories over Tampa Bay and Columbus, teams
that regularly have troubled the Revolution with dynamic forwards
such as Mamadou Diallo, Jeff Cunningham, and Dante Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who arrived from San Jose in a trade for Burns and
Calichman May 30, has allowed the Revolution to switch to the 3-5-2
alignment that Clavijo had planned to install in the preseason. And
Eyre and Pierce have emerged as effective marking backs.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, a candidate for MLS most valuable player last season,
had a difficult start to his Revolution career. His reputation
suffered after he clashed with San Jose coach Lothar Osiander, then
struggled to adjust to his new team. The most linguistically
versatile interviewee among the Revolution starters even declined
comment after a particularly devastating loss in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been everything I thought he would be, as a leader and
as an individual,'' Clavijo said. ``He has been screaming his head
off at the younger players, and they have responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before he came here, people were saying he was lazy in
practices and doesn't want to do this or that. But here he is
staying late after practice, and he has been great. It makes you
wonder how these problems arise.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright had interpreted the libero position very literally in San
Jose, distinguishing himself more for his adventurous offensive
forays than for discouraging the opposition. Once joining the
Revolution, he soon was convinced to be more selective in going
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the freedom to go forward,'' Clavijo said. ``He is an
attacking defender. But he needs to pick the times to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright three times abandoned the central defense against the
Crew Saturday night. Each time, a scoring opportunity resulted.
Wright was involved in a scramble with Todd Yeagley that resulted
in Imad Baba's 35th-minute penalty kick to tie it in the 35th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to stay at home, it's no problem for me,'' Wright
said. ``I play for the Revolution, and you have to do what the
coach wants. I have to take care of the other defenders because we
are playing with three, especially against a team like Columbus,
which has some of the fastest players in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is getting better. We lost against Columbus earlier
in the season, but now we are playing better (on) defense. If we
only give up one or two goals, that gives a lot of confidence to
the rest of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   A more enterprising Wright might produce more offense, but that
might compromise the team's effectiveness. The Revolution have
surrendered more than one goal in regulation time only twice, and
no more than two goals in a game, since a telling 4-1 loss at
Columbus. Wright has increased the volume since then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3803 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-FLEETBOSTONCLASSI     08-28 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-FLEETBOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUN AT HEART OF RODRIGUEZ' GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-RODRIGUEZ-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ Chi Chi Rodriguez's surgically repaired heart
was filled with joy Sunday as he was poignantly reminded that he
still has the heart of a champion.
</P>
<P>
   His final-round 5-under-par 67 earned him a share of third place
in the FleetBoston Classic at Nashawtuc CC, his best finish in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's 31 on the back nine, in fact, had him smilingly
comparing himself with Tiger Woods. ``Just call me Lion
Rodriguez,'' beamed Chi Chi, who playfully took a spectator's seat
at the 18th green before getting up and narrowly missing a 15-foot
birdie putt from the fringe. ``And tigers don't mess with lions.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who was champion here at the former Digital Seniors
Classic from 1986-88, hasn't won a PGA Senior Tour title in six
years. His earnings, and his scores, have steadily declined. And
two years ago, 10 days before his 63d birthday, he had surgery
following a mild heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, however, his three-round total of 8-under 208, tying him
with Allen Doyle and Bruce Fleisher, netted him his biggest payoff
in years _ $78,000. Coupled with his check for $17,853 for his
third-place finish in the Georgia-Pacific Super Seniors portion of
the tournament, it was nearly a $100,000 weekend, more money than
he has earned on tour all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm back. My heart is strong again. I have new arteries and
I'm getting more oxygen in than I have in years and I'm stronger
than I have been in six years,'' said Rodriguez, who hadn't been in
the top 25 in a tournament this year.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Sunday's nostalgic _ and at times spectacular _
round, which marked his best finish since 1996 when he was
runner-up to Gil Morgan at the Ralphs Senior Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's 33 on the front Saturday hinted at things to come,
but putting woes on the back left him at 3 under, five strokes
behind second-day leader Kermit Zarley. And when he stayed at 3
under through the front nine Sunday, it appeared Rodriguez wouldn't
be sharing space on the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Rodriguez _ a big fan of the Red Sox, Pedro Martinez
in particular, and Boston scrod _ turned back the clock in dramatic
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied the 10th (60 feet), 11th, 14th, 15th, and 16th holes,
while exciting the record crowd of 42,000-plus with his trademark
swordsman routine as each birdie putt fell.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reminder of days past, and a tribute to friends who
recently had passed on. Rodriguez said he has dedicated his 2000
tour season to the former chairman of Toyota of America, Yuki Togo,
who died a month ago and ``was like a brother to me. I'm trying to
win one for him and for my (late) manager, Eddie Elias.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who has been stuck firmly at 22 PGA Senior Tour
first-place finishes, was at his humorous best after Sunday's
round, his lowest at a tour event this year.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about a tricky downhill chip that he parlayed into a
save for par at 17, Rodriguez said, ``If I was Chester, I would
have had a flat lie because I could have taken my wooden leg off,''
a reference to a character from the 1960s western TV series
``Gunsmoke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The gallery was really rooting for me. They always have, but
it's pretty tough to be rooting for bogeys and double bogeys like
I've been making,'' added Rodriguez, who felt he ``blew'' the
tournament Saturday when he ``must have taken 20 putts.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's been a long, long time since Rodriguez, who turns 65
Oct. 23, has been able to look back on a round and lament what a
stroke or two could have meant _ and that significance was not lost
on him.
</P>
<P>
   And it's why, as he walked to the 18th green after a great sand
shot that gave him a chance at 9 under, it was time to bond one
last time with a gallery that kept calling his name.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez dipped under the rope and gestured to a man to step
aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to move and he didn't know what for,'' said
Rodriguez. ``Then I took his chair. You could tell that chair was
not electric.''
</P>
<P>
   But the atmosphere created by a golfer who suddenly had found
the fountain of middle age certainly was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-VIRGINIATECH-VICK     08-28 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VIRGINIA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICK SIGNALS SUCCESS AT VIRGINIA TECH 
</HEADLINE>
 TECH-VICK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKSBURG, Va. _ For years, they had a schedule softer than
pudding. It wasn't so much whom they played, but whom they didn't
play. The Hokies' opponents each week were teams from the
Mid-American Conference and other lightly regarded leagues,
sometimes even Division 1-AA teams. Teams no one would notice even
if someone were looking.
</P>
<P>
   Then, under the steady guidance of Frank Beamer, Virginia Tech's
schedule got better, and so did the program: from a 2-8-1 record in
1992 to 64-20 ever since. The Hokies have become one of the Big
East elite, better than Miami, better than Syracuse, better than
anyone else in a league that as a whole has fought for respect
beyond the boost Miami brought with it from its glory days of the
mid '80s to early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Tech climbed almost to the summit, charging through
the regular season unbeaten to earn a spot in the national
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   The critics still disrespected them, claiming that a perennial
power such as Nebraska or Tennessee was more deserving of being
matched against Florida State in the Sugar Bowl for the national
title.
</P>
<P>
   But something was different this time. Tech no longer needed to
make excuses to anyone, because the Hokies had a quarterback who
could make them, on any given Saturday, the equal of anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Vick has made Virginia Tech a legitimate national
contender. In fact, in last January's national championship game,
Vick brought Tech within reach of Florida State. Vick has made the
Hokies a force.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, Vick was scheduled to begin what some believe
will be his final season at Virginia Tech, despite the fact that,
in terms of eligibility, he is just a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. That is a matter to be decided down the road. For
now, the focus for Tech was on beginning a new season in the
relatively bright spotlight of a nationally televised game against
Georgia Tech in the Black Coaches Association Classic. However, a
lightning storm forced postponement of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Vick is what makes Tech special. Under normal circumstances, a
team would take a big hit by losing the heart of a defensive unit
that led the country in scoring defense and was third in total
defense. Losing marquee players such as defensive ends Corey Moore
and John Engelberger would hurt any team.
</P>
<P>
   And the Hokies do feel the losses. Even in reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the perception of Virginia Tech going into the season.
Miami once again is on top of the Hokies in the national rankings,
despite the fact that the Hurricanes have lost to them the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
   But the 'Canes don't have a Michael Vick.
</P>
<P>
   No one does, which is why you can't count out Virginia Tech.
Just as you can't get much of an argument when you start talking
about Heisman Trophy favorites and Vick's name at the top of your
list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is something else, isn't he?'' said Beamer, managing to
smile and shrug at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not easy being so special. The glare of the spotlight
has toughened Vick and, to some extent, wearied him.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas a year ago no one had heard of him, everyone wants a
piece of Vick now. The questions are endless, the demands on his
time neverending. He is no longer just a kid. ``I stopped being a
regular student when I became the starting quarterback,'' he said.
``I stopped being a regular person when we got to the Sugar Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   It used to be casual at Virginia Tech, not just for Vick but for
those who follow him. You wanted to talk to Michael Vick, you
simply tracked him down on campus. Now everything is organized. His
time is partitioned. Windows of opportunity are rarer and rarer as
the Virginia Tech people try and build some fenses around their
star player.
</P>
<P>
   Prime-time status has rubbed off on the Hokies as a whole. No,
they don't get the automatic respect that a Florida State or a
Nebraska does, year after year. But they are making progress. Take
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's game, for example. The Hokies wanted to play in a
preseason game, but no one wanted to play them. They searched and
searched and heard ``No, thank you'' from teams in the Pacific 10,
Big Ten, and Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Georgia Tech, coached by Beamer's friend George
O'Leary, said, ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets are in a year of transition. No one expects
them to be much of a factor in their own league, much less
nationally, in this first season without talented quarterback Joe
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary wanted an early indication of the character of his team,
so he opted for the money and the exposure, knowing full well his
team might take a beating.
</P>
<P>
   For Virginia Tech, the stakes are different. No longer is it the
little program that could. The Hokies are on a new level, and
people are watching closely to see if they fail. That comes with
the territory of being close to the top.
</P>
<P>
   The word around Blacksburg is that Tech will not be as good as
it was last season, but better than many people are predicting.
</P>
<P>
   As for those Miami fans out there, Tech is making it clear that
it is not ready to concede anything.
</P>
<P>
   Not as long as Michael Vick is around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
