   TREES (FLAGSTAFF, ARIZ.)
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has seized upon a Flagstaff-area
fire-danger reduction program as a possible national model for the
country's fire-ravaged forests. But even some locals involved in
the plan say it's not the sweeping success the administration would
like to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The forest-thinning plan is being touted to Congress and the
public as way to make forests more fire resistant - in effect, to
undo 100 years of uninformed forest management, decisions that have
left the nation's forests snarled with underbrush and thick with
diseased trees.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan has critics - even among those instrumental in
designing and implementing it.
