<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3814 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-INDIANS-LA     08-28 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-INDIANS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SET HR RECORD IN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Chuck Finley's name is all over the Angels'
record book, but Sunday he added his name in a way he'd rather not
remember.
</P>
<P>
   Now pitching for the Cleveland Indians, Finley yielded Tim
Salmon's 30th homer of the season in the Angels' 10-9 victory in
front of 31,504 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The homer made the Angels the first team in American League
history to have four players with 30-plus homers in a season. It's
happened six times in the National League _ the Dodgers (1977,
'97), Rockies (1995, '97, '99) and Braves (1998) having achieved
the feat.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon joined Troy Glaus (37), Mo Vaughn (31) and Garret
Anderson (31) to set the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the other three guys got there, I was hearing about
it,'' Salmon said. ``But with a month left in the season, I was
bound to run into one. When I first heard about it, it seemed a
little surprising no other American League team had done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon has been the hottest Angels hitter of late. His past four
homers have come against Pedro Martinez, Roger Clemens, Mike
Stanton and now Finley. In three games against Finley this season,
Salmon is 5 for 8 with three homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no secret,'' Salmon said. ``He's one of those guys you
have to sit back and react to what he throws. I just reacted. You
can't sit back 3-1 and think he's going to throw you a heater. He
might drop in that forkball. Sometimes, against guys like him you
have your best at-bats because you just react instead of guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the postgame talk in the Angels clubhouse focused on the
home runs, but Angels manager Mike Scioscia was quick to emphasize
the Angels' ability to manufacture runs. And they needed every last
one Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels knocked Finley out of the game in a five-run sixth to
take a 10-4 lead. But the Indians rallied against the Angels'
bullpen with five runs _ including a grand slam by Roberto Alomar _
in the top of the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine (3-4) had relieved shaky starter Kent Mercker (3 2/3
innings, 4 runs, 8 hits) and held the Indians in check until tiring
in the seventh. After the Indians knocked around Mike Holtz and
Mark Petkovsek, Shigetoshi Hasegawa entered to start the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa will go back to a set-up role now that Troy Percival is
healthy again, but he went out with a bang, retiring all six
batters he faced to earn his eighth save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also got some big plays from their defense, throwing
out three runners at the plate. Anderson made the biggest throw,
nailing Manny Ramirez trying to score from second on a two-out
single to center by David Segui in the seventh, keeping the Angels'
lead at 10-9.
</P>
<P>
   Long before all the late-inning fireworks by both offenses, the
focus was on the return of Finley, who was making his first start
at Edison Field since he left the Angels to sign a three-year, $27
million contract with the Indians this past winter. It turned out
to be his worst performance of the season.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up eight runs and 11 hits, including home runs to Glaus
and Salmon. Finley went 1-0 with a 2.13 ERA in starts against the
Angels in Cleveland, but was gone after 5 1/3 innings Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored only five runs in two games against Finley in
Cleveland, but finally broke through against him in the third
inning Sunday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
