<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3815 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-AZR &LR;      08-28 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    A DOCTOR WHO TOOK HIS MEDICINE(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS. MOVING IN ``A''
AND ``K'' CATEGORIES)(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E.J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it wasn't me he'd come to visit, I'd hurry to meet Dr.
Owens at the front gate, hoping he'd let me carry his black satchel
into the house.
</P>
<P>
   We lived in one of the small, duplex homes built by the Jones &AMP;
Laughlin company for the immigrants who worked in the steel mill.
Dr. Owens visited patients throughout the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   He was stately and grand as a sorcerer, his leather doctor's bag
like the gripsack of Merlin. Inside it, the bottles and vials
jiggled and bumped into one another as he walked, making music like
muffled bells.
</P>
<P>
   In my memory, it's almost always me Dr. Owens comes to treat.
</P>
<P>
   These were the days before I had my tonsils out, when my throat
would be so inflamed and my fever so high I sometimes saw the face
of Lucifer coming straight at me from across the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to call Dr. Owens,'' my mother would say, growing
calm simply by voicing the old man's name. He was the doctor who'd
delivered my brother and me. He'd helped my mother and father care
for their ailing parents. Something in his demeanor, as much as the
potions in his black bag, brought comfort to the families on our
block.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't describe what his face looked like anymore, but I
remember he had large warm hands, and he wore stiff white shirts
that carried the scent of a man who'd just been to the barber shop.
</P>
<P>
   I've thought a lot about Dr. Owens since reading the series of
stories by (beginitalic)The Arizona Republic's (enditalic)David
Parrish and Jodie Snyder. For a week, their articles have detailed
the failings of many local physicians and the discipline, or lack
of it, they received from the Arizona Board of Medical Examiners.
</P>
<P>
   If Dr. Owens were around today, practicing the kind of hands-on,
deeply personal medicine I remember so well, I have no doubt he
would stand out {hellip} as one of the most potentially dangerous
physicians in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of each visit to our house, Dr. Owens would linger in
the kitchen. He'd chat with my mother about food and make small
talk with my dad about baseball or football. Then he'd have a shot
of whiskey. His ``medicine,'' he called it. In the winter, he'd
sometimes pour the liquor into a cup of coffee. In summer, there
may have been a glass of ice water.
</P>
<P>
   I don't suspect we were always the last stop on Dr. Owens'
rounds. I'm not sure he followed the same social routine at every
house.
</P>
<P>
   I do know he was a soft old man willing to work a tough old
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who would have filed a complaint against him with the
local medical board, or caused him to cease making home visits,
would have had reason to fear for his own health from the people of
Third Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   I've talked about this with friends, who laugh and say standards
were lower in those days.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations were lower. The cost of medical malpractice
insurance was lower. The threat of lawsuits was lower.
</P>
<P>
   But in terms of humanity, standards were very high.
</P>
<P>
   We expect more of doctors, now, I've been told. But just the
opposite is true. We expect them to be scientifically faultless, to
be procedurally flawless, to be perfect as robots. All of which
adds up to something less than human.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Montini at ed.montini(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8978
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
