<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS PLAYING AS IF THEY CAN'T STAND HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE Consider your 50 cents for this newspaper especially
well spent this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Contained herein is the solution for the Mariners' woes, which
after the slow-drip 2-1 defeat to the White Sox Sunday officially
have worn out the term ``slump'' and are being fitted for
``debacle'' on the way toward ``collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it advocates what is anathema in sports, the solution is
not one offered by anyone in the clubhouse. But in the absence of
any other plausible theory on how a good team can go so bad so
suddenly for so long, we offer this suggestion in the spirit of
adding to the chaos:
</P>
<P>
   Just lose, baby.
</P>
<P>
   The division lead, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Mariners pulled ahead in the American League West
by seven games, they have acted as if they were the bewildered
first possessors of the Old Testament. They are staggering around
under its responsibility, playing as if a bobble or bungle will
plunge civilization back to the dark days when rocks were the
favored item of worship.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a team that plays well from ahead. The franchise has
virtually no history in the activity.
</P>
<P>
   None of the dogs that were allegedly let out earlier this month
was an overdog. Despite the fancy new doghouse, these guys are
underdogs. They know about seven-game leads what New Guinea
tribesmen know about microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   The lead has been enormously troublesome. They desperately need
to get behind, only the Oakland A's won't cooperate. The Mariners,
losers of 12 of their last 14, have been free-falling for a couple
of weeks, only to look over and see the A's, losers of 14 of 21,
burning up on re-entry themselves.
</P>
<P>
   If this continues, the Anaheim Angels will win the division, and
no one interested in the preservation of the American way of life
wants to see that.
</P>
<P>
   Were the Mariners to fall behind, they could finally relax. The
milk would be on floor, and the time for laments would end and the
mopping could begin.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as they stay ahead, the sort of agonized flailing
visible this weekend seems destined to continue.
</P>
<P>
   While pitching deservedly has been the biggest source of the
collective hand-wringing, the three games against the team with the
AL's best record showed marked improvement on the mound. Also
better was the previously wretched defense.
</P>
<P>
   What has not improved is hitting, especially clutch hitting.
Lost in the body count during double-digit opponent run totals is
the fact that four of the 12 defeats were by a single run,
including Sunday, when the Mariners were stymied by someone named
Sean Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   A late replacement for Sox ace James Baldwin, the obscure middle
reliever had won seven games over parts of four major league
seasons before the Mariners hitters reincarnated him as the second
coming of Cy Young.
</P>
<P>
   This guy should have been a piata for the Mariners, and instead
Lowe and relievers Lorenzo Barcelo and Keith Foulke shut them down
on four crummy hits.
</P>
<P>
   The same futility was obvious Friday, when the Mariners lost 4-1
despite loading the bases in the ninth inning for the heart of the
order. All three outs in the inning were K's, including the first
out by Edgar Martinez that had what may have been his career-worst
cut on a third strike.
</P>
<P>
   To borrow a phrase from the pro golf tour, Martinez's swing
resembled an octopus falling out of a tree. He was trying so hard
he practically torqued himself out of his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's happened to me a few times too,'' admitted Alex
Rodriguez, who joined Martinez as the final two outs Sunday _ both
whiffs. Each player has the capacity for a one-swing game
resolution, but they are so desperate to make something happen that
they are hacking like adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to hit the ball over the stadium,'' Rodriguez said.
``When things don't go well, you think you have to hit the home
run. You're trying to give the team a lift. But it's a combination
of everybody trying to do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Mariners, the lack of clutch hitting isn't
a recent phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday added a modest three to the only offensive category in
which the Mariners lead the major leagues {ndash4/5 runners left on
base. Over the weekend, they became the first team to strand 1,000
runners this season. It will be several more games before another
team crosses that frontier of futility.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they were playing well, the Mariners weren't very good
in the clutch-hit department. After GM Pat Gillick failed to come
up with a big bat before the trading deadline, many fans were
seduced by the early August success into believing that more
offense wasn't necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that while the pitching and fielding had been good
and are showing signs of recovery, hitting this season has always
been mediocre and gained little with the trading-deadline addition
of Al Martin (.259 with two homers and seven RBIs in 20 Mariners
games).
</P>
<P>
   Now, even the good hitters, drunk on desperation, have become
choppers.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Lou Piniella: Anybody pressing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressing? No, I don't think that's the problem,'' the Mariners
manager said. ``Outside of our young third baseman (Carlos
Guillen), we have a veteran ballclub out there.''
</P>
<P>
   After 12 losses in 14 games, it's apparent that even the vets
are getting squirrelly. They know that a slump is no longer the
proper word. Pressing is exactly what they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only way to stop the pressing is by stopping the
leading. The Yankees, in town for three games starting Monday
night, are, as defending champions, uniquely qualified to help get
the Mariners back where they can handle things.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3818 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      08-28 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS CAN'T FIND RALLY CAPS; CHICAGO WINS WITH TWO SWINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Zero. It's the biggest number.
</P>
<P>
   Zero. It's the number of times the Mariners have won a game when
trailing after the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday it happened again. For the 49th time. Down 2-1 in the
ninth inning to Chicago, the Mariners went nowhere and lost 2-1 to
the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   You can't blame it all on one inning, mind you. The Mariners
went nowhere for much of the day in losing for the 12th time in 14
games. The White Sox threw their closer at the Mariners in the
ninth, and Keith Foulke was up to the challenge, getting Raul
Ibanez to pop up and Alex Rodriguez and Edgar Martinez to strike
out.
</P>
<P>
   No team wins much in the ninth. The White Sox, for example, lead
the American League in wins with 77 and have won just four times
when trailing after eight. But at least the White Sox have done the
deed. The Mariners haven't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little surprising to hear that,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting coach Gerald Perry said that, and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely haven't had many big hits late (in the game)
this year,'' Perry said. ``I can't put my finger on why that is.
We've got good clutch hitters. I wish I could say.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have gotten this one would have been nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 49 were simply unwinnable, like the 19-3 loss the
Sox handed the Mariners on Aug. 9. No team can be expected to come
back from 16 runs down with only three outs left.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game was winnable. Difficult, but winnable. But Foulke
threw strikes, and the Mariners never got the ball out of the
infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never going to win many of these games in the ninth,''
manager Lou Piniella said. ``The other team has its best pitcher in
there. You never want to face the White Sox trailing in the ninth
inning. Or the Yankees (who come into town Monday night). Good
teams put games like those away.''
</P>
<P>
   So what can the Mariners do? Simple. They have to score more
runs early. And they could start by getting more than four hits in
a game.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the second time in three days the Mariners finished
the day with just four hits. That's a disturbing trend, given that
the starting pitching seems to have turned a corner. The Mariners
starters threw 21 full innings in the three games this weekend
against Chicago, and the White Sox scored in just three of those.
</P>
<P>
   But with the offense still in shackles, the Mariners remain
enslaved to the thought of getting help from the rest of baseball.
The M's still have a 2{-game lead over Oakland in the AL West
despite winning just twice in the last two weeks. That says more
about the slumping A's than it does about the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Yankees, who took two of three from the A's this
weekend, arrive for a three-game Safeco Field set. They've got one
of the best closers in the game in Mariano Rivera. Seattle has to
find a way to neutralize him. Jumping out early would be good.
</P>
<P>
   The only trouble is, Monday night's starter is Roger Clemens,
and The Rocket is a handful for anybody. If you're not already in a
slump, he can put you there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys we've faced lately have been pitching like they were
Clemens,'' Rodriguez said, breaking into a grin. ``It's always a
challenge to face him.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's starter Sunday, Sean Lowe, isn't Clemens. You wouldn't
have known that from watching the Mariners, however. Seattle got
one run in the fifth inning when Mike Cameron singled, stole second
and scored on Mark McLemore's single.
</P>
<P>
   That tied the game at 1-all. Instead of that being a starting
place, however, it was the end. Seattle didn't get another
baserunner. And that meant that Freddy Garcia's first eight-inning
start of the year would go for naught.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Konerko homered off Garcia in the second inning and Ray
Durham went deep in the eighth. Two pitches. Two runs. Too much for
the Mariners to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``What some people don't realize is that we're not a
powerhouse,'' Piniella said. ``We're a respectable club that when
all goes right and we play well, we'll win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, not much is going right _ a botched call by third
base umpire Tony Randazzo might have cost the Mariners a run and a
possible big inning in the third. And the Mariners aren't playing
great. The last three games have seen the M's play better than in
the first 11 games of the slump. But the A-game _ the one that
produced a seven-game lead in the West just two weeks ago, is still
on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a funk right now,'' Cameron said. ``I don't think
we're going to fall, though. If we come through this, we'll come
out in shining armor.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have doubted us now that we're in this little
slide. But no one in this clubhouse doubts us. (The division title)
is laid out for us. We've just got to find the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Score early. Score often. Those are good keys.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com.
</P>
