<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HEADLONG &LR; , by Michael Frayn. (Picador USA, $14.) The author
uses his skills as a playwright to create a fast-moving internal
novel about a philosopher named Martin who stumbles onto what he
suspects to be an unknown Bruegel masterpiece in the home of a
country gentleman. With dollar signs in his eyes, Martin plays
scholarly detective to uncover the painting's provenance, hiding
his scheme from his wife and gambling his career and marriage. In
this ``rueful and amusing'' tale, which was chosen by the editors
of the Book Review as one of the best books of 1999, ``the big
action is Martin turning a page _ movingly, comically,
delightfully,'' Randy Cohen wrote here.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DREAMING WITH HIS EYES OPEN: A Life of Diego Rivera &LR; , by
Patrick Marnham. (University of California, $18.95.) The great
Mexican muralist is portrayed as an amoral chameleon who managed to
befriend capitalists like the Rockefellers while attacking them in
his Marxist-flavored art. Last year our reviewer, Michael
Kimmelman, called this an ``urbane and entertaining biography.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LEPER'S COMPANIONS &LR; , by Julia Blackburn. (Vintage
International, $12.) In this novel, a bereaved Englishwoman
retreats internally from the modern day into her same village in
the year 1410, where she takes up with a band of pilgrims headed
for the Holy Land. In 1999 in these pages, Bruce Bawer praised the
book's ``hypnotic vision of the world's horror and beauty, banality
and sacredness _ and of the frailty and splendor of the human
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 'TIS: A Memoir &LR; , by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $14.) The author picks up his life story where ``Angela's
Ashes'' left off, describing his journey from Ireland to New York
at the age of 19 and his fitful development as son, lover, husband,
writer and teacher. His ``narrative gift'' and ``spirited
intelligence'' inform this ``exploration of the elusive American
dream,'' Maureen Howard wrote here in 1999. `` 'Tis a success
story.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE GREAT SHAME: And the Triumph of the Irish in the
English-Speaking World &LR; , by Thomas Keneally (Anchor, $18), the
author of ``Schindler's List'' tells the story of the Irish
diaspora in the 19th century, especially the thousands of men and
women sent in chains to penal colonies in Australia, among them a
core of political prisoners who continued to fight for an
independent Ireland. The result is ``an epic tale of courage and
ingenuity,'' Jay P. Dolan said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DONA INES VS. OBLIVION &LR; , by Ana Teresa Torres. (Grove, $13.)
Speaking to a variety of people, both living and dead, this novel's
narrator tells how her cloistered life as matriarch of a wealthy
Caracas family slipped into chaos and tragedy. ``Dona Ines' cranky,
engaging, importuning, resentful, obsessed and relentless voice
guides us through a family history that is also mired in Venezuelan
history,'' John Vernon wrote here in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEMINGWAY: The Final Years &LR; , by Michael Reynolds. (Norton,
$15.95.) In the final volume of his five-part life of Ernest
Hemingway, the author, who died last month at the age of 63,
describes the writer's experiences during World War II, his rocky
relationship with his fourth wife, Mary Welsh, and his dependency
on alcohol and prescription drugs. Last year in these pages, James
Wood called this an ``excellent and exhaustive biography.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WAY PEOPLE RUN: Stories &LR; , by Christopher Tilghman. (Picador
USA, $12.) Many of the lonely, middle-aged protagonists in these
tales continue to feel the afterburn of sibling spites and other
family hurts, yet are unable to match the intensity of their
childhood experiences. ``Tilghman has a deft, Cheeveresque way of
lending risky undertones to the rituals of suburban life,'' Rand
Richards Cooper wrote in the Book Review last year. ``These are
long stories'' that ``read almost like miniature novels.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CELEBRATION, U.S.A.: Living in Disney's Brave New Town &LR; , by
Douglas Frantz and Catherine Collins. (Owl/Holt, $15.) A
correspondent for The New York Times and his wife (also a
journalist) describe the mixed blessings of living with their two
youngest children in Disney's micromanaged Norman Rockwell
fantasyland in central Florida. Their account ``reflects a
scrupulously maintained reportorial balance,'' David L. Kirp wrote
here in 1999. ``Its tales of family life ring true because they are
drawn directly from the authors' own experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ELUSIVE EMBRACE: Desire and the Riddle of Identity &LR; , by
Daniel Mendelsohn. (Vintage, $12.) A classical scholar explores his
family's complex history and the landscape of gay and heterosexual
desire. ``This charming apercu-filled memoir is ... a personal myth
about undoing family myths,'' Jonathan Lear wrote here in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
