<HEADER>
A3854 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN30-COX     08-28 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bush pitching tax cuts to indifferent electorate
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taxes. How we love 'em!
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not exactly love them, but the inability of
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush to animate the
electorate with his plans for whopping tax cuts suggests we're not
all that angry about them, either, despite years of hysterical
tutoring by talk-radio alarmists, anarchy-lite libertarians,
supply-siders and, of course, Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   It has become an article of GOP faith that taxes are too high
and, cut, would still be too high. With the Cold War won and
anti-communist dramatics thus moot, the party increasingly has
leaned on its animus toward taxation for a defining issue.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Republican candidates is that beyond the circle
of party faithful, proposals for broad tax cuts play to an
electorate vacillating between indifference and antagonism to the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Polls typically rank taxation as somewhere in the second tier of
voter concerns, and usually toward the bottom of that second tier.
Twice in recent years the congressional GOP leadership has pushed
broad tax cuts only to find the grassroots so unmoved the pitches
flopped even with Congress's Republican majorities.
</P>
<P>
   To create issues for the election, those majorities did pull
themselves together this year to repeal the estate tax -- newly
renamed, for political purposes, the death tax _ and to fix,
supposedly, the so-called marriage penalty. President Clinton
casually swatted both aside with veto messages that pointed out the
estate tax repeal was mainly a giveaway to the rich and the
marriage-penalty fix showered unwarranted benefits on couples who
actually benefit from the current code.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bush is promising to push both again as president and, on
top of that, proposes a general tax cut of $1.6 trillion over 10
years. (Actually a $1.9 trillion cut, figuring in the additional
interest the government would have to pay.)
</P>
<P>
   All of this plays off projected federal budget surpluses that
are about half speculative at best and dependent upon a level of
budget discipline that has escaped both parties even in bad times.
(Democratic candidate Al Gore is proposing $500 billion in cuts and
tax favors that are targeted to middle income earners, which may
make them more socially responsible but still nearly half as bad
economically.)
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Bush pitches his cuts as a way to excite economic growth
-- which is exactly what we don't need more of right now. That
would push economic expansion beyond the productivity increases
that hold inflation in check. The all but sure result would be a
Federal Reserve slapping inflation down with high interest rates
that would wipe out much of the pocketbook gain.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will be time to discuss big cut taxes after we pay down
the national debt, nail down Social Security and Medicare and
perhaps even shake off the Reaganist government-is-bad-for-you
trance that has left us without, for just one instance, enough
safety inspectors to keep killer tires off the market.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 0948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
