<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3862 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN30-CO     08-28 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Lieberman overplays the religion hand
 &HT;    For release Aug. 30, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I admit to some manner of exhilaration at Al Gore's landmark
decision to have Joe Lieberman as his running mate. Nevertheless, I
have worried about Lieberman since his Bible-quoting first
appearance alongside Gore in Nashville earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Already, I am playing with words. If a Christian candidate was
quoting from the Bible during a political appearance, I would call
it Bible thumping; more of a pejorative expression. Why give
Lieberman a break because he's from the same religion as am I?
Lieberman is a Bible thumper. There, I've said it!
</P>
<P>
   We're not exactly brothers, more like cousins. He's Orthodox,
I'm Reform. The Orthodox types like to say that us Reforms are more
assimilated into American society than are they. That's code for
meaning that they believe we don't put as much stock in our faith
as do they, and that we've acquiesced to a Christian-dominated
society.
</P>
<P>
   I quarrel with that. Our differences are in style, not in
belief.
</P>
<P>
   But I digress. Lieberman, a man whose devoutness to faith I
respect and admire, has brought religion firmly into the
presidential campaign. It is rare that a political candidate for
high office has not expressed his faith in the Almighty, but he's
done it as a personal gesture. Lieberman is making a crusade of it.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the vice presidential candidate told a congregation
at a Detroit church that religion needs to return more to public
life. You can take that several ways, but I fear that Lieberman is
sending a message for religion to intermix with politics and
government. If he's not sending that message, then his delivery is
being misinterpreted by many, including Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following Lieberman's Nashville quotations from the
Book of Chronicles, I spoke with several (Jewish) friends who were
stunned by Lieberman's speech. We agreed that if such a delivery
had come from the mouth of a Christian candidate, we would be
alarmed; we would be using terms like the Christian Right _ also
pejorative, if you're not a member of the Christian Right.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was a one-time thing, some of us rationalized. Maybe
Joe got caught up in the excitement of the moment in being the
first Jew on a national ticket. His advisers will calm him down, we
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But he was at it again in Detroit last weekend. ``I stand before
you today as a witness to the goodness of God,'' he told his
audience amid his calls to rededicate the United States ``to God
and to God's purposes.'' (As a Jew, expressions such as this always
have bothered me, as God's role in the Holocaust continues to
puzzle and haunt me.)
</P>
<P>
   I know where Joe's coming from. He's looking to put America back
on a higher moral ground (and getting all those votes from others
who want America on a higher moral ground.) And that's all right.
We can use it.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a fine line in this separation of church and
state issue with which we have to deal. Like most Americans, I'm
not certain where that line is drawn but I worry that Lieberman, by
his constant reference to Biblical citations and blessings to God,
is straddling that line quite precariously.
</P>
<P>
   I do, however, find a difference in what Lieberman is doing and
what the Christian Right represents. Lieberman is calling for a
return to faith and moral high ground, no matter your religion _
and even tolerates those who have no religion. The Christian Right
would like to impose its religious beliefs on all of us.
</P>
<P>
   This is a difference with a distinction, but it is unsettling
nevertheless. There can be a campaign of regaining that undefinable
moral ground without testing the precarious waters of separation of
church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Religion is an extremely personal circumstance. It is not
campaign material. In 1960, in answer to inane concerns that he
would be a tool of Rome, John Kennedy did his best to separate his
Roman Catholicism from his political career.
</P>
<P>
   While presidential (and vice presidential) candidates always
have adhered to their religious beliefs, have shown up in church on
Sundays and have been advocates of morality (well, at least they
said they were), they have not worn religion on their sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, Joe Lieberman does. It troubles me.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
