<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-ID-FRAUD-2TAKES     08-28 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-ID-FRAUD-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB CREATING AN ERA OF IDENTITY THEFT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Includes tips text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It couldn't possibly be happening again,'' Jerry Coleman
remembers thinking in October 1998, when his credit card was
rejected over a $38 dinner of lamb kabobs. ``Not to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman is an assistant district attorney in San Francisco. He
has prosecuted dozens of identity-theft cases, and he teaches a
course on fraud and forgery at nearby San Jose State University. He
even travels around the country training police officers and fellow
prosecutors about identity theft.
</P>
<P>
   But Coleman's track record is not so good when it comes to
protecting his own identity.
</P>
<P>
   After that 1998 dinner, he discovered someone had gone on a
weeklong, $25,000 spree with his card _ more than the credit limit
theoretically allowed. Worse, it was the third time in 18 months
that someone had assumed Coleman's identity to rack up thousands of
dollars in bogus charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you travel as much as I do, you're at high risk and
there's not always much you can do to prevent it,'' he said this
week. ``That's why identity theft has become, quietly perhaps, the
most common white-collar crime in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so quietly, perhaps. Identity theft, in fact, is fast
becoming a bogeyman lurking in the shadows of mainstream America.
And while identity thieves are still often low-tech con artists,
the rise in cases, say experts, has roughly paralleled the
proliferation of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Low-tech or high-tech, identity theft occurs when a criminal
uses another person's Social Security number, date of birth, or
other identifying information to apply for credit. The victim,
whose name the resulting debt is in, is left to deal with the
fallout _ usually after the thief disappears.
</P>
<P>
   A phone poll done by New Hampshire-based Image Data LLC last
September found that 21 percent of American adults said they or a
member of their family have been a victim of identity theft. Of
those, 96 percent said the resulting problems were ``serious'' or
``very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers have beseiged authorities with complaints in recent
years about phony credit-card and cell-phone accounts, misused
Social Security numbers, and all kinds of fraudulent loans taken
out in their names. State and federal legislators have responded
with new laws and stiffer penalties, and a trio of government
summit meetings on identity theft are scheduled for this fall in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Identity theft isn't a violent crime in the traditional sense,
but it's a highly invasive crime,'' said Bruce Townsend, director
of the financial crimes division of the Secret Service. ``Victims
show the same kind of (psychological) signs as those who have been
through violent crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In the nine months since the Federal Trade Commission created a
toll-free hotline specifically to deal with such cases, it has
received more than 23,000 calls. The rate at which the calls come
in has almost doubled since the beginning of summer, to 1,000 a
week _ 60 percent filing complaints, 40 percent seeking
information.
</P>
<P>
   Many, if not most, cases still result from old-fashioned
chicanery, such as intercepting mail, digging through the trash,
stealing a wallet, or conning someone into giving personal
information over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an Internet crime and never was,'' said US
Inspector General James Huse, the man responsible for policing
illegal use of Social Security numbers. ``But technology has
created new ways of storing and selling personal information . . .
(and) it's likely to create more and more headaches in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Mari Frank still doesn't know how whether her imposter used
technology to hijack her name four years ago, or whether she went
the old-fashioned route. A lawyer in Laguna Niguel, Calif., Frank
was alerted that she had a problem when a bank called asking about
an unpaid $11,000 bill on a credit-card account she hadn't opened.
</P>
<P>
   When police raided her namesake's apartment, they found a
variety of bills in Frank's name, checks, and a driver's license
with her name but the imposter's face and address, and even a stack
of Frank's business cards. All told, the woman had accumulated
almost $50,000 in spurious debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still amazed that she had driven four hours to steal
business cards from my office,'' said Frank, who has written a book
on her experience and who now represents other identity theft
victims in court. ``I can't explain how violated I felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank has plenty of company. Among the notable victims of
identity theft in recent years are FTC chairman Robert Pitofsky, US
Senator Dianne Feinstein, and dozens of high-ranking military
officers who were up for promotions at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, the names aren't as well known, but some of the cases
are just as startling.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Dana-Farber Cancer Institute sent letters to 12,000
patients earlier this month, alerting them that a part-time
employee may have stolen their records and used them for no good.
And last month, a 29-year-old Natick, Mass. woman pretended she was
going into labor to escape from police custody after being arrested
on more than 50 outstanding warrants for identity theft.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, police dubbed Woburn, Mass. resident Kerrin Alfonso
``the queen of identity fraud'' after she allegedly assumed the
identities of co-workers, friends, a former roommate, and her
beautician in a $300,000 spending orgy. Among her purchases were a
matching set of $50,000 Lexuses and a $35,000 Toyota Avalon, a down
payment on a house, and a vacation to Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Most cases are smaller, typically involving thieves who take on
the identity of someone else, quickly charge a few thousand
dollars, and then drop the ruse and disappear before the victim
catches on.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how much money is involved, it can be devastating
for the victim,'' said Massachusetts Attorney General Tom Reilly.
``They'll be fighting an uphill battle to clear their name for
years, maybe forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said his office gets half a dozen complaints a week from
identity theft victims, up from one or two when he took office in
January of last year. Staffers have even created a brochure for
victims, telling them about their rights and what they should do to
clean up their credit histories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Identity fraud is becoming a major issue for us,'' Reilly
said. ``I've been talking with other attorneys general and others
in law enforcement, and everybody is being forced to devote more
resources to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The typical victim takes two years to clean up his or her credit
history, according to a survey by the US Public Interest Research
Group. The average amount of sham charges: $18,000.
</P>
<P>
   Once things are straightened out, victims aren't held
accountable for such illegitimate bills.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, though, many lose their ability to borrow, as
the bad credit caused by identity thieves keeps reappearing under
their names like a trick candle that won't blow out. Occasionally,
thieves accumulate an arrest record in someone else's name, too.
</P>
<P>
   Even Coleman, the San Francisco prosecutor, had a hard time
getting the illicit charges removed from his credit history. Like
all identity theft victims, the burden of proof fell on him to show
that he hadn't made the purchases in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same department stores that overwhelm me with evidence if
they've been robbed couldn't be bothered to look up receipts and
other information I needed to clear my name,'' Coleman said. ``They
just don't care, which makes it a lot harder to clean up your
credit report after something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Until 1998, when Congress made identity theft a federal crime
and 22 states (including Massachusetts) followed suit, victims
often felt snubbed by the police, too. Investigators and credit
bureaus typically viewed lenders as the victims and didn't want to
spend time or money chasing down nonviolent criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 law, though, also required the FTC to establish the
consumer hotline and create a central database of identity theft
statistics. That has helped law enforcement agencies coordinate
multiple investigations and has made it easier for victims to make
their cases to local police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investigators may not have the resources to chase down one
person's $7,000 complaint, but what if they go into our database
and find 20 similar complaints?'' asked Betsy Broder, who heads the
FTC effort. ``Suddenly, it's a much bigger case and it's more
likely they'll find the resources to track it down.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
