<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S DOWNRIGHT COLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not only is vacation over for a lot of us in this melancholy
last week of August, but winter has begun, at least in the stores,
and that makes the whole thing worse.
</P>
<P>
   Boots, sweaters, coats, furry slippers, red gift boxes, and the
absolute psychic crusher _ Christmas ornaments _ are proliferating
in retail land, as though the winds were already howling and the
bathing suits were packed away in the bottom drawer, as though the
holiday shop clock were running, and the populace cared.
</P>
<P>
   The populace does not care. OK, some of the populace cares, but
they are the compulsives, tucking gifts away in the back of the
closet so they can say ``I got it all done early.'' They will say
that right through autumn and deep into December when the rest of
us are fried at the mall. They will say it so often that we will
want to tuck them away in the back of the closet.
</P>
<P>
   The average human being in a post-vacation slump cannot deal
with efficiency or get excited about a gaggle of snowmen on a
string.
</P>
<P>
   The snowman ornaments arrived in the stores in July, along with
the dancing bears, clowns, and gingerbread houses. They glittered
from displays covered in red paper at Hallmark outlets, heralded on
mall marquees shouting: ``The 2000 Ornament Debut!'' Some stores
opened at midnight to let in the crowds, as though Harry Potter
books or Rolling Stones tickets were inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for collectors,'' says Linda Odell, spokesman for
Hallmark headquarters in Kansas City, explaining that the company
releases 200 new ornaments in the summer and another 100 in
October. Yes, before Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   There are 31 million ornament collectors in the United States
and they can't get enough, even though the average human being in a
post-vacation slump might figure there would have to be a limit to
the number of things that can hang from an evergreen branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think multiple trees,'' says Odell. ``Five and six trees in a
house, each with a different theme.''
</P>
<P>
   The image is too much for someone sitting at a desk watching the
tan line fade. One tree is too much, even if it twinkles from the
corner of a gift shop or is supposed to blend with the quilts and
knitted socks at county fairs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockland Lobster Festival held in Maine at the beginning of
August had a twinkling tree and Santa faces in the crafts tent.
They did not blend with the midway noise, the fried dough smell,
and the humid ocean air. It was a bad case of When Worlds Collide,
sending a shiver down a tourist's spine as the season of lists
encroached on the season of bare feet.
</P>
<P>
   That encroachment has been happening since Memorial Day in
catalogs, where holiday candles, pumpkins, back-to-school items,
and fleece are advertised along with beach towels and straw hats.
</P>
<P>
   But a person can toss out a catalog. Reality is something else,
especially when it's unreal.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should all go live in France for a while. Summer is
summer there, and August is the piece de resistance of the season.
A retail executive returning from that country was amazed at the
merchandising mindset along the Seine: ``The stores are full of
summer stuff!''
</P>
<P>
   What a concept _ buying and selling in the present.
</P>
<P>
   In America we can get so far ahead of ourselves that we forget
where we are. ``Somewhere all of Christmas has happened already,''
said the retailer. ``It's on board ships. It's in warehouses. It's
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some of us are spending too much time multitasking in
cyberspace. A person goes out there, talks to six people at once
while taking a conference call with three more, and simultaneously
checks the portfolio. What city are we in again? And what day is
it?
</P>
<P>
   Things happen very fast in the business cycle _ so fast that
someone can think December has come and gone and it's the end of
next August.
</P>
<P>
   The average human being in a post-vacation slump sinks to the
bottom of the well contemplating that one, because it means two
vacations are over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
