<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE DATING SERVICE SENDS YOU SOME DUDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Single women are always lamenting the poor quality of men out
there in the dating pool, but Suzanne thought she had found a way
to weed out the losers.
</P>
<P>
   The New Bedford, Mass. resident, who asked not to be identified,
paid the Successful Singles dating service in Wellesley $1,895 for
six referrals. The company plays matchmaker using a computer that
analyzes customer answers to a lengthy questionnaire on a wide
range of subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary objective is to refer people who are mentally and
emotionally compatible,'' the Successful Singles contract states.
``Minimums and maximums in age, height, weight, etc. are used as
secondary guides, not absolutes.''
</P>
<P>
   In her description of the perfect date, Suzanne told me she
would be interested in someone with similar interests, including
animals (she has two cats), dining out, the theater, and movies.
But she had specific physical requirements as well. She preferred a
man between ages 31 and 40 who was physically fit, tall (between 5
feet 9 and 6 feet 2), with dark eyes, dark hair, and no facial
hair. Because she drives a lot for work, she also was interested in
someone who lives within 40 miles of her.
</P>
<P>
   Her first referral from Successful Singles didn't match several
of her physical preferences and told her he had once had a drinking
problem. She claims he told her that he had also done time in jail.
That didn't suit her taste, so she moved on to the next name.
</P>
<P>
   Her second suitor was 5 feet 4 inches tall, sported a mustache,
and was allergic to cats. Suzanne said bachelor number two also
made a number of inappropriate sexual comments. ``I said I like
animals, not that I wanted to go out with one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After that experience, Suzanne began pressing Successful Singles
for her money back, even though the three-day right of recision had
already passed.
</P>
<P>
   As she discussed her situation with company officials, another
name arrived in the mail, so she decided to give Successful Singles
another try. Bachelor number three had a beard and a mustache and
lived more than 40 miles away, but otherwise she said he was
satisfactory. There just wasn't any personal chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Suzanne said she had had enough. When I pointed
out to her that matchmaking is hardly a science, she acknowledged
it's a crapshoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take your chances no matter what,'' she said. ``But when
you tell them what you want and they don't pay any attention,
that's unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne said the referrals she received didn't meet the
dictionary definition of successful (``having wealth, fame, or
rank''). She was particularly irked at Successful Singles for
sending along someone who had done time in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys were barely making it,'' she said. ``I can meet a
mess in a bar. I didn't need to pay all this money to do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   When Successful Singles refused to refund her money, Suzanne
contacted her credit-card company to dispute her payment. The
credit-card company, noting she signed a contract with only a
three-day right of recision, sided with Successful Singles.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne then filed a complaint with the attorney general's
office that was referred to its consumer assistance council in
Hyannis. The attorney general's office has received four complaints
about Successful Singles this year, and a total of 19 since the
beginning of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer assistance council failed to negotiate a resolution
of Suzanne's complaint. Ronald Cater, the president of Successful
Singles, responded to the complaint by saying Suzanne had been
promised six referrals and had received eight. ``The contract has
been more than fulfilled, therefore there is no refund due,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Cater defended his company's
compatability profiling approach and said Suzanne knew what she was
in for when she signed the contract. He said the company relies on
its customers to be truthful in their answers to survey questions.
</P>
<P>
   Cater said he checked out Suzanne's claim that her first
referral had done jail time and said it was a minor offense, not a
felony conviction, close to a decade ago. Bachelor number one told
me he had been arrested for operating under the influence of
alcohol in 1992 and has been sober ever since.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he had a good time on his date with Suzanne and
thought she was a lot of fun. He said his experience with
Successful Singles was generally positive, although he didn't renew
his membership after receiving his initial referrals. He said it
was too expensive, even though he said he purchased a cheaper
membership than Suzanne's.
</P>
<P>
   Told that Suzanne had paid $1,895 for her referrals, he said:
``Holy crap! I'd be after them too if I paid that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Bachelor number two did not return my phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Cater, after initially downplaying the concerns Suzanne raised,
said he would be happy to extend her membership for another six
months and do the initial screening himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a customer that's unhappy. We want to try to make her
happy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Suzanne said she wants nothing more to do with Successful
Singles. She said careful screening was what she paid the service
for in the first place; she said she didn't want to take a chance
on what they would send her next. She said she contacted me to
alert other consumers to the pitfalls involved with dating
services.
</P>
<P>
   The warning is worth passing on. Dating services work for some
people and not for others, but for obvious reasons few come with
money-back guarantees. Read the fine print carefully and make sure
you're comfortable with how the service works before signing
anything.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL; 
Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --RCN prices rise in New York. Jamie Houde, who lives in
Manhattan and uses RCN for cable TV and high-speed Internet
service, says the company increased his cable TV rate 23 percent
just two months after he signed up. He says his cable bill rose
from $26 a month to $32 a month due to what the company said was a
``significant increase in operating and programming costs.'' An RCN
spokeswoman said the increase was confined to New York and there
are no plans for similar hikes in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   --Prius follow-up. Our report on the problems one consumer had
in tracking down the new hybrid car from Toyota prompted varied
responses from readers. Andrew Garvin of Newton, Mass. said he put
down a $500 deposit for a new Prius in mid-June with Wellesley
Toyota and it's been ``nothing but misinformation, delays, and
confusion since then.'' By contrast, Paul Milner of Sharon, Mass.
said he pulled into Boch Toyota in Norwood last weekend for a
quick, pleasant test drive. Kevin Ford of Somerville, Mass. says
the Prius is too pricey for his economy-car budget and offered this
suggestion: Why doesn't the state rebate all sales and excise taxes
on hybrid cars for the first five years of ownership to encourage
their purchase and their environmental benefits?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
