<HEADLINE>
WELL-FEATHERED NEST AUGURS WELL FOR FUTURE RETIREES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We hope to retire in two to five years, after our children
finish college. We have a home with a $630,000 market value and a
$100,000 mortgage, plus a fully paid country home we will probably
use as our retirement residence. We'd like to have a gross income
of $100,000 to $125,000 in retirement. Are we too conservative or
not conservative enough? Is there a better place to put the money
market holdings? It seems we should be able to obtain our income
while preserving a good part of our assets. To do this, is it
better to draw down the taxable or tax-deferred accounts first?
</P>
<P>
   I.D., Cambridge, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your nest is well-feathered. To achieve a $125,000 income in
retirement, you would need to withdraw at a level representing only
3.67 percent from your total savings. Moreover, you would have an
income stream of $105,632 if you simply withdrew the yield from
your various fixed-income accounts and the dividends from your
common stock, plus the Social Security and pension _ and that is
not factoring in any growth between now and the time you retire. (I
estimated 5 percent returns from the fixed-income holdings, since
most are money market funds; the total might be a bit higher.)
</P>
<P>
   The nice thing is that you have enough savings that you can
afford to take a very conservative investment stance. I would
suggest only two changes, one of which you should be able to make
at once, the other over many years.
</P>
<P>
   The first involves the big question as to whether to continue
holding that huge money market position, now representing more than
38 percent of the portfolio. It seems foolish to me, in view of the
fact that you can currently purchase five-year jumbo CDs with rates
as high as 7.81 percent, entering last week. If you invested all of
your money market funds at this rate (although I would not
recommend that CD investments at any one institution exceed the
level of FDIC insurance) it would represent a difference of $19,341
in annual income, presuming you are averaging 5 percent on the
money market funds.
</P>
<P>
   (In normal times, I would suggest a good GNMA fund for such a
position in the portfolio, but it seems the current fixed-income
market favors CDs. The Vanguard GNMA fund has a current yield of
6.85 percent, and a 7.67 percent 10-year total return. With the
prospect of interest-rate hikes ahead and a yield trailing that of
long-term CDs, this isn't the time to go with the GNMA, or any bond
fund, for that matter. It could well be that in five years when
your CDs mature, the relative yields will have returned to more
normal levels, and it would be advantageous to switch tactics.)
</P>
<P>
   The second change I would suggest is to divert whatever
dividends you get from your assorted stock funds to the purchase of
common stock in taxable accounts. This is because you indicate you
are concerned with maintaining a substantial estate for your
children. When it comes to taxes that come due to your heirs, it
doesn't matter what you are holding in your tax-deferred accounts _
they will have to pay. But in the taxable accounts, if they inherit
common stock they will enjoy the benefits of the so-called step-up
rule, which allows them to treat the value of the holding at the
date of the death of the owner as their base cost, and ignore your
base cost. That can make an enormous difference.
</P>
<P>
   You should probably hire either a financial planner or a tax
specialist; your holdings are large. Many tax strategies could make
enormous differences. (For example, my instinct would be to draw
the yields from both taxable and deferred accounts as spelled out
above, so as to reduce the accumulation in the accounts from which
you will be forced to make withdrawals after age 70 1/2. But a tax
expert might suggest a better alternative.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Note to D.B., Palm Harbor, Fla.: Without going into the details
of your situation, I suggest you follow the reasoning about CDs as
detailed in the previous exchange, taking the returns from
five-year jumbos that should easily outpace either the Guaranteed
Investment Contract, a bond fund, or laddered holdings of
individual bonds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently left my employer. While I intend to remain active,
it will largely be through nonincome-producing endeavors. I have
sufficient assets to meet my needs of $6,000 a month without
working. What are the best penson options for me?
</P>
<P>
   G.M., North Andover, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It seems pretty clear that you should wait until age 55
before drawing anything. If you take the lump sum available today,
of $101,181, you would have to earn 14.98 percent average annual
returns to get the $179,980 that would be available if you stayed
in the plan until 55. There would be comparable (and in some cases
much greater) gains if you choose one of the four annuity options.
For example, by waiting four years, the value of your lifetime
annuity payment would go from $596 to $1,386 a month; if you go
with the option at the lowest level, which guarantees the payments
through both your life and your spouse's, the payments would rise
to $1,237 a month, from $551.
</P>
<P>
   Look at what happens if you wait until age 65: If you chose the
lump sum at 65, it would bring you $218,585. That calculates out to
5.51 percent average annual returns over the next 14 years _ quite
far from that calculation of nearly 15 percent over the first four
years. Worse, the growth in the lump-sum account for the years from
age 55 to age 65 comes out to a 1.95 percent average annual return
_ almost certainly not even keeping pace with inflation.
</P>
<P>
   (To me, the numbers make little sense; one hypothesis I have
developed is that while you are 51 your 52nd birthday is probably
drawing nigh. I also considered the chance of a typo here and
there, but rejected it because the value of the other options are
similarly unappetizing if you wait until age 65 to draw on the
plan. The only conclusion I can draw is that the plan is designed
to provide a strong incentive to retire and/or receive benefits at
age 55 and not before, and an equally strong incentive not to wait
until age 65 to retire or take benefits.)
</P>
<P>
   Now that we've established that 55 is the best age to take
benefits, the question arises as to what is the best of the annuity
or lump-sum options. If you took the $1,386 a month lifetime
annuity rather than the $179,980 lump sum, you would need an
investment that would earn 9.25 percent to provide the income
stream without invading principal. (You could argue that the
required earnings level would be lower, because the principal
should be entirely drawn down by the time you die to make a precise
calculation. But given that your age at death is at this point
incalculable, and that you should expect many years of living after
age 55, the differential would likely be very small.)
</P>
<P>
   The basic advantage of a lump sum over an annuity is that the
sum will be available to you, your spouse, or your heirs,
regardless of when you and/or your spouse die. Obviously, the
writer of the annuity is the big winner if one or both of you die
early; if one or both of you live well beyond the average life
expectancy, you win and the writer either loses or makes less money
on the proposition than it anticipated. It's nice to bet on your
own longevity, and that of your spouse, as well. It seems to me
that the variance between the lifetime annuity for yourself _
$1,386 monthly at age 55 _ and the $1,237 that would be payable to
either you or your wife, whoever lived longer, is sufficiently
small to make the 100 percent joint and survivor option the most
attractive annuity.
</P>
<P>
   Which gets us to the bottom line. You mention that you have
savings sufficient to support yourself now, without working. The
question then is whether you have sufficient savings to continue to
do so after age 55, after factoring in the inflation that is likely
to pester you for the balance of your financial life. For a start,
reflect on the fact that it will cost $1.15 by the time you reach
age 55 to buy what $1 does today, and $1.62 a decade later,
provided inflation averages 3.5 percent during those periods.
</P>
<P>
   So my answer is this: If you have sufficient savings to provide
your required income stream for the balance of your reasonable life
expectancy, you can view this as a long-term investment. If you
invest the lump sum in stocks for about 20 years, you should expect
returns in the 10 percent annual range _ it would not only be a bit
higher than what you'd need to replace the income stream from the
annuity, but the money would belong to you or your estate. On the
other hand, if you suspect that at some point this money will
become important in your day-to-day living, it seems to me that the
returns offered from the annuity are generous, relative to most of
these instruments I have analyzed, and I would take the 100 percent
joint and survivor option at age 55.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
