<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3871 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-ID-FRAUD-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     08-28 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-ID-FRAUD-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... it down.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But many, including Massachusetts attorney general Reilly, don't
think Congress has gone far enough. They would like to see even
stiffer penalties for identity thieves, as well as rules to deal
with online information brokers, which compile and sell personal
information on individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to happen on a national level,'' Reilly said. ``These
cases often cross state and even national borders, so
jurisdictional issues make it pretty hard for states to deal with
on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly and the others may soon get their way. Several bills have
been proposed in Congress that would deal with specific aspects of
identity theft, and Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore has
proposed a law that would make it illegal to sell Social Security
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   That became an issue last fall when 21-year-old Liam Yoens shot
former classmate Amy Boyer outside her Nashua office. Yoens was
able to track down Boyer using her Social Security number, which he
bought from a Web site for $45.
</P>
<P>
   ``As information about us is collected and aggregated and sold
on the Internet, where does it end?'' asked Huse, the Inspector
General. ``That's a question that still hasn't been answered.''
</P>
<P>
   How Congress answers it will go a long way toward determining
how easy it is for crooks to use the Internet for the next
generation of identity theft. The trick, experts say, is to limit
illegitimate uses of information without making it too hard for
legitimate businesses online.
</P>
<P>
   While such issues are being debated, the best thing for people
to do is take steps to protect themselves in the offline world (see
box).
</P>
<P>
   ``These people will tear your credit to shreds and then, when it
doesn't do them any good, move on,'' said Robert Bethel, spokesman
for the US Postal Inspection Service, which has seen its identity
theft arrests quadruple in the past three years. ``In cities like
Boston, especially, take the extra step to protect yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
TO PROTECT YOURSELF FROM IDENTITY THEFT:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --DON'T carry your Social Security card or birth certificate in
your wallet. Keep them in a secure place, such as a safe deposit
box.
</P>
<P>
   --GIVE out your Social Security number only when absolutely
necessary. The numbers were created to keep track of your taxable
earnings, not as a universal identifier. Request a different number
for your driver's license. Never give the number (or other
identifying information, such as date of birth or mother's maiden
name) to unsolicited telephone callers or over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   --CHECK your wallet for any cards, such as health insurance
cards, that include your Social Security number. Contact the
service provider and ask to use a different number.
</P>
<P>
   --CARRY only those credit cards you use regularly, and cancel
all unused cards.
</P>
<P>
   --PHOTOCOPY everything you carry in your wallet and keep copies
in a safe place, such as a safe deposit box. Also include a list of
bank and investment accounts in your name. Update the file
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   --LOOK closely at all credit card and bank statements each month
for any unusual activity or unauthorized charges. Also be on the
lookout for any bills that don't arrive on schedule, which could be
a sign an identity thief has changed the address on your account.
</P>
<P>
   --SHRED or destroy all pre-approved credit-card solicitations.
To reduce the number of solicitations you receive, call
888-567-8688 and ask to be removed from the marketing lists of the
major credit bureaus. The request is valid for only two years and
it won't stop every solicitation, but it will dramatically reduce
the volume of unwanted offers.
</P>
<P>
   --DESTROY or shred all documents containing personal information
rather than trashing them whole. Put the ones you keep in a safe
place.
</P>
<P>
   --ORDER and review copies of your credit report from each
national credit reporting agency at least once a year.
Massachusetts residents are entitled to a free copy from each
agency anually. Contact information: Equifax, 800-685-1111;
Experian, 800-682-7654; Trans Union, 800-916-8800.
</P>
<P>
   --DON'T use your birthday or other easily guessed information as
a password or personal identification number, or PIN. Make sure the
PINs you use can't be seen by anyone while you're using an ATM or
public phone.
</P>
<P>
   --CALL the local post office or postal inspector if you suspect
your mail is being stolen or tampered with. Drop off bill payments
only at a post office or in secure boxes on the street. Stealing
them in transit is a goldmine for thieves.
</P>
<P>
   --PICK UP new checks at the bank, if possible, rather than
having them mailed to your home.
</P>
<P>
   --BE CAREFUL about sending personal information over the
Internet. Send PINs, credit card numbers, or other important
information only over encrypted systems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU THINK YOU MIGHT ALREADY BE A VICTIM:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --FILE a report with local police and keep a copy for your
records.
</P>
<P>
   --KEEP a record of all efforts you make to correct your credit
history, including the measure you took, to whom you spoke or
wrote, and the date and time of your call or letter. Send all
letters certified mail and keep copies.
</P>
<P>
   --DON'T pay any bill or charge that resulted from identity
theft.
</P>
<P>
   --CALL your bank and creditors immediately. Close your checking
account and request new bank account numbers and ATM cards. Cancel
all credit cards and request that new accounts be opened with new
account numbers. Follow up in writing and ask that the accounts be
closed ``at the customer's request.''
</P>
<P>
   --CONTACT the credit reporting agencies right away and request a
``security alert'' be placed on your accounts. Again, follow up
with a written letter. Contact information for the agencies'
fraud-investigation units: Equifax, 800-270-3435; Experian,
888-397-3742; Trans Union, 800-680-7289. At the same time, request
and carefully review copies of your credit reports, looking for
other bogus accounts or loans.
</P>
<P>
   --INFORM the post office in writing that you are a victim of
identity theft and that change-of-address request forms submitted
on your behalf should not be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   --REQUEST a new driver's license with an alternate number from
the Registry of Motor Vehicles. Also, ask that your old number be
flagged so the police will know if anybody attempts to pass it off
as valid.
</P>
<P>
   --CALL the Social Security Administration's fraud hotline at
800-269-0271 and advise it of your situation. As a last resort, ask
about getting a new number issued, while flagging your old one for
fraudulent use.
</P>
<P>
   --CONTACT the Federal Trade Commission's identity theft hotline
at 877-438-4338. Counselors there can give you advice about
cleaning up your credit history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SOURCE: Federal Bureau of Investigation, Federal Trade Commission,
Massachusetts Office of the Attorney General
</P>
</TEXT>
