<HEADLINE>
$ADV30 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release: Wednesday, Aug. 30, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you stand one more reality show? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopkins 24/7,'' a limited series debuting tonight at 10 on
ABC, is an honest-to-goodness _ and ABC would probably prefer we
whisper this word _ documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The producers spent three months in Baltimore's Johns Hopkins
hospital, recording all the life, death and occasional humor that
went on there with hand-held digital cameras. Then they cut it down
to six hours _ airing tonight, tomorrow and the next four
Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   This is ``ER'' territory, bouncing from the tragic (a girl with
uterine cancer) to the bizarre (a sick sea turtle), but generally
without the soap opera. You have to feel for the patients here _
and maybe more so because of the camera's presence.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: Just about everyone in the house got
nominated for banishment last week, and tonight somebody goes. Both
of you who still care, feel free to tune in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear God,'' CBS at 9: Garry Marshall directed this mild 1996
PG comedy, starring Greg Kinnear and Laurie Metcalf, about a
postman who answers a letter to God and starts a chain of good
deeds. Jon Seda and Donal Logue are in the cast, as well as Tim
Conway and Anna Maria Horsford.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Wing,'' NBC at 9: Somehow, these people make drama out of
the school-vouchers issue. Even Bush and Gore can't do that! Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew Carey Show,'' ABC at 9: Mr. Wick causes Drew problems at
the store. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order,'' NBC at 10: Guest star Robert Clohessy _ you'll
recognize his face if not his name _ turns in a strong performance
as one of those bad dads who've been in the news so much in recent
years. His son is the suspect in a 16-year-old's murder, but it's
Dad who provided the weapon and perhaps the attitude. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Open Tennis update, CBS at 12:35 a.m. From Flushing, N.Y.
(USA cable covers the matches beginning at 7:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
