<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3925 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-STRANGE-WILL-BOS &LR;      08-28 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRANGE-WILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGER'S BEQUESTS INCLUDE GONZALEZES, AMIRAULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Okla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT S. GREENBERGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anne Katherine Abernathy of Shawnee, Okla., never met the
Amiraults of Massachusetts or the Gonzalezes of Miami. But as she
prepared to take her own life, Abernathy scribbled a four-page will
disinheriting her own relatives and leaving her $500,000 estate to
two families she apparently viewed as victims of government power.
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy, 57, shot herself in the chest five weeks ago, just
hours after her mother died of natural causes in the large Shawnee
home they shared.
</P>
<P>
   Before she picked up the family's .22 Magnum, Abernathy picked
up a pen. Unmarried and childless, she rewrote her will to leave
her property to the Amiraults, who were accused of molesting
children at their Malden day-care center in the mid-1980s, and the
Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez, whose refusal to turn over the
Cuban boy to federal authorities prompted a government raid in
April to seize him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give away freedom for power is hollow and tragic,''
Abernathy wrote, referring to the stories of both families. ``May
God, such as He is, bless and care for America _ what's left of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy's relatives, who say she has been mentally
incapacitated for years, are challenging the will. A judge was to
review the case at a hearing Monday in Shawnee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a painful, sad, and difficult situation,'' cousin
Robert Abernathy, the main petitioner, told the Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   The Amiraults' attorney, James L. Sultan, has retained an
Oklahoma lawyer to represent the family's interests at that
hearing. Sultan said a will that is in the handwriting of the
deceased and is signed and dated is valid under Oklahoma law. That
would not be true in most other states, including Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My interpretation of this document, which may or may not be
accurate, is that she felt that both the Miami family and the
Amiraults had been victimized by abuses of government power, and
that she felt some kinship to them because of what they had
suffered at hands of official power,'' Sultan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It strikes me as a heartfelt political expression from
somebody who was obviously in tremendous pain.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to leaving her valuable property to the two
families, Abernathy left her notes and photographs to Dorothy
Rabinowitz, a Wall Street Journal columnist who publicized the
Amiraults' story. In her will, Abernathy described the case as a
``scam.''
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy left her dog, Mai Ling, to Oklahoma University
president and former Oklahoma Senator David Boren.
</P>
<P>
   The Amiraults' trial, during which children testified about
talking robots, public torture of animals, and sex abuse, led to a
national debate. Cheryl Amirault LeFave and her mother, Violet
Amirault, were convicted in 1987 and received 20-year prison
sentences, but were freed on appeal in 1995. Violet Amirault died
in 1997. LeFave's brother Gerald Amirault is still in prison but
will appear next month before the state's Advisory Board of
Pardons.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at her Dorchester home, Cheryl LeFave declined to
comment on Abernathy's bequest. But Sultan said the family, which
would probably use the money to help pay the college tuitions of
Gerald's two daughters, is ``incredibly touched and honored.''
</P>
<P>
   Manny Diaz, an attorney representing Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's
great-uncle, told the Miami Herald that the family would not
comment on the Abernathy's will. But he said members are checking
the hundreds of letters they have received to see whether Abernathy
had sent one.
</P>
<P>
   According to an obituary in the Shawnee News-Star, Abernathy
graduated from Shawnee High School and Oklahoma University, where
she was named ``Outstanding Woman Student'' as a senior. She lived
for years in Houston, where she was in the Junior League and the
Daughters of the American Revolution and was active in civic
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   She moved back to Shawnee two years ago to care for her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very artistic person, involved in fine arts and
several museums down there,'' Max Shumacke, pastor of the United
Presbyterian Church of Shawnee, told the Miami Herald. ``She was an
excellent calligrapher and a home decorator. But I don't know if
you'd call that a business. She was just very good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
