</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With LABOR. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANGES IN AMERICAN LIFE
</P>
<P>
   In 1900
</P>
<P>
   Most common jobs: Farm laborer, domestic servant
</P>
<P>
   Average work week: 59 hours
</P>
<P>
   Average annual salary: $375
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment rate: 5.0 percent
</P>
<P>
   Average life expectancy: 47.3 years
</P>
<P>
   Average household size: 4.7 persons
</P>
<P>
   Percentage of women working outside home: 18.3 percent
</P>
<P>
   In 2000
</P>
<P>
   Most common jobs: Office worker, sales worker
</P>
<P>
   Average work week: 43.2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Average annual salary: $23,505
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment rate: 4.0 percent
</P>
<P>
   Average life expectancy: 76.5 years
</P>
<P>
   Average household size: 2.6 persons
</P>
<P>
   Percentage of women working outside home: 63 percent
</P>
<P>
   Sources: American Chronicle, Bureau of Labor Statistics, U.S.
Census, Federal Reserve Bank
</P>
<P>
   FASTEST GROWING OCCUPATIONS
</P>
<P>
   1900 to 1920
</P>
<P>
   (percentage increase in number of jobs)
</P>
<P>
   1) Finance and/or real estate worker, 173 percent
</P>
<P>
   2) Transportation worker, 99.5 percent
</P>
<P>
   3) Factory worker, 82 percent
</P>
<P>
   4) Teacher, 80 percent
</P>
<P>
   5) Coal miner, 70 percent
</P>
<P>
   1998 to 2008
</P>
<P>
   (expected percentage increase in number of jobs)
</P>
<P>
   1) Computer engineer, 108 percent
</P>
<P>
   2) Computer support specialist, 102 percent
</P>
<P>
   3) Systems analyst, 94 percent
</P>
<P>
   4) Database administrator, 77 percent
</P>
<P>
   5) Desktop publishing specialist, 73 percent
</P>
<P>
   Source: U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics
</P>
