<SLUG> BC-LABOR-NCR-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCR'S FOUNDER WAS A PIONEER IN CARING FOR WORKERS
 &HT;    With LABOR. Repeating for all needing in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    By LYNN HULSEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A hundred years ago, an eccentric and visionary
industrialist was setting a pattern for business and labor
practices now in common use.
</P>
<P>
   He was John H. Patterson, a co-founder of National Cash Register
Co. Patterson was famous for impulsive actions, often firing
executives who displeased him. But he also had a paternalistic
interest in workers' welfare.
</P>
<P>
   For many men and women, getting hired on at ``the Cash'' was the
ticket to a lifetime job at the world's largest producer of
mechanical cash registers.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson understood, long before his contemporaries, that a
happy, comfortable worker is a more productive one. He offered
higher wages and a cleaner, safer work environment than the typical
1900-era factory.
</P>
<P>
   Company cafeterias sold hot meals for less than it cost to
provide the food. The well-lit factories had first aid stations,
locker rooms and a ventilation system. Employees were even
permitted two baths a week on company time in company bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The hours were long. Employees typically put in 59 hours per
six-day week in 1902. Weekly wages for a messenger totaled $5 per
week, while a carpenter could expect to take home the handsome sum
of $14.85. By 1917, company records show that Patterson offered
time-and-a-half wages for work exceeding 48 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton businessmen criticized Patterson for paying workers more
than they were worth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, paid vacations were still many years away, but
Patterson would load employees onto trains and take them on an
expenses-paid, out-of-state excursion.
</P>
<P>
   Total employment was 2,269, mostly men engaged in the
manufacture of cash registers at the Dayton headquarters. NCR also
operated far-flung international sales offices that used
Patterson's pioneering sales techniques, including quotas,
territories and regular communication with salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   According to local historian Claudia Watson, Patterson ``would
always say he was selling a system, not a cash register. He would
understand the term 'business solution'.''
</P>
<P>
   But the company once known for innovation failed to adapt
quickly to the world of microelectronics. It suffered a wrenching
period of downsizing, restructuring, a 1991 takeover by AT&AMP;T and,
at its worst, near collapse in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of 1996, the company was again restructured. Its name
was changed back to NCR, and it began shedding unprofitable
businesses and rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it is a high-technology, publicly traded company involved
in the collection, warehousing and analysis of data for retail,
financial and communications industries.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Hulsey writes for the Dayton Daily News. Her e-mail address
is lynn(underscore)hulsey(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
