<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECHNOLOGY, SOCIAL FACTORS HAVE RESHAPED THE TEACHER'S JOB
 &HT;    With LABOR. Repeating for all needing in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    By DICK STANLEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the early 19th century, Abraham Lincoln and
his youthful peers attended so-called ``blab'' schools, where they
repeated their lessons aloud, over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   When Deborah Husak left public school more than 150 years later,
recitation and memorizing still were in vogue. But when Husak began
teaching in 1968, education was undergoing a fundamental change.
Students were being encouraged to think for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``A teacher is really more of a facilitator now,'' said Husak,
who teaches fourth grade at Mills Elementary School in South
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Blackboards and chalk have given way to computers and overhead
projectors, and personal counseling, even ethics instruction, have
joined readin', writin', and 'rithmetic. The profession of an
estimated 3 million people nationwide has never been more
challenging _ even if the pay remains relatively low and respect is
a now-and-then thing.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the frightening new circumstance of being potential
targets of kids with guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that guns can be at your school makes the whole
environment very unstable,'' said Leyla Cohlmia, a chemistry
teacher at Austin High School.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, teachers must compete with television, radio, movies,
wireless communication, computers and the Internet _ especially the
Internet. These technology choices offer children a wealth of
sophisticated information that they expect to encounter in school.
They get angry and bored when they don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we have to be that much more prepared,'' Cohlmia said. ``We
never thought of talking to someone in England on the Internet
about their weather. We went to the encyclopedia.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers have to be ready, as well, to act as emotional,
financial and even ethical counselors to the young survivors of the
disintegration of the two-parent family. At the same time, they're
teaching a new generation of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers work,'' Husak said. ``Sometimes there's no one at
home. Sometimes kids speak the language, and sometimes they
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another problem that teachers must solve, said Jackson Pace,
who teaches physics and computer networking at LBJ High School, is
that while contemporary education encourages children to think for
themselves, employers increasingly complain that new graduates
can't do it. Pace believes the problem is caused by students'
overriding need to master multiple-choice tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids scope out the teachers, and the way they test, and forget
the content,'' Pace said. ``They don't know biology, but they're
making A's in biology. The multiple-guess test has got to go, if
you're trying to figure out if they can think.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Stanley writes for the Austin American-Statesman His e-mail
address is dstanley(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
