<HEADER>
A3942 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-LABOR-RAILROAD-$ADV03     08-28 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-RAILROAD-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RAILROADS HAVE SHRUNK, BUT JOBS LARGELY THE SAME
 &HT;    With LABOR. Repeating for all needing in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    By JANITA POE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When retired Southern Railroad machinist Bill Purdie
began his career in 1936, old-timers could remember the Civil War,
and the railroad was still the main mode of long-distance travel.
</P>
<P>
   His starting salary? Twenty-two and half cents an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Purdie spent the next several decades doing pretty much the same
thing: making and repairing steam engine parts.
</P>
<P>
   The steam engine required a lot of welding and drilling holes
and making bolts, parts and castings, said Purdie, now an
85-year-old retiree. ``It was hard work and heavy repair.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as they did a century ago, laborers still build, repair and
maintain the railroad engines, equipment and lines, and conductors
still oversee business on the train.
</P>
<P>
   ``Railroading, in general, is fundamentally about the same job
as years ago,'' said conductor Jack Hunt, 46.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard the Crescent, an Amtrak train that links New Orleans and
New York, conductor Hunt recently sat down in the lounge car and
penciled in numbers on his ``turnover sheet'' and ``delay report,''
just as historians say early conductors did in the mid-1800s.
</P>
<P>
   The only new technology Hunt regularly uses on the job is his
cell phone, which replaced his radio last year as his tool for
contacting the engineers at approaching stations. While radios had
limited frequencies, he said, cell phones almost guarantee
immediate contact.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant change in railroad work can be found in the
type of labor required to build a train or a railroad line, said
Lesa(cq) Campbell, a historian with the Southeastern Railway Museum
in Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Around the turn of the century, railroad tracks were built with
the brawn of outdoor laborers. But today, most of the line work now
involves repair and maintenance. Instead of 30 work gang members
driving spikes, one by one, a crew of about six skilled workers
operates hydraulic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The job of engine shop and roundhouse workers also has became
less labor-intensive in the second half of the century. After the
diesel engine replaced steam in the 1950s, their work evolved into
what now is primarily parts assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The number of workers needed to operate the railroads has
declined sharply from earlier years. Currently, about 24,000
employees work for Amtrak, according to spokesman Steven
Taubenkibel. Another 200,000 work for the four major freight
railroad companies _ CSX and Norfolk Southern in the East, and
Burlington Northern Santa Fe and Union-Pacific in the West.
</P>
<P>
   According to Campbell, 1.8 million people worked for the
railroads in 1917, one of the peak years for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Janita Poe writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution. Her
e-mail address is jpoe(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
