<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3955 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-SERVICE-ECON-SCH     08-28 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-SERVICE-ECON-SCHULZE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINCE WHEN DID I ASK TO HELP MYSELF? 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Sunday, Aug. 27, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By HORST SCHULZE    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the great paradoxes of our aging service
economy is that actual service, with a human face and a helping
hand, has disappeared from most American companies. The service
that most of us encounter these days is virtual, supplied by voice
mail, e-mail, satellite pagers and, of course, the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are noticing the difference. According to the American
Customer Satisfaction Index, compiled by the University of
Michigan, customer-service satisfaction has dropped since 1994 in
nearly every sector of the economy, with much of the blame going to
the increased use of technology.
</P>
<P>
   Call any business today _ your insurer, an airline, a credit
card issuer, a computer manufacturer, the phone company, your local
bank _ and whether you are trying to make a purchase, reserve a
seat, check your balance or, heaven forbid, obtain technical help _
odds are that you will be directed to the company's Web site to
fend for yourself. In other words, service has become self-service.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine walking into a fine restaurant and being told: ``Foie
gras is over here, truffles are over here, and sorry but our bread
is on back order, but you can check the status of your bread order
online, and don't forget your express service tag when confirming
your entree.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are fortunate enough to get a human being on the phone,
it is certain that you will be asked to verify your account number
and nature of your call, even though you have spent the past 10
minutes doing just that through the automated voice menu. And,
should you require further assistance, the person you are speaking
with is often powerless to do anything but transfer you to a
supervisor who will either shunt you back into the automated system
or suggest you visit the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations think they have the situation covered by assuring
customers that ``this call may be recorded to ensure quality.'' But
what does call monitoring really say about service? To the
employee, it says: ``We don't trust you to do your job
professionally. We will be watching and listening. Should you
deviate from your approved script or linger too long with a caller,
you will be disciplined.'' To the customer, the subtle message is,
``If you dare to complain, we will have evidence to show that our
personnel acted in compliance with our corporate courtesy policies
while you lost your cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, who besides the legal department would ever take comfort
in the fact that a given business records its service calls?
</P>
<P>
   What customer would be likely to think: ``It took 20 rings, six
menu options and three service reps to find out that my account
still hasn't been credited for the returned items, but at least
they taped my call.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest that companies don't deserve the latest
in call-routing networks or that they shouldn't have the best
customer management software on their Web sites. But too many
businesses are using these technologies as proxies for real service
because it so much easier to invest in systems, which can be
programmed and paid for once, than in people, who need to be
trained and retrained, not to mention incentivized, energized,
refreshed and promoted.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox is that much of what is passed off as customer
management is in fact anti-customer and anti-employee, and
companies are beginning to pay a price for their steadfast reliance
on such tools. Employees in jobs requiring direct human contact
perform less well when the basic dynamic of a customer relationship
has been taken away from them. Ultimately, they flee from boredom
or a sense of hitting a dead end, or else their jobs are outsourced
to third-party providers, whose allegiance is to the contract with
the client and not the customer.
</P>
<P>
   Volume, speed, economy, ``scalability'' _ these are the
watchwords of modern customer relations management. Emphasis on
attributes like these is born of business models and strategic
plans fixated on increasing ``eyeballs'' and transactions while
decreasing costs, rather than building loyalty among customers and
employees and reducing mistakes in delivery of the product.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that so many dot-com companies are struggling?
I bet you that all of them have very ``robust'' service models,
with powerful tracking and data-mining software for customer
profiling. Yet I wonder how many of these businesses have made the
same commitment to their hiring and orientation practices, or have
taken the time to create a hard measure of their own service
glitches, or have entrusted their employees to use their own
judgment when correcting problems rather than relying on the heavy
team approach that characterizes the technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that these enterprises are offering innovative
products and services. Their common failing is they haven't learned
to treat their customers the way they themselves would like to be
treated.
</P>
<P>
   (Horst Schulze is the president and chief operating officer of
the Ritz-Carlton Hotel Co.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
