<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3957 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-CLASS-WAR-LEBEDO     08-28 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-CLASS-WAR-LEBEDOFF-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CLASS WAR GORE COULD LOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Sunday, Aug. 27, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By DAVID LEBEDOFF    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ George W. Bush claims Al Gore is campaigning on
the issue of class warfare, and of course he is right. What Bush
doesn't mention is that he's running on class warfare, too _ but
the classes are different. For Gore, it's rich vs. ``working
families,'' and he's against the rich. For Bush, the war is between
the meritocracy and everyone else, and he's against the
meritocracy.
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate is on the right side to win, depending on which
war is really being fought _ or, more accurately, on which war most
the voters would rather win.
</P>
<P>
   If it is an economic class war, Gore has a chance of victory.
There is a widespread perception of the growing disparity in
wealth, and no one disputes that the tax cut Bush proposes would
greatly benefit the very rich. But a more immediate question is how
to keep the good times rolling, and Bush would claim that the
credit for them lies elsewhere than with the Clinton-Gore
administration, and that he is the true champion of working
families.
</P>
<P>
   The economic battle for the presidency could go either way. And
that brings us to the other battle, the one that Bush expects to
win: the war against the meritocracy.
</P>
<P>
   This is a war over what kind of people should be in charge, and
it has been raging for decades. To some extent it's a values war.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the GI Bill, college has depended increasingly
more on measurable scholastic ability than on the status of wealth
or birth. The good schools, and afterward the good jobs, public and
private, have been going to those with the highest grades and SAT
scores. The trend accelerated in the 1960s, as federal scholarships
and loans and needs-based financial aid further widened the college
applicant pool. It is widely assumed that Bush could not get into
Yale today but that Gore would have a shot at being admitted to
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the matter with merit? Absolutely nothing _ assuming
that merit can be measured. But what if it can't? Do good college
grades tell us who is better at life in its wider scope, and not
just college courses? Do they tell us who would be a better
president?
</P>
<P>
   The meritocracy thinks that they do. This isn't just conceit.
People are naturally grateful to the source of their success. To a
businessman, it's the free market. To Prince Charles, it's the
monarchy. To millions of Americans holding better jobs than their
parents ever dreamed of, it's the school work or the SAT. Only
that's not what they think. They all think it's merit.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the meritocracy is that it believes it's
certifiably better at everything. It has demonstrated a proficiency
at reasoning skills, and therefore thinks every problem can be
solved entirely with that proficiency. If this were indeed correct,
then Herbert Hoover would have been a better president than
Franklin Roosevelt, and Jimmy Carter would have ranked higher than
Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem with the meritocracy is that it doesn't really
believe in majority rule, because if we already know who the
smartest people are, why should we bother to solicit the opinion of
anyone else?
</P>
<P>
   This has caused, not consciously but very, very pervasively, a
restructuring of our institutions to avoid the will of the
electorate. The classic example is Hillary Clinton's plan to
overhaul health care, devised away from the public debate, in rooms
full of policy experts. Increasingly, too, major decisions are made
by judges and administrators virtually immune from electoral
reproach, let alone removal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is hoping that the backlash against this elitist approach
is focused on Gore. To be seen primarily as a wonk is fatal to a
candidate today. Clinton flew under the voter radar because he was
a Southern governor who had the good old boy thing down perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Bush is really the Midland, Texas, scamp whose drawl
can make Lyndon Johnson sound like Dean Acheson. He's the
descendant of gentry, the Democrats continually point out, while
Gore is in fact the son of parents who worked their way out of
poverty in the South.
</P>
<P>
   So why does this war favor Bush? Because the voters are so
alienated by the effect of the meritocracy on the very concept of
consent of the governed that our elections have been transformed.
Campaigns are framed to be less about issues than about the
candidate's background and outlook. If a presidential candidate is
seen as primarily a member of the meritocracy, the voters seem to
push the other lever, even if it means tax cuts for the rich.
</P>
<P>
   Values play into this war. A candidate whose principal faith is
in pure reason, rather than experience, frightens most voters. As
an alternative, they look for someone guided by values: tradition,
constancy, patience, resolve, tolerance, dispassion, compassion,
courage, good humor, humility, faith.
</P>
<P>
   Faith is a good example. If you believe in God and religious
tenets, you possess values other than total reliance on the power
of intellect. That's why this campaign has been marked on both
sides by more protestations of faith than were ever provoked by
Torquemada.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is very vulnerable in any contest decided by resentment of
the meritocracy. In two interviews in The New Yorker, his
statements are almost impossible to read _ tortured self-analytical
psychobabble and social science prose. These are potentially more
damaging than Bush's gaffes _ since a lack of expertise probably
plays better than excessive expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would do well to reproduce millions of copies of the Gore
interviews and drop them from planes over every swing state. The
economic class war being played out in this election could go
either way; the new elite class war, only one.
</P>
<P>
   (David Lebedoff, a lawyer, is the author of ``The New Elite''
and ``Cleaning Up.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
