<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Walking through ritzy stores great, but Web helps thrifty
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Many shoppers have a love/hate relationship with
upscale department stores.
</P>
<P>
   We love what they sell but can't always afford it. And even if
we can, the salespeople can often make us feel like we should all
get back on our turnip trucks and drive back to Podunk or whatever
Godforsaken backwater it is assumed we have crawled out of.
</P>
<P>
   I vividly remember trying to buy a bottle of trendy perfume in a
certain high-end department store. Getting the attention of the
sales staff was tougher than getting past the velvet ropes at
Studio 54 in its heyday. Across the sales floor a friend of mine
was trying to purchase a silk tie for his new job. After a while,
he meandered over to me, without a purchase, muttering, ``I really
don't care. I'm just going to that tie store near the food court.
These people make me feel like a bug.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, if you've got the time and you've got some mad money, skip
the snotty salespeople and try department store shopping online.
Trade magazine The Industry Standard argues in its current issue
that half the fun of luxury department store shopping is the
elegance of the surroundings, the glorious feeling of actually
touching a pair of Gucci loafers or a Prada tote bag or trying on
that fabulously chic Armani suit. The Standard points out that the
luxury stores' online counterparts don't have half the inventory
their brick-and-mortar stores have and that shoppers don't want to
spend hundreds, perhaps thousands, of dollars ordering a dress
online that might not be the right color or that might not fit.
</P>
<P>
   To this concept, we say ``phooey.'' We also say visit the new
Neiman Marcus Web site (www
</P>
<P>
   .neimanmarcus.com). What we have here is a flashier version of
Neiman's numerous hard copy ``look books'' mailed to its credit
card customers that display the store's hot picks for any given
season. There's a ``shop by trend'' section that lets users sigh
over cashmere sweaters from Marc Jacobs or Donna Karan separates
the store dubs ``Wall Street Chic.''
</P>
<P>
   But by far the best thing about the Neiman site is the Manolo
Blahnik shoe salon. Launched with the help of Atlanta-based firm
RichFx, this area of the store is a virtual video game for designer
shoe fans _ and you know who you are. Even if you have no idea what
Manolo Blahnik shoes are, go ahead and download the RichFx player
and take a look at the shopping experience Neiman's has the
potential to offer shoppers visiting the rest of its online store.
The software program that runs within the Web site looks like the
computer game ``Myst,'' only you're examining shoes instead of
spaceships. There are original drawings from the designer and even
his motto: ``My shoes are not fashion,'' he says. ``They are
objects ... gestures that happen to be fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh my.
</P>
<P>
   For a certain element of the population this is more fun than
the Godiva chocolate site.
</P>
<P>
   But if Neiman's isn't your style, walk across the virtual street
to Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Again, selection is slim compared to the brick-and-mortar store.
The ladies who lunch and then presumably spend the rest of the day
shopping have vetoed this site. However, for ordinary working girls
eating salads at their desks, the Saks site is a delightful
diversion. From designer evening gowns from Badgley Mischka, to
workplace-appropriate clothes from the store's very stylish
in-house line, or accessories from the usual designer suspects
Jimmy Choo, Kate Spade, Calvin Klein and HugoBoss, they're here.
And yes, the teensy and trendy Fendi baguettes are here.
</P>
<P>
   While the official jury is still out on high-end department
store Web sites, they do have numerous advantages for time-crunched
and cash-crunched shoppers who every now and then do like to sample
the finer things in life.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, every site lists prices. Sometimes when one is
looking at accessories or jewelry in department stores, the tags
are discreetly turned over to hide the three- or four-figure price.
</P>
<P>
   On even the most ancient of computer monitors, the colors and
the design of the products show up beautifully. And, if it's
something you really, really want, you can either order it on the
spot or perhaps call your local store and see if it has the same
item and can hold it for you.
</P>
<P>
   Department stores like Neiman and Saks undeniably rely on
well-heeled customers wandering through their stores like Lauren
Bacall in ``How to Marry a Millionaire'' pointing at item after
item and commanding, ``I'll take that and that ... and that and
that and that!''
</P>
<P>
   However, for the ordinary shopper who places buying a Chanel
handbag in the same class as putting a down payment on a car, sites
like these give you the information you need to be a better
consumer of luxury goods.
</P>
<P>
   You know the prices, you know the designers and when you need a
special dress for a gala event or just want to splurge on a sharp
new tie to wear to work, you can check out the goods right here.
</P>
<P>
   And if you want, snap up that tie for the job interview _ a
couple of clicks, no waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
