<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bundles of fun
 &HT;    By Shaun Conlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   For kids not content with mere ogling and cooing over their
latest bubblegum card acquisition or setting up a fantasy
competition via linked game machines, Bandai's Gundam Wing toys
offer hands-on, tangible toys for imaginary-world play. Better
still, Bandai bundles two activities into one package as the toys
are also available as Gundam Wing plastic model kits ($5 to $25;
www.bandai.com). When the glue-less snap-together figurines are
finished _ complete with weapons, decals and accessories _ they
become effective and interactive posturing models with some 40
points of articulation. A slightly sophisticated motor-skills
challenge and a long-term toy craze all in one. Pretty neat.
</P>
<P>
   THE GENTLE LULL OF A JACKHAMMER?
</P>
<P>
   There's one thing mechanical wind-up mobiles have over lazy-age
motorized, doll-dangling, eye-catching baby distracters: They're
not motorized! That is to say, while Fisher Price's Sparkling
Symphony Mobile with Remote Control ($25; www.fisher-price.com) is
indeed ultra modern, colorful and pleasing to behold visually, the
diminutive powerhouse rotating its dangling moon and stars is
notably audible. To compensate, the symphony of nursery rhyme
electronica is fixed at a fairly loud volume, which is all well and
good if you're grooming a future rock star or jackhammer operator,
but it's not at all peaceful late in the night when a soft,
soothing lullaby is all that's required. A wonderful daytime
distraction, to be sure, but clicking on the remote from up to 20
feet away and setting the moaning wheels and enthusiastic digital
orchestra in motion somewhat defeats the purpose of stealth tactics
in the nursery.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
