<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `X-Men' geared toward fans of comic book version
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``X-Men's'' popularity seems to be peaking again with
a recent movie starring America's favorite mutant fighters, along
with a new video game titled ``X-Men: Mutant Academy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Activision product is a gem for PlayStation owners. The
console system is rapidly losing attention from the industry's top
developers because of the approaching arrival of the PlayStation 2
on Oct. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Men'' was the most successful comic book property of all
time. The game pays respect to the history of the mutant heroes,
while providing challenging fighting duels at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   There are many modes to the game, including Training, Survival
and Arcade. Choosing the first option, you and your selected
character go to visit Professor X, who patiently teaches you to
throw simple punches and kicks as well as elaborate combination
moves.
</P>
<P>
   In Survival mode, you battle until your energy meter goes out.
After defeating all of your opponents in the Cerbro mode, you are
treated to an animated history three minutes or longer about your
chosen mutant.
</P>
<P>
   Like the good and evil that exist in the world of ``X-Men,''
there are good and bad things to say about the video game.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, the simple moves are a lot flashier than
comparable fighting games. They also do an excellent job of falling
in with the character's personality. There are special features,
such as 24-hit combination by Toad that can do fierce damage.
</P>
<P>
   Despite today's state-of-the-art technology, Activision opted to
remain two-dimensional with the fighting. In other words, you can
only duck and jump to avoid hits, not step aside to the right and
left as you can with 3-D titles. ``X-Men'' does have a tad of 3-D,
which is only used in the completion of special moves. As the
finishing blow is being launched, the camera angle will move around
to the back of your mutant for an up-close look.
</P>
<P>
   The graphics are only average, but the fighting action runs
smoothly. What really stands out is when a character does a simple
special move and the game goes to slow motion for about two or
three seconds as the final hits are made.
</P>
<P>
   The music at the beginning of the game _ from the movie _ is
excellent, as are the introductory themes for each character. But
when the fighting begins, the music becomes annoying. It is without
purpose and fails to follow the action.
</P>
<P>
   You'll love this game if you love ``X-Men.'' When the game is
loading, screen shots of the old comic books appear on the screen.
It brings back wonderful memories of the evolution of the world's
superheroes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
