<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Game Boy Advance, Gamecube from Nintendo due next year
 &HT;    By Troy Oxford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nintendo fans have something to cheer about. The
company revealed its new video gaming systems Thursday at the
Spaceworld trade show in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The Game Boy Advance, successor to the Game Boy Color portable
gaming device, will feature a 32-bit processor, 50 percent larger
color LCD screen, higher resolution, 32,000-color display and
improved audio. The system will also be able to play current Game
Boy color games.
</P>
<P>
   The system will be available July 2001 and retail for $90.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo also unveiled the Gamecube home video game system. The
new system is powered by a 450-megahertz processor, an ATI graphics
co-processor and 40 megabytes of memory.
</P>
<P>
   Gamecube games will come in 1.5-gigabyte optical disk format,
and accessories will include a 56k modem and a wireless controller.
</P>
<P>
   The system is set to launch in North America in October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
