<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-ANIMALS0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aussie animals
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You've heard of kicking kangaroos and the furry koala.
They're two of Australia's most recognizable animal friends. But
did you know that about 95 percent of the mammals Down Under and 88
percent of the reptiles can't be found anywhere else in the world?
</P>
<P>
   Take a peek at Australia's unusual wildlife, from the furry and
fuzzy to the dangerous and deadly.
</P>
<P>
   KANGAROO: Kangaroos are marsupials _ that means they are
mammals, but the female has a pouch to carry and feed her young. A
baby kangaroo is called a joey. Australia is home to many
marsupials. The kangaroo (above) is the largest.
</P>
<P>
   Different types of 'roos are found on the continent, from the
small tree kangaroos to the large red kangaroos. They eat grass and
are active mainly at night.
</P>
<P>
   Kangaroos have large, strong tails. They stand on their tails
when they fight other 'roos _ that allows them to kick with their
big feet, as well as punch.
</P>
<P>
   KOALA: These cuddly-looking marsupials (top) live high in the
eucalyptus trees in the Australian states of Victoria, New South
Wales, South Australia and Queensland. They eat the trees' leaves,
which contain a lot of water. In fact, they eat so much eucalyptus,
about 2.5 pounds a day, you will rarely find a koala on the ground
looking for a watering hole. ``Koala'' is an aboriginal, or native
Australian, word that means ``no drink.''
</P>
<P>
   PLATYPUS: The platypus is yet another marsupial, but it's one of
two such animals that actually lay eggs. The other is the echidna,
which is also found only in Australia. Their eggs have soft shells,
unlike a bird's. When the babies hatch, they feed in their mother's
pouch.
</P>
<P>
   Platypi are strange-looking animals that make their homes in
burrows in the banks of rivers. Many people look at the platypus'
bill and four webbed feet and assume it is related to a duck. But
they aren't related.
</P>
<P>
   A platypus bill is about 2 inches long, flat, and covered with
shiny black skin. Platypi use their bills to find food. They eat
crayfish and worms and drink stream water.
</P>
<P>
   DINGO: Dingoes (left) are wild Australian dogs that are found
all over the continent, except on the island of Tasmania. They have
been there for at least 7,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Dingoes live at the edge of forests and in the bush and
grasslands. They eat lizards and rabbits. If they team up, they can
catch large kangaroos. If dingoes kill more food than they can eat,
they bury the leftovers for later.
</P>
<P>
   SALTWATER CROCODILE: The saltwater croc (right) is the largest
reptile in the world, with some growing as long as 17 feet. They
live mainly in coastal areas of northern Australia and southeast
Asia, though they sometimes venture into rivers and swamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salties'' generally eat fish, turtles, crabs, birds and small
mammals. But larger crocodiles have been known to eat other crocs,
water buffalo and even humans. They catch their food by lying in or
around the water and then ambushing their prey. Salties use the
crocodile ``death roll'' to rip animals into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   INLAND TAIPAN SNAKE: Don't confuse the inland taipan snake with
the less poisonous coastal taipan. While both make the Top 10 list
of Australia's most poisonous snakes, the inland taipan is No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The snakes can be found in old rat burrows, soil cracks, sink
holes or rock crevices in the dry plains and grasslands of central
Australia. They eat rats, frogs and small to medium mammals. The
taipan can strike its victims in a single bite or several quick
bites. The snake's future meal doesn't have time to fight back
before the venom takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   ATRAX SPIDER: The atrax is Australia's most poisonous spider.
Some people say it is the most poisonous spider in the world to
about an inch long. They can be ferocious if they are provoked. The
atrax can be found in the wet, coastal areas of New South Wales _
and it is often referred to as the Sydney Funnel Web Spider.
</P>
<P>
   MULGA SNAKE: Also known as the King Brown snake, this reptile
(below) is No. 2 on Australia's list of most deadly snakes. While
its venom is not as poisonous as other snakes, the mulga releases
much, much more venom in a single bite, paralyzing its prey. That's
what makes it so dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Mulgas feed on lizards, frogs, rodents, birds and other snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
