<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Something's fishy with the new Dreamcast virtual pet, Seaman.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Hinting at the video game industry's mounting ability to
permeate daily living in the digital age, Sega offers a virtual pet
quite unlike any other. While Seaman ($50; www.dreamcast. com; for
the Dreamcast) does require the Dreamcast console hardware to
function, the resemblance to traditional video games pretty much
ends there. Seaman, a half-man, half-fish creature of enigmatic
lineage, is born and raised right there on one's television screen
in computer-generated glory. Bundled with a microphone and
state-of-the-art voice recognition software, users can actualloggle
your mind as you un-boggle the mystery behind his origins.
</P>
<P>
   While the video game industry and the movie industries both
compete for your entertainment dollar, a new trend in convergence
is emerging: Video games based on movies and movies based on video
games are beginning to launch simultaneously. Such is the case with
X-Men Mutant Academy ($40; www.activision.com; for the
PlayStation), which is a game simpatico with the recent summer
blockbuster, which in turn is based on an immensely popular comic
and cartoon franchise. Unfortunately, the game is merely another
means to brand name us with X-Men; it has little to do with the
film. In fact, it only vaguely resembles a modern video game in the
first place. Mutant Academy is a well-drawn, well-animated 2-D
fighting game _ and that's it. There's no adventure akin to a movie
plot, just the various super-anti-heroes duking it out in a
face-to-face, side-scrolling romp. Even on the aging PlayStation
console, most fighting games are known to contain so much more than
flat-action eye-candy, such as three dimensions. Nevertheless,
X-Men Mutant Academy is a very good 2-D fighting game complete with
trademark super-moves and painful powers of mutant punishment. But
it's the weakest member in the grand amalgamation scheme of
console, cartoon, comic and cinematic extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing about this PlayStation version of Worms Armaggeddon:
($30; www.hasbro-interactive.com; for the PlayStation) Sony
initially nixed the idea of a 2-D,
cuter-than-dimples/funnier-than-Looney Tunes action/strategy game
starring squeaky-voiced invertebrate simply for the fact that the
idea of a 2-D, cuter-than-dimples/funnier than Looney Tunes
action/strategy game starring squeaky-voiced invertebrate didn't
seem like a viable PlayStation game a few years back when Sony was
marketing a hardcore gamer's machine. Now, of course, Sony will
license everything just to saturate the market, which is usually a
bad thing in the watered-down library sense of things, but a very
good thing in this specific case as Worms Armageddon is a
surprisingly great 2-D, cuter-than-dimples/funnier-than-Looney
Tunes action/strategy game starring squeaky-voiced invertebrate.
Excellent even.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   The real-time strategy genre is hitting maturity with fully
fleshed 3-D worlds (think Homeworld, Shogun: Total War and the
upcoming Dark Reign 2), and none captures this territory better
than Ground Control, a future-war adrenaline pumper from Sierra
($35; www .sierrastudios.com/games/groundcontrol; for Windows).
Beautiful to behold and a blast to play, this fast-paced game skips
the tedium of resource gathering, so prevalent in the genre, and
goes straight for the gut, dropping the player (after an excellent
tutorial) into the fight for Krig-7B, a distant planet bursting
with an innovative array of infantry, artillery and aircraft. A
compelling sci-fi plot unfolds, lending context as the fights
become increasingly brutal and spectacular. Camera control and unit
placement can get awkward, but the multiplayer aspect is
innovative, and the terrain and units are stunningly detailed as
the game scales from point-blank range to the 2,000-foot level in
an instant. In short, Ground Control delivers the full wallop with
attention paid to every last detail.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joe Stafford
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
