<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    11-year-old to play Harry
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fans of J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter books can now put
a real face on the boy wizard. Eleven-year-old British actor Daniel
Radcliffe has been cast as Harry for the movie ``Harry Potter and
The Sorcerer's Stone.'' Radcliffe has previously played the Charles
Dickens character David Copperfield in a British Broadcasting Corp.
TV program.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's friends Hermione and Ron will be played by newcomers
Emma Watson, 10, and Rupert Grint, 11. Both have performed in
school plays in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICANS HELD IN CHINA
</P>
<P>
   Three Americans are among 131 people who were arrested in China
last week. They are Christian missionaries from California who were
attending a revival meeting banned by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   The missionaries were working with the China Fangcheng Church,
which does not have the government's approval to hold meetings.
Christianity is allowed in the Communist nation, but the government
says the Fangcheng Church is a cult. The government has recently
fined and arrested members of unapproved religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is working to find the Americans and bring
them home.
</P>
<P>
   FORD REPLACING BAD TIRES
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. said last week that it will temporarily stop
making trucks, so that it can use 70,000 new truck tires to replace
faulty tires on trucks and SUVs already on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The bad tires, made by Firestone, were standard on Ford
Explorers, Ford Rangers and Mecury Mountaineers. Firestone recalled
about 6.5 million of the tires after determining they could come
apart. The tires may have caused 62 deaths and more than 100
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The tire company was flying in replacements from factories in
Japan over the weekend to help meet demand in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Center for Auto Safety, a Washington-based
organization, says the recall isn't broad enough to catch all the
faulty Firestone tires. It says 12 million more tires should be
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   GERMS MAY HELP BABIES
</P>
<P>
   Babies who are in day care may get more colds now, but they
might avoid getting asthma or allergies in the long run. The
reason? Day care babies are exposed to more germs, which could
actually help their immune systems develop, researchers now say.
</P>
<P>
   Infants under 6 months old in day care seem to have less chance
of developing asthma or allergies than their counterparts who
aren't in day care.
</P>
<P>
   Having an older sibling can help, too. The more older brothers
and sisters in the house, the lower the chances that a younger
child would develop allergies or asthma, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
