<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Accessory-deprived? Writeable CD drive a handy tool
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I am often a great disappointment to those who meet
me.
</P>
<P>
   Most people assume that _ here at Technology Ranch in exotic
Smyrna, Ga., _ I have all the latest in computer equipment. They
envision banks of blinking lights, PCs with processors so fast that
special cooling units are needed to prevent meltdown, and shelves
stocked with every new accessory that comes along.
</P>
<P>
   But today I am sitting in a bedroom that serves as my home
office, bare feet propped on a desk where my father once sat
presiding over a failing boat-manufacturing company. I am typing
away on a 350-megahertz computer that any self-respecting
13-year-old would sneer at.
</P>
<P>
   I love gadgets and computers. It's just that I am promiscuous
with my love and my money and have flings with fly rods, golf clubs
and cameras as well as computers. My modest income gets spread too
thin to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   So when the public relations woman called to ask me to test the
new MP3 audio gadget that her company was promoting, she explained
that I would need to use my writeable CD drive as part of the test.
I had to tell her I hadn't gotten around to buying one. You could
hear the disdain of my high-tech poverty in her silence.
</P>
<P>
   Then, being highly trained in the art of human relations and in
advanced table manners, she said she would lend the drive to me so
I could test her product. When the drive arrived, it sat _ unopened
_ for a week while I went about my more usual tasks of cleaning up
after the cat and trying to find my lost wallet.
</P>
<P>
   I still haven't tested her product. But I did install the CD
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a few days of messing with it, I am already looking
closely at my No. 2 fly rod, thinking I may pawn that sucker and
buy my own writeable CD drive. I am finding uses for the drive that
didn't strike me until I used it.
</P>
<P>
   It passed the Husted Test for Practicality. It has multiple
uses, and all of them have actually solved one problem or another
for me.
</P>
<P>
   I've used it to make audio CDs of some of my favorite vinyl
albums. Now I can drive along in my car accompanied by Peggy Lee.
Those who have heard me sing _ even trendy people who listen to
more popular music _ appreciate hearing her instead of me.
</P>
<P>
   My hard disk was clogged with electronic photographs. There's
the (I swear this is true and can provide witnesses if necessary)
photo my electrical engineer uncle sent of his new license tag,
countless family photographs I scanned in, photos of various
friends, and pictures that I no longer remember taking but hesitate
to throw away. I've copied most of them to a CD and tucked them
away so _ years from now when this hard disk meets up with the law
of entropy _ I'll have them.
</P>
<P>
   Then I did something that surprised even me. For years I have
been urging readers to make a backup copy of the personal data on
their hard disks. But _ since I did not have a tape drive, or even
a Zip drive _ the notion of inserting countless dozens of floppy
disks to save my tax data, e-mails and writing documents was
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   I felt guilty about not doing it, but a guy can get used to
guilt. Now I have a true backup copy of my data. (I didn't bother
making copies of programs since it's almost always necessary to
install them from scratch in a new installation.)
</P>
<P>
   What I'm saying is: Go out and get a writeable CD drive if you
don't have one.
</P>
<P>
   I know many of you are nervous about tasks that involve opening
up the innards of your PC. But it's truly easy _ a 30-minute job at
most. I won't take you through the steps since it's far smarter to
follow the step-by-step instructions that come with the drive. But
I can tell you that installation simply involves sliding the drive
into your computer and fastening it with two screws.
</P>
<P>
   Then you plug in two cables. Once you load in the software that
comes with the CD drive, you're set. Those of you who still get the
quivers about things like this needn't be ashamed if you decide to
take your machine in to a computer shop for the installation.
</P>
<P>
   Since this CD drive must soon go back to the manufacturer, I'll
be postponing the purchase of a new sand wedge for my golf bag and
buying a writeable CD drive of my own.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, I may even get around to testing the MP3
gadget that started this whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
