<HEADER>
A4026 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0829     08-28 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPN stations may become part of a new Fox network
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ United Paramount Network passed away on New
Year's Day, 2001, at the age of 5, following a lengthy illness.
Despite slightly improved ratings in recent years, it hemorrhaged
more than half a billion dollars during its brief lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The mini-network is survived by a couple of popular African
American sitcoms, a raucous pro wrestling show and a cult-favorite
sci-fi series in its seventh and final season.
</P>
<P>
   UPN was the child of Viacom and Chris-Craft, created to make
sure Viacom's Paramount-produced shows would be seen if the other
networks decided to buy only programs produced in-house. When
Viacom bought CBS, UPN's raison d'etre disappeared. Now that News
Corp. is buying Chris-Craft and UPN is losing those big-city
stations, that core UPN audience is lost as well.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral will take place at Paramount Studios in Los Angeles.
Trekkers and wrestlers will serve as pall bearers. In lieu of
flowers, viewers are asked to send contributions to the Keep
Voyager Alive Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   UPN, seen in Austin on KVC Channel 13, is battling what many
industry experts believe is a fatal illness now that News Corp. has
bought Chris-Craft Industries, which owns eight UPN stations in
vital major markets such as New York and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   If, as expected, News Corp. owner Rupert Murdoch politely
requests that those stations drop their UPN affiliations when their
contracts expire in January, that would leave the fledgling network
without coverage where network coverage is vital. Death is likely
to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Do we care? Well, some of us do.
</P>
<P>
   Adolescent boys whose hearts go pitty-pat at the mention of
World Wrestling Federation's ``Smackdown!'' certainly care. Big
time. The streets may be crawling with angry teen-agers if their
regular Thursday night testosterone outlet disappears. Other
networks have toyed with the notion of adding wrestling to prime
time, but for sheer outrageousness and camp, it would be hard to
beat''Smackdown!''
</P>
<P>
   A large number of African American viewers will mourn the loss
of ``The Parkers'' and ``Moesha,'' the No. 1 and No. 4 shows,
respectively, among black households. And next month, ABC's
prematurely canceled sitcom ``The Hughleys'' moves to UPN, which
means that group of loyal fans _ and D.L. Hughley himself _ will be
left in the lurch, too.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when network TV has been lambasted for lack of divers-
</P>
<P>
   ity, NAACP spokesman John White expressed concern recently over
the possible demise of UPN because the network ``has one of the
best records in terms of minority hiring and representation.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, legions of near-obsessive fans of ``Star Trek:
Voyager'' are sure to begin hyperventilating by Thanksgiving if the
sci-fi series doesn't find a new home in January.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not among the fans of pro wrestling, sitcoms and
``Voyager,'' you probably couldn't care less about UPN's fate. And
for good reason. Only by an enormous stretch of the definition is
UPN a network at all. For one thing, it only has 10 hours of
programming a week: 7 to 9 p.m. Monday through Friday. That's it.
This fall it will have only six hours of series, including a new
martial arts drama (``Freedom''), a high-tech crime drama (``Level
9'') and one new sitcom (``Girlfriends''). Trust me when I tell you
few people will mourn any of those shows.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, ABC, CBS and NBC have 22 hours of prime-time
programming, plus news, sports and daytime blocks seven days a
week. Fox has 15 hours in prime, lots of kid shows in daytime and a
large chunk of sports programming. Even the WB, the other fledgling
web that's been vying with UPN for true network status, has 13
hours on six nights, along with after-school and Saturday morning
kiddie fare.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of major markets and the bleeding of $100 million to
$150 million a year due to pitifully low ratings add up to doom for
UPN, but that doesn't mean its most popular programs (which aren't
very popular by Big Three standards) won't find a home. Since
Viacom owns both CBS and UPN, a logical home for ``Moesha'' and
``Voyager'' might be CBS, which is always in the market for the
younger viewers those shows attract.
</P>
<P>
   The really bad news in this corporate turnover is that Fox is
threatening to create another network, Fox 2, that would be
anchored by the newly acquired Chris-Craft stations, including two
biggies in New York and Los Angeles. (If Fox doesn't launch a new
network, the former UPN/Chris-Craft stations probably would become
independents. Viacom/CBS owns UPN shows, so Fox probably couldn't
keep those on the stations if it wanted to.) The Fox 2 scenario is
particularly scary because Fox (which also has Fox Family, Fox
News, FX and Fox Sports on cable) is having trouble programming the
one broadcast network it already owns.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's upcoming fall schedule, with little more than a month
before the October premieres, still has three ``To Be Announced''
blocks in prime time _ a half-hour to start the night on Wednesdays
and the entire Thursday lineup _ and a new sitcom starring John
Goodman that still doesn't have a title or complete cast. Not good.
</P>
<P>
   More Fox, less UPN . . . hmmm. Is anybody better off with this
deal, besides Rupert Murdoch? From the couch potato perspective,
it's somewhere between a wash and a negative.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
