<SLUG> BC-SEGA-GAME-REVIEW0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Graphics a big hook in `Ecco'
 &HT;    By Troy Oxford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's been well over a year since I first saw screen
shots of a promising Dreamcast game titled ``Ecco the Dolphin.'' It
was one of the best-looking games I had ever seen, and now it's
finally here and I couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   Once the game loads, prepare to witness some of the best
graphics on the system to date. For the first half-hour I totally
ignored the game play and just explored the vast undersea world in
awe.
</P>
<P>
   The game artists' research spanned several months, and it shows.
From the smooth contour of a dolphin to the subtle cloud of sand
from a shifting stingray, every element is captured realistically.
</P>
<P>
   The beautiful imagery is complemented with a soothing ambient
soundtrack. Some hard-core gamers may be a little skeptical, but
it's actually a refreshing break from the gritty, techno-throbbing
action games.
</P>
<P>
   The sensory experience is nearly perfect, but how does it play?
</P>
<P>
   Again, I was impressed. Ecco, the dolphin, has many abilities,
and although they may take a few minutes to get used to, you'll be
chasing fish and gliding gracefully along the ocean floor in no
time.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ecco's most important abilities is his sonar projection.
The skill allows Ecco to speak to other creatures, wrangle fish and
map out his environment.
</P>
<P>
   The only factor that comes close to polluting this pristine game
is the vagueness of the tasks for each stage.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are info-crystals and sea creatures that guide
Ecco, you'll often be uncertain as to what to do or where to go. I
usually don't refer to hint guides, but I found that I didn't have
much choice if I wanted to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a few unclear missions, ``Ecco the Dolphin'' is a dream.
This is yet another great title that makes me happy I have a
Dreamcast.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
