<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Absent again from big event TV
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Big deal television events put a nonviewer
in an awkward position.
</P>
<P>
   About 51 million people saw the last episode of ``Survivor.'' Or
will admit to it. Enough to stimulate serious media overkill and
dominate conversation in cafeterias, bars, offices, gyms and
student unions everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   When faced with these conversations do you say, ``No, I have no
knowledge of this 'Survivor' thing of which you speak'' and sound
like a snob? A spoilsport affecting the air of an ethical
vegetarian at a weenie roast?
</P>
<P>
   Or do you disguise your ignorance by airily mouthing any
secondhand conventional wisdom you've overheard. ``How did that
creepy Richard guy win? Don't that just burn your breakfast?''
</P>
<P>
   A simple ``No, that's my bowling night'' would be too easy to
verify. It would be hipper to say: ``No, it aired during my
triathlon training.'' But it's hard to sound convincing between
handfuls of potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   The real story? My garbage disposal jammed. My bike chain was
loose. I had a flat tire and relatives arrived from out of town.
The bus was late.
</P>
<P>
   I need to develop excuses because I watch virtually no
television. This is not a moral thing. It is not Some Kind of
Cause.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows it's not an overabundance of good taste - you would
be amazed at the percentage of my wardrobe that depicts palm trees
or identifiable fish species.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the truth is too boring to relate. I'm a sleep-deprived
single parent living in a part of the country with near-perfect
weather. This combination leaves little couch time. At least little
couch time when I'm awake.
</P>
<P>
   I'm just not into TV and went years without owning one.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this year, I've already fumbled with explanations. I've
never seen ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire?'' and missed the
game-show high weirdness of ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with that _ to quote a show I
saw three times during the decade of the 1990s _ it's just hard to
explain without folks suspecting you belong to a cult.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do I dread being shunned for knowing nothing about the
show, there could be professional ramifications. I fear having my
columnist's license yanked for being the only columnist to fail to
write about the parallels between the presidential election and
``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   I am told the final survivor, Richard Hatch, is a consultant.
The biography issued by the network says he ``conducts seminars on
numerous topics including conflict management, team building,
practical negotiation and public speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   He is building a career as a professional survivor right now.
Within eight months, his books, videos, talk show appearances, his
management philosophy will be so overfamiliar even I will catch his
act.
</P>
<P>
   I shudder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' features a crude form of pure democracy in which
all the contestants vote each other off the show.
</P>
<P>
   This might catch on. Next, they'll do business layoffs like
that. I'd be worried if I were working anywhere where Hatch's
consults.
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason to be ready for next time.
</P>
<P>
   The electricity was out. The VCR jammed. The computer was down.
The cable went funny. I lost the remote control so deep in the
couch it will take a reupholsterer to dig it out.
</P>
<P>
   Full-fledged excuse systems are much better than a single
all-purpose excuse. And far better than telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   I think I heard that at a corporate consultant's seminar.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever I come up with will need to be convincing or my
co-workers will vote me out. I'll be on shaky ground for at least
another week.
</P>
<P>
   Unless I can accuse someone else of being a TV snob.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
