<HEADER>
A4037 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0829-COX     08-28 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: We received a letter from Capital Recovery
Inc. in Utah stating that we were due a refund of $774.53 on a
paid-off mortgage held in a trust fund by the government. This
company offered to collect this refund for us for a 25 percent fee.
We are wondering if this is a legitimate deal or a scam. If it is
legit, how would we go about collecting this money ourselves?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ellen Macaulay
</P>
<P>
   A: Not a scam, but you can retrieve this money yourself. If you
believe the tracer's fee is worth the trouble, at least attempt to
negotiate the fee to a lower percentage before agreeing to payment.
Reputable tracers ask a percentage, and remember, payment is made
after you receive the money, not before. Some mortgage holders are
due a refund from the federal government for old FHA mortgages paid
off before Nov. 5, 1990. Contact The Federal Housing Administration
Support Service Center at (800) 697-6967 or visit
www.hud.gov/fha/comp/refunds/fhafact.html to investigate such
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Q: While snorkeling in a nearby river, I found a brass token. On
one side, it has an engraving of a hen and a rooster kissing with
the words ``THE CHICKEN RANCH LA GRANGE, TEX'' inscribed around the
edge. On the back, ``GOOD FOR ALL NIGHT'' is inscribed in the
center and flanked on both sides by two hearts. I've heard about
the Chicken Ranch, but is this brass coin authentic or just a joke?
Who would be able to tell me?
</P>
<P>
   _ Edward F.
</P>
<P>
   A: Could be genuine. A woman well-versed in the history of the
Chicken Ranch, Kathy Carter, director of the Fayette Heritage
Museum and Archives, says there is no way to tell. (Newcomers, the
Chicken Ranch was an infamous brothel located in La Grange. Its
closing was loosely chronicled in the musical and movie ``Best
Little Whorehouse in Texas.'') Tokens like this were common in
houses of ill repute _ but so were counterfeit and commemorative
ones. Drop by the Fayette County museum in La Grange and let Carter
take a look. She is always interested in potentially historical
items. How did the brothel come to be called the Chicken Ranch?
During the Great Depression the reigning madam, Miss Jessie, was
forced to go on the ``poultry standard,'' charging one chicken per
``service.'' Soon chickens roamed the ramshackle place, and the
poultry operation became a profit maker. No one went hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My friend and I have a disagreement as to whether Dr Pepper
has any prune juice in it. She says yes; I say no. Who is right?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.J.
</P>
<P>
   A: You are. Dr Pepper's secret formula, says spokesman Mike
Martin, contains 23 fruit flavors. Prune (plum) is not among them.
Never has been. Dr Pepper's (the period after the r was dropped in
the 1950s) 1999 sales topped 500 million cases in the United
States. That is 12 billion 12 oz. can or 44 cans per person per
year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Miller used to sell a clear beer a couple of years ago. Is
there any way I can get my hands on some?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ralph Henley
</P>
<P>
   A: More than a couple of years ago _ it was a 1993 test market
product for Miller Brewing in Austin, Richmond and Minneapolis/St.
Paul. Not every product turns out to be Miller Lite. No more
exists. If it did, you would not want to drink it because the shelf
life of beer is about four months.This beer was sold in clear
bottles and regular cans and looked like 7Up with a head. The beer
taste was there, but no golden color, no amber bottle.
</P>
<P>
   UPSHOT/UPDATE/UPROAR:
</P>
<P>
   Equal time, folks. An estimated 150,000 balloons and 1,000
pounds of confetti (biodegradable all) rained on the Democratic
delegates after Vice President Al Gore's acceptance speech. Proving
the race is tight in more ways than one _ that is the same number
of balloons the Republicans dropped in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968. Due to the number of
inquiries, Jane cannot respond to every request.
</P>
