<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4039 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0829-CO     08-28 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zoning laws lack protection for those who came first
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Paul Thompson has a pig farm three miles west
of Stuart, Fla. where he, his wife, and the pigs have lived happily
since 1957 _ until recently. In the mid-1990s a developer bought
the neighboring land and built a golf course and some swanky
houses. Now they want the pig farmer to go because the newcomers
are objecting to the smell, and to the country music Farmer
Thompson plays most days to keep his porkers happy.
</P>
<P>
   You tell me _ who was there first?
</P>
<P>
   In Toledo, a bunch of folks built houses practically on top of
the approach lights to the city's airport and then formed an
alliance to complain of the noise. My question to them was: Who was
there first? Their answer: The airport, but we didn't know they
were going to fly so many airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Sure. Lots of cities build airports for show. The upshot is the
Port Authority is buying these folks all new, ultra-thick windows
and central air-conditioning to muffle the noise.
</P>
<P>
   Does that make sense?
</P>
<P>
   An attorney in New London, Conn. doesn't think so. After reading
my snappish column in his hometown newspaper, the New London Day,
he wrote of a similar case in New Hampshire _ with a twist. It
involves an egg farm established by a young couple back in 1961.
Here's what happened:
</P>
<P>
   ``Their farm was located in an agricultural zone and they moved
to New Hampshire specifically to locate an egg farm on that site,
as permitted under the local zoning laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``They invested several years of very hard work and several
hundred thousand dollars of expense to provide equipment, real
estate and buildings for the operation of their egg farm. To their
surprise a retiree arrived and built his `dream home' in the
agricultural zone, with full knowledge of the chicken farm next
door.''
</P>
<P>
   The newcomer then began complaining about the ``malodorous''
breezes wafting from the chicken farm when the wind was right (or,
in this case, wrong), and pretty soon the egg farmers, though
complying with all regulations and disposing of chicken manure and
waste in the prescribed manner, were out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``First,'' the attorney writes, ``the Superior Court of New
Hampshire granted an injunction and imposed a fine of $10,000 a day
for every day that the chicken farm continued in operation. An
appeal to the Supreme Court of New Hampshire
</P>
<P>
   followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``...the farmer offered to purchase the property of the
neighbor, a so-called `balancing of the equities'. The farmer
argued that even though the neighbor was a Johnny-Come-Lately, if
there was anything wrong then the most damages that could ever be
sustained could not exceed...what the retiree paid or the fair
market value of the retiree's property.
</P>
<P>
   The choices were, according to this attorney, ``(1) receive the
highest value of his property in damages and become a
Johnny-Come-Lately elsewhere; or (2) forget about his case and
continue to live in the neighborhood where he had chosen to live,
with the smells found in an agricultural zone. The Supreme Court of
New Hampshire declared itself a `clean-air-jurisdiction' and, in a
unanimous opinion, decreed that the chicken farm had to go; and it
did _ straight into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always amazed at the Johnny-Come-Latelys who, under the
banner of environmentalism, announce that they are in favor of
farms. They are in favor of keeping farms and they are in favor of
conservation zones and land preserves, but not if the deer eat the
flowers, or the chickens smell, and certainly not if the pigs
produce strong odors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fairness to all, those who wish to have residential home
sites should seek land in residential zones, not move in next to
airports, pig farms, chicken farms, and nibbling deer.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as we're talking about ``fair,'' why is it our
courts bust their backsides to protect the rights of murderers,
thieves, and other ``misunderstood'' segments of the population
while honest folks just keep on paying, and paying...and paying. It
seems to me what we're missing in this country of government ``by
the people and for the people,'' is a little equal ``and justice
for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
