<BODY>
 pat_nytimes
 Study Questions the Health Value of Catnaps  
 (Lead)  
 By RICHARD A. MARINI  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  &QL;  &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Siesta. Power nap. Forty winks.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the brief interval of rest is called, catching some Zs
in the afternoon is a tradition in many Latin American and
Mediterranean countries. And some companies in the United States
are promoting the midday snooze as a way to improve employee health
and productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Now wake up and smell the coffee. A study by Hannia Campos, a
researcher in the department of nutrition at the Harvard School of
Public Health, says nodding off for 20 to 30 minutes during the day
could be bad for your health.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the study, published in the International Journal
of Epidemiology, found that those who napped every afternoon had a
higher-than-average risk of suffering a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Campos said she was not surprised by these findings, despite
what she conceded is a common perception that naps are
heart-healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only published study I found on specific health benefits
of napping looked at a small group of agricultural workers who were
obviously very active and probably in fairly good health,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Campos' study compared about 500 Costa Ricans who had survived a
heart attack with an almost equal number of healthy people.
</P>
<P>
   When surveyed, those in the heart-attack group were 50 percent
more likely to have enjoyed a daily siesta than those from the
other group.
</P>
<P>
   These findings appear to be backed up by research showing that
heart attacks are more likely to occur in the morning. This is
thought to be due to a complex chemical reaction that occurs in the
body shortly after waking and increases heart rate and blood
pressure. Such changes may trigger a heart attack in those who are
already at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Campos said an afternoon nap may trigger the same reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Not all specialists agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to note that this study found only an
association between napping and heart attack, not a
cause-and-effect relationship,'' said Nora Walker, a
board-certified sleep physician in private practice in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who've had heart attacks often suffer sleep disorders,
meaning they have trouble getting to sleep and often wake up during
the night. This makes them tired during the day so they'll tend to
nap more. So it shouldn't be surprising that they're more likely to
have a heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Health experts recommend that people get the majority of sleep
at one time, preferably up to eight hours per day for adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' said Pat Britz of the National Sleep Foundations, ``if
you need it, a short, 20- to 30-minute nap will leave you rested,
refreshed and alert. This can be particularly important, especially
if you'll be driving or operating heavy equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by Hearst News Service. The Hearst Newspapers Web
site is at http://www.hearstcorp.com/news.html.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
