<HEADER>
A4049 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-AUDIO-BOOKS-HNS &LR;      08-28 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `BRETHREN' LIVES UP TO ITS BEST-SELLER STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following three audio books have one thing in common: Each
as a hardcover book has been near the top of the best-seller lists
this summer. That said, they enjoy little common ground. One comes
recommended without reservation, one with reservation and one you
are urged to steer clear of. In that order, they are:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Brethren,'' by John Grisham. Read by Michael Beck.
Abridged, approximately 6 hours. Bantam Doubleday Dell Audio
Publishing. $27.95.
</P>
<P>
   Grisham, the uber-successful author of countless legal
thrillers, is in top form with his latest _ though it is more a
political thriller than a courtroom drama. The brethren for whom
the book is titled are three aging former judges who have been
caught in various misdeeds, making them cellmates at a
minimum-security federal prison in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   With too much time on their hands, they have fine-tuned a mail
scam that includes extortion. This gives the three geezers a steady
stream of cash flowing into an offshore bank account. When their
scam happens to ensnare a CIA-influenced candidate for president,
the brethren find themselves challenged beyond their wildest
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The plotting is superb, the developments never completely
predictable. Grisham manages to portray the three judges with some
complexity, both smarmy and likable. Beck, who has performed six
previous Grisham best-sellers, deftly gives each character a voice.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Not A Day Goes By,'' by E. Lynn Harris. Read by Rocky
Carroll. Unabridged, approximately 6 hours. Bantam Doubleday Dell
Audio Publishing. $25.95.
</P>
<P>
   Harris has carved out a special niche amid the fast-growing
field of black writers fixated on romance and conspicuous
consumption. His books feature bisexual and/or gay characters
acting just as superficially as their straight colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' latest brings back John ``Basil'' Henderson, a former
pro football star turned sports agent who, as Henderson describes
it, ``likes to switch lanes.'' The book opens on the morning of
Henderson's wedding day to Yancy Braxton, an up-and-coming, overly
ambitious Broadway star.
</P>
<P>
   We learn in the prologue that the wedding isn't going to happen,
and for the better part of six hours get to hear the juicy,
ridiculous three-month roller-coaster ride that preceded the
scheduled wedding day. Carroll, a regular on the television series
``Chicago Hope,'' cannot be faulted for his reading. It's what
Carroll's reading that can be knocked and enjoyed simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Omerta,'' by Mario Puzo. Read by Joe Mantegna. Abridged,
approximately 5 hours. Random House AudioBooks. $25.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, we find that the adage ``dead men tell no tales'' is not
quite true. If only it were. ``Omerta,'' published almost a full
year after Puzo passed away, is a dreadful book, as lifeless as its
creator. Puzo demonstrated three decades ago with ``The Godfather''
that he could create terrific scenes and memorable characters, but
the energy that went into that seminal novel cannot be found in
``Omerta,'' billed as the final chapter in the author's Mafia
trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   This reads more like a parody of Puzo's best work, the plot
clumsy, the men and women in the story one-dimensional caricatures.
Mantegna is a fine reader, but even he cannot breathe life into a
corpse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
