r l BC-SCHOOL-GADGETS-HNS &LR;      08-28 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-GADGETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RECORDERS THAT EASE THE PAIN OF CLASS NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WILLIAM M. DOWD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has spent a lot of time in classrooms knows you often
miss a lot by taking handwritten notes.
</P>
<P>
   Jotting down what the lecturer just finished saying means you
miss a lot. Lugging around a clunky tape recorder is a drag, and
you always have to keep an eye on when the tape is going to run
out.
</P>
<P>
   Aaah, but what about a three-hour recorder that weighs just two
ounces? Or a nine-hour recorder that weighs about the same?
</P>
<P>
   Two of the best on the market are from Olympus and Voice Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympus Digital VN-180 ($119.95) also stores up to 300
messages and reminders, can have 20 different alarms set, puts
voice memos into 100-message folders, and you can edit content.
</P>
<P>
   The Voice Bank 9-Hour ($149.95) can record nine hours straight.
It also has four 99-message folders.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   FAUX SECURITY FOR THE DORM
</P>
<P>
   Sending the kiddies off to college to live in a wide-open dorm
or off-campus student apartment? Worried about their safety but
unable to afford the bucks it takes to install a security system?
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, fake it.
</P>
<P>
   For $19.95 you can buy a fake surveillance camera from Gadget
Universe that looks so much like the real thing your average stupid
intruder will be scared off _ unless, of course, your kid brags
about the device to all of his/her friends and word gets around.
</P>
<P>
   For details, call 800-478-4703 or check on line at
http://www.gadgetuniverse.com.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   DRAWING ON YOUR SKILLS
</P>
<P>
   Here's a great item for the budding school-age artist or just a
student who likes to illustrate a term paper or school project: The
Pablo-Internet Edition drawing tablet.
</P>
<P>
   It's from KB Gear Interactive and does a lot more than the
standard white computer drawing tablets you may have seen. This
8-by-6-inch device ($99) connects to a personal computer either by
USB or serial port connection.
</P>
<P>
   Using the pressure-sensitive pen, you can draw original art,
animate, photo edit, and so on, using the comprehensive software
suite (Adobe PageMill 3.0, Adobe Photoshop LE, WebPainter 3).
</P>
<P>
   Purchasing details: Call 612-656-6000, or check on line at
http://kbgear.com.
