<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-28 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLITICIANS SHOULD STOP EXPLOITING CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If the political exploitation of children were a
crime, most of our political leaders would be doing hard time.
</P>
<P>
   Put 'em away, I say. Three ``do it for the childrens'' and
you're out.
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican and Democratic conventions, children were
trotted out to sing, deliver slogans and represent the supposedly
compassionate policies of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   A group of children at the Democratic convention even had to
take the stage to recite lines like ``When I grow up, will innocent
kids still be wrongfully touched? Will students go home from school
in a bulletproof bus?''
</P>
<P>
   Wrongfully touched? What kid ever would say that? What kind of
twisted adult would make a kid say it?
</P>
<P>
   Those children were wrongfully dragged out on stage without
informed consent for the propaganda purposes of politicians. Some
day their friends will find old C-SPAN videotape of the event and
they'll never live it down.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of child exploitation happens so often nowadays we
don't even think it's wrong. We don't even realize we're being
played for saps.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Al Gore pointed out a child in the convention
audience who would have benefited from his health insurance plan.
Last week George W. Bush introduced children of a middle-class
couple who supposedly would benefit from his proposed tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Even nonparent Ralph Nader has got into the
do-it-for-the-children racket, going so far as to claim he has
millions of children all over the world. This is one puritan who
gets around.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the San Francisco Chronicle last week,
Nader said he wants to protect children from unhealthy corporate
influences such as violent TV, junk food and even computers donated
by companies to schools.
</P>
<P>
   One foresees Pokemon buy-backs, Teletubby burnings and activist
figures instead of action figures.
</P>
<P>
   Nader said he'd open federally funded ``children's community
centers'' but I'm not sure how much fun the kids will have in these
centers. Will they sit around playing Anti-Monopoly?
</P>
<P>
   In schools, Nader would teach reading and writing as a
``byproduct of contextual citizen skills,'' such as learning how to
file a Freedom of Information Act request, put on news conferences
and develop coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   Then kids can make coalition signs instead of gang signs. And
the school uniform will be unfashionable black suits.
</P>
<P>
   Nader may want to make kids eat spinach and read bureaucratese,
but at least he doesn't want to execute them or throw them into
prison with hardened adults.
</P>
<P>
   He's not a hypocrite like some politicians, who play upon
children's innocence, yet are quick to start the lethal injection
when a jury declares a child guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Americans say they love children, yet we tend to fear and hate
them.
</P>
<P>
   If we didn't fear kids, we'd discipline them.
</P>
<P>
   If we didn't hate kids, we wouldn't give them terrible schools,
ritual doses of Ritalin, parentally organized sports and, yes, the
junk food and TV Nader decries.
</P>
<P>
   Yet we say children are ``precious'' and ``must come first.''
Children are valuable, all right, as human shields for politicians
and special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want gun control say they're doing it for the
children. Those who want universal health care say they want to
start with children's health care. If these things are so right,
what's wrong with doing them for adults?
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream politician don't dare declare a war on poverty.
Instead they pull heartstrings by saying they want to fight child
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that children can't be accused of owning a welfare
Cadillac, unless it's a toy one.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes a child poor? It's not a lousy allowance. It's
poor parents.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has made an issue of child poverty because Texas under Bush
has the second-highest rate of child poverty in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But then, according to the United Nations Children's Fund, the
United States, of which Gore is second-in-command, has the
second-highest child poverty rate of 29 industrial nations. We're
just above Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   This country's 13.5 million poor children represent a lot of
poor parents our major candidates would rather not talk about. But
children are so innocent, they're always good to include in a
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are so innocent we've lost our innocence hundreds of
times, in everything from wars to school shootings. Maybe we're so
innocent we'll buy all the talk about children, education and
family values.
</P>
<P>
   If Nader is serious about his citizenship reading program, and
he's always serious, he'll include a course on political b.s.
detecting.
</P>
<P>
   Start by looking for the word ``children.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
