<P>
   THE `CAT FROM THE BRONX' IS A CLASSICAL ACTOR AT HEART
</P>
<P>
   WESLEY-SNIPES-STARBEAT _ Wesley Snipes doesn't deny that being
an action hero and scoring with audiences has given him clout in
Hollywood. ``I didn't get into the business to do action,'' he
reveals. ``I'm a classically trained actor and I love the more
dramatic stuff, whether it's in theater or in film. But doing films
like `The Art of War' (which opened Aug. 25) has afforded me the
opportunity to do other more sensitive projects. So I'm not
knocking it.'' By Jeanne Wolf. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FOR JAMIE FOXX, LUNACY EXTENDS TO ALL AREAS OF HIS LIFE
</P>
<P>
   JAMIE-FOXX-BAIT-STARBEAT _ Jamie Foxx had to bide his time in
comedy clubs and in TV comedies before his big film breakthrough in
Oliver Stone's 1999 hit, ``Any Given Sunday.'' ``I've always known
that once I got my foot in the door, people would eventually say,
`This kid has got the stuff,''' reveals Foxx, who's now starring in
``Bait'' (opening Sept. 15). But he is down to earth about his
fame. ``I've done a lot of work in a few short years and some
people might expect me to be cocky, but that's not true. In
Hollywood, we're all just commodities,'' he says. By Cindy
Pearlman. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR NEIL LABUTE CAN'T QUITE DEFINE HIS JOB
</P>
<P>
   LABUTE-NURSE-BETTY-STARBEAT _ ``Nurse Betty'' (opening Sept. 8)
will surely catch moviegoers and Neil LaBute aficionados off guard.
It features a woman in the central role and it's far sweeter than
director Neil LaBute's previous films. And although his earlier
films were not great hits, studios continue to take a gamble on
him, perhaps for his real talent, his vision and edge, and his
willingness to play on the cusp of the mainstream. ``I'm pleasantly
surprised that I keep getting to make my movies,'' LaBute says. By
Ian Spelling. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EMMY PICKS: WHO SHOULD WIN _ AND WHO WILL WIN
</P>
<P>
   EMMY-PICKS-STARBEAT _ If this year's Emmy nominations are any
indication, there are fewer than 20 worthwhile shows on TV right
now. The list of overlooked, quality series _ including ``Oz,''
``Action'' and even ``Buffy The Vampire Slayer'' _ is longer than
the list of Emmy nominees. Some of the shows, and the actors who
appear in them, that have the best chances of winning, however, are
``The West Wing,'' ``The Sopranos'' and ``Sex &AMP; The City.'' By
Kevin Dickson of TV Guide Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be published in Canada before Sept. 10. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
