<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4108 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-EMMY-PICKS-STARBEAT-A     08-28 1588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMY-PICKS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMMY PICKS: WHO SHOULD WIN _ AND WHO WILL WIN
</HEADLINE>
 
 EMBARGOED for use by CANADIAN CLIENTS until SEPT. 10.  (Includes a color photo of Jane Kaczmarek in ``Malcolm In The
Middle.'' Color photo of Nancy Marchand in ``The Sopranos'' is
available electronically. Call New York Times Syndicate photo
editor William Gonzalez at 800-972-3550 or 212-499-3355.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By KEVIN DICKSON 
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada 
 Not to be published in Canada before Sept. 10. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    If this year's Emmy nominations are any indication, there are
fewer than 20 worthwhile shows on TV right now. The list of
overlooked, quality series is longer than the list of Emmy nominees
_ including the technical categories! If ``Buffy The Vampire
Slayer'' doesn't get some cred next year with the Emmy voters, I'm
going after them with a stake.
 &HT;    The lack of recognition of ``Oz'' cast members Lee Tergesen,
Rita Moreno and Christopher Meloni, and the series itself is a
crime worthy of landing Emmy voters in Emerald City.
 &HT;    In its short TV life, ``Action'' proved itself to be the rarest
of network series: Gutsy, groundbreaking and brilliantly written, a
coal-black indictment of the Hollywood lifestyle with killer
left-hook punch lines. Illeanna Douglas' tour de force as Wendy,
the child-star-turned-hooker-turned-movie-producer was, for my
money, the year's standout performance.
 &HT;    With sour grapes out of the way, let's get on to the
nominations:
 &HT;    
 &HT;    OUTSTANDING LEAD ACTOR _ COMEDY
 &HT;    Kelsey Grammer's ``Frasier'' nomination is almost a knee-jerk
reaction. Same can be said for Ray Romano's, although John
Lithgow's continuing Emmy support becomes more questionable with
every passing season of ''3rd Rock.'' The series just isn't
providing him with the material any more. Eric McCormack in ``Will
&AMP; Grace'' has turned into the show's Jerry Seinfeld, with one
Elaine and two Kramers. This is important grounding for the
longevity of the show. Michael J. Fox's emotional last season on
``Spin City'' was unfortunately poorly written, denying the
talented and beloved TV actor the chance to retire on a high note.
 &HT;    Who Should Win: Eric McCormack
 &HT;    Who Will Win: Michael J. Fox
 &HT;    
 &HT;    OUTSTANDING LEAD ACTOR _ DRAMA
 &HT;    Jerry Orbach and Sam Waterston of ``Law And Order,'' and even
Martin Sheen of ``The West Wing,'' did not get the delicious
balance between hardass and softie that Dennis Franz (``NYPD
Blue'') and James Gandolfini (``The Sopranos'') got to investigate.
Points against Franz include the tear-jerker feel of his
character's leukemia story line. Hasn't this guy been through
enough? On the other hand, Gandolfini's Tony Soprano walked a
supremely nuanced line, continuing to make a vulnerable monster
lovable.
 &HT;    Who should win: James Gandolfini
 &HT;    Who will win: James Gandolfini
 &HT;    
 &HT;    OUTSTANDING LEAD ACTRESS _ COMEDY
 &HT;    There's no competition in this category. Jenna Elfman's kooky
Dharma is as stale as Woodstock acid. Patricia Heaton (``Everybody
Loves Raymond'') and Jane Kaczmarek (``Malcolm In The Middle'') do
good jobs as sitcom moms, but there's no heat there. Debra
Messing's Grace suffered this season from writers who were
determined to turn a successful, self-employed woman into a
neurotic update of Lucille Ball. Sarah Jessica Parker (``Sex &AMP; The
City'') leads the field by a mile with her finely tuned portrayal
of Carrie Bradshaw, the all-too-human romantic journalist.
 &HT;    Who should win: Sarah Jessica Parker
 &HT;    Who will win: Sarah Jessica Parker
 &HT;    
 &HT;    OUTSTANDING LEAD ACTRESS _ DRAMA
 &HT;    Solid performances by Amy Brenneman (``Judging Amy'') and Sela
Ward (``Once And Again'') will likely be eclipsed by the other
women in this category. Since ``The Sopranos'' didn't utilize
Lorraine Bracco much this season, the battle will be between her
co-star Edie Falco, who took Carmela Soprano to new heights of
frosty determination, and Julianna Margulies, whose tastefully
conflicted departure from ``ER'' was among TV's great sign-offs.
 &HT;    Who should win: Edie Falco
 &HT;    Who will win: Edie Falco
 &HT;    
 &HT;    OUTSTANDING SUPPORTING ACTOR _ COMEDY
 &HT;    Peter Boyle and Brad Barrett work well in ``Everybody Loves
Raymond,'' but don't stand out. David Hyde Pierce has turned Niles
into the jewel in the ``Frasier'' crown over the years, and his
value to the show is inestimable. Sean Hayes (``Will &AMP; Grace'') is
a laser blast of comic energy, and there's nothing quite like him
on TV these days. Still, it would be nice if the writers let him
calm down occasionally and develop a heart. Peter MacNicol's
slippery Cage (``Ally McBeal'') tempers the show's crazy-girl vibe,
but overall, ``Ally'' went south this year, which might hurt
MacNicol's chances.
 &HT;    Who should win: Peter MacNicol
 &HT;    Who Will Win: Sean Hayes
 &HT;    
 &HT;    OUTSTANDING SUPPORTING ACTOR _ DRAMA
 &HT;    Another powerhouse field, with two nods each for ``The
Practice'' (Michael Badalucco and Steve Harris) and ``The West
Wing'' (Richard Schiff and John Spencer), but it would be remiss
for the Emmy voters to overlook Dominic Chianese's tightly wound
portrayal of devious Uncle Junior in ``The Sopranos.'' Watching him
squirm the entire season under house arrest _ whether becoming
hooked on ``The Bold &AMP; The Beautiful'' or courting an elderly
admirer while still trying to run the business _ was one of this
year's guilty pleasures.
 &HT;    Who should win: Dominic Chianese
 &HT;    Who will win: Dominic Chianese
 &HT;    
 &HT;    OUTSTANDING SUPPORTING ACTRESS _ COMEDY
 &HT;    Let's face it _ if any of the female leads deserve an Emmy, it's
Courteney Cox Arquette, not nominees Lisa Kudrow and Jennifer
Aniston, whose characters veered awfully close to self-parody this
year. Doris Roberts shone with matriarchal glee on ``Raymond,'' but
didn't steal the show. Kim Cattrall could steal any scene she
appears in on ``Sex &AMP; The City,'' and it's a testament to her skill
as an actress that she knows when to pull back and give others the
spotlight. Megan Mullally, however, ain't afraid to chew the
scenery, and her hilarious schtick as the cashed-up lush is what
keeps millions of fans tuning in each week to ``Will &AMP; Grace.''
Mullally deserves the Emmy because this award is about acting _ and
Karen Walker couldn't be further from Mullally's sweet, earnest
real-life disposition.
 &HT;    Who should win: Megan Mullally
 &HT;    Who will win: Kim Cattrall
 &HT;    
 &HT;    OUTSTANDING SUPPORTING ACTRESS _ DRAMA
 &HT;    The real ``Sophie's Choice'' of the night. An incredibly strong
selection of actresses, all talented and blessed with great
scripts. Picking between ``The West Wing's'' Stockard Channing and
Allison Janney, ``Judging Amy's'' Tyne Daly, ``The Practice's''
Holland Taylor and ``The Sopranos''' Nancy Marchand would be like
choosing one of five perfect yet different diamonds of equal value.
It's a matter of taste. Sadly, Marchand's recent death prevents her
from running again next year, so let's give it to her.
 &HT;    Who should win: Nancy Marchand
 &HT;    Who will win: Nancy Marchand
 &HT;    
 &HT;    OUTSTANDING COMEDY SERIES
 &HT;    Of all the nominees, only ``Sex &AMP; The City'' is working outside
the standard sitcom formula, upping the ante of interpersonal
relationships and unexpected humor for the genre of TV comedy.
Three of the nominees, ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' ``Frasier'' and
``Friends,'' cannot count the 2000 season as their finest, and
while ``Will &AMP; Grace'' was able to build momentum from last year,
it's still maturing _ expect it to win this category next year.
 &HT;    Who should win: ``Sex &AMP; The City''
 &HT;    Who will win: ``Sex &AMP; The City''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    OUTSTANDING DRAMA SERIES
 &HT;    Surprising choices in this category, mostly due to the omission
of HBO's ``Oz'' in a year where ``ER'' and '' Law &AMP; Order''
faltered somewhat, and ``The Practice'' suffered from creator David
E. Kelly spreading himself a bit too thin. The second season shone,
but ``The Sopranos'' didn't weave as wicked a web as the first
season. The brilliant team of writer Aaron Sorkin and director
Tommy Schlamme turned ``The West Wing'' into riveting drama, which
clearly deserves to win this category, despite the shootout in the
last episode!
 &HT;    Who will win: ``The West Wing''
 &HT;    Who should win: ``The West Wing''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Kevin Dickson is Los Angeles correspondent for TV Guide
Canada) 
 &HT;    
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada 
<TEXT>
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features. &QL;
