<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABUTE-NURSE-BETTY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR NEIL LABUTE CAN'T QUITE DEFINE HIS JOB
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a color photo of director Neil LaBute on the set the
movie, ``Nurse Betty.'') 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By IAN SPELLING 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Directing, notes the man behind the acclaimed films, ``In the
Company of Men'' (1997) and ``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors'' (1999),
involves making a statement and shaping a piece of art. But it's
also about pleasing the masses, or at least some of the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're there to entertain an audience,'' film director Neil
LaBute says. ``If there's a statement, it's hopefully already in
the screenplay _ and you, the director, are just heightening it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entertainment can be something different, can be an artistic
expression. When I think of myself as a viewer, I look at
entertainment strictly as something that's good. It can shock me,
make me cry, surprise me or just make me laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute's latest film, ``Nurse Betty,'' which opens Sept. 8,
rates as both good and engaging, but also risky. Renee Zellweger
stars as Betty Sizemore, a small-town waitress who escapes her
boring existence and lousy husband Del (Aaron Eckhart) by
fantasizing about her favorite character, Dr. David Ravell (Gregg
Kinnear), on her favorite soap opera. Then, after witnessing Del's
brutal murder at the hands of father-and-son hit men, Charlie
(Morgan Freeman) and Wesley (Chris Rock), Betty loses her grip on
reality and heads to Los Angeles to reunite with Dr. Ravell, with
Charlie and Wesley hot on her trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty'' will surely catch moviegoers and LaBute
aficionados off guard. It features a woman in the central role and
it's far sweeter than LaBute's previous films or any of his plays,
among them ``Filthy Talk for Troubled Times,'' ``Sanguinarians &AMP;
Sycophants'' or ``bash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what drew me to it,'' LaBute, 37, said excitedly on a
recent trip to New York. ``I admired the script (by John C.
Richards and James Flamberg) because there were such familiar
elements, but they were done in a very clever way. They took me by
surprise constantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know exactly where anything was going to lead, and
that's the way I like to write _ and to watch _ something. The
writers conveyed a great regard for the characters throughout.
Reading this script, I felt the audience had really to like Betty
to see her through all the things she goes through.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone concerned that LaBute is turning soft need only watch the
sequence in which Wesley slays Del. Wesley doesn't just shoot, stab
or choke Del to death. He scalps him in a moment as nasty and
cold-blooded as anything ever depicted on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Gruesome as the scene is, it has been toned down significantly.
Test screening results impelled the director to pull back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I go the other way when people tell me to do
something, but in this case I watched the audience watch the scene
and they were very much taken aback,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris, even though he's the perpetrator of this event, wins
the audience back along the way. You find him funny. But I'd hit a
wall where I could feel the audience turn off ...''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute makes other significant strides as a filmmaker with
``Nurse Betty.'' It's vibrantly lit and full of long, wide shots
that soak in vistas and streets and crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew `Nurse Betty' required something different, so I worked
with a familiar production team, but a new cinematographer, Jean
Yves Escoffier, who had a great visual sense. And I relied a great
deal on him to create that more open look and feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also expanded a bit in terms of the actors I worked with.
They all have a lot more experience as actors than I do as a
director, but I felt ready to work with, stand up to or give in to
these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, for example, knows what's good for him as an actor. He
understands what works, and LaBute frequently deferred to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no ego involved,'' he says. ``It was all about what
was best for the performances, what was best for the movie. I
listened to everybody, and it was, `Whoever was right, let's go
with that.'''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute's earlier films didn't wow anyone at the box office and
chances are that ``Nurse Betty,'' which cost $25 million to
produce, won't rake in a fortune. Nevertheless, studios continue to
take the gamble on LaBute, who will next direct Aaron Eckhart and
Gwyneth Paltrow in a film version of ``Possession,'' a
time-tripping romantic drama based on the novel by A.S. Byatt.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they appreciate real talent and that LaBute possesses
both a vision and an edge. It's also possible that they see a guy
who's willing to play on the cusp of the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleasantly surprised that I keep getting to make my
movies,'' LaBute says. ``I understand that this is a business. You
put something in and you hope to get more out than you put in. I'm
very clear-eyed about that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Neil LaBute, director of ``Nurse
Betty,'' consult the official web site at www.nurse-betty.com. And
check out The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL;
</P>
