<HEADER>
A4110 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-JAMIE-FOXX-BAIT-STARB     08-28 1499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMIE-FOXX-BAIT-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR JAMIE FOXX, LUNACY EXTENDS TO ALL AREAS OF HIS LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a color photo of Jamie Foxx in a scene from ``Bait.'') 
 ART NOTE: A color caricature by Vance Lehmkuhl of Jamie Foxx as he
appears in ``Bait'' is available for purchase. 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN 
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Jamie Foxx, lunacy extends to all areas of his life. Take
his name. On his birth certificate, he is simply Eric Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would go to these open-mike nights and I realized that women
got more time up at the mike,'' Foxx explains. So early in his
comedy career he changed his name. ``It was crazy. I would hear the
MC say, `Jamie Foxx? Where is she? We've got plenty of time for her
act!'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, now Hollywood has plenty of time for his act. Foxx is
hot these days. And he knows the secret of his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make it easy for Hollywood. You don't have to teach me much
anymore because I've been around. Just give me a script. I just
have to learn my lines and then let me go,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Foxx gets his name above the title in ``Bait,'' which opens
Sept. 15. He plays Alvin Sanders, a man tossed in jail for stealing
a prawn. But old Alvin's services are needed when a treasury agent
(David Morse) enlists the con as bait to catch a dangerous thief
(Doug Hutchison) who is planning a gold heist at the U.S. Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks that somewhere in jail Alvin picked up a
secret code that leads people to the gold,'' describes Foxx. ``It's
really a story, though, about redemption because all Alvin wants to
do is go straight so he can be with his girlfriend (played by
Kimberly Elise).
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are a lot of obstacles in his way, including the
cops, his rotten brother (played by Mike Epps) and all these
criminals who want to lure him back into the life,'' Foxx adds.
</P>
<P>
   The life, for Foxx, is movies. After a star-making turn last
Christmas in Oliver Stone's football epic, ``Any Given Sunday,''
the comic actor knew that he would not be content to stay on the
small screen for long.
</P>
<P>
   Why did it take him so long to get to the multiplexes? ``You
know what's sad? I was so wrapped up in `The Jamie Foxx Show' for
so many years that I had no idea of what movie scripts were
actually out there,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, I would watch a great movie come out and say,
`Damn, why didn't anybody call me?''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Oliver Stone did just that for ``Any Given Sunday.''
And Foxx got his big film breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Foxx couldn't believe he got the call. ``I remember going over
to read for Oliver Stone. I thought it was for a smaller part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically you know when an audition is awful because the
director just sits there not saying much. You never hear, `What the
hell are you doing?' It's just total silence followed by, `Thanks
Jamie, you're not good for this one,''' he says, wincing. Stone
said just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back and read for another part and Oliver shook his
head again. I was like, `Is it me? Am I missing something?' But
Oliver said, `I dig you. And as a matter of fact the lead role is
open. Do you think you can do it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Rapper Sean ``Puff Daddy'' Combs originally had the lead but had
pulled out of the film when the shooting schedule changed. But the
studio wasn't sold on the idea of Foxx, who didn't have much of a
name at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to put myself on tape. I said, `This is what we going to
do. I'll get six of my friends. We'll do a mock training camp. I'll
pretend I'm the new rookie and I'm getting out of a Mercedes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I wore my favorite Dallas Cowboys jersey. I even came up with
a rap, `I'm Willie Beemer. I keep the ladies screamin'.'''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. saw his tape and was convinced, which later lead to
the studio and director Antoine Fuqua (``The Replacement Killers'')
casting Foxx as the lead in ``Bait.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always known that once I got my foot in the door, it
would just be a matter of time before people said, `This kid has
got the stuff,''' Foxx says.
</P>
<P>
   Foxx's own story has all the right stuff for a movie script. He
was born as Eric Bishop on Dec. 13, 1967 in Terrell, Texas. His
mother Louise experienced tough times when her marriage to Jamie's
father hit the skids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have money, but I was not allowed to become a punky
kid,'' Foxx says. ``I had the type of childhood where you weren't
allowed to hang out on the streets. I was put in Boy Scouts. I was
in the church choir.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also the quarterback of his high school football team. As
an athlete, Foxx was good enough that major Dallas newspapers
predicted he'd someday join the NFL. ``I had quite a following as
an athlete,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   There was a flipside to such young fame. ``It was a lot of
pressure. It was vicious. The fans would actually boo a 15-year-old
kid for missing a pass. Your self-esteem was nothing after those
kinds of games,'' Foxx says.
</P>
<P>
   But his lowest moment? ``The preacher of my church booed me like
I had sinned. He was screaming, `Lord have mercy! Boo. Foxx
stinks,''' says Foxx. ``This was my preacher! But it was a good,
humbling lesson in not believing in your own hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Foxx eventually ditched sports to study music in college, but
that fell by the wayside in 1989 when a girlfriend dared him to go
onstage during an open-mike night at a Dallas comedy club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started talking. I don't even remember what I said that
night. But I could feel the waves of laughter,'' he says. ``It was
like lightbulbs had gone off in my head. This is where I
belonged.''
</P>
<P>
   After logging time at comedy clubs across America, the producers
of the TV series ``In Living Color'' caught Foxx's act and cast him
in 1990. The following year, he was cast on the TV series ``Roc.''
</P>
<P>
   Movie roles followed including ``The Truth About Cats &AMP; Dogs''
(1996), ``The Great White Hype'' (1996), ``Booty Call'' (1997),
``The Players Club'' (1998) and ``Any Given Sunday'' (1999).
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he finally released his first album, ``Peep This,'' and
two years later, he created ``The Jamie Foxx Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Foxx is down to earth about his fame. ``When it comes to
Hollywood, we're all commodities,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done a lot of work in a few short years and some people
might expect me to be cocky, but that's not true,'' Foxx says. ``I
can easily be shut up. I'll meet a great director or actor and I
want to change everything I ever thought about life. I'm that much
into the art.''
</P>
<P>
   Foxx is upset about the lack of movie roles for African American
males. But he doesn't blame Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear brothers complain and say, `If only I was white.' I say
back, `Are you ever going to be white? No? Then stop complaining
and get to work. Find the right scripts. Get on with it. Don't talk
about how bad it is out there. Do something to fix it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a black man in Hollywood is not the most difficult
thing. It's also hard being a black man in society,'' Foxx says.
``But you've got all these different things you can do about it
now. Start your own production company. Write a script. Haul
yourself around to meetings. Stop whining and get to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Foxx says he isn't immune to an occasional pity party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said at times, `Damn it, if I were white I'd be in that
film. No longer do I say those kinds of things. I say, `Damn it, if
I just looked for a good role, I would be in a film.'''
</P>
<P>
   These days he is being considered for most of the good roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a wonderful ride,'' Foxx says. ``I look at my life
and think, `You could be doing a lot worse things.'''
</P>
<P>
   He could still be at those open-mike nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd still be hearing guys saying, `When is that Jamie girl
going to go on? I hope she's hot,'' he says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Jamie Foxx in the movie,
``Bait,'' consult the official web site at www.baitmovie.com. And
check out The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------------------------------- &QL;
</P>
