<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4127 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-WAR-HNS &LR;      08-28 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-WAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NOT MUCH ART IN WESLEY SNIPES' `WAR' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note cast box at end)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The Art of War,'' Wesley Snipes squares off against a
cartel of designer Chinese killers, and, to the surprise of perhaps
only his trail of dead, he looks better than they do in a leather
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   He'd probably look even better if the director and the
photographer had any idea how to light him. But Snipes doesn't seem
to have been hired to appear dashing or be terribly pensive. His
job is to run, kick, shoot, punch and be punched, and if he can
escape from a fight with his appeal as a matinee idol intact, more
power to him.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he and his stunt double are chained to
inexplicable action sequences that probably make more sense as
something you'd encounter at a PlayStation. As plot detours,
they're lame. Of course, this is also a movie that believes it has
discovered some ancient Chinese secret by naming itself after the
Sun Tzu military philosophy handbook. Sun's manipulation treatise
dates back at least 2,500 years, and so do the cliches rolled out
here.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell which was more inspirational: those writings
or every martial-arts flick ever made. Famous passages are spoken,
in ``The Art of War,'' by the likes of Donald Sutherland and Anne
Archer. You can see how they're meant to complement the tale of
international corruption the screenwriters don't seem to
understand.
</P>
<P>
   What we have is one of those ripped-from-the-headlines numbers
that, accordingly, has its characters walk and talk in tabloid. In
Archer's case the news sounds like it's being delivered by a
phone-sex attendant. She keeps hinting at a different kind of art
and a different kind of war. So do Snipes' needless ``snooping''
excursion to a Chinatown sex club and his demand that his
mysterious gal Friday (Marie Matiko) debug by tossing her clothes
out of the passenger-side window.
</P>
<P>
   But it's one caution-to-the-wind too many. Matiko plays a United
Nations translator with ties to an assassinated U.N. ambassador,
and wardrobe seems determined to keep her a 9-7-6 fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Snipes plays Neil Shaw, a covert operator framed for the murder
of the ambassador. He's a member of one of those highly classified
teams that does the surreptitious international bullying when
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's schedule doesn't permit.
Snipes glides along the margins of a far-reaching international
cabal involving the Chinese government. He actually gets North
Korea to submit to peace talks _ it must be the high-kicking and
that tuxedo. And we get a whiff of what a seductive Bond Snipes
would make.
</P>
<P>
   He also seems to be having fun pretending he's in a ``Mission:
Impossible'' dream. (At some point, for some reason, Snipes is
dressed to look like U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.) But
Christian Duguay isn't a director so much as a plagiarist with no
panache. (But his next assignment is the third ``Terminator,''
anyway.) When Snipes is framed minutes before China signs a pivotal
trade agreement, the film plunges into perpetual dinginess.
</P>
<P>
   Plot twists are served, but they have to curl through the plot
holes first. Thirty minutes in, Maury Chaykin shows up as an FBI
special agent, and I wanted to cash in my chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just like wrestling,'' he observes. It's also like
``The Matrix'' and all the staples in the Wesley Snipes oeuvre. But
just when you're ready to forgive ``The Art of War,'' a rumble
breaks out in the lower lobby of the United Nations, and a gun
spins through a plate-glass replica of the organization's trademark
insignia. And suddenly, peace talks never looked so stupid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of War''
</P>
<P>
   CAST Wesley Snipes, Anne Archer, Donald Sutherland, Marie Matiko
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR Christian Duguay
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS Wayne Beach and Simon Barry
</P>
<P>
   RATED R
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4140 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-COKE-USA29-COX     08-28 1866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-USA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marketing realities bring Coca-Cola into new era
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The World of Coca-Cola is located next to Underground
Atlanta. But the New World of Coca-Cola is on the 14th floor of the
company's U.S. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Step out of the elevator and you'll experience a work
environment previously unknown to Big Red or its employees here.
</P>
<P>
   Drab gray carpet has been ripped up and replaced by a concrete
floor with chipped pieces of Coke bottles glazed into it.
</P>
<P>
   A bank of TV sets is stationed just a few yards from a fake Coke
fountain motif with countertop and stools.
</P>
<P>
   Right across from the ``media fountain'' is the ``bubble
conference room'' for the marketing and advertising gurus to bubble
up the latest ideas promoting their fizzy products. The room's main
wall is frosted glass, highlighted by sporadic see-through shapes
of round and oval bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   The floor, which houses the marketing, ad and innovation staff,
is organized in collective work bays to foster increased
communication _ both planned and spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creativity doesn't happen in cages,'' said Jeff Dunn, who is
now deputy president of Coca-Cola's North America operations but
will take over as president in October.
</P>
<P>
   There are many more conference rooms and far fewer partitions
and individual offices than in the rest of the building. The
conference rooms range from small ``cabins'' to large ``brand
trailers'' _ with walls made of erasable whiteboards so the
marketing and ad people can do their thing.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the ``consumer immersion room,'' with its
un-Coke-like orange floor and Jetsons-like chairs, where teens can
come and unwind while brand marketers pick their brains about the
latest fads.
</P>
<P>
   While dramatic, the recent changes on the 14th floor are more
than cosmetic. Coke execs and employees say they symbolize the
wholesale transformation taking place to turn the company around
after lagging profits and stock performance.
</P>
<P>
   Reshaping the North American operation _ the company's largest
regional group _ is key to the turnaround. And the challenges are
substantial.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, after posting gains for most of the decade, Coca-Cola's
carbonated soft drink business in the United States suffered a
decline in case sales while Pepsico and the overall industry posted
modest growth, according to Beverage Digest.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, several industry analysts and observers worry that
U.S. consumers' love affair with carbonated soft drinks, especially
colas like Coke Classic, may be on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cola growth has been slow for a long time, and now we're
seeing a slowdown for brands like Sprite, Mountain Dew and Dr
Pepper,'' said John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage
Digest. ``Part of this has to do with increased pricing, but part
also has to do with consumers' growing interest in bottled water
and noncarbonated beverages, such as SoBe, Snapple and the sports
drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   To deal with a potential change in taste buds, the company needs
to become a nimble innovator of new brands and products. But its
North American operation, which includes the United States and
Canada, has not had a particularly good record of innovating over
the past several years. Some analysts say it has been averse to
taking risks and bureaucratic in decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   All that, however, is in the process of changing, Dunn and Steve
Jones, the company's worldwide chief marketing officer, said in
recent interviews with The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a dramatic shift in orientation,'' Dunn said. ``I
think it's just common sense. We need creativity, innovation and
new thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   But not too much thinking, especially if it inhibits action.
Coke has the reputation for studying an issue to the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistake you can make is overthinking,'' said Pina Sciarra,
brand director for Sprite and several other company beverages.
``You can miss the opportunity. ... We can't be so perfectionist.
Let's try some things.'' Sciarra, Dunn and Jones are trying to
implement Chairman Doug Daft's ``think local, act local'' mantra,
with hopes of creating a sleeker, more responsive company that
understands consumers better than it ever did before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a one-drink-at-a-time business,'' Dunn said. ``You build
it on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why, Dunn said, Coke North America is transferring many
employees closer to the ground level, where its drinks are sold. In
the past, Dunn said, between 90 percent and 95 percent of the
decisions affecting the U.S. market were made in Atlanta, either by
corporate or North American executives. Less than 10 percent of
those decisions were made locally.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, about half the decisions are made in Atlanta,
while the other half are being made at the regional or local level.
The company has divided its North American market into 12 regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're shortening the fuse between the local market and the
local decision-maker,'' Sciarra said. ``It's more real-time.'' Some
decisions are now being made in three weeks, compared with six
months under the old system.
</P>
<P>
   One of those decisions involved Coke's bottled water product,
Dasani, and Webvan, the online grocery delivery service. Coke
discovered that the demographics for both Dasani and Webvan _ busy
women over 25 who are looking for ways to simplify their lives _
are quite similar.
</P>
<P>
   So, in three weeks' time, the Dasani marketers came up with a
special promotion that gave a free six-pack to Webvan customers. If
the recipients buy Dasani five times through Webvan, they get
another free six-pack. It's a straightforward promotion that didn't
get lost for months somewhere in the Atlanta bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did a letter of intent between Coke and UPromise, which
was inked in 30 days, instead of what would have taken six months
under the old system, Dunn said. The deal, announced two weeks ago,
will set up tax-deferred savings accounts for kids, financed by
rebates from their Coke purchases as well as purchases by their
parents and grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to make consumers more brand loyal over the long
haul _ year in and year out _ not just from one short-term
promotion to another.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term strategic alliances will become more common for Coke
in the United States, Dunn said, partly because of the knowledge
the company gets about consumers without having to reinvent the
wheel. America Online, for example, knows more about how consumers
use the Internet than Coke does. That's why the beverage giant
signed a multiyear agreement to develop innovative marketing
programs with the nation's largest Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 50 alliances in the hopper right now, in the
negotiating stage,'' Dunn said. ``We're much more open to different
types of business relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these alliances, Dunn said, the company is
changing its philosophy on introducing new products. Over the past
seven years in the United States, he said, Coca-Cola introduced
``very few big, new products. ... We didn't take many swings at the
plate.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, the company is poised to take many more swings, hoping
to at least hit some singles, if not home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be many smaller new products and packages,'' Dunn
said. ``Maybe one out of 10 will work. But it increases the odds,
and we'll be learning.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited Red Flash, a sweet and fruity carbonated soft drink
recently developed for central and south Texas that will be rolled
out to some other markets in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Coke is also experimenting with a smoothielike coffee beverage
in four U.S. markets, which will be sold at fountains _ not in
bottles or cans.
</P>
<P>
   While it sells canned ``Georgia Coffee'' in Japan, it has no
bottled or canned coffee product in the United States. That left a
void in the portfolio of its biggest bottler, Coca-Cola
Enterprises. So Atlanta-based CCE has decided to start distributing
``Planet Java'' bottled coffee in New York. The coffee is owned by
a Queens company.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn described CCE's deal with Planet Java as a ``short-term
relationship'' that will provide important information to both CCE
and Coke, which owns 40 percent of the bottler.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn would not specifically comment on Coke's coffee plans in
the United States, or on what other new products may be on the
drawing board. But he said the U.S. innovation team is now fully
staffed and ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer wants more variety and choice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, the company must grow its major
brands, such as Coke Classic, Diet Coke and Sprite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foundation of the North American business is cola and,
therefore, the sustenance of that segment is vital to the overall
health of Coke's North American beverage business,'' said Scott
Wilkins, an analyst with Banc of America Securities. ``So much of
your basic business is cola. Clearly you have to reconnect with the
teenager, thereby lessening your dependence on the older cola
drinker. The marketing has to be clever enough to give new
consumers a reason to drink cola.''
</P>
<P>
   The company recently started airing new TV ads for Classic, with
more on the way targeting the teens Wilkins talks about.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sprite, which has been languishing lately after 12 years
of dramatic growth, the company will begin a new promotion
targeting online teenagers. Sprite has teamed with RocketCash, an
online gateway that allows teens to shop for a variety of products,
including music, books, sportswear and electronic games, without
using a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Oct. 15 and running at least through the end of next
year, Sprite will try to entice those teens to go to Sprite.com to
find out how much money they won from under a bottle cap.
</P>
<P>
   More than a billion caps on three different Sprite bottle sizes
will have a special code, indicating prizes from 20 cents to $1
that can be deciphered only on the Web site. That money can then be
used to purchase goods from RocketCash merchants. Each teen with an
account also can supplement it with money orders, checks or gift
certificates.
</P>
<P>
   Reinvigorating Coca-Cola's key brands in the United States is
critical. Dunn believes the combination of new and existing
products will allow the company to beef up its growth rate in case
sales to 4 percent to 6 percent annually. Last year, by contrast,
volume grew only 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A better performance in the United States is needed, Dunn said,
for Coca-Cola to hit its worldwide target of 7 percent to 8 percent
annual growth, which is what Wall Street expects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke will definitely return to higher growth in the U.S. in
the balance of this year and next year,'' said Sicher, of Beverage
Digest. ``How strong that growth is depends on the pricing
environment, the success of its new advertising and marketing, and
its product innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With its resources and powerful bottling system and brands,
there is no reason Coke shouldn't be poised for another chapter of
strong growth and success. That's the challenge, and that's the
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
