<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ARCHITECT WHO HELPED CLINTON RENOVATE GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case you haven't noticed, what Democratic political
consultant Celinda Lake calls ``the dreaded F word'' is making a
strong comeback across the ideological spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the federal government, of course. Whether it's
performance or need or the economy or whatever, the change in image
and confidence from Ronald Reagan's ``the problem'' of 20 years ago
to something Al Gore and George W. Bush compete to harness is
stunning.
</P>
<P>
   The thought occurred to me last week as President Clinton was
quietly marking (in newfound deference to Gore's presidential
campaign) the fourth anniversary of welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Joining federal and state governments to the private and
nonprofit sectors to help stimulate and manage the transition from
dependency to self-sufficiency by 1.1 million welfare recipients
was at the heart of the president's vetoes of the first two
versions of welfare reform to reach his desk more than four years
ago, when he was battling the Newt Gingrich-led revolution that
wasn't. Clinton's final decision to sign a third, improved bill
divided Democrats, but the new law opened the door to what is now
called welfare to work, a work in progress that has had
considerable success to date.
</P>
<P>
   And it opened another door to service by an old Clinton friend
who stands as a symbol of the change in thinking about government
that is going to be one of the administration's legacies. He was
one of those who thought the president should not have signed the
welfare reform legislation, even in its third form, but who says
today, simply, ``I was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Eli Segal is hanging out on Martha's Vineyard these days,
contemplating the rest of his barely middle-age life and waiting
for the completion of the building in Boston where his new condo
awaits, as befits a successful businessman who has been dabbling in
politics for a good 30 years. As Segal likes to say, his life until
1992 was ``a combination of business ventures and support of losing
Democratic presidential candidates,'' from George McGovern through
Gary Hart.
</P>
<P>
   But old pal Clinton changed his life. Instead of the top White
House job he thought he coveted after running the campaign
headquarters in Little Rock in 1992, Segal was given what turned
into a far more rewarding challenge: leading the effort to create,
sell, and then run in its formative period the national service
program Clinton had championed as a candidate and that new-thinking
Democrats had been championing for years, all the way back to
Robert Kennedy in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The result is Americorps, which, with something around 150,000
alumni, has twice the number in just a few years that the Peace
Corps has from its own proud history of nearly 40 years. For help
with college bills, young people give a year at very low pay of
service as everything from tutors to urban cleanup workers. By
broad consensus it works for both the kids and the communities.
</P>
<P>
   It also works because in setting it up, Segal had the sense to
reach out for maximum local inputs, local business support, and
Republican help. Americorps does not have the media cachet the
Peace Corps does, but in the areas it serves, its roots are very
deep. This is a classic example of a public-private partnership
that ends up being more than the sum of its parts.
</P>
<P>
   And that is almost exactly the philosophy that Segal relied on
when Clinton tapped his buddy again four years ago to chair the
partnership created to make welfare to work more than just a name.
The results can't be summarized just by the numbers _ more than a
million hires within some 20,000 participating firms, plus some
50,000 hired by the federal government in an effort overseen by
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Just the sales job by Segal has been impressive. What is even
more impressive has been the way the partnership has changed both
the culture of business and the culture of poverty. The latest
report to Clinton from key CEOs involved in all this (representing
the likes of United Airlines, Marriott, and Sprint) reflects
important lessons. Among the most important is that the very idea
of risk associated with participation in this venture needs
reassessment in light of the higher retention rates exhibited by
most former welfare recipients getting their first real test of
real opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Equally impressive in the CEOs report is their understanding of
how much more needs to be done to make work pay, including
restoring funds cut from food stamp budgets and increasing
participation in Medicaid and child care programs.
</P>
<P>
   But the results so far are stunning. That these results were in
part the work of a guy who had just helped create another major
public-private partnership is even more stunning. Not a bad eight
years of work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
