<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4145 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ARTS-DUMBING-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     08-28 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-DUMBING-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... did Stravinsky.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new economics of the arts has enhanced the experience of
audiences and performers alike, says Ellen Highstein, director of
the Tanglewood Music Center. In the classical music realm, ``there
was the option of not paying attention to the rest of the world for
a long time.'' That is no longer the case. ``Organizations are
looking for new ways to present material'' to audiences made up of
people who may not all fully understand, say, ``a Mahler
symphony,'' she says, ``but all can appreciate it on different
levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to do is to make people comfortable. That doesn't
mean playing easy-listening music or the equivalent thereof. By and
large, people are pretty smart and know when they're being pandered
to. The key is connecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecting and ``contextualizing,'' says Ben Cameron, executive
director of the Theater Communications Group. Theatrical producers
now invite audiences to post-performance discussions, particularly
of new plays. ``Ten years ago,'' he says, ``a dramaturge would come
out and say `Here is how you should interpret this work; this is
the author's intent.' '' Today's audiences, who see theater as a
participatory and social experience, aren't interested, and ``arts
organizations are surrendering power,'' he says. ``Audiences are
taking their authority to interpret away.''
</P>
<P>
   Presenting work in contexts that draw nontraditional audiences
to the once elite arts is ``enriching the arts right now,'' says
Steve Maler, director of Commonwealth Shakespeare Company. People
who've never been exposed to Shakespeare are experiencing it, and
those who've only read it are ``seeing it as drama _ a public event
_ which is how it is meant to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on is quite the opposite of dumbing down.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How does a surge of public enthusiasm for Puccini, Mozart, and
Verdi square with the contention that ``high culture'' is dumbing
down?
</P>
<P>
   --The US opera audience grew by nearly 25 percent between 1982
and 1992. According to Opera America, there are 114 professional
opera companies in the United States today. More than half of those
have been established since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   --The National Endowment for the Arts reports that in 1997, the
most recent year for which figures are available, nearly 5 percent
of the public saw at least one opera.
</P>
<P>
   --While many arts organizations are worried about the
``graying'' of their audiences, the median age of opera attenders
is dropping. Nearly one-third of the US opera audience is under the
age of 35.
</P>
<P>
   --The opera audience is racially and ethnically diverse. In
1997, minority group members were better represented in opera
audiences than in most arts and sports.
</P>
<P>
   --Opera is drawing people interested in both the old and the
new. Between 1990 and 2000 the number of North American works
produced by opera companies in the United States doubled.
</P>
<P>
   --Boston Lyric Opera is one of the fastest growing in its
league. In 1992, the Lyric counted 1,371 subscribers. In 1998, the
last year the company performed at the Emerson Majestic Theatre, it
sold 5,000 season subsciptions. Since it has moved to the Shubert
Theatre and expanded its program, the Lyric has grown again. In
late July, a spokeswoman said the organization had filled 7,038
orders for season tickets for the 2000-2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   Opera America attributes the success to the crossover influence
of pop culture: Broadway shows such as ``Tommy'' and ``The Phantom
of the Opera,'' which have spurred interest in the art form;
audience outreach and accessibility, primarily through the use of
surtitles; and the fact that many operas tell big, visually
elaborate stories set to music _ in much the way that MTV does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4147 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-INNOCENCE-BOS &LR;      08-28 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-INNOCENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TASTE OF GOTHIC POP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
INNOCENCE 
By Jane Mendelsohn. Riverhead Books. 199 pp. $21.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As she more than confirmed with her best-selling 1996 novel, ``I
Was Amelia Earhart,'' Jane Mendelsohn knows a good myth when she
sees one. Combining a savvy intelligence with lyrical prose, she
recognized in the Earhart legend all the fertile ground that lies
between fable and history _ all the hopes and dreams and dark
what-ifs, enhanced by her own free-for-all imagination. This
shrewdness of judgment is not all that common in literary fiction,
where a certain loftiness of vision can preclude steelier insights
about democratic tastes. Mendelsohn has an appreciation for both:
She may love a finely wrought sentence for its own sake, but she
also understands why America might fall for the bedtime story
behind it.
</P>
<P>
   She grasps the allure of ``Carrie'' as well as ``Sister
Carrie,'' in other words, as ``Innocence'' testifies. It's a minor
but sophisticated little piece of Gothic Pop _ sinister, campy, as
sure of its intentions as Norman Bates. Borrowing classic
ingredients from the genres of horror films and popular literature,
Mendelsohn has concocted a coming-of-age tale about a Manhattan
girl's adolescence; this is a story of innocence, all right, but
that nebulous concept today means finding your way in a
media-saturated, sometimes dangerous culture. If Beckett Hirsch,
our desperate, likable protagonist, seems frozen somewhere between
``Revenge of the Vampire Sluts'' and ``Catcher in the Rye,'' that's
because the world she's grown up in is beholden to both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Innocence'' began as a film treatment, and you can feel that
cinematic tilt from its opening scenes: shadowy fears and noir
angles and cross-cutting through time and space. (Mendelsohn is one
of the few people in America to have read the wonderfully titled
sleeper ``Men, Women, and Chainsaws: Gender in the Modern Horror
Film,'' and she acknowledges author Carol J. Clover for borrowing
the concept herein of the Final Girl _ the last heroine left
standing.) Having just moved to the Upper West Side from Long
Island with her father, Beckett is in some ways an archetypical
teenager: navigating her way through school cliques, encountering
the joys and terrors of sex, falling in love with a sweet kid named
Tobey. But the monster waiting in the wings is one who has already
taken vengeance: Beckett and her dad have moved back to Manhattan
because they just lost her mom to a drunk driver on the highway.
``Great heroines have dead mothers,'' she announces in the novel's
opening pages. ``That's what I told myself when she died.''
</P>
<P>
   That tone _ laconic and edgy and begrudgingly tragic _ suffuses
``Innocence,'' and makes the novel engaging in an eyebrow-cocked
kind of way. Watching Beckett's nightmares unfold, one feels
admiring but distant _ it's like watching a scary movie and
applauding its special effects instead of screaming over them. Dead
bodies appear in one of the first scenes of the novel; there are
also, fairly quickly, a rash of suicides, a demonic school nurse,
an untrustworthy shrink, and a dominatrix lurking in a basement
hallway. Beckett, marked as the Final Girl from the outset, is the
predator's mark _ a good girl by default, fighting evil and
banality and wicked witches everywhere she turns.
</P>
<P>
   But just how demented is this little Upper West Side universe?
Is Beckett really in peril, or are we seeing the unfolding of a
terrifying hallucination _ and thus listening to the ultimate
treacherous narrator, the voice of madness? Do the blood-stained
visions that Beckett shares with us belong to her own repressed
rage, a thirsty gang of uptown vampires, or the monthly mix of fear
and sexuality that every teenage girl can anticipate? So _
``Waiting for Menarche''! With its slippery descent into the world
of Eros and Thanatos, ``Innocence'' provides a simultaneous
allegory and sendup of such universal themes: It's an absurdist,
creepy entertainment cloaked in its own ironic commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the cheerful B-movie director, Mendelsohn tips her willing
audience to this device early on, when in English class Tobey is
introduced to the concept of the unreliable narrator. ``Oh,'' says
Tobey. ``So you mean like it's okay to lie.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the teacher counsels the student; it's a literary technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool,'' Tobey retorts, assuming position. ``I had sex with
every girl in this school.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the mouths of punks: Somehow this scene _ funny,
unpretentiously candid _ suggests the overall mood of
``Innocence,'' in spite of the shadowy milieu it assumes. The novel
is onto itself as well as the formulas it exposes, offering a
darkly appealing glance at popular culture and modern urban mayhem.
Like Jeffrey Eugenedies's ``The Virgin Suicides'' and Jay
McInerney's ``Bright Lights, Big City,'' Mendelsohn's story muffles
its death and sorrow in terminal irony, though the trait is less
irritating than it might be because ``Innocence'' doesn't try to be
more than it is. Following in the footsteps of all the Final Girls
who have gone before _ ``Persephone, Dorothy, Lolita,'' Beckett
tells us _ this heroine, too, tries to find her way back home. But
her yellow brick road is more redolent of subway tunnel than
flower-strewn path; in ``Innocence,'' there's nary a munchkin in
sight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
