<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTHING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIAN AMBROSE RECREATES A NATION'S UNIFYING MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
NOTHING LIKE IT IN THE WORLD 
The Men Who Built the Transcontinental Railroad 1863-1869 
By Stephen E. Ambrose. Simon &AMP; Schuster. 416 pp. Illustrated. $28. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theodore D. Judah, the visionary who dreamed of building a
transcontinental railroad, called the notion ``the most magnificent
project ever conceived.'' The effort, said William Tecumseh
Sherman, would be ``a work of giants.'' The New York Tribune called
it ``the great absorbing fact of the West.'' And Stephen E. Ambrose
called it ``the greatest engineering achievement of the nineteenth
century.''
</P>
<P>
   The day the construction project ended, a telegram was sent to
President Grant: ``Sir: We have the honor to report that the last
rail is laid, the last spike is driven, the Pacific Railroad is
finished.'' Another went to the secretary of war: ``The great work,
commenced during the Administration of Lincoln, in the middle of a
great rebellion, is completed under that of Grant, who conquered
the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the railroad _ built by dreamers, financiers, surveyors,
engineers, construction crews, even politicians _ a
transcontinental trip took months. After the railroad, it took a
week. Before, it cost $1,000. After, $70.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose is no stranger to heroics; he is the leading biographer
of Dwight D. Eisenhower, the chronicler of Lewis and Clark, and the
poet laureate of the D-Day invaders. And in his latest volume,
``Nothing Like It in the World,'' he examines the heroics of
building the railroad, the symbol of the age.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad was a triumph of what you might think of as the six
essential elements of the American experience _ engineering,
technology, finance, natural resources, ingenuity, and audacity. It
was equal parts of all of them, and one thing more: It was a
metaphor. It bound the nation together, an iron belt that united
the country east and west after a war that had split it north
against south. It stood as a symbol of Americans' transcontinental
journey. It accelerated the movement of the machine into the domain
of nature. It was the last giant project accomplished predominantly
by muscle and sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next to winning the Civil War and abolishing slavery, building
the first transcontinental railroad, from Omaha, Nebraska, to
Sacramento, California, was the greatest achievement of the
American people in the 19th century,'' Ambrose writes. Together,
the process of constructing the railroad and then the actual
running of the railroad transformed the country, shrinking
distances, creating new markets, opening up new areas to
settlement, even (because the railroad couldn't operate with a
patchwork of nonstandardized time) regularizing clocks across the
country and creating time zones.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad crossed miles of untouched territory, but the story
of the railroad is itself not exactly virgin territory; just last
autumn, for example, Viking published David Howard Bain's ``Empire
Express,'' which, at 797 pages, left few boulders unturned. That
said, this is a book with a difference. Its focus is on the men
(there were few women) who built the trestles, hammered the spikes,
blasted the tunnels, and constructed sheds that covered almost 50
miles of track and protected it from the snow. Almost nothing about
this story is on a human scale, and yet it was performed by humans
with superhuman endurance and all-too-human weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``To build a railroad it would take real men, dedicated men,
adventurous men, men of muscle and brain power, men without
equal,'' Ambrose writes. ``They must be giants to build it without
steam shovels, pile drivers, or power saws, without pipes with
water running through them, without portable houses and hospitals,
with no internal-combustion-engine trucks and jeeps to move
materials.''
</P>
<P>
   The railroad caused change to sweep across the country like a
vast, irresistible storm. Omaha doubled in size in the year 1865
alone. The wilderness was tamed, or at least subdued. New
communities sprang up. New fortunes were made. Old fortunes were
lost. New tensions were created. Old tensions were muted. ``The
tame,'' as Ambrose put it, replaced ``the wild.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a permanent change, wrought by a work force that had no
equal, mostly because it was organized along military lines; many
of the laborers who worked at the rate of three strikes of a
sledgehammer per spike and 10 spikes to a rail were veterans of the
Civil War. ``It was the best organized, best equipped, and best
disciplined work force I have ever seen,'' wrote Grenville Dodge, a
prominent general who helped direct the construction project. ``I
used it several times as a fighting force and it took no longer to
put it into fighting line than it did to form it for daily work.''
</P>
<P>
   Accidents were common. The men fought exhaustion, fires,
thieves, and Indians. Mostly they fought storms; there were 44 of
them in the winter of 1866-67 alone. They crossed mountains and
forded streams. One bridge was 126 feet above a streambed and 700
feet long. It swayed in the wind. But it held.
</P>
<P>
   This was a triumph, too, of the surveyor's art. Ambrose reports
that about a century later, when modern surveyors, traveling by air
and equipped with sophisticated technology, set out to find a route
for Interstate 80, they chose almost the exact route the railroad
surveyors had; the original tracks are often visible from your car
window as you speed along I-80.
</P>
<P>
   This was a great construction project, but it also was a great
race _ the Union Pacific against the Central Pacific. In truth, it
was the country that was racing _ across the continent, against
nature, against the notion that man's dreams should have limits.
When the Golden Spike was hammered into the last tie, the country
changed more than its principal mode of transportation. It changed
the way it thought.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of distance had been conquered, the danger of
transcontinental travel removed, the sovereignty of nature
compromised, the idea of the West changed. Westward movement became
attainable for ordinary Americans, and their destination became
vulnerable to mass culture and mass settlement. By the 1890s, the
Census Bureau would declare the frontier had disappeared. The
railroad was one cause. But in eliminating the frontier it also
created new possibilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
