<HEADLINE>
`MAD MOVIES' SERIES HAS FUN WITH CLASSIC FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIDEO ANTICS: There's nobody better to watch a movie with than
Kent Skov, an improv artist with the L.A. Connection. For years,
Skov and his band of merry men and women have performed live
talk-along bits at movie theaters. They'd sit in the front row
uttering inspired, improvisational dialogue and injecting
preplanned special effects, creating a unique movie experience. The
shows eventually evolved into a syndicated television program that
ran for years on various networks, including A &AMP; E and Comedy
Central. ``Mad Movies With the L.A. Connection'' hammers feature
films into a half-hour format with the wisecracks and newly dubbed
dialogue adding outrageous fun to such classics as Jose Ferrer's
``Cyrano de Bergerac.'' Skov is hoping that his success in theaters
and television will lead to success in the video marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying this as an experiment,'' he says of his plan to
offer fans 130 shows on VHS on a subscription basis. ``We're going
to release a new tape every two weeks for five years. A full
subscription costs about $400.''
</P>
<P>
   Skov realizes that might be a little pricey for people who can't
afford the entire plan, so they're developing reasonable
alternatives, including the possibility of offering each tape for
$15. Since it costs approximately $30,000 per episode to produce,
and Skov and his group are producing the first tape next month,
they need a solid subscriber base to bankroll their ambitious
efforts. You can check out their Web sites at
www.laconnectioncomedy or www.maddestmovies.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW ON DVD: ``Edward Scissorhands'' _ Many of the directors'
commentaries on DVDs are nothing more than ego-driven,
back-slapping, self-congratulatory paeans to themselves. Not this
one. Tim Burton is as informed and articulate when it comes to
talking about movies as he is when he's making them. He uses the
commentary track to talk about the conception of the film, Johnny
Depp's performance, and a variety of other themes and influences.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS: Tuesday: ``Braveheart,'' ``The Big Kahuna''
(DVD), ``I Dreamed of Africa'' (DVD), ``28 Days,'' ``Girl'' (DVD),
``Longitude'' (DVD), ``The Sound of Music'' (DVD). Sept. 5:
``American Psycho'' (DVD), ``Edward Scissorhands'' (DVD), ``Any
Given Sunday'' (DVD), ``A Summer's Tale'' (DVD), ``The Unknown
Jonathan Winters'' (DVD), ``The Unknown Peter Sellers'' (DVD).
Sept. 12: ``Tweety's High Flying Adventure.'' Sept. 19: ``A Map of
the World'' (DVD), ``Ready to Rumble'' (DVD), ``Tales of the Kama
Sutra'' (DVD). Sept. 26: ``Molokai,'' ``Final Destination,''
``Black and White'' (DVD). Oct. 24: ``American Beauty'' (DVD),
``The Patriot'' (DVD), ``U-571'' (DVD). Oct. 31: ``Touch of Evil''
(DVD). Nov. 7: ``The Bridge on the River Kwai'' (DVD).
</P>
