<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLING-SPREE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS FOLLOW CONNECTICUT SLAYINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERBURY, Conn. _ A friend said Mark Cote had talked
despairingly about his urge to kill his former wife's boyfriend.
Cote's girlfriend told her mother that he had hit her.
</P>
<P>
   People who knew him said he was volatile and depressed, but they
also said that they saw no signs of danger. They never saw him as a
potential killer.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Saturday morning, Cote shot three people in three
different locations in less than 20 minutes. He finally turned a
gun on himself. Cote, 29, and his three victims all died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any idea what caused him to snap,'' said Cote's
mother, Rachael Cote. ``He knew right from wrong. He knew.''
</P>
<P>
   The first vicitm was Brian Miller, 30, Cote's upstairs neighbor,
with whom he was reportedly friendly. The two had purchased their
guns together and practiced together at a shooting range.
</P>
<P>
   Cote's second victim was Jamie Quinones, 38, reportedly his
former wife's boyfriend. Quinones, a firefighter, was collecting
money for charity when he was gunned down.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Cote killed Maria Hernandez, 39, his former
girlfriend's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Cote spared his former girlfriend, Maria Perez, and her
children. Before releasing Perez, he told her he had killed her
mother ``to take away from her what she loved the most,'' said
Perez's brother, Marcelo Hidalgo, 22.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking his own life, Cote called his mother at work to
say goodbye. ``I'm sorry for what I did,'' Rachael Cote said her
son told her. ``I don't want to go to jail. I don't want to live.''
Then he hung up.
</P>
<P>
   The killing spree was a blow to Waterbury, an old indstrial city
of about 120,000. The blue-collar community, known as the ``Brass
City'' from its manufacturing days, has seen a spate of violence
this week. There were three shootings unrelated to Cote's Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Cote's troubles began in the mid-1990s with his failed marriage,
which lasted for about a year and a half, Rachael Cote said. She
said his wife revealed that she had been having an affair when Cote
caught her with Quinones.
</P>
<P>
   Cote immediately filed for divorce, but his mother says his
former wife and Quinones spent years trying to make his life
miserable. They obtained restraining orders against him, then
haunted him by idling in a car outside his house, eating often in a
restaurant where his mother worked, Rachael Cote said. Quinones
came by the appartment the mother and son shared as recently as
Thursday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cote's former wife could not be reached Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Cote had spoken of his desire to kill Quinones, said a friend,
Juan Nazario.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a couple of years, he said he was going to do it,''
Nazario said. But, he added, ``I didn't see it coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Nazario insisted Cote was distressed but not mentally unstable.
``He was a beautiful person,'' Nazario said. ``He was my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Cote had dated Perez for about a year before they broke up
amicably, Rachael Cote said. But Hidalgo said Cote was jealous and
temperamental and had struck Perez before she decided to leave him,
just days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all liked him in the beginning,`` Hidalgo said. ``He was a
nice guy. I guess he couldn't handle breakups.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo said that a day or two before the shootings he saw Cote
in a parked car, watching the house where Perez lived with her
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had it planned already,'' Hidalgo said. ``He knew what he
wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hidalgo said he believed Cote was plotting violence,
Rachael Cote said her son's behavior was normal as late as Saturday
morning, when he kissed his grandmother goodbye on his way out the
door. She said he had a pleasant phone conversation with Perez that
morning and planned to take her shopping for her childrens' school
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quinones I understand, although I don't condone,'' Rachael
Cote said. ``If I live to be a million years old, I will never
understand Brian and Maria's mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Cote and Miller were friendly, the mother said, although they
had normal neighborly disputes.
</P>
<P>
   At about 10:50 Saturday morning, Cote shot his neighbor while
Miller was seated in his red Honda. He then pulled Miller from the
car and shot him again, before taking off in the Honda, according
to police.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes later, Cote found Quinones collecting donations
for a ``fill the boot'' campaign for muscular dystrophy. He shot
the firefighter several times and took off again, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen minutes after that, police got a 911 call from Perez's
address, but the caller hung up. When the dispatcher called back, a
man answered and said everything was OK and hung up. When the
dispatcher called a second time, Perez answered the phone in
hysterics.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hidalgo, Cote had shot Hernandez as soon as he
walked into the house. Then he spoke briefly to Perez on the second
floor before allowing her to leave. While police were surrounding
the house, they heard a shot. After they entered, they found Cote
dead with two semiautomatic weapons, according to a police
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives said Hernandez was a loving, motherly figure with
three children, four grandchildren, and five stepchildren. She had
also raised four other children, who were the offspring of
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't deserve to die like that; she deserved to die
old,'' said Ronnie Quintero, 17, who said Hernandez raised him
since he was a toddler. ``She was hoping to see all of our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinones was a dedicated firefighter, a six-year veteran of the
Fire Department who also served in the Marines for 11 years, said
the acting fire chief, James Trainor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very respectful and had a good military bearing.''
Trainor said. ``He was quiet. Just a regular guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Miller could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Some Waterbury residents said they were shaken by the death.
``It's very sad to lose a firefighter who's out collecting charity,
because some loser decides to start killing people,'' said Alisha
Weinstein, a teacher who lives in the neighborhood where Quinones
was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Rachael Cote said her son was happy at his job with a lab
company, where he took blood samples for people, often for drug
tests. She blamed what he did on his stress over the divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it just ate away at him,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
