u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-28 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISING PESSIMISM'S PROFILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANTE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As one who goes through life expecting the worst, I was
interested to read about a symposium titled the ``The Overlooked
Virtues of Negativity,'' which took place recently during the
annual meeting of the American Psychological Association in
Washington. It's about time somebody got positive about being
negative.
</P>
<P>
   For years I've been collecting notes for a book titled ``The
Power of Negative Thinking,'' but I can't seem to write it because
I keep telling myself that I'll never be able to get it published.
Reading about this symposium gave me new hope for the project, or
if maybe not hope, exactly, then a slightly more realistic view of
my prospects. Although maybe the word ``realistic'' is putting it
too strongly.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the problems with negative thinking. You're always
second-guessing yourself. Not that there's anything wrong with
that. In fact, there's a lot that's right about being negative,
according to some of the psychologists who participated in the
symposium. Actually, ``a lot'' may be overstating the case. But
it's probably fair to say that being negative isn't necessarily a
bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times report on the event quoted Barbara Held, a
clinical psychologist at Bowdoin College, as saying that her
profession, indeed America as a whole, has succumbed to the
``tyranny of the positive attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Held is the author of ``Stop Smiling, Start Kvetching,'' a
defense of creative complaining, in which she contends that
kvetching helps people see their problems more realistically. She
writes that we are all under enormous pressure from therapists,
self-help gurus, ``inspirational'' speakers, and others to be
happy, or worse, to act happy, even when we're not. This is very
stressful, according to Held, because life is hard, and it's harder
when we feel we have to deny just how hard it is.
</P>
<P>
   Held makes the point that being a pessimist doesn't mean walking
around in a state of perpetual gloom. ``Just because I hate life
doesn't mean I can't have fun,'' she writes. That could be the
pessimist's creed.
</P>
<P>
   One of those exerting the pressure to be happy is Martin
Seligman, former president of the American Psychological
Association, a leading light in what's known as the positive
psychology movement, and author of the popular book ``Learned
Optimism.'' Seligman believes that pessimists get the short end of
life's stick. He claims they don't do as well as optimists in
school, at work, in sports. They don't age as well as optimists.
They don't live as long. If it's true that pessimists die younger,
and I'm not convinced that it is, I suspect it's because optimists
wear us down, always telling us, ``Don't worry, be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Seligman believes pessimists can learn to be optimists by using
certain cognitive therapy techniques in his book. But why would a
pessimist bother to try to be an optimist? A true pessimist knows
you can't fool your brain into believing something that obviously
isn't true.
</P>
<P>
   The Times story described a coping strategy called ``defensive
pessimism,'' in which people anticipate all the possible outcomes
of a given situation, dwelling on everything that could go wrong.
Research has shown that those who approach life with this attitude
are prepared for anything, and are as likely to perform tasks as
well as optimists. All of which would be very encouraging, if I
believed it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4168 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-KOREA-REUNION-BOS &LR;      08-28 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-REUNION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING HEART IN SEOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ There is an unwritten code among reporters that we
should remain detached from the events and people we write about.
Objectivity is the name of the game, so we are careful not to
reveal our political or moral leanings, not to clap or boo during
impassioned speeches, not to cry or get angry over tragedies and
injustices that outrage us.
</P>
<P>
   We are weaned in a professional culture that tells us to be
tough, unflappable, and unmoved in the face of strong emotion _
partly to ensure fairness in our reports, and partly to protect
ourselves from being overwhelmed by what we experience.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes that doesn't work. This month, I cried on the job
for the first time in my decade as a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   There were ample opportunities before. When I was a Boston
police reporter, I sympathetically stroked the arms of a number of
mothers who lost children to gang violence. In Chile and Indonesia,
I watched millions dance in the streets to celebrate the ouster of
military dictators and the birth of democracy. In Bosnia and East
Timor, I visited miserable refugee camps, counting rows of diseased
and dying, soothing women who had been raped and children who were
orphaned. Like my colleagues, I chronicled their grief, but kept my
own sadness to myself, knowing I had seen this before and would see
it again.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nothing had prepared me for the half-century's worth of
agony, longing, and tears that flowed when 200 Korean families,
long divided by war, were reunited briefly this month in Seoul and
Pyongyang. These were not the pathetic and emaciated victims of war
we have come to expect. They were doctors and professors, writers
and laborers, common people like us who had the bad fortune to be
born at the wrong time in the history of their country.
</P>
<P>
   I watched as 100 aged Northerners walked with wobbly feet and
hopeful faces into a Seoul convention center to greet their
long-lost loved ones _ people they hadn't dared to dream were still
alive. I listened as the room rang with cries of ``My son!'' ``Oh,
how I've missed you!'' and ``Dear, I've come home'' _ cries that
laid bare 100 personal tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1945, Korea was divided into the Soviet-backed North
and the US-backed South. The North attacked in 1950 to force
reunification, but the conflict ended in permanent division. Phone
calls, letters, and travel were (and still are) forbidden, so
families whose loved ones vanished in the war spent their lives not
knowing whether the missing had died, or were alive in a place
beyond their reach.
</P>
<P>
   I watched as 90-year-old mothers tried to climb out of their
wheelchairs to embrace 70-year-old sons; as husbands tried to
comfort wives who had waited all their lives and never remarried.
</P>
<P>
   The families hugged for minutes, patting each others' backs to
see if they were really there, clutching one another tightly as if
they would never let go. As I thought of my own parents, and how
lucky I am to be separated from them only by a long-distance
telephone call, I struggled not to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Few of us who have grown up in the late 20th century in an
affluent democracy can imagine starving from famine, being
imprisoned for our religion, or being hacked to death in an ethnic
war. But all of us have parents and siblings, partners or children
from whom we cannot imagine being separated.
</P>
<P>
   For four days, I watched Korean families come together for
all-too-brief meetings, holding last rites for parents who didn't
live to see this day, sharing stories and photos and sentimental
gifts. I watched elderly mothers spoonfeed grown sons who had
vanished when they were still boys.
</P>
<P>
   I imagined the guilt that must have haunted the woman who
brought shoes to her now-grown son, whose small bare feet had been
cold in those final minutes before they were separated as they
tried to flee war-torn Pyongyang 50 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   On the final day, I weaved through the crowd, catching snippets
of desperate farewells as relatives were forced to part, probably
forever. Tears flowing, North Koreans pressed trembling hands to
the glass of the buses that would whisk them away. Shoulders
heaving, they mouthed kisses and last wishes. One man traced the
character for mother on the window again and again.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, the parking lot of a luxury hotel in Seoul
seemed a sadder place than any refugee camp I had ever seen. Hong
Kil Soon, an 87-year-old woman whom I had shadowed that week,
watched her eldest daughter, now 67, sob and wave from the back of
the bus until it pulled out of sight. I am sure that Hong saw Kim
Ok Bae not as the aging woman she is now, but as the teenager who
disappeared from her school one day during the war.
</P>
<P>
   When the bus vanished, Hong turned to me and took me in her
arms, and I cried as inconsolably as she did, my body shaking as if
a member of my own family had disappeared into a black hole, never
to be heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   There are 10 million members of separated Korean families, one
in seven citizens of the divided peninsula. In the south alone,
there are 1.23 million first-generation members of divided
families, and if only 100 Northerners visit each month, it would
take 1,000 years for everyone to meet.
</P>
<P>
   But after witnessing the heartbreak of these families along with
millions of Koreans who watched their televisions spellbound, it is
hard to believe it will take that long. Since the landmark leaders'
summit in June, every week has brought a surprising new
breakthrough. As in the former divided Germany, people-to-people
contacts seem the surest road to mutual trust, and emotion seems
more likely than negotiation to tear down the last Cold War
barrier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Indira A. R. Lakshmanan is the Globe's Asia bureau chief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4176 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS &LR;      08-28 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELISHING THE LANDSCAPE OF AGATHA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I can't resist encyclopedias, so naturally I took the advance
uncorrected proofs of Matthew Bunson's ``The Complete Christie: An
Agatha Christie Encyclopedia'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster/Pocket Books, $35
hard cover, $18.95 paper) off with me when I traveled down from
Oxford to Devon and Cornwall this month to visit the Burgh Island
Hotel, an art deco oddity where Christie wrote (and, it is said,
set) two of her mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Christie tourism is booming, with Torquay, where she grew up,
promoting an Agatha Christie Mile and Torre Abbey providing a
chance to look at her typewriter. I reread ``And Then There Were
None'' (first published in London under an appallingly racist
title, though yet other editions come out as ``Ten Little
Indians'') and thought it still held up as one of her three or four
best books, and I trawled through the encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   It's full of interesting stuff, including summaries of all
Christie's books, short stories, film and television adaptations,
and plays, and, above all, a list of all the characters who walk in
and off Christie's stages. There is a good bit of Who Cares?
information _ how many Christie novels featured a butler _ and
Bunson doesn't provide much by way of critical judgment, but there
is plenty here to entertain during the dog days of summer, out on
the lawn in England, thankfully almost free of annoying insects.
</P>
<P>
   I have a similar affection for the work of Sarah Caudwell, from
whom, alas, there will be no more, as she died in January. Happily
her fourth mystery novel, ``The Sibyl in the Grave'' (Delacorte,
$23.95) was virtually finished, and also happily, it is her best
book. Caudwell invented an Oxford don, Hilary Tamar, whose gender
the reader is unable to determine; Tamar is Tutor in Legal History
at St. George's College, Oxford, and is mentor to four clever,
irritating, and trouble-prone young barristers. The plot here is
complex yet clear, and it is all about huge and perhaps improper
returns on short-term investments in the village of Parson's Haver.
These days, in England, one risks rebuke if one refers to a person,
book, or landscape as ``very English,'' since the English seem
quite confused about who they are. But I will stick by an earlier
remark: Caudwell's novels are very English and quite wonderful and
how very sad that this is the end.
</P>
<P>
   The last of my Devon days books was ``The Waters of Babylon,''
subtitled ``A Novel about Lawrence after Arabia'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $24), by David Stevens. I had high expectations, for the
dust jacket tells us that Stevens wrote the screenplay for
``Breaker Morant,'' but I guess writing a novel is not the same
thing, as the prose is stiff, flatly descriptive, and in fact reads
very much like stage directions. Still, a good intelligence is at
work here, and this novelized version of what we know or might
reasonably guess about Lawrence after he takes the name T. E. Shaw
is intermittently interesting and provides a plausible solution to
a mystery or two.
</P>
<P>
   Devon and Cornwall do tend to Anglophilia, and after a year here
in England, now ready to return to the States, I wanted to end my
summer languors with some gritty American noir. Stephen Hunter's
``Hot Springs'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) provides a homecoming with
bite: Set in Arkansas in summer 1946, the book tells of Earl
Swagger, a tough lawman in Polk County, a center of prostitution,
organized gangs, and plenty of racism. This is not an America one
would want to visit, much less live in, and yet people did and do,
and Hunter's account of what history calls the GI Revolt is terse,
convincing, and just right for reentry into the American
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   David Compton provides for the final stage to this reader's
reentry. ``Impaired Judgment'' (Dutton, $24.95) is about conspiracy
in high places, as was Compton's previous book: Paula Candler is a
federal judge in Virginia; she is also the nation's first lady and
_ surprise _ there is a shocking secret in her past. She is to
preside over the trial of a reputed member of the Mafia, whose
defense lawyer decides can best be defended by blackmailing
Candler.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds quite a bit contrived, and it is, but then so was
``And Then There Were None.'' And as Christie made her formula work
brilliantly, so too does Compton. This is the ultimate
end-of-summer book, and it sets just the right tone for the
upcoming election campaign. All that Christie and Caudwell share
with Hunter and Compton is the use of the English language, but
that's enough this time of year, in either country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
