<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4182 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-POPLIT-BOS &LR;      08-28 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-POPLIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST OF THE BEACH BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nonliterary fiction. Beach books. Page-turners. Whatever you
call them, these books are mainstays of bestseller lists. They can
be romances, or thrillers, or historical fiction. Some defy
categorization. Some even defy rational description. And some are
trash. (It's probably belaboring the obvious to note that the word
``trash'' isn't necessarily a perjorative when it comes to popular
fiction.)
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, a page-turner has a diverting story and interesting
characters. The writing shouldn't make you wince too often. And the
plot shouldn't require you to think a lot. It's the sort of book
you can read while keeping one eye on the kids, or eating a
solitary lunch, or riding the T, or listening to the Red Sox game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vineyard'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) is a portrait of family
pathology, thwarted passion, and life-changing love that seems
worthy of a TV miniseries. Even the title is made-to-order.
Asquonset, near the Rhode Island shore, is a successful
wine-producing operation presided over by 76-year-old Natalie
Seebring, who might be described as a strong-willed matriarch, but
isn't, to author Barbara Delinsky's credit.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie's grown children are shocked when, barely three months
after the death of her husband of 58 years, she announces plans to
marry an old friend, longtime vineyard manager Carl Burke. Natalie
has another surprise for the kids: She's writing her memoirs.
Angst-ridden single mother Olivia Jones, a Cambridge
writer/photographer, signs on to help with the project. Olivia and
her dyslexic 10-year-old daughter, Tess, come to live at Asquonset
for the summer. Olivia draws out Natalie's secrets, while
attempting to understand the Seebring family's complicated
resentments. She also finds herself feeling faint stirrings for
Simon Burke, Carl's attractively brooding son, the vineyard's
current manager, ``the kind of man she had spent a lifetime
fantasizing about.''
</P>
<P>
   Delinsky is the author of 60 novels, many of them bestsellers.
She is a straightforward storyteller whose prose neatly
accommodates plot and research (she has done her grape-growing
homework). And she has a deft way with a sex scene, not an easy
skill to master.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many women novelists, Rosamunde Pilcher has been tagged
``a Jane Austen for our time.'' The praise is doubtless well-meant,
but it is unfair to both writers. Pilcher's novels are fine on
their own terms, but Jane Austen she's not. She lacks, among other
things, Austen's sharp wit, although she has a dry sense of humor
that suits her understated style. ``The owner stood behind the bar,
and did not appear to be enjoying his job,'' she writes, describing
an austere pub in a bleak Scottish town. ``Around the place were
small round tables and uninviting chairs, and in a tiny fireplace a
peat-fire smouldered. Over the fireplace an enormous fish, with
cold eyes, hovered in its glass case, and all smelt of old beer and
whisky.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously Pilcher is skillful at evoking place and atmosphere,
but her chief strength is her ability to create believably complex
characters, with recognizably human flaws and frailties. ``Winter
Solstice'' (St. Martin's, $27.95) is a big, comfortable novel that
you can sink right into. At its heart is a story of two people in
their mid-60s, wounded by separate tragedies. When the man she
loves dies of Parkinson's disease, Elfrida Phipps, a raffish
retired actress, leaves London and settles in a country village.
There she makes friends with Oscar and Gloria Blundell and their
12-year-old daughter, Francesca. Elfrida warms immediately to
Oscar, a retired choirmaster and organist who seems oddly matched
with the horsey, heavy-drinking Gloria. After Gloria and Francesca
are conveniently killed in an auto accident, Elfrida agrees to
accompany the grieving Oscar to Creagan, a town in northern
Scotland, where he owns a house. Pilcher's prose proceeds at a
leisurely pace as the plot expands to include three younger
characters, each in the throes of separate life-altering crises.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Steel's latest, ``The House on Hope Street''
(Delacorte, $19.95), is a two-hanky tear-jerker that shot to the
top of bestseller lists as soon as it was released. Her novels _
this is number 49 _ may be short, cliched, and formulaic, but with
420 million copies in print, Steel clearly is giving her readers
what they want. She dishes it up once again in this
write-by-the-numbers story about another strong yet vulnerable
woman coping with life's vicissitudes. Young lawyer Liz Sutherland
(``with her bright red hair and flashing green eyes'') struggles to
carry on after her husband and law partner, Jack, is murdered, and
on Christmas Day no less. There's the law practice to maintain and
five children to rear, the youngest of whom, Jamie, is
``learning-delayed'' and yearning to train for the Special
Olympics. When Liz's oldest child, Peter, is injured in a diving
accident, Dr. Bill Webster enters Liz's life (``He was tall, and
his dark eyes looked grim, but the gray at his temples made her
want to believe that he knew what he was doing''). Naturally he
knows exactly what he's doing, and Steel knows exactly what she's
doing too. Does she ever.
</P>
<P>
   Take a likable young priest who's battling cancer, his beautiful
sister, his FBI agent best friend, toss in one homicidal psychopath
and you have the main elements of ``Heartbreaker'' (Pocket Books,
$24.95), Julie Garwood's first foray into the thriller genre.
Garwood can't write to save her life, but her many fans apparently
couldn't care less. She's made a huge name as a writer of romantic
fiction, and it shows. ``Lordy, lordy, he had blue eyes. Brilliant
blue eyes that didn't miss a trick,'' muses Laurant Madden on first
meeting her brother's federal agent friend Nick Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Father Tom Madden, whose ``boyish good looks had earned him the
amusing nickname `Father-What-a-Waste' from all the high school and
college girls,'' hears the confession of a nut who says he has
killed one woman and plans to kill Father Tom's sister. The priest
calls in his old friend Nick to keep an eye on Laurant, and he
does, in more ways than one. He tries to keep a professional
distance, but he can't help noticing, ``those incredible long legs,
the soft swell of her breasts under the thin fabric, her beautiful
neck, her flushed cheeks, and that perfect mouth of hers.'' One
thing inevitably leads to another. Garwood knows how to move a plot
in unexpected directions, but her writing is stiff and
cliche-ridden, with too many rough edges. Basically, this is a
romance/thriller as opposed to a thriller/romance. If you're not
too particular about your prose, and you're looking for a
fast-paced story that won't tax your brain, ``Heartbreaker'' could
be a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rivers Siddons's ``Nora, Nora'' (HarperCollins, $25) is a
charmer, set in Lytton, a small town near Atlanta, in 1961. Peyton
McKenzie is 12, an awkward girl haunted by guilt because her mother
bled to death shortly after giving birth to her. She lives in a big
house with her emotionally distant father, Frazier, and the
family's longtime housekeeper, Clothilde. Peyton's only friends are
the two fellow misfit members of The Losers Club, who meet every
afternoon to decide which of them did the dumbest thing during the
course of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Peyton's dispiriting existence gets a jolt of energy when her
cousin Nora Findlay drives up from Key West in her pink
Thunderbird. Nora is 30-ish, red-haired, freckled, sexy. She
smokes, drinks, and wears makeup. She assures Peyton, ``There is a
world beyond Lytton Grammar School, and it's a hell of a lot more
interesting.'' Everything about Nora shocks Lytton's conservative,
small-town sensibilities, but especially her liberal views on race.
She signs on as a substitute teacher and arranges an honors English
class that mixes students from the black and the white high
schools. She takes Peyton to a sit-in in Atlanta, and to Sunday
services at Saint John's African Methodist Episcopal Church. But
when Peyton discovers the cousin she idolizes is flawed, she's
forced to grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Siddons, a perennial fixture on bestseller lists, has created
some wonderfully original characters. She also does a fine job of
portraying the strained social climate of a small Southern town at
the beginning of the civil rights movement. Occasionally her
writing is just a little too self-consciously beguiling (``A wind
from somewhere far off brushed her heart.''), but it never detracts
from the essential humanity of her storytelling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
