<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4187 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-BUYING-UNDERWEAR     08-28 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-BUYING-UNDERWEAR-ONLINE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELUCTANT UNDERWEAR SHOPPER FINDS A METHOD THAT CLICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    (ART ADV: Color photo of Victoria's Secret's Web site is
available in JPEG format by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.) 
 By LISA NAPOLI  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I don't like to think much about
underwear. I always find it disturbing when people said you had to
have nice underthings on in case you were hit by a bus and had to
be taken to the hospital, where an utter stranger might witness
your tattered skivvies.
</P>
<P>
   Call me crazy, but what I was wearing, should I need to be
carried somewhere on a stretcher, seemed low on the list of Things
to Lose Sleep Over.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as I grew up, I learned there were other reasons that
would make a woman attend to her underlayer. But even they haven't
made lingerie one of my raisons d'etre. Heck, I'm not even into
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   This is why, for me, the idea of buying underwear online _
buying anything online, really _ is so appealing. I can do it when
I want without going out of my way, I can do it fast and I feel as
if I'm getting a present in the mail as a bonus for my trouble.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that I'm not alone. The grande dame of underwear
and hosiery manufacturers, Sara Lee, which makes Hanes, Bali,
Playtex, Wonderbra and other well-known brands, reports that online
sales have tripled in the last year. And it sells only irregulars
and discontinued styles on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean that the intimate-apparel shoppers of the
world are flocking to Web sites in such numbers that the lingerie
clerks at the department stores are standing around like Maytag
repairmen.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rachel Strasser, the vice president for business
development at the Web business Figleaves.com, is banking that some
day soon, they will be.
</P>
<P>
   Figleaves.com, which opened in March, is all about what the
apparel industry calls ``essential wear'' _ a niche Strasser said
she and her colleagues focused on after first considering a broader
plan to get into the online apparel business.
</P>
<P>
   She ticked off a list of reasons she contended had made
underwear and hosiery a workable business on the Web: ``You can't
try packaged underwear on in the stores, anyway. People often know
what size they wear. The only way to reorder is to go to the
department store. Upscale brands are primarily sold in department
stores, but they don't have as extensive a selection because square
footage is limited on the selling floor _ both from a style and
size perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short time that Figleaves.com's virtual doors have been
open, Strasser added, she has discovered another benefit to the
medium: it attracts men. While women buy 75 percent of the
underwear sold over the counter, online shoppers at her site are,
so far, evenly divided between the sexes, according to her analysis
of credit card transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Not all online underwear shoppers, though, are after hassle-free
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   For Christine Butler, the Web is a lifeline to her favorite
underwear store. When her family was relocated to London from
Chicago, she was worried about losing access to Victoria's Secret.
The company, based in Columbus, Ohio, has 900 stores in the United
States, but does not have any abroad, nor does it plan to open any.
</P>
<P>
   It does, however, have a Web site, which has been open for
business since December 1998. Since then, the site has attracted
buyers from 137 countries, said Anne Marie Blaire, the director of
Internet brand development for Intimate Brands, Victoria's Secret's
parent company.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria's Secret executives are also aware that their catalogs
are famous as entertainment as well as sources of information, and
they are trying to capitalize on that success online. Last month,
the company held its second online fashion show, a live video
recording from Cannes, France, during which viewers could click on
a model's garment and place it in a virtual shopping cart. The
first show, advertised just once, during the Super Bowl in 1999,
got so much traffic that the servers broke, a gaffe that the
company saw as a sign of success.
</P>
<P>
   Video specials are one way Intimate Brands intends to use the
Victoria's Secret site. Visitors to the site can sign up for
memberships, which entitle them to announcements by e-mail
messages. There is also an interactive bra finder, which allows
buyers to specify a particular bra need (for example, strapless)
and find a product to match it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun for the customer,'' Blaire said, adding that it was
also an easy way to indulge in a guilty pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the ultimate pick-me-up for a girl?'' she asked. ``It's
lingerie or a lipstick. It makes you feel pampered and indulged.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler, the expatriate Victoria's Secret shopper, had a baby
recently, and wanted to treat herself to ``some pretty p.j.'s and
lingerie,'' she said. Without the Web site, she would have had her
sisters send her catalogs, place her orders and then bring the
goods on their next visit. This way, she skips those steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great way to get the things I liked without the
hassle,'' she said in an e-mail interview.
</P>
<P>
   Even a lingerie Luddite like me knows that Victoria's Secret is
not for everyone. Susan, my friend and lingerie adviser, who
declined to be identified by her last name, emphasized this as we
discussed bras and panties on the phone from our workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing Susan wax rhapsodic about underwear is enough to make
even a colorless plain-cotton gal want to rush out and expand her
collection.
</P>
<P>
   But would Susan buy this stuff online? She ruminated over this
serious question as we both called up Figleaves.com, a site she had
not seen yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a bra shopper, I generally buy the same stuff over and
over,'' she said. ``It's a little nerve-racking, but I guess you
could do it'' online, she added. ``But I don't think most women
would feel comfortable buying a new brand online. Bras are so
individual. I kind of like to touch them.''
</P>
<P>
   If the online purchases didn't fit, she reasoned, she could send
them back. But then she remembered merchandise she had bought from
a catalog months ago, which had been sitting under her desk,
waiting to be returned.
</P>
<P>
   She confessed, however, that despite her misgivings about online
clothes shopping, she liked the look of Figleaves.com, as well as
the brands it offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still don't know what they feel like,'' she said. ``Oh,
DKNY. Let's go see that.''
</P>
<P>
   The brand name lured Susan, as Strasser had hoped. Susan was
particularly enamored of an underwire bra that could be converted
to strapless. ``It's hard to find a good strapless bra,'' she said.
But she worried about size.
</P>
<P>
   I pointed out that Figleaves.com offered customer service online
with the click of a mouse. Seconds later, a representative who
called herself Eve responded vaguely to Susan's query about what
size DKNY bra she might need.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her skepticism, Susan found her mind filled with
possibilities. ``I could see how you could get addicted,'' she
said. ``If I buy a new bra and panties, I feel so much better. It's
like buying new barrettes.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired, I bought the strapless bra and matching panties for
myself _ in case a bus did make unwanted contact with my body, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   They turned out to be so nice that I'm thinking of having a new
set shipped every three months.
</P>
<P>
   (Lisa Napoli is the Internet correspondent for MSNBC.)
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
