<HEADER>
A4188 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-CHURCHES-ON-WEB-     08-28 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-CHURCHES-ON-WEB-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGURING OUT WHETHER E-MAMMON CAN FIT IN THE TEMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 By ARI L. GOLDMAN  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   On the Web site of the East Liberty Presbyterian Church in
Pittsburgh, a visitor can see photographs of the historic church,
check the schedule of potluck dinners, research the church's
history, read recent sermons, connect with other members and even
get directions to the church, known as the Cathedral of Hope.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing the visitor cannot do at the site,
www.cathedralofhope.org, is spend money. No banner advertisements
flash across the screen, and no one is trying to sell, buy, trade
or solicit. ``This is a nonprofit organization,'' said Jeffry Blake
Johnson, the church's associate director of music and its Internet
coordinator. ``We're in the business of providing community, and
not in the business of making money. Everything we do, we lose
money. Why should the Web site be any different?''
</P>
<P>
   While almost everyone is trying to figure out how to make money
on the Web, most congregations remain commercial-free zones. But
that does not mean they are not thinking about e-commerce. The
challenge for religious organizations is incorporating e-commerce
into their primary missions and making it consistent with their
messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense of, `How are we going to steer our way around
commerce?''' said Edward J. Murray, the president of the National
Interfaith Cable Coalition, which will soon introduce a virtual
network called Faithandvaluesmedia.org. ``The answer is, we won't.
We'll be there to offer people what they need to carry out their
missions. But whatever commerce we'll do, it will be related to our
mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray noted that his group, like its constituent church groups,
was a nonprofit corporation. But ``that doesn't require you to lose
money,'' he said. ``We'll operate within the not-for-profit
boundaries; any margin will go back into our ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   Some churches and religious organizations are cautiously
experimenting with a limited amount of e-commerce, like the sale of
religious books and gifts. But deciding what fits and what does not
is not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone would agree that selling Bibles fits. But what
about best sellers like ``Chicken Soup for the Teen-age Soul'' or
New Age music? Kosher and hallal foods? Acupuncture and reflexology
treatments? Funerals? Then there is the highly profitable area of
spiritual and religious travel _ trips to the Holy Land and Rome,
as well as to Lourdes, the Ganges River and Tibet. Do these fit?
Should they be priced for profit or for maximum dissemination?
</P>
<P>
   ``Throw it all together and we're talking about a $40 billion
market,'' said Robert Nylen, a co-founder and co-chairman of
Beliefnet.com, a commercial Internet business that offers an online
spiritual community for prayer and knowledge against a backdrop of
advertisements. Beliefnet will soon introduce Web Start, a template
for congregations to create sites linked to Beliefnet and its
commercial ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The number of congregations with Web sites is unknown, but it is
clearly growing. Tens of thousands of churches have them, with
Roman Catholics leading the way. Of the 189 dioceses in the United
States (each with dozens or hundreds of churches), 82 percent are
on the Internet. Of the 11,000 congregations in the Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America, about 2,000 are on the Web. Of the 800
Conservative Jewish congregations, roughly half are online.
</P>
<P>
   One church that has taken the plunge into e-commerce is Grace
Episcopal Cathedral in San Francisco. At www.gracecathedral.org,
users find an archive of sermons and inspirational columns and
features. There is also a virtual tour of the Gothic cathedral and
a church bulletin, Gracenotes. But the home page included an icon _
computer, not religious _ with prayerful hands that said, ``Support
Grace Online by Shopping at Amazon.com.'' The church receives a
commission for sales made through the site.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Gracecathedral.org can also join the church online
(credit cards accepted) and shop at the cathedral gift shop for
books, videos and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie Ward, a spokeswoman for the church, said the items sold
online were related to the church, like labyrinths, the medieval
meditation paths that people walk through or trace with their
fingers. Ward said that the cathedral had not signed up with any of
the virtual-religion networks and that it was proceeding cautiously
into e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Jerome M. Epstein, the executive vice president of the
United Synagogue of Conservative Judaism, acknowledged that a few
years ago, he considered Web sites to be passing fads. Today, Rabbi
Epstein said, they are becoming essential tools that link
congregants to one another and to their synagogues. People use the
sites to stay in touch when they are away. Others looking to move
into a community will often use the sites to see what a
congregation offers.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for church and synagogue sites seems limitless,
religious leaders say. Users can stay at home and hear and see the
choir and the delivery of the sermon. If they miss the service,
they can catch it later.
</P>
<P>
   And the growing religious presence on the Web means potential
customers. ``We've been getting all kinds of pressure to sign up
with different businesses and nonprofits,'' the rabbi said. ``We've
resisted because we don't want to make our congregations feel that
what we're about is merchandising.''
</P>
<P>
   One person struggling to find a balance between commerce and
faith is John Lynner Peterson, the director for public media at the
Lutheran Church Association and a consultant to
Faithandvaluesmedia.org. He drew a distinction between the
Internet's dot-orgs and dot-coms like Beliefnet.com and
Christianity.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not responsible to venture capitalists who are putting
pressure on their relig.coms to turn a profit,'' Peterson said.
``We're more interested in being prophetic than in being
profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   What his dot-org group would like to do is link houses of
worship from a cross section of denominations. The interfaith group
that is sponsoring Faithandvaluesmedia.org is a coalition of 70
religious groups with thousands of churches. United under one
network, these groups will be able to share intellectual and
spiritual resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be using e-commerce, but commerce won't be the final
arbiter of who we are,'' Peterson said. ``We are about ministry. We
are about connecting with people where they are on their spiritual
journey.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ari L. Goldman, a former religion writer for The New York
Times, teaches at Columbia University.)
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article,
it must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
</TEXT>
