<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4192 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-SPINAL-BOS &LR;      08-28 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SPINAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPINAL TAP ROCKS ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There is a fine line between stupid and . . . '' says
English-accented singer-guitarist David St. Hubbins, who then gets
stuck for the next word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clever,'' chimes in bassist Derek Smalls.
</P>
<P>
   It's a classic moment from a cult classic film, Rob Reiner's
directorial debut, ``This Is Spinal Tap,'' a mockumentary about a
would-be mighty faux rock band called Spinal Tap. It debuted in
1983 and quickly became noted as the rock movie _ or, at least the
one that hilariously captured the arrogance, self-absorption,
pretentiousness, and self-delusion with which many a rock band
carry with them unaware. A portrayal of simple, shaggy-coifed,
bandwagon-hopping musicians who believe themselves to be artists,
visionaries maybe. ``This Is Spinal Tap'' is a band-on-the-road
film that takes most every rock 'n' roll cliche _ introduces us to
the nasal, whiny publicist (played TAP, Page N &QL; 
by Fran Drescher) and the sycophantic A&AMP;R man (played by Paul
Shaffer) _ and satirically spins them so that the inanities of
Spinal Tap are just one small step removed from the inanities of
many a real rock band.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is Spinal Tap'' _ which screens starting Sept. 8 at the
Nickelodeon and is being released by MGM on DVD Sept. 12 with an
hour's worth of outtakes and other sundries tacked on _ is so
realistic it has fooled people into believing parts of it.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Halpern, a vice president of special projects at the film
company StudioCanal, was at a bachelor party in England not long
ago and the subject of Spinal Tap came up. The musicians who played
Spinal Tap were writers/comic-actors Michael McKean (St. Hubbins),
Harry Shearer (Smalls) and Christopher Guest (Nigel Tufnel). His
bachelor party friends _ born not long before ``This Is Spinal
Tap'' came out _ were certain the band was comprised of real Brits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, New York talk show host Joe Franklin interviewed Spinal
Tap without doing any prep work and did the interview believing
they were indeed a real band. (This is captured on the new DVD.)
</P>
<P>
   Talk to anyone in the music business today _ nearly two decades
away from Spinal Tap's inception _ and they will tell you the
essence of ``This Is Spinal Tap'' still rings true. As to the
Spinal Tap of 1983 and the rock scene today: The sound may change
and the players certainly do, but behind the scenes it's the same
as it ever was. The song remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   Real musicians love the (in) joke. Fleetwood Mac's Mick
Fleetwood took the drummer's stool for their recent appearance on
VH1's ``The List'' and may play with them in the future. Spinal Tap
legend has it he answered a newspaper ad reading, ``Drummer Died,
Need New One.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Spinal Tap _ the entity itself _ lives again. The group has
released a new song called ``Back From the Dead,'' which St.
Hubbins has described as ``a good hard-rock-industrial-Latino
-desperate-attempt-at-a-hit-single, really.'' It is downloadable
via Tapster. That's right, Tapster. There is only one song you can
download with Tapster.com. Spinal Tap reckons this makes it a whole
lot less confusing than the myriad choices Napster offers. About
85,000 fans have downloaded the tune in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tap canon
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Said Tufnel: ``There's nothing wrong with being shameless.
There's a fine line between opportunism and exploitation.'' Added
Smalls: ``We're not unnecessarily concerned about intellectual
property _ this isn't about Harvard, Yale and Oxford.'' Lyrical
bits from the song: ``There's nothing more fun than flipping off
the reaper'' and ``Give me resurrection or give me death.'' ``Back
From the Dead'' joins the Tap canon with ``Tonight I'm Gonna Rock
You Tonight,'' ``Big Bottom'' ``Bitch School'' and ``Hell Hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Halpern, 32, was the guy who discovered 30 hours of outtakes
from the movie. He had seen the movie dozens of times. As vice
president of special projects, his job for StudioCanal, the French
company that bought the roster of the defunct Embassy Pictures (the
original home of ``This Is Spinal Tap''), involves cinematic
excavation. Halpern was aware of a blurry 4 1/2-hour (!) version of
the movie that had made the bootlegging circuit. He says after
StudioCanal took over Embassy, he was searching in a salt
mine-cum-storage facility in Kansas, where he found 30 hours of
footage. ``We brought it back to Paris,'' he says, ``where Rob
Reiner said he was happy to have the outtakes used, but the film
that came out (originally) is the director's cut of the film.''
</P>
<P>
   But fans will see Tufnel tediously explain how Spinal Tap
incorporated Indonsian scales into their music and they'll witness
much of the _ now they can be named! _ Shut Up and Eat mime troupe
that caters a Spinal Tap party. Billy Crystal is fabulous as the
profane and verbally ticked-off head mime/waiter. Other scenes are
less scintillating, more banal. And, yet, as banality is central to
Spinal Tap's ethos, even that makes sense _ just as their
ponderously long (two-and-a-half hours) show at the former Great
Woods Center for the Performing Arts in 1992. Message: You've got
to love rock 'n' roll in order to loathe it. Or vice versa.
Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing the movie communally, says Halpern, can be a ``Rocky
Horror Picture Show'' type of thing, with audiences reciting the
lines along with the actors.
</P>
<P>
   When we spoke to Tufnel back then, he championed the generic
nature of Spinal Tap's music. ``I don't think it's anything to be
ashamed of,'' he said. ``We are, in record shops in England, listed
under `generia.' They've got hard rock, speed metal, industrial,
slash and thrash and bash _ stupid names like that to make it sell
_ and then generia. It's much more shameful to say we are thinking
of a new description of music.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though Spinal Tap is an amalgamation of cliches, we always
thought two bands at the core were the British groups Status Quo _
who like the Tap had an early psychedelic-pop hit and then went
hard rock _ and Judas Priest. Christopher Guest, who first created
the Tufnel character in 1975 for a series of National Lampoon radio
shows, wouldn't drop any names when we talked. He did say this
inspired him: ``I saw a band check into a hotel I was staying in in
Los Angeles and these guys walked in _ I don't remember what band
it was _ and they were English and one of the musicians said to the
manager `I don't know where my bass is.' The manager said `What do
you mean?' And he says `I think I left it at the airport.' And the
manager says `You left your bass at the airport?' `Yeah, I don't
know where it is,' says the musician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, this went on for about 20 minutes and I thought, `This
is insane, here are these guys, they're incredibly dim and they're
traveling around in a cloud of stupidity. Boy, this is funny. Some
day, God, I've got to get this on film.'''
</P>
<P>
   And, Spinal Tap is with us again. Spinal Tap plays a concert in
Los Angeles at the Hard Rock Cafe Sept. 5 to celebrate its
re-emergence. There are plans for a show in London and the
possiblity of a US tour. Will they be with us always? Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``They absolutely love these characters,'' says Halpern of the
three writer-actors, ``and they love doing Spinal Tap. They stay in
character the second they walk out of the dressing room.'' Coming
soon, maybe: Action figures and an animated TV series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4194 &Cx1f; tdt-z
