<SLUG> BC-ARTS-DUMBING-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE THE ARTS DUMBING DOWN? 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN DEZELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this era of infotainment, Americans are supposed to be glued
to their tubes. But as anyone who's been to an art museum, theater,
or concert hall recently can attest, what was used to be called
``high culture'' is wildly popular right now.
</P>
<P>
   Museum of Fine Arts galleries are thronged with visitors on wet
winter evenings and weekend afternoons in high summer. Commonwealth
Shakespeare Company drew 1,500 to 2,000 people on clear nights to
see ``The Tempest'' on Boston Common in early August. The Boston
Lyric Opera scrambles to keep up with subscription demand.
</P>
<P>
   Public enthusiasm for art, music, theater, and dance is raising
some highbrow eyebrows, however. Academics, connoisseurs, and
critics maintain that as arts organizations market themselves to
draw new audiences, the quality of their offerings has been
``dumbed down.'' ``Popularity is not necessarily a measure of
success'' in the arts, cautions James Cuno, director of the Harvard
Art Museums. Too many institutions, he says, are compromising their
standards as they scramble to respond to ``bottom-line pressures
that reared their ugly heads in the 1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   It is now a common perception in visual arts circles that
museums in general and the MFA in particular pander to the palate
of an unsophisticated public with a steady diet of blockbuster
exhibitions (see sidebar). Boston Symphony Orchestra musicians
complain that the classical repertory of the Boston Pops is
devolving to meet the demands of television and mass audiences.
Accusations of ``dumbing down'' crop up more and more often in
cultural news and reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dumbing down'' surfaced as a buzz phrase in the early 1980s
and has since been used ``to describe the perceived deterioration
of almost anything,'' says sociologist Herbert J. Gans, author of
``Popular Culture and High Culture: An Analysis and Evaluation of
Taste.'' It is bandied about a lot these days to describe political
discourse, TV quiz shows, the world as seen through the lens of the
Farrelly brothers _ and the state of the arts.
</P>
<P>
   But is a Monet exhibition really comparable to ``There's
Something About Mary''? Does a megamusical like ``The Phantom of
the Opera'' diminish or increase the vitality of theater and opera?
(See sidebar.) Is keeping an eye on the bottom line really
detrimental to art?
</P>
<P>
   Not at all, says Gans. As he sees it, some of the most vocal
avatars of aesthetic standards are in high dudgeon not because the
arts are getting dumber, but because they're increasingly
democratic. As elite arts institutions have been forced out of
``commercial necessity'' to expand their constituencies, he says,
the people who used to control them and ``use them for status''
have gone into a ``cultural panic.'' To some traditional patrons,
the market-minded museum is dumbing down, he says. ``To people who
are seeing it for the first time, it's smartening up.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the cri de coeur over cultural deterioration emanates
from what John Seabrook, author of ``Nobrow: The Culture of
Marketing _ The Marketing of Culture,'' calls ``townhouse
culture.'' It is, he says, the once rarified realm of a largely
``Ivy League educated, mostly Protestant establishment'' whose
aristocratic taste for painting, music, theater, ballet, and
literature for many years functioned as ``high culture for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, they were able to present their standards as
a matter of common sense and good taste,'' he observes. During the
culture wars of the 1980s, as ``it became clear that this
particular subculture's values did not represent the culture at
large, the jig was up.''
</P>
<P>
   Government arts funding was slashed. The self-made and
business-minded started displacing men of inherited wealth on
institution boards, and they encouraged new efficiencies and the
building of new constituencies. In-house academics accustomed to
curating exhibits for the art savvy, musicians used to playing for
experienced concertgoers, and playmakers who once mounted shows for
theatergoers who knew Chekov and Shakespeare had to change their
assumptions about presenting a performance.
</P>
<P>
   The sizes of all arts audiences surged. The latest figures
available from the National Endowment for the Arts show that more
than half of American adults go at least once a year to one or more
of the following: a jazz or classical music concert; opera; the
ballet; stage musical; play; or an art museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The status that one used to get from going to hear classical
music _ the assumption that you went because you were a sort of
tasteful person _ isn't guaranteed anymore,'' says Seabrook.
Townhouse denizens were losing social as well as institutional
power. ``As they felt their power to uphold standards eroding, they
started crying `dumbing down' about everything.'' They complained
about crassness, marketing, ``the masses,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But the public that is coming in the townhouse door is hardly
uncivilized, Seabrook says. ``The masses are watching Martha
Stewart and going to Pottery Barn.''
</P>
<P>
   The developments certainly seem to be disturbing a very vocal
sector of the local culturati: the critics of MFA director Malcolm
Rogers who Rogers says have dismissed his successful audience
outreach efforts, telling him, ``Well, it's fine that more people
are coming to the museum, but they're not really `museum people.'
'' Or the small-town music critic FleetBoston Celebrity Series
executive director Martha Jones saw ``get up at intermission and
blast three people for clapping between movements'' at a symphonic
concert at Jordan Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Concerts and plays are shorter today than they were a decade
ago. Museums have upgraded their retail outlets and restaurants for
the simple reason that Americans like to eat and shop when they go
out. Most arts organizations have beefed up ``branding'' efforts to
increase public awareness in a time of information overload. The
buses emblazoned with Vincent van Gogh portraits this summer bring
the artist, the show, and the MFA to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations that barely recognized one another's existence as
recently as five years ago are doing joint programming and
cross-promotion. Last winter's ``Egypt in Boston'' collaboration
among the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston Lyric Opera, the Wang Center,
and the Science Museum did boffo box office business for one and
all. Chicago cultural organizations essentially replicated the
program this summer when ``Pharoahs of the Sun: Akhenatan,
Nefertiti, Tutankhamen'' went from the MFA to the Art Institute of
Chicago, and the Boston Lyric Opera production of ``Akhnaten'' was
mounted at the Chicago Opera Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that all of us have become more market
oriented,'' says Don Sturdy, director of artistic operations at
Boston Ballet, and a veteran arts administrator. In the last
decade, arts organizations have ``had to balance our budgets on the
basis of marketing, and when you do that, you have to find out what
people want.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of competition out there, it's harder to get and
hold people's attention. It's a challenge to maintain your artistic
agenda and meet the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   But any organization ``worth its salt in this town'' is doing
that, Sturdy says. ``Sure we've seen examples of bad art produced
because someone thought it would be commercially successful. We've
seen bad art that isn't commercial'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Celebrity Series is among arts presenters that are scaling
back ``the number of presentations and the number of events within
each discipline,'' says Jones. ``When we had six or seven classical
music concerts, the halls were not full. We now have two to five. I
have many more subscribers in the past two years than I had five
years ago and more people are coming to classical music concerts
than there were five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The BSO has moved some of its youth concerts out of Symphony
Hall and into churches in Roxbury and South Boston. It plays more
free concerts now. ``For a long time, we had a very inward focus,''
says BSO managing director Mark Volpe. ``In this world, that's
counter to your best interests. Orchestras are fighting for
relevance in ways they didn't have to 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boston Symphony and Boston Pops belong to everyone. We had
to broaden,'' says Volpe. ``It's a change. That threatens some
people. But democratizing isn't dumbing down. When we played in
Franklin Park, we did some popular music. We also did Stravinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
