<HEADER>
A4195 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ART-GILOT-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     08-28 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-GILOT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... cold tones.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gilot was able to leave Picasso in 1953 with their two children
_ Paloma and Claude, who is now a Paris-based designer _ because
she had both guts and money. While Picasso later rejected the
children, she's stayed close to them all their lives. (She has a
third, a daughter, Aurelia, from her marriage to artist Luc Simon
from 1955 to 1962.) Images of her children close the BC show, and
while they're hardly sentimental _ sentimental isn't Gilot's style
_ they're the work of a loving mother. They're essays in roundness,
as some of Picasso's baby portraits of Claude and Paloma are as
well. Gone are the needly angles with which Gilot drew their
father. In Gilot's ``The Door,'' Claude enfolds his little sister
like a blanket and tickles her chin. In the background is a
Lilliputian door, the kind that might lead to a fairy-tale land.
</P>
<P>
   As for Picasso, ``The whole thing around him is hysteria,''
Gilot says. ``Everybody knows that name. You ask people if they
know Jasper Johns, and many don't. Good or bad, a book about
Picasso will sell.'' She's written a couple herself: ``Life With
Picasso'' and ``Matisse and Picasso: A Friendship in Art.''
Meanwhile, a huge book about her comes out this fall: the 450 page
``Francoise Gilot: Monograph 1940-2000,'' to be published by the
Lausanne-based Acatos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pablo is good subject matter,'' she says, ``but he didn't
produce that many masterpieces. There will be a reassessment of
him, to eliminate the rubbish. It takes time to assess a career.
There are misconceptions, and anecdotes take over. Not so much
would be written about van Gogh if he hadn't cut his ear off.
Cezanne had a quiet life, so not that much is written about him.
The life of the artist doesn't explain the art. Verlaine was a
drunk, but that doesn't explain Verlaine.''
</P>
<P>
   In the annals of 20th century art, the reputations of precious
few women artists have matched those of their male artist
companions or spouses. Frida Kahlo and Georgia O'Keeffe, whose
reputations soared posthumously, come to mind. Not many others do.
Gilot believes that the painter Lee Krasner, who was married to
Jackson Pollock, ``eventually will come into her own.'' As for her
own status, ``I am being recognized,'' she says. ``If I'd been a
man, I would have been recognized earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years after those covered in the BC show, she's stayed
prolific as a painter. Her marriage to Salk was as unconventional
as other aspects of her life, structured so each could focus on one
thing at a time. ``We agreed to spend six months of the year
together and six months apart,'' she says. ``We got all our
separate business done during the months apart. Why should Jonas
have to go to an art opening? Why should I have to go to a
scientific congress? During our time together, we had no
interruptions.'' Ditto for when they were in lab or studio. ``Jonas
once told his first wife, when she said something to him while he
was working, `You have my undivided inattention.' I feel the same
way when I'm painting.''
</P>
<P>
   Long ago, Gilot inherited her grandmother's house in the chic
Parisian suburb of Neuilly. She immediately sold it, because ``My
grandmother was still in the rooms for me. I did the same when
Jonas died; I sold the house right away. I want the memory, not the
thing. It would be unbearable to be there. When someone I love
dies, I usually can't paint for about six months. My paintings look
intellectual, but they're based on very strong feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   From her years with Picasso she kept just one of his paintings _
his famous 1946 portrait of her, ``Woman-Flower.'' It's Picasso's
response to Matisse's comment that if he were to paint Gilot, she'd
have blue skin and green hair. Picasso, ever competitive, beat him
to it.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Gilot finally sold ``Woman-Flower.'' ``I thought
it was bringing me bad luck,'' she says. ``It's important to detach
from the past _ so you can move into the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
