<SLUG> BC-ART-GILOT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THE CERTAINTY IN FRANCOISE GILOT'S WORK IS CLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``There was never anything tentative in my work,'' says
Francoise Gilot. ``I was a good painter when I was 12 years old.''
Nothing remains of her earliest art, though. It was all on a truck,
laden with her family's valuables, that was bombed by the Germans
as it headed south from occupied Paris in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Gilot, now 78 and based in New York, has built a
six-decade track record as an artist who has exhibited and sold
internationally. Her current show at Boston College's McMullen
Museum attests to her talent _ especially in works on paper, where
she is first-rate. Banners up and down Commonwealth Avenue outside
the museum reproduce one of her drawings: The subject is Pablo
Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   Gilot had the decidedly mixed blessing of a decade-long
association with the 20th century's most famous artist. She was as
un-tentative in their relationship as she was in her art. Of all
his wives and long-term mistresses (she's in the latter category),
she was the only one to walk out on him, after a history of such
incidents as his burning her cheek with a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Gilot later had a much calmer 25 year marriage to Jonas Salk,
developer of the polio vaccine, which ended with his death in 1995.
She is the mother of Paloma Picasso, the high-profile jewelry
designer. She is more famous by association than on her own,
although her face is eerily familiar from Picasso's portraits, at
least from the less scrambled-looking ones, and from the iconic
Robert Capa photograph of her walking triumphantly on the beach as
a beaming Picasso trails behind, holding a huge umbrella to shield
her from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   But Gilot's 1944 drawing of Picasso _ the one on the BC banners
_ is severe, and hints at his celebrated sadism. The lines of his
forehead suggest an arcane geometry lesson. His eyes are huge and
hypnotic; his mouth drawn, as if his teeth were clenched. His
Adam's apple is a protruding egg.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Adam. Gilot reverses the roles of the biblical Adam
and Eve in her 1946 drawing of ``Adam Forcing Eve to Eat the
Apple.'' ``I was always annoyed at the biblical story,'' she says,
standing in front of the drawing during a recent visit to BC. ``One
of the most important things in my character is I always wanted to
know by myself, and not swallow what I was told just because it was
in a book.'' Her Picasso/Adam stuffs the apple down Gilot/Eve's
throat, while pounding his other fist. It's a sexually violent
image, the bold, black angles on Picasso's face an economical way
to suggest nastiness. Gilot's hands, meanwhile, lie awkwardly on
the table, as if she were momentarily unable to force their muscles
into action.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso was world-famous and 40 years older than she when they
met in 1943. One strategy she used to skirt the danger of imitating
his potent art once she moved in with him in 1946 was minimalism,
paring down both color and composition. She calls it ``my white
period. When I started to live with him, I preferred to work in a
more restricted palette.'' She learned that ``If you have the means
to say 10 things, say 3. Keep it powerful.'' Picasso is present in
some of her paintings, in the liberties she took with the human
figure. But Matisse is there, too, in the liberties she took with
color, and some of her work calls Gauguin or van Gogh to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pablo once asked me, `If you were condemned to death by a
judge and had to do a drawing very fast to save your life, what
would you draw?,' '' she recalls. ``I said, `a circle, which I
could do perfectly, without a compass.'' Which is what she did in
``The Painter,'' an austere exercise in balance. Against a snowy
white gouache ground floats a long rectangle with a single knowing
eye in it, her eye. An arrow _ her symbol, as a Sagittarius _
points directly up from it, barely touching a balloonlike orb, a
perfect orb. The arrow seems both creator and potential destroyer.
</P>
<P>
   Francoise Gilot has impeccable posture, vivid features capped by
the eyebrows Matisse compared to circumflex accents, blunt-cut hair
a convincing shade of auburn, and stamina: She stood for a two-hour
interview in the BC museum, so we could look at her art while we
talked. She was wearing a long chiffon print dress and, among her
other jewels, a gigantic ring, designed by her daughter, in which
peridot and amethyst jostle for space.
</P>
<P>
   She and McMullen director Nancy Netzer deliberately restricted
the BC show to work from 1940 to 1950, the first decade of her
career. Gilot wanted BC students to see what she was doing when she
was their age. Whether this will inspire or intimidate them will be
seen after the fall semester starts. Gilot hardly revolutionized
painting, but her art, even early on, is both beautiful and sure.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by her work, she talked about the formidable feminist
heritage that has at times kept her going: a great-grandmother who
was a disciple of George Sand; a grandmother who knew Marie Curie.
Her own mother was a watercolorist who started teaching her
daughter to paint when Francoise was 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I received the Legion d'Honneur'' _ France's highest award _
``for being a feminist and as a painter,'' she says proudly. ``I
said, `What did I do as a feminist?' They said, `It's not what you
do, it's what you are.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, she is solitary. ``I was an only child. And
as a painter, you're alone in your studio. You're kind of a monk.''
When students ask her if they have what it takes to become a good
painter, she poses a question to them: ``How many hours can you be
alone in a week, a month, a lifetime?''
</P>
<P>
   While she knew from early childhood that she wanted to be a
painter, Gilot enrolled in law school in Paris, following the
wishes of her father, a wealthy agronomist. In 1940, as a law
student, she joined a rally at the Arc de Triomphe to protest the
German occupation. ``There was a little fighting,'' she recalls, ``
and I was put on a list of hostages.'' If the French killed any
Germans, she'd be jailed _ or worse. She had to report to the
police daily, until her father bribed them to remove her from the
list. ``It was a very strange feeling: I was alive because my
parents were affluent.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't finish law school, although ``I must say I did not
dislike it. It teaches you to analyze. I just didn't want to do it
all my life.'' She attended art schools in Paris, ``but I didn't
learn anything so special. I knew painting from the beginning. What
was interesting to me was drawing and composition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has never been easy to enter the art world, but for a woman
it's more normal in France than here,'' she says, citing a list of
French predecessors from Rococo portraitist Marie-Louise-Elisabeth
Vigee-Lebrun to the Impressionist Berthe Morisot. ``Wanting to
paint was not exceptional for a woman in France,'' she says, ``but
the US was still a century behind when I came here the first time,
in 1961.''
</P>
<P>
   Her 1941 ink portrait of Hungarian painter Endre Rozsda hangs in
the BC show. I refer to him as her ``teacher.'' ``He was my
mentor,'' she corrects, as if by then she didn't need teaching. The
drawing of Rozsda and one of herself, also from 1941, both show
that by the time she was 20, Gilot was a completely confident
draftsman. She looks straight out of the picture, with a stunned
expression, as if she's seen Hell but is not about to be cowed by
it. The line is as unflinching as her expression. ``This was made
during the War,'' she says. ``We didn't know if we'd be alive at
the end of it _ or even the next day. I had to make a complete
testament in my art, to be decisive.''
</P>
<P>
   She learned to camouflage her subjects through symbolism to
avoid persecution by the Germans. The 1943 ink drawing of ``Dead
Rooster on a Piece of Newspaper'' is ostensibly just that. But the
rooster is also a symbol of France, and the newspaper bears the bad
tidings that France has died. Both are emblems of agony: The paper
is crumpled; the rooster is contorted, its claws flailing in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Her 1942 ``Fish and Knife'' is, on the one hand, a version of an
age-old still-life subject. But she painted it to show how she felt
about the slaughter of French culture. It's a riveting little
picture, with the purplish fish oozing blood, a dirty yellow table
and black background all setting off the blade that became a
recurring symbol of the Nazis in her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fish and Knife'' is a fine example of Gilot as daring
colorist; so is that head of Picasso, which is backed by a
brilliant saffron yellow. ``I've always favored primary colors,''
she says. ``I'll use one of them for two or three years, then
switch. The yellow behind Pablo expresses the intensity of his
being. I thought my own personality was more blue, symbolized by
those cold tones.''
</P>
<P>
