<HEADER>
A4198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-EXECUTE-INNOCENCE-BOS     08-28 1857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECUTE-INNOCENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRY OF INNOCENT TRUMPS MORAL CLAIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The full-page advertisement by the American Civil Liberties
Union shows a man in an electric chair, strapped in and hooded and
ready to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to modern science,'' the ad says, ``17 innocent people
have been removed from death row. Thanks to modern politics, 23
innocent people have been removed from the living.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU's bold and unattributed assertion _ that 23 innocent
men and women have been executed in the United States _ is
compelling stuff, an example of the new tactics by which the foes
of the death penalty have transformed the debate over capital
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   By raising the specter that innocent people have been condemned
to die _ rather than employing the more traditional argument that
capital punishment is immoral _ the ``innocence movement'' has
caught supporters of the death penalty by surprise, put them on the
defensive, and taken a huge bite out of public support for capital
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the death penalty has dropped from 80 percent to 66
percent in some public opinion polls, and to below 50 percent when
respondents to the poll are guaranteed that criminals will serve
life without parole as an alternative. ``Death Knell for Death
Row?'' asked the headline in the June edition of the ABA Journal,
the publication of the American Bar Association, which has called
for a national moratorium on executions.
</P>
<P>
   All this despite the fact that _ the ACLU's advertisement
notwithstanding _ no one has ever proved that a specific innocent
person has been put to death in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The innocence argument is powerful, its proponents say, because
it can generate sympathy and concern for members of a decidedly
unsympathetic group _ death row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most sympathetic person in a death penalty case is always
the victim,'' says Richard Dieter, director of the Death Penalty
Information Center, an advocacy group opposed to capital
punishment. But as DNA technology and other developments have led
to the release of a growing number of prisoners in recent years,
``we have gotten to see innocent people, who had been released,
telling their story,'' said Dieter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That generates sympathy. And the system becomes the focus:
that there must be systemic problems if this many mistakes are
being made.''
</P>
<P>
   The innocence movement ``has had an enormous impact,'' said US
Representative William Delahunt, the Democrat from Massachusetts, a
former prosecutor who opposes capital punishment and has coauthored
one of several bills in Congress to overhaul the system. ``There is
no doubt this is a sea change, an absolute sea change.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of capital punishment, while conceding that the
innocence argument has been an effective rhetorical device for its
foes, accuse their opponents of manipulating the truth and the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The steady drumbeat of the abolitionists is that prosecutorial
misconduct and police misconduct is rampant, that eyewitnesses
frequently misidentify people, that jailhouse snitches lie, and as
a result we have literally scores of innocent people languishing on
death row,'' says Joshua Marquis, the district attorney in Astoria,
Ore., speaking on behalf of the American District Attorney's
Association. ``It is very deceptive . . . and irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Marquis: ``The people of which there are real questions of
factual innocence is an infinitesimal tiny number.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a Globe review of the 660 executions since the US
Supreme Court reinstituted the death penalty in 1976 shows that
about 9 out of 10 of those put to death were anything but innocent:
They pleaded guilty, confessed, volunteered for execution, or
apologized to the families of their victims as they were about to
be executed. Still others claimed to be innocent of the actual
murder, but admitted they participated in the robbery or rape that
led to the homicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such proof of an innocent executed in the US since
1900,'' says Dudley Sharp, a representative from Justice For All, a
Texas-based victims' rights group.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of capital punishment have cause to gripe about the
abolitionist tactics. The ACLU ad campaign, with its elastic
definition of the phrase ``modern,'' demonstrates why.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the ``innocent'' who were executed can be found on
the ACLU Web site. They were compiled by Hugo Bedau, a philosophy
professor at Tufts University, and a colleague for a 1987 article
in the Stanford Law Review, which the ACLU cites as its source.
Ninety percent of the men on the list were executed in the first
part of the 20th century, among them such debatable ``innocents''
as Bruno Hauptmann, executed in 1936 for the kidnap-killing of the
Lindbergh baby; union organizer Joe Hill, executed in Utah in 1915;
and anarchists Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo Vanzetti, who were
executed in Massachusetts in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   Only one man on the ACLU list _ James Adams, who was executed by
Florida in 1984 _ is among the 660 people put to death since 1976.
And like Hauptmann, Hill, and others on the list, the case for
Adams's innocence is far from settled.
</P>
<P>
   Adams was arrested shortly after the robbery and murder of a
Florida rancher in 1974. Though there are questions about
eyewitnesses and physical evidence in the case, Adams was found
with the victim's eyeglasses, and with money and clothing stained
with the victim's type blood, in his possession. A witness saw
Adams's car parked at the victim's house at the time of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Bedau can show that hundreds of innocent people were convicted
of murder and sentenced to die in the 20th century, only to be
freed from death row when a lawyer, court, or media organization
revealed the flaws in the state's case. But he acknowledges that no
scientist or historian has conclusively proven, nor any judge or
government agency ruled, that an innocent has actually been
executed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, in a follow-up to their Stanford Law Review article,
Bedau and his colleages wrote that ``We have not proved these
executed defendants to be innocent; we never claimed that we had.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem is that lawyers with access to the
evidence in these cases are so overwhelmed by the cases of the
living that they don't have time to worry about the dead,'' Bedau
says now.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most educated supposition is a poor basis for the
setting of public policy, especially in such an emotionally
charged, life-and-death matter as capital punishment. But advances
in DNA testing may allow news organizations to re-test the evidence
in a handful of well-known ``innocence'' cases in the coming
months, contributing the first scientific answers to the debate.
(In Georgia last month, the Globe won the first court order to
conduct such tests.)
</P>
<P>
   If no one can name an innocent who was executed, how has the
innocence movement made such gains? The real power of the
abolitionist argument is a matter of odds and logic: If the
judicial system is so prone to error, the abolitionists ask, is it
reasonable to believe that it has never made the ultimate, fatal
mistake?
</P>
<P>
   ``With the number of executions now over 600 and the number of
wrongful convictions . . . I don't have any doubt we have executed
innocent people,'' says William Lofquist, a professor of sociology
at the State University of New York in Geneseo. ``I think it is a
certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bloodsworth, for example, was convicted of raping and
killing a 9-year-old Baltimore girl in 1984. He had been placed at
the scene by several eyewitnesses, who picked him out of a police
lineup. The jury took just two hours to find him guilty, and he was
condemned to death. It was not until 1994 that Edward Blake, a
pioneer in the new science of forensic DNA analysis, tested a tiny
semen stain on the victim's underwear and proved Bloodsworth
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Bloodsworth is a figure on two lists of innocents saved from
prison or death. The first is the list of inmates convicted of
serious felonies who have been cleared and released from prison
and/or death row by DNA tests. It now stands at 70, according to
the New York-based ``Innocence Project,'' led by lawyers Barry
Scheck and Peter Neufeld.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty's defenders, nothing if not determined, refuse
to concede that all the inmates on the DNA list are innocent. When
DNA testing of semen and hair found at the crime scene freed Dennis
Fritz from life in prison and Ron Williamson from death row in
1999, the case was trumpeted by the innocence movement as a typical
injustice that resulted from the perjurious testimony of jailhouse
snitches and faulty, old-fashioned forensic hair analysis.
</P>
<P>
   But Oklahoma officials continue to maintain that Williamson was
involved in the crime. ``Scheck . . . can claim Williamson as
poster material for actual innocence, but I would look further
before creating federal legislation based upon his case,'' Oklahoma
Attorney General W. A. Drew Edmondson told a US Senate committee in
June. ``It is arguable whether he is innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmondson's accusation is a variation of what death penalty
critics contemptuously call the ``unindicted co-ejaculator''
theory, in which law enforcement authorities are forced to concede
that the convicted man may not have performed the crime, but insist
that he could have been present while an unnamed accomplice
assaulted the victim.
</P>
<P>
   A second, and somewhat overlapping list, of ``innocents,'' is
maintained by the Washington DC-based Death Penalty Information
Center. The DPIC list contains the names of 87 condemned men who
have been freed from death row because of either DNA tests or other
legal maneuvers. It has its own critics.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp says that the DPIC list is misleading because fewer than a
third of the people on the list can be said to be factually
innocent; the rest are categorized ``innocent'' because a retrial
or legal technicality voided their original conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Muneer Deeb's lawyers, for example, got his death sentence
overturned on appeal, and at a subsequent retrial he was acquitted
of his part in the brutal murder of three young people in Waco,
Texas. But Sharp notes that three of Deeb's alleged accomplices in
the case were convicted on the same evidence and one, David Spence,
was executed. While the legal outcome of the case raises questions
about the capriciousness of capital punishment _ If they were all
guilty, why was only Spence executed? _ it is not proof that Deeb
was factually innocent.
</P>
<P>
   For the abolitionist community _ largely comprising idealistic
professionals, civil libertarians, and underpaid lawyers who have
watched their clients march off to death _ any fudging of the facts
is justified by the scope of the moral evil they believe they are
battling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am troubled by some of the claims of innocence,'' Lofquist
acknowledges. ``On the other hand, I take the perspective that we
as a nation are doing something that is clearly wrong and barbaric
and out of step with the rest of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
