FILMS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!! 1/2 ``Aimee and Jaguar'' Affecting, handsomely made,
superbly acted German film based on a true story about a
dangerously impassioned lesbian love affair in Nazi Berlin in
1943-'44. Maria Schrader is the bold, flirty Jewish cosmopolite
with doom in her flashing eyes. Juliane Kohler is no less affecting
as a hedonistic housewife who can't resist smiling a goofy smile as
her bourgeois world is turned upside down. (Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``Bring It On'' Kirsten Dunst stars in a comedy of Southern
California high school cheerleading angst, squeaking her way
through one crisis after another with improbable allure, aided
mightily by a couple of much cooler big-city girls played by
Gabrielle Union and Eliza Dushka. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``The Crew'' Retired mobsters Richard Dreyfuss, Burt Reynolds,
Dan Hedaya, and Seymour Cassell get into trouble in Miami Beach
when, faced with the loss of their low-rent hotel, they revert to
their old bungling ways. A few laughs, but mostly it's as lame and
poky and predictable as its geezers with guns. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Steal This Movie!'' An earnest but scattered biopic about
counterculture radical and street theater provocateur Abbie
Hoffman. His charismatic antics, persecution by the FBI, and years
on the lam are depicted with gusto, but only intermittent success,
by Vincent D'Onofrio in a piecemeal film that never quite
convincingly captures the superheated '60s and '70s. (R)
</P>
