<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4203 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-INNOCENCE-MOVEMENT-BO     08-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INNOCENCE-MOVEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SACCO AND VANZETTI TO DNA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The origins of the modern innocence movement can be traced to
Massachusetts, and to Sara Ehrmann, a foe of capital punishment
whose husband was one of the lawyers for Nicola Sacco and
Bartolomeo Vanzetti, two anarchists who were executed in Boston in
the Red Scare of 1927.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the Mother Courage of the anti-death penalty
movement,'' says Hugo Bedau, 73, a Tufts professor of philosophy
who knew Ehrmann and read ``a little article she wrote, published
about 1960, in which she mentioned some cases in Massachusetts and
New England where she believed there was pretty strong evidence the
executed person was not guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Bedau took up the cause, and published a series of works on
capital punishment, which culminated in the 1987 article for the
Stanford Law Review that he turned into a book, ``In Spite of
Innocence: Erroneous Convictions in Capital Cases,'' with
co-authors Michael Radelet and Constance Putnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``That book spurred a strong response,'' says Richard Dieter,
the director of the Death Penalty Information Center. The Reagan
administration assigned its own legal experts to rebut Bedau's
work. In 1993, a US House Judiciary Subcommittee chaired by
Representative Don Edwards of California asked the DPIC to assess
the question of wrongful executions. The DPIC's subsequent report
contained the first list of modern ``innocence'' cases.
</P>
<P>
   But the prevailing political tide was running the other way.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, President Clinton and the Republican-controlled
Congress expanded the federal death penalty for dozens of new
crimes. In 1995, Clinton and Congess eliminated financing for
federal Death Penalty Resource Centers, where lawyers for indigent
defendants got expert advice. In 1996, Congress passed and Clinton
signed the Anti-Terrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act, which
curbed the ability of death row inmates to appeal their cases in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The abolitionists responded as best they could, and stumbled
upon the effectiveness of the ``innocence'' argument
</P>
<P>
   The new science of biotechnology, meanwhile, was evolving at a
rapid pace. In 1988, DNA testing led to the first exoneration of a
wrongfully convicted man, who had spent more than a decade in
prison for a rape he didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of subsequent reports, the US Justice Department
warned prosecutors across the nation that DNA testing was exposing
the inherent flaws of eyewitness testimony, jailhouse informants,
forensic hair analysis, and other standard tools of the criminal
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   A milestone was reached in November 1998, when Lawrence
Marshall, a professor of law, and David Protess, a professor of
journalism at Northwestern University, organized a national
conference on wrongful convictions and the death penalty. Dozens of
former death row inmates came to Chicago, including some who had
been freed by the work of students in Protess's journalism classes.
A year later, Illinois Governor George Ryan, a pro-death penalty
Republican, announced a moratorium on executions in his state.
Illinois, it turned out, had released more innocent men from death
row (13) than it had executed (12) in the modern era.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, conservative icons like The Washington Times,
columnist George F. Will, and evangelist Pat Robertson _ noting
that the taking of innocent life and liberty is the ultimate sin of
big government _ have emerged as critics of capital punishment as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The turn of events has left longtime abolitionists shaking their
heads in wonder. ``If you had asked me in August 1998 whether I
thought that in less than two years there would be a moratorium on
executions in Illinois, and growing distress among politicians and
the media and the general public over the risks of executing the
innocent, I would have said it was impossible _ not a snowball's
chance in hell.'' Bedau says. ``But it seems we are beginning to
face up to the realities of what is going on in this country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4204 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MALE-PILL-ART-BOS &LR;      08-28 1758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALE-PILL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 WILL MEN USE A CONTRACEPTIVE PILL? WILL WOMEN TRUST THEM TO? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As medical breakthroughs go, no one thinks it will be as
revolutionary as the female contraceptive that celebrates its 40th
(non)birthday as a commercial product this month.
</P>
<P>
   But now, four decades after the advent of the pill that finally
divorced the joy of sex from the fear of pregnancy, male hormonal
contraception appears to be on the not-so-distant horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Not just a pill, mind you; it's not quite that simple. This
contraceptive will probably require an implant or injection to
work.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of experiments, including, most recently, one
conducted at the University of Edinburgh, have come up with a
hormonal combination that has proved remarkably successful in
suppressing sperm production in men.
</P>
<P>
   Details are expected early next month, when researchers offer a
fuller presentation of their findings at the International
Federation of Gynecology and Obstetrics meeting in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But initial reports on their work have raised new hope for an
effective male hormonal birth-control method. Richard Anderson, a
clinical scientist working on the project, predicts the day will
arrive in the not-so-distant future when a male method will hit the
market. ``It is not going to be within five years, but within five
to 10 years, I would be very disappointed if there isn't something
available,'' says Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   If so, it will mark the solution to a complicated biological
puzzle, for the science of male birth control is more complicated
than that of the female pill.
</P>
<P>
   First, a female hormone, or gestagen, is used to stop sperm
production. But because that hormone also blocks the body's
production of testosterone, which fuels the libido and supports
other functions, men must also be given a replacement androgen, or
male hormone.
</P>
<P>
   In some subjects the University of Edinburgh research team has
succeeded in effectively eliminating sperm production while
maintaining libido through a pill of the synthetic female hormone
desogestrel, combined with implants that slowly release
testosterone to replace that suppressed by the female hormone.
</P>
<P>
   Male birth control has its skeptics, to be sure. Robert Friar, a
professor of human physiology and sexuality at Ferris State
University in Michigan, insists that, however promising the
research, basic biological differences make an effective male
``pill'' unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really want to reduce fertility in men, there is a way
to do it that is highly effective, easy to do, very inexpensive,
and safe: It is called vasectomy,'' says Friar.
</P>
<P>
   And why not a hormonal method? A matter of math, says Friar.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman releases one egg a month. A man's ejaculate is from
330 to 500 million sperm, so even if you are 99 percent effective,
there will still be thousands of sperm.''
</P>
<P>
   That warning aside, the Edinburgh researchers are confident an
effective male birth control combination is possible. And if the
early promise of their project proves out, then within the next
decade, a male method could bring about a seismic shift in sexual
responsibility roles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite increased condom use, specialists say birth control has
remained primarily a female responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many men have more or less taken the position that it is the
woman's responsibility,'' says Howard J. Ruppel Jr., executive
director of the American Association of Sex Educators, Counselors,
and Therapists. ``I think that is the predominant attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   According to United Nations estimates, two-thirds of couples
practicing contraception worldwide use a female method.
</P>
<P>
   Data from the Alan Guttmacher Institute, a leading nonprofit in
family planning and reproductive health, shows that 28 percent of
American women practicing contraception rely on sterilization,
while 27 percent use the pill.
</P>
<P>
   By gender contrast, 20 percent use male condoms, while 11
percent said their partners have had a vasectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Women even tend to bear the responsibility in those cases when
logic suggests men could more easily do so, says Lawrence B. Finer,
PhD, senior research associate at the institute, who points to the
disparity in sterilization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the fact that male sterilization is a simpler and
safer procedure, it is still that cases that among couples who get
sterilized, female sterilization is much more common than male,''
says Finer.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises several interesting questions.
</P>
<P>
   How willing would men be to use a new birth-control technology _
and how willing would women be to trust them with the
responsibility of birth control?
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly most men seem to agree that they don't play a major
part in contraceptive decisions. A 1997 survey by the Kaiser Family
Foundation, a national health research and education organization,
found that more than two-thirds of men and woman said men should
play a bigger role in choosing and using contraception.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one-fifth of men surveyed confessed to knowing little or
nothing about the range of choices, with another 37 percent saying
they knew only ``some'' about contraceptive options.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Glass, a Baltimore clinical psychologist and marital
therapist, says some men would have masculinity issues with a
birth-control method that stops sperm production.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a man has an empty ejaculation, as occurs in men who have
vasectomies, they might feel emasculated by that,'' Glass says.
Still, in several surveys, men have shown a receptivity to at least
trying such a hormonal method of contraception.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser survey found that 71 percent of men said they would
be willing to consider at least one male birth control option,
while 29 percent said they would not try any male methods. Men
showed most receptivity to birth-control pills, with 66 percent
saying they would try those, compared to 43 percent who said they
would try an injection and 36 percent said they would try an method
that used implants.
</P>
<P>
   International surveys show similar interest in a possible
product, but a marked preference for a pill. In a 1996 study of men
in Edinburgh, Hong Kong, Shanghai, and Cape Town, 44 percent (Hong
Kong) to 83 percent (Edinburgh) said they would try a male pill,
but were less receptive to injections. Only about one-third of Hong
Kong, Shanghai , and Edinburgh men said they would try that method,
compared with 55 percent of the Cape Towners.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the rub: Real-life choices for men aren't likely to
be as simple as swallowing a pill. Although there are a number of
effective female hormones that can be taken orally, thus far no
effective androgen, or male hormone, has been formulated that can
be consumed that way.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, supplying both sperm-suppressing female hormone and the
replacement male hormones will likely require more than a pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oral options are either not very safe or very effective,''
acknowledges Anderson. ``So we need to give it by injection or
implant across the skin,'' through a patch similar to those that
people use to quit smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that if there is ever going to be a product men
are going to be using . . . it will be injectable or an implant,
something that is long acting,'' says Jeff Spieler, chief of
research division of US Agency for International Development's
population office.
</P>
<P>
   But others fear that if the method gets complicated (a
combination of two methods), inconvenient or uncomfortable
(injections), men will be less inclined to use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only know that in clinical trials, men find the procedure
relatively acceptable and would continue using them if they were
available,'' says Spieler.
</P>
<P>
   At least one study of experiment participants explored why men
agreed to try the new birth control method, which in that test
required somewhat painful weekly injections.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most frequent reason given was a need to change
contraceptive method because their partners had had experienced
problems from the pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly every focus group participant whose partner had used
the pill mentioned that she had experienced . . . side effects,''
wrote researcher Karin Ringheim in the June 1995, issue of
International Family Planning Perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   Several other prominent reasons suggested similar concerns,
saying their partner or doctor had urged them to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is particularly interesting in light of the
possible male hormonal method: Some men simply didn't trust their
partner to take birth control regularly.
</P>
<P>
   If some men don't trust women in that regard, would women trust
men with a birth control method that, after all, separates primary
responsibility from primary consequence?
</P>
<P>
   Tina Hoff, director of public health information and
communications for the Kaiser Family Foundation, who has conducted
a number of focus groups on issues of contraception, remains
skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It raises some real trust issues,'' says Hoff. ``For a lot of
women, I think the sense is that it is still up to them to make
sure they are protected since they are the ones who will get
pregnant.'' That, after all, is the message sexual educators and
counselors have long hammered home, says Ruppel.
</P>
<P>
   ``In committed relationships, it certainly could be a symbol of
a man's consideration,'' says Glass, the clinical psychologist and
therapist. ``But in casual relationships, I think that women would
be suspicious about whether a man had really taken it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which suggests male contraception may hold its primary promise
for committed, modern, monogamous couples, particularly those who
have had problems with female contraception.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, says Anderson. He points to a recent survey
connected with his project that showed women overwhelmingly thought
a male hormonal method was a good idea and that only 2 percent said
they wouldn't trust their partners to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even an optimist like Anderson acknowledges that male
hormonal contraception isn't likely to find the open embrace that
the pill has met with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not going to rival the supremacy of the pill, but there
are a lot of other methods around that are only used by small
percentage,'' he says. ``And considering that everybody has sex,
even a small percentage is an awful lot of people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
