<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-BAGELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAND OF SALMON WELCOMES THE BAGEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ In just a generation, the Irish capital has reinvented
itself: Sleek, continental cafes have elbowed their way alongside
the traditional, wooden pubs where the likes of Brendan Behan and
Patrick Kavanagh would trade insults as often as literary bons
mots.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that long ago that the only readily available ethnic
food here was fish and chips, which some Dubliners considered
foreign because so many chippers were run by Italian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Dublin is as cosmopolitan as most European capitals, and
you can dine on anything from Belgian moules (mussels) to
Indonesian rice.
</P>
<P>
   But until recently, it was impossible to get a decent bagel in
Dublin, not to mention all of Ireland. The bagels produced in
Portobello, home to Dublin's dwindling Jewish community, were a
pale imitation of those being made in Jewish bakeries in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   As Dublin began attracting an increasingly cosmopolitan
population of both tourists and residents, a French bakery tried to
fill the void. But their mass-produced bagel, sold in supermarkets,
tasted like a bread roll.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the Kemp sisters. Though they are both accomplished
equestrians, Peaches and Domini Kemp are also enterprising
entrepreneurs. Having sampled the real thing in New York, they knew
there was a market in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   And so itsabagel was born. Nestled on Lower Liffey Street, the
shop has become a shrine for those in search of a bagel fix in
Dublin. At lunchtime, crowds snake around the corner toward the
river for which the street is named.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing better than we could ever have hoped,'' Peaches
said, taking a break from one of her 14-hour days.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters grew up in the Bahamas. Their father was Scottish,
their mother Irish. Peaches, the elder, went to high school in
Virginia. But after their father died in 1983, their mother decided
to move back to Ireland. Peaches and Domini became accomplished
riders and show jumpers, but they also knew that they had to pay
for their horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a catering business in the early '90s, doing mostly
dinner parties, and Domini helped me,'' said Peaches. ``Domini went
to England to work, and did a course at the Cordon Bleu in
London.''
</P>
<P>
   Domini returned to Dublin and became the business partner of
Conrad Gallagher, one of the most imaginative chefs in Ireland,
helping him to establish Peacock Alley, one of Dublin's most
celebrated restaurants. But when the relationship ended, Domini and
her sister became partners again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Domini had the idea about bagels,'' Peaches said. ``We had
bagels in the States, and we knew there was nothing like it in
Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the sisters assumed they would bake their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found it was more complicated than we thought,'' Peaches
said.
</P>
<P>
   From a business standpoint, it was more attractive to import
bagels from New York than to bake them in Dublin, or even bring
them in from North London, where there is a plethora of Jewish
bakeries.
</P>
<P>
   So, displaying a business acumen and chutzpah that goes down
well in New York, the sisters Kemp asked the venerable bagel maker,
H &AMP; H of New York, if they could be its exclusive agents in
Ireland. Given that no one was knocking their door down for the
rights to the Irish market, H &AMP; H agreed and the rest was, well,
itsabagel.
</P>
<P>
   If H &AMP; H is good enough for Barbra Streisand, Peaches reasoned,
they're good enough for the punters in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took some convincing,'' Peaches reported, noting that a
company that bakes more than 200 million bagels a year for export
to Germany, France, Japan, and the ultimate bagel critics in
Israel, was somewhat taken aback by the approach from two Gentile
sisters from the most Catholic country in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But the relationship between the kosher company and the Irish
entrepreneurs has proved a mutually beneficial one.
</P>
<P>
   When the first shipment of 80,000 bagels arrived at Dublin
Airport in January 1999, perplexed customs officials scratched
their heads, never having seen anything resembling the mass of
dough before them. But they eventually let in the consignment.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up shop in the Epicurean Food Hall, a temple to the
changing tastes of a Dublin that once considered a balanced diet as
three pints of Guinness and three sausage rolls, itsabagel took off
and hasn't looked back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had New York Jews come in here and praise our bagels,''
said Peaches, offering perhaps the ultimate testimonial.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, bagels are on offer in some of Dublin's better hotels.
You can get a big, fat New York bagel at the K Club, the exclusive
golf course just outside Dublin. The Kemp sisters are the
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Not ones to rest on their laurels, the Kemp sisters are putting
their own stamp on the New York bagels, garnishing them with Caesar
salad, goat cheese and roasted red peppers, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Kemp sisters been born a century ago, they would, no
doubt, have been part of literary history. One can imagine Leopold
Bloom, the protagonist of James Joyce's ``Ulysses,'' taking a pass
on his gorgonzola sandwich at Davy Byrnes's pub and instead making
a beeline across the Liffey for itsabagel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
