r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     08-28 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES WRESTLE OVER PHANTOM SURPLUS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By J.R. LABBE 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republican and Democratic presidential candidates are
working themselves into a lather, seeing who can impress the most
voters with plans for the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore wants to spend it on more federal programs. He has such
a long litany of new programs, in fact, that his promises extend
way beyond the money projected for the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush wants to give a goodly portion of it _ $1.3
trillion _ back to the taxpayers in the form of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Don't parse this campaign promise too carefully. Even if the
surplus materializes, it's not as if every American _ or even just
the rich ones _ will be getting checks in the mail. Bush doesn't
mean to literally give it ``back''; he means that the government
shouldn't exact as much in taxes in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore may be diametric opposites when it comes to
governing philosophies, but they are blood brothers on the subject
of the surplus: Neither can afford to have the American people
figure out that it is nothing more than political smoke and
mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Never were two men more happy about the fact that journalists
run from numbers stories like Willie Nelson from the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   People, there is no federal budget surplus _ not if you remove
Social Security taxes from the mix of money rolling into the U.S.
Treasury. Yes, thanks to a firecracker-hot economy, the nation's
operating budget last year was just about balanced for the first
time in almost four decades. But one good year does not make up for
39 years of deficit spending.
</P>
<P>
   How best to explain this ... Say your family's living expenses
for a year total $50,000. Last year, because of a generous boss and
sales bonuses, the income-earners in the household brought in
$60,000. You're 10 grand ahead, right? Hello, surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Because you've conveniently overlooked the $25,000
balance you owe on those credit cards _ a balance that you've just
been chipping away at by paying the minimum amount every month plus
interest. Even if you put the total $10,000 toward paying off this
debt, you're still $15,000 in the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Our nation's deficit spending has put the national debt at a
staggering $5.6 trillion, appropriately known in government
parlance as the Gross Federal Debt. The interest alone in 1999 was
$353 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly held debt _ money borrowed from the private market _
was $3.6 trillion at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For the mathematically challenged, this means the government
owes itself a whopping $2 trillion after borrowing from places like
trust fund surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   And what would be the trust fund of choice from which the
government borrows? Social Security, which for now takes in more
money than it pays out.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, use the word ``borrow'' and the implication exists
that one day _ someday _ the money will be paid back. Baby boomers
need to be asking _ no, demanding _ that ``someday'' is now. 'Cause
when they start to retire in droves come 2010, the money they
believed would be available to fund part of their golden years
isn't going to be there.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton pushed the surplus deception headlong into the
public psyche when he announced that America had a $124 billion
federal budget surplus in 1999. In June, he added to the
misinformation by telling America that the federal budget surplus
would total nearly $1.9 trillion over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   One tiny little detail was left out of the press release: Almost
every last dime of it was in the Social Security trust fund, which
is not part of on-budget accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Office of Management and Budget's ``A Citizen's Guide
to the Federal Budget'' explains it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the unified budget first booked a surplus of $69 billion
in 1998, the on-budget accounts were /still in deficit by $30
billion.'' In 1999, the unified budget ran a $124 billion surplus,
nearly all of which was the result of the Social Security surplus.
The on-budget accounts were almost exactly in balance'' (emphasis
added).
</P>
<P>
   The ``surplus'' is almost all in an account that isn't supposed
to be touched for anything other than Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   When you hear the presidential candidates talk about projected
budget surpluses that reach into the trillions, and about only
using that portion of the surplus that isn't needed to shore up
Social Security, remember that Gross Federal Debt. Even if they
repaid the $2 trillion taken out of the trust fund, talking about
tax cuts and new federal programs when we're still $3.6 trillion in
debt is ... well, gross.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1409EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
