<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Aug. 29:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-FIRE (Moscow) _ Developments in the aftermath of a fire
guts Moscow's television tower, knocking networks off the air. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AFRICA (Dateline to kum) _ Developments in President
Clinton's African trip: He witnesses a Burundi accord signed in
Arusha, Tanzania, then travels to Cairo for Mideast peace talks
with Hosni Mubarak, the Egyptian president. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ABORTION (Mexico City) _ The debate over abortion,
illegal in much of Mexico, grows as the governor of the state where
President-elect Vincente Fox used to be governor is set to announce
Monday whether he'll sign new state law barring abortion for women
who have been raped. Critics say the new law reflects how the Roman
Catholic Church and its allies in Fox's conservative party have
been energized by his election. By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-ELECT (Beirut) _ Early election returns show
government's candidates doing poorly. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   BURMA-DISSIDENT (Bangkok, Thailand) _ The roadside standoff
between pro-democracy leader Aung San Suu Kyi and the military
government _ the fifth in recent years _ is a test of endurance,
which she is expected to lose again, that mirrors the broader
political situation. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-GULEN (Istanbul) _ The Turkish government has dropped
sedition charges against Getullah Gulen, a religious leader who
lives in Pennsylvania. Gulen is the head of a prospering Islamic
community with hundreds of schools in Turkey, the Balkans and
Central Asia. For many years he was an unofficial ambassador for
Turkey who promoted a moderate brand of Islam. He preached
tolerance, meeting with Pope John Paul II and other religious and
political leaders, among them Turkey's prime ministers and
presidents. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-VII (Undated) _ Feature on the 1988 presidential
campaign and George W. Bush's role in his father's successful race.
By Nicholas D. Kristof. Lastest in a series looking at the career
of the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-DEBATES (Washington) _ The candidates' positions on
debates seems to be as divergent as their competing plans for tax
cuts. Al Gore wants to participate in as many as possible; George
W. Bush is willing to join a handful, but he wants to control the
format as much as possible, and in the process he's challenging the
organization the parties set up in 1984 to hold presidential
debates. The commission plans to hold the first one at the John F.
Kennedy School of Government, but the Bush camp considers Boston to
be hostile turf. Bush also wants a more relaxed format ... more
like a Larry King show than Lincoln-Douglas. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Austin, Texas) _ George W. Bush speaks to B'nai B'rith and
holds a news conference on education. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Tallahassee, Fla.) _ Al Gore talks to seniors about
prescription drugs. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ARYAN-NATION-SUIT (Couer d'Alene, Idaho) _ A woman and son who
were beaten by Aryan Nation guards hope their lawsuit against the
ultra-right group will put it out of business. Jury selection
starts on Monday. By Jo Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   PUMICE-MINE (Flagstaff, Ariz.) _ Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt is expected to announce a final agreement Monday for the
closing of the White Vulcan Mine, whose pumice is so important to
stone-washed jeans. The strip-mining operation has long been an
issue to environmentalists as well as Native Americans, who
consider the area sacred ground. By Ross E. Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   VOUCHERS-MINORITIES (Undated) _ A study shows that minority
students who used vouchers improved their test scores after going
to private schools. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Undated) _ Developments in the recall of Firestone
tires. With reporting from Detroit and Caracas, Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC-SUIT (Undated) _ Hearings are set for Monday in
the copyright infringement trial of Seagram's Universal Music Group
against MP3.com. Universal and four other major record labels sued
MP3.com in January. MP3.com has settled with four of the companies.
By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ECON (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Two days after he was
sworn in as Indonesia's economic czar, Rizal Ramli says that the
International Monetary Fund has become overly involved in the nuts
and bolts of the economy in the course of its $43 billion bailout.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks are moderately higher in early
trading. Seven stocks on the New York Stock Exchange and six stocks
on the American Stock Exchange begin trading in decimals Monday. By
Kenneth Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   LOEWS-WARNING (New York) _ Looking at the sorry state of the
movie theater business after Loews Cineplex Entertainment warns
that second-quarter earnings will be substantially lower than last
year and that it may default on its debt. The stock falls more than
50 percent, to $1.75.
</P>
<P>
   AMC-MMC (Undated) _ Applied Micro Circuits, whose chips speed
data traffic on fiber-optic networks, has agreed to buy
microprocessor designer MMC Networks for $4.5 billion in stock to
fill a gap in its product line. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BOURSES (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The Frankfurt stock
exchange says that it will step in with a counteroffer to save its
planned merger with the London Stock Exchange if a Swedish company
persists with its unsolicited takeover attempt of the London
market. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI (Tokyo) _ Shares of Mitsubishi Motors tumble as
speculation mounts that its president will resign a day after
Japanese police raid the company's headquarters. The company
admitted last week that it had concealed customer complaints about
vehicle defects for 23 years. By Miki Tanikawa.
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-WORRIES (Boise, Idaho) _ Few people still talk about
fretting over whether they can find work. Worries over the quality
of those jobs, however, remain a signature part of the economy for
many people. Many say they are concerned that they cannot keep up
with technological changes or that they are working too many hours
or that their health care coverage is inadequate. This insecurity
may be less significant than the version of early and mid-1990s,
and it may even be exciting for many young or well-educated
workers. But economists say the shift helps to explain perhaps the
most enduring mystery of today's economy: why wage pressures, while
on the upswing, remain more modest than they were in the milder and
shorter economic booms of the recent past. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
