<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos of Dale Russell, a dinosaur aorta and a skeletal
fossil, a photo of a tarantula, a photo of a researcher at a
computer, a photo of a pinball machine, and a photo of an
automobile are available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez
at 212-499-3355.)
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DINO HAD A WARM-BLOODED HEART
</P>
<P>
   A high-tech look at a fossilized dinosaur heart suggests the
beasts that once ruled the Earth may have had more in common with
humans than lizards.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does this specimen have a heart, but computer-enhanced
images of its chest strongly suggest it is a four-chambered,
double-pump heart with a single systemic aorta, more like the heart
of a mammal or bird than a reptile,'' according to Dale Russell, a
paleontologist at North Carolina State University.
</P>
<P>
   The 66 million-year-old Thescelosaurus, found in South Dakota in
1993, was later acquired by the state's Museum of Natural Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The specimen is unique because it has an intact heart. Russell's
colleagues at his state's veterinary medicine school made
two-dimensional computerized tomography scans, from which they
created a 3D model. ``It challenges some of our most fundamental
theories about how and when dinosaurs evolved,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ICE HINTS AT WATER ON MARS
</P>
<P>
   Geologic structures associated with ice on Earth have been
spotted on the first close-up images of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   The features, which are about the size of an SUV, look like
gullies and the deposits of soil and rocks caused by flowing water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The features appear to be so young that they might be forming
today,'' says Michael Malin, of Malin Space Science Systems, San
Diego, Calif., the principal investigator for the Mars Orbiter
Camera on the Mars Global Surveyor spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists previously discounted water on Mars because the
atmospheric pressure at the surface of the red planet is so low
that water would immediately begin to boil.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers now conjecture that when water evaporates, it cools
the ground. Water behind the initial seepage site freezes, creating
an ice dam. When it breaks, it pushes a flood of debris down the
gully.
</P>
<P>
   To follow up on this discovery, NASA plans to put
instrumentation on its 2003 mission to Mars to confirm that the
structures are indeed formed by ice.
</P>
<P>
   TARANTULA IS A HEART-STARTER
</P>
<P>
   University of Buffalo biophysicists have identified an
ingredient in Chilean tarantula venom that can be used to treat
patients with congestive heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   The compound, called GsMTx-4, is one of 150 components isolated
from the venom. It can interfere with the swelling that occurs
during congestive heart failure. The way it interacts with cells
suggests it might be useful in treating other conditions, such as
brain tumors.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to turn the venom component into a drug for
humans.
</P>
<P>
   SEEING HOW RADIATION DAMAGES CELLS
</P>
<P>
   Add to the list of accidental scientific discoveries the first
``movie'' of radiation damaging a protein.
</P>
<P>
   ``The observation was stunning,'' says Joel Sussman, a visiting
biologist at the Brookhaven National Laboratory in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have long known that the energy associated with
various types of radiation can split apart proteins. While
attempting to image the chemical reactions that take place in an
important enzyme of the nervous system, scientists found that the
X-ray beam they were using to illuminate their target was
systematically destroying it. ``It looks like we are seeing weak
points in protein structures that are particularly sensitive to
ionizing radiation,'' says Sussman.
</P>
<P>
   Brookhaven scientists now plan to examine the anti-radiation
potential of various chemicals for use in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   PINBALL TEACHES PHYSICS
</P>
<P>
   Students at Maine East High School in Park Ridge, Ill., have
found a way to harness the powerful force of pinball machines to
learn physics.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a $10,000 grant from Toyota Motor Sales USA,
students constructed the Imagination Maze _ a 9-by-11-foot vertical
pinball machine.
</P>
<P>
   The student-designed maze uses a screw lift to bring a billiard
ball to an elevated starting point. The ball then randomly falls
into one of four tracks. On the way down it strikes a series of
bells, ramps, trampolines, dominoes, loops and jumps before coming
to rest. At the bottom, it's back up the screw lift for another
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with giving this year's students the hands-on experience
of creating a real machine, we intend to use this to teach future
physics students,'' says adviser Scott Welty.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE TEAMS BOW TO CADETS
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know how to stretch a gallon of gasoline, talk to
the cadets at St. Thomas Academy in Mendota Heights, Minn. The
military school's entry into this year's Supermileage competition
achieved an astounding 1,131 mpg.
</P>
<P>
   The team not only beat the second-place winner in the high
school category by 500 mpg, they also out-drove all 10 college
teams. The best that first-place winner Cedarville College of Ohio
could do was 632 mpg. And the trip to the Eaton Proving Grounds in
Marshall, Mich., wasn't even the cadets' best race. Their car
reached 1,322 mpg at the Minnesota Technology Education Association
Supermileage Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The 100-pound, 3.5-horsepower car is built around a carbon-fiber
and foam-core body.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
