<HEADER>
A4231 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-CUTTING-LOOSE-POPMECH     08-28 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUTTING-LOOSE-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUTTING LOOSE: CORDLESS SAWS COME OF AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Illustrations showing each of the saws and a chart of
specifications of each are available on Newscom or by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 By THOMAS KLENCK 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first question we all want answered when any new cordless
tool hits the marketplace is how close does it come to corded-tool
performance. Face it, 120-volt AC is still the standard. And until
someone fits 100 of those 1.2-volt cells in a battery pack, we'll
have to make a few compromises in power and performance. But
circular saws are looking better and better.
</P>
<P>
   To get the real story, we rounded up eight of the latest,
high-voltage cordless saws built for both consumers and
professionals. What did we find? Well, don't buy one to build a
house, but for everything from light-duty remodeling to modest
framing projects, these tools are real contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT THE SAWS
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when a cordless circular saw was only suitable
for handling 1/4-inch-thick panels. The saws we tested are all
designed to handle 2-inch stock, and the high-end tools even cut
through standard framing lumber with the blade set at 45 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   All of the saws come with thin-kerf, carbide-tipped blades for
good reason. More than any corded saw, the performance of these
tools is dependent on the blade _ there's no reserve to force it
through if it is at all dull, and a narrow kerf requires less
energy because there's less wood to remove.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers are not selling just cordless saws, they're
selling cordless systems. So, a good portion of our test tools are
marketed in combination packages with one or more other tools that
use the same battery pack. Skil, for example, doesn't offer its saw
as a stand-alone product, and the only way to buy a Ryobi 18-volt
saw without a drill is to buy it without a battery pack and
charger.
</P>
<P>
   Most experienced carpenters view an unplugged power tool as a
safe tool. However, it's easy to forget that when the battery pack
of a cordless saw is in place, the tool is effectively plugged in.
Extra care is needed with these tools as it is dangerously easy to
get the blade spinning without intending to.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK &AMP; DECKER CS144
</P>
<P>
   The B&AMP;D Firestorm consumer-level entry has a few design features
that make it stand out, even when compared to the high-end tools.
For example, instead of placing the handle over the motor housing,
B&AMP;D puts it directly over the blade. While balance suffers when the
tool hangs in your hand, the idea works because it centers pushing
effort behind the blade. And B&AMP;D makes an honest stab at improving
blade visibility with a clear plastic window in the blade guard.
It's a great idea as long as you keep it clean.
</P>
<P>
   While the Firestorm cuts 2-by-4 lumber at 90 degrees, it won't
cut at 45 degrees. And, at 14.4 volts, you can tell that framing
lumber is an effort. However, our test places this tool's
performance near that of Ryobi and Skil, and you don't need to buy
a drill with the saw.
</P>
<P>
   BOSCH 1660K
</P>
<P>
   With 24-volt power pushing a 6 1/2-inch, 18-tooth, thin-kerf
blade at 3500 rpm, you may just forget that the Bosch 1660K has no
cord.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of features, we liked the highly visible blade-depth
scale on the rear of the blade guard, and there's a hinged dust
port for a shop vacuum. We found the rubber-backed grip
comfortable, and the trigger and trigger-release both worked
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   While the bevel quadrant has a setscrew stop for 90-degree cuts,
there isn't one for 45 degrees. Instead, the saw has a spring-clip
stop that you push out of the way to allow the blade to go beyond
45 degrees. We found this mechanism uncertain and clumsy. Finally,
at 9.6 pounds, the Bosch is almost as heavy as a corded saw.
</P>
<P>
   DEWALT DW007K
</P>
<P>
   Like the Bosch, the 24-volt DeWalt DW007K is heavy, powerful and
big. Unfortunately, blade visibility is not very good. The saw's
cast-aluminum baseplate is the largest in our group, providing a
stable, heavy-duty feel. The base has an integral bevel quadrant
and a setscrew for 90 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   DeWalt uses a battery pack that slides in laterally, rather than
the plug-in version most other makers prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Without a dust port, blade-depth scale, on-board blade wrench,
45-degree bevel capability and adjustable kerf indicator, this is a
no-frills saw, but one that's sure to meet the requirements of most
power users.
</P>
<P>
   HITACHI C6DC
</P>
<P>
   If the Bosch and DeWalt are the heavyweights of this test, the
Hitachi C6DC falls in the middleweight category. The 18-volt saw
feels relatively light and handy _ qualities that might easily be
more important than sheer power for many cordless users.
</P>
<P>
   This carefully detailed saw is well-balanced with comfortable
grips and an easily accessible trigger release. It has good blade
visibility because the pivot link for the baseplate is on the motor
housing rather than the front of the blade guard. What really
helps, though, is a small lamp that illuminates the area in front
of the blade as soon as the trigger release is depressed.
</P>
<P>
   The baseplate is a nickel-plated casting with integral quadrant
and adjustable kerf indicator. The degree scale is precise and
there's a setscrew for the 90-degree position.
</P>
<P>
   MAKITA 5620DWA
</P>
<P>
   As the Bosch and DeWalt saws encourage comparison, so do the
Hitachi and Makita. Both are 18-volt, both just over 7 1/2 pounds
and both combine good power with cordfree user friendliness.
</P>
<P>
   Makita's businesslike entry features a heavy, 5/32-inch-thick
aluminum baseplate instead of the ribbed cast versions on most
other high-end tools. And in place of the integral bevel quadrant
on cast bases, Makita has a simple screwed-on steel quadrant. While
it lacks the glamour of a casting, this base may better handle
abuse, and the saw should be easier to repair. The base has scales
to help determine blade position on the work, and the kerf
indicator is a simple, fixed notch.
</P>
<P>
   This saw is well-balanced and smooth running. The
trigger-release button is very easy to reach and engage _ almost
too easy to be an effective safety device.
</P>
<P>
   PORTER-CABLE 9845
</P>
<P>
   The 9845 is the cordless version of Porter-Cable's popular Saw
Boss circular saw. It features a stamped-steel baseplate with
oversize levers that lock bevel angle and blade depth, cast blade
guards and a hinged dust port.
</P>
<P>
   P-C uses a unique 19.2-volt battery pack that slides into the
rear of the tool, much like the DeWalt design. Although the saw is
not that much longer than the DeWalt, it seems like it is. To
accommodate the pack, the handle is elongated toward the rear,
which makes the tool very nose heavy.
</P>
<P>
   The 9845 has a 6-inch blade, but still manages to saw 45-degree
bevels in 2-inch stock. In fact, it cuts deeper at 45 degrees than
the Makita and Hitachi 6 1/2-inch saws. The bevel quadrant features
setscrew stops for 90 degrees and 45 degrees, and the base has an
adjustable kerf indicator.
</P>
<P>
   RYOBI R10730K2
</P>
<P>
   The 18-volt Ryobi saw comes in a combination kit with a drill,
and is aimed at medium- to light-duty use. We found this left-blade
saw comfortable to handle , and the bevel and depth adjustments are
easy to make. It has a stamped-steel baseplate that adjusts to 50
degrees, with a setscrew stop at 90 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   While Ryobi usually combines performance with good price, we
found this saw on the light side for the tasks it seems intended to
handle. Crosscutting 2-by-4 lumber is an effort, and ripping 2-inch
stock was out of the question. In fact, we easily managed to
overheat the saw's motor.
</P>
<P>
   Although the tool has an arbor lock to facilitate blade
changing, it didn't work on our tool. And, the 5 1/2-inch blade
doesn't cut as deeply as the 5 3/8-inch blade on the Skil or B&AMP;D
tools.
</P>
<P>
   SKIL 289SK
</P>
<P>
   Like the Ryobi, the Skil saw is bundled with a drill for those
who want an entry-level cordless system. Like both B&AMP;D and Ryobi,
this tool won't handle 45-degree bevel cuts in 2-inch stock. It
features a small stamped-steel baseplate, fixed kerf indicator,
50-degree bevel capacity, and it comes with a rip guide. The Skil
has a dust-collection port, although it's covered with a plug that
looks easy to lose.
</P>
<P>
   We found this tool comfortable to use and easy to adjust, even
though the motor sounds considerably rougher than the other tools.
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
POPULAR MECHANICS news service and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article,
it must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
