<HEADLINE>
AUTO CLINIC Q&AMP;A 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: An illustration showing a car engine and a hair dryer is
available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.)
 By MIKE ALLEN 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIGHT SHOW
</P>
<P>
   Q: Every time it's drizzly and cold out, my car won't start _ at
least not until the sun comes out for a few hours and things dry
out. Really cold weather is fine, it's just rainy days and nights.
</P>
<P>
   I opened the hood to look at the engine and had my wife turn the
key. Arcs and sparks danced up and down the wires. Is my car
possessed by rain-hating aliens? Do I have to move to the desert?
</P>
<P>
   _ Henry Fishbine, Bangor, Maine
</P>
<P>
   A: The short-term solution is to use a hair dryer, and just dry
out the wires when this happens. Be sure you use a heavy-gauge
extension cord because your hair dryer uses a lot of current. Those
arcs you see in the dark are the high-voltage pulses intended to
fire the spark plugs running to ground down the lower-resistance
path created by the moisture along the wet outer insulation of the
wires.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term solution is to replace the wires with new ones.
This might be expensive _ new wires for some cars are over a
hundred bucks. Try removing the wires one at a time and cleaning
them with some mild detergent. Don't use any solvent-based
cleaners, as this might degrade the insulation on the wires. In
fact, detail the entire engine compartment to keep the area clean
and, consequently, drier.
</P>
<P>
   Tow-truck operators see this no-start condition a lot. Their
quick-start fix is to spray the wires with some petroleum-based
water-displacing penetrating lubricant. It gets the car started,
but it leaves a gummy, dirt-retaining film on the wires. If you are
forced to do this, be sure to clean up afterward.
</P>
<P>
   WIMPY WAGON
</P>
<P>
   Q. We bought a 1997 Ford Escort LX wagon, figuring it would be a
good second car. It has been running fine. But when I turn the
heater or air conditioner on, the engine really lags. There's a
noticeable drop in performance when the air-conditioning compressor
cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a common problem with Escorts? Are the electrical power
requirements of the heater and air-conditioning equipment too
demanding for its electrical system?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ernest Hardee, Newport, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not the electrical demand. It's the pure mechanical
input needed to spin the air-conditioning compressor and pressurize
the refrigerant. The horsepower needed for this represents a
substantial proportion of the excess power available from the
Escort's underpowered four-banger. And when you load it up with
several people and luggage, passing reserve is pretty much a joke.
</P>
<P>
   I drove a rental car in Colorado Springs a few years back that
didn't have enough power to pull third gear in the automatic
transmission on the freeway if the air conditioner was on. I had to
either shut off the air conditioning, or leave the transmission in
second to keep it from hunting back and forth between third and
second when I tried to use drive. The high altitude sapped enough
power to leave the engine totally maxed out just keeping up with
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   TIME TO DIAGNOSE ABS
</P>
<P>
   Q: My ABS and brake lights came on after pulling a trailer and
boat home. I took my time and did not overuse the brakes. Trying to
get the light to go off, I unhooked the battery for 30 minutes, but
the light was still on when I hooked it back up. I've changed the
front brake lines and the brake fluid is clear. The only code on
the truck was 12 after I hooked up the battery.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scott, via Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: I doubt that towing a trailer was responsible, unless, of
course, you towed this boat out of the water on a boat ramp and
water got into the ABS sender. If you're sure the system is bled
properly, and all the normal hydraulic and mechanical bits are up
to snuff, it's time to start diagnosing the ABS.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately that's difficult to do without access to the
computer-based diagnostic tool designed for this purpose. It could
be something as simple as a loose connector on one of the ABS
tone-wheel sensors or something as complicated (and expensive) as a
failed ABS hydraulic pump/controller. Get the appropriate manual
and start diagnosing, if you feel up to it. Judging by the tone of
your letter, you're already over your head. It's time to consult a
mechanic who works on Dodge ABS systems regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ALONE IN THE GARAGE
</P>
<P>
   A. Recently my 1996 Infiniti Q45 was left in a closed garage
with the motor running for five hours. When I discovered it, the
temperature gauge was reading normal. The engine oil had been
changed three weeks before. The car seems fine. But should I
perform any preventive maintenance or other diagnostics? Should I
worry about any future problems?
</P>
<P>
   _ Manny Gonzalez, via Internet
</P>
<P>
   It's fine. I normally don't recommend warming a car up for more
than the time it takes to set your seat position and rearview
mirrors and buckle your seatbelt. You should have no problems. I
wouldn't even bother to change the oil early.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that police cars are subject to extensive periods of
idling during their life spans, as well as ambulances and other
types of working vehicles. If the cooling system is up to the task,
the only real concern is premature camshaft wear. That shouldn't be
a problem with the overhead-cam valvetrain on your Q.
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
POPULAR MECHANICS news service and other features.
</P>
