<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH CARE IS ONE LINE IN THE SAND FOR GORE AND BUSH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JIM WRIGHT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The basic, irreconcilable difference between Vice President Al
Gore and Gov. George W. Bush, and between their respective parties,
comes into sharp focus when we consider the issues relating to
public health.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants to work toward universal health care insurance for
every citizen, starting first with the children. Bush, in response,
asks why President Clinton didn't compromise this matter out with
the Republican Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants to provide by law that the cost of prescription drugs
be covered under Medicare. Bush says he prefers a GOP resolution
that merely encourages HMOs and insurance companies to include
drugs in their health care packages.
</P>
<P>
   Gore unequivocally endorses the Patients Bill of Rights pending
before Congress. The bill, among other things, places
decision-making power on individual cases in the hands of attending
physicians, not insurance carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush refers vaguely to a substitute being considered by GOP
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore points to studies showing that more and more Americans have
no health coverage at all; that medical bills are going up much
faster than wages (with prescription drugs rising fastest of all);
and that Americans of modest income increasingly find
hospitalization unaffordable.
</P>
<P>
   Bush responds that Gore, by reciting these facts, is promoting
class warfare.
</P>
<P>
   So the general debate proceeds on issue after issue. A pattern
is forming. The vice president offers a specific proposal to abate
a specific problem. Bush retorts by attempting to discredit Gore
personally.
</P>
<P>
   On the need to reform campaign finance, Gore in June laid out
his plan to curb abuses. Bush, ignoring the substance of the plan,
demanded that Gore explain again why he attended a fund-raiser at a
Buddhist temple four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Again, in his acceptance speech, Gore declared that the first
bill he'll send to Congress will be to clean up campaign spending.
He also said he'd eagerly sign the bipartisan McCain-Feingold bill
to outlaw ``soft money'' if Congress will pass it.
</P>
<P>
   Without revealing whether he'd sign such a measure, Bush
reiterated simply that the vice president has ``no credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did opine once during the New Hampshire primary that any
Republican would be foolish to vote for McCain's bill. He said it
would amount to ``unilateral disarmament.''
</P>
<P>
   These widely differing attitudes in both substance and campaign
style come to a head on that range of issues affecting health care.
The public has an increasing stake in their outcome. Consider the
following:
</P>
<P>
   _ During the 1990s, the cost of drugs more than doubled. In the
last two years, prices for the 50 most prescribed drugs for older
Americans have shot upward four times faster than the rate of
inflation. Some of them have risen by 100 percent or more.
Clorazepate, a monopoly of Mylan Laboratories, rose by 3,200
percent!
</P>
<P>
   More and more, elderly citizens living on modest fixed incomes
face daily choices between buying prescribed medications or buying
food.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medical expenditures, the typical family's fastest-escalating
economic necessity, already cost Americans about $1 trillion
annually. They're predicted to double by 2007 and then to gobble up
16 percent of our entire gross national product. (That's more than
twice the share in any other advanced democracy.)
</P>
<P>
   _ The personal outlay required of average citizens has grown,
while corporations shuck off health care costs by outsourcing
contracts and downsizing their own employment rolls. The number of
firms offering health benefits to employees fell sharply in the
'90s. As result, more individual citizens are left without
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of uninsured Americans keeps growing. About 46
million have no health insurance today. An estimated one-fourth of
all adults between 18 and 64 go without needed treatment because
they can't afford it.
</P>
<P>
   Others who want and need insurance can't buy it because of their
medical histories. They're adrift. Need it, can't buy it, can't get
treatment without it.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to go more than a week without hearing of some new
outrage involving denial of physician-prescribed treatment to some
suffering patient by bottom-line-oriented health care providers on
strictly financial _ not medical _ grounds.
</P>
<P>
   This issue may be the real sleeper this year. It won't be solved
by tax cuts or by flailing at ``big government.'' Nor is it an
answer to silence debate by decrying ``class warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is real, and people want solutions.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
