<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN29-COX     08-28 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: New ways to view the English
countryside
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Friend of mine called from England last week to
tell me what a good time he and his wife were having.
</P>
<P>
   I have a theory about people calling from faraway places to tell
me what a good time they're having.
</P>
<P>
   The more they call, the more they're wishing they were back
home.
</P>
<P>
   My friend called twice in two days.
</P>
<P>
   First day he called, he was telling me how exciting it was to be
traveling the English countryside. Flowers were everywhere. The
villages were delightful. The quaint little inns were everything
you could wish for.
</P>
<P>
   Jolly good.
</P>
<P>
   For a fact, I have traveled somewhat in the English countryside.
I don't remember the flowers so much, but it was very exciting.
</P>
<P>
   It was very exciting to be driving on the wrong side of the road
on country roads about the width of a driveway back home.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why I didn't see the flowers. I was too occupied
seeing my impending death by car crash about to unfold before my
very eyes.
</P>
<P>
   As for the villages, they are nice enough. Never mind the
pungent odor of burning plastic. That's from their major industry _
American tourism. This time of year the credit card imprinting
machines are fairly smoking.
</P>
<P>
   I, too, have stayed at quaint little inns. The operative word is
``little'' _ room, bed, bathroom, food portions _ everything but
the rate.
</P>
<P>
   Groucho Marx said it well about a Hotel Hovel where he once
stayed:
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing thinner than the towels were the walls.''
</P>
<P>
   My friend, when he called that first time, was all aglow about
the Old English ambience of their inn, what he called a manor, on
the outskirts of the village. Later he and his wife planned to walk
into town to enjoy the evening.
</P>
<P>
   The manor staff, he said, had suggested they go across hill and
vale rather than along the road, for a real taste of the English
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   He called again the next day. It was much the same story.
Flowers were still everywhere, villages were still delightful,
quaint little inns were still everything you could wish for.
</P>
<P>
   Except... Well, he wished the manor staff hadn't directed them
to take the route into the village over hill and vale.
</P>
<P>
   It seems he got a real taste of the English countryside, indeed,
when he managed to trip and fall face first into an expansive area
of muddy English countryside.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time they finally reached the village, his appearance
being what it was _ and to the English, appearance being everything
_ weary and hungry though they were, no restaurant would allow him
entrance. His lovely wife, yes; the muddy American, no.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could any taxi driver be convinced to take them back to
their quaint little inn _ not for even double the fare, not if it
meant the muddy American defiling a public conveyance.
</P>
<P>
   Not so jolly. Not so good.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a pub owner took pity on them and, for a price that was
exceedingly more than a pittance, allowed them a serving fish and
chips at the bar and use of the toilet for my friend to tidy
himself up. Eventually, they were able to find a cab back to the
manor.
</P>
<P>
   And they're back home now. Fact is, they returned a day earlier
than planned. But when I asked my friend if he were glad to be
home, he just sighed.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, England, he said. How he wished they were still in England.
The flowers, the villages, the inns ...
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, England, I said. Let us toast England. The flowers, the
villages, the inns ...
</P>
<P>
   Here's mud in your eye.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; Website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
