 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, the weird twists and turns life in Hollywood can take. Once
upon a time, Bob Saget was a moderately successful white-bread
stand-up comedian. He became better known as the Olsen twins'
on-screen dad in the saccharine kiddie sitcom ``Full House,'' then
scored again as the host of ``America's Funniest Home Videos.'' Now
he turns up tonight as the director of ``Becoming Dick,'' a comedy
about the terrible things you have to do to make it in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, debuting at 9 on cable's E!, stars Harland Williams
as Richard, an unemployed actor whose best friend (Saget again, in
a small role) tells him he's just too nice a guy to succeed in the
industry. Richard wakes up four years later, a major star and a
major creep, and tries to figure out what happened to him. The
supporting cast includes Robert Wagner as his butler (Talk about
twists and turns!) and Elizabeth Berkley as his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   If it's backstage savagery you want, of course, just flip on
``E! True Hollywood Story.'' But you can't blame Saget if he wants
us to know that he does, in fact, have an adult thought in his
head. He's suffered so much, the least we can do is watch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Open Tennis, 7:30 on USA: There's also a wrap-up show at
12:35 a.m. on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: Allegations have surfaced over the
last couple of weeks that this repellent ``reality'' show is even
more manipulative than we've suspected. (Check out the online
magazine Salon.com for details.) One more reason not to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends,'' NBC at 8: It's the one with Bruce Willis as the
father of the student Ross is dating. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``WWF Smackdown!'' UPN at 8: Regis Philbin hosts. (Kidding! Just
checking to see if you're paying attention!)
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC at 9: Regis Philbin
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave,'' CBS at 8:30: Popular 1993 comedy about an everyday Joe
who's drafted to impersonate the president, who's had a stroke
while committing a Clintonian indiscretion. Kevin Kline stars.
There are nice turns by Sigourney Weaver (as the first lady) and
Kevin Dunn, but the best is Bonnie Hunt in a now legendary bit as a
goofy White House tour guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' NBC at 8:30: Two reruns air back-to-back. In
the second, Sydney Pollack, the director (``Tootsie'') and actor
(``Eyes Wide Shut''), guests as Will's father, who isn't as
comfortable with Will's gayness as he seems to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali: An American Hero,'' Fox at 8: Lively biopic covers Ali's
struggles with the American government as well as with Joe Frazier
and George Foreman. David Ramsey stars, and the excellent
supporting cast includes Joe Morton as Malcolm X, plus Clarence
Williams III and Vondie Curtis Hall. Premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopkins 24/7,'' ABC at 10: You could watch an ``ER'' rerun, or
you could check out some real emergency-room drama with the second
episode of this six-part ABC documentary series.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My Date with the President's Daughter,'' Disney Channel at 7:
Will Friedle of ``Boy Meets World'' lives the title adventure.
Grown-ups can enjoy watching Dabney Coleman and Jay Thomas in
supporting roles. And when it's over, watch ``Dave'' without the
kids for another perspective on White House romance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ming's Quest,'' Food Network at 10: The Boston-based ``East
Meets West'' chef hits the road for culinary adventure. Tonight he
joins a lobstering expedition out of ``The Perfect Storm'' port of
Gloucester, Mass. Premiere.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Stein hour, Comedy Central at 10: An episode of ``Win Ben
Stein's Money,'' followed by the idiosyncratic talk show ``Turn Ben
Stein On.'' Tonight's guest on the latter is Todd MacFarlane
(``Spawn'').
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: S'marvelous:
Tony Bennett and Diana Krall perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Mel Gibson and
Blue Man Group. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05: At
Maricopa County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 1:05 a.m.: Jason
Biggs and Everclear. Rerun. (Note time after tennis update.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Britney Spears
and Kyle McLachlan of ``Twin Peaks.'' Write your own joke. Rerun. &QL;
</P>
