$ADV01 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release: Friday, Sept. 1, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the start of a holiday weekend, the end of summer, too, and
the television outlook is dismal. So we might as well go all the
way and answer the question, what's the worst we can watch?
</P>
<P>
   Made-for-cable movies are always likely candidates. ``Best
Actress,'' a TV movie debuting at 9 on E!, has potential. It's the
sudsy story of behind-the-scenes Oscar machinations, and the cast
includes Thomas Calabro, Rachel Hunter and Gary Busey, plus Anthony
Stewart Head _ better known as the guy in the Taster's Choice
commercials, and more recently, that English guy on ``Buffy.''
Sounds grim. ``The Darkling,'' on Sci Fi at 9, also seems
promising. F. Murray Abraham _ remember him? _ plays a guy who
makes a pact with a demon and _ duh! _ lives to regret it.
</P>
<P>
   UPN is often a good place to look for bad TV. On ``The Strip,''
at 8, Vegas gumshoes Elvis and Jesse probe an arrogant magician's
death. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   On pay-per-view tonight, ``Deuce Bigalow, Male Gigolo'' is all
over the schedule. And Will Smith's ``Wild, Wild West'' disaster is
on HBO at 8.
</P>
<P>
   For news fans, there's ``Is America No. 1?'' with John Stossel
on ABC at 10. Stossel's tilting against the windmills of political
correctness once seemed endearing, but now his ego alone makes this
a candidate for the night's worst show. The recent brouhaha in
which some test results were misrepresented in one of his segments
adds flavor. And if that's not enough, it's a rerun.
</P>
<P>
   But once again, as on most nights, the winner of tonight's
worst-show award is ... ``Big Brother,'' on CBS at 8. If this is
reality, give me UPN anytime.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Providence,'' NBC at 8: One of those wacky episodes that
long-running series occasionally indulge in to break the monotony.
Tonight, a migraine puts Syd (Melina Kanakaredes) in Alice's
Wonderland. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Blues,'' WB at 8: Back-to-back reruns of the animated
comedy based on the popular comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making the Band,'' ABC at 8:30: The boys hit Cancun for some R
and R. Think they'll meet some girls in bikinis? (Last week's
episode is rerun at 8.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit,'' NBC at 10: One complaint
about this show has been that there's not enough of Detective
Munch, the mordant cynic that actor Richard Belzer transferred over
from ``Homicide'' when that series was canceled. Tonight, Munch
steps to the fore, befriending a TV reporter (Jennifer Esposito)
who was assaulted. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``U-Pick,'' Nickelodeon at 8: An hour of viewer-chosen segments
includes bits from ``Real Monsters,'' ``SpongeBob'' and
``Rugrats,'' some more entertaining than most of what passes for
adult TV tonight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. Open Tennis,'' USA at 7:30: There's also a wrap-up on CBS
at 12:35.
</P>
<P>
   ''1999 Video Music Awards,'' MTV at 8: Warm up for next
Thursday's 2000 festivities with this rerun of last year's Chris
Rock-hosted ceremony. Performers include Ricky Martin and Kid Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``VH1 Confidential,'' VH1 at 8: Why is age 27 so dangerous for
rock stars?
</P>
<P>
   ``Varsity Blues,'' Showtime at 8: James Van Der Beek and Jon
Voight star in a 1999 high school football drama that's better than
it sounds. Voight is the martinet coach who needs an irreverent
replacement player (Van Der Beek) to lead the team to victory.
Rated R.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: D.L. Hughley
of ``The Original Kings of Comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Tom Cruise, Tracey
Ullman and band Stone Temple Pilots. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05: More
from inside Maricopa County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 1:05 a.m.: Shawn
and Marlon Wayans. Rerun. (Note time after tennis update.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Nathan Lane and
musical guest Loudon Wainwright III. Rerun. &QL;
</P>
