<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: The articles described below moved MONDAY,
AUGUST 28, 2000, in the 'l' news file. The material was filed by
The New York Times Syndicate for use by LIFEBEAT clients.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement
with the Syndicate. For purchase information, see end of text. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDENS THAT HARNESS NATURE'S HEALING POWERS
</P>
<P>
   HEALING-GARDENS-LIFEBEAT _ It was a sunny day in the garden at
the Pleasant Bay Nursing and Rehabilitation Center in Brewster,
Mass. Bill Ellis, a former manufacturing executive from Wisconsin,
found out he had Parkinson's disease six years ago, and has been a
resident of the center for more than a year. His wife, Pam, visits
daily, along with their dog, Kaleigh. The garden, they have found,
is a cheerful place to congregate. Just off the dining room, it is
nestled in the northwest corner of the X-shaped complex. The
triangular space measures about 5,000 square feet, with views of
pines and sky to the west. By Anne Raver. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos of the residents and garden at Pleasant Bay
Nursing and Rehabilitation Center are available on Newscom or by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IS YOUR CHILD HEADED FOR AN EATING DISORDER?
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-EATING-DISORDER-LIFEBEAT _ Jack is a vegetarian. ``I don't
want to kill animals to eat,'' he told his parents one night. Soon,
however, his ban on red meat was extended to chicken, fish and
anything with the smallest amount of fat. Caitlin, star of the
school play, goes to the girls' bathroom two or three times a week,
puts two fingers down her throat and throws up before going on
stage to rehearse. Youngsters today are more concerned than ever
about their body images. Many are developing unhealthy eating
habits that can become full-blown disorders with potentially
life-threatening consequences. By Margery D. Rosen. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   THE TOP FIVE SUPERMARKET TRAPS
</P>
<P>
   SUPERMARKET-TRAPS-LIFEBEAT _ My kids and I stopped at the
supermarket to pick up a loaf of bread, 100 percent fruit juice and
a few other staples. We raced around the store and sped through the
express lane. But when I unpacked the groceries I realized that I
didn't buy whole wheat bread or the 100 percent fruit juice. I
picked up a brown loaf made with white flour and a beverage that
was 100 percent natural, but only 10 percent juice. So you (or I)
don't fall into these traps again, children's nutrition experts
went shopping to find the five most common types of products
masquerading as health foods, and tell you how to spot a phony. By
Mindy Hermann. 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   PIPER PERABO: LUCKY STAR
</P>
<P>
   PIPER-PERABO-LIFEBEAT _ Piper Perabo had to beat out a lot of
other actresses to get ugly _ ``Coyote Ugly.'' The 23-year-old
virtual unknown nabbed the lead in the Jerry Bruckheimer produced
film, a project that has been widely anticipated as the
career-making vehicle for aspiring Hollywood starlets. By Ted Loos.
500 words. (North American Rights Only)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos of Piper Perabo are available on Newscom or by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) &QL;
