<HEADLINE>
FIVE TOP 'HEALTHY FOOD' SHOPPING TRAPS AT THE SUPERMARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.  
 NOTE: The name Keith-Thomas is CQ. The word percent in parentheses
has been used in place of the symbol, which may not transmit
properly to many newspapers. 
 By MINDY HERMANN   
 c.2000 Child magazine   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few months ago, my kids and I stopped at the supermarket
before soccer practice to pick up a loaf of bread, 100 percent
fruit juice and a few other staples. We raced around the store,
sped through the express lane and made it to practice with a minute
to spare. I was proud of my speediness until I unpacked the
groceries and realized that I didn't buy whole wheat bread or the
100 percent fruit juice. I picked up a brown loaf made with white
flour and a beverage that was 100 percent natural, but only 10
percent juice.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure you've made some similar mistakes. Who could blame you?
With the typical grocery store stocking 50,000 items, twice as many
as a decade ago, it's impossible to read every label, let alone
wade through an entire ingredients list. So we often rely on visual
shortcuts to size up nutritional value _ pictures of fruits and
vegetables on the package must mean it's healthy; grainy-looking
brown bread must be whole wheat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturers know you're in a rush at the supermarket and
some do whatever they can to make their products seem more
nutritious than they really are,'' points out Bridget Swinney,
R.D., of El Paso, Texas, author of ``Healthy Food for Healthy
Kids.''
</P>
<P>
   So you (or I) don't fall into these traps again, Swinney and
other children's nutrition experts went shopping to find the five
most common types of products masquerading as health foods, and
tell you how to spot a phony.
</P>
<P>
   MULTIGRAIN BREADS: A FAKE TAN
</P>
<P>
   The disguise: Manufacturers may add caramel coloring or molasses
to bread made with mostly white flour so it will appear darker and
more nutritious, says Sandy Nissenberg, R.D., a Buffalo Grove,
Ill.-based author of children's cookbooks. Then they give the bread
a healthy-sounding name, like ''12-grain,'' ``multigrain'' or even
``whole grain.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, breads made with mostly white flour aren't bad, but
they contain about half the fiber, magnesium, zinc, vitamin E and
potassium, as well as far fewer phytochemicals (healthy plant
compounds) as loaves made with only whole grain flour. That's why
the USDA recommends that half your child's daily six to 11 grain
servings _ a slice of bread, an ounce of cereal or a half-cup of
rice or pasta counts as one _ be whole grains.
</P>
<P>
   Spot a phony: See if enriched wheat flour or enriched flour is
the first ingredient. Those are fancy names for white flour _ the
same kind of flour used in white bread, explains Nissenberg.
</P>
<P>
   To find a whole grain loaf, check for the word ``whole'' in the
name of the first ingredient. Or skip the ingredients list and buy
a brand with the words ``whole wheat'' in its name. The U.S. Food
and Drug Administration requires that the only flour in ``whole
wheat'' breads (unlike ``multigrain'' or even ``whole grain''
breads) be whole grain.
</P>
<P>
   Quick picks: Stroehmann 100(percent) Whole Wheat, Pepperidge
Farm Natural Whole Grain, Wonder Stoneground 100(percent) Whole
Wheat, Freihofer's Stone Ground 100(percent) Whole Wheat, Sahara
100(percent) Whole Wheat Pita.
</P>
<P>
   SKIM-MILK PUDDINGS: OIL SLICK
</P>
<P>
   The disguise: Manufacturers plaster the phrase ``made with
wholesome skim milk'' or ``made with nonfat milk'' on the label.
You think the pudding is made entirely with skim milk, but, for
creaminess, manufacturers have added several grams of partially
hydrogenated vegetable oil, points out Dr. Keith-Thomas Ayoob, an
associate professor of pediatrics at Albert Einstein College of
Medicine in New York City. Not only do these puddings end up with
four grams of fat _ the same as those made from whole milk _ but
the type is trans fat, which Ayoob says is as risky for heart
health as saturated fat.
</P>
<P>
   Spot a phony: Look for the phrase ``partially hydrogenated oil''
in the list of ingredients. That's a sure sign that the product
contains trans fat, explains Ayoob. (The FDA is considering a
proposal that would require the amount of trans fat to be listed on
the label.) Choose a brand that is ``fat free'' or is made with
skim milk and canola oil, which is heart-healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Quick picks: Fat-Free Jell-O, Swiss Miss Fat Free, Handi-Snacks
Fat Free.
</P>
<P>
   POULTRY HOT DOGS: PLUMPED WITH EXTRA FAT
</P>
<P>
   The disguise: You may presume that poultry hot dogs are made
with low-fat white-meat turkey or chicken. Truth is, many
manufacturers throw in the skin and dark meat for extra moistness.
As a result, most poultry franks give you a paltry fat savings when
compared with their beef counterparts. Furthermore, some brands may
have exactly the same amount of fat as beef franks _ up to a
whopping 13 grams!
</P>
<P>
   Spot a phony: Zero in on the frank's fat content. If each frank
has more than four grams, it's probably made with dark meat and/or
skin. Choose the lower-fat versions instead.
</P>
<P>
   Quick picks: Oscar Mayer Fat-Free, Ball Park Fat Free, Dietz &AMP;
Watson Gourmet Lite, Butterball Fat Free.
</P>
<P>
   100 PERCENT NATURAL JUICE BOXES: WHERE'S THE JUICE?
</P>
<P>
   The disguise: Manufacturers often highlight the phrase
''100(percent) Natural'' on the package and show pictures of fruits
or vegetables. You think you're buying 100 percent juice, but that
claim, and the photos, have nothing to do with the amount of juice
in the product. It simply means the product is free of artificial
additives or preservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these products contain only 10 percent or 25 percent
juice,'' says Swinney. ``Since kids like 100 percent juice as much
as they do 10 percent juice, why not buy the product that's
healthier for them?''
</P>
<P>
   Spot a phony: Check the side panel to see the percentage of
juice the product packs. Buy a brand that's 100 percent natural
(also called all-natural) and 100 percent juice.
</P>
<P>
   Quick picks: Minute Maid Apple, Orange, Grape or Cherry juice
boxes with calcium; any flavor of Juicy Juice, Mott's, Sesame
Street or Apple &AMP; Eve.
</P>
<P>
   PASTA AND RICE SIDE DISHES: SHRINKING VEGGIES
</P>
<P>
   The disguise: Call it photographic license. The meal shown on
the package is chock-full of veggies. ``Unfortunately, when you
cook the side dish at home, you realize there are hardly any
vegetables at all. In fact, some brands have as little as a quarter
of a teaspoon of vegetables per serving,'' says Ayoob.
</P>
<P>
   Spot a phony: Check the Nutrition Facts label on the package. If
the product doesn't contain at least 20 percent of the Daily Value
of vitamins A or C per serving, it's probably skimpy on veggies,
since these are the nutrients that are abundant in most produce.
</P>
<P>
   Quick picks: Bird's Eye Italian Style Vegetables &AMP; Bow-tie
Pasta, Cascadian Farm Mediterranean Pasta Salad, Green Giant
Broccoli &AMP; Cheese Flavored Sauce (add to pasta or rice).
</P>
<P>
   (Mindy Hermann is a registered dietitian.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
