u l BC-PIPER-PERABO-LIFEBEAT     08-28 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPER-PERABO-LIFEBEAT-500-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPER PERABO: LUCKY STAR
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text. 
 ART ADV: Photos of Piper Perabo are available on Newscom or by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355. 
 North American Rights Only 
 By TED LOOS 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Piper Perabo had to beat out a lot of other actresses to get
ugly _ ``Coyote Ugly.'' The 23-year-old virtual unknown nabbed the
lead in the Jerry Bruckheimer produced film, a project that has
been widely anticipated as the career-making vehicle for aspiring
Hollywood starlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is about a girl from New Jersey who moves to New
York to pursue her dreams in the big city,'' explains Perabo, a
Toms River, N.J., native who now lives in Manhattan. ``Right away I
thought, this is me.''
</P>
<P>
   Having announced their intention to cast only newcomers in the
main parts, the filmmakers auditioned literally hundreds of
actresses. Perabo says that at her first audition she simply told
first-time director David McNally that it was kind of ``scary'' how
similar her life was to the character's, which she thinks helped
win him over. ``I should start all my auditions that way,'' she
jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The plot, which sounds a lot like ``Cocktail'' meets
``Flashdance,'' follows an aspiring singer-songwriter named Violet
who leaves home but can't land a job. She gets work pouring shots
and strutting her stuff at Coyote Ugly, a rowdy bar with a tough
owner (Maria Bello) and even tougher fellow bartenders (Tyra Banks,
Izabella Miko and Bridget Moynahan). ``Her biggest fear is stage
fright,'' says Perabo of Violet, who literally has to sing for her
supper in the film. ``And at Coyote Ugly, the deal is that the
waitresses get up on the bar and hoof it. She shows up on the first
night, and it's her worst nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Stage fright has not exactly been a problem for Perabo, who
talks so fast and with such enthusiasm that her words seem to blend
together. She graduated from Ohio University in 1998 with a theater
degree and was promptly cast in the indie film ``Whiteboys,''
playing the girlfriend of a white guy from Iowa (Danny Hoch) who
wants to be a gangsta rapper. Perabo, who came across as a more
free-spirited Natalie Portman, played her exasperation with
effortless charm.
</P>
<P>
   She was shooting a role as FBI agent Karen Sympathy in the
current ``Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'' when her agent sent
her the ``Coyote'' script. She auditioned first for McNally, and
then for Bruckheimer. ``It was real,'' says Bruckheimer of Perabo's
reading. ``What you look for in an actor or an actress is honesty,
and she's got it.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Perabo actually failed Waitressing 101 when working in
a New York City bar not too long ago. ``I'd always sit down and
talk to people,'' she says now. ``I would end up chatting in a
booth, with my 10 other tables going, 'Hel-lo?''' No bar dancing
was required.
</P>
<P>
   As for her unusual handle, chalk it up to her family's literary
bent. ``My dad is a poetry teacher, so I think he just thought it
was a good alliteration,'' she says of her first name (the last is
Portuguese). ``My parents chose it from a long list of hippie
names.'' Indeed, she was almost India Star Perabo. She adds with a
laugh, ``I'm really happy with Piper.''
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
