<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4269 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-SKIN-COLOR-HNS &LR;      08-28 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIN-COLOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RESEARCHERS OFFER NEW EVIDENCE LINKING SUN TO SKIN COLOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Scientists studying why human skin comes in such
a diverse palette of colors have found a ``strong correlation''
between the skin color of indigenous peoples in different parts of
Earth and the amount of ultraviolet (UV) light falling on each
region.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, Nina Jablonski and George Chaplin of the
California Academy of Sciences, lends powerful support to the
belief that over evolutionary time, bodies change their skin colors
to adjust to different levels of UV light. Light skin absorbs lots
of UV, while dark skin absorbs less.
</P>
<P>
   UV light, which affects the skin's production of important
biochemicals, is both good and bad: Exposure to too little UV means
the skin doesn't generate enough of these chemicals, some of which
enhance one's chances of successful reproduction, while too much UV
risks destroying those same chemicals or triggering skin cancers.
</P>
<P>
   The research shows that evolution modifies skin colors to adjust
to the regional intensity of UV light. This helps the body strike a
reproductively healthy balance between the extremes of too much UV
and too little UV.
</P>
<P>
   Measurements by the Total Ozone Spectrometer satellite run by
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration support Jablonski
and Chaplin's thesis. As humans have migrated around the globe,
evolution has altered their skin color with extraordinary subtlety
to match local levels of solar UV, technically known as UV
``flux.'' Solar UV varies from place to place because of latitude,
humidity, cloudiness and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   Evolution adjusts skin color to regional UV levels to boost the
chances of reproductive success, according to Jablonski, an
anthropologist, and Chaplin, a geographic information systems
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   UV affects the likelihood of reproduction by influencing bodily
production of two bio-molecules vital for healthy offspring: folate
and vitamin D-3. The findings are reported in the July issue of the
Journal of Human Evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Folate, considered part of the B vitamin complex, occurs
naturally in many foods, and is found in highest concentrations in
green, leafy vegetables, beans and grain. It is essential for
proper development of the nervous system in fetuses and for sperm
production in adult males.
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin D-3 helps build and maintain strong bones and an alert
immune system, particularly in fast-growing human embryos.
</P>
<P>
   The hypothesis may also explain why human females tend to be
slightly lighter skinned than males. Light skin admits more solar
ultraviolet light, enhancing female production of vitamin D-3
needed to support fetal growth during pregnancy, and to nourish a
newborn via breast feeding.
</P>
<P>
   C. Loring Brace, a biological anthropologist at the University
of Michigan, said the paper written by Jablonski and Chaplin is
``an excellent piece of work . . . a marvelous survey.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Brace has technical reservations about certain aspects
of the paper, all in all ``I don't think you're going to find a
skeptic.''
</P>
<P>
   Jablonski, 46, received her doctorate at the University of
Washington in 1981. Chaplin, 46, is her husband and a specialist in
geographic information systems (GIS), which are computer systems
for the analysis and visualization of geographic data.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, scientists have debated the cause of differences
in human skin color. They have long known that skin lightness and
darkness vary with skin levels of melanin, a large organic
molecule. The more melanin in your skin, the darker it is.
</P>
<P>
   The melanin levels in a newborn's skin are genetic: For example,
dark-skinned people are more likely to give birth to dark-skinned
children.
</P>
<P>
   But why do melanin levels vary so dramatically from one human
population group to another?
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time,'' Jablonski said in a telephone interview,
``scientists have thought that skin color varies from place to
place to balance out the advantages and disadvantages of local
variations in solar UV light. On the one hand, UV stimulates the
production of vitamin D in the skin; on the other hand, too much UV
can cause skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this explanation was considered weak by some scientists
because skin cancer has little or no effect on people's ability to
reproduce, which is really the bottom line of every evolutionary
spreadsheet.''
</P>
<P>
   The research provided what Jablonski called strong evidence for
the old thesis about UV light and skin color. They have done so by
showing exactly how UV modifies skin color over time via evolution
and human reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   They say their research refutes the old notion that skin color
differences can be used to understand evolutionary relationships
among human populations living in different places on Earth. This
notion, Jablonski noted, endures in popular folklore _ especially
racist mythology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all the same under the skin,'' Jablonski said. ``What we
think of as racial categories or racial groupings are actually
highly variable constellations of physical and physiological
characteristics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
