<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4270 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-FOSSIL-AUCTION-HNS &LR;      08-28 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSSIL-AUCTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUYER OF DINOSAUR FOSSIL TO GIVE ITEM TO MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Also filed in ``a'' category)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DEMIAN BULWA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A retired businessman who spent $167,500 to buy
a 200-million-year-old flying reptile fossil has thrilled
paleontologists with his pledge to give the significant find back
to a New York museum.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Spight said he decided to buy the fossil after reading
about it in the newspaper and then discussing it with
paleontologists at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important that science has access to these kinds of
things,'' he said. ``I couldn't stand the thought of it going into
a private collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Paleontologists who have railed against the sale for profit of
scientific artifacts were delighted that the sale of the fossil
Sunday night was hardly a blockbuster. Instead, it brought in the
minimum bid required to keep Butterfields auction house from
pulling it back off the block.
</P>
<P>
   Resembling a large dragonfly and preserved on a shale slab,
Icarosaurus siefkeri has a storied and controversial 40-year
history. It once convinced scientists that vertebrates glided
through the air millions of years earlier than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the fossil has given flight to a debate about whether
scientific artifacts should be sold on the open market _ a debate
that has escalated with the growth of Internet-based auctions.
</P>
<P>
   The fossil was discovered in 1960 by three teen-agers in North
Bergen, N.J. One of them claimed ownership and 10 years ago removed
it from the American Museum of Natural History in New York, saying
he needed to sell it to pay his medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfields, which is owned by the eBay Internet site and has
locations in Los Angeles and San Francisco, offered hundreds of
natural-history relics for sale during Sunday night's auction. The
house also auctioned a grab handle from the Apollo 11 module that
landed on the moon in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sale is being probed by the National Aeronauts and
Space Administration, a 41-year-old retired computer industry
executive from Monterey Bay, Calif., who declined to give his name,
spent $34,500 on the piece and said it was ``just a really cool
thing'' that he wanted all his friends to touch.
</P>
<P>
   The highest drama of the night occurred courtesy of Spight.
Spight in 1996 sold Diablo Communications, an antenna tower
company, to the larger American Tower Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Auction officials said Spight was one of at least three bidders
interested in the late Triassic-period fossil, and one of at least
two who planned to donate it to a museum. They declined to identify
the others.
</P>
<P>
   Spight successfully bid $150,000 for the fossil. He also must
pay a $17,500 buyer's premium.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted at his New Jersey home Sunday evening, the seller of
the fossil, Alfred Siefker, 56, was shocked to hear the price,
which he said was the minimum allowed. It was listed at $250,000 to
$350,000 in the auction guide, and Siefker years ago had hoped it
would fetch up to $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my god, I can't believe that,'' Siefker said. ``I had a
stroke 10 years ago, I'm in pain 24 hours a day. That was my lease
on life _ I don't know what I'm going to do now.''
</P>
<P>
   Siefker, who had been criticized by some paleontologists for
trying to profit from the artifact, said he was glad to learn that
the buyer planned to donate it to a museum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
