<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4284 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-STEVIERAY-LEGACY-TEX     08-28 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEVIERAY-LEGACY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEN YEARS LATER, NO ONE HOLDS A CANDLE TO STEVIE RAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first hint there might be something wrong was on early
morning wire service reports that greeted us as we arrived at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helicopter didn't arrive ... possibly carrying a musician ...
took off from Wisconsin bound for Chicago ... several helicopters
left the site after the show, which featured Eric Clapton and Texan
Stevie Ray Vaughan...'' and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the rumor was that Clapton and Vaughan were on the
missing helicopter, a prospect that brought a co-worker to tears.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the hope was that the missing helicopter had set
down in a field after having mechanical problems. Or maybe it made
an emergency landing at some small airport between Alpine Valley,
Wis., (where Vaughan and Clapton had performed with Buddy Guy and
Jimmie Vaughan).
</P>
<P>
   But soon, our worst fears on Aug. 27, 1990, were realized.
Stevie Ray Vaughan, one of the greatest bluesmen ever, was dead at
35, his helicopter having crashed just minutes after takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram newsroom was as close to silent as
a newsroom gets at midday. There were tears, there was disbelief
and there was, for me, numbness. I had been too young to fully feel
the impact of the deaths of Robert Kennedy and Martin Luther King
Jr., so the closest I had come to feeling a loss was the death of
John Lennon a decade earlier.
</P>
<P>
   When there is tragedy in my life, I don't get weepy. I get
angry. And I remember thinking something along the lines of, when I
get up to heaven, the first thing I'm going to do is ask why this
was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan was a stunningly intense, brilliant guitarist; when I
saw him performing in bars in the early '80s, just before he hit it
big, there would be times when he would be playing so well that
everyone (the dancers, the waitresses, the guys talking at the bar)
would simply stop and stare, sometimes with a bottle of beer
hoisted halfway to their mouths.
</P>
<P>
   He was beyond the boundaries of technique, of absorbing the
licks and sounds of his heroes, such as Albert King. In Texas, a
place with dozens of worthy guitar-slingers, he stood out like a
beacon of light on a lonely country road. He just had that
undefinable ``thing'' that says, pay attention, because you won't
be seeing the likes of me again.
</P>
<P>
   And, 10 years later, we haven't. With old heroes dying off,
mediocre songwriting everywhere and a sack of obvious Stevie Ray
clones who think volume and a long guitar solo equal being a bona
fide bluesman (it doesn't now, it never did, and it never will,
thanks), the blues are at their lowest artistic ebb ever.
</P>
<P>
   Stevie Ray would have earned his place in the blues pantheon if
all he'd done was make memorable records and astound people in
concert. But that was only part of his legacy: After years of
substance-abuse problems, he cleaned up and returned with 1989's
``In Step.'' This was his finest hour, a collection of songs with
fierce playing and a palpable sense of renewal and progression.
</P>
<P>
   He had turned the cliche of the drunk/stoned/troubled bluesman
on its head and showed us that inspiration does not come from a
bottle or a vial.
</P>
<P>
   Little more than a year later, he was gone. We missed him
horribly then, but we miss him worse, perhaps, now _ because of his
warmth of spirit, because of his mix of passion and technique,
because he transcended the musical and social cliches of the blues.
And, finally, because those qualities seem to be in shorter supply
these days.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the best way to honor Vaughan's memory is to make a
point of not sounding like him. Don't copy the licks. Don't buy the
Fender Stratocaster and try to get his tone. And, for heaven's
sake, don't wear the hats.
</P>
<P>
   Learn from him, but learn more about yourself and what you want
to express and how you want to express it. Find out who you are and
put your own spin on his music, and the music of Muddy Waters and
Jimi Hendrix and B.B. King and whoever else you love.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Stevie Ray Vaughan did it, and that's why so many
people are marking the decade he's been gone.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
