   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-BAGELS (Dublin) _ What does cosmopolitan Dublin need? A
bagel shop run by two Gentile sisters with an exclusive contract
with N.Y. bagelmeisters H&AMP;H. By Kevin Cullen. 950 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-JOURNAL (Ramenskoye, Russia) -- It has been ``black
August'' for many Russians, but for others it has been the rock 'n
roll summer of love amid non-stop rock festivals. By David filipov.
750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-HMOS (Washington) _ Gore campaign aides say there is no
real disagreement between Al Gore and Joe Lieberman on the health
insurance and pharmaceutical companies, at least not any longer. By
Michael Kranish. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MALE-PILL (Undated) _ If the female birth control bill helped
launch the sexual revolution, an effective male contraceptive could
change the burden of contraceptive responsibility inside intimate
relationships. But would men use a male hormonal contraceptive --
and would women trust them to? By Scot Lehigh. 1750 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTE-INNOCENCE (Undated) _ By raising the specter that
innocent men or women have been condemned to die _ rather than the
more traditional argument that capital punishment is immoral _ the
``innocence movement'' has caught supporters of the death penalty
by surprise. By John A. Farrell. 1900 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   INNOCENCE-MOVEMENT (Undated) _ The origins of the modern
innocence movement can be traced to Massachusetts, and to a woman
named Sara Ehrmann. By John A. Farrell. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   KILLING-SPREE (Waterbury, Conn.) _ Mark Cote didn't seen like a
guy who would erupt into violence, but he did, killing a neighbor,
his ex-wife's lover and the mother of his former girlfriend before
turning the gun on himself. By Marcella Bombardieri. 1140 words.
</P>
<P>
   STRANGE-WILL (Undated) _ Shortly after her elderly mother's
death _ and just before she took her own life _ a 57-year-old
Oklahoma woman rewrote her will leaving her estate, estimated in
excess of $500,000, to the Amirault family and the American
relatives of Elian Gonzalez. By Scott s. Greenberger. 840 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCNAMARA-COLUMN (Undated) _ You don't have to be a
computer-phobic Luddite to have some doubts about a university
without classrooms and a faculty without faces. By Eileen McNamara.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-REUNION (Seoul) _ What was it about the reunion of
families from North and South Korea that caused a journalist's
tough exterior to crack. By Indira A. R. Lakshmanan. 1020 words.
</P>
