<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4323 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-RAIDERS-SEASON-HN     08-28 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-SEASON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RAIDERS HAVE A LONG WAY TO GO BEFORE BEING NO. 1 IN AFC WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANK BLACKMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Sports Illustrated predicts the Oakland
Raiders will finish the regular season in first place in the AFC
West. This is either another example of superb investigative
reporting by the magazine that was the first to bring you nearly
naked babes on the beach or a wild guess no more reliable than
something divined by Madame Magda, who earns her living reading tea
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Napoleon Kaufman plays football for the Raiders, which should
make him a better source than either SI or Madame Magda. He says he
doesn't know how good his team will be this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see so many ups and downs,'' the running back said of the
team's preseason performance. ``So many glimpses of greatness. . .
. And then the next week, you come out and you don't do quite as
well. So the best thing is just to wait until the season starts.
Get rolling into the season a bit. That's when you find out what
the team is going to be about.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with predictions is that they are often based on how
a team does in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, wise to ignore this so-called evidence,
remembering instead that they are exhibitions. That's why regulars
play sparingly or not at all if they are troubled by as much as a
hang nail, and the suckers who paid regular-season prices instead
see guys from Sewanee Tech wage spirited battles for roster spots
that will earn them the right to be mangled on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   So the Raiders concluded the 2000 preseason with a 20-0
destruction of Seattle Thursday evening at the Coliseum and won
three of their four games.
</P>
<P>
   Just a reminder for those who are now contemplating wagering the
next year's house payments on the Raiders to go all the way: The
games didn't count. Mike Holmgren's Seahawks are not likely to be
embarrassed again Oct. 22 at the Coliseum, when the game counts.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Raiders know they will be as ready as they possibly
can for the start of the real games. They emerged from the
preseason for the most part in excellent health. The players who
line up against the San Diego Chargers Sunday afternoon at the
Coliseum will be the ones coach Jon Gruden wanted to have out
there.
</P>
<P>
   The only consequential player to be seriously hurt in the
preseason was reserve wide receiver Terry Mickens, who suffered a
season-ending spinal injury in the game against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Management wasted no time bringing in Andre Rison, who'd been
cut by Kansas City. Perhaps because Oakland's general managing
partner, Al Davis, has spent the last few decades profitably suing
the rest of the NFL, the Chiefs did not provide the Raiders with a
heads-up that Rison was facing new legal problems, which surfaced
on Friday when the player was indicted for bouncing checks worth
$158,000.
</P>
<P>
   While Raiders management says it is investigating this new
difficulty confronting an athlete already facing trial for
allegedly swiping a $1,000 tape recorder, the team appears to have
no intention of dismissing Rison, who made an impressive debut in
the victory over Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He joins a veteran offense that appears confident it will be
able to move the ball either on the ground, with Kaufman and Tyrone
Wheatley doing the bulk of the work, or through the air, with
accurate passing supplied by quarterback Rich Gannon, who played
well in limited duty in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   This is predicated on the offensive line doing its job, which is
to either open holes for Kaufman and Wheatley or protect Gannon.
This is, however, a reconfigured line, with Matt Stinchcomb the new
left tackle after missing his entire rookie season with a shoulder
injury and Mo Collins shifting to right guard.
</P>
<P>
   Although line coach Bill Callahan labored long and hard to turn
these large men into a cohesive unit, it is still too soon to know
how well his tutoring took. If the line does not play well, then
the offense will struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Tim Brown remains the offense's marquee player.
Brown is one of those guys who probably will be buried in great
shape. However, he is 34 years old, has lost at least one step and
is now a possession receiver instead of a deep threat. One more
lost step could be trouble. And since he hardly played in the
preseason, it's difficult to know if that step is still his.
</P>
<P>
   The two best players on the defense _ corner Charles Woodson and
tackle Darrell Russell _ are young and spry. They should continue
to improve and make things extremely difficult for opposing
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   But Woodson is the lone sure thing in the secondary. The other
corner, 35-year-old Eric Allen, has been playing even longer than
Brown, and works at a much more demanding position. If he loses a
step, it's six points. Two offseason additions _ Marquez Pope and
Anthony Dorsett _ are the new safeties. Pope's a survivor, having
been a member of all three California NFL teams plus the Rams when
they called Los Angeles home.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett is starting for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive line has been rebuilt, with at least one and
possibly two new starters joining Russell and end Lance Johnstone.
But Johnstone was held out the final two exhibitions with an
injury. Grady Jackson, the new nose tackle, sat out the Seattle
game. Off-season addition Regan Upshaw was invisible for most of
the preseason until rousing himself against the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   How well this unit does now that the games count obviously is
critical. Only the experts from SI and the good Madame can pretend
they know for sure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
