<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4329 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-BALLPARK0827-CO     08-28 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BALLPARK0827-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tome that takes you over the ballpark
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only book a baseball fan will want to read until Richard Ben
Kramer's book on Joe DiMaggio arrives, is ``The Ballpark Book''
(The Sporting News), a lovely coffee-table guide to the evolution
of the baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   They're all here, the quick and the dead, but as part of every
baseball fan is a preference for the dead over the living, the part
that most fans will turn to are the sections on places like Shibe
Park (Philadelphia), League Park (Cleveland) and the Polo Grounds
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the book particularly valuable are the aerial photos
of the stadiums and their surroundings, which give a vivid
impression of the often bizarre configurations that no on-the-field
shot can ever quite capture.
</P>
<P>
   They're all here, along with sections on the impersonal,
short-lived behemoths such as the Astrodome, and the new, retro
stadiums that attempt, with considerable success, to re-create the
Zeitgeist of the old parks that were torn down with such alacrity
in the '50s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   A must-have for the sports fan.
</P>
<P>
   Just the facts ...
</P>
<P>
   Viking's series of brief biographical lives has aroused
competition with a new series called Oxford Portraits. The first to
be published is ``George Orwell: Battling Big Brother,'' and it's
quite well done; although the book is only 109 pages long, Orwell
died at 47 _ there's less of a sense of ruthless concision than
with some of the Viking books.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford series introduces some nice sidebars into the mix,
such as manuscript pages, interesting stills and excerpts from the
work.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford books _ the series includes volumes on Thomas Paine
and Arthur Conan Doyle _ are $22 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Prize roundup ... The James Michener Prize of $10,000, for
authors who publish their first book at 40 or later, has been
awarded to William Gay, author of ``The Long Home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Prize for fiction ((British pound)30,000) has been
awarded to Linda Grant, author of ``When I Lived in Modern Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicola Barker won the IMPAC Dublin Literary Award of 100,000
Irish pounds for her book ``Wide Open,'' beating out others on the
short list that included Philip Roth, Michael Cunningham and Toni
Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Quote Unquote ... ``To promote a book you are expected to get it
up eight or ten times a day, sometimes in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Roy Blount, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
