<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4330 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-FORK0829-COX     08-28 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FORK0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stick a fork in it: This `Road' is done
 &HT;    FORK IN THE ROAD, by Denis Hamill. Pocket Books; 480 pages;
$24.95.
 &HT;    RUN, by Douglas E. Winter. Knopf; 259 pages; $23.
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With sincere apologies to Yogi Berra: If you're browsing a
bookstore and come to ``'Fork in the Road,'' don't take it.
</P>
<P>
   But if you see a copy of ``Run,'' buy it, run home, read it.
It's gonna make a great action movie, although the book will not
long be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fork in the Road,'' however, is doomed on both counts, movie
and book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela's Ashes'' begot the revival in and fashion of
Irish/Celtic literature, memoirs and histories, all things Erin.
``Fork in the Road'' will set it back, if not kill it outright.
</P>
<P>
   Our hero, Colin Coyne, is a young American screenwriter who
seeks inspiration in Ireland because his dying mom told him to go
there. This from mom on her deathbed: ``Colin, love, I must tell
you something I never told anyone else. You have another brother, a
brother you don't even know about.''
</P>
<P>
   The second half of that sentence seems a tad superfluous, no?
But the description of Colin's response to mom's revelation boggles
the reader: ``Colin is startled.''
</P>
<P>
   So Colin goes to Ireland to plumb the family past. Immediately,
a Gypsy pickpocket goes to work on his pocket as he sips a
Guinness. He turns around, and the pickpocket is drop-dead
gorgeous, ``more woman than Maureen O'Hara in ``The Quiet Man,''
and Colin says, ``Buy you a drink?'' Then the tinker woman says,
``Good Irish women don't need your durty Yankee dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Colin tells her she's beautiful. She says: ``Go way out of dat,
you moldy eijit.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the book there is much use of the word eijit.
</P>
<P>
   I found myself using it, as in: I must be an eijit to keep
reading this book.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it Mark Twain who said if you're going to write
vernacular dialect, get it right or don't even try it?
</P>
<P>
   So Colin brings the pickpocket home to America and they settle
down to kids and screenplays, and she shoplifts and yells a lot,
stuff like ``You eijit.'' But I don't want to spoil the tale, so
read it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Or, read ``Run.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a romp. And, blessed be the day, 'tis not an Irishman
or dying Irish mother in sight, leastwise nobody saying ``eijit.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about guns, gunrunners and gun battles. It's so
preposterous, it's fun. More people are killed in a single shootout
between white gun dealers, black drug dealers, cops, Feds, a
minister, phony cops and phony Feds than died in the Gulf War. And
that's just the scene that sets up the big shootout.
</P>
<P>
   The hero, Burdon Lane, is a Vietnam vet with an atrophied
conscience. He sells guns. Legally. Sort of. He's more arms
merchant than gun dealer. He loves his gats, packs three or more
Glocks at a time.
</P>
<P>
   He's the good bad guy, surrounded by bad bad guys, a good bad
guy and one good bad girl, or bad good girl as the case may be.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of this narrative is Elmore Leonard on amphetamines.
The book is aptly named and slows only when Burdon unloads his
political philosophy on the reader.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Winter has an imaginative ear and a gift for dialogue, a
gift occluded at times by scenes in which dialogue is inserted into
the most unbelievable of circumstances. At one point, two guys of
few words _ shoot-first, talk-later types _ who have been gunning
for each other for 12 chapters face each other down and start ...
talking.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you know a showdown is coming, Armageddon actually.
</P>
<P>
   And there are some nice plot twists. And a black gang leader,
Doctor D, who speaks some of the most memorable lines in print. I
see Samuel L. Jackson playing that role. Bruce Willis plays Burdon
Lane. Fun movie. The NRA will not approve.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Run'' is not yet a movie. That's the problem. It's a book.
Remember the name, though. If money's tight, borrow the book, wait
for the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Email: paulreid(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
