<HEADER>
A4331 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKSM-MILES0827-COX     08-28 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKSM-MILES0827-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   New book an entertaining look at musical giant Miles Davis
</P>
<P>
   MILES AND ME, by Quincy Troupe. University of California Press;
189 pages; $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Neal
</P>
<P>
   c, 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - All right, immersion therapy time.
Everyone repeat after me:
</P>
<P>
   ``$&AMP;%!''
</P>
<P>
   Again! And again!
</P>
<P>
   Good. Now that we're past the profanity, on to its prince.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Davis gets his Boswell in ``Miles and Me,'' a personal
take on the genius by the poet who helped write his autobiography,
``Miles .'' That filthy yet fascinating frolic _ a tour de force on
the F-word that spoke some ugly truths and stung some beautiful
people _ made Quincy Troupe famous. It also made him one of the few
to penetrate the mask and glimpse the heart behind the horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miles and Me'' is a much lesser book, but it's an
indispensible and entertaining look at the musical giant in his
more mundane moments. Just remember to duck whenever the big man
speaks.
</P>
<P>
   Hear Miles embrace his adoring, autograph-seeking fans: ``(at)$%
you, you jive $(! Get the (at)$% outta my face and take yo silly
little %$(at)&AMP; with you!''
</P>
<P>
   Eavesdrop as the Prince of Darkness acknowledges a buddy's
Howdy-do: ``(at)$% you, man! I don't hafta speak to your (at)$%
every time I see you. (at)$%, who the (at)$% you think you are?''
</P>
<P>
   Or listen in as our hero butters up a journalist before an
interview: ``Well, (at)$%, don't just sit there. Ask me some (at)$%
questions!''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, that Miles Davis, what a swell guy.
</P>
<P>
   Except he really was a swell guy _ sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Because we also see Miles playing sweetly with the poet's young
son, caressing his horses, crying when his longtime pal James
Baldwin dies, laughing with his St. Louis homeboys, stressing over
the shade of his skin and forming a grudging but lasting friendship
with Troupe as they sit together day after day recording the tapes
that would become the notorious ``Miles.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one complicated dude _ ``irascible, contemptuous,
brutally honest, ill-tempered when things don't go his way,
complex, fair-minded, humble, kind, and a son of a bitch,'' Troupe
says.
</P>
<P>
   He's also someone we need to figure out, for he was one of the
greatest musical minds the world has ever known, according to the
poet, and the driving force for musical art in this country for
more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Troupe spends dozens of pages making his case for Miles'
greatness, tracing the music's effect on his development as man and
writer and arguing that race is the reason we teach Bach and
Beethoven and ignore Miles and Coltrane in our schools.
</P>
<P>
   Troupe is a soulful, sharp and persuasive commentator _ and he
might even get you to give ``Bitches Brew'' another chance _ but
he's a better reporter. The book's at its best when he's in Miles'
face, hanging out in his New York apartment, taking his heat,
hearing his passion and filing away the details.
</P>
<P>
   Who was the voodoo woman? What did Miles eat? Did he have AIDS?
What was all the gum-chewing about? What movies did he watch? How
did he talk, practice, work, live?
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, those details _ those bits of trivia that point
toward truth _ make up the meat of the book, and it's tasty meat
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Email: danneal(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
