<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4332 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-MOVIES-HANKGREENBERG0     08-28 1529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HANKGREENBERG0827-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Documentary on baseball great Hank Greenberg runaway hit
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Passy
</P>
<P>
   c, 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - He didn't have Babe Ruth's
larger-than-life appeal. He didn't marry a movie star a la Joe
DiMaggio. And if you look up his name in the books, you'll find
he's not at the top of the list in any career categories.
</P>
<P>
   So, why is a movie about Jewish baseball great Hank Greenberg
the runaway documentary of the year?
</P>
<P>
   It's a question that no one can easily answer, not even Aviva
Kempner, the 53-year-old writer and director of ``The Life and
Times of Hank Greenberg.'' What should have been a picture that
only ran in major markets and small festivals _ it was shown last
year at the Palm Beach International Film Festival and the Palm
Beach Jewish Film Festival _ is now in the midst of a full national
release.
</P>
<P>
   It's already among the top 20 grossing documentaries in the
United States, making more than $1 million at the box office.
Granted, those aren't Star Wars numbers, but this is a film that
begins with a rousing rendition of Take Me Out to the Ballgame _ in
Yiddish!
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not a lot of films that three generations can go to,
and in that respect it's real rewarding,'' Kempner says.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the picture's unexpected popularity, she says that
``there are two natural audiences who gossip _ the Jewish-American
audience and baseball mavens.'' It's such gossip that she believes
has helped Hank Greenberg find its way to moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   John Vanco, co-president of the picture's distributor, Cowboy
Booking International, agrees. ``I can't remember such a pure
word-of-mouth film with as much momentum,'' he says. ``We expect
the film to continue to break records.''
</P>
<P>
   For those unaware of Greenberg's name and reputation, here's a
crash course: The product of a middle-class Jewish family from New
York, Greenberg, who died in 1986 at 75, ignored his parents'
advice that he pursue a ``professional'' career _ say, as a lawyer
or doctor _ and let his love of baseball be his guide.
</P>
<P>
   Although never a particularly nimble athlete, he had a natural
strength and commanding presence, standing 6-foot-4. He was signed
by the Detroit Tigers in 1933 and soon established himself as one
of the American League's premier power hitters, nearly topping Babe
Ruth's record of 60 home runs in a single season when he belted 58
in 1938. He also led his team to World Series appearances and was
selected the league's Most Valuable Player in 1935 and 1940. He
ended his career with the Pittsburgh Pirates in 1947, playing his
final year for the record-breaking sum of more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenberg's story is only partly about baseball. As the
first Jewish superstar in any professional sport, he became a
symbol for the hundreds of thousands of first- and
second-generation Jewish-Americans who were shedding their ties to
the ``old country'' and looking to establish an identity for
themselves in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Although not particularly religious, Greenberg never denied his
Jewish heritage _ and his decision not to play on Yom Kippur, the
most sacred Jewish holiday, during a 1934 pennant race made
national headlines, with gentile fans respecting his move. Even
more noteworthy was that Greenberg did all this in Detroit, a city
that was home to such notorious anti-Semites as auto magnate Henry
Ford and radio personality the Rev. Charles E. Coughlin.
</P>
<P>
   Kempner makes sure to include footage of Ford and Coughlin at
the Tigers' ballpark, one of the film's many subtle ways of
underlining Greenberg's triumph against the odds. The director and
writer came to the subject naturally. The daughter of Jewish
immigrants from Europe _ her mother is a Holocaust survivor _
Kempner was born and raised in Detroit and remains an ardent
baseball fan. Although she never saw Greenberg play, she remembers
hearing plenty about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hank's name was invoked so much growing up, I thought he was
part of the Kol Nidre liturgy,'' she says, referring to the Yom
Kippur religious service.
</P>
<P>
   Kempner, who lives in Washington, decided to do the film as soon
as she heard of Greenberg's death. She had just completed the
widely praised ``Partisans of Vilna,'' a documentary about Jewish
resistance against the Nazis, and was looking for a new subject. If
Partisans was about the Jewish experience in Europe in the '30s and
'40s, Greenberg would reflect the American side of the coin. It's
the story of one man, but in a larger sense, it's the story of an
emerging people in a new society.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary covers Greenberg's life through his retirement
in 1947 and builds with the quiet intensity of a dramatic film.
Greenberg essentially ``narrates'' the picture _ through interviews
captured either on video or audio (he was recording his memoirs at
the time of his death). Complementing the package are newsreel
clips and interviews with everyone from Greenberg's family members
and former teammates (Bob Feller, Charlie Gehringer, Ralph Kiner)
to such prominent Jewish-Americans as lawyer Alan Dershowitz and
Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The latter are especially important because they give a sense of
Greenberg's importance to a younger generation of Jewish-Americans.
Although there were other Jewish role models in politics and law,
they couldn't compare with a star slugger. ``It's just the same
with Jackie Robinson and blacks. It meant for blacks they could
enter that arena (of popular culture),'' says Kempner. ``For Jews,
it made them feel more American.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the film, Kempner poignantly captures the
first encounter between Greenberg and Robinson, when the Jewish
great offered words of encouragement while the emerging black star
praised him as a role model. For New York Times sports columnist
Ira Berkow, who's also Jewish, that one moment distills the essence
of Greenberg _ and the film. ``You would hope a person of Jewish
background would act the way Greenberg did toward Robinson. ...
Hank never let us down,'' says Berkow, who helped edit Greenberg's
autobiography and served as a consultant on the film.
</P>
<P>
   Such special moments weren't necessarily easy to come by.
Kempner spent more than a decade doing research and interviews. She
says the process was largely slowed by a lack of money. Even though
the film cost only $1 million to make, it was hard finding
financial support, particularly since Kempner started working
heavily on the project at the same time Ken Burns was doing his
baseball documentary for public television.
</P>
<P>
   When Kempner approached potential contributors, be they
individuals or private foundations, she was told, ``Ken's doing it
all.'' In the end, she had to rely on support from the Greenberg
family _ and she admits she still hasn't paid all the bills,
including her own salary.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the project is that it's unlikely Greenberg, an
extremely modest man, would have approved of it. ``He didn't
realize how important he was to the American people. He had no
idea,'' says the slugger's sister-in-law, Marilyn Greenberg, an
Atlantis resident who appears in the film. ``He thought he was a
good ballplayer, but this would have come as a big shock to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many women who knew the twice-married athlete during his
lifetime, Marilyn Greenberg, who is married to Greenberg's brother
Joe, was consistently awed by his looks and charm, another facet
that comes across in the film. ``He was the handsomest guy I have
ever seen in my life,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together and you almost wonder why Greenberg didn't
make a stab at politics during his post-baseball career; instead,
he worked in management with the Cleveland Indians and Chicago
White Sox and eventually retired in California, where he played
tennis regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Kempner can't help but compare Greenberg's story to that of Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, who recently became the first Jewish-American to
be nominated on a presidential ticket. But even she admits,
Lieberman may have an easier time in his run with Al Gore for the
White House. Greenberg had to endure anti-Semitic taunts in
ballpark after ballpark. As Kempner notes, ``It's more a political
and social glass ceiling with Lieberman.''
</P>
<P>
   But it took Kempner's mother to put the Lieberman nomination and
the film's success in proper perspective. She told her daughter
that it took a baseball great to pave the way for the vice
presidential nominee _ and the picture is the conduit that conveys
that idea to the public. Lieberman ``can do it now because of your
film. People feel proud,'' said the elder Kempner to her child.
</P>
<P>
   That may be overstating the case, but who's to argue with a
Jewish mother? Certainly, not Kempner, who says Jewish-Americans
``don't forget our heroes.'' And like the man himself, The Life and
Times of Hank Greenberg proves that there's no predicting the path
of glory.
</P>
<P>
   To everyone's surprise, this 95-minute, independently made
documentary has become a home run of a release.
</P>
<P>
   Email: charlespassy(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
