<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS WHO WERE HAZED
</P>
<P>
   All types of hazing combined .... 48 percent
</P>
<P>
   Humiliation ............................ 43
</P>
<P>
   Potentially illegal ..................... 29
</P>
<P>
   Substance abuse ..................... 23
</P>
<P>
   Dangerous .............................. 22
</P>
<P>
   Note: Based on a mail survey of a sample of the 91 percent of
high school students who belong to groups.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT KIND OF HAZING GOES ON IN HIGH SCHOOLS
</P>
<P>
   Hazing: ``any humiliating or dangerous activity expected of you
to join a group, regardless of your willingness to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Humiliation: ``socially offensive, isolating or uncooperative
behaviors.''
</P>
<P>
   Substance abuse: ``abuse of tobacco, alcohol, or illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dangerous hazing: ``hurtful, aggressive, destructive, and
disruptive behaviors.''
</P>
<P>
   PERCENT OF NEWCOMERS HAZED
</P>
<P>
   Fraternity or sorority ................ 76 percent
</P>
<P>
   Peer group or gang .................. 73
</P>
<P>
   Sports team ............................ 35
</P>
<P>
   Cheerleading squad .................. 34
</P>
<P>
   Vocational group ...................... 27
</P>
<P>
   Church group ........................... 24
</P>
<P>
   Music, art theater group ............ 22
</P>
<P>
   Political or social action group .... 21
</P>
<P>
   Social club or organization ......... 21
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper or yearbook ............. 12
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic/intellectual club ......... 12
</P>
<P>
   Source: Alfred University, ``Initiation Rites in American High
Schools.'' Details online at
www.alfred.edu/news/html/hazing(underscore)study.html
</P>
