<HEADER>
A4354 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-HOT-STARTUP-CASE-STUD     08-28 2025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-STARTUP-CASE-STUDY-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTREPRENEURS VS. EXECUTIVES AT SOCABA.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Mon., Aug. 28, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is from the July-August
issue of HARVARD BUSINESS REVIEW, the premiere source of
information on the art and science of business and management. For
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or about The Syndicate's new offerings from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By REGINA FAZIO MARUCA  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PLEASE NOTE: This case study presents common managerial
dilemmas and offers concrete solutions from experts. As written, it
is hypothetical, and the names are fictitious. Also, because of the
length of this article, editors may elect to delete one of the
reactions from the experts.)
</P>
<P>
   Joe Castle, Dave Souza and Ryan Bahar had been close friends
since their freshman year in college, when fate brought them
together as roommates.
</P>
<P>
   They were an unlikely threesome. Different backgrounds,
different interests. But as business partners, they were a perfect
fit. Socaba.com, the company they founded six months after
graduation, had taken off, and they hadn't looked back in the four
years since then.
</P>
<P>
   Socaba.com sold furniture, office supplies, computer equipment
and office-management services to small professional service firms.
</P>
<P>
   Dave had come up with the original idea for the business, so he
was the president, CEO and chairman. A computer geek, he oversaw
the site's construction and had the clearest ideas about strategic
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Joe, the English major, had been the company's marketing guru
from day one.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, whose parents owned a chain of discount stores, handled
the company's back office.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ryan and Joe were senior vice presidents, but the titles
meant little to the team. When they had to make any major decision,
they made it together.
</P>
<P>
   Early customers were drawn to Socaba's one-stop shopping. And
now that it had a large network of customers, it was able to
negotiate discounts on equipment and services from a broad set of
suppliers. It had also recently added new service offerings, such
as low-cost group insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company had electronic bulletin boards where
customers could discuss the products, seek advice and network.
</P>
<P>
   But predictably, Socaba's success had created a need for more
help at the top to handle fulfilling the orders, negotiating
contracts with suppliers, integrating new software and managing
staff.
</P>
<P>
   The team had struggled with these new tasks for months when
Karen Poole had begun to talk with them about bringing in managers
from outside. She was the venture capitalist from a small local
firm that was Socaba's biggest source of funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry, guys, you'll still have plenty of say in running
the business,'' she had promised them, ``but you need to get some
professionals in here to bring the company into the major leagues.
Face it, Socaba is growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   The founders realized she was right.
</P>
<P>
   Karen recruited a COO, a CIO and a CFO about six months ago. The
COO, Margaret Satchel, had come from the top management ranks at a
major office supply company.
</P>
<P>
   The CIO, Cliff Singer, had launched a successful e-tail business
of his own and sold out at a tremendous profit not long before
coming to Socaba.
</P>
<P>
   And the CFO, Darlene Seibel, had been second in command at a
major HMO. Besides her financial skills, she was widely respected
as a progressive thinker on the potential of the Internet to
improve health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you have a full team,'' Karen had said at the lunch to
welcome the three new executives. ``This business is really going
to grow and prosper.'' Apart from this initial cheerleading
session, though, she had pretty much left them on their own.
</P>
<P>
   One of the group's first projects: to seriously consider an
offer from OfficeOne to merge with Socaba.com.
</P>
<P>
   INNOCENT MISTAKES?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, while the business continued to do well, the team
never gelled.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the group of six had started off by holding regular
Monday morning meetings. Over time, however, several of the
meetings had been canceled for various reason, and formal meetings
between the insiders and outsiders had become sporadic.
</P>
<P>
   The three senior people found themselves taking counsel with one
another more and more frequently and generally ignoring the younger
trio.
</P>
<P>
   On day, during a meeting of the top dozen or so people in the
company, Joe had casually mentioned that he was ready to sign a
partnership agreement with an accounting services firm.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret interrupted him immediately with a terse ``What are you
talking about?'' and Darlene followed up with a short, heated
speech on the importance of sharing information. Cliff just folded
his arms and stared into space.
</P>
<P>
   Joe insisted that he hadn't left the managers out of the loop
intentionally. Along with Dave and Ryan, he pledged to do better in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT HAPPENED?
</P>
<P>
   In Dave's apartment, the three young friends rehashed the events
of the past six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been them against us,'' Dave said. ``It's not that
they grew apart from us. We never really joined ranks in the first
place. And that's our fault.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not entirely,'' Joe disagreed. ``They started out talking more
to each other than to any of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like we really made an effort?'' Dave countered. ``Like we're
making an effort now? Look at us. Why are we having another meeting
before a meeting?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe, you're the one who wanted to talk about this tonight,''
Ryan said. ``Do you really think it's that much of a problem?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do'' Joe said. ``Almost every day we find an excuse to meet
without them _ to make some decision behind their backs. Karen
called today, and she's worried. Cliff is ready to walk. Says he's
frustrated. The only thing holding him here is the options.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan looked horrified. ``You waited until now to tell us that?
What the hell were you thinking?''
</P>
<P>
   Dave opened his mouth to agree, but Joe put his hand up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying an experiment,'' he said. ``I was trying to make
you feel like they must feel. Left out. I think it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a long silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Point taken,'' Ryan conceded. ``But we still have a big
problem: the OfficeOne deal. I wouldn't be surprised if our three
colleagues weren't also holed up somewhere discussing their
strategy. Who's in charge here, anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' Joe said, ``we can't make the deal with OfficeOne. If
we do, we'll lose our relationships with all the other big
suppliers. We didn't start this business to be a unit of some fat
incumbent. Socaba can be bigger than OfficeOne.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan shook his head. ``Yeah, but if we say that, it'll just
confirm what they all believe: that we're just three naive dreamers
who've been lucky so far. They want the sure bet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that the OfficeOne deal is a bad idea,'' Dave said,
``but if we just go in and say no, we'll lose Cliff, and we might
lose Karen. We lose Karen, we're in serious trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SHOULD SOCABA'S CO-FOUNDERS DO TO KEEP THE COMPANY ON
TRACK?
</P>
<P>
   FIRST ANALYSIS: Tom Scott is the co-chairman of Nantucket
Nectars, a Cambridge, Mass.-based juice company that he founded in
1989 with former college classmate Tom First.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Dave, Joe and Ryan didn't know what they were
getting into when they accepted VC funding and then, at the VC's
urging, brought in new managers. They probably saw dollar signs and
knew they could get the money.
</P>
<P>
   To me, building a great company isn't just about making money.
It's also about creating something of value that can last. The guys
probably had that view initially, but they now seem to be stuck in
a situation in which they've given up control over the company's
vision and direction. Their best bet may be just to get out of the
business. I'd rather do that than work with people I didn't see eye
to eye with.
</P>
<P>
   In our case, Tom First and I have always retained control over
the board and management. In my view, 75 percent of a startup's
success comes from emotion, and 25 percent comes from skill and
experience. We always had the commitment to making our company
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Also, no matter what percentage of the company you own, you have
to have the skills to be CEO _ or else you shouldn't have the job.
You should be in the job because of the value you bring to the
company, not for legal reasons. It's hard to know if Dave is really
suited to be Socaba's ongoing CEO. If he is, he's got to start
acting like a leader _ and the OfficeOne deal is a good place to
start.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with OfficeOne needn't be a problem. Tom and I sold
half of Nantucket Nectars to Ocean Spray in 1998, and we did so
because they wanted us to stay on as presidents of the company and
run it as a separate corporation. So if control is the issue, the
OfficeOne partnership may be right for the Socaba founders,
provided they retain their authority.
</P>
<P>
   The Socaba guys started off as entrepreneurs, but by taking on
venture funding, they may have lost the chance to see their ideas
through to the end. Now they must decide if their problems with the
new managers are because of poor communication or deeper concerns
that stem from their gut feelings about the business. If it's the
latter, and they don't feel they can work with the outsiders, they
should take their money and move on.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND ANALYSIS: Christine Comaford is a managing director of
Artemis Ventures, a Sausalito, Calif.-based company that invests in
start-ups which offer business-to-business Internet software and
services. Comaford's analysis:
</P>
<P>
   The problems are clear: lack of leadership, passivity from all
the players and a failure to define roles and company direction.
</P>
<P>
   Dave, Joe, Ryan and Karen should have hammered out who would own
what area. Karen just parachuted the executives in and expected
things to work out. But without clear roles, the two sides will
fight for turf.
</P>
<P>
   I would have made Dave the CTO and Cliff the CEO _ Cliff seems
like a seasoned entrepreneur. Ryan would likely report to the COO,
Margaret. Joe could still handle marketing. At this stage, you
wouldn't need both a COO and a CFO.
</P>
<P>
   And who's in charge of sales? It's a bad sign that people were
hired without a thoughtful plan based on Socaba's needs.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the regular Monday meetings is a major problem.
The VC should know who's driving the marketing team, who's driving
the operations, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The executive team should hold weekly meetings, as well as
monthly meetings with their VCs. The latter would include an
operational review, followed by a board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The kids must realize that they must give up the control they've
enjoyed for the past four years. That's what happens when you seek
out venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   About the OfficeOne deal, it will be impossible to make an
informed decision until roles are defined and a leader emerges.
</P>
<P>
   If Socaba continues to drift internally, it will end up as
nothing more than a blip on the screen of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   (Regina Fazio Maruca is a Sandwich, Mass.-based free-lance
writer.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
