<HEADLINE>
VENTURE PHILANTHROPIST: MARTIN VARSAVSKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Mon, Aug. 28, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is from the July-August
issue of HARVARD BUSINESS REVIEW, the premiere source of
information on the art and science of business and management. For
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or about The Syndicate's new offerings from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By MARGARET HANSHAW  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Information Age is opening up a new world of economic
possibilities _ but not for everyone. Those who don't have access
to computers and the Internet are being left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Unless countries and communities find a way to bridge the
digital divide, the economic disparities between rich and poor will
likely worsen.
</P>
<P>
   But just throwing dollars at the problem won't be sufficient. As
technology guru Esther Dyson recently wrote, ``Just as in venture
finance, money alone isn't always enough if it's used inefficiently
and support systems aren't in place ... The skills it takes to
build companies must translate to the task of building a better
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Martin Varsavsky. A 40-year-old entrepreneur based in
Madrid, Spain, he has founded six companies over the past two
decades, including telecommunications and Internet start-ups
Einsteinet, Internet Factory, Jazztel, Ya.com and Viatel.
</P>
<P>
   Having made his fortune in high tech, Varsavsky is now applying
his entrepreneurial expertise to the philanthropic work of closing
the digital divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motivations of an Internet entrepreneur and a
philanthropist are essentially the same,'' he says. ``They both
pinpoint problems, economic or social, and set out to solve them in
a new way. At best, they both have people's interests at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   AN EDUCATIONAL PORTAL
</P>
<P>
   The focus of Varsavsky's venture philanthropy is his native
Argentina. He is donating $11.2 million to help the country's
Ministry of Education launch an Internet portal that will give
Argentina's 10 million grammar, high school and university students
access to learning tools, online texts, e-mail, chat rooms, forums
and research.
</P>
<P>
   He is also helping the ministry establish a company, Educar SA,
to operate the portal. The company will sell online advertising and
e-commerce capabilities, generating funds to buy computers and
networking hardware for the country's 40,000 schools.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the company will be privatized, providing even more
money for improving the schools' technological infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   For Argentine educators and government officials, Varsavsky's
proposal must seem like a dream come true: According to the current
plan, all the country's schools will be wired within four years.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its educational benefits, the project makes business
sense as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students, teachers and school workers account for one in three
Argentines,'' Varsavsky says. ``That's a huge market, representing
$50 billion in annual spending, and companies will pay handsomely
to reach it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for any criticism about mixing commerce and education,
Varsavsky has a blunt reply: ``The ideal, of course, would be to
have a portal without advertising, but we need the ads to generate
the money to get computers into the schools. No ads, no access.''
</P>
<P>
   GETTING PERSONAL
</P>
<P>
   Varsavsky has a large personal stake in the venture. In 1977,
when he was just 17, his family was forced to flee Argentina, which
at the time was ruled by a military dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a family of Jewish intellectuals,'' he says, ``and
we were chased out of our home for refusing to buckle under the
fascist government. We were reluctant to leave, but when the
military kidnapped and killed my cousin, David Varsavsky, my father
realized that we had to go in order to protect ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience left Varsavsky with deeply divided feelings about
his former home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a part of me that will never forgive Argentina for
putting my family and many others through such pain,'' he explains.
``But when I saw that Argentines were being left out of the new
economy, that the Internet revolution was passing the nation by, I
felt like I had to do something. The better educated the Argentines
are, the less likely a terror like the one I lived through will
happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Varsavsky's effort in Argentina may provide a
template for other successful entrepreneurs who want to give
something back to society.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to closing the digital divide, business-building
skills may be more valuable than cash, and lending those skills may
be more fulfilling than just writing checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you donate money, you feel happy to have contributed,''
Varsavsky says, ``but the feeling is not nearly as profound as when
you put your time and energy into helping create something out of
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Hanshaw is a manuscript editor for Harvard Business
Review.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
