<HEADER>
A4363 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BREAST-FEEDING-NY     08-28 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BREAST-FEEDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIGHING THE POVERTY FACTOR IN BREAST-FEEDING GUIDELINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A recent study in India suggests that
breast-feeding alone may not provide enough sustenance to babies in
the developing nations when their mothers are severely
malnourished.
</P>
<P>
   The report adds fuel to a debate about a decade-old campaign by
the World Health Organization and other U.N. agencies that advocate
an exclusive reliance on breast milk for the first six months of
life.
</P>
<P>
   The study _ an Indian National Family Health Survey report
titled ``Are WHO Guidelines on Breast-Feeding Appropriate for
India?'' _ concludes that babies can and should be given
supplementary liquids or soft foods as young as 2 or 3 months to
overcome the deficiencies in the milk of a malnourished mother.
</P>
<P>
   The new survey drew immediate criticism from officials from the
World Health Organization and Unicef, the U.N. Children's Fund.
Both groups say that breast-feeding provides the safest, most
health-giving nourishment, providing antibodies against diarrheal
disease and eliminating risks posed by contaminants often
introduced into baby formula or other supplements through the use
of dirty water.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about breast-feeding in the developing world have
arisen because of AIDS, with studies still assessing the possible
transmission from mother to baby of the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization's guidelines say that
breast-feeding should begin immediately after birth and that
infants should receive no other food until they are 4 to 6 months
old, when supplements may be added to provide additional nutrients.
Breast-feeding, in combination with other foods, is recommended
until a child is at least 2 years old.
</P>
<P>
   In India, with a population of 1 billion, decades of maternal
health programs have failed to dent significantly the high
incidence of malnourishment among children, according to the World
Bank, which says that more than half the children under 4 in India
are severely malnourished and 60 percent of mothers are anemic. Put
another way, 40 percent of all the world's malnourished children
are Indian. Infant mortality in India is still high, at 79 for
every 1,000 births.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the new survey on the role of breast-feeding in
nutrition and mortality was published jointly by a state
demographer from South India and a specialist in population and
health studies from the East-West Center in Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   The report looked at breast-feeding practices measured against
not only infant mortality statistics but also social and economic
factors in the lives of the mothers in three groups of
high-mortality, medium-mortality and low-mortality Indian states.
Breast-feeding is the norm everywhere in India and usually
continues beyond infancy, providing a common backdrop for the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   While the authors _ Ravilla Anandaiah, demographer for the Tamil
Nadu directorate of family welfare, and Minja Kim Choe, a senior
fellow at the East-West Center _ did not dispute the value of
breast-feeding, they wrote that the purpose of their survey was
``to shed light on how infant survival in India can be improved by
modifying infant-feeding practices and to evaluate the
appropriateness of the WHO guidelines for breast-feeding _
especially the guideline recommending exclusive breast-feeding up
to 4 to 6 months.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors surveyed mothers of children born in the previous
four years, asking them at how many months a baby was regularly
given plain water, other milk, other liquids or solids or mushy
food.
</P>
<P>
   They found that almost everywhere, babies were being given
supplementary liquids or solids at an age lower than international
health officials had recommended, and that the food was apparently
safe because the presence of supplementary food was not related to
higher death rates. Advocates of only breast-feeding say that the
risk of contamination, particularly by dirty water, rises when
other foods are introduced.
</P>
<P>
   The new survey found that in all mortality groups, both
exclusive and nonexclusive breast-feeding seemed to lower mortality
rates in the early months. But the benefits of exclusive
breast-feeding dropped for older infants, the authors concluded,
because ``children's nutritional needs are not met completely by
mother's milk after the first few months of infancy.''
</P>
<P>
   By 3 to 6 months in states with high mortality rates, the survey
says, ``mortality is higher among those who are breast-fed
exclusively.'' In these high-risk states _ Assam, Bihar, Madhya
Pradesh, Orissa and Uttar Pradesh _ ``breast-feeding with
supplements has the most beneficial effect on child survival.''
Mothers who breast-fed exclusively were the poorest, most
illiterate and likely to be the most malnourished.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
