<HEADER>
A4364 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-SURVIVOR-COMMENT-S     08-28 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-COMMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUDY SURVIVES HIS POLITICALLY INCORRECT ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something about Rudy.
</P>
<P>
   As in, bigot. As well as public favorite and media darling.
</P>
<P>
   Now that ``Survivor'' is over, he's either going to fade back
into his Florida retirement oblivion or stay in the limelight to
cash in on his streak of celebrity. He might even turn up on the
next ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Unexpectedly, Rudy became a sort of national cuddly bear by the
time the TV series ended last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' inadvertently gave us American television's first
openly gay male lead, Richard Hatch, who effectively defined the
show and won the million-dollar competition.
</P>
<P>
   But it also gave us Rudy Boesch, who apparently stood for the
endearing side of unabashed homophobia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get home (and) my wife asks me about who was with
you,'' he said at one point on the show, ``I'll say a queer who ran
around bare-assed half the time, for one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He was Archie Bunker all over again. But Rudy wasn't the
caricatured invention of a liberal TV producer, as Bunker was.
Rudy's puss is the face of real-life, bad-ass bigotry. And viewers
loved him.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy's popularity was partly because of his age, 72, and his
military record _ two Bronze Stars.
</P>
<P>
   It was partly because of his this-too-shall-pass stoicism. He
didn't whine or sulk; he just sat and gazed. It was partly because
of his hidebound sense of honor. He gave his word and kept it.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also because he didn't run his comments through the
laundry bleach of political correctness. When Rudy spoke at all, he
said pretty much whatever popped into his little mind, usually in
single syllables.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think it was entirely guileless. In the
post-``Survivor'' town hall show on CBS on Wednesday, I was struck
by the little smile that accompanied one of his ``queer''
references to Richard.
</P>
<P>
   It was a smile that said he knew he was being amusing, and
knowingly naughty. I'll bet he's ribald fun at cocktail parties
with his old Navy buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I called him `queer' is so all my good SEAL team
buddies will know what I'm talkin' about,'' Rudy told Bryant
Gumbel.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting. In the recesses of the Pentagon, did some Navy
public relations officer slam his palm to his forehead when he
heard that?
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel tried to nudge Rudy into one of those feel-good TV
revelations, asking him if his island bond with Richard had changed
any of his preconceptions.
</P>
<P>
   You can lead a bigot right up to the creek, but you can't make
him drink. ``Nah,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Gumbel should have practiced a variation of the don't ask,
don't tell doctrine. But you knew the subject would come up.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone laughed and applauded. That's just Rudy. Besides,
there's something oddly liberating about the vicarious experience
of bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   But what might gay viewers have thought? That this is what Rudy
learned in wearing the uniform of the United States of America for
more than 40 years?
</P>
<P>
   And mightn't it have occurred to gay viewers that Rudy was paid
and equipped all those years by taxes collected in sizable measure
from the very people he curled his lip at on national TV?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously it wouldn't have occurred to Rudy himself. He's a
product of the tight sphere of the U.S. Navy, and there's a dark
side to Navy tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Seomin, entertainment and media director for the Gay and
Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation in Los Angeles, says that among
the branches of the U.S. military, ``overall the two most
homophobic are the Marines and the Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, the American Civil Liberties Union Foundation
of Southern California charged that the Navy penalized homosexual
activity more severely than it punished sailors for child
molestation or rape.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, it was the Navy that tried to blame a gay
sailor, Clayton Hartwig, for an explosion that killed 47 sailors,
including Hartwig, aboard the battleship Iowa in 1989. Hartwig was
later exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   But enough of that. Back to Rudy, the grumpy gay-basher. Seomin
also noticed the laughter and applause when Rudy talked about
``queers'' on the post-``Survivor'' special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy is one thing,'' Seomin said, ``but America's reaction to
him is something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had called Gervase (a black contestant on the show) the
N-word, the audience would not have been laughing or applauding.
They'd have been gasping. ... Any attack on any other minority
would not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rudy was a sufficiently appealing figure to make TV safe
again for gay-bashing, if only for the 13 weeks of ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a throwback. The pertinent question is whether the
country laughed with him or at him.
</P>
<P>
   Some of each, I suspect. The ratio is a fair measurement of how
far we've come, and how far we have to go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
