<SLUG> BC-GAME-SEAMAN-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MONSTER IN A BOX: Virtual pet can make every day a living hell
_  in a good way  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By NEVA CHONIN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are many evil people in the world, but not one of them
deserves to be insulted by a fish.
</P>
<P>
   Especially not a droll verbal piranha like Seaman. This digital
amphibian with a human face pretends to be a virtual pet game from
Sega. He's not. He's more a conniving roommate hell-bent on running
his owner's life.
</P>
<P>
   Try working while, in the next room, a voice calls, ``Hey, skin
puppet! You out there? I'm hungry!''
</P>
<P>
   Try making dinner as, from the virtual television fish tank, an
oily Seaman coos, ``Hell-ooo-oo, my little fuzzy one. Can we
talk?''
</P>
<P>
   Seaman likes to tell his owner to ``get a life.'' This is
impossible. The owner is too busy catering to Seaman to get a life.
</P>
<P>
   How is such an abomination possible? Easy. Sega's virtual pet
simulation uses the Dreamcast console's voice-recognition system to
create a chatty interactive environment. One of Dreamcast's
best-selling titles to date in Japan, the game requires players to
raise a humanoid fish from an egg, then bond with him and be driven
crazy by him for more than a month before he evolves and gives them
a little peace.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the nuts and bolts: The Seaman game comes with a
special Visual Memory Unit, which records the fishy one's progress
and vital data. Players communicate with Seaman using a microphone
attached to the Dreamcast controller. The console's digital pad
operates various functions such as lighting, water temperature and
oxygen content.
</P>
<P>
   The game boasts Leonard Nimoy as narrator and guide. In his
inimitable drone, Nimoy introduces each session with insights into
Seaman's needs and personality quirks. All action _ can swimming
lazily and offering droll commentary be considered action? _ takes
place in Seaman's aquarium, with the ability to toggle to a food
screen and a terrarium where larvae are raised to meet the scaly
one's culinary requirements. He must be fed twice a day or perish.
</P>
<P>
   Once hatched from his egg, the soon-to-be-Seaman evolves into
four little humanoid ``gill-men'' who soon graduate from baby talk
to monosyllabic conversation. Time passes, and through a hideous
process of natural selection, the gill-men eliminate one another
until only two adult Seamen remain. Eventually one of these knocks
off the other in a gut-churning mating ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Hint: Seamen in ecstasy are not a pretty sight. Warning: The
surviving Seaman _ your pet _ is not above making indecent
propositions to humans. Proceed with caution.
</P>
<P>
   As his vocabulary develops, the inquisitive fish will troll the
player's personal life, asking about age, sex, marital and
employment status and other pertinent data. At his most garrulous,
Seaman will launch into monologues on the state of Internet
culture, sports, politics and the nature of being. Seaman loves the
sound of his voice when he's dissembling.
</P>
<P>
   The human can always take revenge, however. Use the cursor to
tickle Seaman, flick him or lift him squealing out of his tank. For
the ultimate cruelty, chant ``PlayStation,'' a word guaranteed to
rankle Dreamcast's star fish.
</P>
<P>
   He might dish out scads of grief, but Seaman is also a hoot to
have around. He looks cute paddling around on the TV screen,
singing to himself and ruminating on scaly metaphysics. His dry
asides can brighten an afternoon. When times are hard, he'll even
deign to offer solace.
</P>
<P>
   For all the weird fun, there's also lots of downtime with
Seaman. If he's grumpy and uncommunicative, the game is reduced to
hours of tedious fish-tank voyeurism. Watch Seaman swim. Swim,
Seaman, swim.
</P>
<P>
   Potential boredom isn't Seaman's only drawback. The speech
recognition system often garbles messages, leading to surreal
conversations in which the player chats about the temperature and
Seaman talks about Toshiba laptops. Game play can be slow when
there are too many objects onscreen _ say, multiple moths and
spiders in the terrarium _ and the visuals, while lovely, are
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Seaman is great for those who enjoy verbal sparring or just want
a little virtual companionship. Those looking for the thrills of
``Crazy Taxi'' or other high-energy Dreamcast games might want to
consider taking up bungee jumping instead.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there's always swordfishing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEAMAN &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Video-game virtual pet. Sega/Vivarium. Dreamcast platform. &LR; 
 &UR; $49.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
