<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4370 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WINDOWS-WINDOWS-SFCHR     08-28 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDOWS-WINDOWS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 &HT;    FEW CALL WINDOWS 2000 A SMOOTH SELLER &HT;    By KELLY ZITO
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Microsoft introduced its most ambitious
software project to date in February to the wailing guitar of
Carlos Santana, the company said Windows 2000 was a ``bet the
ranch'' product.
</P>
<P>
   But now, six months after the final notes of ``Smooth'' have
faded, some wonder whether the product has inspired the fervor
embodied by the launch party.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Windows 2000, the software for running corporate
computer networks and desktops, have fallen short of some analysts'
expectations. And that has left some to speculate whether the
company, known for setting off around-the-block lines for its
consumer software, will make good on its goal to elbow its way into
the high-end business market, now dominated by the likes of arch
nemesis Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says it's right on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales of Windows 2000 have met and in some cases exceeded our
expectations,'' said Jim Ewel, vice president of Microsoft's
Windows 2000 servers division.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Redmond, Wash., software titan said it had sold
about 3 million Windows 2000 licenses through June 30. While that
figure sounds impressive, it fell roughly 20 percent short of
influential Goldman Sachs analyst Rick Sherlund's benchmark for
that time period _ though Microsoft contends Sherlund was comparing
the product to Windows 95, the wildly popular consumer operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   And because Microsoft didn't disclose which licenses were for
desktop versions of the software and which were for servers that
run corporate networks _ the market Microsoft clearly is trying to
capture _ some industry watchers believe most of the licenses were
for the former.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question Microsoft has `gazillions' of units on
small machines, but their real goal is to be a player on large
machines,'' said Jeff Tarter, editor of industry newsletter
Softletter. ``If a lot of those units are desktop machines, that
doesn't buy them anything against Sun or Linux.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Microsoft and some analysts who track the company
have stressed that the successor to the NT product would take time
to catch on, since big organizations often take more time and money
to install so-called enterprise systems. Microsoft has not released
any target figures for Windows 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an enterprise product, not a departmental product,''
said Melissa Eisenstat, analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer. ``As a bigger
enterprise product, it requires a longer evaluation cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   However, some analysts suspect a certain confluence of events in
the information technology industry may be gnawing at Windows 2000
sales. First of all, some companies just lifted their Year 2000
spending freezes this summer, meaning they're just beginning to
evaluate or install Windows 2000 now.
</P>
<P>
   Second, many businesses, be they mom-and-pop operations or giant
multinationals _ are trying to ``fatten their pipes'' for
transmitting data and build Web sites for selling goods and
services online, said Laura DiDio, analyst at Giga Information
Group.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the latest operating system from Microsoft
simply isn't as sexy as e-commerce or Internet infrastructure, or
even Linux, the Unix variation that has garnered a grassroots
following by painting itself as the anti-Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the product's sheer complexity _ it represents
about 35 million lines of code _ translates into more time in the
training room for IT workers and additional ramp-up time for
third-party developers _ which means there may not be as many
Windows 2000-compatible applications on the market yet for some
tastes (Ewel said that 10,000 applications run on Windows 2000 and
that 500 are being added per month).
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft wanted to make sure that when Windows 2000 shipped,
it had a very high level of applications compatibility,'' DiDio
said. ``So they made the certification and testing requirements
more stringent for third-party developers, which is a great idea in
theory, but a lot of them are small _ they're not Oracle or Seibel
_ and it takes longer for these vendors to make sure their
applications qualify, and not all of them have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   One factor in Microsoft's favor: Many of those who have
installed the product give it high marks for reliability, speed and
cost savings.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo estimates that it will save several million dollars
in redundant, inefficient software and hardware when it finishes
shifting all of its 125,000 employees to Windows 2000 by October
2001.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, some analysts believe the product will catch
on _ famously, in fact. But with some companies just starting to
look serious at Windows 2000, it may not happen until very late
this year or early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NT 4.0 was a three-bedroom, two-bathroom house, this is
akin to packing up all your stuff and building a mansion that you
have to design, rewire and buy new furniture for,'' said DiDio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely not something people can just jump into,''
said Dustin Sauter, enterprise systems engineer at Wells Fargo.
``That would be like giving yourself a self-inflicted gunshot
wound.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not give financial analysts _ who often expect
Microsoft to see a major bump in revenues immediately following a
release _ anything to crow about in the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   But over the long haul, many do expect the product to give
Microsoft a firmer footing in the corporate marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major product,'' said IDC analyst Dan Kusnetzky.
``It's going to change the way people do things. It's just going to
take awhile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4372 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TECH21-TECH21-SFCHRON     08-28 2498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH21-TECH21-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 &HT;    TECH 21: TAKING STOCK OF INTEL'S ACTIONS (COLUMN) &HT;    By HENRY NORR
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last week, I cranked out four news stories about
Intel Corp. and the technologies and initiatives it was announcing
at the fall edition of its semiannual technical conference, the
Intel Developers Forum (IDF).
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of coverage _ probably more than The Chronicle has
given to any other tech company in years, except those in deep
trouble with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a friend of mine who suggested that the paper put an
``Intel Inside'' logo on the front, I haven't received any
complaints about the quantity of ink we devoted to the IDF, but a
couple of readers wrote in to grouse about the quality. In effect,
they suggested that I had succumbed to a snow job from the
chipmaker.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, they're right _ I  &LR; am &LR;  impressed with Intel. Of
course, I'm not alone in this _ Wall Street seems to feel the same
way. The company's shares ended last week just shy of the all-time
high they hit on Wednesday. During the past year they have nearly
doubled, and during the past five years they have grown roughly
tenfold.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I've followed the company closely since the early
1990s. At that time I worked in the Macintosh trade press, and
Apple, of course, didn't _ as it still doesn't _ use Intel
processors. But two seemingly contradictory developments persuaded
me to study up on the Santa Clara chipmaker.
</P>
<P>
   One was that the Mac, then based on Motorola 68000-family chips,
always seemed to be struggling to keep up with the latest PCs in
processing performance. The other was that Apple had joined with
IBM and Motorola to develop a new chip family called the PowerPC,
and those companies were claiming that they were about to deliver
processors with twice the performance of Intel's best _ at only
half the price.
</P>
<P>
   The new chip, they argued, would turn the industry on its head,
forever shattering the desktop dominance Intel had acquired when
IBM adopted its chips for the first PC.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this rhetoric came from marketers paid to hype the
upcoming PowerPC. More of it came from Mac zealots who made up in
enthusiasm what they lacked in knowledge. But in those years, many
genuine experts were also talking trash about Intel.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the issue was that the company's PC chips _ the
so-called x86 family, including the 386, 486 and what was soon to
become the Pentium line _ were based on a design philosophy known
as complex instruction-set computing, or CISC for short. Motorola's
68000 series was, too, but the PowerPC reflected a newer approach
called reduced instruction-set computing, or RISC.
</P>
<P>
   In essence (propeller heads please pardon the simplification),
CISC chips include circuitry specially designed to carry out some
complicated kinds of calculations _ even some that programs use
relatively rarely _ on a single command. The idea behind RISC was
to get rid of much of this specialized circuitry and concentrate on
executing basic, commonly used instructions as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   With RISC, a complex calculation would require multiple
instructions to the processor, but streamlined hardware could
perform each of them faster. The net effect was supposed to be a
sharp increase in overall performance as well as reduced costs.
</P>
<P>
   The case for RISC sounded pretty plausible, and most academic
computer scientists seemed to buy it. Most persuasively, all the
leading workstation makers _ Sun, IBM, Hewlett-Packard and others _
had moved from CISC to RISC for their high-performance products.
</P>
<P>
   But I did notice a few flies in the ointment. One was that
serious people from Intel, although very familiar with RISC _ the
company had produced several RISC designs of its own, for non-PC
applications _ were insisting that their CISC-based x86
architecture had decades of life left in it.
</P>
<P>
   The other problem was the empirical data. In general, according
to technical benchmarks, RISC chips did outperform their CISC
cousins. But over time Intel's x86 chips weren't falling any
farther behind _ when you graphed the improving performance of
successive generations, the curve was parallel to that of the RISC
processors.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1993 I raised this issue with a top technical
manager at Apple, a former professor of computer science at a
distinguished university, who had been laying out the standard case
for RISC to me. He leaned close and said, ``Yeah, but you know what
the problem is? They (Intel) aren't playing fair _ they're throwing
 &LR; too much money &LR;  at the problem!''
</P>
<P>
   I gasped. What else did he expect? What did ``fairness'' have to
do with anything? Intel's near monopoly on the desktop generated so
much revenue that, practically speaking, there were no limits on
what it could afford in R&AMP;D, and the company had every incentive to
spend whatever was necessary _ including hiring some of the
brightest engineers around _ to defend its position at the center
of the PC world.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the brilliant engineers it was hiring were busy
assimilating the lessons of RISC. To maintain compatibility with
the software that customers already had, they couldn't change the
x86 instruction set, but they adopted many other design features
common in the RISC chips _ technical tricks like
``superpipelining'' and ``out-of-order execution.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, internally, x86 chips have gradually grown more similar
to RISC processors. They just decode the complex x86 instructions
into simpler ``micro-ops'' that are roughly equivalent to RISC
instructions. That entails some extra work upfront, but once it's
done, the ``execution engines'' that do the actual data crunching
inside the chip can operate as efficiently as anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Intel has also taken advantage of its vast resources
and talents to push ahead on the manufacturing front, developing
ways to etch ever smaller and faster transistors onto its silicon.
IBM may be the technical leader here, but Intel is the champ in
terms of high-volume production. The result has been declining
costs and increasing frequencies, which translate into ever-better
performance from a given chip architecture.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, many RISC proponents refused to accept the
reality of all this. Another memorable moment in my dealings with
Apple came in 1995, when I listened to Michael Mace, then head of
the Cupertino company's competitive-analysis group, deliver a
presentation about the ``brick wall'' he argued Intel was about to
hit.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail exchange afterward I pointed out that Intel's
financial results looked a whole lot better than Apple's at that
point. He assured me that Intel's top executives would be ``out on
the street'' within a year, once the company's board realized that
they had steered it down a technical dead-end.
</P>
<P>
   I offered to bet my annual salary against his that that wouldn't
happen. Unfortunately for me, he refused to accept the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Mace, by the way, is now ``chief competitive officer'' at Palm.
For that company's sake I hope he doesn't underestimate Microsoft's
Pocket PC and other challenges as badly as he did Intel's
processors.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a few well-publicized but quickly corrected screw-ups
_ for example, the Pentium math bug, the privacy-threatening serial
number issue and some slowness in recognizing the trend toward
lower-cost PCs _ Intel ``executed,'' as the MBAs put it, almost
flawlessly through most of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years it has had more problems. This year, for
example, it badly underestimated demand, thereby opening the door
for rival Advanced Micro Devices to capture significant market
share with its own increasingly impressive x86-compatible
processors.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has also suffered a number of serious delays and even
recalls, mainly stemming from its efforts to push the PC industry
into a new style of memory called Rambus or Direct RDRAM. The
company seems to have overestimated the performance benefits of
this new technology and underestimated how much memory
manufacturers would charge for it. And when it met with determined
resistance in the marketplace, Intel whipped up a technical quick
fix _ an intermediary chip that was supposed to make it possible to
use older-style RAM with Intel products originally designed for
RDRAM _ that turned out to be so problematic the company finally
had to scrap it.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Officer Craig Barrett acknowledges that these
glitches have been embarrassing. ``I don't believe in bad luck,''
he said in a conversation last week. ``It was a series of
management failures _ we kind of dropped the ball.'' But he
insisted his team knows what to do to prevent recurrences: ``We're
just going back to the basics _ the same techniques we've relied on
in the past, like monitoring the critical paths and making sure the
key projects get the staffing they need to get done on time.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that will be sufficient, or new approaches will be
required to deal with the exponentially increasing complexity of
the products the company develops, only time will tell. Based on
the record, though, I don't think it pays to bet on Intel failing.
</P>
<P>
   But over the long haul the company confronts some larger issues.
Its bread-and-butter business, PC processors and chipsets,
continues to grow, but not at the astronomical rates of years past.
And within that arena I think Intel is bound to face an
increasingly difficult challenge in trying to persuade customers,
whether at home or in business, to keep trading up to newer and
faster processors every few years. I know I used to consider myself
a performance junkie, but I'm having a hard time justifying
replacing my 400-MHz Pentium II system.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, I'm convinced it's going to get harder to
persuade people to pay the premiums Intel has always commanded for
its top-of-the-line processors. And those chips make grossly
disproportionate contributions to Intel's margins and thus its
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, for instance, a 1-GHz Pentium III carries a wholesale
price of $990, while the 800-MHz version goes for only $294 _ even
though both are made of the same materials on the same equipment,
probably on the very same production line.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett pooh-poohed this issue when I posed it to him last week.
``For 10 years that's the most common question I've been asked,''
he said. ``It's usually reporters who are getting old who ask it.''
</P>
<P>
   Touche.
</P>
<P>
   (The gruff tone, by the way, is characteristic, but Barrett may
have been especially testy when I met him, for very understandable
reasons: He was just back from a weekend fighting the wildfires
that had already swept 5,000 acres of his 10,000-acre ranch in
Montana. He had also been dealing with firefighting officialdom
that, to hear him tell it, was ``government bureaucracy at its
worst.'')
</P>
<P>
   To the substance of my question, he said, ``The good news is
that there are younger people coming along doing MP3s, digital
video, voice recognition, and so on'' _ activities that soak up
processor cycles like they're going out of style.
</P>
<P>
   He has a point, of course, and he has the sales figures to prove
it. At least for now, Intel's biggest challenge is too much, not
too little, demand for its products.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, though, Barrett recognizes that the company has to
diversify if it is to maintain anything close to historic rates of
growth. That's why he has extended its processor line up-market,
into the lucrative server arena (with the Xeon and soon the
Itanium), and engineered the dozens of acquisitions that are making
Intel into a powerhouse in the burgeoning field of networking and
communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Here again, it remains to be seen how all these new ventures
will work out. Many of the products and services Intel has
announced in these areas are just beginning to reach the market,
and Barrett acknowledges some mistakes in assimilating its
acquisitions, mainly by ``smothering them with kindness.''
</P>
<P>
   But networking and communications are obviously the places to be
at this point, and the speed with which Barrett and his team have
been moving to get the company there is impressive.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not involved in the PC industry, there's something
else about Intel you might not know: Over the last decade the
company has gradually adopted the role of point man in pushing the
PC forward, not just by making faster processors, but also by
developing or rallying support for innovations in other parts of
the platform.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Intel-led initiatives have produced many of the key
features of today's PCs: the PCI standard for expansion cards, the
Universal Serial Bus (USB) for external peripherals and the AGP
slot for graphics cards. Others, like Serial ATA, a superfast new
interface for hard drives, and Bluetooth, a low-power radio
technology that will link up computers, peripherals and cell phones
wirelessly, will almost certainly enter the mainstream during the
next year or two. And many other such efforts are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Intel doesn't always succeed in these efforts. As I noted last
week, its attempts to promote more stylish and consumer-friendly
industrial design by funding the development of ``concept PCs''
hasn't yielded much fruit yet. Another effort, a once-promising
plan for an expansion scheme called Device Bay, has pretty much
evaporated. And in at least one area _ wireless home networking _ I
happen to think the company has been backing the wrong horse,
pushing a new standard called HomeRF instead of 802.11, a rival
technology that already works well and has wide industry support.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it do all the work by itself. In each area the company
brings together other key industry players in a working group to
set goals, hammer out standards, test for interoperability and
develop marketing materials and programs. And Microsoft, for better
or worse, plays a key role in determining whether and when these
innovations make it into the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   But the main point is that by taking leadership Intel has filled
a serious void. IBM, of course, originally defined the PC standard,
but during the course of the 1980s, as it lost market share to what
were then called ``IBM compatibles'' or ``clones,'' it lost the
clout to steer the industry in new directions. Compaq tried,
notably with its ``EISA'' card standard, but few of its jealous
rivals were willing to follow.
</P>
<P>
   The result, for a while, was technical stagnation _ or, perhaps
worse, fragmentation into multiple incompatible standards. Remember
the proliferation of video-card technologies in the early 1990s?
</P>
<P>
   Intel's leadership has gone a long way to alleviate this
problem. Of course it doesn't do it out of charity _ its goal is
plainly to sell more of its own processors, chipsets and in some
cases more specialized products. But insofar as it promotes its own
interests by making the PC more versatile and, especially, easier
to use, we're all the beneficiaries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
