<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INMATE-VISITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VISITS IN PLEXIGLAS BOOTHS PROPOSED FOR CALIF. DEATH ROW
INMATES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Death row inmates in California, who were facing
the possible end to a long-standing tradition of open-room contact
visits, might instead be visiting their relatives and friends
inside Plexiglas booths.
</P>
<P>
   Under a proposal awaiting formal approval, assorted Plexiglas
booths would be constructed for condemned inmates at San Quentin
State Prison.
</P>
<P>
   While the booths are triggering consternation and anger from
some inmates, visitors and prisoners' rights advocates, they
represent a compromise of sorts. A few months ago, San Quentin
Warden J.S. Woodford favored outright termination of all contact
visiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad that the prison now recognizes that some form of
contact visits should be reinstated,'' said Kevin Neel, a spokesman
for the San Francisco Bay Area chapter of the Campaign to End the
Death Penalty. ``But the restrictions inherent with the Plexiglas
booths are still unnecessary. There's a community feeling in the
visiting room that would be lost because everyone would be
isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact visits, which for years have taken place inside a
spartan room that functions much like a social hall _ inmates could
freely circulate among friends and family _ were suspended after a
violent outburst March 31 between two inmates, rival gang members,
in the East Block visiting room.
</P>
<P>
   The clash marked the first time in prison history that two
inmates had fought within the ``neutral territory'' of the room,
according to San Quentin spokeswoman Lt. Patricia Blanson.
</P>
<P>
   After the incident, prison officials curtailed contact visits
because of safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   California is one of only a few states permitting contact visits
for condemned prisoners deemed to be on good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Following disclosure of a proposed permanent halt to contact
visits, as well as tightened restrictions requiring appointments
and limiting the number and duration of visits, relatives and
prison rights activists unleashed a storm of protest, calling the
crackdown unduly harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, a copy of a protest petition signed by 178
condemned inmates was delivered to the San Francisco office of Gov.
Gray Davis. A new petition, protesting the Plexiglas booths, is
being circulated on death row.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Fama, a staff attorney with the Prison Law Office who has
been involved in discussions with San Quentin over the visiting
program, said that about a dozen booths are expected to be
constructed in the East Block visiting room.
</P>
<P>
   Fama said that ``a less expensive answer is for the prison to
return to the program that existed before, and more carefully
consider who they put into the waiting room at the same time. Many
inmates believe the March 31 incident was isolated and wouldn't
have happened if prison officials had kept apart the two
individuals who they had previously determined shouldn't be allowed
on the same exercise yard.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Fama, the booths are a modification of an earlier
proposal to install a U-shaped table in the East Block visiting
room _ inmates would have sat within the U while their visitors
lined the table's perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are going to build the Plexiglas booths there needs to
be improvement in terms of San Quentin's telephone system and
increasing staff to handle the calls and addressing the special
needs of those who travel long distance,'' Fama said. ``Problems
with the scheduling process threaten to undermine the entire
visiting program. I think they ought to go back to the way it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Vernell Crittendon, a San Quentin spokesman, declined to
address any specifics, including costs, of the proposed plan,
saying that approval from the California Department of Corrections
may take several more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a plan,'' he said. ``We're not going to publicly
release it. We are working to develop a safe visiting procedure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
