<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EBOOKS-EBOOKS-SFCHRON     08-28 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBOOKS-EBOOKS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 &HT;    BOOK PUBLISHERS LEARN FROM NAPSTER &HT;    By BENNY EVANGELISTA
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With the online release of his electronic
novella ``Riding the Bullet,'' scare master Stephen King has proved
the power of the printed word is the same even without the ink and
paper.
</P>
<P>
   But King's venture into the unknown realm of digital is also
helping to put a scare into the publishing industry, which sees the
rapidly developing e-book revolution as both filled with promise
and uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, book publishers want to avoid getting slashed by
an unforeseen menace like their counterparts in the music industry
discovered with digital music, MP3s and Napster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music industry let the genie out of the bottle _ letting
digital music get out before anyone anticipated that was a
problem,'' said Gene Gable, general manager of Seybold Seminars,
host of this week's major publishing industry conference.
</P>
<P>
   E-books will be the hottest topic at Seybold San Francisco 2000
as about 30,000 publishing industry representatives converge on the
city's Moscone Center to discuss how they can control and master
the digital age.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the book production process has been digital for
years, but the final product remained in print, allowing publishers
to maintain control of the distribution, Gable said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the final product also starting to come out in
electronic form, authors like King can reach their public directly
and consumers can access reading material they couldn't before,
like research material and out-of-print books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most publishers think of themselves as distribution
companies,'' Gable said. ``Now, manufacturing and distribution is
less of a part of their business than their content. In some ways,
both the opportunities and the threats get much larger. It's a
little bit scary, too, because losing control is a concern.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of companies, from well-known players such as Microsoft
and Adobe to newcomers Mightywords and Barnes and Noble-backed
IUniverse, will occupy an 11,000-square-foot ``e-Book showcase'' on
the floor of the Moscone Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a dozen firms that have some sort of service or
technology'' for digital rights management of electronic books,
said Mark Walter, editor of the Seybold Report on Internet
Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   This is a critical time for the publishing industry: Emerging
e-book platforms must maintain enough copyright protection without
making it so complicated that consumers will choose easier but
illegal methods of downloading books. That's the conundrum the
recording industry still hasn't been able to solve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing is, digital rights management is not just
protection, but for promotion,'' Walter said. ``How do publishers
sell books in a new way to new people in a way that doesn't let the
genie out?''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, digital music in formats like MP3 is still far more
popular than e-books because music is already widely available in
digital form on CDs. The publishing industry, which has basically
controlled the distribution of the printed word almost since the
invention of the Gutenberg press, had been wary of making its
content widely available in digital form.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the popularity of e-books _ novels, reference books and
other printed matter made available for reading on computers or
handheld devices designed to make the reading experience similar to
that of a print book _ has so far been limited because consumers
still prefer reading text on paper instead of on a screen.
</P>
<P>
   But King's ``Riding the Bullet,'' released only in e-book form
in March, was the first book from a best-selling author to be
released in all-digital form. His three-part serial ``The Plant,''
which premiered July 24, was also all-digital.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Riding the Bullet,'' downloaded about 400,000
times in just the first 24 hours, opened eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, big publishing houses like McGraw-Hill and Time Warner
books have their own e-book divisions. Just last week, Simon &AMP;
Shuster became the latest major publisher to get in on the act. The
company, a unit of media titan Viacom, announced plans to publish a
list of titles _ including ``Star Trek''-related books and one
about the ``Blair Witch Project'' _ in digital form.
</P>
<P>
   And Thomson Multimedia, which makes the well-known RCA consumer
electronic products, last week said it will jump into e-books with
an RCA-brand device. The RCA REB1100, which will have a 51/2-inch
touch-screen display, will use technology developed by Rocket
E-Books, the Bay Area company bought by Gemstar-TV Guide
International Inc. earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's Adobe, with its widely distributed Acrobat software,
and Microsoft, which recently introduced its Windows Book Reader
software for personal computers, are jostling to make their
software the dominant e-book reader platform in another potential
Microsoft-versus-Netscape battle, Walter said. Both software
companies are expected to make important e-book announcements this
week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   An often-quoted study by Andersen Consulting said the demand for
e-books will grow to $2.3 billion in the United States by 2005,
representing a significant new revenue stream for the $24 billion
U.S. book industry.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of EBOOKS28 (20066 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  But a Seybold study to be released today shows publishing
industry insiders have a slightly more skeptical view of e-books
than the Andersen study suggests.
</P>
<P>
   A random sample of Seybold seminar attendees in Boston and San
Francisco during the past year found only 11 percent believed print
books, newspapers and magazines will be replaced by electronic
print in the next 20 years. And only 33 percent of those who
already tried using an e-book reading device said they would buy
and read a book on a computer or handheld device.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also indicated that the Seybold attendees who were
e-book users did not want leisure reading material like a horror
story, but that 64 percent wanted to use computers to read
reference books, maps and travel guides.
</P>
<P>
   Seybold's Walter said that while recreational books are now
grabbing the headlines, reference books and text books figure to
generate more revenues in the short term. Publishing houses that
now edit and lay out books digitally are experimenting with using
the same process to create custom printed books.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, a college professor can compile the best
chapters from five different text books and have then printed into
one custom textbook for his students.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe Chief Executive Officer John Warnock says he believes
``print on demand'' e-books will outpace the sale of e-books
downloaded into ``cute'' book-reading devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see if any of these devices takes off,'' Warnock said.
``But I don't think that's the compelling part of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   E-books may be still in their infancy, but they could grow up
quickly, Gable said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people say `I love books' (that) they're never going
to replace the feeling of a real book,'' Gable said. ``But when you
start to think about the kids now using the Internet, they're not
going to have that romantic attachment to the printed word as we
had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1603EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4377 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GENOME-GENOME-SFCHRON     08-28 1956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-GENOME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 &HT;    SEEING GREEN IN GENES &HT;    By TOM ABATE
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Now that the map of the human genome is nearly
complete, investors are wondering how to profit from the knowledge
locked in the double strands of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the various companies involved in genomics _
the study of how genes influence health and disease _ have taken
different paths toward the pot of gold at the end of the double
helix.
</P>
<P>
   One group, including Incyte Genomics of Palo Alto and
DoubleTwist Inc. of Oakland, aspires to be information brokers,
selling genetic data to pharmaceutical and biotechnology firms,
which pay millions for clues that might speed the development of
billion-dollar drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A second group of genomics players, including Neomorphic Inc. of
Berkeley and Hyseq Inc. of Sunnyvale, has decided to get into the
drug business, using their understanding of genes to find and
develop promising potential drugs.
</P>
<P>
   This clash of business plans is echoed on the national stage.
Celera Genomics, the Maryland company that was first to sequence
the human genome, has adopted the info broker model. Its neighbor
and rival, Human Genome Sciences, has taken the drug development
route, as has Millennium Pharmaceuticals of Massachusetts, another
genomics leader.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to predict which of these firms will succeed, or
which business model will win. But the stories of these San
Francisco Bay Area genomics players provide a microcosm of the $1.5
billion gene-research industry that is widely expected to change
the way drugs get developed.
</P>
<P>
   INCYTE
</P>
<P>
   Genomics wasn't even a common term, much less an industry, back
in 1991 when Roy Whitfield and Randy Scott founded Incyte. During
the 1990s, Incyte helped pioneer modern gene discovery techniques,
which rely on sophisticated instruments to extract DNA from cells
and then figure out how DNA's chemical code makes the body work.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Incyte has amassed information about thousands of
specific genes that seem to be involved in cancer, heart disease
and other medical conditions. It has already received patents on
hundreds of genes or gene fragments, and has thousands more
applications pending before the patent office.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen of the world's 20 largest drug companies pay Incyte
millions of dollars annually to mine this huge repository of
proprietary gene data for hints about how they can fashion new
drugs that might switch bad genes off or turn good genes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first espoused the principle of selling a database of
information in the biological field, people called us nuts,'' said
Incyte chief executive Whitfield, who presides over a company with
1,300 employees and projected revenues of more than $190 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biotech world was wedded to the notion that the only way
you made money was by putting drugs into clinical trials, or doing
the early discovery and licensing them off,'' said Whitfield, who
likens early-stage drug development to ``putting money in the slot
machines at Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   But Whitfield has plunked plenty of quarters into his
drug-discovery factory in Palo Alto, where the machines run
round-the-clock, threshing DNA samples for potential gene patents.
Incyte, which was profitable in 1997 and 1998, has been losing
money ever since it made huge investments in gene-discovery
equipment to build its database of patented genes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Oakland, Incyte faces competition in this
data-for-sale business from an upstart that hasn't spent a penny of
its own on gene discovery.
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLETWIST
</P>
<P>
   Privately held DoubleTwist is a reincarnation of Pangea Systems,
which was founded in the early 1990s to write software to analyze
biological data. Pangea sputtered along on venture capital _ the
record shows at least two cash infusions totaling $25 million by
1999 _ until earlier this year when new chief executive John Couch
pulled off a remarkable transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Couch focused the company's software tools on the biggest set of
free genetic data on the planet _ the information being generated
by the Human Genome Project.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years, this government-funded effort has been posting
genetic data on the Internet. But this raw data, though free, is
not easy to sift through. Nor is this data cross-linked with other
sources that might be useful to drug researchers _ such as patent
libraries showing whether a gene of interest is controlled by a
rival.
</P>
<P>
   In this genetic babel, Couch saw an opportunity to become the
Yahoo of the genome, creating an Internet portal that didn't need
to create any new gene discoveries. Rather, his goal was to polish
the free data to make it more useable, and then to license and
resell proprietary data provided by niche companies that could
never hope to match Incyte alone.
</P>
<P>
   With this vision in mind _ and an additional $45 million in
investment capital _ Couch rechristened the company as DoubleTwist
earlier this year. Unlike Yahoo, however, DoubleTwist appeals to
such a narrow audience of people in lab coats that advertising
support is minimal. Therefore DoubleTwist hopes to make money by
selling annual subscriptions, ranging from $5,000 to $5 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 15,000 registered users already,'' said Couch, who
declined to say how many were paying and how many were freebies.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Bay in Palo Alto, Incyte's Whitfield views tiny
DoubleTwist _ it has a staff of about 170 _ with disdain. ``They're
competing on the basis of tools to view and manipulate the data,''
he said. ``They have no content of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   DoubleTwist argues that its growing network of data sources will
ultimately pull together a more-useful array of information than
Incyte's gene discovery factory can produce on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can be the best at everything,'' said Rob Williamson,
DoubleTwist's second in command. ``We're going to aggregate the
best-of-breed (genomic data sources) from across the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   NEOMORPHIC
</P>
<P>
   While Incyte and DoubleTwist vie to be a one-stop-shop for
genetic data, Berkeley's Neomorphic Inc. is trying to evolve from
the software world into an early-stage drug-discovery company.
</P>
<P>
   Neomorphic was founded in 1997 by three University of California
graduate students who had written software to analyze fruit fly
genes. It turned out that drugmakers like SmithKline Beecham and
Novartis were willing to pay up to $500,000 for their programs,
which analyzed human genes as well as those of fruit flies.
</P>
<P>
   With orders in hand, the three students _ Cyrus Harmon and Gregg
Helt of UC Berkeley and David Kulp of UC Santa Cruz _ bootstrapped
Neomorphic. After running their 40-person private firm in the
black, and without venture capital, they decided this year to use
their own software to mine gene data for clues about creating new
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (software development) was a great business, but it's a
small business,'' said Harmon, Neomorphic's chief executive. ``The
real money comes from creating drugs and diagnostic tests.''
</P>
<P>
   To fund its drug discovery dreams, Neomorphic got $2.5 million
in outside financing earlier this year, and plans to seek an
additional $15 million or so. The money will help move the company
out of its proletarian warehouse offices in West Berkeley into the
sort of stainless steel facility they will need to do laboratory
work for early-stage drug discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The young entrepreneurs _ at 33, Helt is the trio's ``old man''
_ say they are helping invent the genetic tools that will change
the way drug discovery is done.
</P>
<P>
   It boils down to a single word: targets. All drugs target some
bodily process. When the drug hits its target it triggers a domino
effect; angina pills, for instance, dilate the arteries, which ease
blood flow, which relieves heart pain.
</P>
<P>
   During the last 100 years, beginning with the discovery of
aspirin in 1899, drug discovery has been a hit-and-miss process
that owed a great deal to serendipity _ some scientist noticing
that a chemical thrown into a batch of sick cells seemed to do some
good.
</P>
<P>
   And during that same 100 years, according to Bert Spilker, vice
president for science at the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturer's Association in Washington, D.C., all of
pharmaceutical research has discovered about 500 targets.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the human genome data coming into focus, drug
discoverers have, for the first time, bits and pieces of the master
blueprint for how the body works. That blueprint, said Spilker,
probably contains 10,000 new drug targets _ a twentyfold increase
over all the targets identified since aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why there's this excitement about genomics,'' Spilker
said. ``With all these new targets, drug researchers are bound to
discover new drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Neomorphic view, therefore, it doesn't matter that it's a
company of fresh-faced kids _ because gene analysis is such a new
field that most drug and biotech firms don't have the expertise to
simply buy data from DoubleTwist or Incyte, and find those 10,000
putative drug targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will partner exclusively with drug companies to do their
target research,'' said Neomorphic's Harmon, who envisions signing
a series of multimillion-dollar collaborations with drugmakers.
</P>
<P>
   HYSEQ
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the young turks at Neomorphic, across the bay in
Sunnyvale, one of the patriarchs of biotechnology hopes to lead
Hyseq Inc. into the promised land of genomic-based drug
development.
</P>
<P>
   George Rathmann, 72, took over Hyseq earlier this year, in what
could be the last hurrah of a long career that includes being a
founder of biotech giant Amgen.
</P>
<P>
   Hyseq is a curious contender in the genomics game. It was
founded in the early 1990s around a technology that proved useful
in identifying rare genes. Led by patent attorney Lewis Gruber,
Hyseq went public in 1997 and competed with Incyte, Celera, Human
Genome Sciences and Millennium Pharmaceuticals in the race to
discover and patent genes.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, however, the Hyseq technology, while more
sensitive perhaps at detecting rare genes, wasn't as fast as the
process used by its competitors. As it became obvious that Hyseq
didn't have the critical mass of proprietary data to compete with
the other gene-discovery contestants, Rathmann decided to turn the
company into a drug developer _ figuring Hyseq's technology had
discovered some rare and useful genes the company's swifter rivals
might have missed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Rathmann faces a series of tough tasks. Hyseq has filed
thousands of patent applications, but so far none has been granted.
From among that pile of potential discoveries he must pick a
handful of gene targets and start lab tests to see if any of them
respond to possible drugs. Since such experiments are costly, he
must persuade a drug company to help him co-develop these
compounds. And in his spare time he must go back to Wall Street for
money because Hyseq needs more cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to undergo a metamorphosis,'' says Rathmann, with the
calm assurance of one who has been there and done that.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who want to bet on any of these pioneers have got to
be ready to accept the risks inherent in doing business at the
frontiers of biotechnology. Ultimately, the main premise of
genomics is probably sound, that new gene knowledge will provide
the maps that point to new drug targets, and the profits that lay
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, said Neomorphic's Harmon, is that no one can really
say for sure which of the various genomics companies will hit pay
dirt in the next two or three years _ the time horizon of many
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you look back 20 years from now, you know the change
will be historic,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
