By LEAH GARCHIK 
Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HOW THE TEN GOT SO PRETTY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The beautification of  &UR; Alexander Hamilton &LR; , as he appears on the
new $10 bill, is grist for the mill of Allure, a magazine that
focuses on the looks of people.
</P>
<P>
   Engraver  &UR; Kenneth Kipperman  &LR; of the Bureau of Engraving and
Printing was responsible for the new face, which he told the
magazine is ``99 and nine-tenths'' true to a portrait of Hamilton
that he used for reference. That other tenth:
</P>
<P>
   ``I did take some artistic liberties,'' he said, including a
chin reduction. ``I didn't want it to look like  &UR; Jay Leno &LR; 's.''
Kipperman also did a minor makeover on Hamilton's hair, which in
the portrait ``reminded me of ice cream and the Lollipop Guild kids
from `The Wizard of Oz.' I knew if I interpreted it the way I saw
it, it would be too comical.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Meanwhile, thanks to all the little guys who go that extra
mile to help out women in need. ``Soon it won't be necessary to
wait for the results of an allergy test to get collagen
injections,'' Allure reports. ``By early next year, the McGhan
Medical Corp. is expected to apply for FDA approval to market
collagen that's been produced from an unusual human source: the
donated foreskin tissue of a healthy newborn.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Honor roll: The Port Authority of New York will place a
larger-than-life statue of  &UR; Jackie Gleason &LR; , who played a bus
driver in ``The Honeymooners,'' in front of its bus terminal in
Manhattan. The work, commissioned by TV Land, a cable channel that
shows the series, shows Gleason in a bus driver's uniform, holding
a lunch box. Furthermore, the city of Gdansk, Poland, has made
 &UR; Margaret Thatcher &LR;  and  &UR; Ronald Reagan &LR;  honorary citizens for their
``historical role in dismantling the Iron Curtain.''
</P>
<P>
   -In Leipers Fork, Tenn.,  &UR; Wynonna Judd &LR;  had a garage sale over
the weekend, unloading costumes, shoes, books, furniture, Christmas
decorations, household appliances and memorabilia. ``She knows a
lot of neighbors might want some of the stuff,'' said her
spokeswoman,  &UR; Kerry Hansen &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - O.J. Simpson &LR; 's children started school last week in Coral
Gables, near Miami. The assistant director of the Gulliver Schools,
where they are enrolled, told the Miami Herald that school
officials do not know where the children live, as they use a
friend's address for mail and will be driven to school by another
friend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - John McEnroe  &LR; tells the New Yorker this week that ``any good
male college player'' could beat either  &UR; Venus &LR;  or  &UR; Serena &LR; 
 &UR; Williams &LR; , ``and so could any man on the senior tour.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CURRENT ERA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Perusing a Cyber Youth Ministry chat room,  &UR; Marc Krizack &LR;  got
a history lesson from a correspondent describing the earth ``in the
beginning,'' when ``God created the heaven and the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time while billions of years could have passed,''
said the chatter, ``when scientists and evolutionists theorize the
Ice Age, Smithsonian, Jurassic era, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   - IBM measured the Q-rating _ a test of public popularity _ of
its chess-playing Big Blue supercomputer, and found it equal to
that of  &UR; Carmen Electra &LR;  and the Teletubbies.
</P>
<P>
   - Women in search of dewier legs might like Hanes' new opaque
tights impregnated with moisturizing beads, which Self magazine
says will last through five washings. The number of women fretting
about dry legs isn't great, but the new stockings will meet the
needs of bank robbers with chapped lips.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAW AND ORDER  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A Groveland police log entry cited in the Union Democrat of
Sonora and forwarded to Personals by &UR; Rob Irwin &LR;  describes the
plight of a resident who reported that her garbage can had been
stolen. ``The can was returned but half her garbage is missing.''
</P>
<P>
   And what was that motorcycle cop from the ``Twin Cities'' of
Corte Madera and Larkspur doing taking his official vehicle to
lunch with a pack of biker friends in a Guerneville bar last
Sunday? The spy who saw him says it's true that he could have been
on a legitimate lunch break, but he definitely broke the law by
making a U-turn to the bar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are very cynical with actors trying to tell
them what to believe in, or lobbying for any kind of changing of
government policy. ... There's just something annoying about having
Charlie Sheen tell me, `It's your responsibility to vote,' in an
admonishing way on MTV.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Janeane Garofalo &LR; , who plays Abbie Hoffman's wife in ``Steal
This Movie!,'' in Mother Jones magazine.
</P>
