A4383 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-PRAYER-LAWSUIT-TEX     08-28 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAYER-LAWSUIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS OF TEXAS COASTAL TOWN WORK TO COUNTER BIGOTED IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ART CHAPMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, Texas _ The once quiet, rural towns that line Texas 6
from Sugar Land to Galveston are now swollen with suburban
commuters who have brought social and cultural change to this Gulf
Coast region.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Fe, the changes have been profound. The community is no
longer virtually all Anglo, all Protestant, or all alone.
</P>
<P>
   The town of 10,000 residents, nestled southeast of Houston and
close to Galveston, was recently at the center of a U.S. Supreme
Court case banning official prayers at high school football games.
In the 1970s, Santa Fe was the site of a Ku Klux Klan rally that
some residents say still tarnishes the town.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the school district is facing a multimillion-dollar lawsuit
filed by a Jewish family who says that, two years ago, their son
was the target of anti-Semitic slurs.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, who was 11 at the time, was circled by other students
who shouted, ``Hitler missed one,'' ``No more Jews,'' and ``Heil
Hitler,'' according to the suit filed this summer.
</P>
<P>
   It also says that students drew a swastika on the boy's books
and called him a ``dirty Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   The family has moved, but the publicity from the lawsuit was
rapid and widespread, and the city quickly reacted by hoisting two
large billboards along Texas 6 that proclaim Santa Fe a place
unsuited for hate. A place where biases will not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   But many residents say that hatred was never an issue here. It
was simple ignorance, they say. Ignorance of other cultures, other
religions and other races.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe, incorporated in 1978, was always an overwhelmingly
Anglo town, a Protestant town, they say, and when change came, the
attitudes remained unaltered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those (southern suburbs) are the areas that are undergoing
rather rapid cultural and social change, and that change
understandably can generate that feeling of `let's hold on to what
we've always had,''' said William Martin, a sociologist and
professor of religion and public policy at Rice University.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Cardella, who owns a car lot directly beneath one of the
town's new billboards, said that Santa Fe is still a provincial
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tight community,'' Cardella said. ``People don't
like change here. They look at the crime rate _ and there isn't one
_ and they worry things will change. I'm sure there is some racism
here, but I don't think there is any more here than anywhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe doesn't look different from other towns along the
highway. It is flat and hot and marked with endless strip shopping
centers. There are franchised fast-food restaurants, but local
cafes still draw the pickups and cattle trailers.
</P>
<P>
   The largest building is the new high school on the north end of
town, along the four-lane highway.
</P>
<P>
   Down at Tibaldo's Feed and Supply on Texas 6, Daryn Hinze said
that Santa Fe's demographics are changing but that some of the old
sentiments still linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I grew up here, it wasn't anything but rice fields and
cow pastures,'' the 25-year-old said. ``Everybody knew everyone
else and knew their families. There weren't any minorities going to
the high school when I was there, and I think there probably aren't
more than two or three now.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the school district's approximately 4,360 students in the
1998-99 school year, about 89 percent were Anglo and 10 percent
were Hispanic, according to the Texas Education Agency. Those
demographics were almost unchanged from four years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Hinze laments that Santa Fe isn't the rural community it used to
be, the kind of town that prides itself on the county fair or
ribbons won at the livestock shows. But he understands the changes
that have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot more new neighborhoods around town now,'' he
said. ``We have a lot of commuters living here, and they didn't
grow up like we did.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a good deal of misunderstanding in the community, he
said. Today's students aren't being taught how to deal with people
of different cultures and races, but there isn't any real hatred,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all this publicity _ the sign and everything _ has to
do with our reputation. People talk about the KKK here, and they
hear about the lawsuit and put the two together.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have that earlier reputation, this deal with the
Jewish boy would just be considered an isolated incident,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Cominsky, regional director for the Anti-Defamation
League, tends to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure Santa Fe is a hotbed of anti-Semitism,'' he said.
``I think the town and the school district were simply
underprepared for their changing demographics.''
</P>
<P>
   Cominsky and the league came to the city with the idea for the
new billboards. Cominsky said that he met with city, school and
Chamber of Commerce officials and that they all agreed that Santa
Fe needed to send a message.
</P>
<P>
   They decided to work together to promote diversity and to change
the town's image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the 1970s, there were problems all along the Gulf
Coast area concerning the Vietnamese fishermen,'' Cominsky
recalled. ``And reputedly there was a meeting of the KKK here in
Santa Fe. But only a few people showed up, and none of the people
who came were from Santa Fe. But it gave the perception that the
community was hateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Cominsky also said that, according to popular folklore, a sign
once stood at the town's city limits warning African-Americans that
they couldn't stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one actually remembers seeing that sign. There are no
pictures of that sign. There is no record of it ever being there.
It is only a perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we wanted to do these billboards. It is not a
perception that the town doesn't want hatred here. It is a reality.
The signs exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Cominsky said the Santa Fe Police Department, the school
district and the city government have all agreed to increase
diversity training.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Christian community,'' he said. ``There is not an
ingrained hatred here. We, the ADL, have a strong relationship with
a community that could have said, `Go away,' and they haven't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the groundwork has been laid, and I would give the
town a pretty positive view.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice University's Martin said he also doubts that Santa Fe is a
town filled with anger or hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would suspect a large number of people there are deeply
embarrassed and personally troubled about the anti-Semitic
incident. And I think it could bring about efforts to educate
children better.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that, while growing up, he often heard people say things
like, ``Jewing people down.'' Most of them didn't realize ``Jew''
was a noun instead of a verb.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were thoughtless, but not really anti-Semitic. But they
were reflecting an anti-Semitic ethos somewhere in their
background. They have to be taught not to do that. They're trying
in Santa Fe.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX
</P>
<P>
   The Gulf, Colorado and Santa Fe Railway was built through the
area in 1877, but the community of Santa Fe grew slowly. It was not
incorporated until January 1978. By the 1980s, it had absorbed the
towns of Arcadia and Alta Loma. The 1990 census reported a
population of 8,429, of whom more than 90 percent were Anglo and 8
percent Hispanic. 2000 Census data are being compiled.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Handbook of Texas/U.S. Census
</P>
<P>
   _
