<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA DEREGULATION WOES MAY COME TO TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By R.A. DYER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In sun-drenched San Diego _ the first American
city to feel the full wallop of electric deregulation _ light bills
climbed so high that even school districts won't pay them.
</P>
<P>
   Should Texans, whose state lawmakers passed a deregulation law,
be concerned? Does calamity in California foreshadow tough times in
Texas?
</P>
<P>
   Under deregulation, the state government relinquishes much of
its control over the power system to the free market. Experts are
divided on the effect, but some say that hardship is a real
possibility. At the very least, consumer advocates predict that
Texans should prepare themselves for a bumpy ride.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Steve Wolens, D-Dallas, co-architect of the Texas
deregulation law, was vacationing in San Diego this month when he
read accounts of residents seeing two- and threefold price
increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked when I picked up the newspaper,'' said Wolens,
who recalled telling himself: ```Holy smokes! I hope that this
won't happen to us.'''
</P>
<P>
   On reflection, Wolens says he's convinced that a deregulated
Texas will learn from California's costly missteps.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, administrators with the city's 141,000-student
school district were stunned by a nearly 200-percent increase. They
joined a growing boycott of San Diego Gas &AMP; Electric and paid this
month's bill at last year's rates.
</P>
<P>
   Some businesses responded by increasing prices, reducing
operating hours, or both. The elderly, the poor and anyone else who
pays for electricity and lives on a fixed income have felt the
pinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My measure for success _ in the medium-term and the long-term
_ is whether customers are paying less under deregulation,'' said
Richard Rosen, executive vice president of the Tellus Institute, a
Boston-based, nonprofit research organization that advises
government utility commissions and consumer advocates. ``I
personally predict failure. I see problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolens ushered his bill through the Texas House with Republican
lawmakers, supported by an unlikely coalition of environmentalists,
utility representatives and union leaders. With the very notable
exception of major consumer organizations, a wide range of groups
supported the law.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Wolens' success was much like that of his
California counterpart, state Sen. Steve Peace, who pushed through
deregulation without a single no vote.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Peace, witnessing the unfolding chaos in San Diego and
the prospect of rolling blackouts elsewhere, called upon California
Gov. Gray Davis to intervene. He also urged utility customers to
withhold payments for a month. It had become that bad.
</P>
<P>
   Wolens ultimately concluded that the California problems could
not happen in Texas. Like state Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, who
co-authored the bill, and Public Utility Commission Chairman Pat
Wood III, Wolens argues that the Texas law is different.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged California's grief but said it stems from
defective legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``California rushed their law so much,'' Wolens said. ``Before
we passed our bills, we went to California ... and we all got back
persuaded that we would not pass a restructuring bill in Texas. We
thought that we don't want that. California demonstrated what we
didn't want.''
</P>
<P>
   After further study trips to Britain, Pennsylvania and
elsewhere, lawmakers here became convinced that Texas could
successfully deregulate. In theory, market forces would drive down
prices and newly formed retailers would compete for customers.
</P>
<P>
   The result, according to Wolens, Sibley, Wood and other
supporters: better deals for consumers, improved service, cheaper
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   A study issued Aug. 1 by the California Public Utilities
Commission pinpointed flaws in that state's newly deregulated power
system.
</P>
<P>
   Power wholesalers, it said, engaged in dysfunctional bidding
behavior. An organization overseeing the state's power grid did not
sufficiently represent the interests of the region's economy or
consumers. And the deregulation law simply gave away too much state
control.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area blackouts, the run-up in prices in the wholesale
electricity markets and the rise in retail electricity prices in
San Diego show that the new system is not working in California,
the report states.
</P>
<P>
   Californians will pay billions more for electricity because of
tight supply and serious market defects, it said. And higher prices
don't necessarily fund expanded generating capacity but may be
pocketed as profits, it warned.
</P>
<P>
   Something like this could happen here, says Janee Briesemeister,
an Austin-based analyst with Consumers Union. She contends that
Texas _ with its rapidly growing economy and sweltering summer heat
_ is not that different from California.
</P>
<P>
   Like Californians, she says, Texas consumers only have minority
representation on the nonprofit panel overseeing the state power
grid. And as with California, she said, the potential for
dysfunctional bidding in the wholesale market remains high.
</P>
<P>
   Like most industries, electric utilities deal with wholesale and
retail markets. Under deregulation, electric retailers would
purchase wholesale electricity from power generators, then send
that energy to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Texas does not face the energy shortfall now
confronting California, Briesemeister said demand pressures and the
structure of the Texas market can nonetheless lead to dramatically
inflated prices.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   As an example, she cites the shortage of transmission lines from
Fort Worth-Dallas to other parts of Texas. Unable to bring in
wholesale energy from outside, a Metroplex electric retailer may
have no choice but to buy wholesale power from a major generator,
such as TXU. Under such a scenario, Briesemeister said, limited
transmission lines would lock out potential wholesale suppliers _
and could give one company at least partial monopoly control in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   So what if someone in Laredo is willing to sell you power
cheaper? Briesemeister says. If you can't get the power , it
doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Unforeseen outages caused by natural disasters could further
tighten power supplies, thereby eroding competition, Briesemeister
said.
</P>
<P>
   TXU spokesman Christopher K. Schein acknowledged the
anti-competitive effects of transmission and power supply
shortages.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of companies, including TXU Electric, have identified
where the new lines need to be built, Schein said. Texas, he said,
is already in the process of permitting and building much of that.
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern are new state environmental rules that
require the utility to make steep cuts in power plant emissions,
Schein said. The rules could restrict energy supplies in the
Metroplex, making deregulation more difficult, the utility
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Are there external factors that can change the carefully laid
groundwork? The answer is 'yes,' Schien said.
</P>
<P>
   Severin Borenstein, director of the Energy Institute at the
University of California, also foresees Texas experiencing many of
his state's problems. His views are based on a few hard and fast
facts about electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of deregulation insist that electricity will be like
any other commodity, with market forces pushing down prices while
weeding out bad competitors. But Borenstein notes differences
between electricity and other commodities.
</P>
<P>
   First off, no economical way to store electricity exists.
Secondly, small shortfalls can have grave consequences, such as
giant blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   So even if one firm has only of the generating capacity, they'll
know the system needs them in the market or the whole grid will
collapse, Borenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, they can charge anything they want.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen, the regulatory consultant, raises other concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old system, regulators set electric prices that
compensate power producers for expenses, plus some moderate profit.
</P>
<P>
   With the new system, however, market competition sets prices.
This means that even cheaply produced power from, say, old
coal-fired plants, directly benefits from higher market prices even
though its production costs might not rise, Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, a temporary rate freeze has protected consumers from
instability in the wholesale market. Under the deregulation law,
residential rates remain frozen until 2002, and then drop by 6
percent for five years or until the major utilities lose 40 percent
of their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen notes that other states have created similar default
pricing as part of their deregulation laws _ and in most cases,
those defaults are the only thing between consumers and high bills.
</P>
<P>
   When the default rate was lifted in San Diego, prices went
through the roof. And when it expires in Texas, he said, it could
get so bad that the whole thing blows up.
</P>
<P>
   But Wood, the PUC chairman, said Texas electric consumers have
little reason to fear the future. Much of California's problems, he
says, are simply the result of a shortage of power.
</P>
<P>
   Power plant construction has not kept pace with a vibrant
economy _ no major plant has been built in California in a decade.
So on hot summer days, the Golden State comes perilously close to
blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Electric wholesalers can charge well beyond
production costs and remain confident that their power will sell.
But Wood, speaking in his trademark Port Arthur drawl, said, That
won't happen here.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Texas have more reserve generating capacity than
California, but more plants are coming online soon. Likewise, it
takes only two to three years to permit and build a plant in Texas
_ as compared to five to seven in California.
</P>
<P>
   Texas also limits utilities to no more than 20 percent of the
market when competition begins in 2002. This provision _
characterized by Wood as a key difference between Texas and
California law _ should also encourage competition.
</P>
<P>
   And Texas consumers have an escape hatch _ one last legislative
session, which opens in January 2001, before retail electric
competition starts 12 months later.
</P>
<P>
   We've been watching California closely, to make sure we don't
make the same mistakes, Wood said. I know it will work out. And
even if it doesn't, allows for customers to be held harmless and
for the Legislature to put Humpty-Dumpty back together again.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1623EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4396 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-DIRECTORY-ASSISTANCE-     08-28 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTORY-ASSISTANCE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: same thing.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wireless phone industry, meanwhile, operates under its own
system. A wireless subscriber who dials 411 is generally connected
to a directory assistance operator affiliated with his wireless
carrier. Those operators generally use a national database.
</P>
<P>
   But no one disputes that the quality of directory assistance
service varies from provider to provider.
</P>
<P>
   The listings themselves are generally compiled and controlled by
the roughly 1,300 individual local phone companies around the
country. Big carriers like AT&AMP;T and Verizon contract with outside
companies to pull together phone listings from the multitude of
local phone databases around the nation. To save money, other,
smaller companies may sometimes try to compile listings by scanning
phone books, property records or other sources that are less likely
to be up to date and reliable.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, big phone companies say that directory assistance
listings are about 95 percent accurate. But if there are, as is
estimated, 3 billion directory assistance calls in a year (the
actual figure may be higher), that adds up to 150 million wrong
numbers annually.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Louis S. Richman is restive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a really annoying aggravation that when you call
for the headquarters number for a major corporation that you get
some branch office delivery dock,'' said Richman, finance editor of
Consumer Reports magazine, in New York. ``Or you call for a major
hospital in a major city and they never heard of it, or a
restaurant that you knew was there a week ago but they can no
longer find it or you get a fax number.''
</P>
<P>
   It may help if callers understand that there are gazetteering
limitations with today's patchwork directory assistance. And the
limitations begin with four words: United States Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone listings are almost always governed by the post office
address of the residence or business listed. Take Brighton, the
town in upstate New York supervised by Frankel. A letter to her
town must be addressed to Rochester; the Postal Service does not
recognize Brighton as an official mailing location. Given this, and
the fact that there is another community in New York known as
Brighton, near Buffalo, it is understandable that a directory
assistance operator in Omaha, Neb., or elsewhere may become a bit
confused.
</P>
<P>
   But the Postal Service rationale carries little weight with
Frankel. ``I would think that the telephone directory services are
something that should be upgraded,'' she said. ``The technology is
there to do it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It may depend on which company is wielding the technology.
Although the main local phone company for most of New York state is
Verizon, the local phone company for the Brighton that is near
Rochester, and for Rochester itself, is Frontier.
</P>
<P>
   In an unscientific test conducted from phones in Manhattan,
directory assistance operators for AT&AMP;T and Verizon were routinely
able to find numbers in Brighton for the Twelve Corners Apothecary,
the Bagel Bin Cafe and Frankel's two home numbers. In most cases,
though, the operator would note that the listing was in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   And in a second unscientific test, directory assistance calls
placed from Rochester and within Brighton, also succeeded without
exception in finding those same numbers. The volunteer tester,
Jennifer Leonard, president of the Rochester Area Community
Foundation, a charitable group, called various directory assistance
services to obtain the listings for the apothecary and Frankel's
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, who lives in Brighton, called a Frontier operator from
her office in Rochester, a Frontier operator from a pay phone in
Brighton, an operator affiliated with her local phone company, Time
Warner Communications, and a Verizon operator from her wireless
phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the operators were located in Rochester and all of them
had both numbers and had no problem with the location of Brighton,
N.Y.,'' Leonard reported.
</P>
<P>
   Whether directory assistance in Brighton is as truly bad as
Frankel has found it, or as reasonably good as this informal test
might indicate, it is certain that there are many more paths than
there used to be to that tantalizingly helpful operator's greeting,
``What listing?''
</P>
<P>
   With all the variables, it may be that the best hope for a
caller _ besides keeping those keypad fingers crossed _ is to be
very, very precise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most cases you can find the one you're looking for,'' said
Agerton at BellSouth, which handles more than 500 million directory
assistance calls a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what happens a lot of the time,'' Agerton said, ``is
someone calls and says, `I want Bill Smith in Roanoke, Va.' And so
you pull it up and there's Bill Smith, so you put them through. But
then they call back and in fact they wanted William T. Smith on
Lovers' Lane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
