<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4397 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-THESTREETCOM-RALLY-NY     08-28 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THESTREETCOM-RALLY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY I EXPECT THE MARKETS TO RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from TheStreet.com, the
premier business/finance Web site, is available from the New York
Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By JAMES J. CRAMER  
 c.2000 TheStreet.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each day I come to work and I try to hide my bullishness.
Sometimes I am simply embarrassed about it. Things just can't be
this good, I say to myself. Other times I simply say, we don't need
to play. We are having a good year, why press the issue?
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the end, I come back to the fundamental tenets that a
ton of things are going right, and more could go right.
</P>
<P>
   So let's examine the bull case, by giving it a thorough
going-over, and explaining what makes me think that the opportunity
is up, not down, despite all of the warning signs of complacency
and lack of worry and stress.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST, the game of money management is a simple game. It's all
about beating the averages and making a lot of money. Some very
large funds this year aren't doing either. Note the clock is
ticking. Unless they get a selloff soon, they won't be able to go
into the fourth quarter saying anything good about themselves. This
money-management business has become extremely competitive as
individuals realize that they don't have to stay with the managers
that they picked if they aren't generating any performance.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be more specific. How much longer can Fidelity Contrafund,
for example, a multibillion-dollar fund, stay in the doldrums? (I
own shares in this fund, and I have for a long time.) At what point
do they say ``The heck with it, get me some winners, I have to make
some money here or be in a state of perpetual redemption and
withdrawal''? This giant pool of capital is a prime candidate to
jump into Nortel, Sun Microsystems and Intel in a very big way.
</P>
<P>
   The fund may already have large positions in these stocks. I
only have about $100,000 in the fund so I am not entitled to know
what is in it. But I figure Contra is going to step up in a much
bigger way than it already is in these fiber-optic/fiber-channel
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   What makes me think this will happen? Because it happens every
year. Because this is the crummy business we money managers have
chosen. Take last year at this time. Right about now the folks at
Soros realized they had nothing to say for themselves in a year of
otherwise solid performance for the competition. So they loaded the
boat up with the Qualcomms and Veritas' of the world and generated
mucho performance. It was a brilliant move and they won the derby!
They gave themselves super performance.
</P>
<P>
   So, the first rule of money management: when in doubt, buy and
buy like there is no tomorrow, will certainly play a big role in
taking the stock market, particularly the winners, higher.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND, we like the way tech is shaping up for the fourth
quarter. Sure we had that overabundance of handsets in the system,
but that will clear up. And yes, maybe we had too many chips that
were being made for too few handheld devices. But the overall tone
of the personal computer market is healthier than it has been in a
long time and these stocks and their cohort aren't that expensive.
It makes me want to plunge in with both feet.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Cisco hasn't acted that well. And yes, Microsoft has
melted under federal scrutiny and soft Windows 2000 sales. However,
these stocks are well off their 52-week highs and nothing justifies
further price appreciation than being able to say ``I am buying
this much lower than it has traded before.'' That's a recipe for
higher prices if there ever were one.
</P>
<P>
   THIRD, we have a genuine, damn the torpedoes, full-speed-ahead
cycle happening in aerospace. We tend to forget that aerospace is a
giant part of our economy and when it is in full tilt it pulls up a
lot of players. We like to have a giant cycle that involves huge
Dow stocks like United Tech and General Electric and Boeing. Really
gets the fund managers going.
</P>
<P>
   FOURTH, the Net has settled into a winner-take-all situation,
and the two winners are America Online and Yahoo! When this
AOL/Time Warner deal closes, I believe we are going to see that
stock rip to new highs.
</P>
<P>
   FIFTH, oil, which is up huge, could, shockingly, go down, which
would take away one of the big bear cases out there that has kept a
lot of money on the sidelines. Can you imagine the hand-wringing if
the bears lost this prop? Dreadful.
</P>
<P>
   SIXTH, no more silly Fed watch. Things have cooled enough that
we don't have to sit on the sidelines waiting for the Fed to sound
the all-clear signal, which it never does anyway. That puts us in
the November 1994 portion of the time line where you could buy
financials, tech and cyclicals. Only the drugs and the Cokes of the
world rest during this period. Lots of positive moves coming in the
advance-decline lines!
</P>
<P>
   SEVENTH: Like it or not, neither candidate is bad for the stock
market. The Republicans would like to cast Gore in a light that is
negative for stocks, but I don't think that will have much traction
given how unbelievably positive the Clinton years were for the
market, and Clinton isn't as ``smart'' about the economy as Gore. I
personally don't like what Bush wants to do with taxes, but I know
better than to get into a political debate on this site, so I will
save it for other venues.
</P>
<P>
   EIGHTH: A whole new generation of kick-butt CEOS is coming up,
giving us a new group of stocks to buy. I read that unbelievable
interview with Keith Krach from Ariba this weekend and tell me you
don't want to bet with these guys. You want to bet against Greg
Reyes at Brocade, who had a battle plan ready if anyone ever tried
to pull an Emulex with his company? You may not believe in the
Exodus story, but I do. If you can't beat Ellen Hancock, at least
you can own shares in her company. And while I am at it, isn't this
John Roth from Nortel a serious heavy-hitter?
</P>
<P>
   NINTH: A couple of sleeping giants seem to be awakening. Last
year IBM got taken down by Y2K, as it should have (if anyone should
have seen this one coming from years away, it should have been
IBM). That's now behind them and I think this stock is rocking
here. AT&AMP;T, another stock that I felt betrayed, beaten up and
crushed by, seems to be turning the ship around. Yes, in the 50s
and 40s I saw no case for AT&AMP;T. Even in the 30s. But when this
thing trades back to the low 30s high 20s, it seems like the
essence of cheap. It owns a fantastic wireless division growing at
60 percent _ AT&AMP;T Wireless. It has assembled a massive cable
network, which could come on strong now that DSL seems to be
faltering again courtesy of labor problems in the East and who
knows what in the West. Its business unit may not have done that
well lately, but that can be turned around by management, as I
don't know anyone who is angry at AT&AMP;T or thinks it is a crummy
company. Sure, consumer is a drag, but if it can be contained
without spending a lot of money, what's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of John Malone being angry or upset with
AT&AMP;T's management, but I think that is a pile of hogwash, just a
bunch of reporters trying to get a story going. I think Malone's in
there making some solid suggestions that will get traction with
stockholders eventually. In the meantime, when the Germans are
willing to pay $50 billion for some network nobody has ever heard
of, what is AT&AMP;T worth? Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   TENTH, and finally, the banks and the brokers. This group is
hot, hot, hot. And it is never a false tell. One thing I do a lot
of work on is group leadership. While there is always plenty of
splash behind technology leadership, the bulk of securities out
there trade off the financials, not off of Intel or Cisco. There
are literally thousands of financially related stocks out there
that really color the advance-decline line. When these stocks go
up, they create a healthy hue that forces bears to capitulate.
That's what is happening now.
</P>
<P>
   So, there's your list of why I expect the markets to rally here.
I am sure that there will be potholes along the way _ potholes that
will be well covered, no, make that overcovered, by the media. When
we stumble into them, refer to this list. It is more powerful than
any of those ruts in the road.
</P>
<P>
   (James J. Cramer is manager of a hedge fund and co-founder of
TheStreet.com. At time of publication, his fund was long Ariba,
AT&AMP;T, AT&AMP;T Wireless, Brocade, Exodus, IBM, Intel, Cisco and Nortel.
His fund often buys and sells securities that are the subject of
his columns, both before and after the columns are published, and
the positions that his fund takes may change at any time. Under no
circumstances does the information in this column represent a
recommendation to buy or sell stocks. Cramer's writings provide
insights into the dynamics of money management and are not a
solicitation for transactions. While he cannot provide investment
advice or recommendations, he invites you to send comments on his
column at jjcletters(at)thestreet.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
