<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4401 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-PARALYSIS-REHAB0829-C     08-28 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARALYSIS-REHAB0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disabled could lose life-enhancing services with closing of
Franciscan Rehabilitation Center
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Even though she is paralyzed below her neck and
breathes through a tube, Pat Bodie works for a living. She can type
and dial the telephone through her computer, moving and aiming a
radio signal on her forehead. She can operate her television and
stereo from her wheelchair or bed, flicking a special switch with
the slight movement she can control in one wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do so much more than when I was younger,'' said Bodie,
now 64 and paralyzed from polio since 1954. ``Without the
technology I have, I would not be as independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Access to that technology is in jeopardy with the liquidation of
Franciscan Medical Center, where Bodie was retrofitted for daily
life in the Franciscan Rehabilitation Center's nationally
recognized assistive technology services component. The doctors,
therapists and engineers there have been adapting technology for 10
years to help people get around and communicate when they otherwise
could not.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Franciscan's other marquee departments, rehab is not
landing intact at another hospital. Sports medicine is moving to
Kettering Medical Center. Psychiatry and the family practice clinic
are part of Grandview. Although parts of rehab are splintering off
from Wayne to Middletown, the assistive technology equipment is
being reduced to numbers on a liquidation inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going around putting price tags on stuff _ that's like
selling off the Taj Mahal brick by brick,'' said Dr. David
Mitchell, who directed rehab at Franciscan. ``This program is
priceless with all the pieces together. It's worthless brick by
brick. It's worthless without the therapists and engineers. The
community's losing a treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other comparable programs in Ohio are in Cincinnati and
Cleveland, and, as Bodie said, ``I can't just jump in a car and go
somewhere.'' She doesn't know what she'll do when her equipment
needs to be repaired or upgraded. But at least she has what she
has.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people who really need these things won't be able to
get them,'' she said. Even if they can travel elsewhere, rehab
engineer Heather Bridgeman said Franciscan treated a lot of
Medicaid patients and the unemployably injured who don't qualify
for funding through Ohio Rehabilitation Services Commission's
Bureau of Vocational Rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exceptional rehab program, something the community
will desperately miss,'' said executive director Joseph Baldasare
of United Rehabilitation Services of Greater Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   URS accepts Medicaid, offers augmentative communication
technology and plans to hire some more therapists, but it lacks
Franciscan's size and scope. Goodwill Industries of the Miami
Valley is ``very interested'' in assuming the whole assistive
technology program, president Amy Luttrell said, but is waiting for
information from Franciscan about accounting and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the therapists familiar with it are scattering to new
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The sad irony is, there have never been so many technological
solutions available for overcoming disabilities, said Pat
Cashdollar, the program director and co-founder of the Technology
Resource Center, a nonprofit organization that procures such
equipment, especially for enabling vocal or visual communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for the most part it's affordable. But to find a place to
help you get the right solution for you, and to show you how it's
being done, that's hard to find. Franciscan had the team for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;  With multiple sclerosis, Ann Hitchcock has a lot of
doctors. ``It was so nice to have them all in one place,'' she
said. She'll follow one of them to Kettering, but the one going to
Sidney is too far from her Dayton home.
</P>
<P>
   For the majority of Franciscan patients, Baldasare said,
switching doctors and therapists will be the hardest part. That's
especially true of MS patients, Hitchcock said. They go through
life knowing they could wake up paralyzed tomorrow, so emotional
support is as important as good medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people know you after awhile,'' Hitchcock said. ``They can
see if something's bothering you today. You trust them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cared about their patients at Franciscan in a way that I
have never seen. And I'm ex-military, so I've been to a lot of
hospitals in my life. Other hospitals just won't be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the staff will follow the physicians _ Dr. David Johnson
is directing rehab at Wayne Hospital, Dr. David Seymour at
Middletown Regional Hospital, Dr. Richard Beers at Kettering, where
a new inpatient rehab center will open this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Valley Hospital has the area's only inpatient rehab center
until then. ``They're doing it just fine,'' said Mitchell, who will
practice in the Kettering, Centerville and Englewood offices in
addition to Middletown and Wayne. Miami Valley also had programs
already that were similar to Franciscan's for hand and spinal cord
injuries and for teaching disabled people to drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Muscular Dystrophy Association expects to find a home for
Franciscan's MD clinic next month. The amputee clinic has moved to
Middletown. The clinic for custom-designing wheelchairs and
Franciscan's driving program are in flux, part of the assistive
technology program that is looking for a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no money in assistive technology services,''
Cashdollar said, ``so you have to package it with something that
can make more money.'' With that in mind, Mitchell was encouraged
to hear of interest from Miami Valley as well as Goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   Franciscan had about 12 inpatients and 150 outpatients for rehab
at any given time in the last year, including 15 in the technology
program, according to hospital figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sit in awe of the expertise in that unit,'' said Dr.
Mark Clasen, a Franciscan tenant as chairman of family medicine in
Wright State University's School of Medicine. ``They worked with
people with such extreme disabilities and got them doing things
where they could get on with their life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;  Bodie does her publicity writing and newsletter
editing one letter at a time. She points the gizmo on her forehead
at a keyboard on her computer screen, selects a letter with a flick
of her wrist and moves on to the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are productive and intelligent beings,'' said Bodie, who
does advocacy work for the disabled from her nursing home in
Springfield. ``We just need to be given a chance to show what we
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology changes so quickly and makes so many advances,''
Bodie said. ``I can't just go to Best Buy or look in a catalog. I
need someone who's an expert to help me pick things out and train
me on using them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeman, the rehab engineer, will still help people through
ORSC, she said, ``but there's a whole set of clients that won't be
seen because they don't have job potential. Those folks who simply
want to increase their quality of life, they're the ones who will
suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of someone who's a quadriplegic in a wheelchair and can
hardly move or speak but could possibly access a computer. What a
huge world the Internet can open up to them! I don't recall ever
turning anyone away at Franciscan. There was always something we
could do, no matter how impaired someone was.''
</P>
<P>
   The applications for rehab technology have grown exponentially
in the first decade after the Cold War, Mitchell said. ``With the
breaking out of peace, they wanted to take technology for killing
people and find out how to use it to save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology is useless, he said, unless people compare the
medical problems with engineering discoveries. For example,
engineers had no idea that doctors worried about protecting
brain-damaged patients who might blithely drive a wheelchair onto a
busy street, and doctors had no idea there was technology that
could detect impending collisions and stop the wheelchair. Their
conversations led to a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be that kind of creativity in looking at
things,'' Mitchell said. He helped form the Consortium for Applied
Rehabilitation Technology about 10 years ago so creative people
from various disciplines could brainstorm together. ``But we were
missing the business sense,'' he said, and now Dayton is losing
another corridor that linked technology and rehab medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could use a couple of leaders now who see the bigger
picture,'' Cashdollar said, ``some leaders like Charles Kettering
and John Patterson.''
</P>
<P>
   Email: at kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com
</P>
