<P>
   MET-ASIAN-ART (New York) _ Thirty years ago, Asian art led a
marginal life at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. In 1970 the only
Chinese work on view was a room of Buddhist sculpture and a few
cases of ceramics. As late as 1990, Indian art meant an assortment
of objects crammed into dimly lighted vitrines on the Great Hall
balcony. Things have changed. The museum now has more than 50
permanent galleries devoted to the largest and most comprehensive
collection of Asian art under one roof anywhere. These days the Met
is fond of calling itself a ``museum of Asian art within a
museum,'' and it's justified in doing so. By Holland Cotter.
