<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4404 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MIRANDA-WARNING-HNS &LR;      08-28 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRANDA-WARNING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN TURNABOUT, CALIF. POLICE ARE TOLD TO OBEY THE MIRANDA RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a dramatic about-face, police across the
state are being warned to obey the U.S. Supreme Court's famous
Miranda rule and stop interrogating citizens who invoke their
rights to remain silent or have legal help.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers in California for years were trained to ignore
suspects' Miranda rights and keep grilling them, a tactic called
``questioning outside Miranda.''
</P>
<P>
   Although judges eventually criticized the procedure as ``very
troubling,'' ``police misconduct'' and ``slippery and illegal,''
the state Department of Justice continued to tell officers it was
OK.
</P>
<P>
   But on June 26 the U.S. Supreme Court reaffirmed the Miranda
decision in a Virginia case and let stand a California case that
said officers could be personally liable for deliberately trampling
Miranda rights. Since then, the state Justice Department has
reversed itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line now must be: Do not intentionally violate
Miranda,'' it says. ``This is because an intentional violation will
virtually guarantee a civil rights suit against you and your
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Area prosecutors also are cautioning police that deliberate
violations may land them on the wrong side of the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when the bailiff announces, `Will the defendants please
rise,' don't look to the suspect that was arrested to stand up,''
said July 13 memo from the San Mateo County district attorney's
office. ``The bailiff is talking to you.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco District Attorney Terence Hallinan, a long-time
supporter of Miranda, told police in a July 17 memo: ``Failure to
adhere to this rule may result in the personal civil liability of
the officers involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors say the high court's ruling still lets them use
evidence that police obtained from interrogations in which they
violated Miranda rights, as long as they did not coerce the
suspect. And defense lawyers were not convinced police would honor
Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old habits die hard,'' said Kenneth M. Quigley, a San
Francisco defense lawyer. ``If there's a true change in this
particular area by the Police Department, I'll eat my socks.''
</P>
<P>
   In a series of articles in June, The San Francisco Examiner
documented widespread police violations of Miranda that, along with
other improper interrogation tactics, caused costly court hearings,
hindered criminal investigations, helped accused criminals go free,
or produced allegedly false confessions that threatened innocent
people with jail.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of people are interrogated each day in California,
typically in isolation and under intense police pressure. While out
of public view, interrogations can profoundly shape the course of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court's 1966 Miranda ruling examined what the
court called the ``inherently compelling'' nature of custodial
interrogation, and became its best-known decision on criminal
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   To counterbalance psychological pressure against suspects and to
protect the Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination, the
court required police to give the equivalent of what has become
known as the Miranda warning: You have the right to remain silent.
You have the right to the presence of an attorney. If you cannot
afford an attorney, one will be appointed for you. Anything you say
can and will be used against you.
</P>
<P>
   To enforce the rule, the court said that if police violated it,
``no evidence obtained as a result of the confession can be used.''
In later years, the high court narrowed that exclusionary measure.
The court still punished police violations of Miranda by barring
prosecutors from introducing the subsequent confession in court to
prove the suspect's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   But the court said police could use the confession _ if it was
not the result of coercion _ to find other evidence and witnesses.
Prosecutors could also use the statement to challenge the
credibility of defendants who took the witness stand and
contradicted their confessions.
</P>
<P>
   The court said in 1975 that it was only ``a speculative
possibility'' that police would breach Miranda to gain such
advantages. But in training sessions certified by California's
Commission on Peace Officer Standards &AMP; Training, thousands of
officers were told that, as long as they did not threaten or coerce
suspects - they could choose when to honor a suspect's Miranda
rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4407 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ARTEXHIBITIONS-1200(3     08-28 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTEXHIBITIONS-1200(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS OF MUSEUM TOURS REVEALS COMPLEX WORLD OF MONEY, INFLUENCE
AND LUCK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ANDREW MARTON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In the parlance of master impresario Ed
Sullivan, the acclaimed Russian exhibition ``Stroganoff: The Palace
and Collections of a Russian Noble Family'' is a ``really big
show.'' Its more than 230 precious objects give it scope. Its
stunning tableaux, from Botticelli to Van Dyck, lend it artistic
grandeur. That its riches are being shown together for the first
time outside the palaces of old imperial Russia imparts historical
heft.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the lines of spectators for this stellar collection
will snake around the golden quartet of America's museums: the
Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York, the National Gallery of Art
in Washington, D.C., the Art Institute of Chicago and the J. Paul
Getty Museum in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Well, think again. Of course, the exhibit has drawn impressive
crowds, except that they haven't been in New York, Washington,
Chicago or LA. Instead, they've been at the Portland Art Museum in
Oregon and, currently, at the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth.
From Fort Worth, the show heads back to Russia to close its run at
the State Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   That ``Stroganoff'' has been shown in two smaller museums,
leap-frogging the country's premier cultural showcases, suggests a
complex riddle. Why exactly does one museum host an exhibit and
another miss out? Asking why an exhibition ends up where it does
reveals a Gordian knot of little-understood, occasionally
conflicting factors, including relationships between museum
directors, the quality of a museum's permanent collection,
preferences by living artists, and, naturally, money. Invisibly,
these elements team up to determine whether an exhibit appears at a
museum near you.
</P>
<P>
   One important and undeniable factor is, not surprisingly, money.
A prized exhibit can cost a museum from $250,000 to as high as $2
million to $3 million. But while the costs are prohibitive for many
museums to stage major exhibitions, the payoff can be huge for
those that do. One way to measure the dollars-and-cents motivation
for landing a touring show is its financial impact on the
surrounding community. The American Association of Museums reports
that in 1996 when the Portland Art Museum staged its exhibit ``The
Imperial Tombs of China,'' Oregon's economy received a boost of
$92.3 million. That same year, a Cezanne exhibition originating at
the Philadelphia Museum of Art was estimated to inject $86.5
million into greater Philadelphia's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Swift and efficient access to a large pool of money is often
needed to secure a museum's inclusion in a prestigious national
tour. When the world-renowned ``Impressionist Masterpieces From the
Barnes Collection: Cezanne to Matisse'' exhibition hit the road in
1994, the fee charged to each host museum added up to between $2
million and $4 million _ too pricey for almost every national
museum except the National Gallery of Art, The Philadelphia Museum
of Art, and the Kimbell, which was able to tap into large financial
resources much faster than other, larger museums.
</P>
<P>
   An increasingly common solution to these cost requirements is a
shrewd alignment with culture-minded corporate sponsors, which
allows regional and smaller museums to compete with the country's
biggest and most prestigious. The Boeing Co. has shouldered many of
the local expenses for numerous Seattle Art Museum exhibits. And
next spring, The Saint Louis Art Museum will be the only American
venue hosting ``Vincent Van Gogh and the Painters of the Petit
Boulevard,'' thanks largely to a $1 million corporate-support
package from the Kemper Foundation, Commerce Bank and the Baer
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When museums in New York or Los Angeles know we are able to
command $1 million in sponsorship, that is big news indicating that
cost isn't going to be an issue for us,'' says Brent Benjamin,
director of the St. Louis museum.
</P>
<P>
   Not that money is always the determining factor. Never
underestimate the simple matter of geography when it comes to
influencing where an exhibit is shown. Exhibitions of consequence
tend to visit three museums, usually one located on each coast,
with one in the country's middle.
</P>
<P>
   When a region is omitted from a national tour, it is likely to
be the Midwest, the South or Southwest. Currently, the National
Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C., is working with the Louvre in
Paris to stage a retrospective of Jean Antoine Houdon, the late
18th-century French sculptor. The 80-piece exhibition will make
only two key-geographic stops: the National Gallery and the Getty.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the limited venues are purely practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that it was only responsible, in light of the rigors
of shipping and packing the works and the lenders' sacrifices, that
three venues would be enough,'' says Dodge Thompson, chief of
exhibitions at the National Gallery, who also indicates that if a
museum tour involves a relatively obscure artist and must limit
itself to a bare-bones number of stops, it will likely concentrate
on the large population areas of the coasts.
</P>
<P>
   But for shows with a chest-beating populist appeal, the quest
for geographic diversity carries exhibits to a wide variety of
venues. When the current tour of the Norman Rockwell collection was
initially planned, for example, both the Norman Rockwell Museum at
Stockbridge (in Massachusetts), and the High Museum of Art in
Atlanta decided that such venues as Chicago, Washington, Phoenix,
San Diego and New York's Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum should be
part of its itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1648EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
