<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4410 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ARTEXHIBITIONS-2ndTak     08-28 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTEXHIBITIONS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 FORT WORTH, Texas: its itinerary. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We are in a rural section of Massachusetts, lacking real
racial and ethnic diversity,'' says Maureen Hart Hennessey, chief
curator of the Rockwell museum. ``One of our goals was to see
future audience development for Rockwell's art, so we were looking
at museums with all kinds of different audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   But geographic proximity can either hinder or help the
likelihood of an exhibit's landing in a certain museum. When Fort
Worth's Amon Carter Museum shops many of its exhibitions around, it
doesn't often look toward the New Orleans Museum of Art, simply
because it is, in relative terms, in Fort Worth's back yard.
However, the Seattle Art Museum would not be averse to circulating
a focused exhibition to a trio of regional museums in Tulsa, Kansas
City and Fort Worth. ``Frankly, sending the show to several museums
so close to each other is a good way to help recoup exhibit
expenses,'' says Gail Joice, senior deputy director of the Seattle
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as decisive as geography in determining which museum is
chosen is an exhibit's theme. The current exhibit at Kansas City's
Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, ``The Architecture of Reassurance,''
presents the art behind the Walt Disney theme-park designs. The
350-object exhibit is very timely for Kansas City, which is
celebrating its 150th anniversary, and looking to honor Disney, who
had his first studio in that city.
</P>
<P>
   And when ``Star Wars: The Magic of Myth'' was organized by the
Smithsonian, it seemed only natural that the exhibit stop next
spring in Houston, the home of Mission Control. ``Some art museums
would have been afraid of something like this, thinking it was too
popular, but I saw it as a fabulous application of fine art and
creativity,'' says Peter Marzio, director of the Museum of Fine
Arts, Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Along with financial clout and prime geographic real estate, the
quality of works in an institution's permanent collection often
gives it the inside track to being selected as an exhibit site.
Museums with sprawling and high-quality permanent collections have
a leg up on museums with smaller holdings, not only because they
can use more of their art as the core for their own touring shows,
but also because they have greater ability to loan major works to
other museums that are organizing shows.
</P>
<P>
   When several Venetian museums in 1990 organized a Titian
retrospective, for example, the National Gallery of Art in
Washington, D.C., earned a spot on the global tour thanks to the 12
Titians in its permanent collection. And there was only one reason
why the relatively obscure Albright-Knox Art Gallery of Buffalo was
a key participant in the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth's landmark
Arshile Gorky exhibit of 1996. The Buffalo museum happened to hold
one of Gorky's most significant works, and when it contributed the
1944 abstract-expressionist painting to the tour, it was
immediately added to the itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   But, for a smaller museum, what the Buffalo museum did ``is
tricky, because when a museum temporarily parts with one of its
most famous and popular works, one has to be very careful about
disappointing loyal visitors,'' says Timothy Potts, director of the
Kimbell. ``Scheduling a tour of two venues means the work of art is
away from home for at least six months, which quickly makes the
tour a sacrifice many lending museums are not willing to make.''
</P>
<P>
   But to a certain degree, every museum lives by this quid-pro-quo
credo. If it rejects the chance to participate in a touring exhibit
through lending one of its works, it is running a risk. The
punishment for rebuffing another museum's request for a work might
be a kind of ostracism that puts the institution out of the running
for upcoming events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Implicit in a museum lending out art to a touring show is that
down the line, it will want to have an important piece from the
same borrowing museum when it puts its own future tour together,''
says Stephen Phillips, associate curator of the Phillips Collection
in Washington, D.C. ``Again, this scenario means that museums with
the stronger collections will always hold more playing cards down
the line.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, other important considerations. There are,
for example, a selection of museums seen as glowing venues for
touring shows, museums that carry a reputation for mounting
aesthetically pleasing shows with fastidious scholarship.
``Remember that certain artists and owners of great art will
absolutely refuse to show in certain museums because they feel the
buildings are poorly designed,'' says Michael Auping, chief curator
of the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Frick Collection has a solid reputation for staging
high-quality shows of works on paper and other drawings. The San
Diego Museum of Art can thank its historic facility for helping it
edge out the city's Museum of Contemporary Art in snaring the
touring Rockwell exhibit. And the Kimbell, thanks to the
architectural splendor of its Louis Kahn-designed home and its
polished curatorial standards, will join the Met in New York as
hosts for one of next year's most anticipated exhibits, ``Treasures
From a Lost Civilization: Ancient Chinese Art From Sichuan,''
organized by the Seattle Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
