<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4411 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ARTEXHIBITIONS-3rdTak     08-28 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTEXHIBITIONS-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 FORT WORTH, Texas: Seattle Art Museum. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which museums have a reputation for best handling of such
fragile exhibitions as ``Lost Civilization'' also helps determine
where a show will land. A recent show of delicate crayon drawings
by Antoine Watteau was limited to just New York's Frick Collection
and the National Gallery of Canada. And when the American
Federation of Arts orchestrated the touring exhibition of German
artist Wolfgang Laib, whose work is made almost entirely of wax and
bee pollen, only museums with near-perfect humidity, lighting, air
conditioning and other environmental controls, could take the show.
</P>
<P>
   With artwork fragility clearly a prime concern, many private
lenders of personally treasured masterpieces aren't shy about
specifying just how long their holdings can circulate on a museum
tour. When the Phillips Collection helped set up a recent exhibit
honoring the work of French painter Honore Daumier, it was
co-organized by the National Gallery of Canada and made only one
U.S. stop _ at the Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other museums would have loved to have had that exhibition,
but it would have been too much to ask a private collector to live
without a major work of art in his or her living room for a year,''
says Phillips, the Phillips Collection curator.
</P>
<P>
   Contacts, contacts, contacts. The behind-the-scenes friendships
between curators and directors also can help steer an exhibit
toward a particular museum. Often, during the twice-annual meetings
of the Association of Art Museum Directors, museum directors will
stage their version of a ``smoke-filled room'' meeting, where
exhibition ideas can germinate into a future tour.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was through a series of meetings between Fort Worth's
Michael Auping and Steven Nash, chief curator at the Fine Arts
Museums of San Francisco, that the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth
could line up the upcoming Wayne Thiebaud show.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he told us about it, I remember not flinching for a
moment, saying to him we wanted to be involved and to let us know
when the next slot on the tour would be,'' recalls Auping.
</P>
<P>
   The personal touch similarly helped the Kimbell secure the
Stroganoff exhibition. In early 1999, the Portland Art Museum was
in the advanced stages of curating and organizing ``Stroganoff.''
It was Portland's director, John Buchanan, who had sown the seeds
for the collection's appearance in Oregon. Buchanan devoted four
years to cultivating numerous ties with various curators at the
Hermitage museum, a primary contributor to the final exhibit, and,
most importantly, with Baroness Helene de Ludinghausen, the last
surviving member of the Stroganoff family.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Potts, the Kimbell's director, had already established a
strong rapport with several curators at the Portland museum and
intimated that the museums could collaborate on several shows.
Potts eventually received a set of images and documentation from
the Portland museum that outlined the Stroganoff collection. A
presentation to the Kimbell staff by several Portland curators
followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What `Stroganoff' touched in me was that very important recent
development in art history, which is the whole appreciation for the
history of collecting and its impact on, in this case, Russian
style and taste,'' says Potts.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the Kimbell was already one of the obvious venues for
this exhibition,'' adds the Portland museum's Buchanan, ``because
it was not only one of the country's highest-caliber museums, but
also because I loved the parity of showing a grand family's private
collection in a museum that had its origins in a private
individual's collection.''
</P>
<P>
   It is fitting that when the Norman Rockwell exhibit opens at the
Guggenheim in November 2001, few of those attending the show will
ever realize that, as with most major exhibitions, there were
dozens of micro machinations that transpired over three or four
years to deliver it. Few will remember that three years ago, the
National Museum of American Art published an important monograph on
Rockwell, and few will realize that Robert Rosenblum, curator of
20th-century art at the Guggenheim, reviewed that monograph.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, few will remember that Rosenblum would take that
opportunity to stun the snobbish art world by announcing that he, a
famous proponent of abstract expressionism, was a closet fan of
Rockwell's. Fewer still would know that a flurry of notes was
exchanged between Rosenblum and the Rockwell museum's director
expressing Rosenblum's interest in staging a show at the
Guggenheim.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, he'll get his wish.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew Marton is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7679, or e-mail:
amarton(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
