<HEADER>
A4419 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      08-28 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PERCEPTIONS: When Your Milkshake Gets Pumped Up
</P>
<P>
   If you want to eat less, add a little air.
</P>
<P>
   A study from Pennsylvania State University published in The
American Journal of Clinical Nutrition examined what happened to
the appetites of men given milkshakes whipped up to varying degrees
of frothiness. The researchers found that those given glasses
filled twice as full ate 12 percent less a half hour later. The
shakes were identical in ingredients and weight _ though not in
taste, according to the participants, who preferred their shakes
stirred, not pumped up.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDHOOD: Day Care, for Keeping Asthma at Bay
</P>
<P>
   The endless sniffles and ear infections that go along with day
care may have some benefit: children with high rates of exposure to
other children in infancy are less likely to develop asthma later
on, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, published August 24 in The New England Journal of
Medicine, researchers from the University of Arizona College of
Medicine in Tucson looked at the medical records of 1,035 children
who had been monitored since birth as part of a broader long-term
study.
</P>
<P>
   They found that children who were enrolled in day care or who
had older siblings had episodes of wheezing more often as toddlers
than did eldest or only children who were cared for at home,
according to their parents' recollection at age 6.
</P>
<P>
   But yearly surveys of children between 6 and 13 found that fewer
of the exposed children had received asthma diagnoses. And, among
all the children who did develop asthma, those children exposed to
others were reported as having fewer attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma is on the increase worldwide, but particularly in more
affluent countries, and many researchers have speculated that the
cleanliness of the modern world has led to less robust immune
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``One theory suggests that infections play an important role in
the maturation of the immune system, causing the immune system to
become less allergic,'' said Dr. Anne Wright, the lead author.
``This study supports the view that infections, or exposure to
other children, protect against the development of asthma and
allergies.''
</P>
<P>
   UPDATE: Promise and Problems of Supplements
</P>
<P>
   A review of clinical trials over the last decade has found
mounting evidence that some herbal medicines can be effective in
treating mild psychiatric symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers who conducted the review cautioned consumers
to be aware that many herbal products did not contain what their
labels stated and urged them to tell their doctors before taking
the substances, particularly if they were taking other medicines.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the September issue of Psychiatric
Services, a journal of the American Psychiatric Association, found
that five of nine well-controlled trials of St. John's wort
suggested that it had some effect on depression (that is, more than
a placebo), and four showed that it was equal to low doses of
conventional antidepressants.
</P>
<P>
   DIAGNOSIS: Staying Vigilant for Signs of Autism
</P>
<P>
   All young children should be screened for signs of autism at all
routine visits to the pediatrician, the American Academy of
Neurology recommended last week in a new set of practice
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines, published on the academy's Web site,
www.aan.com, cited studies showing that although about a quarter of
the children in the average pediatric practice have some sort of
developmental problem, pediatricians performed developmental
screenings at less than a third of all checkups.
</P>
<P>
   The most widely recognized treatment for autism, behavioral
therapy, has been shown to be more effective the earlier it begins,
the academy said. But ``the diagnosis of autism is often not made
until two or three years after symptoms are noticed, primarily
because of concerns about labeling or misdiagnosing the child,''
the guidelines stated. ``Identifying childen with autism and
initiating intensive, early intervention in the preschool years
results in improved outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy suggested that doctors be attuned to these
milestones in particular: babbling and gesturing by 12 months, use
of single words by 16 months and two-word spontaneous phrases by 24
months, or the loss of any language or social skills at any age.
</P>
<P>
   Children who fail to meet those milestones should have their
hearing checked and be given more specific screening tests for
autism.
</P>
<P>
   AGING: A Healthful Gain When Toto Calls
</P>
<P>
   Doctors whose elderly patients are asking to be discharged early
from the hospital should consider whether a pet has been left at
home, a letter this month in The Annals of Internal Medicine
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have recently come to appreciate that the separation of
hospitalized patients from their pet dogs can make both parties ill
and can therefore be called the `pet separation syndrome,''' wrote
Dr. John Burnham of Tuscaloosa, Ala. He cited several cases,
including one in which a woman's depression and arrhythmia
``improved dramatically when her dog, Toto, was brought, hidden in
a basket, to visit her in her hospital room.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that in Britain, dogs could be taken to visit long-term
patients, he concluded that for some ``man's best friend could be
the best medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   NOSTRUMS: Breathing Easier? Not With Nose Clip
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of athletes are using nasal dilators _ nose
attachments that hold the nasal passages open _ in the belief that
the dilators allow more oxygen into the body and enhance
performance.
</P>
<P>
   A researcher at Rice University in Houston, Joseph O'Kroy,
decided to test that theory. He had 15 subjects perform the same
exercise test three times: once wearing a nose clip, once wearing a
breathing mask that actively pumped air to the nose and once with
the same mask's nose circuit turned off. He found no difference in
oxygen uptake, work rate or perception of fatigue, according to a
study published in this month's issue of Medicine &AMP; Science in
Sports &AMP; Exercise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
