<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4422 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-AFRICA-ART-NY     08-28 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AFRICA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CLINTON AND MANDELA LOOK ON, BURUNDI PEACE ACCORD FALLS
THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARUSHA, Tanzania _ President Clinton had hoped to witness the
signing of a major peace deal and cease-fire among the warring
factions in Burundi, but negotiations to end the country's
seven-year civil war became bogged down Monday when some Tutsi
minority parties refused to sign a deal with the Hutu majority.
</P>
<P>
   Former South African President Nelson Mandela, who is brokering
the peace talks, delivered a blistering attack on the Tutsi parties
for backing out of an agreement and turning their backs on ``the
slaughter of innocent people inside Burundi.'' Mandela had invited
Clinton and leaders from about a dozen African nations to this
resort town for the signing by Hutu rebels and the Tutsi-dominated
government.
</P>
<P>
   When it became clear that a major agreement would not be reached
by Monday's deadline, Clinton instead used the occasion to plead
for peace among the warring Tutsis and Hutus.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't do it, what is the price?'' the president asked.
``If you don't do it, what is the chance that the progress you have
made will unravel? If you come back in five to 10 years will the
issues change? The gulf between you will not narrow, but the gulf
between Burundi and the rest of the world will grow greater if you
let this moment slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton winds up a four-day trip to Africa early Tuesday morning
after a meeting in Cairo with President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt.
Clinton, eager for lasting foreign policy achievements in the final
months of his presidency, is struggling to build support among
Arabs for a breakthrough deal between the Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The peace accord for Burundi that Mandela has been working
toward during the past two years envisions an eventual return of
power by the Hutu majority _ who make up nearly 85 percent of the
population _ but with protections for the Tutsi. Monday's
agreement, signed by some but not all of the parties, fell
considerably short of even an end to hostilities, laying out most
rules of engagement for continued talks.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela criticized the Burundi president, Pierre Buyoya, in
particular, saying he has denied that he is holding political
prisoners, even though, Mandela said, such inmates are being
``treated worse than animals'' in Burundi jails.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the talks are the sheer number of parties involved
_ 19 in all. They include 10 Tutsi political parties, seven Hutu
parties, the Tutsi-dominated army and Buyoya's government. Two key
Hutu rebel groups are boycotting the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can force peace,'' Clinton told the Burundians before
him. ``You must choose it.''
</P>
<P>
   The civil war in Burundi, which has claimed 200,000 lives and
forced more than a million people from their homes, dates to 1993,
when Tutsi paratroopers assassinated the first president from the
Hutu majority, Melchior Ndadaye. But ethnic violence between Tutsis
and Hutus has flared since Burundi broke from Belgium in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   On the first trip by a U.S. president to Tanzania, Clinton told
a welcoming party at the airport that ``we still share your
sorrow'' over the 1998 terrorist bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Dar
es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the terrorists went after Tanzania, Kenya and the
United States precisely because we are dedicated to tolerance,
understanding and cooperation across frontiers and lines of
division,'' the president said. ``They took a lot of our loved
ones, but they failed utterly to deter us from advancing our common
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people gathered along the highway waving
green tree branches and flags at Clinton's passing motorcade, which
sped past banana and coffee fields and wandering herds of goats and
sheep on its way to the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed an agreement with President Benjamin W. Mkapa of
Tanzania that will give airlines in each country access to airports
in the other, an ``open skies agreement'' that officials hope will
increase passenger travel and commerce between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   In brief remarks, Clinton said Tanzania should be thankful it
has avoided many of the crises that have focused the world's
attention on other parts of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you have avoided headlines about repression, famine
and war, and instead focused on the steady progress of democracy
and development, being generous to your neighbors, and being a
cause of peace and cooperation across the region, too many people
in our country do not know enough about your country,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
