<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TO MUCH YOUNG TALENT MAY HURT 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEVIN LYNCH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Forty-one days, five exhibition games, scores of
practices, and what have we learned about these 49ers?
</P>
<P>
   1. This team will be better than 0-16.
</P>
<P>
   2. Not much better.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' 1-4 exhibition record proved this: They will play
just well enough not to win on most Sundays. They'll compete gamely
in most instances. Their young players will excite and tantalize,
but bone-headed rookie mistakes will cause the team to unravel in
the crucial moments of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It could be worse. Remember, this team is still in a controlled
burn phase brought on by the out-of-control growth of spending.
Salary cap rules are forcing the 49ers to smoke out older, highly
paid veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-man roster will now include all 11 drafted rookies and
maybe four or five of the undrafted variety. Once one of the oldest
teams in the league, the 49ers' average age this season will hover
around 25.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven players (Ray Brown, Jerry Rice, Derrick Deese, Jeff
Garcia, Rick Mirer, Ken Norton and Matt Willig) are older than 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to find out if these puppies can bite,'' Norton
said of his young teammates. Indications are the youngsters can
bite enough to leave a mark. Coach Steve Mariucci said at the San
Francisco Chamber of Commerce kickoff luncheon that fans would look
back at this season's draft class 20 years from now.
</P>
<P>
   While that might be overstating it, this draft class is
intriguing. First-round cornerback Ahmed Plummer is playing like a
polished 10-year pro. First-round linebacker Julian Peterson oozes
with talent, and will play often once his shoulder heals and he
learns the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Third-round inside linebacker Jeff Ubrich could push for playing
time by year's end if he recovers from nagging ailments.
Seventh-round quarterback Tim Rattay is a find. Safety John Keith
is a special teams whiz with a starter's potential. Cornerback
Jason Webster will see plenty of playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Even the club's last player chosen, tight end Brian Jennings,
will contribute. He fulfills the obscure but vital role of snapper
on punts and kicks.
</P>
<P>
   The team also cashed in on a two-for-one sale this year with
rookies. Injuries obliterated last season's draft class _ defensive
tackle Reggie McGrew, cornerback Anthony Parker, guard Tyrone
Hopson and wide receiver Tai Streets hardly played at all.
</P>
<P>
   This season, McGrew and Parker will see plenty of time on
defense. Streets bristles with talent and could be a future star.
Hopson is recovering from gall bladder surgery, but could be fine
in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Pierson Prioleau, one of the few who escaped last year's
rash of injuries, is now the starting free safety. And Terry
Jackson, a fifth-rounder from last year, will be the first running
back off the bench this season at fullback and halfback.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Chike Okeafor also figures to get plenty of
playing time. Of the 19 players drafted in the last two years, only
one didn't make the team, three will probably start and another 11
will play significantly.
</P>
<P>
   The predominance of young players does thrust Mariucci into an
unsolvable paradox. By the time the 49ers mature, the team will hit
the wall. Colleges play an 11-game schedule with no exhibition
season. After this summer's exhibition games, a rookie's body is
already telling him the season is half over.
</P>
<P>
   When November dawns, first- and second-year players will be
spent. But, frankly, another mediocre season is needed. At 4-12 or
5-11, the 49ers would once again position themselves well for
April's draft.
</P>
<P>
   The use of high-priced free agents to spackle holes in a roster
can send a team into salary-cap hell. No team knows better than the
49ers. So the draft is the only way to rebuild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
