<HEADER>
A4426 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV03-NYT     08-28 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
 By RAY CORMIER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Joan of Arc Tower
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the Tour de Jeanne d'Arc in Rouen, where Joan of Arc was
imprisoned, open to the public? _ Nicolina Tack, Madison, Wisc.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Joan of Arc tower is the sole remnant of a medieval
castle where Joan was imprisoned in 1430 during her trial. It and
the other important sites related to her in Rouen, on the Seine, 70
miles northwest of Paris, are around the Place du Vieux-Marche, the
old town center.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Joan was burned at the stake on May 30, 1431, and
traces from the fire are still visible on the ground, as are marks
from the tribunes set up for her judges. About 20 years ago, a
65-foot Cross of Rehabilitation was installed to commemorate this
spot, on the northern edge of the plaza. A small gallery of
drawings and signs tracing the history of Joan and of the Place du
Vieux-Marche stands beside the Jeanne d'Arc church, built in 1978
with Renaissance stained-glass windows saved from St. Vincent
Church, destroyed in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The castle tower is open to visitors. It has a small Joan of Arc
exhibit, with objects from the period and from the original castle.
Admission to the tower is about $1.35, at the rate of 7.3 francs to
the dollar, and free for those under 18. The tower is open from 10
a.m. to 12:30 p.m. and from 2 to 6 p.m., Wednesday through Saturday
and Sunday from 2 to 6:30 p.m. Information: (33-2) 35.98.55.10.
</P>
<P>
   The Musee Jeanne d'Arc, 33 Place du Vieux-Marche, houses waxwork
scenes from Joan's life, from her childhood in Domremy to her
death. It also displays several models of the 15th-century Place du
Vieux-Marche and historical objects.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is open from 9:30 a.m. to 1 p.m. and 1:30 to 7 p.m.
mid-April through mid-September, and 10 a.m. to noon and 2 to 6:30
p.m. the rest of the year. Admission is about $3.50, $1.75 for
those under 18 and students. Information: (33-2) 35.88.02.70 or
www.jeanne-darc.com.
</P>
<P>
   The tourist office in Rouen, perhaps the best source of
information on how to organize a small walking tour of the town, is
at 22 Place de la Cathedrale, and is open daily. A free brochure in
French and English, ``In the Footsteps of Joan of Arc,'' is
available to guide visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The office also has a roster of accredited bilingual guides for
group tours of Joan of Arc sites and of the winding cobbled streets
of Rouen's medieval quarter. You can reserve guided tours, about
$90, through the tourist office, (33-2) 32.08.32.40, or go to
www.mairie-rouen.fr/gb/tourism/index.html, for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to Newfoundland
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to visit my grandfather's birthplace, near Bonne Bay
on the western (French) coast of Newfoundland. Is it better to fly
into St. John's and drive across the island, or take a ferry? Is
there public transportation? _ Susan Stockwell Yates,
Croton-on-Hudson, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Newfoundland is not the easiest place to reach, and you'll
have to weigh time and cost in deciding how to get there. The best
source of information is the province's tourism information line,
(800) 563-6353.
</P>
<P>
   There are no nonstop flights from New York to Newfoundland; you
must go through Toronto or Halifax to St. John's, the provincial
capital. According to Travelocity.com, the lowest published fare
recently has been $637 round trip on Canadian Airlines, (800)
426-7000, or Air Canada, (888) 247-2262.
</P>
<P>
   Marine Atlantic, (800) 341-7941, runs four or five ferries daily
from North Sydney, Nova Scotia, to Port-aux-Basques, in southwest
Newfoundland, about 180 miles from Bonne Bay. A high-speed
catamaran leaves at 10:30 a.m. and 6:30 p.m., making the trip in
under three hours. Another ferry, taking about twice as long,
leaves at various times depending on the day. Both ferries cost
about $13.50, at 67 cents to the Canadian dollar, plus $42 a car.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a 15-hour ferry to Argentia, on the southeast
coast, about 65 miles from St. John's, should you want to visit the
capital and drive the 350 or so miles across the island. This ferry
leaves North Sydney on Monday, Wednesday and Friday at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   According to the tourist office, the only mass transit on
Newfoundland is the DRL bus line, (709) 738-8088. It charges $25
for the three-and-a-half-hour trip from Port-aux-Basques to Deer
Lake, near Bonne Bay, and $50 from St. John's to Deer Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Hostels in Macedonia
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am interested in biking and hiking in western Macedonia,
especially around Lake Ohrid. Do you know of any youth hostels or
similarly inexpensive accommodations? _ Nick Simmons, Madison,
Wisc.
</P>
<P>
   A. While Macedonia is a frontier for American travelers, the
area around Lake Ohrid has been a popular vacation destination for
years. Lakes Prespa and Dojran also are developing as summer
resorts, and the mountains around Mavrovo attract winter sports
enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign tourism in this former Yugoslav republic is still in its
infancy, though, so there isn't a lot of travel information
available. The Macedonian Youth Hostel Association is an associate
member of Hosteling International (www.iyhf.org), but reaching the
office in Skopje, the capital, where there is a 26-room hostel, is
a bit like playing roulette. The address is Prolet 25, 1000 Skopje;
phone (389-91) 239-947, fax (389-91) 235-029.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of information is the Croatian Youth Hostel
Association, Savska cesta 5-1, 10000 Zagreb, Croatia; (385-41)
482-9294, fax (385-41) 482-9296. According to the Croatian
association's president, Goran Richembergh, Macedonia is generally
safe for travelers and English not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   The Mladost Hostel, (389-96)21-626, is on the road to Struga,
two miles from Ohrid. It is open all year and charges about $3.50
for a bed and breakfast. The hostel is next to the Magnus Hotel,
(389-96) 21-671, which has 38 rooms, a restaurant and its own
beach. The Magnus charges about $24 a person, and reservations can
be made through the hostel association.
</P>
<P>
   A rare source of information about Macedonia in the United
States is Ohrid Travel, 264 Parker Ave., Clifton, N.J. 07011, (973)
340-3210, fax (973) 340-9124. The owner, Vera Svrgovska, said
hotels in the Lake Ohrid area are bargains but fill up quickly in
the summer. She pointed to the recently renovated 131-room Palace
Hotel, (389-96) 260-440, fax (389-96) 35460. It is right on the
lake in Ohrid and has two restaurants. Rooms, priced in German
marks, cost $24 to $33 a person, with breakfast, at 2 marks to the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the country, see www.vmacedonia.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
