<SLUG> BC-OLY-TABLE-TENNIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TABLE TENNIS CHAMP TAKES A LONG ROAD TO OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Khoa Nguyen was only 9 when the warning came.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of my dad's told him we had to leave Vietnam, now,''
Nguyen said.
</P>
<P>
   This was just before the North Vietnamese took over South
Vietnam in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to us was pretty unexpected,'' Nguyen said,
``but my dad was an air traffic controller for the U.S. government,
so he probably would have been put into a concentration camp if we
had stayed. So we just packed up. It was really hard because two of
my sisters were not living with us. We didn't want to leave them
behind, but we had to.''
</P>
<P>
   It was several years before the family _ Nguyen's parents and
his three brothers and three sisters _ was reunited in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived in a small town in Arkansas first,'' Nguyen said,
``then two years later we drove all the way to California and
settled in Stockton, before moving to San Jose in 1980.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe as a needed diversion amid all the turbulence, Nguyen's
dad, who had played some table tennis in Vietnam, began teaching
the game to Khoa and his brothers, Khai, Roger and Khoi.
</P>
<P>
   Khoa was something of a natural.
</P>
<P>
   By the age of 15, he was a member of the U.S. junior national
team, and at 21 he won a gold medal at the 1987 Pan American Games
and competed at the world championships.
</P>
<P>
   And then, in 1988, his long Olympic odyssey began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't too close to making the U.S. team that year,'' he
said, ``but I was the first alternate in both 1992 and 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   Which might have been worse than finishing far out of the
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was especially tough not to make it in 1996,'' Nguyen said.
``I took a lot of time off from work to train and play, and I was
really focused.''
</P>
<P>
   He also was coming off a brilliant year in 1995. After spending
considerable time training in Sweden against top world players, he
won the national doubles title, was runner-up in singles and was
named U.S. Table Tennis Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   But at the '96 Olympic trials, Nguyen lost to Todd Sweeris, a
player who had never beaten him, for the third U.S. team spot in
Atlanta. And after that disappointment, Nguyen decided he'd had
enough of table tennis.
</P>
<P>
   He had graduated from San Jose State University with a computer
science degree in 1991, and decided to concentrate on his career as
a senior software engineer and his family.
</P>
<P>
   But the lure of sport was always there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I stopped in '96, I was at my peak,'' he said. ``I was
playing really well. So in late 1998, I decided I wanted to start
training for the Sydney Olympics. I was lucky that my company
manager was a gymnastics coach and judge. He understood and
supported me. That was the key. From then on, I started training
really hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But the return wasn't smooth at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult decision to start playing again
because it meant I would have less time to spend with my family.''
(He and his wife Pauline have two daughters, Khamille, 3, and
Khassidy, 1.)
</P>
<P>
   He also found that a number of his former competitors were
surprised that he was back, and some of them weren't too happy
about it. And some of his touch, which included perhaps the best
forehand attack of any American player, didn't come back
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating,'' he said. ``The first tournament, I lost
to players I had never lost to before.''
</P>
<P>
   Things gradually turned around, however, and Nguyen, who'll turn
34 in October, was undefeated in the first of this year's Olympic
trials. He didn't play as well at the second trials, the North
American singles qualifying tournament, but he partnered with Cheng
Yinghua of Montgomery Village, Md., to win the doubles there and
finally earn a trip to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbelievable,'' Nguyen said. ``I never could have
imagined this would happen now. But I know I appreciate it more at
this stage of my life than I would have earlier. Pauline and I had
our honeymoon in Sydney in 1993, so it's going to be really nice to
get back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
