<SLUG> BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASTERT OFFERS KEY CONCESSIONS ON RAISING MINIMUM WAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated.) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT and LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Dennis Hastert on Monday offered key
concessions to Democrats on a plan to raise the federal minimum
wage, moving to end months of stalemate on a popular bill that
Republicans feared would damage them at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate earlier this year approved an increase in
the minimum wage by $1, to $6.15 an hour, but since then the
proposal has stalled causing some Republicans to fear they are
handing Democrats a potent campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   With only five weeks left on the congressional calendar after
lawmakers return from summer recess next week, Hastert sought in a
letter Monday to take that threat off the table. He agreed to
Democrats' demands to spread the $1 increase over two years, not
three years as Republicans had wanted.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed dropping pension provisions and a repeal of the
estate tax attached to the bill that Democrats criticized as a
giveaway to wealthy Americans. The measure would still contain $76
billion in tax breaks over 10 years, mainly to small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very clear that a vast majority of congressional
Democrats and Republicans would like to see a balanced approach
before we adjourn,'' said Hastert, who said Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott of Mississippi shared his views.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address on July 29, just before the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, Clinton appealed to
Republicans to help end the procedural impasse that has blocked
passage of the first minimum wage increase since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Republican leaders really want to make their compassion
count, they ought to join me in getting back to business and
raising the minimum wage,'' Clinton said. ``I hope the majority
will join the Democrats to seize this moment, to stop the delays,
to work with me to help our working families.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats applauded Hastert's offer, but seemed
tempted to squeeze even more political mileage out his obvious
political predicament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal that the speaker made was in the right
direction,'' said Rep. David Bonior of Michigan, the second-ranking
House Democrat. ``It raises the question of whether 50 cents a year
is enough or whether we want to do 50 cents a year over three
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4430 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER0829-COX     08-28 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A prescription for campaign gains
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With polls suggesting that voters view Al Gore as the candidate
most likely to boost the nation's health care system, his campaign
moved this week to put the issue front and center. Gore began a
weeklong focus on health care Monday by telling older voters his
plan for prescription drug coverage will help them while George W.
Bush offers only political ads. Gore campaigned at a small pharmacy
in Tallahassee, Fla., to underscore his drug proposals. He knelt
and spoke with Myrtle Jennings, 82, who said she has to choose
among her prescriptions because she can't afford the more than $200
in a month in drug expenses. The Democratic National Committee is
backing Gore with a new ad on prescription drugs to begin running
today in nine states.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION AS CAMPAIGN ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   Along with economic and health care issues, Joe Lieberman keeps
bringing up God. ``We are not only citizens of this blessed
country; we are children of the same awesome God,'' he said at an
interfaith breakfast with about 150 Chicago religious leaders. On
Sunday, touching on the constitutional separation of church and
state, Lieberman told members of a black church in Detroit that he
hopes his candidacy as an Orthodox Jew will reinstate ``a place for
faith in America's public life.'' But Lieberman also gave a nod to
nonbelievers. He said people of faith must ``reassure them that we
share with them the core values of America, that our faith is not
inconsistent with their freedom, and our mission is not one of
intolerance, but one of love.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW TROUBLED THE MILITARY?
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney acknowledged in a series of television interviews
that George W. Bush may not have been entirely correct when he
charged in his convention speech that some military units are not
currently prepared to fight a war. Cheney conceded that Bush had
used out-of-date data when he said that two of the Army's 10
divisions are not prepared for battle. But the vice presidential
candidate and former defense secretary said Democrats have overseen
a military deterioraton in the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
   BIG BUSINESS IN PEACEKEEPING
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton Co., the giant oilfield services company run by Dick
Cheney until he joined the Republican presidential ticket, reaped
$2.2 billion in Pentagon contracts to feed, house and support U.S.
troops on Clinton-era peacekeeping missions that George W. Bush
said have helped run down the military. U.S. military deployments
in Bosnia, Kosovo, Somalia and elsewhere are the kinds of missions
Bush has pledged to reduce if elected. Halliburton's Brown &AMP; Root
Services construction subsidiary has received the lion's share of
the Pentagon's troop support business in the years since the
Persian Gulf War, which Cheney helped direct as secretary of
defense under Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY'S EARLY RETIREMENT
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney said he's examining different scenarios and ``will
take any steps I have to'' to avoid a possible conflict of interest
involving Halliburton Co. stock options worth millions of dollars.
After five years as CEO at the Dallas-based oilfield services
company, Cheney is walking away with about $33.7 million in stock
and stock rights. The early retirement package includes options to
buy 1.16 million Halliburton shares (currently around $54 a share),
more than 233,000 of which can't be exercised until 2001 and 2002,
after the new administration comes into power. The Democrats are
seeking to make hay of the retirement package, saying the oil
industry is investing in what they derisively label the ``Big Oil''
ticket of Cheney and George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   THERE'S THE POPULAR VOTE . . .
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore continues to cling to a small lead over George W. Bush,
a new Newsweek poll shows. Registered voters favor Gore 46 percent
to 42 percent over Bush in a four-way match-up that includes the
Green Party's Ralph Nader and the Reform Party's Pat Buchanan. The
results are similar in a two-way match-up, with 49 percent favoring
Gore and 45 percent favoring Bush. Both surveys had a margin of
error of plus or minus 4 percentage points, making Gore's lead just
barely statistically significant.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND THERE'S THE ELECTORAL VOTE
</P>
<P>
   National polls show the presidential race neck and neck, but
according to a state-by-state breakdown by National Journal's
Hotline, George W. Bush is leading by a huge margin where it really
counts: in the Electoral College. Surveying poll results from 31
states, Hotline found Bush leading in 23 states with 246 electoral
votes _ just 24 fewer than the 270 needed to win in November. By
comparison, Al Gore was leading in just eight states, with 170
electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-AMERICAN PAC MAKES PICK
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, an Asian-American political action committee
has endorsed a presidential nominee. and vowed to deliver 80
percent of Asian-American votes to Al Gore. The action by the 80-20
Initiative in Los Angeles followed two days of spirited
discussions, debates and caucusing over which presidential nominee
would best serve the interests of the nation's 11 million people of
Asian ancestry. Chang-lin Tien, former chancellor of the University
of California-Berkeley and chairman of the endorsement committee,
was quick to note that neither political party has done a lot ``to
advance issues'' important to Asian-Americans. But on balance, he
said, Gore and the Democrats have done more.
</P>
<P>
   BUT WHEN YOU HAVE TO SUE _
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, who as Texas governor successfully pushed for
tort law legislation limiting lawsuits, filed a case of his own
against a rental car agency over a minor accident involving one of
his daughters. Bush, according to the New York Daily News, sued
Enterprise Rent-A-Car in April 1999 for the Sept. 8, 1998,
accident. No one was hurt, and police weren't called. The lawsuit
said his 1995 Jeep Cherokee was hit while one of Bush's twin
daughters, Jenna, was driving. The lawsuit alleged that Enterprise
shared blame because it had rented a car to a driver with a
suspended license. The case was settled within a few months for
$2,000-$2,500, Breen said.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN TO CARRY PARTY BANNER IN S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, who finished second in South Carolina's 1996
Republican presidential primary, will be on the ballot this
November. But this time Buchanan will be the Reform Party's
candidate, after edging quantum physicist John Hagelin at the
party's state convention over the weekend. Meeting behind locked
doors in West Columbia, delegates voted 12-10 to put Buchanan's
name on the state's November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   DIVERGENT VIEWS ON DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' positions on debates seems to be as divergent as
their competing plans for tax cuts. Al Gore wants to participate in
as many as possible; George W. Bush is willing to have a few, but
he wants to control the format as much as possible. And in the
process, says the New York Times, Bush is challenging the
organization the parties set up in 1984 to hold presidential
debates. The Commission on Presidential Debates set the first one
at the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard, but the
Bush camp considers Boston to be hostile turf. Bush also wants a
more relaxed format _ more like a Larry King show than
Lincoln-Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
