<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How political opposites reconcile differences
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone knows that politics make strange bedfellows, but as the
cover story in George ($2.95) points out, some bedfellows make
strange politics. Reporter Michele Willens takes a look at how
married couples such as Cindy Crawford and Rande Gerber, James
Carville and Mary Matalin, Arnold Schwarzenegger and Maria Shriver
handle their political differences. Mostly, says Shriver, she and
her Republican husband never talk about politics.
</P>
<P>
   Also of note, Lydia Chavez addresses the problem of popular
culture and violence and why the candidates are not speaking out on
the topic. Since Tipper Gore began her crusade against explicit
song lyrics 15 years ago, hate rappers such as Eminem have emerged
to dominate the airwaves. So why are Al Gore and George W. Bush
avoiding the issue? No one wants to risk losing votes and campaign
money from Hollywood, Chavez says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More than cookies: It's hard to imagine Martha Stewart crying
about anything, but the style maven confesses to shedding tears
daily in an interview with Oprah Winfrey in O, the Oprah Magazine
($2.95). ``Every day there is something more important to cry about
than business,'' Stewart says. ``I can handle my business, but I
can't handle famine in Ethiopia.'' She apparently is still having
trouble handling her divorce. Stewart seems a little miffed when
Winfrey asks her about her relationship with ex-husband Andrew
Stewart. ``I don't even care about that anymore,'' she says. ``I'm
sorry that I haven't spoken to him _ or he hasn't spoken to me _
for all these years.'' Oprah's magazine, by the way, appears to be
a big success despite problems with the editorial staff. This
month's ad-packed 320-page issue is heftier than some phone books.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Uncomplicating your life: Real Simple ($2.95) was the target
of much criticism when it debuted earlier this year, primarily
because it focused on upscale lifestyles with ads for $250
sweaters. Well, the magazine's advertisers still cater to the
well-to-do, but the articles have gotten more informative. The
September issue (with a cover photo of a porch swing at Greyfield
Inn on Cumberland Island) features articles on hiring a caregiver,
organizing your closets, finding the right indoor grill and the
benefits of debit cards.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Looking ahead: Both Time ($3.50) and Newsweek ($3.50) offer
fall previews of the best in movies, books, art, music, theater and
television. Likely hits include CBS' ``Bette'' with Bette Midler,
the film version of ``Charlie's Angels'' and the yet-to-be-titled
CD from the Backstreet Boys. In the literary field, Newsweek
recommends ``The Blind Assassin'' by Margaret Atwood and ``On
Writing'' by Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Booked: Speaking of things literary, Book ($4.95) features a
cover story on Anne Rice on the eve of the release of ``Merrick,''
her new witchcraft/vampire novel, a profile of ``Remains of the
Day'' author Kazuo Ishiguro, an interview with science fiction
pioneer Ursula K. Le Guin and a roundup of the best books written
about all the U.S. presidents. And, yes, there is a biography of
Millard Fillmore.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New on the stands: Men's Health has launched a new magazine,
MH-18 ($2.99), aimed at guys in the 13-18 age range. Written in a
hipper style than its older brother, MH-18 offers a variety of
lifestyle articles to complement its pieces on health and exercise.
For example, the premier issue features pieces on dirtboarding,
dating, successful teens and the latest in backpacks, video games
and high-tech gadgets. The magazine is scheduled to go bimonthly
next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Long before ``Survivor's'' Richard Hatch emerged
as the man we loved to hate, tennis pro John McEnroe filled that
role. Now older and mellower, McEnroe tells The New Yorker ($3)
some of his outbursts on the court were simply theatrical. McEnroe
is complimentary of Venus and Serena Williams but can't resist
declaring that ``any good male college player'' could beat
them..... Discover ($4.99) reports that science and technology will
be a major factor in the success of Olympic athletes in Sydney. For
instance, Olympic boxer David Jackson is training on a computerized
punching bag that analyzes each jab or hook, and the U.S. archery
team is using arrows with a slippery carbon-graphite coating that
reduces drag.... Everything you want to know about fall fashion
trends for men can be found in the 450-page September issue of GQ
($3.50). Articles include how to dress according to your age and
the latest in the collections from Paris and Milan. Nonfashion
features include an interview with Kid Rock _ who talks about
Britney Spears, Madonna and his days of dealing crack _ and a first
look at Ford's new Thunderbird.... In an unscientific but
interesting poll, People ($2.99) asked 1,000 women about their
bodies and how their self-esteem is influenced by Hollywood stars.
Eighty percent said images of women in entertainment and
advertising made them feel insecure about their looks. So who do
women want to look like? First choice was Cindy Crawford (21
percent), followed by Halle Berry (18 percent) and Jennifer Lopez
(15 percent).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
