<SLUG> BC-SPAS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spas can help lead to better health, but real challenge comes
after leaving
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brenda Levinson came back from the spa a new woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really healthy,'' says the 28-year-old Alpharetta
teacher, recalling the afterglow from a four-day getaway to Canyon
Ranch in the Berkshires, in Lenox, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson, who braved the upscale retreat's rigorous fitness and
nutrition programs with her mother, Fran Wolkstein, was in such
fine fettle she had a hard time settling back in to the sins of
daily life.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few days after, we went out to dinner with my father,'' she
says. ``It was this big Italian meal. My mother and I just looked
at each other and looked at the food. We couldn't eat half of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many spa guests end their stays in a similar state of detoxed
euphoria. And more people than ever are feeling the rush, using a
spa experience as a way to jump-start a resolve for healthier
living. The number of total spa visits, including day spas and
extended-stay resorts, rose 16 percent from 1998 to 1999 to an
average of 33,000 visits per spa annually, according to a survey
conducted last year by the Kentucky-based International Spa
Association. Of those visitors, 35 percent were men _ a substantial
increase over previous years.
</P>
<P>
   But the fit feeling that follows you home may be fleeting.
Whether the focus is on fitness, diet, stress-reduction or a
combination of the three, sustaining the momentum of the spa's
programs requires planning and perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   Those are also the necessary skills for any healthy lifestyle
change, but a spa visit offers a starting advantage.
</P>
<P>
   `` It removes temptation _ you're not sitting next to a
refrigerator full of goodies,'' says Walter Inge, 67, a freelance
medical writer from northwest Atlanta who spent a week this summer
at the Tennessee Fitness Spa, near Waynesboro, Tenn. ``Also, it
helps that you're with a group of people who are working toward the
same goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is to keep the regimen going outside that
insulated atmosphere. For dieters at least, the odds are long _
researchers at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
estimate that 80 percent to 95 percent of people who diet will
eventually gain back whatever weight they lost.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Gilburth, director of the Center for New Beginnings, a
facility in Dahlonega that hosts wellness groups, cautions that the
transition from a health retreat to the noisy, smoggy workaday
world can be ``a shock. You keep asking `Which world is real?'''
</P>
<P>
   You should prepare yourself for an onslaught of distractions
from work, family and friends. ``Expect everything and everybody,
including yourself, to try and get in the way of practicing what
you've learned'' Gilburth says. ``It's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Udell, lifestyle director at the Pritikin Longevity
Center &AMP; Spa in Aventura, Fla., has heard all the excuses for
falling off the fitness wagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always, `I'm taking care of my
mother/father/child/uncle/neighbor.' Or `I'm in charge of the
church suppers,' or `I travel too much for my job.' But you need to
make time for you. I call it being healthfully selfish.''
</P>
<P>
   That may include distancing from friends who are mired in bad
habits. ``If you hang out with people who smoke and drink and say,
`Fried calamari for everybody!,' you are fighting an uphill
battle,'' Udell says.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Wickersham is trying hard to live the lessons she learned
from a trip to the Green Valley Spa in St. George, Utah, in
February. A freelance marketing specialist for the wellness
industry and a vegetarian for 10 years, Wickersham, 52, of
Buckhead, has always prided herself on her healthy habits. But the
spa's nutrition program _ heavy on the whole grains and fresh
fruits and vegetables _ made her take a second look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I wasn't being good,'' she says. ``I was eating too
many refined foods, too much pasta, too much high-fat salad
dressing _ little things that taste good but that you should do
without.''
</P>
<P>
   Those indulgences caused her to gain 15 pounds over two years.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning from the spa, Wickersham has changed her ways.
``I used to eat pasta two or three times a week, now I try to stick
to once every two weeks,'' she says. ``And I try to use vegetable
juice salad dressings that are less than 20 calories a serving.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, she became a vegan, cutting animal products entirely
out of her diet. She also walks up to four miles a day.
</P>
<P>
   The diligence has paid off _ Wickersham has lost five pounds
since February. But she admits it can be a struggle. ``I continue
to work at it. If you go to an Italian restaurant, what do you eat?
But I think I'm doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Mira Bergen's post-spa lifestyle may include a career change. A
commercial real estate agent for 17 years, Bergen traveled to the
Pura Vida spa in Costa Rica earlier this month ``to de-stress and
detox. I realized I hadn't been on a vacation since 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   There, the 53-year-old Buckhead resident found stress relief by
taking classes in Bikram yoga, a practice in which yoga movements
are performed in a room heated to more than 100 degrees. ``It's
wonderful,'' Bergen says. ``It cleanses all the toxins from your
body.''
</P>
<P>
   She's continuing the practice at the Bikram Yoga school on
Cheshire Bridge Road, and taking a hard look at her high-stress
occupation. ``I've realized I'm a caregiver, and that I'd like to
incorporate more of that into my life.'' A certified reflexologist,
Bergen plans to augment her real estate practice with work at
alternative treatment centers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important key to staying on track, experts say,
is cutting yourself some slack. ``If you have a relapse _ I call it
an `oops' _ you forgive yourself and continue on,'' Udell advises.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Hampton, fitness director for the Tennessee Fitness Spa,
agrees. ``Maybe you've had a bad day at work and you come home and
eat the whole chocolate cake. Let it go. Yesterday's gone and
tomorrow brings a new start. This is not something you're going to
do for the next six months. This is for the rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
