<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 3)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Western Wildfires Disrupt Vacations
</P>
<P>
   The wildfires that have swept through parts of a dozen Western
states this summer, destroying homes, businesses and millions of
acres of recreational land, have also disrupted or ruined vacations
and crippled businesses dependent on the tourist trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an absolute disaster for campers, hikers, rafters
and other outdoorsmen over a big portion of the West,'' said
Dorothy Maitland, the owner of Travel by Maitland, a tour operator
in Kalispell, Mont. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A major entrance to Yellowstone National Park was closed for
several days in mid-August, Grand Teton National Park in Wyoming
was shrouded in smoke, and fear of wildfires kept visitors away
from Glacier National Park in Montana. Mesa Verde National Park in
Colorado, a trove of ancient cliff dwellings and ancient Anasazi
artifacts, was closed twice for a total of almost three weeks
before reopening Aug. 14.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although small businesses near recreational areas have suffered
and individuals have had to change camping and hiking plans, tour
operators in the affected states had surprisingly few
cancellations. They juggled schedules; when the south entrance to
Yellowstone was closed, some went in via the west, said Keither
Griffall, chief executive of Western Leisure in Salt Lake City.
``It took another three hours or so, but by staying in close touch
with the Forest Service we were not badly affected.'' And as long
as visitors do not think they are in danger, he said, many of them
enjoy what he described as ``a little spice'' during their tours. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Mesa Verde was closed, Tauck Tours of Westport, Conn.,
rescheduled tours to Aztec Ruins National Monument in New Mexico.
``We had a lot of people calling to inquire,'' said Phil Otterson,
a vice president, ``but we had very few cancellations.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maitland, a former president of the National Tour Association,
said that there was a falloff in early August, but that tours
picked up when her company stuck to most itineraries and
rescheduled others. ``But it was definitely a challenge,'' she
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The United States Forest Service's Web site for checking fire
conditions is www .fs.fed.us/fire/news.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Symphony Hall Turns 100 With a Splash
</P>
<P>
   A concert and an open house with free performances are two of
the events scheduled next month to celebrate the 100th birthday of
Symphony Hall in Boston, home of the Boston Symphony Orchestra.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the concert, on Oct. 14, Seiji Ozawa, music director of the
orchestra since 1973, will share the podium with Keith Lockhart,
conductor of the Boston Pops, which also performs in the hall, and
the composer John Williams, Lockhart's predecessor. Soloists that
night will include the cellist Yo-Yo Ma and the violinist Gil
Shaham, with the Tanglewood Festival Chorus and the Chieftains, the
traditional Irish band.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at the open house the next day, from noon to 10 p.m.,
will be the Boston Symphony, the Boston Pops, the Boston Pops
Gospel Choir, the Greater Boston Youth Orchestra, the Handel and
Haydn Society Chorus, as well as jazz groups from the Berkeley
School of Music, the New England Conservatory, the Longy School of
Music and the Boston Conservatory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting this month and running through July, the orchestra will
offer free tours of the hall on Tuesday morning and Wednesday
afternoon and on the first Saturday of the month, except December. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the fall and spring, an exhibition in the corridors
will focus on the making of the hall and its role in 20th century
music. The hall was designed by Charles F. McKim of McKim, Mead &AMP;
White and opened on Oct. 15, 1900. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A limited number of tickets, costing $90 to $500, are available
for the Oct. 14 concert. Another event in the hall, a benefit ball
on Oct. 12, will include a Champagne reception, dinner and dancing
to the Peter Duchin Orchestra, for $2,000 a person.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information: (617) 638-9422; concert tickets: (888) 266-1200 or
www.bso.org.
</P>
<P>
   Designers Tackle a Colonial House
</P>
<P>
   Mount Hope Farm, a Colonial house in Bristol, R.I., has been
chosen as the site for the Newport Showhouse Guild's Showhouse
2000. It will be open to the public from Saturday through Oct. 9.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Built by Isaac Royal in 1745 and added to in 1840 and 1890, the
four-bedroom, two-story Colonial house is on the National Register
of Historic Places. William Bradford, the Rhode Island governor and
later a United States senator, bought the property in 1783 and
played host to George Washington there. In 1917, R.F. Haffenreffer
took over, and the house remained in the Haffenreffer family until
1999 when the Mount Hope Trust acquired it. The estate, on the
banks of Mount Hope Bay, comprises 127 tree-filled acres; it also
has a barn, a playhouse, a 10-room guest cottage and a pool house.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eight landscape designers and gardeners and 26 interior
designers _ many from Rhode Island and some from as far away as
England _ have signed on for the transformation. Among the
highlights will be the kitchen and breakfast room designed by Joan
Peters of Osterville Inc. in Osterville, Mass., and the library by
Ron Alose, a Newport interior designer. Albert Lynch and William
Hullsman of William Hullsman Designs in Beverly, Mass., will
recreate the pool house with a snappy 1940s cocktail flavor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The house will be open daily from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. On
Wednesdays, designers will be present from noon to 8 p.m. Tickets
are $20. A luncheon followed by a lecture and slide presentation by
Chris Casson Madden, a writer about design and a television
personality, is scheduled for Sept. 16. Lecture and lunch, $50,
lecture only, $35. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A special Bristol Day Ticket, which includes admission to the
house as well as to the nearby Blithewold Mansion, Gardens and
Arboretum and to Linden Place, an 1810 Federal mansion, is also
available. Bristol Day tickets are $30. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information: (877) 694-7300 or (401) 253-8585;
www.newportshowhouse.com.
</P>
<P>
   Holocaust Exhibit at London Museum
</P>
<P>
   A permanent exhibit devoted to the Holocaust has opened in a new
five-floor wing of London's Imperial War Museum.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The main focus of the exhibit, which takes up 13,000 square feet
of space on two floors, is the persecution of European Jews,
beginning with the turbulent post-World War I period when radical
movements were flourishing on both left and right.
</P>
<P>
   Persecution of other groups, such as Gypsies, Poles, Soviet
prisoners of war, people with disabilities, homosexuals and
prisoners of conscience, is also addressed in the exhibits, which
include photographs, documents, newspapers, posters, archival film
and interviews with Holocaust survivors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sections are entitled Jewish life before the Nazis; Euthanasia;
News Reaches Britain; Invasion of the Soviet Union; Jewish Armed
Resistance; Inside the Camps; Rescue and Survival; Destroying the
Evidence; and War Crimes Trials. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the exhibits are a deportation railroad car acquired from
Belgian Railways and a funeral cart used in the Warsaw ghetto. Also
on view are personal mementoes, letters, diaries, family
photographs and concentration camp uniforms. There is also a model
of Auschwitz 40 feet long.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Imperial War Museum, Lambeth Road, London SE1 6HZ; (44-891)
600-140 (recorded information), (44-207) 416-5320; www.iwm.org.uk.
The museum is open from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. daily, exhibit from 10:15
a.m. to 5 p.m. Not recommended for children under 14. Admission
$8.35; free for children under 16 and seniors. Advance booking is
advisable on (44-207) 416-5439.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
