<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OLYMPICS: WOMAN HAVE COME A LONG WAY, BUT NOT FAR ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ To great fanfare, the Olympics are letting in
more women than ever. They are also letting too many of them off
easily.
</P>
<P>
   In road cycling, that second X chromosome is good for a
119-kilometer discount.
</P>
<P>
   Women swimmers stop at 800 meters freestyle. The men do 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain bikers cover 40 to 50 kilometers if they are male, only
30 to 40 if they are female.
</P>
<P>
   What are the Olympic pooh-bahs so afraid of? The specter of
fainting spells and smelling salts should have evaporated by now.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there was quite a panic during the first marathon for
women, in 1984, when a Swiss runner entered the Los Angeles
Coliseum looking like a zombie, wobbling, listing to one side, her
eyes glazed.
</P>
<P>
   But if Gabriele Andersen-Scheiss was evidence that women lack
the fortitude to race 26 miles, gold medalist Joan Benoit was a
stunning rebuttal. She won the U.S. Olympic trials 17 days after
undergoing knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a male rower has passed out in a pairs race, and a
female gymnast has vaulted onto a damaged ankle. Kerri Strug's wild
leap became one of the great video highlights from Atlanta _ and a
thorough repudiation of Barron Pierre de Coubertin's justification
for keeping women out of the original modern Games in 1896.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is indecent,'' he said, ``that the spectators of these
Games should be exposed to the risk of seeing the body of a woman
smashed before their very eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   A mere 104 years later, listen to Mark Schubert, coach of the
U.S. men's swim team: ``It's degrading to the women that they don't
do the 1,500 at the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Schubert, the mentor to backstroke superstar Lenny Krayzelburg,
has coached some of the best distance swimmers in U.S. history,
including Janet Evans. The best-known American swimmer since Mark
Spitz, Evans probably never swam her best event on the grand
Olympic stage.
</P>
<P>
   She was a pure distance swimmer, and her windmill stroke looked
utterly tireless over 1,500 meters. She could swim the event at
world championships, at national championships, but not at the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But coaches like Schubert never push for a 1,500 without
clarifying that they want to keep the 800, and extend it to men,
too. Now, male swimmers jump from the 400 to 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Don Talbot, head of the Australian swimming program, visited the
U.S. Swimming Trials and talked to several American coaches about
advocating for an 800 and 1,500 for both sexes. He knows how hard
it is to get new events added, and he worries that the
International Olympic Committee will only expand in the direction
of the sexier, more-ready-for-prime-time sprints. Already, three
new 50-meter races, in the breaststroke, backstroke and butterfly,
are in line to become events at the world championships.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the disparity between men's and women's distances has
nothing to do with sexism anymore. Maybe it's just about the bias
against taxing the television viewer's attention span.
</P>
<P>
   If the 1896 definition of indecency was watching a woman crash
on a track, the 2000 version is imagining the semi-mythical soccer
mom _ the prime target for Olympic broadcasts _ hitting her remote
control.
</P>
<P>
   But that can't be the explanation for the difference in the
race-walk, which could last five city blocks and still not end up
on TV in its entirety. The women will race 20K in Sydney, up from
10K in Atlanta. The men have a 20K and a 50K, which, like
fraternity hazings and prostate trouble, doesn't seem to be the
source of much female envy.
</P>
<P>
   But equality is equality. And the absence of a women's 50K is a
direct descendant of Barron Pierre's silly remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Debbi Lawrence has qualified for three Olympics in race-walking.
When the distance doubled for 2000, she had doubts about her
ability to adapt. She never considered herself, as a woman, low on
stamina. She had simply conditioned herself to be a 10K racer
because that's what would get her into the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence is a case of supply following demand. Until 1988, she
had only dabbled in race-walking when an injury prevented her from
running. Then the IOC announced that in 1992 women would be allowed
to compete in the discipline, which had been held for men since
1908. Lawrence became a full-time race-walker.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many 50K walkers among women right now. The
Olympics still ask for more from men.
</P>
<P>
   Next time around, the Olympic Games should pile on the yardage,
the mileage. The women can take it. They always could.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
