<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LIGHT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     08-28 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
` PROPERTIES OF LIGHT':   CEREBRAL ARDOR IN AFFAIRS OF THE MIND AND
THE HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rebecca Goldstein's characters are descendants of Ingmar
Bergman's chilly intellectuals and Nathaniel Hawthorne's
coldhearted curmudgeons. They want to subordinate the heart to the
head, the spirit to the word; they dream of perfectly controlled
worlds where messy emotions are subjugated to the ordering dictates
of reason.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Childs, the narrator of Ms. Goldstein's lumpy new novel,
``Properties of Light,'' is no exception. Like Eva in ``The
Late-Summer Passion of a Woman of Mind'' and Hedda in ``The Dark
Sister,'' Justin lives inside his head, and he has equipped himself
with forbidding intellectual armor. Even as a child he was an
absolutist, reciting the law of the excluded middle. (``Every
statement is either true or false, and no statement is both!'')
Now, as a physicist at a well-known university, he devotes his days
and nights to trying to decipher the hidden rules of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Justin's affair with a beautiful young woman named Dana _ who
just happens to be the daughter of an eminent physicist named
Mallach, revered by Justin for his unorthodox theories _ tests his
rationalist view of the world and gives Ms. Goldstein a chance to
explore her perennial themes about the dichotomies between mind and
body, intellect and passion, logos and eros.
</P>
<P>
   It is Ms. Goldstein's achievement in this volume that she has
managed that very difficult task of making palpable the sort of
cerebral ardor possessed by scientists and thinkers working at the
very height of their powers. She communicates the almost erotic
power that ideas can impart, ``the bliss'' experienced by Justin
and his colleagues when they make a breakthrough in their work,
lifting ``a bit of the heavy veil the material world wears across
her face'' to catch ``a feature of a feature never quite so
glimpsed before.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing this, however, she spends an enormous amount of time
trying to convey to the reader the intricacies of Justin's work in
quantum mechanics, a feat she never manages to pull off. There are
pages and pages of ponderous and _ to the lay reader, at least _
perplexing discussions of matters like ``wave function,'' something
that is ``Lorentz invariant'' and ``backwards causation.'' Worse,
the novel's characters are given to saying things like:
``Nonlocality is merely the expression of quantum entanglement.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, who once taught philosophy at Barnard College, is
interested in using Justin and Mallach's theories about ``a
realistic model of nonrelativistic quantum mechanics'' to explore
the relationship between reality and theory, and the role that
randomness and chance may play in the cosmos, concepts that also
serve as metaphors for her characters' personal dilemmas.
Unfortunately her descriptions of their work feel so contrived, not
to mention impenetrable, that the reader's attention soon begins to
wander.
</P>
<P>
   Her depictions of her characters' emotional lives can be equally
heavy-handed. Justin comes across as a parody of the arrogant,
unfeeling scientist. He's the sort of fellow who seasons his
childhood reminiscences with Latinisms and who cannot comprehend
the notion that there are sensations ``that lay deeper down than
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   He grows irritated with Dana for adoring her dead mother,
because he regards her mother as a clownish drunk with silly New
Age beliefs. And he's so possessive of Dana that he resents her for
having an inner life inaccessible to him: ``It was a torment to
need so desperately to know the contents of her mind, the hidden
variables behind her words and silences and laughter, the varieties
of intent behind her murmured mmm's.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana herself emerges as a sort of variation on Rappaccini's
daughter, depicted in the Hawthorne story of that name. She has
devoted her life to her brilliant, eccentric father, and her
devotion alters the course of her life. She is a strange, dreamy
girl, described as being ``mind-proud'' the way ``other women are
house- or husband-proud.''
</P>
<P>
   As for her father, Mallach, he is portrayed as a sort of alter
ego to Justin _ another enormously gifted but fatally self-absorbed
physicist with a similar proclivity to anger. Years ago, we're
told, Mallach formulated a groundbreaking theory that was ignored
by the academic establishment, and that experience, coupled with
his wife's betrayal, has driven him to the brink of madness.
</P>
<P>
   He has more or less put aside the practice of physics until
Justin appears on the scene and proposes that they _ along with
Dana _ collaborate on finding a way to reconcile quantum mechanics
and relativity, ``the two monumental theories of 20th-century
physics.'' It is a hubristic proposal that reawakens not only
Mallach's long-buried scientific gifts but also his fury at being
marginalized and betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's impossible not to admire Goldstein's efforts to
write a Gothic suspense story that's also a novel of ideas, her
characters remain too two-dimensional and her storytelling too
ponderous for the reader to ever become fully engaged. There are
some brilliant glimpses of scientists' passion for their work and
some well-observed depictions of life in the hothouse world of
academe, but in the end, sadly, they're not enough for either a
thriller or a philosophic novel.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `PROPERTIES OF LIGHT'
</P>
<P>
   By Rebecca Goldstein
</P>
<P>
   244 pages. Houghton Mifflin. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
