<HEADER>
A4446 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PRACTICAlMAN0829-COX     08-28 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAlMAN0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Practical man turned off by appliance salesman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - The practical man went to war last week.
</P>
<P>
   At an appliance store.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, he knows. That's what he gets for breaking his First
Commandment _ thou shalt not shop. But he did it for you.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so he also needed a fridge. But that's not why he was there.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, when the practical man needs an appliance, he doesn't
go shopping. He visits his favorite used-appliance joint and tells
the owner to load the truck with as much appliance as $150 will
buy. This brilliant stroke not only saves time and money. The units
never fail to last a few years, and once or twice, the colors have
even matched the kitchen countertop.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the practical man was out to save the world.
Before he made his purchase, he'd price new refrigerators,
calculate how much he saved buying used, and spread the gospel in
his column. But when he opened the door of the new-appliance store,
he stepped into the line of fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's it going!? My name's Paul. How can I help you today?''
</P>
<P>
   A raw recruit on the consumer battleground, the practical man
was stunned by the barrage but kept his head. He knew better than
to look the enemy in the eye, so he stealthily scoped out the scene
with a sideways glance.
</P>
<P>
   Paul _ pudgy, bald, middle-aged _ had broken away from a platoon
of salesmen bivouacking at the customer service desk. He was
charging right for the practical man with ... was that an
outstretched hand or _ sweet Jesus! _ a bayonet? To slow him down,
the practical man slung some lead of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just looking,'' he shot back, then bolted behind a massive
Magic Chef range. But portly Paul was Private Persistence. Smelling
blood, he boinked his scorched skull around the exhaust hood, then
blindly sprayed the area with a hail of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, look around. What you see isn't all we have. We can
order anything you want. If you have any questions, just give me a
holler. Name's Paul.''
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, the practical man made it to the microwaves with
his pocketbook unpunctured, and then an eerie hush fell on the
killing field. Warily, the practical man crept out of a foxhole
he'd found among the Frigidaires and peered past the A/C units to
the customer service camp. Paul was waddling back to his comrades,
beating a hasty retreat.
</P>
<P>
   This was the practical man's chance! He glanced left, glanced
right, poked his nose in a couple of iceboxes. Prices. Prices!
Where were the prices? Were they classified information? Would he
have to go through Paul?
</P>
<P>
   Then _ disaster. He closed the door of the third fridge and _
booby trap! _ Paul popped out from behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What exactly are you looking for? Is it for a new house or a
remodeling job? Have you seen our new stainless-steel models?''
</P>
<P>
   Yikes! Flushed, flummoxed and fearing for his wallet, the
practical man dashed for the dishwashers, sought safety amid the
stackable washers and dryers _ but there was nowhere to hide. Paul
pursued, blistering the practical man with buckshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a dimensional dilemma I can help you solve? We have a
new `ultra-thin' line ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Treed at last, the practical man had no choice. He whipped out
his big gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, Paul. Let's do business. I want prices. I want
prices, sizes, brands and features. And I want a list lining them
all up so I can pick the best deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ooof! The shot hit Paul like a panzer blast to the solar plexus.
He wobbled, wheeled round, began to wander aimlessly back toward
camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be a lot of work,'' he muttered. Shellshock-
</P>
<P>
   ed, he shook his head and began mechanically heaving huge
three-ring binders from beneath a desk. ``The catalogs are all over
the place, and of course in this business, there's no such thing as
uniform pricing. Can't I interest you in our sale models?''
</P>
<P>
   Paul was pulverized, but the practical man took pity. He aborted
the mission before Paul could work up a sweat. After all, a price
comparison was by now pointless _ he wouldn't trade at this joint
if the fridges were free.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: I have a question that bothers me a great
deal. It requires a not-especially-practical answer but one that is
truthful and not just funny-funny.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, I read the obituaries. It's not as you perhaps think
_ to see if my name is there. It's to see if friends or
acquaintances have died. Lately, I notice that most who have died
are my age!
</P>
<P>
   Now the problem. I cannot picture myself dead. OK, I'm 79 years
old. Nevertheless, mentally I feel 19, and physically somewhat
older. But dead? No way!
</P>
<P>
   PM, what is it like to be dead? Remember, I don't want a funny
answer. I want only the truth!
</P>
<P>
   I'm waiting for your answer. And hurry ...
</P>
<P>
   _ L.L. Trescott, Lake Clarke Shores
</P>
<P>
   Gee thanks, L.L. Nothing makes a humor column crackle like a
discussion of death. But all right; since you were worried enough
to write, here goes.
</P>
<P>
   You want the truth about death? Easy. Remember how it was before
you were born? It's like that _ only you're bigger.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that was a joke, but what do you expect the practical man to
say? He doesn't know what it's like to be dead, and he doesn't
wonder about it, either.
</P>
<P>
   A practical man doesn't waste time on insoluble problems, and
neither should you. Sure, you can make all sorts of guesses, plug
them into the death equation and come up with an answer, but your
answer is going to be garbage because it's not based on facts.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say, for example, we postulate an omnipotent, judgmental
creator of a human-centered universe. Do the math, and voila:
Heaven and hell. Or, instead, let's toss a disinterested God and
randomness into the mix. Oops! Now we're all on a treadmill to
oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Or wait _ let's go with a hippie love god (hey, it could happen)
who means well but gets a little fuzzy on the details. L.L., we're
going to become one with that spirit in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   This is an amusing game _ for about five minutes. And then you
realize you're wasting precious time puzzling _ to no purpose,
considering plenty of real, soluble problems on this side of the
great divide. Like what can you do right now about that leaky
faucet? Or what can you do tomorrow to make the day worth living?
Or what can you do this month to make life better for your kids and
grandkids?
</P>
<P>
   Concentrate on life. You'll have plenty of time to solve death's
dilemmas after you're gone.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: Come out of the closet. Am I the only one
who realizes this column is written by either a woman or a gay man?
Men don't use words and phrases such as ``yummy'' or ``wee ones''
(alliteration notwithstanding). Nor are your ideas ``practical,''
or even ``manly'' (whatever that means). This must be quite a joke
around the newsroom, but I think it has run its course.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous, via e-mail
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, the practical man just came out of the
closet _ his girlfriend's closet, and he wasn't in there to swap
tops.
</P>
<P>
   Bah! How many times does the practical man have to answer this
insipid inquiry? And what difference does it make, anyway? But just
for the record: The practical man is male, 39, divorced, four kids,
has lived in Palm Beach County 25 years, worked for The Post since
1988.
</P>
<P>
   That's all you get. Begone!
</P>
<P>
   But wait, before you go _ slowly, gently drop ``yummy'' and
``wee ones'' onto the floor and kick them back over to the
practical man. There's no way he's going to let women and gays walk
off with all the good words.
</P>
<P>
   E-mailPractical Man(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
