<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4447 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-INDIAN-ASTRONOMY-     08-28 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INDIAN-ASTRONOMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKY SHOW PRESERVES A TRIBE'S ASTRONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By ANNE E. RUDERMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the Skidi Pawnee of the Nebraska Plains of the early 19th
century, the nighttime sky served as clock, calendar, compass and
weather channel, all in one.
</P>
<P>
   But for members of the modern tribe, the stories and traditions
of the Skidi's unique relationship to the sky have nearly been
lost.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a new emphasis on the astronomy of other cultures,
Chicago's Adler Planetarium and Astronomy Museum has revived Skidi
Pawnee astronomy in a sky show that is unusual among cultural
shows. To create the show, ``Spirits From the Sky, Thunder on the
Land,'' the Adler astronomers took their research beyond books and
records and onto the Pawnee reservation where they sought out
members of the Skidi Pawnee tribe to work with them in creating the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Skidi Pawnee tradition, the grandparents would instruct
the grandchildren, which is what we mimic in the show,'' said
Phyllis Pitluga, the program director. ``They passed on their
observations of the real sky and real events in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the Pawnee Nation numbers 2,500, compared with 10,000 in
the early 19th century, and its people live on a reservation near
Oklahoma City, instead of a Nebraska plain. The Skidi, or ``Wolf,''
Band is one of four that make up the Pawnee Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Pitluga said that Skidi astronomy was the most accurate and also
the most carefully recorded by anthropologists at the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Skidi Pawnee observed changes in the sky and folded them
into their creation story,'' Pitluga said. In the Skidi creation
story, the union of Mars and Venus created the first woman and the
overlapping of the sun and the moon created the first man.
</P>
<P>
   These stories and many others in a system where ``Dippers'' are
``Stretchers'' and ``Orion's Belt'' is ``Three Deer'' are seldom
remembered by the new generations of Skidi.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two decades Skidi stories have been most carefully
preserved by a researcher for the Smithsonian Institution, Von Del
Chamberlain, who discovered anthropology notebooks and tribal
artifacts at the institution. ``I came across a chart of the sky
and it's just such a beautiful and unusual thing, having stars on a
piece of leather. I don't know of anything like it in the world,''
said Chamberlain, who wrote a book on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chamberlain's and Pitluga's leadership, a team of
astronomers and Skidi elders met regularly and at length over the
last two years, sharing Skidi ceremonies where elders teased out
childhood memories, laughing and arguing over shared and forgotten
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made sure that the Pawnee stuff they were doing was true and
that the stuff they were doing was OK with our people,'' said Pat
Leading Fox, a Skidi chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spirits From the Sky'' cost $1 million to produce, twice as
much as a usual sky show because of the extensive research
involved. It was financed in part by a grant from the National
Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The Adler is also providing for the construction of a portable
planetarium on the Pawnee reservation. Leading Fox said it will
provide a useful teaching tool, since fewer and fewer Skidi know
the old stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our elders are trying to teach the ones who are interested,''
Leading Fox said. ``We've lost so much that now we're trying to
hold on to what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
