<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MEDICINE-USVI-TRAVEL-ENDPAPER-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH MEDICINE IN THE US VIRGIN ISLANDS 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. &HT;     
 (ART ADV: Photos of Veronica Gordon, Olasee Davis and the Charlotte
Amalie farmers' market are available on Newscom or by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    
 (Free to clients of Way to Go!) 
 BY TERESE LOEB KREUZER 
 &HT;    (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I first saw Bobby Olivacce one hot December night, walking down
a narrow street in Savan. He had a long dark beard, Rastafarian
dreadlocks, and the gaunt, intense face of an Old Testament
prophet. He was holding a large bunch of wheatgrass.
 &HT;    I was driving through this 200-year-old section of Charlotte
Amalie with my friend, Jacquel Dawson, who pulled over in front of
the high stoop of the Red Ball Grocery Store and introduced us. She
told Bobby I had come to the U.S. Virgin Islands to learn about how
herbs were used to cure and prevent disease, and specifically to
learn about what the old-timers call ``bush medicine,'' _ the use
of herbs that could be plucked from the forest and transformed into
teas, poultices, healing baths and restorative tinctures.
 &HT;    Bobby peered through the open window of Jacquel's battered,
rust-colored Toyota and told me that herbs were his way of life.
 &HT;    ``All Rastafarians are herbalists,'' he said. ``Some know more
than others,'' he added, modestly omitting to mention what Jacquel
later told me, that in the 16 years since he had come to St. Thomas
from his native Dominica, he had become known far and wide as a
healer. Some people consulted him when they were sick, while others
just needed some advice about how to use an herb in their backyard.
Bobby was a sort of roving herb shop, sometimes ministering to as
many as 100 people a day.
 &HT;    There are still many people in the U.S. Virgin Islands who would
rather go to an herbal healer like Bobby than to a medical doctor,
and there are some who go to an herbalist when ``modern'' remedies
have failed.
 &HT;    A rooster crossed the road and two men lounged on a stoop
drinking beer as Bobby said, ``If someone with a cold comes to me
for help, I remind them that the cold has a cause, and the cause is
bad eats and drinks, shallow breathing, laziness and wickedness.''
 &HT;    '' Wickedness?'' I asked.
 &HT;    Bobby smiled slightly. ``Wickedness is a way of life that is
selfish and that affects others adversely.''
 &HT;    As Jacquel and I said good-bye, Bobby invited me to look him up
and ``reason'' with him next time I was in town. I said I would.
 &HT;    Where Bobby comes from _ Dominica _ is still a wild place of
rain forests, farms and small villages. The same can't be said of
the U.S. Virgin Islands, which have been territories of the United
States since 1917. They have a patina of American culture _ cars,
television sets, large resort hotels, housing projects, a love
affair with all that money can buy.
 &HT;    Of the four U.S. Virgins (St. Thomas, St. Croix, St. John, and
tiny Water Island), St. Thomas in particular has been built up. The
once-quiet streets of Charlotte Amalie, the capital, are often
thronged with tourists who debark from enormous cruise ships by the
thousands. As they scurry to spend their money in the duty-free
shops, the chances are that few suspect that there's another side
to this island. I wouldn't have known, either, if Jacquel hadn't
shown me.
 &HT;    Just a block beyond the end of Main Street's (Droningen Gade's)
shopping strip is the old Market Square. There's been a market here
since the 17th century. In sugar plantation days, this was one of
the places where African slaves were sold when they first came off
the ships.
 &HT;    The Africans brought with them their knowledge of medicinal
herbs and how to contact ancestral spirits. They adapted their
practices to the new world, blending what they knew with what they
learned from the Amerindians.
 &HT;    On Saturdays, beginning at 3 a.m., farmers arrive at the market.
They sell fish, meat, fresh produce and herbs _ black wattle, worry
wine, several kinds of sage, cattle tongue, Spanish needle, bay
leaf, lemongrass and japana _ to name a few.
 &HT;    Some of these herbs will be used in cooking, while others will
be bought strictly for medicinal purposes. Many are herbs that used
to grow profusely in the bush or in people's yards. But life on
these islands began to change around 50 years ago _ at first,
gradually, then drastically. People moved to the states to get jobs
or go to college and never came back. At the same time, there was
an influx of people from other islands _ the Dominican Republic,
Dominica, Haiti, St. Lucia, St. Kitts, Antigua. Housing was built
to accommodate them. The bush was cut down or cut back. Some plants
that were once common became hard to find or virtually extinct. The
lore that had passed within families from generation to generation
about how to recognize plants and how to use them medicinally was
no longer as widespread as it once was.
 &HT;    This is not to say that the use of bush or an affection for it
disappeared. But it became diluted. Today, for instance, a store
called The Fruit Bowl in the Wheatley Shopping Center in Charlotte
Amalie sells an herb labeled ``Tea Bush.'' It's lemongrass,
certainly one form of tea bush, but only one of scores of herbs
that have traditionally been used to make medicinal tea on these
islands.
 &HT;    One afternoon, Jacquel took me back to Savan to meet Mavis de
Jongh who was born on St. Thomas in 1920. She has a pretty, white
house surrounded by tamarind and flamboyant trees on the edge of
town. Leaning on her cane and looking up at the steep hill dotted
with houses above her dwelling, she says that she remembers when
there was nothing there but trees.
 &HT;    She also remembers that when she was little, bush was used for
all occasions. ``If you had a cold, you were given black wattle. We
took lemongrass for fever, anise for stomach ache, pigeon pea for
abscess in the mouth, Spanish needle to cleanse internally. Bush
teas were used originally to prevent problems and to sustain
health. My grandmother knew what to use.''
 &HT;    Today, Mrs. de Jongh goes to medical doctors, but she still has
bush growing in her yard _ and she knows how to use it if she needs
it.
 &HT;    Mrs. de Jongh's recollections of her childhood are not unusual.
Many people attest to the wisdom of their mothers and grandmothers
who knew what to do for most run-of-the-mill complaints. In more
serious circumstances, they might consult a weedwoman. She was a
respected member of the community with a specialized knowledge of
herbs. She would gather them and sell them in the marketplace,
dispensing not only the herbal remedy, but instructions on how to
use it. She might also serve as a midwife, prescribing herbs to
prepare a woman for birth and administering a bush bath to help her
recover afterward.
 &HT;    The best-known weedwoman in the U.S. Virgin Islands at the
moment is Veronica Gordon, 52, of St. Croix. Her family has lived
on St. Croix for seven generations.
 &HT;    When she was 4 years old, she contracted polio. In the
aftermath, her father, Patrick N. Gordon, a respected herbalist,
``picked a feg of aloe cloves'' which he whipped up with egg
whites. Then he took her down to the sea, dipped her in, anointed
her with the mixture he had prepared, and rubbed her legs.
 &HT;    ``Oh, God, I was sore,'' she remembers. ``But it worked. My legs
were fine. I could climb trees a year later. This was my
introduction to bush medicine.''
 &HT;    Veronica learned about bush medicine from her father, who had
learned from his mother. ``In my family, the knowledge goes from
gender to gender,'' she says. ``It has to be first-born male to the
first-born female.''
 &HT;    Now, as her father did before her, she sees private clients. She
also occasionally gives demonstrations and lectures at the St.
George Village Botanical Garden on St. Croix.
 &HT;    The 16-acre botanical garden, which is set among the ruins of an
old sugar plantation, has more than 1,000 species of trees, vines
and shrubs, including an herb garden devoted just to the plants
that were used historically on the island by the weedwomen _ and
often, still are.
 &HT;    Another St. Croix resident, botanist Olasee Davis, has been
working diligently for years to preserve this knowledge and
transmit it to a younger generation. He writes an ecology column
for a local newspaper and was a major contributor to a book called
``Traditional Medicinal Plants of St. Croix, St. Thomas and St.
John.''
 &HT;    Olasee, an extension specialist with the University of the
Virgin Islands, leads hikes to the wild regions of St. Croix.
Though most visitors never see them, they're not far from the
shopping centers, the Hess Oil refinery and the highway that links
the two major towns _ Christiansted and Frederiksted _ of this
82-square-mile island.
 &HT;    One morning, as he precedes a group of teen-agers from a local
junior high school down the arid, wind-swept beach of Jacks Bay on
the eastern end of St. Croix, he stops every few yards to talk
about another plant.
 &HT;    ``This is inkberry,'' he says, pointing to a shrub with purple
stems and dark green leaves. ``Our grandparents used to crush the
berries for ink.'' He also tells the students that the leaves can
be used to treat thrush, boils and burns.
 &HT;    He shows them how sea grape leaves can be used to make a cup or
a plate and how the stiff twigs of the maran bush can serve as a
toothbrush or a yard broom. He tells them that the leaves of a
common evergreen tree called the starvation apple can be made into
a poultice to treat arthritis, burns, sprains and swelling. He
pauses in front of the familiar, bright yellow, bell-shaped flowers
of the ginger thomas bush (the U.S.V.I.'s national flower) and
mentions that the leaves can be made into a tonic to treat high
blood pressure and diabetes.
 &HT;    Olasee estimates that he hikes with more than 8,000 students a
year, but he also takes off-island visitors on his
``eco-educational tours'' of St. Croix's bays, rain forest, salt
ponds and wetlands.
 &HT;    After meeting Olasee, Veronica and Bobby, I drove around St.
Croix with new awareness. I noticed the women selling homemade
maubi by the side of the road. Bittersweet Maubi, a local beverage
made from bark, is refreshing in this hot climate, and is also said
to ameliorate diabetes, liver problems and diarrhea.
 &HT;    I stopped in Armstrong's ice cream shop on Route 70 and observed
that the flavors included soursop, which comes from a tree whose
leaves are made into a sleep-inducing tea.
 &HT;    I went into the Pueblo supermarket where I bought sorrel (said
to be helpful for kidney and bladder ailments), senna (a mild
laxative) and eucalyptus leaves (to make a tea that relieves colds
and fevers).
 &HT;    And I thought about something that Olasee had told the children.
``In nature, everything has a function,'' he had said. ``There are
no weeds.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    FOR MORE INFORMATION
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Hiking with Olasee Davis on St. Croix. Cost, $15/person. Call
(340) 778-9491 or (340) 692-4069.
 &HT;    ``Traditional Medicinal Plants of St. Croix, St. Thomas and St.
John,'' by Toni Thomas with major contributions by Rudi G. O'Reilly
Jr. and Olasee Davis; University of the Virgin Islands Cooperative
Extension Service, rev. June 1997. $8.75 from the University
bookstore (340) 692-4162. Higher elsewhere.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    St. George Village Botanical Garden, St. Croix. open daily from
9 a.m. to 5 p.m., November through May, and Tuesday through
Saturday, 9 a.m. to 4 p.m., June through October. 16 acres with
over 1,000 species of trees, vines and shrubs growing among
historic plantation buildings. (340) 692-2874.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Restaurants that serve local food and beverages, including
maubi, sorrel, soursop and ginger beer: On St. Croix, Kim's at 45
King Street in Christiansted. Open from Monday through Saturday for
lunch and dinner. (340) 773-3377. On St. Thomas: Cuzzin's at 7
Backstreet in Charlotte Amalie. Open from Tuesday through Saturday
for lunch and dinner and on Mondays, for lunch only. (340)
777-4711. Gladys' Cafe at Royal Dane Mall West in Charlotte Amalie.
Open for breakfast and lunch from 7 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Monday
through Saturday. Open Sunday from 8 a.m. to 2 p.m. (340) 774-6604.
 &HT;    -------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    (Terese Loeb Kreuzer has written about England, Scotland,
France, Italy, Poland, Guatemala, China and the Caribbean as well
as about many places in the United States.)
 &HT;    c.2000 Terese Loeb Kreuzer 
