<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN COPENHAGEN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slides and B&AMP;W map available.) 
 FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES 
 By CORINNE LaBALME  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Amid its human-scale skyline, century-old cafes, pedestrian
streets and lush gardens, Copenhagen still finds room for
contradictions. That's to be expected from a city that nurtured
both Hans Christian Andersen and Soren Kierkegaard.
 &HT;    In a city under constant renewal, two dazzling avant-garde
projects have been completed over the last 12 months: the dramatic
Black Diamond addition to the Royal Library and the shimmering
Danish Design Center. And a 10-mile bridge-and-tunnel connection to
Malmo, Sweden, the Oresund Fixed Link, was inaugurated on July 1.
It ties southern Sweden to the Continent for the first time.
 &HT;    Founded in the 12th century, Copenhagen was nearly destroyed on
several occasions, most notably by a fire in 1795 and the 1807
British bombardments during the Napoleonic wars. Thus, most of the
city's neoclassical architecture dates from the early 19th century,
when Danish arts and letters flourished.
 &HT;    From now through Sept. 10, the city celebrates the achievements
of the years 1800 to 1850 with the biennial Golden Days in
Copenhagen Festival. In conjunction with the festival, the
Copenhagen City Museum (Bymuseum) just unveiled its renovated
Kierkegaard Room, lengthening an already crowded museum roster.
 &HT;    Because many museums and castles have limited hours,
time-conscious visitors often have lunch at the convenient museum
snack bars. Nevertheless, getting to know this city means at least
one break for smoerrebroed _ the open-face Danish sandwiches
generally topped with fresh shrimp, herring or egg _ in a
waterfront cafe in the recently gentrified Nyhavn quarter.
 &HT;    Another essential taste of Copenhagen is found at the enchanting
Tivoli amusement park, open through Sept. 24, with outdoor concerts
and carnival rides.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    EVENTS
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Golden Days Festival unites 60 cultural institutions in
Copenhagen. Highlights include exhibitions and performances in
historic sites, notably the restaging of Bournonville's romantic
ballet ``Kermesse in Bruges'' at the Royal Theater Aug. 31 and
Sept. 4, 5 and 8. Tickets are $8 to $55, at 8 kroner to the dollar.
Programs are available at www.goldendays.dk/english.
 &HT;    Golden Days maps, in English, found at the tourist information
center near Tivoli at 1 Bernstorffsgade, pinpoint architectural
details like the sober pediments of the Christianborg Palace Chapel
(1826) and the Egyptian ornamentation on the Krystalgade Synagogue
(1833).
 &HT;    The City Museum (Copenhagen Bymuseum), 59 Vesterbrogade, (45) 33
21 07 72, recently inaugurated its expanded Soren Kierkegaard room,
with his books and furnishings, including his desk. Open Wednesday
to Monday 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.; after Oct. 1 from 1 to 4 p.m.
Admission: $2.50; children free.
 &HT;    ``Symbolism in Danish and European Painting'' opens the fall
season at the Statens Museum for Kunst (Danish National Gallery),
48-50 Solvgade, (45) 33 74 84 94 or www.smk.dk, on Sept. 29,
continuing through Jan. 14. With 80 paintings from 1870 to 1910,
this exhibition includes works by Edvard Munch and the Danish
masters Ejnar Nielsen, Vilhelm Hammershoi and Joakim Skovgaard,
whose ``Christ in the Realm of Death'' has just been restored by
the museum. Open Tuesday to Sunday 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., Wednesday
(free) until 8 p.m. Admission: $5, $7.50 with the exhibit.
 &HT;    From now to Oct. 17, the Royal Theater, Det Kongelige Teater,
Kongens Nytorv, (45) 33 69 69 69, www.kgl-teater.dk, offers an
intriguing double dance bill with a contemporary ballet
choreographed by the former Paul Taylor star Lila York presented in
tandem with the classic ``Giselle,'' performed by the Royal Danish
Ballet. Tickets: $6.25 to $43.75.
 &HT;    The Danish diva Anne Margrethe Dahl stars in the Royal Theater's
opulent production of Verdi's ``Traviata'' through Sept. 16.
Tickets: $9.50 to $65.60.
 &HT;    The Danish Design Center, 27 H. C. Andersens Blvd., (45) 33 69
33 69, a showcase for the best of Danish and international design
that opened in January, honors the 75th anniversary of the Danish
electronics company Bang &AMP; Olufsen through Sept. 17, with
photographs, early advertising posters and pioneering designs _
including the Bauhaus-inspired Hyperbo 5RG combination radio-record
player from 1934 and a sleek molded Bakelite radio from 1939 _
displayed alongside contemporary designs. Open Monday through
Friday 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., weekends and holidays 11 a.m. to 4 p.m.;
$3.75.
 &HT;    Royal Copenhagen's headquarters on the Stroget, 6 Amagertorv,
(45) 33 13 71 81, the pedestrian shopping avenue in the center of
town, is also popular. The porcelain firm honors the 225th
anniversary of its signature Blue Fluted pattern with a new line of
historic re-editions, and presents a retrospective exhibition
through Sept. 2. Open Monday to Thursday 10 a.m. to 6 p.m., Friday
to 7 p.m., Saturday to 5 p.m., Sunday through September noon to 5
p.m. Free.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SIGHTSEEING
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Despite busloads of camera-toting admirers, the Little Mermaid
appears justifiably disconsolate at being seated in the harbor
across from an oil storage silo on the north edge of town. Nearby,
the relatively unknown Danish Resistance Museum in Churchill Park,
(45) 33 13 77 14, details daily life in Denmark from 1940 to 1945.
Open Tuesday to Saturday 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. and Sunday 10 a.m. to 5
p.m; after Sept. 16 Tuesday to Saturday 11 a.m. to 3 p.m. and
Sunday 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. Free.
 &HT;    The Hirshsprung Collection, 20 Stockholmsgade, (45) 35 42 03 36,
reopened in March after a year's renovation. The collection of
19th-century Danish painting and sculpture that belonged to the
tobacco baron Heinrich Hirshsprung is housed in a
neoclassical-style mansion filled with furniture from the homes and
studios of the artists. Open Thursday to Monday 11 a.m. to 4 p.m.
and Wednesday 11 a.m. to 9 p.m. Admission: $3; children free.
 &HT;    Fans of the Vikings can begin their Nordic quest at the National
Museum, 10 Ny Vestergade, (45) 33 13 44 11, where runestones,
jewelry, weapons and mummified remains from Viking graves are
displayed with clear English explanations. The delicate Sun Chariot
sculpture is one of the museum's major Bronze Age artifacts. Open
Tuesday to Sunday 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; $5; children free.
 &HT;    Tivoli, 3 Vesterbrogade, (45) 33 15 10 01, has enchanted
visitors since 1843 with its lavish flower gardens, fanciful
pavilions, rides and numerous restaurants. Two Chinese-inspired
attractions for children _ Dragon Boats and the Panda's Tower _
opened this year. The Valhalla Funhouse and the Viking Ships ride
are much scarier. Open Sunday to Thursday 11 a.m. to midnight,
Friday and Saturday 11 a.m. to 1 a.m. Closes Sept. 24 and reopens
Nov. 17 to Dec. 23. Tickets: $5, children $2.50.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    WHERE TO STAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The conveniently situated 51-room Hotel Danmark, 89 Vester
Voldgade, (45) 33 11 48 06, fax (45) 33 14 36 30, between Tivoli
and the National Museum, offers a friendly welcome and uncluttered,
traditional decor with bold colors. The typically tiny, spotless
bathrooms have built-in hair dryers. The private garage ($9.40 a
day) is a bonus. Doubles: $137.
 &HT;    Near the Amalienborg Palace, the 366-room Copenhagen Admiral
Hotel, 24-28 Toldbodgade, (45) 33 74 14 14, fax (45) 33 74 14 16,
is housed in an 18th-century granary with atmospheric
barrel-vaulted hallways. Harborside rooms offer views of cruise
ships and sailboats. And although rooms derive great charm from
200-year-old rough-hewn pine beams, the landmark wooden
infrastructure means no air-conditioning. Amenities include a
nightclub and sauna. Doubles: $128 to $164.
 &HT;    Budget: A cheerful children's playroom and an enclosed outdoor
patio adjoin the dining room at Ibsen's Hotel, 23 Vendersgade, (45)
33 13 19 13, fax (45) 33 13 19 16, in a residential district near
the lush Botanical Gardens. Most of the 118 rooms display clean,
no-frills Scandinavian design, although top-of-the-line suites have
more ambitious decor and kitchenettes. The generous buffet
breakfast is included in the room price. Doubles: $131 to $156.
 &HT;    Luxury: The gracious Hotel d'Angleterre, 34 Kongens Nytorv, (45)
33 12 00 95, fax (45) 33 12 11 18, was built in 1755 in the Grand
Hotel tradition. Its 124 rooms are decorated in a variety of
styles; some with sumptuous canopy beds with French provincial
textiles. The hotel has two restaurants, Internet access from rooms
and an indoor pool and spa. Doubles: $287 to $449.
 &HT;    While far smaller in its dimensions, the 84-room Nyhavn 71, 71
Nyhavn, (45) 33 43 62 00, fax (45) 33 43 62 01, exudes considerable
antique charm. Its pint-size rooms, with exposed beams and colorful
textiles, are squeezed into an 1804 warehouse on a scenic stretch
of waterfront with views of the old naval base. Work is under way
on a 44-room annex. Doubles: $187 to $224.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    WHERE TO EAT
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The sleek, minimalist dining room in the Royal Library's new
Black Diamond wing, 1 Soren Kierkegaards Plads, (45) 33 47 49 49,
which opened in September, offers some of the city's most
sophisticated cuisine. The menu includes grilled catfish paired
with succulent Norwegian lobster and superb smoked Baltic salmon
with dill and scrambled eggs. Waterfront views are sensational at
sunset, so ask for a window table. A three-course dinner for two
with a modest bottle of wine is $113.
 &HT;    In an upscale neighborhood of power brokers and power shoppers,
Cafe Zeze, 20 Ny Ostergade, (45) 33 14 23 90, serves eclectic
European fare, like lamb filets topped with shiitake mushrooms and
an exotic vegetarian pasta laced with coconut cream and hot chili
pepper. While the lunch crowd is mostly suit-and-tie, this
streamlined bistro attracts a younger, cooler clientele after dark.
Dinner and Tuborg for two: $45.
 &HT;    Tourism has tamed the once disreputable Nyhavn waterfront, and
open-air restaurants have ousted tattoo parlors and brothels. At
Nyhavns Faergekro, 5 Nyhavn, (45) 33 15 15 88, the all-you-can-eat
lunch buffet with 10 varieties of Scandinavian herring for $11 is
one of the best seafood bargains in Copenhagen. The famous fish
cakes with remoulade sauce or smoked lamb sandwiches, both $5.60,
also make a fine light lunch. At dinner, there is a fixed-price
two-course menu for $19.
 &HT;    High ceilings and leaded-glass windows lend a lofty look to
Cafeen I Nikolaj, 12 Nikolaj Plads, (45) 33 11 63 13, which serves
down-to-earth Danish fare in a deconsecrated church site. The
creamed seafood chowder is superb, and the classic lunch
combinations of herring, smoked eel, shrimp or salmon tartare never
disappoint. Two for lunch will spend $35. It is open for dinner
from spring to Sept. 2 with an expanded menu that includes steak
tenderloin or lemon sole. Dinner for two with wine: $75.
 &HT;    The Stroget takes its festive ambience from street mimes and
musicians. At Cafe Europa, 1 Amagertorv, (45) 33 12 04 28, the
outdoor tables are tantalizingly close to the Royal Copenhagen and
Georg Jensen showrooms. An oversized Danish sandwich topped with
marinated artichoke, sun-dried tomato, roasted eggplant and fresh
basil costs $8. A glass of wine or beer is $3.50. (No
reservations.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Corinne LaBalme writes frequently about cultural events in
Europe.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Corinne LaBalme 
