<HEADER>
A4456 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-ROOM-SERVICE-TRAVEL-S     08-28 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOM-SERVICE-TRAVEL-SHOPPING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: TRENDS IN ROOM SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's WAY TO GO! feature package. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of WAY TO GO! _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 (ART ADV: Color slide included.) 
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 c.2000 Everett Potter  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some hotels will answer just about any room service request.
When a guest of the Eden Roc Resort &AMP; Spa (4525 Collins Ave., Miami
Beach, FL 33140; 800-327-8337; www.edenrocresort.com) was boating
offshore last year, he asked for a pizza from hotel room service.
The hotel obliged and arranged to have a helicopter sent out to the
yacht to deliver the pizza. The tab was $100 for the pizza _ a
Supreme with everything on it. The delivery charge was $1,800.
</P>
<P>
   Good room service can jump-start someone's morning mood, erase
the headaches of a difficult trip and elevate a hotel stay to a
memorable experience. But many hotels are taking room service way
beyond delivering a good club sandwich in less than 20 minutes.
Here's a look at what some properties are doing to keep their
guests happy.
</P>
<P>
   A cheese Danish and coffee may be a satisfactory start for many
travelers but not for every guest at The Phoenician (6000 E.
Camelback Rd., Scottsdale, AZ 85251; 800-888-8234;
www.thephoenician.com). That hotel's ``Champagne Breakfast for
Two'' includes smoked Atlantic salmon, caviar and scrambled eggs on
a toasted brioche with sauteed oyster mushrooms and chives. It
comes with seasonal berries with lemon creme fraiche, breakfast
pastries, coffee and a half-bottle of Tattinger champagne. The cost
is $95.
</P>
<P>
   At Four Seasons Hotel Chicago (120 E. Delaware Place, Chicago,
IL 60611; 800-819-5053; www.fourseasons.com/chicagofs), toasters
are delivered to the room with breakfast so guests can toast their
own bread, bagels or English muffins exactly the way they like
them.
</P>
<P>
   And at Turnberry Isle Resort &AMP; Club (19999 West Country Club
Dr., Aventura, FL 33180; 800-327-7028; www.turnberryisle.com), room
service didn't blink when a couple requested that their early
morning breakfast be delivered to the 18th hole of the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of hotels are offering in-room dining
options that rival their public dining facilities. In upstate New
York, for example, the Mirbeau Inn &AMP; Spa (851 W. Genesee St.,
Skaneateles, NY 13152; 877.MIRBEAU; www.mirbeau.com) serves their
Mirbeau Estate Cuisine as either a three- or five-course dinner
exactly as they would in the dining room. The servers use Frette
linen tablecloths and set up a candlelight dinner using fine china,
silver and crystal. Guests are served course by course.
</P>
<P>
   A room with a view can be wonderful, especially if it's in
scenic Vancouver. Almost three-quarters of the 489 rooms at The
Waterfront (900 Canada Place Way, Vancouver, BC V6C 3L5, Canada;
800-441-1414; www.thewaterfronthotel.com) offer views of the harbor
and North Shore mountains. The hotel enhances the view by offering
binoculars through the room-service menu. The price is about $21.
</P>
<P>
   Bath menus are popping up all over. For example, at the
Ritz-Carlton, Kapalua (One Ritz-Carlton Drive, Kapalua, Maui,
Hawaii 96761; 800-262-8440; www.fourseasons.com) on Maui, guests
can opt for a butler-drawn bath, which is available during the
evening for a charge of $50 per bath. It must be ordered at least
30 minutes in advance and it includes music, towel warmers and
chocolate truffles. The hotel says that many guests choose this as
a way to relieve jetlag.
</P>
<P>
   Among the baths to choose from are the Ka Au'au Pili Aloha (The
Romance Bath), a romantic bath by candlelight that includes milk
whey powder, lavender bath oil, rose petals and a half-bottle of
champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Pets are pampered at The Ritz-Carlton Chicago (160 E. Pearson
St., Chicago, IL 60611; 800-621-6906; www.fourseasons.com) with the
``Gour-r-r-met'' room service menu. For dogs, the choices include
``Our Lovable' Chopped Filet Mignon'' for $12 and ``Tail Waggin'
Good' Grilled Breast of Chicken'' for $6. Cats can partake of
``Chicken Liver Pate'' for $5, filet of salmon ``Chopped Charlie''
for $8 and get a ``Side Order of Anchovies'' for $2.50.
</P>
<P>
   Many hotel chains are also trying to improve the ``service''
aspect of room service at all of their properties. About a year
ago, Wyndham Hotels &AMP; Resorts (1950 Stemmons Freeway, Suite 6001,
Dallas, TX 75207; 800-Wyndham; www.wyndham.com) instituted a
five-minute call that's made prior to room-service delivery.
There's also a follow-up call to make sure that nothing else is
needed. And that service level is audited by each hotel.
</P>
<P>
   As an increasing number of travelers opt to take food along on
airplanes, more hotels are making it easier for them to do so. For
example, the Hay-Adams Hotel (800 16th St. NW, Washington, D.C.
20006; (202-638-6600; www.hayadams.com), which overlooks the White
House, has gourmet lunch boxes made to order. The choice includes a
roasted vegetable sandwich, a curried chicken salad sandwich or a
tuna with wasabi sandwich with the guest's choice of bread. All
sandwiches are served with fresh seasonal fruit, homemade potato
chips, freshly baked cookies and Evian water. The cost is $25 per
lunch box.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for a good's night sleep, The Benjamin (125 East 50th
St., New York, NY 10022; 888-4BENJAMIN; www.the benjamin.com) has
an 11-pillow room service menu. There are gel-filled and
hypo-allergenic pillows, water-filled and buckwheat varieties and
even a magnetic therapy pillow, in addition to the hotel's down
pillow, standard in every room. There is no extra charge for using
any of the pillows.
</P>
<P>
   -----------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
