<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASK THE TRAVEL EXPERT
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's WAY TO GO! feature package. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of WAY TO GO! _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: The word AT in parentheses has been used in an e-mail
address instead of the symbol.) 
 By WILLIAM T. TOMICKI 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. It looks like another summer has come and gone and I still
haven't learned how to Rollerblade. Help!
</P>
<P>
   A. Here's an idea to get you rolling. If you book an ocean-view
room between September 15 and November 15 at Hotel Casa Del Mar in
Santa Monica, Calif., you'll get complimentary breakfast and a free
hour of inline skating lessons from a professional instructor _ or,
if you prefer, you can choose an hour of fitness work with a
personal trainer. The offer is priced at $399, single or double
occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Instruction takes place on the beach in front of this elegant
1920s hotel, which reopened a year ago after a $60 million
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The 129-room Hotel Casa Del Mar, once the grandest of Santa
Monica hotels, has re-emerged as one of the most luxurious on the
West Coast. Near the historic Santa Monica Pier with its antique
carousel and close to excellent dining and shopping, most rooms
have panoramic views of the Pacific Ocean from Palos Verdes to
Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's refurbished guest rooms are decorated with bamboo
and wicker furniture and have marble bathrooms. The hotel offers
gourmet dining and a lively bar.
</P>
<P>
   For information or reservations, call (310) 581-5533; website:
www.hotelcasadelmar.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q. A friend of mine just got ripped off by an unethical tour
company. How can I keep this from happening to me?
</P>
<P>
   A. Two good signs of reliability are the Better Business Bureau
(visit www.bbb.org) and membership in the National Tour Association
(see www.ntaonline.com). Both organizations maintain up-to-date
information and make it easy for you to check out a company.
</P>
<P>
   Another method would be to call the U.S. tourist office for the
country you plan to visit. They can be very helpful in establishing
a tour operator's reputation. Travel agents can also prove
indispensable in finding out if a tour operator has a good track
record.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the company you choose, before you give them a
deposit, ask for a written itinerary that lists all details,
especially what is included and what is not. Also, familiarize
yourself with their refund policy.
</P>
<P>
   Q. In passing, I heard someone mention a new play encompassing
the events of the Trojan War but I can't remember where or when it
is playing.
</P>
<P>
   A. You must be referring to ``Tantalus'' _ a 10-hour 30-minute
chronicle of the Trojan war by John Barton, which is making its
world premiere in Denver in October 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This two-day event is the result of a collaboration between the
Tony-Award winning Denver Center Theater Company and the Royal
Shakespeare Company.
</P>
<P>
   From October 20 through December 3, The Westin Tabor Center,
Denver, is offering a ``Tantalus'' package every weekend, priced at
$905 per couple. This includes two reserved tickets to the
Saturday-Sunday production at The Stage Theater at The Denver
Performing Arts Complex, a three-night stay at The Westin Tabor
Center, Denver, meals served between acts on both days, daily
breakfast at the hotel's restaurant and transportation between the
hotel and theater complex.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, The Westin offers packages in conjunction with the
``Best of Broadway'' series at the Denver Performing Arts Complex.
Show dates and package prices vary.
</P>
<P>
   For package information and reservations, call the The Westin
Tabor Center at (303) 572-9100.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there an easy way for me to get information about Southern
Africa?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, the Regional Tourism Organization of Southern Africa
will send you its official directory, ``The Essence of Africa,''
free of charge. The RETOSA directory contains more than 200 pages
on everything a visitor needs to know about travel in the countries
of Angola, Botswana, Democratic Republic of Congo, Lesotho, Malawi,
Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, Seychelles, South Africa,
Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Included are the 10 best reasons to visit each of these
countries as well as places of interest, activities, climate, entry
requirements, transportation, currency and answers to frequently
asked questions.
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of ``The Essence of Africa,'' call (212) 286-9300 or
e-mail vhaynesbca(AT)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have recently become interested in the sport of clay
shooting and wish to combine this with my next vacation. How can I
go about this?
</P>
<P>
   A. For marksmen (and women) of all skill levels, The Cloister at
Sea Island, located off the coast of Georgia, is hosting its
first-ever Sporting Clays Championship. The competition will take
place from Nov. 3-5 at the resort's Sea Island Shooting School on
Rainbow Island just south of the Cloister.
</P>
<P>
   The school offers three types of clay target shooting,
customized instruction and superior equipment to help novice and
advanced shooters perfect their skills.
</P>
<P>
   A three-night Sea Island Sporting Clays Championship package at
The Cloister includes luxurious accommodations, three meals daily,
two days of shooting (100 clays per day) on the resort's Sporting
Clays Course, and a reception and awards dinner at the end of the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The package is priced at $130 per person per night double
occupancy or $180 for single occupancy. There is also a $180 per
person registration fee for the competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Cloister at Sea Island, just an hour from Savannah, is
consistently ranked as one of the world's top resorts, with miles
of private beaches, golf courses, superior dining, tennis and a
seaside spa. For more information call (800) 732-4752; Web site:
www.seaisland.com.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
