<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4462 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-ADIRONDACKS-LAKE-GEOR     08-28 2432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADIRONDACKS-LAKE-GEORGE-TRAVEL-FARE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VOICE FROM THE MET'S FIRST SEASON
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's WAY TO GO! feature package. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of WAY TO GO! _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By CONSTANCE ROSENBLUM 
 c.2000 Constance Rosenblum 
 From The New York Times 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hidden in a grove of pines on a finger of land overlooking Lake
George in the foothills of the Adirondacks is a shrine to a
remarkable woman. Her lovely musical name was Marcella Sembrich,
and though virtually forgotten today, this Polish-born soprano was
once one of the glories of the operatic stage.
</P>
<P>
   During a career that spanned half a century, she sang all the
big roles, performed with the greats of her day and won nothing but
raves. Critics and fans adored her. At the 1909 gala at the Met
that marked her retirement from opera performances shortly before
she turned 51, ``an audience of monstrous size packed the house to
suffocation,'' a critic for The New York Sun noted.
</P>
<P>
   Gustav Mahler led the orchestra in the march from ``Figaro''
that evening as Sembrich was escorted to a throne and showered with
gifts and rose petals. The event was Page 1 news in The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   The shrine in question is a doll-sized studio of pink stucco
where Sembrich embarked on a second career as a voice teacher. She
made her summer home in the tiny village of Bolton Landing in 1922,
opened the studio in 1924 and taught there until shortly before her
death in 1935. Two years later, the studio was converted into a
small house museum, and although Sembrich and her acolytes are long
gone, this trove of operatic memorabilia offers a haunting picture
of an extraordinary era.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly, Bolton Landing appears to be your typical lakeside
tourist center, pleasantly sleepy in comparison with Lake George
village, its slightly raucous neighbor to the south. But the
Sembrich Museum recalls the hamlet's heyday at the turn of the
century. Along with Lake George village, it was a summer haven for
New York's moneyed class, a place where gilded age Knickerbockers
built imposing mansions on pine-scented lakefront, thereby savoring
both incomparable views and the lush comforts of home.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the fine buildings that once lined the lake are gone,
replaced by far less glamorous newcomers. Typical of the upstarts
is the Melody Manor Resort, which sits on property once occupied by
the grandly named Marie Antoinette Villa. Its past occupants
included the millionaire Harry K. Thaw, forever remembered as the
husband of Evelyn Nesbit _ the ``Girl in the Red Velvet Swing'' _
and the man who fatally shot her lover, the architect Stanford
White. All that's left of the place is a stone gatehouse, its
original function long forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Of the few historic structures still standing, the bulk are in
private hands and off limits to visitors. For the most part, the
self-directed driving and walking tours suggested by the Town of
Bolton Bicentennial Committee (the town celebrated its 200th
birthday last year) take a visitor past sprawling lawns and
insistently modern structures. With only an occasional granite wall
or rusting wrought-iron gate to suggest what stood long ago, it's a
frustrating but tantalizing, and unexpectedly moving, journey.
</P>
<P>
   From books, photographs and the occasional survivor that has
escaped the wrecking ball, it's possible to piece together a vivid
picture of what life must have been like in what was one of the
most desirable enclaves in the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   The best guide to the area is ``The Great and the Gracious on
Millionaires' Row: Lake George in Its Glory'' by Kathryn E. O'Brien
(North Country Books, 1978), a delightfully anecdotal study of the
families who summered along the 10-mile strip between Bolton
Landing and Lake George Village.
</P>
<P>
   As I learned from reading this lavishly illustrated book and by
doing a little discreet trespassing on my own, one of the surviving
splendid buildings is the William K. Bixby mansion on Mohican
Point, just south of the center of town. A spanking white
Colonial-style structure, it was built at the turn of the century
and is still a summer home to descendants of the original family.
</P>
<P>
   The family made its money in railroads, and money was no object
when it came to outfitting its lakefront quarters. Period documents
reveal that a veritable fleet of different types of boats once
departed from its dock and a corps of gardeners tended its
plantings. With its pillars, gables and forest of chimneys, the
Bixby mansion still stands tall, visible from both the road and the
water.
</P>
<P>
   The Bixby family may be best known because Harold Bixby, a son
of William K., provided both the main financial backing and, in a
tip of his hat to his old hometown, the name for Charles
Lindbergh's Spirit of St. Louis. Even more interesting, at least to
local school children who get to make shivery visits to the site,
is the stuff about the ghost.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the first Bixby set foot on the property, an Indian
maiden was said to have been burned at the stake near one of the
mansion's locust trees. As the flames shot up, an apparition
swooped down to rescue her, and the blood-red markings on a stone
that sits beneath that same locust is regarded as proof of this
event.
</P>
<P>
   The Sagamore resort lacks a ghost, but has its own stories to
tell. It opened on Green Island, just north of the village center,
in 1883, a great wedding cake ringed with porches. Like virtually
all the lakefront hostelries, it commanded a spectacular view, and
its decorative accents _ massive beams, terra-cotta fireplaces,
gleaming dark woodwork _ did a good deal to conjure up 16th-century
England.
</P>
<P>
   But bad luck seemed part of its fate. In 1893, the Sagamore was
destroyed by fire, and though a year later an even more lavish
hotel rose on the site, the year 1914 brought a second fire, as
devastating as the first. By 1930 a third hotel had been built, the
huge white palace that sits on the island today.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Sagamore's checkered history, a sense of its
original grandeur lingers. One afternoon I spent a few hours
wandering through its spacious, high-ceilinged public rooms and
wide, quiet corridors, pretending to be a refugee from an Edith
Wharton novel. It wasn't hard. The crystal chandeliers, the
slow-moving ceiling fans, the plump sofas and wicker chairs, the
potted plants and swags of drapery made me feel as if I were back
in another time. The gentle color scheme of rose and tea and
celadon had a lulling effect.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite stroll took me along a flower-fringed pathway that
led from the back of the hotel down a sloping greensward, at the
foot of which a protected beach has been set up for children. It's
possible to sit off to one side and watch Lake George's signature
steamboats chug across the water as they have since the mid-19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   The Sembrich Museum, Bolton Landing's other notable survivor, is
outwardly less imposing than the Sagamore but even more evocative
of the past, for crammed into this modest cottage is a veritable
history of opera during its golden age. And understandably, for
Sembrich's career spanned some of the richest years of opera.
</P>
<P>
   The singer, whose story is told in an affectionate book called
``A Recollection of Marcella Sembrich'' by H. Goddard Owen (Coneco
Litho Graphics, 1995), was born in 1858 in a hamlet near Lemberg.
She studied piano and violin as a little girl and enjoyed a stellar
early career singing in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1877, she married her piano teacher, a man 13 years her
senior with whom she remained through his entire life. (Miss
Sembrich, who had no children, took her mother's name as her
professional name). In 1883, she came to New York and made her
American debut in ``Lucia di Lammermoor'' on the second night of
the Met's first season.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of Sembrich _ a seemingly endless number of them can
be seen in the museum that bears her name _ reveal that she was
adorable, with a mass of dark curls, huge, soulful eyes, and a
winsome smile that kept her looking girlish well beyond her youth.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, she was also a world-class charmer. Henry
Krehbiel, music critic for The New York Tribune, made special
mention of her ``pretty witcheries, graceful coquetries'' and
``captivating ingenuousness.'' But it was the heavenly quality of
her voice and her ability to capture the intellectual and emotional
nuances of the music that lay at the heart of her gift. It was said
that Franz Liszt once instructed the young Sembrich: ``Sing, sing
for the world, for you have the voice of an angel.'' Her dear
friend Brahms added: ``Sembrich has a mind, a heart and a soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Even for someone who is not an opera aficionado, the collection
of memorabilia crammed into her museum offers a fascinating window
into a personality and an era. Though modest in size, the place
opens with a bang, with a sumptuous display of Sembrich's costumes
in the little foyer. (As was typical of divas of the day, Sembrich
provided her own wardrobe and routinely traveled with 20 or 30
trunks.)
</P>
<P>
   Among the outfits on view is the gray cloak she wore as Mimi in
``La Boheme,'' a delicious-looking cherry velvet bolero jacket, her
Queen of the Night tiara with moon and stars set against dark blue
velvet from ``The Magic Flute,'' an assortment of fetching bonnets,
fans dripping with feathers and sequins and a great deal of ermine,
lace and embroidery.
</P>
<P>
   The main room, with its beamed ceiling, heavy dark furniture,
Steinway grand piano and Oriental carpets, looks much as it did
when Sembrich instructed her pupils in proper breathing and
intonation.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every inch is crammed with mementos, for there were
few stars of the turn-of-the-century operatic world whose lives did
not touch Sembrich's. There is no end of tributes. From
Rachmaninoff, ``I weave daisies into the crown of Marcella
Sembrich.'' From Edmond Rostand: ``To the nightingale, to the
thrush, to all who excel in song.'' From the conductor Bruno
Walter, ``In thankful remembrance of the most glorious impressions
of my young manhood.'' From Puccini: ``You are the Mimi.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a profusion of scores, letters, telegraphs,
portraits, autographed scores and photographs and programs _ from
Brahms, Liszt, Verdi, Mahler, Toscanini, both Strausses _ the list
is long. And there is a marble bust of the young Beethoven, tribute
wreaths of oak and laurel leaves exquisitely wrought in silver, a
replica of Chopin's death mask, an ostrich fan with a
diamond-studded monogram from the Rothschild family, a loving cup
from Caruso, with whom she performed in ``Rigoletto'' at his Met
debut in 1903, and a miniature model of the Met stage.
</P>
<P>
   A few oddities reveal that she had a life off the operatic
stage, among them a letter from Mark Twain inviting her to his
``doe'' luncheon. (She declined.)
</P>
<P>
   In the sunroom, a bay window offers yet another sweeping view of
the lake, along with a glimpse of the path that winds deeper into
the pines along which Sembrich must have taken many a restorative
walk. In summer, concerts are held in the studio.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over this little kingdom is a gentle, soft-spoken man
named Richard Wargo, the resident curator and composer in
residence. As I was strolling through the rooms, alone on a warm
Sunday morning, he played a recording of Sembrich singing the waltz
from ``The Merry Widow.'' With his flick of a switch _ CD, not
Victrola, for Sembrich has been remastered for the modern age _ the
room was flooded with scratchy but deeply suggestive sound. Any
visitor would have paused to savor this eerie, wonderful moment.
</P>
<P>
   If you go to Bolton Landing
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   Bolton Landing is 200 miles north of New York City, a four-hour
drive on the New York State Thruway and Interstate 87. Take Exit 22
off I-87 and head north on Route 9N (Lakeshore Drive).
</P>
<P>
   ACCOMMODATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The Sagamore, on Lake George at Bolton Landing, (800) 358-3585,
has 100 rooms, including 46 suites, plus 240 rooms in lakeside
lodges, half with fireplaces and terraces. Prices range from $135
for a single in the winter to $465 for a suite in the summer. The
inn has a golf course, a spa, conference facilities and a range of
dining options, from informal to formal.
</P>
<P>
   Hilltop Cottage Bed and Breakfast, 4825 Lakeshore Drive, (518)
644-2492, is a converted farmhouse operated by Anita Richards,
administrative director of the Sembrich museum, and her husband,
Charlie. Two rooms and a cabin, ranging from $70 to $85 for a
double. The price covers a hearty breakfast on the front porch; the
menu includes such German specialties as apple pancakes. Open May
15 to Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   DINING
</P>
<P>
   Bolton Landing's main street is lined with a number of friendly,
informal restaurants, many featuring local seafood. Typical is
Frederick's, 4970 Lakeshore Drive, (518) 644-3484, a favorite among
local camp counselors, who congregate there for late-night suppers.
The wraparound porch, which affords a good view of the main street,
is especially pleasant on summer evenings. A dinner for two that
included grilled salmon, linguine marinara, a huge platter of
nachos, a couple of pina coladas and dessert came to $60, including
tip.
</P>
<P>
   VISITING THE MUSEUM
</P>
<P>
   The Marcella Sembrich Opera Museum, 4800 Lakeshore Drive, (518)
644-9839, www.operamuseum.com, is open daily June 15 to Sept. 15
from 10 a.m. to 12:30 p.m., and from 2 to 5:30 p.m. Concerts and
lectures on the grounds are over for this season and will resume in
June.
</P>
<P>
   (Constance Rosenblum is editor of the City section of The New
York Times.)
</P>
<P>
   ----- &QL;
