<SLUG> BC-SONOMA-FOOD-HISTORY-TRAVEL-MATURE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: TASTING YOUR WAY THROUGH SONOMA
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: The word AT in parentheses has been used in an e-mail
address instead of the symbol, which many computer systems at
newspapers can't interpret.)  
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 &HT;    
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    September and Sonoma _ the two go together.
 &HT;    Sonoma County, Calif. though known for its wines, is an
agricultural paradise, with a benign climate year-round. However,
it is especially bountiful in September when apples, corn, figs,
plums, raspberries, strawberries and tomatoes as well as wine
grapes, reach their peak. Along with farm products, roadside stands
overflow with lavender, bonsai, honey, flowers, mustard, herbs,
cheese and bread.
 &HT;    Since surveys confirm that many mature travelers spend their
leisure hours gardening when they aren't traveling, the best part
of visiting Sonoma for some may be going from farm to farm
throughout the county, admiring the ripe produce. And many Sonoma
farmers also sell a tempting array of items made from their
products: apple butter or cider, jams, olive oil, relishes, breads
and fruit-filled pastries.
 &HT;    Sonoma County, 45 miles north of San Francisco, stretches from
the Pacific Ocean on its western edge through inland redwood
forests to the Mayacamas Mountains in the east.
 &HT;    Here, you will find the romance of small-town California_ and
plenty of history. Sonoma was the site of California's northernmost
mission, San Francisco Solano de Sonoma, begun in 1823 when
California was under Mexican rule. (The present church was built in
1840.) And the central plaza in the town of Sonoma is where the
short-lived Bear Flag Revolt against Mexico took place in 1846,
with the insurgents declaring California a republic until U.S.
troops rode in and took over.
 &HT;    History of another sort is here for literary aficionados who can
visit Jack London State Park in Sonoma's Valley of the Moon. A
trail meanders through a forest of oaks and firs to the ruins of
the author-adventurer's lavish four-story mansion, which burned
down one hot August night in 1913, a few weeks before he and his
wife planned to move in. The stone walls, fireplaces and window
openings remain.
 &HT;    In Santa Rosa, the county seat, tourists can visit the home and
gardens of horticulturist Luther Burbank, who lived here for more
than a half-century. Here, he developed more than 800 plant
varieties, including the potato that helped defuse the Irish potato
famine. He called Sonoma, ``the chosen spot of all this earth as
far as nature is concerned.'' The Burbank home is at the corner of
Sonoma and Santa Rosa avenues (707-524-5445).
 &HT;    After leaving the city and traveling along the winding roads of
Sonoma's Farm Trails map (call 800-207-9464 or see
www.farmtrails.org.), mature travelers may find themselves
persuaded to stop at roadside stands to buy tomatoes and apples
that glisten like jewels.
 &HT;    There are also dozens of established stops along the trail, such
as Kozlowski Farms (www.kozlowskifarms.com or 707-887-1587) in
Forestville, a three-generation business now in its 50th year. This
is a good place to pick up an apple pie or any of the other 99
items made there in small batches.
 &HT;    Sonoma's special events are tied closely to food; many center
around farmers markets such as the one in Santa Rosa on Thursday
nights where you can wander from stand to stand sampling the food
and feasting your eyes on the work of county artists and artisans.
 &HT;    Other markets are held in Healdsburg on Tuesdays, Petaluma on
Saturdays, Sebastopol on Sundays and Sonoma on Fridays. Many of
these towns also offer markets on other days, depending on the time
of year. In the fall and winter, you can pick your own pumpkins and
cut your own Christmas trees.
 &HT;    Other food events include the Pumpkin Festival (October) in
Healdsburg, Butter and Egg days in Petaluma (April), the
Gravenstein Apple Fair in Sebastopol (August) and wine tastings and
auctions in many of the romantically named growing regions in the
area.
 &HT;    For those with an interest in cooking, Sonoma County offers a
variety of classes and demonstrations such as those at Ramekins
(707-933-0450 or www.ramekins.com) in the town of Sonoma where the
culinary director, Bob Nemerovski, urges students to ``come
hungry'' since eating is part of experience. The three-hour
demonstrations cost from $35-$65, while hands-on classes in
anything from a Chinese Dim Sum party to Chocolate Showstoppers run
from $50-$80. The Depot Hotel (707-938-2980 or www.depothotel.com),
also in Sonoma, has classes, too.
 &HT;    Sonoma's visiting foodies are not finished after touring a few
farms, festivals and farmers markets. An exciting mix of
restaurants serve Sonoma products with style. Conversation over
breakfast might include an item-by-item review of what each person
ate the night before, and as they rehash yesterday's meals, they
will not fail to compare the wines _ possibly from the county's
more than 190 wineries _ with which they washed down their food.
 &HT;    For more information, contact the Sonoma County Tourism Program
at (800) 576-6662, or visit www.sonomacounty.com on the Web.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Adele Malott 
<TEXT>
