<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Aug. 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Monday, readings soared past 100 degrees once again from Kansas
to northern Texas. The hot high-pressure system that has suppressed
cloud cover and prompted the excessive heat will hold steady
Tuesday. As a result, record high temperatures will likely be
broken in a few places. Farther north, a cool front intercepting
the hot air will initiate isolated afternoon thunderstorms from
Nebraska to Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Converging streams of humid air will set the stage for numerous
showers and storms in the Southwest. Rapid runoff of water from the
storms will result in localized flash flooding.
</P>
<P>
   A wedge of dry air will accompany high pressure in New England
while farther south, onshore winds will bring clouds and spotty
showers to the Middle Atlantic states. Elsewhere, the Great Lakes
will be warm with some thundershowers in central sections.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: RIPE FOR RAIN
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, torrential rain fell in parts of the Southwest
and Northeast. The excessive rain flooded homes in Arizona and
carried away cars in northern New Jersey. Late summer and early
autumn is a time when the atmosphere is ripe for rain. By the end
of August, the temperature and evaporation rates from the waterways
bordering the nation are peaking, assuring high concentrations of
water vapor in the air. Furthermore, the still potent late summer
sun provides the energy required to initiate updrafts of humid air,
which are the precursors of tall cumulus clouds and torrential
rain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
