<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4473 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-28 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     RICH v. NOT-RICH  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George W. Bush responded to Al Gore's scrappy
acceptance speech vowing to fight for ``working families'' by
accusing Gore of waging ``class warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Horrors. Take that, Gore. Bush really nailed you for a terrible
sin, defending the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't this what politics is all about _ a struggle for
primacy among competing social and economic interests? What exactly
is Bush's squawk, except that Gore is giving him a scare he didn't
expect?
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore have tailored their appeals to specific
income levels whether they admit it publicly or not. Using a
pejorative term such as ``class warfare,'' designed to conjure up
divisive, threatening images, is a dishonest tactic meant to
override legitimate political differences over who gets what share
of the economic pie.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Gore's surprisingly effective acceptance speech at
the Democratic National Convention, his Republican rival, Bush,
complained that Gore's pitch to working waitresses and
middle-income folks was ``the rhetoric of the past. That's class
warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   This theme is already being recycled by GOP surrogates. A
rejected Bush vice presidential hopeful, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio,
scoffed in a Sunday television interview that warnings about Bush's
massive tax cut plan were nothing but ``class warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and many tax experts point out that the whopping Bush
plan heavily benefits the rich, providing 37 percent of its charms
for the wealthiest 1 percent of the nation. That leaves mere crumbs
for the rest of us and drains the federal surplus so that not much
will be left to pay down the debt and bolster Medicare and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich says: ``You don't punish people when they are
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, if that isn't waging warfare at the expense of others on
behalf of the already financially well-rewarded upper crust, what
is it? Since even a federal budget with a surplus has finite
limits, the inevitable consequence of the Bush-Kasich approach is
punishing people when they are NOT successful or not VERY
successful.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon me, but can't the rich stand up for themselves? The rest
of us need somebody to stand up for us, and there's nothing wrong
with Gore trying to do that. Fairness, after all, is a principle
worth fighting for, and it doesn't hurt politically if it benefits
a majority who can determine an election.
</P>
<P>
   Class warfare, in one guise or another, is always with us. It
will exist so long as some executives get $35 million retirement
benefits from their companies and other employees barely scrape by
with the $5.15 minimum hourly wage.
</P>
<P>
   But by resurrecting that polarizing cry, it is Bush, not Gore,
who is indulging in the rhetoric of the past, repeating the themes
of President George Bush's political generation.
</P>
<P>
   Republican class preferences happen to be just as marked as
Democratic ones, merely more upscale and elitist. Guess which
financial level is most helped or least hurt by Bush's top-heavy
tax cuts, opposition to raising the minimum wage, support for
ending taxes on estates over $1 million, plan to subsidize private
schools with vouchers, willingness to toss Social Security benefits
into Wall Street wallets and resistance to specific prescription
drug benefits?
</P>
<P>
   Gore has targeted a different economic group. He is focusing on
benefits for ordinary non-rich families _ child care credits for
working mothers, public school assistance, low-income savings
accounts and continued economic growth through paying down the
federal debt while shoring up Medicare and Social Security, the
lifelines for millions of middle class seniors.
</P>
<P>
   During the lavish social era of Ronald Reagan, Republicans
justified their preferential treatment of what they called ``the
most productive among us'' by painting the non-rich as jealous
losers who wanted to ``redistribute'' wealth. The crime of the
middle class was described as accepting handouts in the form of
college aid, Medicare and other benefits from government
bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   This fakery worked fairly well so long as Reagan papered over
his policies with a friendly smile and Democratic control of
Congress kept the middle class reasonably protected. But it won't
work again. Real issues are involved here, and Gore's decision to
be specific about them will eventually mean that Bush has to drop
the tired old slogans and deal with them as well.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
