<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4474 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-28 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK STAMP ON PATRIOTS INCREASINGLY APPARENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Throughout preseason _ and especially the
past two days _ Bill Belichick, the Patriots' de facto director of
player personnel, has been set into action. Only a few
administrative superstars are able to wear many hats and wear them
all well. Sometimes one doesn't fit quite right. Just ask Rick
Pitino, the Celtics' president and head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year or two, Belichick, like Pitino, will be under
a microscope. His coaching and personnel decisions will be analyzed
and dissected. Most Patriots fans, and certainly owner Bob Kraft,
wanted a return to one boss after the head coach/personnel director
system didn't work out in the Pete Carroll/Bobby Grier era.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Belichick, like Pitino, will have a grace period, just
as Carroll and Grier did. There's no sense overanalyzing the
decision to drop Sean Morey and keep Dane Looker, or debating
whether dumping Ben Coates and picking up Eric Bjornson was wise.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots haven't played a game under Belichick yet.
</P>
<P>
   But in looking over the past few months, some interesting things
have become apparent about Belichick and his capable young
assistant, Scott Pioli.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Belichick hasn't been afraid to sign them, draft them,
then cut them. He drafted 10 players, and four of them _ tight end
Dave Stachelski, linebacker Casey Tisdale, defensive tackle Jeff
Marriott, and running back Patrick Pass _ are gone.
</P>
<P>
   If any draft pick can be second-guessed, it might be Stachelski,
who was chosen in the fifth round as a possible heir apparent to
Coates. While some teams knew there were problems surrounding
Stachelski's mindset, the Patriots evidently ignored them and
drafted him anyway. Stachelski also was cut by New Orleans, which
picked him up after he left New England.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick's first pick, Adrian Klemm, drafted in the second
round out of Hawaii, was injured early in rookie orientation camp
and hasn't practiced since. On Sunday, he was placed on the
physically unable to perform list, meaning he'll miss at least six
weeks, but Belichick thinks he will play before the year is over.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick isn't shy about having free agent rookies on the
roster; there are seven of them. One is Josh Rawlings, a
6-foot-3-inch, 306-pound offensive lineman who had been in Kansas
City's camp. The Patriots watched him for a quarter, and he made
the team. Adam Davis, a rookie from Oklahoma State, will be a
backup guard, and Lonie Paxton of Sacramento State was kept as a
long snapper.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the free-agent process, the Patriots cut long
snapper/backup tight end Mike Bartrum, who not only did his job
well but could have protected the Patriots at a shallow position.
But the Patriots had Lance Scott in mind, and now Scott is on
injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The roster choices were bold. Four quarterbacks? That's unusual.
Two tight ends? Most teams carry three, maybe four. Two halfbacks?
Some teams carry five. Five linebackers? Some carry eight.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick signed defensive Jon Harris, a former No. 1 draft
pick, but cut him after one minicamp. Belichick decided he didn't
fit his scheme. Raymont Harris was the No. 1 back for most of camp,
but after five exhibition games, he is loking for work.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting his losses is not a difficult task for Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   He dumped Vincent Brisby, feeling Tony Simmons had surpassed him
and Brisby had slowed. He then signed 32-year-old Chris Calloway,
dumped Sean Morey, and retained a pair of rookie free agents,
Shockmain Davis and Dane Looker, trading a sixth-round pick to the
St. Louis Rams for Looker.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick dumped Coates, Bruce Armstrong (who came back at a
reduced price), and Zefross Moss, and didn't re-sign Steve Israel,
Shawn Jefferson, Terry Allen, Chris Sullivan, and Marty Moore.
Antonio Langham replaced Israel, who is out for the season in New
Orleans with a broken leg; Sullivan has been replaced by journeyman
Bobby Hamilton, who rarely saw the field with the Jets last year;
and fourth-round pick Greg Robinson-Randall has replaced Moss, who
retired.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Belichick kept players who fit into his system and
weeded out the ones who don't. After initial resistance, he moved
Tebucky Jones from cornerback to free safety and seems to have
found the physical player at that position who fits his system. If
he is accused of cutting Carroll's guys, he can always point to
Jones. On the other hand, he did cut Carroll's starter at free
safety, Chris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick brought back familiar cornerbacks in Langham and Otis
Smith, a familiar linebacker in Rob Holmberg. He signed veteran
linebacker Chad Cascadden, then realized Cascadden was all done and
announced he had retired.
</P>
<P>
   He signed Scott, who at the time was recovering from an injury.
Scott missed all of training camp, then played sparingly the past
two weeks. Now he's gone for the season with a foot injury suffered
in the Carolina game, and it appears that Scott's agent, Tony
Agnone, is about to begin work on an injury settlement with the
Patriots that would release Scott from his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick allocated five players to NFL Europe _ Morey, Marc
Megna, Noel Scarlett, Garrett Johnson, and Ed Ellis _ and cut them
all.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, Belichick has quickly put his stamp on the team.
Salary cap money has been scarce, so he's had to do it as
economically as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In two or three years, will Belichick's teams get farther than
Carroll's did? Will they be better than 8-8, the low point of the
Carroll regime?
</P>
<P>
   Poor drafts in two of the last three years have set the Patriots
back, but Belichick did not inherit a disaster. He inherited a .500
team that was in the Super Bowl four years ago. The Patriots never
hit rock bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Will Belichick create a team that must take a step back before
it can go forward? Pitino certainly stared that very scenario in
the eye when he took over for M.L. Carr. Now, the focus is on what
Belichick does with his opportunity as player personnel director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
