<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USAMAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY PUTT ENDS BAY STATER'S QUEST FOR AMATEUR GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, N.J. _ Slowly, it rolled toward the hole, picking
up speed as it navigated a slippery slope. Jeff Quinney's putt was
on line, but James Driscoll never once looked at the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching him to see what he was doing,'' said Driscoll,
``because usually you can tell just by watching the guy if he
thinks he's made it or not. And his eyes were getting a little
bigger when it was getting near the hole. I was like, `Oh, man,
this is going in.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dead center, from 30-35 feet. A birdie on the par-3 third hole
at Baltusrol Golf Club Monday morning that put an end to the 100th
US Amateur championship. In his bid to become the first
Massachusetts-born winner of this tournament since 1956, Driscoll,
of Brookline, Mass., was halted in a stunning calmness that was in
contrast to the wild drama that he had produced late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lose, you lose,'' said Driscoll, 22, when asked if getting
beaten by a birdie _ and not losing via a bogey _ was any
consolation. ``But at the same time, it's a much better way to end
it like that. It's more exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   It was minutes after the sudden defeat, and Driscoll was trying
to sort out his feelings. So much had happened since early Sunday
evening that he had a dozen different emotions tugging at him. He
had authored a stirring comeback, winning the final three holes
Sunday to erase a three-hole deficit and force a playoff with
Quinney, 21, and he wanted nothing more than to finish the match
that night. But Mother Nature rudely interrupted. Lightning forcing
a suspension in play after two playoff holes had been halved in
pars. So back he and Quinney trudged for a 9 a.m. resumption at
their 39th hole, the par-3 third.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll had gone to bed Sunday night with visions of the 5-iron
he would swing first thing in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect,'' he said. ``A full 5-iron for me is 205. That's
exactly what it was to the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven times (five pars, one birdie, one bogey) during the
match-play portion of match play Driscoll had played this downhill
hole, so he knew the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That green is pretty forgiving if you're on the right side,''
he said. ``It's going to come down a little bit, even as wet as it
was. I was going middle of the green, trying to draw it.''
</P>
<P>
   The air was heavy, thick with humidity, so Driscoll told himself
to swing hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't leave anything in the bag in the swing,'' he said.
But he pushed the shot slightly right.
</P>
<P>
   ``On another day, that same shot would have kicked down, ridden
the slope and been close,'' said Scott Fischer, a Baltusrol caddie
who was working for Driscoll for the 10th straight day, dating back
to practice rounds before this weeklong event had started.
``Unfortunately, it was wet and didn't come left.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it stayed in the rough, a yard off the green, 50-55
feet from the pin. Advantage Quinney, the Arizona State senior who
had led this 36-hole finale from the opening hole until Driscoll
staged his three-hole theatrics to pull even.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's about a half-club ahead of me usually,'' said Quinney,
who chose 4-iron and knew that his opponent had gone a little long
and right, in the rough. Just put it on the green, he said to
himself, with a smooth swing.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll knew Quinney wouldn't have an easy putt but quickly
turned his attention to his own chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pretty good lie,'' said Driscoll. ``It wasn't sitting down,
but it was a lot faster than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   It ran some 12 feet past the hole, coming to rest inches off the
green, and Driscoll just stared and stared at the line he faced to
save par. The matter, for the moment, was out of his hands. It
never returned to him, for Quinney's putt _ just the fourth stroke
in the resumption of play _ tracked the bottom of the cup all the
way. It was the first birdie Quinney had made in 22 holes, dating
back to the 17th hole of the morning 18 Sunday, and standing to the
side of the green, a father was overcome with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed a lay-in with 10 seconds to go in the high school
basketball championship (of Oregon), and that haunts me to this
day,'' said Bob Quinney, Jeff's father. ``I worried about Jeff
being remembered for losing a three-shot lead with three holes to
play. Now, he's erased that and that makes me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing nearby, Driscoll accepted congratulations from his
father Richard, his mother Rosemary, five brothers, a sister, and
countless cousins and friends, some of whom had left the Boston
area at 3 a.m. to get there in time for the resumption of the
playoff. The support, he said, was overwhelming, but quickly the
questions turned to his future plans. Originally, Driscoll had
talked of turning pro in time for next month's New England Open,
then going to PGA Tour Qualifying School.
</P>
<P>
   Now? He isn't so sure. With his runner-up finish at the US
Amateur, Driscoll earns a spot in the Masters field next April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have to wait and play in the Masters,'' he said.
``Who doesn't do that? I mean, I think I'd be stupid not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Driscoll stood just outside the large crowd that
gathered at the third green. Quinney was being presented the
winning trophy, and it was noted that Driscoll joined illustrious
company: None other than Bobby Jones had finished as US Amateur
runner-up at Baltusrol in 1926. Though his son had not become the
first Massachusetts winner since another Charles River golfer 54
years ago _ Ted Bishop _ Richard Driscoll couldn't stop smiling and
shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to be disappointed,'' he said. ``We had such a great
week. Just the thrill of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
