<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4487 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VENICE-SINKING-AR     08-28 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VENICE-SINKING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT SINKING FEELING, AGAIN, IN VENICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 (Science Times)  
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE, Italy _ Science often rests on chance discoveries. So it
is that an American archaeologist studying the origins of Venice
has stumbled on clues suggesting that a multibillion-dollar plan to
build floodgates to save the city from rising waters is doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be careful,'' Dr. Albert J. Ammerman warned as he pulled a
tarp from an archaeological dig, freeing swarms of mud wasps.
</P>
<P>
   The pit, 10 feet deep and more than 30 feet wide, had been dug
next to an ancient basilica. The hole was below sea level, with a
pump keeping it from filling with water. At its bottom lay one of
the oldest known pieces of evidence of human habitation in the
Venetian archipelago _ a stone walkway dated to around the second
century.
</P>
<P>
   This and kindred discoveries show that, over the ages, people
living here have had to haul in countless tons of dirt, silt, wood
and stone to fortify their swampy isles and keep them from
disappearing into the sea. They suggest that the floodgates plan _
one of the biggest public works projects of all time _ will be an
inadequate solution rife with problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to see this to understand how the ground builds up,''
said Ammerman, a Colgate University archaeologist who has studied
the origins of Venice for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   That the city of Venice rests on millions of wooden stilts
pounded into marshy ground is well known. But the age and
surprising abundance of other supporting materials is only now
coming to light, with large implications for public policy.
</P>
<P>
   The lost world of artifacts and structures is letting Ammerman
and his colleagues in Italy and the United States estimate both
past and future rates of subsidence. The news is bad for a city
whose famous piazzas already flood with alarming regularity.
</P>
<P>
   For complex reasons, scientists say, Venice is sinking faster
than ever and in the coming century the encroaching waters of the
Adriatic Sea could devastate this celebrated city of art and
architectural gems. The situation will only get worse if global
warming causes sea levels to rise.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they say, surging waters will overwhelm the main way
Italy is planning to fight the danger _ 79 mobile floodgates meant
to cut off the Venetian lagoon and its islands from the highest of
the high tides. The plan, drawn up decades ago and debated since
then, is on the verge of approval by the Italian government. It is
estimated to cost $2 billion to $4 billion, and has won backing
from Italian companies eager for lucrative contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Ammerman, 58, a walking encyclopedia about things Venetian, has
decided to air his findings widely in hopes of thwarting the
project and spurring research on alternative ways of saving Venice,
a cultural icon that 10 million people visit each year. It is also
his home.
</P>
<P>
   The mobile floodgates ``will have ceased to offer any
protection'' from extreme tides soon after they are built, he wrote
last week in the journal Science. Saving the city will take fresh
thinking, he added, perhaps through an international competition
for new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a test case for the future,'' said Charles E. McClennen,
a Colgate geologist who aids Ammerman's inquiries here and who
collaborated on the Science article. ``We got into this research by
accident. But now we see its general importance for cities in many
coastal regions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammerman's work is financed by Colgate, the Delmas Foundation,
the Kress Foundation and the National Geographic Society.
</P>
<P>
   That Venetians live a few precarious inches above sea level is
evident to any visitor to this city of interconnected islands.
</P>
<P>
   Its canals teem not only with gondolas and motorboats but fish
large and small, as well as algae and seaweed. On hot summer days,
the canals at low tide tend to give off a pungent odor said to be
based partly on decomposing sea life and partly on the outflows of
ancient plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, the tides here go up and down about three feet. Tides
that are more extreme, known as ``acqua alta,'' or high water, tend
to occur between October and April and periodically inundate
Venice, most alarmingly in 1966 when flooding caused wide damage
and economic losses. The tidal surges are driven by heavy rains,
winter weather patterns and southerly winds that blow Adriatic
waters northward.
</P>
<P>
   On many old buildings, the red bricks of the ground floors are
coated by a patina of white _ corrosive sea salt soaked up by the
absorbent bricks, which weakens them and causes them to crumble.
Low wooden doors are often stained or rotted away at the bottom
because of past flooding, and commercial shop doors in fashionable
districts often have metal guides that allow the quick installation
of waterproof gates. Raised walkways are set up in heavily traveled
areas during winter floods. Some tour books recommend high boots.
</P>
<P>
   It was sheer accident that Ammerman came to delve into the
origins of Venice, and that his work opened a new window on the
dimensions of the flooding menace.
</P>
<P>
   An environmental archaeologist trained at the University of
London, he worked in Italy in the 1970s and 1980s studying sites
around Parma, Calabria and Rome, including the Forum. A specialty
of his was extracting core samples and dating materials to better
understand the original context of ancient objects and monuments.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Ammerman was living in Venice, happy to have a break
from Rome's gritty bustle, when Dr. Maurizia de Min, a senior
archaeologist at Venice's Superintendency of Monuments, asked him
for help. She was helping restore a church, San Lorenzo, and wanted
him to probe beneath it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit stuff three feet down, five feet below mean modern sea
level,'' he recalled. ``We hit archaeological things. We moved
lower. It was always the same _ layers of living and building
materials.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the turning point,'' Ammerman said. ``We started to
realize that there was a whole world down there that no one had
ever imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians had long known that Venice rose to power in the ninth
century, its swampy isolation a bulwark against invaders, its
location on the Adriatic a boon for trade. But the scientists
managed to discover its lost infancy, going back in time more than
500 years further.
</P>
<P>
   Through the 1990s, working closely with de Min and the
Superintendency of Monuments, Ammerman investigated six sites in
Venice and its lagoon. Each proved a revelation about past
habitation and building practices, the evidence always surprisingly
deep and speaking volumes about subsidence rates over the ages.
</P>
<P>
   The most extensive dig was on the isle of Torcello, next to the
ancient basilica.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent visit there, Ammerman stepped carefully into the
deep pit where the scientists had uncovered the low stone walkway
dated to the second century. Higher up, and thus younger, he
pointed out a stone hearth, dated to the sixth century, and a road
surface made of aligned stones, dated to about the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   A major breakthrough in his work was understanding that the
depth of such artifacts could yield a way to gauge old sea levels,
and thus the rate of ground subsidence over the centuries. For
instance, Ammerman found that the second-century walkway, probably
of Roman origin, had been erected near the edge of the island about
18 inches above what was then the sea level.
</P>
<P>
   Back at his apartment in Venice, he displayed a long, clear
plastic tube filled with a deep core sample recently taken from
below the walkway area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tells you these sediments are typical of a marsh
island,'' he said, pointing to streaks of brown and yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of such samples and depth calculations have revealed the
arc of accelerating subsidence since the Venetian lagoon formed
6,000 years ago. Ammerman calculates that, per century, human
artifacts sank at a rate of about three inches, then five, then 10,
with the fastest decline in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The causes of the speedup are complex, he said. Factors include
local industry's pumping of water from beneath the Venice region
(which has been stopped), the oxidation of peat that forms as part
of the substrate, the compaction of spongy sediments under the
growing weight of buildings, and slow changes in plate tectonics
and the region's geology.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1999, Ammerman, McClennen, de Min and Dr. Rupert Housley
of the University of Glasgow published an overview of their speedup
findings in Antiquity, a top archaeology journal.
</P>
<P>
   It was this research that led Ammerman to conclude that Italy's
main solution to the flooding problem would not work because it was
based on flawed estimates of the subsidence rate.
</P>
<P>
   The floodgates, he reasoned, would have to close 94 to 150 times
each year during high tides, destroying the lagoon's delicate
ecological balance, cutting it off from the sea and its cleansing
flows.
</P>
<P>
   The floodgates would be built in lines at the entrances to the
Venetian lagoon. Lying flat in housings built into the seabed, they
would in theory have no effect on shipping or regular tides. When
storm surges were forecast, compressed air would be pumped into
their hollow inner cavities, forcing out water and causing the
hinged gates to tilt upward and rise to the surface to block
incoming swells.
</P>
<P>
   Since the worst tides come mostly in winter, Ammerman and
McClennen wrote last week in Science, gate closure ``will end up
taking place repeatedly, day after day and week after week.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the plan are unmoved, saying Ammerman is
exaggerating the difficulties. Anyway, they say, if the water rises
faster than expected, as Ammerman says it will, the barriers are
all the more crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gates become even more urgent if the worst scenarios are
right,'' said Dr. Rafael L. Bras, an environmental engineer at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology who led an international
assessment of the floodgate plan.
</P>
<P>
   But in all likelihood, he said, the gates would have to close
far less often than Ammerman foresees and would do little or no
ecological harm.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Bras said he was saddened to see
Ammerman's paper in Science. ``I think his article will just
continue the debate and, in the meantime, nothing is done and the
city is in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The Consorzio Venezia Nuova, the bloc of Italian companies eager
to build the floodgates, denounced the Colgate researchers as
``clearly less concerned with the validity of scientific data than
they are with attempting to persuade the Italian government to
withdraw the concession granted to Italian construction
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   John Keahey, a journalist working on a book about saving Venice,
said Ammerman's arguments were ``having a big impact'' on Italian
politicians. ``They could use this as an excuse to delay a
decision,'' Keahey said. ``The government is in a struggle to
survive, they would probably rather use the money to give the
citizens a tax break.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammerman said the Consorzio would rather attack him than face
the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants a silver bullet,'' he said. ``But that doesn't
exist,'' at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Something may emerge in an international competition, he said.
But in the meantime, Venice needs to continue what it has already
started: raising canals and sidewalks, elevating power supplies and
telephone lines and moving people out of the first floors of
residences.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should do what people have always done here since the
beginning, which is to build up the ground,'' Ammerman added.
``This buys you time to work up a better solution that doesn't
create equally bad problems.''
</P>
<P>
   A rise in key spots of just a few inches, he said, could buy
Venice a half century of breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have lots of time,'' Ammerman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
