<SLUG> BC-GILRUTH-SERVICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA PAYS TRIBUTE TO AEROSPACE ENGINEER ROBERT GILRUTH 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Associates of Robert Gilruth, the late aerospace engineer whose
skill, leadership and inspiration helped America reach the moon
more than 30 years ago, gathered at NASA's Johnson Space Center on
Monday to pay tribute.
</P>
<P>
   The 86-year-old spaceflight pioneer died on Aug. 17 in
Charlottesville, Va., after a lengthy illness.
</P>
<P>
   The native Minnesotan's work influenced the design of the
country's earliest supersonic aircraft as well its spacecraft, from
the tiny Mercury capsule to the space shuttle transport. He served
as Johnson's first director, a post he filled in Houston for nearly
a decade until his departure in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Gilruth enabled this nation's human spaceflight program,
enabled us to get humans into orbit, but he did much more,''
Johnson Space Center director George W.S. Abbey, told more than 400
who assembled at the Clear Lake research facility for a memorial
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``He enabled us to get men to the moon successfully, and bring
them back to Earth safely. He left us a legacy,'' said Abby. ``When
humans get out of Earth orbit again, go back to the moon and take
the first steps on the planet Mars, Bob Gilruth will be there with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Then chief of aeronautic research for the National Advisory
Committee on Aeronautics, Gilruth was chosen in 1958 to lead the
space task group, a team of 35 experts assembled in Virginia by the
newly created National Aeronautics and Space Administration to
launch an American into space. By 1961, the group had relocated in
Houston as the nucleus of what was known as NASA's Manned
Spacecraft Center. The campus-like complex later was renamed for
former president Lyndon B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   With the relocation came new orders for NASA from then-President
Kennedy. The embryonic space agency was to stage a come-from-behind
victory by reaching the moon with astronauts ahead of the country's
Cold War rival, the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he retired in 1972, Gilruth had directed NASA's
first 25 human spaceflights, including all of the Mercury and
Gemini missions, and four of the six Apollo moon landings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gilruth was a unique individual who had a knack for solving
problems and at the same time developing young engineers to meet
the challenges of the future,'' said Chris Kraft, a close associate
of Gilruth's who became Johnson's second director. ``We were
blessed by his collegial approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gilruth was intimately involved with every basic decision as
we made our way into space,'' Kraft recalled. ``He had the
fortitude to take the risks required to accomplish the task.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilruth's widow, Jo, said her husband was as thrilled as he was
humbled by the challenge of his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he would have worked for nothing if they would have
just given him room and board. He always thought he was the
luckiest man to do what he really loved and with people he
respected,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's tribute closed with a tree planting ceremony. A live
oak, planted in tribute to Gilruth, became the newest addition to a
maturing grove of 29 trees, each a remembrance to a pioneer in the
era of human spaceflight.
</P>
<P>
   Gilruth's tree stands across from Alan Shepard's. The first
American in space, Shepard died in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
