<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Aug. 29 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MINIMUM-WAGE (Washington) _ Speaker Dennis Hastert on Monday
offered key concessions to Democrats on a plan to raise the federal
minimum wage, moving to end months of stalemate on a popular bill
that Republicans fear might damage them at the polls. The House and
Senate earlier this year approved an increase in the minimum wage
by $1, to $6.15 an hour, but since then the proposal has stalled
causing some Republicans to fear they are handing Democrats a
potent campaign issue. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: Early version has moved and will be updated)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-VII (Undated) _ Feature on the 1988 presidential
campaign and George W. Bush's role in his father's successful race.
By Nicholas D. Kristof. Latest in a series looking at the career of
the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT18,19,20.
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTS-GAYS (Undated) _ In the wake of the Supreme Court
decision on gays in Scouting, schools and charities across the
country are considering whether they want to stay involved with the
program. Some are contemplating backing off from their level of
contribution and whether they want to make their facilities
available to the organization. The San Diego Police Department, as
well as the United Way in San Francisco and Santa Fe, have pulled
out as sponsors. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ATTICA-SETTLEMENT (Rochester, N.Y.) _ Declaring that the
inmates who were beaten and tortured during the 1971 Attica prison
uprising were ``humiliated,'' ``dehumanized'' and treated ``like
garbage,'' a federal judge on Monday approved a landmark settlement
that will compensate more than 500 families a total of $8 million
for the inmates' physical and emotional abuse. The settlement
weaves both meticulous financial details and heartwrenching
anecdotes from the inmates in fleshing out a deal reached in
January between New York state and lawyers representing 1,281
former inmates over the storming of the western New York prison by
state troopers. In all, 43 people died and more than 80 were
wounded during the uprising and siege. By David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-U.S. (Washington) _ The U.S. supports its view
that an explosion rather than a collision was responsible for the
Kursk disaster. By Steven Lee Myers with Christopher Drew.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-U.S.-BERENSON (Undated) _ Peru's military court on Monday
revoked the life sentence of Lori Berenson, the U.S. national
jailed in 1996 for involvement with leftist rebels, saying she
would be given a new trial in a civilian court. (Summary from
wires)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLOOD-PRESSURE (Undated) _ The calcium channel blocker drugs
that are commonly prescribed to lower high blood pressure are less
effective than other drugs and their use is leading to nearly
85,000 unnecessary heart attacks and cases of heart failure each
year worldwide, according to a new study being reported today.
Calcium channel blockers are not harmful. Because they are less
effective users do not gain the benefits they would by using other
types of anti-hypertensive drugs. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
