<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-GRAVITY-ART-2TAKE     08-28 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GRAVITY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X-RAYS FROM AFAR BOLSTER A THEORY OF A WHIRLPOOL IN EMPTY SPACE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Ill., Md.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can empty space be stirred like pancake batter? According to
Einstein's theory of relativity, the gravity of a spinning object
should tug slightly on the surrounding space and slowly drag it
around in circles. Any matter would be pulled along, even though
ordinary gravity can only attract matter, not push it sideways.
</P>
<P>
   Observational astronomers have remained skeptical of that
supremely bizarre prediction, since they have never found clear,
direct proof that the phenomenon exists. But with the discovery of
a strange new signal by the Rossi X-ray Timing Explorer, a NASA
satellite designed to measure X-ray sources in deep space, a few
more astronomers may be ready to get on board.
</P>
<P>
   Michiel van der Klis of the University of Amsterdam and two
colleagues will report in the Sept. 1 issue of Astrophysical
Journal Letters that the satellite has detected previously unknown,
oscillating X-ray signals from three superdense chunks of matter
called neutron stars. The powerful gravity of those weird objects
is just what theorists say is required to produce the effect, and
the ringing signals may be generated by space being spun in a
circle.
</P>
<P>
   Van der Klis said that the observations were ``not a definitive
proof'' of the phenomenon, but were just what astronomers expected
if it was happening around the stars. ``Because there is a large
amount of matter spinning around there, general relativity predicts
that space-time will be dragged around a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The neutron stars, which are essentially the cinders that remain
after a star explodes, are probably each in a close orbit around an
ordinary star whose outer, gaseous layers are being torn away by
the powerful gravity of their companions.
</P>
<P>
   As the gas spirals violently into the neutron star and becomes
hot enough to emit X-rays, it begins to rock and shake with some of
the rhythms of the star system, like a cup of coffee resting on the
hood of an idling car _ the faster the engine idles, the faster the
coffee jiggles. Astrophysicists expect one of those jiggles to be
the rate at which the strong gravity of the spinning neutron star
stirs the emptiness of space, and as the gas is pulled along it may
be emitting X-rays at the frequency observed by the satellite.
</P>
<P>
   How can empty space be stirred? In Einstein's general theory of
relativity, gravity and space are not separate concepts, but work
hand in glove. Gravity twists and warps space, and it can also pull
it along as if it were a real substance rather than emptiness.
</P>
<P>
   To see how odd the effect is, imagine riding a merry-go-round in
space. Ordinarily, a rider would feel centrifugal force only when
the distant stars appeared to be spinning around. Both the
centrifugal force and the apparently spinning stars would be
indications that the merry-go-round is, in fact, turning on its
axis.
</P>
<P>
   Under the influence of a massive rotating object, like a neutron
star, Einstein's theory says that space itself would begin
swirling, though not as fast as the star _ gravity is an imperfect
stirring spoon. So if a merry-go-round is turning at the same rate
as space, the centrifugal force would vanish, even though the stars
would still seem to be spinning around. Matter outside a neutron
star can be swept up in this swirling space like sticks in a
whirlpool.
</P>
<P>
   But many of those notions have not yet been tested
observationally where gravity is very strong and they lead to the
most bizarre consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Probing them where the geometry is highly twisted and malleable,
said Frederick K. Lamb, a physicist at the University of Illinois
at Urbana-Champaign, ``is one of the major problems of modern
physics and astrophysics, and it's a regime in which we have had
very little or no information.''
</P>
<P>
   The spinning of emptiness, called ``frame dragging,'' is surely
one of the most bizarre of all those consequences of relativity.
Scientists are still debating whether that explanation for the new
buzz from the neutron stars is the correct one. But Mario Vietri,
an astrophysicist at the University of Rome's campus III, said that
X-ray emissions from those extreme environments were ``the one way
that we know to test general relativity in the strong-field
regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Begelman, an astrophysicist at the University of
Colorado, Boulder, said that the X-ray emissions carried even more
information about the gas and its behavior if scientists could only
interpret it. ``I would say that Rossi has provided an amazingly
rich data set that far outstrips our ability to understand it
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The star systems in question are among the most exotic and
violent in the galaxy, said van der Klis, who did his work with
Peter G. Jonker of the University of Amsterdam and Mariano Mendez
of Amsterdam and the National University of La Plata in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   The systems probably come about when one star much heavier than
the sun and one lighter than the sun are born side-by-side or drift
near each other. The two stars are fated to have much different
lives, since heavy stars use up their nuclear fuel rapidly and can
explode as supernovas after just millions of years _ an eye blink
in cosmic terms _ while lighter stars burn steadily for billions of
years.
</P>
<P>
   When the heavy star explodes, it leaves behind a neutron star, a
superdense cinder of collapsed matter with the density of an atomic
nucleus. Just 10 to 15 miles across, it still weighs more than the
sun. (Extremely massive stars can create objects called black holes
that collapse even further.) Eventually, this dark star and its
rather ordinary companion can settle into an orbit so tight that
both would fit inside a sphere the size of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   At those close distances, the powerful gravity of the
fast-living neutron star begins to rip gaseous material from the
outer layers of its companion. The material does not fall straight
onto the neutron star's surface, but instead spirals downward, like
a satellite whose orbit gradually decays. The material probably
gathers into a flattened disk, called an accretion disk, before
plunging at speeds as high as half the speed of light onto the
neutron star's murky surface.
</P>
<P>
   Because of friction among the gases in the accretion disk and
the violence of the collision at the surface, van der Klis said,
``the end result of the whole process is that an enormous amount of
X-rays is emitted.''
</P>
<P>
   Called low-mass X-ray binaries, about 100 such systems are known
in the galaxy, he said. Because the binaries are dim, distant and
small in size, astronomers regard their copious emission of X-rays
as more than a curiosity. Without the emission, the dark cinder
``is a dead star,'' van der Klis said. The emission ``is the basic
reason that we are able to see this star at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The small, parsimonious companion is generally not bright enough
to be of much help. So for decades, astronomers have launched X-ray
satellites to study these sources and other high-energy displays in
the heavens. Since X-rays do not penetrate very deeply into the
atmosphere, astronomers must study them from space.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NASA launched the Rossi X-ray Timing Explorer in late 1995 with
a highly sensitive detector that is able to pick up high-frequency
variations, often faster than a thousand times a second, in the
output of X-ray sources in space. Astronomers wanted such a
detector partly because they hoped to see not just a steady X-ray
glow, but also a direct signature of the dynamic, whirling motion
of the gases around the neutron star.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite cannot see anything but a flickering point of
X-ray emission. But from the rate of those flickers _ their
frequency _ astronomers can piece together what is happening around
the star.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the frequency with which a clump of X-ray-emitting
gas disappears behind the star and emerges again tells astronomers
how fast it is moving in its orbit. The faster the speed, the
smaller the orbit. Since neutron stars have little atmosphere, and
gas can orbit very close to its surface, that frequency says
something about the size of the star. The relevant frequencies can
be higher than a thousand times a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to measure things that are happening near the
surface of the neutron star, then you're going to have to resolve
that kind of time scale,'' said Jean Swank, an astronomer at the
NASA Goddard Space Flight Center who is Rossi's project scientist.
The satellite's detectors are up to the job, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The information is particularly precious, since the exact size
of neutron stars for a given mass is a major point of contention
among theorists who try to understand how nuclear matter behaves
under tremendous pressures, a relation described mathematically by
a relation called the equation of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``How big a star is for a given density depends basically on the
equation of state _ how compressible the matter is,'' said Tod
Strohmayer, an astronomer at the NASA Goddard Space Flight Center.
The orbital frequency, he said, ``gives information about the mass
and radius of the star.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is not the only telltale frequency that astronomers had
a chance see in the Rossi satellite data. Like the wavering ``beat
frequency'' that is heard when two tuning forks with different
tones are struck at the same time, the rotation frequency of the
neutron star could modulate the first signal through a complex
physical process at the star, creating more tones for Rossi.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the possible frame-dragging effect. If a
spinning neutron star's equator is not in the same plane as the
accretion disk, this dragging might cause the disk to wobble with
yet another frequency that the satellite could detect.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after Rossi was launched in late 1995, teams
led by Strohmayer and van der Klis detected two definite
frequencies from neutron star binaries. They were identified with
the orbiting gas and the spinning star, although theorists have
later come up with alternative explanations.
</P>
<P>
   That debate continues, although Strohmayer said the data had
already yielded information about the possible sizes and densities
of the stars. The Sept. 1 paper by van der Klis and colleagues
announces the discovery of a new oscillation in three X-ray
binaries. Some theorists, including Vietri of Rome, believe the new
data are evidence of frame dragging.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Lamb and his colleague Draza Markovic of the
University of Illinois, believe that the frame-dragging wobble
would be canceled out by other, more mundane effects in the system,
indicating that the new oscillation must be caused by something
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think it's not settled yet,'' Swank said. ``It
seems to me likely that that kind of thing might occur there,'' she
said, referring to frame dragging. But Swank said the issue
probably would not be settled until other features of the
oscillations were known, such as how they changed as the star's
output brightened and dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   The debate could also be influenced eventually by a long-planned
NASA mission called Gravity Probe B, which is expected to look for
the tiny amount of frame dragging produced by Earth's relatively
paltry gravitational pull.
</P>
<P>
   Begelman of Colorado cautioned that some entirely different
effect could yet be behind the new discovery around neutron stars,
such as wave motions that relativity theory predicts should also
exist in the accretion disk. Future X-ray missions with names like
Constellation X and Maxim, will probably have something to say
about resolving those mysteries. Meanwhile, the Rossi satellite
goes on making headlines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
