<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MET-ASIAN-ART-800&AMP;TRI     08-28 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-ASIAN-ART-800&AMP;TRIM(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCHOLAR WHO BROUGHT ASIAN ART TO THE WEST RETIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  By   HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thirty years ago, Asian art led a marginal life at
the Metropolitan Museum of Art. In 1970 the only Chinese works on
view were in a room of early Buddhist sculpture and some cases of
ceramics. As late as 1990 Indian art meant an assortment of objects
crammed into dimly lighted vitrines on the Great Hall balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed. The museum now has more than 50 permanent
galleries devoted to the largest and most comprehensive collection
of Asian art under one roof. These days the Met is fond of calling
itself a ``museum of Asian art within a museum,'' and it is
justified in doing so.
</P>
<P>
   What went right? Several things. The international market in
Asian art opened up. (Trade relations with China were renewed in
1972, and tons _ literally _ of Southeast Asian material found its
way to the West in the wake of the Vietnam War.) In addition a
number of fine American private collections were ripe for
institutional picking. And the Met went into a global expansion
mode.
</P>
<P>
   The catalytic agent, though, was the arrival at the museum in
1971 of Wen C. Fong, a highly esteemed art historian at Princeton
University, as special consultant for Far Eastern affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three decades he wooed collectors, engineered
acquisitions, beefed up the curatorial staff, campaigned for
gallery space and transformed an institution that had come to
collecting Asian material very late in the game into a major
international contender.
</P>
<P>
   On his watch some superb collections came into the museum, and
permanent Asian galleries gradually materialized, many carved out
of space once reserved for blockbuster shows. The Astor Court
garden and the Douglas Dillon galleries for Chinese painting and
calligraphy opened in 1981. Next came Japanese galleries in 1987,
South and Southeast Asian galleries in 1994, new Chinese painting
and decorative arts galleries in 1997 and finally a Korean gallery
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This summer Fong, 69, announced his retirement from the museum,
where he has long been consultive chairman of the Asian art
department. His position has been taken by another Met veteran,
James C.Y. Watt, 63, a curator at the museum for 15 years. Both men
were born in China and both are respected scholars with similar
worries about directions the field is taking.
</P>
<P>
   Fong was born in Shanghai in 1930 and was given a traditional
at-home education. ``I was taught by an old scholar, which meant
that I studied old things,'' he said in an interview. ``But there
was family pressure on me to take up engineering, so I escaped to
this country to study art.''
</P>
<P>
   After finishing graduate work in Chinese art at Princeton, he
taught there almost without break until his retirement from the
faculty last year. He established the first American doctoral
program in Chinese art history there in 1964; many leading curators
and teachers now at work across the country are his former
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas Hoving was the museum's director at the time,'' Fong
explained, ``but the man behind the Asian initiative was Douglas
Dillon, the president of the board of trustees. He wanted to buy
gobs and gobs of art.''
</P>
<P>
   And buy the museum did, beginning with 500 Japanese objects that
it took five years to pay for. In 1973 the Met acquired a group of
Chinese paintings from the collector C.C. Wang, beginning a long
association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collecting opportunities are still plentiful,'' Fong said,
``but the market is so treacherous now in terms of forgeries.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong's path wasn't always smooth. He said that when in 1971 he
proposed mounting an exhibition of calligraphy, the art form
revered above all others by the Chinese, one museum official wanted
to put the show in the ceramics cases on the Great Hall balcony.
``It's just like postage stamps, isn't it?'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, the museum will present the largest Chinese
calligraphy survey ever mounted in the United States. Titled ``The
Embodied Image: Chinese Calligraphy From the John B. Elliott
Collection,'' it will open on Sept. 15 and fill all 13 of the
Chinese painting galleries.
</P>
<P>
   The energy Fong brought to his work was Herculean, as his
successor is the first to acknowledge. Watt was easing into
semiretirement when the Met asked him to take over the department.
``Recently, I've had the great leisure of being able to read for
two hours every morning,'' he said. ``Now I'll have to forgo that
again for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Fong's demeanor is outgoing and voluble, Watt's is low-key
and reticent, qualities reflected in his views of the immediate
direction Asian art at the Met will take. ``We need to quiet down a
bit,'' Watt said. ``We've been rushing headlong since I've been
here, 15 years, with new galleries. Now that we've filled up every
possible space we've been allotted, it's time to stand back and
take stock.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But at least one ambitious Chinese exhibition _ ``Early Chinese
Empire: The First Millennium, Han Through Tang'' _ is very much in
the works. Scheduled for 2003, it will be primarily an
archaeological show, though unlike those recently at the Guggenheim
Museum in Manhattan and the National Gallery in Washington, this
one will be ``a focused exhibition of a certain period rather than
just a random display of masterpieces,'' Watt said.
</P>
<P>
   Even within that definition, the time frame is vast, from the
collapse of the Han dynasty in A.D. 220 and into the Tang, which
began in 618. This was a complex transitional period that produced
what Watt called ``a totally new culture for China.'' The plan is
for all or most of the material to be loans from China itself.
``I'm hoping we'll have some of the best Buddhist sculptures and,
if it can be done, wall paintings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Watt grew up in Hong Kong and, like Fong, had a classical
education at home with a scholar-teacher before going to Oxford. He
then returned to Hong Kong, where he studied at the Chinese
University and worked at the City Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a concentration of great scholars in the city in the
1950s and 60s,'' he said, ``the last of a generation with an
approach going all the way back to the Song dynasty.'' His own
family background included a lineage of scholars, ``rather an
obscure one.'' The last of them to come into public prominence was
a Ming-period writer who became a monk to escape persecution for
resisting Manchu rule during China's last dynasty, the Qing.
</P>
<P>
   Under Manchu rule, which ended in 1912, Watt's family retreated
from public life. ``They were forbidden to do anything,'' he said.
``But they had their libraries.'' They also had access to private
art collections, which they were able both to enjoy and study
intensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to handle an object is so important,'' Watt said.
``That's why some people feel not all art should be behind glass.
But students today don't have that primary experience.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an experience that he was given by his first
scholar-teacher in Hong Kong, with whom he practiced calligraphy,
seal carving and music, disciplines, long associated with a true
education, that can only be taught one-to-one.
</P>
<P>
   The accomplishments that formed the basis of his approach to
scholarship are no longer taught in China, and their spirit will
be, he said, increasingly difficult to convey to young art
historians of the future. ``But somehow,'' Watt added, ``they must
become familiar with the tradition of passing on tradition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
