<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazine lists don't match up
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News ATLANTA - If various magazine lists of
<TEXT>
``biggest'' companies don't match, why should their lists of the
``fastest growing'' companies match? They don't.
<P>
   Three Georgia-based companies are on the latest Fortune (Sept.
11) list of 100 fastest growing companies: Profit Recovery Group
International (59), AHL Services (71) and Nova (98).
</P>
<P>
   But four Georgia companies are on the 100 fastest growing list
compiled by Individual Investor (September): Manhattan Associates
(7), Antec (24), Matria Healthcare (54) and Internet Security
Systems (79).
</P>
<P>
   Fortune ranked companies with at least $50 million in market
value by revenue growth. Individual Investor ranked the earnings
growth of companies with a market cap of $100 million or above.
Only nine companies made both lists: Concord Camera, Cree, Forest
Laboratories, Network Appliance, QLogic. RF Micro Devices, SDL,
Siebel Systems and Triquint Semiconductor.
</P>
<P>
   Business bashing pays
</P>
<P>
   Business bashing is selling well for Democratic presidential
nominee Al Gore, according to recent polls showing him ahead of
Republican George Bush, Business Week (Sept. 4) reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's neo-populist model taps into a growing public backlash
against the concentration of corporate power, yet he does so
without attacking business in general,'' the magazine says. The
message is understood especially well in ``old economy'' states
from Pennsylvania to Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   White knights can tarnish
</P>
<P>
   Placing your bets on management messiahs can be hazardous to
your wealth, says Barron's (Aug. 28). A company's stock may bounce
when the new manager is first hired by a troubled company but
usually it doesn't stay there.
</P>
<P>
   The share prices of Conseco, Hilton Hotels, Exide, Eastman
Kodak, Kmart, AT&AMP;T, Sunbeam, Rite Aid and Xerox are all lower than
the peaks reached after the arrival of their supposed saviors.
</P>
<P>
   The rescuer's prowess may lie in financial engineering instead
of business building, Barron's says. And some companies are in
trouble because they're in fundamentally bad businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   America's markets and communities are being reshaped by young,
skilled, tech-savvy workers who are willing to switch cities and
regions in search of better job and lifestyle opportunities,
American Demographics (September) reports.
</P>
<P>
   State governments from California to Massachusetts are promoting
Internet business as a strategy to rebuild their state economies,
reports Upside (September).
</P>
<P>
   The market for Internet stocks is depressed, but that doesn't
mean your career has to be depressed with it. Fast Company
(September) offers lessons on how victims of failed dotcom
companies can reboot their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
