<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern executive to confer with German officials
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Southern Co. chief executive A. W. ``Bill'' Dahlberg
will fly to Berlin on Wednesday to confer with German officials
about the company's stymied bid to take over two German power
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlberg will make the company's case for expanding its holdings
in Berliner Kraft und Licht, the Berlin electric utility known as
Bewag, and purchasing control of Vereinigte Energiewerke, the
eastern Germany power generator, known as Veag.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Harlan, director of European operations for Southern
Energy Inc., a Southern Co. subsidiary, met Monday with Berlin
Mayor Eberhard Diepgen.
</P>
<P>
   Southern purchased a 26 percent stake of Bewag from the Berlin
government three years ago for $830 million. The company wants to
add the 49 percent stake now being sold by E.ON, the German energy
conglomerate, and bid for both Veag and an east German coal
company, Laubag.
</P>
<P>
   E.ON is being forced by antitrust regulators to sell 49 percent
stakes in both Bewag and Veag.
</P>
<P>
   Veag lost $900 million last year, but Southern believes it can
make it profitable by merging its operations with Bewag. Veag
provides electricity and power distribution for the surrounding
area of 15 million people that was once communist East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   E.ON, however, has announced plans to sell its Bewag stake to
Hamburgische Electricitaets-Werke, the utility known as HEW that
serves Hamburg. HEW is majority-owned by Sweden's state-owned
utility Vattenfall.
</P>
<P>
   Details of Dahlberg's schedule Thursday were not released.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
