<HEADER>
A4515 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BIOTRANSPLANT-SWINE-B     08-28 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTRANSPLANT-SWINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM DEVELOPS TRANSPLANT-QUALITY SWINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists at BioTransplant Inc. say they have created a breed
of miniature swine that doesn't infect human cells with potentially
harmful viruses, removing a major obstacle for using pig organs for
human transplants.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlestown, Mass. biotechnology company began breeding the
pigs years ago in hopes of developing a safe source of organs for
the hundreds of thousands of patients who every year find
themselves waiting for hearts, livers, and kidneys _ and for the
thousands of them who die waiting.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed by other scientists, the discovery could ease fears
about infection in xenotransplantion, or cross-species
transplantation. But scientists warn that such transplants are
still years away from reality. And other issues, primarily the
body's immune attack on foreign invaders, must be overcome before
pig organs could be succesfully transplanted in humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (advance) addresses one of the potential concerns that
exist around xenotransplantation, particularly its safety,'' said
Elliot Lebowitz, the company's president and CEO. ``It's an advance
that will allow us to move forward more confidently.''
</P>
<P>
   The news Monday drove up the company's stock price 8 percent, on
a day when biotech stocks overall fell 8 percent. The stock closed
at $12 a share.
</P>
<P>
   For years, scientists have been studying pigs for use in human
transplants because pigs are biologically similar to humans and
carry far fewer deadly diseases than primates.
</P>
<P>
   BioTransplant began creating a highly inbred species of
miniature swine eight years ago to create a pool of potential
organs that were as genetically similar _ and therefore predictable
_ as possible without cloning the animals. The pigs, which weigh
about 250 pounds and have organs similar in size to humans, were
screened for more than two dozen viruses and infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997 British researchers found that a harmless pig virus,
porcine endogenous retrovirus, could infect human cells and become
dangerous. At the time, BioTransplant had already begun studying
the virus. Its early research suggested that a certain line of its
pigs did not transmit the virus to human cells. Last year, the
company hired Clive Patience, a member of the British team, to test
those findings.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, after presenting the results of that research at the
international congress of the Transplantation Society in Rome,
Patience said he fully expected to disprove the company's initial
findings.
</P>
<P>
   He was so confident that he told coworkers he would eat his hat
if the company's findings turned out to be true. He mixed cells
from nine of the highly inbred pigs with a type of human kidney
cell that is most easily infected by the pig virus, but the virus
did not transmit to the human cells. At one point, he said, he was
utterly frustrated that he couldn't get the pigs' cells to transmit
the virus to human cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it as a bit of a personal insult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Patience is eating his words, if not his hat. He said he
doesn't know exactly why the virus in these particular pigs doesn't
infect human cells. The company is continuing its research to find
out. Perhaps, Patience said, generations of inbreeding have
weakened the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the problem that people thought was insurmountable,'' he
said. ``But the results indicate that these pigs are about as safe
as you can get. It's a big step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But xenotransplantation has many critics and most likely will
continue to have critics, even as scientists surmount the many
remaining obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Hubbard, professor emeritus at Harvard University and a
board member of the Council for Responsible Genetics, argues that
how a virus reacts with human cells in a lab experiment could be
different from how it reacts in the living body. If the virus did
become active, she said, it could spread into the community and
become a public health threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is that it would get out of hand before someone
catches it,'' Hubbard said. ``I would say that xenotransplantations
are always going to be dangerous. I think there are other avenues
to explore rather than go that route.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
