<SLUG> BC-TV-HOPKINS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPKINS 24/7: CAMERAS FOLLOW DOCTORS AT WORK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors: Wednesday in 4th graf is Aug. 30) 
By MIKE McDANIEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
(UNDATED) _ ``Hopkins 24/7'' is ``Trauma Center'' with some depth,
``Rescue 911'' without the overwrought schmaltz, ``ER'' without
actors.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Filmed by ABC, which was provided extraordinary access inside
Baltimore's exceptional Johns Hopkins medical facility, ``Hopkins
24/7'' is a documentary series unlike many that have come down the
TV pike. It's six hours, all of them content-justified, all of them
focusing on some of the most important quality-of-life issues
America faces today.
</P>
<P>
   The series brilliantly mixes (begin ital) cinema verite(end
ital) (camera as witness) with storytelling of the most fascinating
kind.
</P>
<P>
   And along the way, ``Hopkins 24/7'' (debuting at 9 p.m.
Wednesday) makes some genuine news and has some lasting impact. For
example:
</P>
<P>
   It tells stories _ medical and personal _ from the patients' and
the doctors' viewpoints. We're familiar with the patients' sides of
the story, but seeing the doctors' sides _ especially the young and
struggling interns' sides _ is eye-opening.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time a hospital has granted television access
inside a ``morbidity and mortality conference,'' where doctors
discuss their deadly mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the few times cameras have been allowed inside a
hospital psychiatric group session. The one observed for this
series, dealing with anorexic girls, is almost frightening to
watch, so emaciated are the victims and so horrifying the stories.
</P>
<P>
   It makes use of a new, hand-sized Sony camera, offering the
exceptional pictures of much larger and cumbersome TV cameras. The
cameras are so small as to be virtually unobtrusive.
</P>
<P>
   A team of 25 spent three months shadowing doctors and patients,
and their efforts pay off handsomely here. It is enough time, as it
turns out, to really get to know some of these people _ and ABC
does an exceptional job in making their stories relatable to us.
</P>
<P>
   An even greater accomplishment: The series successfully tells
complete stories. We get beginnings, middles and ends (sometimes
open ends), just like any other drama series.
</P>
<P>
   And it's wrapped in truth. We freefall into the stories
unraveling before us thinking: ``That could be me,'' ``That sounds
just like what happened to my co-worker,'' or ``I've heard my
friend, Dr. Steve, tell that story.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what's on tap:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Episode 1 &LR;  introduces us to Dr. Edward Cornwell, chief of
trauma surgery, whose mission to save the young black men of East
Baltimore street wars regularly meets with frustruation. This is
the episode that contains the morbidity and mortality conference.
</P>
<P>
   We also meet a young girl with a massive uterine tumor, and
witness the frustration of her parents and her doctor as they
wrestle with HMO folderol. We also get to see a sea turtle secreted
inside the hospital for some diagnostic tests.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Episode 2 &LR;  presents the emotional story of a family who must
decide whether their 4-year-old should have half her brain removed.
We also witness, firsthand, the cruel grind of 100-hour shifts,
which are standard for interns.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; Episode 3 &LR; , a brave 17-year-old faces the enormous risks
involved with lung transplants, and a hard-working, idealistic
doctor becomes emotionally upended when she's exposed to
HIV-infected blood. We also see nervous medical students as they
confront cadavers for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Episode 4 &LR;  reveals the anger of the pediatric emergency staff
when a battered child is brought in unconscious. We also meet two
interesting doctors _ a leading surgeon who also happens to be a
little person, and an oncologist with long hair, an on- and
off-again goatee and a strikingly eccentric bedside manner.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the tissues handy for  &UR; Episode 5 &LR; , a deeply emotional look
inside the bleak world of the anorexic. This is contrasted with the
world of the hard-of-hearing, and one of the series' great moments:
a child's first reaction to a microchip implanted in the ear.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; Episode 6 &LR; , the bottom of the world seems to fall out.
Patients die, affecting family but also having a surprisingly deep
impact on the doctors. In fact, the cameras are there when one
resident says she has had all she can handle and resigns her job.
</P>
<P>
   Each part of the series is as good as the previous. The series
never disappoints in the way it teaches and informs. And is it
sacrilege to say that it also entertains? ``Hopkins 24/7'' is an
important documentary series in the way it provides a more complete
sense of the patient-doctor dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopkins 24/7,'' 9 p.m. Wednesday and Thursday this week,
Wednesdays for the following four weeks, ABC. Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
