<HEADER>
A4533 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HEART-REGROWTH-BOS &LR;      08-28 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-REGROWTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHER SAYS TRIALS SHOW GENETIC HEART CURE WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One of six gene therapy experiments shut down by the
government at St. Elizabeth's Hospital has yielded dramatic
improvement in a small group of patients with advanced heart
disease, the trials' embattled director is reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Dr. Jeffrey Isner and the hospital await federal
permission to resume the research, a report on 13 patients treated
before the shutdown provides ``very solid evidence'' that gene
therapy can work, said Isner.
</P>
<P>
   Most gene therapy experiments, in which genes are inserted into
the body to correct inherited diseases or treat cancer, have failed
to show much effect. This report of success comes as a ``breath of
fresh air'' at a time when gene therapy has been under intense
attack, wrote two doctors in an editorial accompanying the article
in the current edition of the journal Circulation.
</P>
<P>
   In the experiment carried out in 1998-99, Isner and his
colleagues inserted genes that trigger the production of growth
hormones into the heart muscle of patients who had a history of
heart attacks and bypass surgery and continued to have chest pain.
Previous animal work had suggested that the growth factor would
spur new blood vessels to revive damaged heart muscle.
</P>
<P>
   The Circulation report said that 9 of the 13 patients showed
evidence that inactive or ``hibernating'' heart muscle returned to
normal function, and in the overall group episodes of angina (chest
pain) went down sharply.
</P>
<P>
   One of the patients, a manager at a Kansas aircraft plant, said
Isner's treatment brought him major relief from what he had been
told was inoperable blockage in a heart artery that caused angina
pain with almost any exertion.
</P>
<P>
   Within a month, Philip Fletcher, 50, said, ``I was raking
leaves, and that ordinarily would have brought on angina fairly
rapidly, but I raked a big pile and noticed I didn't have any
pain.'' Fletcher said he continues to feel better than before the
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's very encouraging,'' said Isner in an interview.
But he agreed with critics who have said it will be difficult to
prove the therapy's effects until it's tested in a trial alongside
an untreated control group of patients.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration last spring halted all six gene
therapy trials that Isner was conducting, citing a long list of
alleged violations of patient protection rules.
</P>
<P>
   Among the accusations were that a patient with cancer who should
have been excluded from the trials on medical grounds was admitted;
that the researchers didn't monitor the subjects' health closely
enough; and that they they neglected to file required reports on
two patient deaths.
</P>
<P>
   In listing 21 separate violations, the FDA also said that Isner
showed ``a serious lack of knowledge of your responsibilities as a
principal investigator.''
</P>
<P>
   Isner and the hospital have responded to the FDA, saying that
most of the allegations were untrue and that other lapses have been
corrected. Isner said Monday he has had ``several encouraging
interactions'' with the FDA, but has not been told when he might be
allowed to resume the experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Isner has also been accused of having a conflict of interest
because he holds an equity position in a company, Vascular
Genetics, that is sponsoring some of the trials. (The company did
not sponsor the trial in the report.) The president of the American
Society of Gene Therapy has asked Isner to comply with the
society's guidelines prohibiting such conflicts. Monday, Isner said
he was still considering the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Several scientific teams are also trying to treat heart disease
by inserting genes or proteins to stimulate the growth of small
blood vessels, a process called angiogenesis. Isner's results
appear to be the most encouraging to date, he said. Since the trial
being reported, researchers have made the therapy less invasive:
the gene that promotes production of growth factor, called VEGF, is
administered using a catheter snaked through a vein rather than
being injected via a chest incision made under general anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   The editorial accompanying Isner's report, written by Drs. Cam
Patterson and Marschall S. Runge, noted that the St. Elizabeth's
team took a cautious approach, avoiding using a virus to carry the
genes into the patients' hearts. A reaction to such a virus caused
the death of Jesse Gelsinger, a teenaged patient with liver
disease, at the University of Pennsylvania last year, touching off
a wave of criticism of gene therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Isner's group used a simple vehicle _ a ring of DNA _
that succeeded in getting the genes into the heart muscle cells
without causing a defensive reaction by the body.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, of the University of Texas Medical Branch in
Galveston, and Runge, of the University of North Carolina, said the
work was encouraging, but probably won't become a routine tool in
heart disease any time soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4534 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-TURKEY-ARCHAEO-AR     08-28 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TURKEY-ARCHAEO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGGING BEYOND STONE FOR AN ANCIENT CITY'S PULSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   APHRODISIAS, Turkey _ On a lunch break from excavations, Bert
Smith delivered the news of discovery. The marble head of a man had
been found under crumbling steps of an ancient house. The style was
right, and the fit. This must be the missing piece to a headless
statue of a local governor from the fifth century A.D. that had
been recovered years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's recapitation took place the next afternoon in the
little museum here at Aphrodisias, one of the more important and
monumentally impressive archaeological sites of the Greek and Roman
periods in what is now western Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. R.R.R. Smith, known to all as Bert, a classical
archaeologist at Oxford University in England and co-director of
the current dig, lifted the head above the life-size marble body.
With a few turns this way and that, the neck slipped neatly onto
the rest of the statue.
</P>
<P>
   The governor named Oikoumenios was whole again.
</P>
<P>
   It was a small but satisfying triumph for archaeologists working
the Aphrodisias site, a field of dreams for the study of art and
architecture of antiquity. Spreading over a broad plain is an
extravagance of well-preserved stone remains of a prosperous
provincial city: from a huge theater on high ground to the squares
and building walls of the civic center and beyond to the standing
and fallen columns of the Temple of Aphrodite and then the stadium
that once seated 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   But new discoveries in the fine arts are not as common here as
they used to be. Not only have archaeologists thoroughly mined the
most obvious sources, but their excavations have entered a new
phase, a response in part to criticism that classical archaeology
has focused too much on collecting museum pieces at the expense of
exploring the societies that created them.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis in recent digging seasons, organized by the
Institute of Fine Arts at New York University, has shifted to
learning something of what the rest of Aphrodisias was like, beyond
the noble architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here and elsewhere in Turkey, we are making great strides in
understanding ancient cities from an urban point of view, as social
entities,'' Dr. Christopher Ratte of New York University, the other
co-director of the project, said while walking the pavement stones
of old Aphrodisias. ``We are trying to see them less as collections
of monuments and more as complex urban wholes.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward this end, the project has completed an extensive survey,
using subsurface-detection technology, of the open, unexcavated
fields within the city's encompassing defensive wall. Electric
currents were passed through the ground, at depths of a few feet.
By measuring changes in the resistance to the current, scientists
recorded variations in subsurface densities, evidence of buried
building foundations and street pavements.
</P>
<P>
   The survey has thus far revealed a grid pattern of streets and
houses in all directions from the center out to the city wall.
</P>
<P>
   Test trenches have confirmed the findings. Aphrodisias in its
heyday was a planned city, uniform blocks running north and south
and east and west.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in the current issue of The American Journal of
Archaeology, Smith and Ratte reported that excavations guided by
the survey had yielded additional evidence suggesting that ``both
the city center and the residential areas of Aphrodisias remained
occupied and relatively prosperous through the sixth and into the
seventh century, before suffering a sudden and dramatic change of
fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the trenches being explored this summer yielded marble
slabs of a street, drain pipes and the stone side of a house near
the stadium. Other excavations have uncovered a coin hoard showing
that many of the houses were built before the early fifth century
A.D. Elsewhere, coins, pottery and metal objects of rooms date the
latest occupation of the buildings to the early seventh century.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to dig more of the houses of ordinary people that
have shown up in the survey, while continuing to catalog and
analyze the sculpture that has accumulated since systematic
excavations began here in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   The excavations were directed for two decades by Dr. Kenan T.
Erim, a Turkish-born archaeologist at N.Y.U. whose main interest
was sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   From what has been learned so far, Aphrodisias was built on the
site of a rural sanctuary where the goddess Aphrodite, daughter of
Zeus, was worshiped.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone coming here expecting to find voluptuary art, recipes for
love potions or evidence of ancient orgies will be disappointed. A
commanding statue of Aphrodite here shows a robust, fully robed
goddess bearing little resemblance to the Aphrodite or Venus of the
Greek and Roman traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``At lectures, I'm invariably asked about Aphrodite,'' Ratte
said. ``Did they practice ritual prostitution here? Not likely.
This Aphrodite was not your sex goddess of Greek religion. She was
a very local deity, stemming from the goddess Cybele of Asia Minor,
who became associated with Aphrodite but never lost her local
character.''
</P>
<P>
   The native gods of this region were usually conceived of as
feminine, Ratte noted, although they were not all fertility
goddesses.
</P>
<P>
   This Aphrodite appeared to be a warrior goddess and protector of
the place. ``It may be sexism to be viewing them always as
goddesses of fertility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a city, Aphrodisias had the good fortune to lie in the
fertile Meander River Valley, off the beaten track of invading
armies _ the ruins are 100 miles southeast of the Aegean port of
Izmir, ancient Smyrna. It came into its own in the time of Emperor
Augustus in the late first century B.C. ``I have selected this one
city from all of Asia to be my own,'' Augustus declared in offering
the city patronage and special protection.
</P>
<P>
   So the people of Aphrodisias, living near a quarry, celebrated
themselves and the good times of Roman rule with a profusion of
fine marble statues to gods, heroes, emperors and philosophers.
</P>
<P>
   This proved to be a gift to archaeologists, especially because
the city is all but ignored in surviving texts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a statue culture, for which statues are a currency of
life and politics,'' Smith explained. ``If you are a great
benefactor to the city, you will be honored with a public statue.
This was typical after Alexander the Great. Greek democratic
culture before frowned on this practice.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more generous benefactors in the city's building boom
seems to have been a man whose name and likeness appears on statues
and a frieze found near the fortification wall. He was Ziolus, who
was born here, became a slave in Rome and returned rich after being
freed by Augustus. He was credited with financing the 7,000-seat
theater and other buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they are moving in other research directions, the
archaeologists defended their studies of the elite artifacts as
sources of valuable insights into a culture: what people did with
their surplus wealth, how the leading citizens conceived of
themselves and how the aristocracy sought to perpetuate itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is really best preserved at Aphrodisias is the kind of
material evidence for the high civic culture,'' Ratte said. ``We
don't learn much about ancient diet or living arrangements from it,
or anything about the common people. But that does not mean
beautiful objects and monumental buildings are just art history,
and not of anthropological interest.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the stadium, an oval of gray stone the length of
two American football fields, was built in the first century A.D.
with a seating capacity far greater than the population of the city
and its environs, probably about 10,000. Too big and impractical?
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that you could build it when you didn't need it, THAT
was the point,'' Ratte said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   A prominent edifice in the civic center is the Sebasteion, a
kind of hall-of-fame to Roman emperors and other worthies, also
built in the first century A.D. From the layout of the ruins and
the many statues found there, Harry Mark, a Dallas architect
trained in archaeological research, has prepared detailed drawings
of what the colonnaded courtyard and temple looked like.
</P>
<P>
   In a storage depot, Smith pointed out the marble reliefs with
scenes from Greek mythology and depictions of Roman emperors in
heroic, godlike poses that once graced the Sebasteion. Here the
Aphrodisians are presumably revealed trying to come to terms with
those who held power not only over themselves but virtually the
whole world as it was known to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they represented them as gods,'' Ratte said, ``not just to
flatter the Romans but to make sense of the Romans to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes in who was honored with statues seemed to mark a
significant transition in the city's government. After about A.D.
200, the tradition of memorializing the local aristocracy largely
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Governors appointed by Rome or, later, Constantinople became the
more usual subjects of statues. The city, archaeologists surmise,
had become less self-reliant and more dependent on imperial
administration and favor.
</P>
<P>
   In the late fourth or early fifth centuries, statues of two
governors, including Oikoumenios, were erected on inscribed bases
in a place of honor between the public square and the council
house.
</P>
<P>
   It was here that the headless statue of Oikoumenios was found in
1965. A team of workers under Michelle Berenfeld, a doctoral
student in archaeology at N.Y.U., came upon the head 40 feet away,
where it had long ago been dumped with dirt and other stones as
construction fill at the house of a prominent official.
</P>
<P>
   The Temple of Aphrodite itself underwent a transformation around
A.D. 500, reflecting a major change in the city's religion. As
archaeologists and architects have determined, some of the columns
on the east and west sides were dismantled and re-erected along the
north-south sides in such a way as to turn the temple into a much
larger church. The Christians of Byzantium were making an
ideological statement in stone.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists and other scholars cannot account for the city's
sharp decline. In the early seventh century, most of the
Aphrodisians moved out into the countryside. By the 13th century,
the place was completely abandoned, prey to pillagers, many of its
proudly carved stones burned into lime.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it clear, after 40 years of excavations, what moved the
Aphrodisians to such exuberant expressions in stone. They were not
powerful, or especially rich. Perhaps others in the region were
like them, who built in the spirit of Greece and thrived under
Rome, but time was not as kind to the ruins of their cities.
</P>
<P>
   The British writer Freya Stark came away from a visit to
unexcavated Aphrodisias in the 1950s with the impression that its
people had lived ``in undistinguished mediocrity and wealth,
enjoying their world and untroubled by its opinions, except for a
reasonable municipal pride in their city and its credit abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Ionia: A Quest,'' Stark praised this attitude, in contrast
to what she called the inferiority complexes bred by the modern age
of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The Aphrodisians, she wrote, must have ``had an inner security
through all the centuries of their submissions, because of that
genial interest in things for their own sake, which remained.''
</P>
<P>
   One evening, after another day of digging among the stones under
a blazing sun, the archaeologists and architects of the project,
their students and some visitors also seemed to take a genial
interest in things for their own sake. The dinner had been simple,
as usual. But spirits were enlivened by port and fine Stilton
cheese, a gift of Trevor Proudfoot, a stone conservator who had
arrived from England.
</P>
<P>
   Talk turned to the Aphrodisians. Were they an exceptional
culture? Not really. ``They were no more peace loving than
others,'' Ratte said. ``It's just that they came into prominence at
a time of great stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agreed that the city's ruins were extraordinary, so
well-preserved and accessible, and that they might someday produce
insights into what made the Aphrodisians recognize stability as a
condition worth celebrating. For now, though, the archaeologists
lifted their glasses. It was satisfying to have the governor's head
replaced, a museum and storehouse full of sculpture and the new
survey showing the way to future exploration of Aphrodisias.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
