<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4544 &Cx1f; tic-z
r v BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      08-28 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    U.S. FOUNDERS PUT REASON OVER FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
  
What would the founding fathers do?U.S. founders chose &HT;    reason over faith
 &HT;    Many were suspicious
 &HT;    of organized religionBC-FATHERS--AZR(a)  &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BARBARA YOST(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush announces that Jesus is his favorite political
philosopher. Al Gore seeks moral guidance by invoking the pop
refrain ``WWJD? - What would Jesus do?''
</P>
<P>
   But as religious references infuse this year's presidential
campaign, another question arises: ``What would Jefferson do?''
</P>
<P>
   For many Americans in 2000, the answer would be surprising.
</P>
<P>
   In his time, the author of the Declaration of Independence was
branded an atheist in some traditional religious circles. Like many
of the founding fathers, Thomas Jefferson embraced a basic belief
in God - deism - but was also a man of science, intrigued by the
philosophies of the Age of Enlightenment, a European intellectual
movement that contended all of life, including religion, could be
understood through the process of reason.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the men who forged the new American nation embraced God
but distrusted organized religion, disdainful of abuses by the
powerful clergy who ruled the Church of England and held sway over
the English government itself. In one of his letters, Jefferson
charged that yoking church and state turned human beings into
``dupes and drudges.''
</P>
<P>
   Determined to avoid such mischief, the framers of the U.S.
Constitution codified their concerns in the First Amendment:
``Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of
religion or prohibiting the free exercise thereof.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson would interpret this as a mandate for the separation
of church and government. The article also would be construed not
only as freedom of religion but also freedom from religion.
</P>
<P>
   Americans today who hope to paint a picture of the founding
fathers as a pious bunch risk rewriting history.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is really overstated,'' says John Corrigan,
professor of American studies and religious studies at Arizona
State University. ``They (the founding fathers) were not
particularly religious.''
</P>
<P>
   Brook Simpson, ASU professor of history and humanity, calls them
men of reason and enlightenment who saw God's will as expressed in
the laws of nature and whose mixed bag of ideas cannot be
appropriated to fit a particular agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``What goes on today is that they treat the founders as a sort
of cafeteria, where they get to pick and choose,'' Simpson says.
</P>
<P>
   The beliefs held by these 18th-century men were often at odds
with prevailing thought in a time when church and faith held
central roles in society.
</P>
<P>
   By all appearances, Jefferson was a conventional Christian, an
Anglican - the Church of England in the New World. He served as a
vestryman in his parish. He believed that religion holds society
together and goes hand in hand with morality. In the Declaration of
Independence, he refers variously to the creator, nature's God and
divine providence.
</P>
<P>
   But while Jefferson embraced the teachings of Jesus as a good
moral foundation, he doubted Jesus' divinity. He even rewrote the
New Testament, cutting and pasting passages to remove references to
miracles.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson ``preferred a world of science and rationality,''
Simpson says.
</P>
<P>
   So passionate was Jefferson about religious freedom that his
tombstone lists as his three greatest accomplishments the writing
of the Statute of Virginia for Religious Freedom, authoring the
Declaration of Independence and founding the University of
Virginia, a purposely secular institution in contrast with his own
Anglican-run alma mater, the College of William and Mary.
</P>
<P>
   The epitaph he requested omits his role as president of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson's friend and philosophical confederate, James Madison,
also professed a general belief in God and wrote in Memorial and
Remonstrance that an individual's duty to his ``universal
sovereign'' came before his civic responsibilities. But he shared
Jefferson's wariness of what was then termed ``priestcraft,'' or
clerical hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Madison, an Anglican, had been educated at the College of New
Jersey, now Princeton University. Though the school had been
founded by the Presbyterian Church, he chose it for its aversion to
ministerial rule.
</P>
<P>
   As principal author of the U.S. Constitution, Madison was as
adamant as Jefferson about the Establishment clause. Like
Jefferson, he advocated ``a perfect separation between
ecclesiastical and civil matters.''
</P>
<P>
   During his presidency, Madison rejected requests to make
official religious proclamations or to declare religious holidays.
Citizens of the new United States, he insisted, would have to
accept the absence of a state religion - disestablishment.
</P>
<P>
   When creating the American government, its framers not only
believed fervently in disestablishment but also neatly avoided
choosing one religion from among the many faiths espoused in the
colonies, including Episcopalian (Anglican), Congregational (church
of the Pilgrims), Dutch Reformed, Presbyterian, Quaker, Methodist
and Calvinism.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland had been founded as a Roman Catholic colony but fell to
pressures from England to establish Anglican parishes.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of the American Revolution, Corrigan says there were
between 2,300 and 2,500 Jews living in America - with little
anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most complex figures in colonial religious life was
the venerable Benjamin Franklin. As a young man, Franklin had
undergone a conversion to Presbyterianism, but ``it didn't take,''
Corrigan says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for such a champion of democracy, Franklin was
something of an elitist when it came to religion, says Richard
Wenz, ASU professor emeritus of American religious studies. In a
letter to his daughter, Franklin encouraged her to attend church
services and to heed the message of the sermon. But for himself, he
believed he had evolved beyond the need for catechism.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jefferson, Franklin was more intrigued by science than
spirituality. Religion was an intellectual pursuit, useful for
moral grounding. A wise man graduated from the need for further
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he professed a belief in God and, just a month before his
death, answered a friend's request to state his Christian
principles, saying, ``I believe in one God, creator of the
universe. That he governs the world by his providence. That he
ought to be worshiped. That the most acceptable service we can
render to him, is doing good to his other children. That the soul
of man is immortal.''
</P>
<P>
   Immortality was a basic tenet of deism, along with a belief in
God and a love of freedom. America's second president, John Adams,
was solidly deist. For more than 60 years, he embraced the liberal
Unitarian church.
</P>
<P>
   Like his colleagues, Adams denounced the priestcraft and
believed the principles of Jesus had deteriorated into superstition
and hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   George Washington wore his faith as humbly as he did his
political leadership, unfettered by doctrine. Though an Anglican
vestryman like Jefferson, he insisted that ``my tenets are few and
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   To Washington, God was the ``grand architect'' of the universe,
``great ruler of events,'' ``higher cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The faith he expressed in conversation was generic.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, one of the richest and most provocative treatises
on early American religious thought was penned by master wordsmith
Thomas Paine, whose 1776 pamphlet Common Sense helped to incite
passions favorable to the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In 1794, Paine published Age of Reason. Son of a Quaker, Paine
said, ``I believe in one God and no more, and I hope for happiness
beyond this life.{hellip}I believe that religious duties consist in
doing justice, loving mercy and endeavoring to make our fellow
creatures happy.''John Trumbull's Declaration of Independence in
Congress, displayed in the rotunda of the U.S. Capitol, pictures
the founding fathers, who were intrigued with science and reason
and were not particularly religious.not needed
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
