<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-COLOMBIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS SUFFER AMID US-BACKED DRUG WAR IN COLOMBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA _ When they set off into the jungle that morning, they
were just children on a grade school field trip.
</P>
<P>
   Then they walked into an army ambush. Six of them died in a hail
of machine gun fire, and instantly they became tragic symbols in
the debate over protecting human rights as Colombia turns up the
heat in its US-supported campaign against drug growers and
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 students from a tiny rural school in Antioquia state were
heading to a nearby hacienda with their teacher and two mothers.
They had been walking for less than a half-hour when eight of them
pushed ahead into a thicket of shrubs and trees, and the shooting
started.
</P>
<P>
   The bullets were fired by Colombian soldiers who had been hiding
behind the bushes. In the early morning light and shadows, they had
mistaken the children for leftist guerrillas they had been pursuing
through the forest.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombian government and military leaders immediately called
the August 15 shooting ``human error'' and suspended the soldiers
pending an investigation, but the killings sharply escalated the
growing public outrage here over the Colombian military's checkered
human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   It is in this climate of controversy that President Bill Clinton
make a brief visit Wednesday to this violence-scarred country to
personally promote a $1.3 billion US aid package to help fight this
country's exploding illegal drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for his part, has already taken a stand in the debate.
Against the wishes of human rights activists in the United States
and Colombia, he signed a waiver last week that allows the aid
money to be delivered despite Colombia's failure to meet six
conditions in the aid package designed to protect human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, in a press conference in Washington, human rights
officials again criticized both Clinton and Colombian President
Andres Pastrana. The two men will meet Wednesday in the coastal
city of Cartagena _ the first visit by a US president to the
country in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Accidental or not, the shooting of the children in Antioquia has
shown how difficult it is to shield civilians from the three-decade
war that has ravaged this South American country and cost an
estimated 300,000 casualties. The violence escalated dramatically
in the last decade as leftist guerrillas and right-wing
paramilitary groups became more involved in Colombia's cocaine and
heroin trade.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday another 20 people were killed in two separate massacres
blamed on paramilitaries, government officials and news reports
said. Ten were killed execution-style in Cienaga, while another ten
men were taken from a pool hall and shot point-blank, allegedly for
being sympathizers with leftist rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Civil war is not a spectator sport,'' said one Bogota
political analyst who requested anonymity for fear of retribution
from one of the many armed groups in the country's civil war.
``Ordinary people are in as much danger as the troops themselves,
which is why it should be government's obligation to protect our
human rights, and so far it has failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the soldiers' remorse over the children's deaths, public
anger was so great that it overshadowed what should have been a
high point for the Colombia's military: the heroic rescue of six
hostages, including Guillermo Cortes, a well-known Colombian
journalist, from a rebel hideout in Cudinamarca state three days
earlier. More than 100 paratroopers carried out the nighttime
operation, surprising rebel troops of the leftist FARC and freeing
the hostages without suffering a single casualty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be the first to lament a tragic accident, but to say we
are a constant violator of human rights is not fair or true,''
Defense Minister Luis Fernando Ramirez said in an interview Monday.
``I think the Colombian people know that when it comes to human
rights they'd rather trust the military much more than either the
guerrillas or paramilitary groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Colombian officials hope that the US aid package, which was
proposed by the Clinton administration and approved by Congress
this summer, will boost their drug eradication efforts and give
them new leverage in negotiating a peaceful end to the conflict.
Colombia's drug production, which accounts for about 90 percent of
the illegal narcotics sold in the United States, has doubled in the
past five years as insurgent groups have entered the drug trade to
finance their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, at the midpoint of an administration that has seen
both increased violence and a severe economic crisis, is also
counting on the aid to bolster his sagging popularity and to
support his broad social agenda, known as Plan Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   But the aid package has received mostly mixed reviews from
Colombians. Some fear the money will lead to more war and endanger
or displace thousands. Others worry that the heavy military
emphasis of the plan _ which includes 18 Blackhawk and 42 Huey
helicopters and increased US military training _ will draw too much
American involvement in a war that can't be won.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also fear that more hardware and more fighting will
produce more human rights abuses by all sides: leftist guerrillas,
right-wing paramilitary groups linked to the government, and the
military itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are human rights abuses on all sides,'' said
Mauricio Escobar, a 25-year-old college student in Bogota, who
joined tens of thousands of residents in a protest march Sunday.
``These dialogues for peace that we've seen have been like lukewarm
water, sometimes hot and sometimes cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez said the aid package will help strengthen the military's
human rights training and internal judicial system, including the
creation of a US-style judge advocate general's office to prosecute
soldiers and officers accused of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has defended the waiver by saying that Pastrana has
recently taken steps to meet the human rights conditions. Other US
officials said withholding the aid money would have also affect
funding for human rights programs.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the positive steps cited by Clinton, the Colombian
president issued a directive August 17 requiring military personnel
accused of human rights abuses to stand trial before civil courts,
rather than a more lenient military court.
</P>
<P>
   But human rights advocates say the Pastrana directive does not
go far enough to ensure that soldiers accused of abuses will be
tried in a civilian court or adequately punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is one of implementation and the fact that
we've seen a number of presidential decrees regarding human rights
reforms, none of which have been implemented,'' said Winifred Tate,
a senior fellow at the Washington Office on Latin America, one of
the groups that has criticized Clinton's support for the Colombian
military. ``We hope the US will use its influence to change this
situation, but we're distressed by the lack of progress to date by
the Pastrana administration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4548 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBCBEST0829-COX     08-28 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBCBEST0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Olin Buchanan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's most decadent luxuries usually are found in very
specific places.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking the finest champagne? Go to France.
</P>
<P>
   The richest chocolate? Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The softest cashmere? Elgin, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   The tastiest sausage? Elgin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest running backs? Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   There sits the University of Southern California, which through
the years has produced the creme de la creme of college football's
pre-eminent ball carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got Mike Garrett, O.J. Simpson, (Charles) White and
Marcus Allen,'' said ESPN analyst Beano Cook, whose career in
college football spans five decades. ``You've heard the famous
line, `Student body right, student body left?' That came from USC's
running attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Greatness can be measured in statistics and rewarded with
trophies (Garrett, Simpson, White and Allen all exceeded 1,400
yards rushing, and each won a Heisman Trophy at USC), but name
association provides true legendary status.
</P>
<P>
   So, when a college establishes a tradition of great players at a
position, it becomes synonymous with that position.
</P>
<P>
   Take Penn State, which became known as Linebacker U for
producing players such as Jack Ham, Shane Conlan, Matt Millen,
David Robinson and Andre Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happened is Penn State had a bunch of linebackers
that did well in pro football,'' Cook said. ``On Monday nights,
(Howard) Cosell would always mention it and say, `Where is he
from?' And then Don Meredith would say, `Where else, Penn State?'
That helps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like running backs at USC.''
</P>
<P>
   Or defensive backs at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Heisman Trophy running backs Earl Campbell and Ricky Williams
starred at Texas, but the Longhorns are best known for backs on the
defensive side.
</P>
<P>
   NFL defensive backs to come through Texas include Tom Landry,
Stanley Richard, William Graham, Bobby Johnson, Derrick Hatchett,
Ricky Churchman, Chris Carter, Taje Allen, Mossy Cade, Vance
Bedford, Glen Blackwood, Van Malone and Lance Gunn.
</P>
<P>
   And they don't even top the Longhorns' list.
</P>
<P>
   That's headed by Johnnie Johnson, Jerry Gray, Bill Bradley and
Raymond Clayborn, who all enjoyed distinguished NFL careers, and
Bryant Westbrook, who still is.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a stretch in the mid-80s when I was active where
they put on the (television) screen the number of defensive backs
on active squads in the NFL from Texas,'' Johnson said. ``They
needed two screens to put all the guys on the screen. There was an
old saying: If you wanted to prepare for the NFL as a defensive
back, go to Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said there are three factors in building a reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Great athletes. (Such as Johnson).
</P>
<P>
   A system that attracts athletes. (Man-to-man coverage).
</P>
<P>
   Coaches who are good teachers. (Johnson's position coach was
Alan Lowry.)
</P>
<P>
   The coaches change (Lowry is now coaching in the NFL), but the
contributing factors remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tradition has to be developed and produced,'' Johnson said.
``It just doesn't appear. Someone had to establish that
foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson thinks Texas' reputation for turning out defensive backs
started with Clayborn, who was the New England Patriots'
first-round draft choice in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   More accurately, it might be traced back to Bradley, who was a
third-round choice of the Philadelphia Eagles in 1969 and
eventually made the Pro Bowl from 1972-74.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson said the source of Texas' reputation isn't as
important as the need for the current defensive backs to realize
there is one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players coming in to play in the secondary need to know they
have a tradition to uphold,'' Johnson said. ``We won't expect
anything less. We expect you to take the torch and run with it. I
took it to a new level, and I expect you to take it to a higher
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they were struggling in the secondary it hurt us like you
wouldn't believe. We take so much pride in that.''
</P>
<P>
   The current defensive backs seem to understand that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told what expectations we have to live up to when I
first got here,'' Longhorns junior Quentin Jammer said. ``You're
not supposed to be a good defensive back at Texas. You're supposed
to be a great defensive back.''
</P>
<P>
   Producing great players is not enough. The production must be at
least fairly consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is not known as a quarterback school. It should not be.
</P>
<P>
   The late Bobby Layne was an All-America quarterback in 1947. The
next Longhorns' All-America quarterback was Marty Akins in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, what's 28 years?
</P>
<P>
   But turning out great players doesn't always guarantee building
a reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as part of Woody Hayes' enduring legacy, casual
observers might still think of Ohio State's offense as three yards
and a cloud of dust. Actually, it's difficult to find a program
that can match the Buckeyes' receiving alumni of Cris Carter, Joey
Galloway, Terry Glenn, David Boston and Paul Warfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something because they went all those years and never
threw the ball,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's quarterback alumni also are overshadowed by the
Crimson Tide's historically run-oriented offense.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama is not thought of as a quarterback school, although NFL
Hall of Famers Joe Namath and Bart Starr, as well as Ken Stabler _
who combined for four Super Bowl victories _ and Richard Todd and
Jeff Rutledge played there
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a quarterback school in a different way because in their
dominant years they ran the wishbone,'' University of Texas Coach
Mack Brown said. ``It's like how (Texas) had Marty Akins, who was a
great (wishbone) quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Miami is a quarterback school from when they had the
(Bernie) Kosars and guys like that. Florida State had a run of
guys. UCLA is a quarterback school, BYU and Washington has had four
or five guys. There's more quarterbacks to come out of (Washington)
than people think.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Lavell Edwards brought a wide-open passing offense to
Brigham Young, and eventual NFL quarterbacks Steve Young, Jim
McMahon, Ty Detmer, Gifford Nielsen and Marc Wilson flourished in
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would ask Lavell how he kept getting good
quarterbacks,'' Brown said. ``He'd say, `I recruit good
quarterbacks.'''
</P>
<P>
   Duh.
</P>
<P>
   You doubt it's that simple.
</P>
<P>
   It's like the chicken-or-the-egg question: Did great
quarterbacks make BYU? Or did BYU make great quarterbacks?
</P>
<P>
   ``The real good schools do a high level of recruiting for
dominant players. They get a lot of publicity, so they get more
prominent players,'' Brown said. ``Usually there's a trend. We had
great running backs in the past because we played the wishbone.
Then with Fred (Akers) we went to the `I,' so running backs were
important. If you have a great running game you need great running
backs, and then you get great offensive linemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern California obviously did. It's no coincidence the
school that produced college football's greatest runners also
produced Anthony Munoz, Ron Mix and Ron Yary _ all NFL Hall of Fame
linemen _ as well as Bruce Matthews and Tony Boselli.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on when a school is good and what is their
emphasis,'' Brown said. ``Every school is known for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown wants Texas to continue its tradition of defensive backs,
but he also wants to be known for something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to continue to recruit quarterbacks,'' Brown said.
``We want to be a quarterbacks school.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas?
</P>
<P>
   A quarterbacks school?
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere Bobby Layne must be laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Email: obuchanan(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
