<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP INDONESIAN ECONOMIST WANTS TO REDUCE ROLE OF IMF 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Two days after he was sworn in as
Indonesia's economic czar, Rizal Ramli said Monday that the
International Monetary Fund had become overly involved in the nuts
and bolts of the country's economy in the course of its $43 billion
bailout.
</P>
<P>
   Ramli, an outspoken economist who has long been critical of the
fund, said he wanted to renegotiate the IMF agreement with
Indonesia to limit the fund's role to broader issues like
macroeconomics and monetary policy. ``By doing that, we reduce the
destabilization that comes every time we review the program,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramli, who was named coordinating minister for economic affairs
by Indonesia's president, Abdurrahman Wahid, as part of a recent
shuffling of the country's Cabinet, said he had spoken to officials
at the fund, who said they were willing ``to exchange views and
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new team,'' Ramli said in an interview. ``We would
like to have a better sense of ownership of the program, so we can
sell it to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Indonesia's fragile recovery from the Asian economic
crisis, and its continued dependence on money from the IMF, it is
not clear how much leverage Ramli will have. But his comments
underscore Indonesia's desire to present a more assertive and
decisive face to foreign governments and markets, which have
watched with alarm as the country has slid into near-chaos in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a no-nonsense guy, and I want results,'' Ramli said.
``When you're in a crisis, you don't have the luxury of holding
long, analytical discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramli acknowledged that Indonesia's new Cabinet got off to a
wobbly start last week. Critics say it is stacked with loyalists of
Wahid and devoid of allies of the popular vice president, Megawati
Sukarnoputri. Those concerns, many said, rattled Indonesia's stock
market and sent its currency, the rupiah, into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   Megawati stoked the controversy by pointedly skipping the news
conference at which Wahid announced the Cabinet. Ramli described
the president and vice president as being like a brother and
sister, who might ``quarrel and grumble'' but would never ``damage
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, under pressure from Indonesia's Parliament,
Wahid agreed to delegate some of his power to Megawati. Ramli said
the vice president would play a central role in developing policy,
noting that he and the chief political minister would meet Megawati
for breakfast every Monday morning _ before meeting with Wahid the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors were also unnerved that Wahid named as finance
minister a former banker who had failed a government test to head a
state bank. The banker, Prijadi Praptosuhardjo, was disqualified
after failing a ``fit and proper'' test that assessed his character
and past dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Ramli, who came to prominence for his attacks on corruption
during the regime of former President Suharto, said Prijadi was a
product of that era. Nevertheless, he said the new finance minister
was a ``relatively decent man,'' with whom he could work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corruption in the Suharto era was of two types,'' Ramli said.
``Active corruption, in which you squeeze businesses for money, and
passive corruption, which is like getting thank-you notes. I would
venture to say he belongs in the second category.''
</P>
<P>
   As chief economics minister, Ramli will chart Indonesia's
economic policy and be its public face to the financial markets and
agencies like the IMF. His predecessor, Kwik Kian Gie, was
criticized for his scholarly bent, which critics said translated
into halting policies.
</P>
<P>
   With a doctorate in economics from Boston University, Ramli, 47,
is also an academic. But his most recent job was running Bulog, the
state logistics agency, which was a den of corruption during the
Suharto era.
</P>
<P>
   ``That he is willing to criticize the IMF is nothing new,'' said
Gustav F. Papanek, an economist who was Ramli's doctoral adviser at
Boston University. ``He is someone who has the courage of his
convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's Parliament voted Monday to investigate allegations
that money was misappropriated at Bulog by a former aide to Wahid.
The incident predated Ramli's tenure there. The Parliament also
approved an investigation of possible misuse of funds involving a
donation from the sultan of Brunei.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was only his first day on the job, Ramli issued a
10-point plan to rebuild Indonesia's economy. He said the
government planned to increase spending on public-works projects in
rural areas to reduce unemployment and increase wages. And he said
Jakarta would spend more on military troops to police strife-torn
parts of the country, like the Spice Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The perception that Indonesia was coming apart at the seams, he
said, was the main reason investors have steered clear of the
country. He said the violence contributed to the chronic weakness
of the rupiah, which closed Monday at 8,245 rupiah to the U.S.
dollar. Without such instability, Ramli said, the rupiah would
trade at 7,500 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Since March, the Jakarta stock market has slid more than 19
percent. Monday, the benchmark index closed down 1.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception in the markets is far away from the reality,''
Ramli said. Indonesia's economy, he said, could grow 4 percent this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
