u w BC-DEUTCH-INDICT-BOS &LR;      08-28 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEUTCH-INDICT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS IN BACKGROUND AS RENO MULLS DEUTCH ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Attorney General Janet Reno decides to prosecute
former CIA director John M. Deutch for mishandling government
secrets, it could be because the political climate, as much as the
law, requires it.
</P>
<P>
   Deutch, a professor and former provost at MIT, has admitted that
he breached security rules when he placed large volumes of
classified material on unsecure computers at his home while he
headed the CIA from May 1995 to December 1996. Earlier this year,
Deutch publicly apologized for the violation.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Justice Department refused to comment on new reports
that a special prosecutor appointed by Reno to probe the Deutch
case is recommending criminal charges be sought against Deutch for
the security breach. If Reno goes forward, such a prosecution would
be the first ever for a Cabinet-rank official.
</P>
<P>
   It would come in a season of public outrage over the federal
government's failure to safeguard its top-secret information _ from
the case against nuclear physicist Wen Ho Lee and missing computer
hard drives at the Los Alamos National Laboratory to the State
Department misplacing laptop computers that contained sensitive
material. And it would answer some of the loud election-year
criticism from Republicans in Congress that the Clinton
administration has assembled a sorry record on security.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Deutch nor his lawyer answered requests for interviews
Monday. But Senator John F. Kerry (D-Mass.), a member of the
Intelligence Committee, said it would be wrong to ``allow this
incident to become a political football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is that this situation is laden with just that
potential: Politics could conspire to elevate the Deutch situation
_ one man's serious error in judgment _ to embarrass an entire
administration,'' the Massachusetts senator said in a statement.
``I think that would be a mistake, particularly as it appears that
we're dealing here with one case of foibles, however
outrageous...rather than systemic troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry noted that Deutch's security clearances had been lifted
earlier this year by CIA director George J. Tenet after a report by
the agency's inspector general asserted that Deutch knew his home
computers were vulnerable to Internet hacking but had taken no
steps to secure them. The report said there was no evidence that
secrets had been compromised, but it did criticize top CIA
officials for being slow in investigating the breach once it was
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   As as result of the report, three current and three former CIA
officials have been disciplined for their role in the probe. It
also prompted Reno to reverse herself _ she had initially closed
the case against Deutch _ and name Paul E. Coffey, a retired
Justice Department prosecutor, to work with the FBI to investigate
the security lapses.
</P>
<P>
   The Deutch disclosures come as defense lawyers for Lee, a
naturalized US citizen born in Taiwan and charged with illegally
transferring and copying Los Alamos's nuclear secrets, say their
client is a victim of racial profiling. They have asked the judge
handling Lee's case to find out why the Justice Department
prosecuted Lee for allegedly downloading top-secret information,
recommended he be held for months under tight security in a Sante
Fe, N.M., jail, and argued against bail while no charges were
brought against Deutch, who also put classified material on his
home computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a problem. The Justice Department put Wen Ho Lee in
shackles, and they did nothing to Deutch, whose actions certainly
have the appearance of recklessness,'' said Theodore Postol, a
professor of science, technology, and national security at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   Postol, who has been outspoken in criticizing his MIT colleague,
said that depending on the contents of the classified documents,
Deutch's security breach was potentially life-threatening to
intelligence agents in the field. He called his action akin ``to
driving through a pedestrian mall at 100 miles an hour and arguing
that because you didn't kill anybody, you did nothing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   A former senior Defense official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the breach that Deutch acknowledged is serious, and
it was aggravated by the fact that the Pentagon was not informed
for ``at least a year'' after the discovery that sensitive defense
documents were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big deal,'' the Defense official said. ``Why was he so
absent-minded to not want to have a hardened computer in his home?
He used a regular computer, with no safeguards, and he surfed the
Internet. It boggles your mind why he was so insistent on not
having a hardened computer.''
</P>
<P>
   In using a secure computer, all the information on the
hard-drive must be downloaded after use, a procedure that can take
up to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Simpson, an expert on intelligence matters at
American University's School of Communication, says what Deutch did
is far from uncommon among top government officials; presidential
libraries are filled with classified documents that never were
meant to enter the public domain. But the Deutch case comes as the
country is in what Simpson calls ``a moral panic,'' fed by
politicians and media reports, about official secrets being
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what we have seen so far, for Reno to prosecute Deutch
would be a very questionable decision,'' Simpson said. ``But there
is a moral panic going on that has to do with the handling of
sensitive information, and Deutch may be the right man at the wrong
time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
John Donnelly of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
