<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4562 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BARNUM-TENT29-COX     08-28 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNUM-TENT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Circus pitches its big tent by the park
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Early Monday morning, it rose slowly above the
northwest edge of Centennial Olympic Park, downtown, white with red
stars and chevrons, looking like a mammoth angel food cake topped
with strawberry slices. It's the performance tent of ``Barnum's
Kaleidoscape,'' opening Sept. 8. The big top is the first in
decades to be erected downtown and the first from the venerable
Ringling Brothers to rise in Atlanta since 1956.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tent of the Cirque du Soleil Age, however _ similar in
shape, size (214 feet across, 50 feet high inside) and comforts
(air conditioning) to that hip Canadian-based circus, coming to a
Turner Field site in November. So, at the paved circus lot (owned
by sponsor Coca-Cola), there was no sawdust or hemp rope, no
essence du elephant wafting on the breeze. The scene looked more
like the setup for a rock festival. Electric winches hoisted the
thick plastic tent on four steel masts loaded with lighting and
sound equipment. There was plenty of work for roustabouts, though:
hosing grime off the tent from its recent Pittsburgh engagement and
tightening support cables _ three men to a cable, yanking in
unison.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that Ringling launched Kaleidoscape last year to
cash in on the Cirque craze with similar, theatrical,
European-style acts. But the American outfit does bring back a few
beloved critters that the Cirque disdains: prancing white horses
and a gaggle of geese, directed at eye level by a Hungarian midget.
The most distinctive feature of the circus, says spokeswoman Becky
Guthrie, is that ``It's all about luxury! We have red plush seats,
hardwood floors, beautiful designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people come out to the lobby tent after the show, to have
dessert and talk to the performers,'' Guthrie adds, ``they'll feel
like they're in P.T. Barnum's parlor in Victorian times.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnum's Kaleidoscape
</P>
<P>
   Opening Sept. 8. 7:30 p.m. Wednesdays-Fridays; 2 and 7:30 p.m.
Saturdays; 1:30 and 6:30 p.m. Sundays. $25-$55. Through Oct. 8.
Under the tent at 284 Techwood Drive N.W. (adjacent to Centennial
Olympic Park).
</P>
<P>
   1-877-922-7686 or www
</P>
<P>
   .barnumskaleidoscape.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
