in corporate America. Stock options dispensed to executives and
workers are not accounted for as an employee expense, even though
they clearly are. So companies that reward their employees with
stock options do not include the costs of those programs in their
overall expenses, giving their earnings a boost. By Gretchen
Morgenson.
