<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-GULEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY DROPS ITS CASE AGAINST ISLAMIC LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ In an abrupt reversal, a state security court
on Monday dismissed an arrest warrant for an Islamic leader accused
by prosecutors of trying to overthrow the secular government.
</P>
<P>
   The state security court here said the case against the leader,
Fetullah Gulen, was too weak to support the warrant issued this
month. The court made its decision after reviewing 12 volumes of
files on Gulen assembled by the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor in charge of the case, Nuh Mete Yuksel, said the
decision was wrong and pledged to open another investigation into
the activities of Gulen and his followers. Gulen's lawyers said the
decision stopped the prosecutor from starting another inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Gulen, 62, is a prominent Islamic leader who has been friendly
with senior politicians and religious leaders. He is the spiritual
leader of a loosely knit Islamic community that operates hundreds
of schools in Turkey, the Balkans and Central Asia, as well as
other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Yuksel, a prosecutor for the security court in
Ankara, opened a criminal investigation of Gulen after television
stations had broadcast excerpts from videocassettes in which he
seemed to urge followers to be patient in infiltrating government.
</P>
<P>
   Yuksel said his inquiry found that Gulen had plotted to replace
the secular government with an Islamic regime, a crime punishable
by death. His effort to obtain an arrest warrant for Gulen was
rejected by one court in Ankara. But on Aug. 11, a second court
there agreed to issue the warrant, though no formal charges were
specified.
</P>
<P>
   Gulen's lawyers appealed the decision, and the security court
here reviewed the case. After having examined the prosecution's
files, that court issued its three-page decision, saying that there
was insufficient evidence to arrest Gulen.
</P>
<P>
   Gulen, who lives in Pennsylvania, denied the accusations last
week and said that his enemies had altered the videos. He said he
only wanted Turkey to be more tolerant of ethnic and religious
diversity. He has been receiving medical care in the United States
for the last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
