<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MFS-SITARA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MFS TAKES FUNDING LEAD FOR SITARA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mutual fund managers are becoming coveted sources of
late-stage venture capital for start-ups that aim to go public.
</P>
<P>
   MFS Investment Management says it will take the lead in a $15.5
million round of financing for Sitara Networks Inc. of Waltham. The
Boston mutual-fund pioneer made its bet alongside the likes of
investment bankers Deutsche Bank and Thomas Weisel Partners, as
well as another fund group, San Francisco's Van Wagoner Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Sitara is in the hot field of telecommunications, selling
hardware to help companies route traffic efficiently on data and
voice networks. Telecom-related deals are the IPO flavor of the
summer, and a venture investment assures a generous serving of
shares when a company goes public _ and potential big gains for
investors.
</P>
<P>
   MFS, whose Technology Fund made the Sitara investment, declined
to discuss its new strategy for investing in pre-IPO companies. But
its name was emblazoned on Sitara's funding announcement,
illustrating the star power that start-ups are seeking from their
venture backers.
</P>
<P>
   John Lambros, vice president of business development at Into
Networks Inc., a Cambridge broadband player that recently raised $5
million from Boston mutual-fund giant Putnam Investments, said fund
companies tend to be longer-term investors than venture
capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike some investors that may want to get in and flip
quickly, these guys have longer staying power,'' Lambros said. And
having investors with strong reputations at the outset is seen as a
boon in attracting interest in a stock: ``To have two of the
pillars of the institutional investing community behind you when it
comes time to do the IPO, that's a huge plus,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments' venture arm, Fidelity Ventures, also
backed Into Networks. So far, Fidelity has not invested in any
private companies through its mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   While the trend toward betting a small slice of assets on
venture capital is clear among some aggressive fund managers, it's
by no means being done everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Malouf, comanager of the aggressive, small-stock Millenium
fund at Neuberger &AMP; Berman in Boston, observed that the risks of
investing in venture capital are bigger than with publicly traded
stocks. Indeed, a fund manager can't easily sell a venture
investment. Investors typically make their money on a private
company when it is acquired or when it sells shares to the public.
If the climate sours for IPOs, as it did earlier this year, it can
be years before investors see any returns.
</P>
<P>
   The rush among funds to make such investments, he said, ``is in
some part a reflection of the success the VCs have had over the
last three to five years.'' But, he said, ``That success is going
to be hard to duplicate.''
</P>
<P>
   Putnam executives say their analysts and portfolio managers are
accustomed to meeting company managers and assessing risks in order
to make investments. They consider it part of their job to stay on
top of hot companies before they go public. And they like the
chance of getting a bigger pop for investors by betting money
earlier on start-ups with promising technology.
</P>
<P>
   Into Networks's Lambros, a former investment banker at Morgan
Stanley, said big investors can be helpful in providing
introductions to large, publicly traded companies. They're also
great sounding boards, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a wealth of connections and some of the best
buy-side research out there,'' he said of Putnam and Fidelity.
``It's really an awesome wealth of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Putnam's new Technology Fund plans to invest up to 5 percent of
its assets in private equity. The firm's OTC fund also has done
tens of millions of dollars in venture deals this year, and a
Putnam offshore fund makes similar investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
