<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET GAUGES NEAR RECORD LEVELS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices staged a broad advance Monday, and major
market gauges crept close to record levels.
</P>
<P>
   Led by American Express and General Motors, the Dow Jones
industrial average rose 60.21 points, or 0.5 percent, to 11,252.84.
The gain put the blue-chip index less than 30 points from its April
11 high of 11,287.08.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index also neared record levels,
climbing 7.64 points, or 0.5 percent, to 1,514.09. Gains in EMC,
General Electric and Oracle pulled the index higher. Its peak of
1,527.46 was set on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose for the 10th time in the last 12
sessions, gaining 27.91 points, or 0.7 percent, to 4,070.59. The
advance put the Nasdaq ahead for the year.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the Nasdaq is up 0.03 percent; the S&AMP;P 500 is
up 3.1 percent; and the Dow is down 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With many on vacation, trading volume was light. On the New York
Stock Exchange, some 733.6 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``You love to see an up market, but with the volume as poor as
it is, it is difficult to tell what it means,'' said Ned Collins,
head trader at Daiwa Securities America.
</P>
<P>
   With activity at a fairly low ebb, Collins and other traders
said there were no real problems with the introduction of
decimalization on 13 listed stocks. But they said a bigger
challenge could well come at the end of next month, when a much
larger group of stocks is scheduled to be quoted in pennies instead
of fractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to draw any earth-shattering conclusions,'' said
Michael Clark, head of global stock trading at Credit Suisse First
Boston. ``There is a reason they decided to introduce this in late
summer, when the volumes are low.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Dow stocks, American Express rose $3.31, to $59.88 a
share. IBM gained $2, to $131, after an analyst from Credit Suisse
First Boston said the stock could reach $150 a share over the next
12 months. GM gained $3.63, to $74.50.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, Microsoft and Cisco Systems were the most actively traded
issues Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Intel gained 94 cents, to $73.88; Microsoft rose 69 cents, to
$71.31; and Cisco closed at $66.07, up 56 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo was a big decliner among technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The stock plunged $12.25, to $122, after an analyst at Lehman
Brothers said problems for Yahoo, the largest Internet search
company, continued to worsen because of sluggish advertising
revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a very good day for brokerage firms and financial
services stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch rose $2.88, to $140.25; Lehman Brothers jumped
$3.88, to $137.25; Goldman Sachs closed at $122, up $2.63; and
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette gained $4.69, to $65.81.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership has clearly shifted to sectors that are
interest-rate sensitive,'' said Jim Paulson, chief investment
officer at Wells Capital Management. ``I think we are going to new
highs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
