<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-WAKEFIELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKEFIELD ROTATED _ OUT OF STARTING POSITION _ AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Tim Wakefield formed a portrait of
frustration, sitting alone in the Red Sox bullpen before the game
with the Devil Rays, staring into the distance of Tropicana Field
and perhaps his future.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield was absorbing the latest blow to his career and his
ego -- the news that he has been yanked again from the starting
rotation, this time to make way for Ramon Martinez, who will start
Saturday at Fenway against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, Wakefield had refrained from publicly
expressing the kind of anger he has vented before when the Sox have
taken away the starting job he believes he merits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't even bother,'' the knuckleballer told a group of
approaching reporters. ``I've got nothing to say. Absolutely
zero.''
</P>
<P>
   The hammer fell after Wakefield got pounded for nine runs (seven
earned) on eight hits and three walks in five innings Sunday in
Kansas City. With the loss, Wakefield (6-9) was winless in his last
eight starts since July 18, and his ERA in that stretch had
ballooned to 7.58.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez (8-6), who has seen no big-league action in August
after an abysmal July, showed signs last Friday that he had
regained his form. Pitching for Pawtucket in Buffalo, he allowed
only two hits, one walk and no earned runs in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams, noting the team is in the heat of a
pennant race with only 34 games to go, said there is little time to
dawdle over personnel decisions. He said Wakefield will pitch out
of the bullpen and probably get a start or two as the Sox play 34
games in the next 34 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this enough to tell you that he should start?'' Williams
said of Martinez's outing in Buffalo. ``Well, we're going to find
out. . . . If Ramon's skills are good enough to help us win, then
we need to do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The urgency comes at an inopportune time for Wakefield, who for
several weeks this summer was Boston's most dependable starter
other than Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   He is earning about $4.5 million this year and the Sox have to
decide whether they want to exercise their option to renew the
contract next year. By pitching out of the bullpen, Wakefield may
have a harder time making the case that he is worth the Sox's
money.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox also have an option on Ramon Martinez valued at more
than $8 million. And Ramon has been anxious to return to action and
try to prove that he is better than the 6.14 ERA he has compiled
this season.
</P>
<P>
   He will pitch in a simulated game Tuesday to stay sharp for
Saturday's return. ``I've been waiting for the chance,'' he said.
``Now they are going to give me that opportunity and I'm going to
take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wakefield, who was abruptly yanked from the starting
rotation just before the season started to make room for the newly
acquired Pete Schourek, it was another lost opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans might argue that he lost this chance himself. But he
clearly holds the view that the starting spot should be his.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Sunday whether his starting job might be in jeopardy,
he said, ``I don't make the decisions around here. I made something
like 10 quality starts. Now I've had three bad ones, and you're
asking me if I'm out of the rotation. Don't ask me that. That's
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield's woes have stemmed largely from the unpredictable
nature of his knuckler. In one of his lowest moments of the season,
he was knocked out of a game against Texas two weeks ago when he
threw 14 straight balls, walking the bases loaded before he gave up
a grand slam to Ricky Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the knuckleball, you're going to give up some runs or
you're going to shut down the best teams in the league,'' Scott
Hatteberg said Sunday after catching Wakefield. ``It's going to
vary. It's a volatile thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Too volatile apparently for the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unhappy,'' Williams said after breaking the news to
Wakefield. ``That's understandable. He likes to start.''
</P>
<P>
   The news brought a mixed reaction from Pedro Martinez, who said
last week that the Sox would need to rely on Ramon's experience
down the stretch. Wakefield is highly regarded by his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good that Ramon is back in the rotation,'' Pedro said.
``But it's hard to see Wakie working so hard and doing the things
he does and always having to be the one who gets pushed around.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming next: Ramon's big test on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it going to work?'' Williams asked. ``I don't know, but
we're going to give it a shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
