<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-BOURSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEDISH COMPANY CONSIDERING HOSTILE TAKEOVER OF LONDON STOCK
EXCHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: name Per E. Larsson is CQ)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ British brokers and traders had a hard
enough time absorbing the idea that a German might soon be running
the London Stock Exchange. But a Swede?
</P>
<P>
   OM Gruppen AB, which owns the Stockholm Stock Exchange, may not
succeed in its audacious and unsolicited bid to acquire the
venerable and much bigger London exchange. But it could well
unravel the already fraying plan of the London exchange to merge
with the Deutsche Boerse AG in Frankfurt, and it provides another
example of how Europe's new generation of competitors often come
from unexpected quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, just three weeks before shareholders of the London
exchange and Deutsche Boerse are scheduled to vote on a full
merger, OM Gruppen made an informal cash-and-stock bid of about 800
million pounds, or $1.18 billion, for the London Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The London exchange rejected the offer, arguing that merging
with the Frankfurt exchange would provide a stronger base in the
long term. OM executives are now weighing a hostile takeover bid
and are expected to spell out their plans later this week.
</P>
<P>
   In response, executives at the Frankfurt stock exchange said
Monday they would consider sweetening their offer if they see the
need. But people close to the German exchange admit the issue is
politically sensitive, because London and Frankfurt officials
labored to formulate an exchange of shares that amounted to a
``merger of equals.'' Increasing the offer would turn the deal into
a takeover and likely increase the hostility of many smaller
brokerage companies that are already upset about having to adopt a
new trading system.
</P>
<P>
   People on all sides are struggling to provide a pan-European
trading system, because national exchanges are under increasing
pressure from electronic trading networks that are faster, cheaper
and potentially better suited to an integrated European
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The Stockholm Stock Exchange is far smaller than its rivals in
London or Frankfurt. But its parent company, founded with in 1985
with nine people, is a fast-growing vendor of trading technology
and has a market value of about $3.7 billion, which is at least
three times that of the London exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not only a stock exchange; they are a technology
company,'' said Andreas Walther, chief financial officer of OZ
Banken, a Swiss investment firm that owns 2.6 percent of OM.
</P>
<P>
   Besides running the Swedish stock and derivatives markets, OM
has supplied trading and information systems to the United Kingdom
Power Exchange, the California Power Exchange, to futures markets
from Hong Kong to Seoul and to stock markets from Oslo, Norway, to
Sydney Australia. In May, it launched a new electronic options
exchange in New York called the International Securities Exchange.
And, in partnership with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, it is starting
its own pan-European stock-trading network called Jiway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are commercial players in a mutual world, which is what
sets them apart,'' said Thomas Johansson, an analyst at Enskilda
Securities in Stockholm. ``They are more aggressive than the
others.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest distinction between OM and most of Europe's other
stock exchanges is its history as a publicly traded company.
Started originally as a company to trade Swedish derivatives, it
went public in 1987 and then orchestrated a takeover of the
Stockholm stock exchange in 1999. Though the merger with the stock
exchange was quite recent, OM itself was always run as a for-profit
corporation rather than cooperative controlled by its members.
</P>
<P>
   In the six months ending last June, revenues climbed 52 percent
over the previous year, to 1.4 billion Swedish kroners, or about
$150 million. OM's stock price has more than doubled so far this
year, to 450 kroner from about 185. Its biggest investors include
Investor AB, the huge holding company controlled by the Wallenberg
family, which owns about 15 percent of its shares.
</P>
<P>
   Per Larsson, OM's 39-year-old chief executive and one of the
company's co-founders, declined to be interviewed today. But when
London Stock Exchange officials publicly announced and rejected
OM's informal offer on Friday, Larsson dismissed the rebuff as
``predictable'' and insisted that ``we are determined that the
London market should have a better alternative'' to its proposed
merger with Deutsche Boerse in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts doubt that OM Gruppen will be successful if it
attempts a hostile takeover of the London exchange. Though the
exchange ended its mutual status and sold shares earlier this year,
most of its stock is held by the banks and brokerage firms that are
members of the exchange. Many of those companies are much more
worried about the exchange's long-term strategic position than its
current share price, and they are likely to agree with exchange
officials who say it makes more sense to merge with a relatively
big exchange than a small one.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed in acquiring the London exchange, a company would
have to obtain 75 percent of the shareholders behind it.
</P>
<P>
   But there is widespread unhappiness among the German-British
merger in London. Smaller trading companies are upset about the
costs of installing new equipment to run the Deutsche Boerse's
electronic trading system, called Xetra. In addition, British
regulators were surprisingly critical in a report last week,
insisting that exchange officials had failed to explain themselves
on a host of important issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own opinion is that neither of the plans will succeed,''
said Johansson of Enskilda Securities.
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
