<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH RIPS GORE OVER QUALITY OF EDUCATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ George W. Bush ripped into Democratic rival Al Gore
over education on Monday, contending that Gore would do virtually
nothing to hold schools accountable for the quality of their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President Gore could be president for four years without
parents ever knowing how their students were doing on his watch,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven years in office and my opponent presides over a national
tragedy. Seventy percent of fourth-graders in our highest poverty
schools still cannot read, and he's offered little to do anything
about it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made the remarks at the Governor's Mansion to help kick off
a campaign week that will take him to five other states and, he
hopes, divert attention from Gore's continuing attacks against him
over health care.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has accused Bush of not offering a detailed plan for
providing prescription drug benefits for the elderly. Gore has
proposed providing such a benefit under Medicare at a 10-year cost
estimated at $250 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said on Monday that he liked a bipartisan congressional
plan that would give Medicare beneficiaries the option of selecting
from a range of private health plans offering drug coverage and
other benefits. He said he plans to provide details of an improved
version of that plan next week.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bush announced a new campaign organization,
``Education Leaders for Bush.'' He was joined by Houston
Independent School District Superintendent Rod Paige and other
educators from several states.
</P>
<P>
   Although most education policies are determined at the state and
local level and Bush calls himself a strong proponent of local
control in education, the governor criticized Gore's record and
said that Gore would do little more than protect the education
status quo if promoted.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement gap between rich and poor and minority and
non-minority students has stagnated _ or gotten worse _ nationwide
during the Clinton-Gore administration, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign responded with Department of Education
statistics showing that low income students are improving their
reading. For example, from 1992-1996, high-poverty 9-year-olds
narrowed the gap in their reading test scores relative to all
students their age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly 25 percent of the gap existing when the Clinton-Gore
administration took office was erased in the first four years,'' a
statement from the Gore campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Bush signed a law in Texas last year that will
require most students, beginning in the third grade, to pass a
standardized state test in certain grades to be promoted. Texas
also has a ``report card'' system, based on test results, for
measuring the performance of public schools.
</P>
<P>
   He has proposed that all states develop similar evaluations of
their schools' performance, including annual testing of students in
third through eighth grades. Schools with persistent failures would
be stripped of some federal funds. The money would be given to
parents, who could use it to send their children to other public
schools or to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Gore's education proposals offer only an ``illusion of
accountability, words with no actions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His only new testing proposal is a voluntary national test,
once in the fourth grade and once in the eighth grade,'' Bush
added.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp acknowledged that its proposed testing would be
voluntary, but added that schools would be required to issue
detailed performance reports and that failing schools could be put
on aggressive improvement programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said that he would change Head Start to give ``top
priority'' to pre-reading and number skills, while Gore would keep
it as a nutrition and health program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
