<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4583 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHINA-POET-BOS &LR;      08-28 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-POET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREED DISSIDENT POET ARRIVES BACK IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dissident Chinese poet Bei Ling, who has lived here for
years while carrying on an underground fight for free speech in
China, returned Monday exhausted from two stress-filled weeks in a
Beijing jail, but passionate in his determination not to give up
his struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Bei, 40, was arrested Aug. 11 for distributing copies of the
small but influential Chinese-language magazine Tendency Quarterly
that he and his friend, Meng Lang, a resident of Cambridge, founded
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the name, only 13 editions were published in seven
years, and circulation never exceeded 3,000 copies. Nevertheless,
Bei caught the attention of central government security police, who
briefly detained and interrogated him several times before this
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday at Logan International Airport, Bei said
the tougher treatment he received this time was triggered by his
having printed the latest issue of the magazine in the Chinese
mainland, and by the authorities' realization that he intended to
move back to China and intensify his campaign for free speech
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised,'' Bei said, describing intense
interrogations during which he was forced to squat, without his
shoes or glasses, with his hands clasped behind his head, and
nights in a cell so crowded the prisoners had to sleep on their
sides. ``I thought they might stop me'' from distributing the
magazine, he said, ``but I didn't know it was so dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   First, security officers told him he was charged with illegal
printing, then they called it illegal publishing. Finally, just
days before his release amid growing pressure from the US
government and international journalists, he was told he would be
charged with illegal business.
</P>
<P>
   But, Bei said, the security forces' real objective in the
interrogations was learning the identity of Chinese citizens who
helped him produce the magazine in China. He was repeatedly told
that he faced a 10-year sentence, but would be treated more
leniently if he told the truth about the underground operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government controls all publishing in China, and people
can't publish anything,'' he said. ``They already knew I had
published in China when they arrested me, but they did not know who
did the typing, who made the films.''
</P>
<P>
   Interrogation sessions sometimes consumed 10 hours of his day _
two hours in the morning, two in the afternoon, and from 8:30 in
the evening until after 2 a.m. Throughout, he said, he insisted
that he had published the edition in Hong Kong, and did not reveal
the names of Chinese who helped him.
</P>
<P>
   Then, gradually, he began refusing to cooperate with the
interrogators' orders. ``I told them I am not a person who robs, I
do not kill people,'' he said. ``I just do my literature and
printing. This is a good journal for the future of China.''
</P>
<P>
   As police officials became more aware of his case, he said, some
of them became easier to deal with. ``Sometimes a gentle,
intellectual 50- or 60-year-old would come as the situation got
bigger,'' he said. ``Sometimes some of them would just watch me
while others asked questions.'' The day before he learned he would
be released, he said, five people whom the jailers described as
``leaders'' came and talked with him until after 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions did not ease in his cell, however. There, Bei was
confined in a space he estimated at 100 square feet with 20 to 25
other people. Their toilet, sink, and shower all were in that
space. He had no change of clothes,there was no hot water, and he
was not allowed to read or write. When he insisted strongly on his
right to reading materials, he finally was given a book by the late
Chinese leader Deng Xiao Ping.
</P>
<P>
   About halfway through his imprisonment, Bei's brother, Huang
Feng, was arrested, but Bei did not learn of this until two days
before his release. That was the worst moment of the whole
experience. ``I was so angry, so sad,'' he said. ``I couldn't
control my feelings, the crying. They kept saying `Your brother
helps you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bei was allowed to see his brother, who also had been released,
and parents, who returned to China from a US visit to help secure
his release, for only a half hour before security men took him to
the Beijing airport and put him on a flight to San Francisco
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to continue to publish Tendency,'' he said. ``We will
move the editing back here'' from the underground editing studio he
had set up in Beijing. ``We will print in Hong Kong. But we will
have big money problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Bei said he will try to regain his appointment as a research
associate at Harvard University's Fairbank Center for East Asia
studies, where his position lapsed in June. He said he may seek
academic work at Harvard or another area university, and may apply
for a fellowship from the Neiman Foundation, which supports studies
by domestic and international journalists at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   But first, he said, he needs to rest, and to see if he can break
his smoking habit. He quit seven years ago, he said, but the
interrogators gave him cigarettes during breaks, and now he craves
nearly two packs a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so happy'' to be back in Boston, he said at Logan, though
he badly wanted to go outside so he could smoke. ``Before, I always
wanted to go back to China,'' said Bei, who has been in the United
States since the late 1980s. ``Now I know I cannot. Now I know this
is my new home, my real home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4584 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-BIO-VII-3RDTAKE-     08-28 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BIO-VII-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: denied it. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aides say that Bush was mostly on the road in the fall campaign
and was not much involved in the Horton episode or other
mudslinging. Some also say that he lacked Atwater's exuberance at
bare-knuckled methods.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Atwater rushed into Bush's office, exultant at finding an
old magazine article saying that Dukakis had once honored a witch.
Wead recalls that Atwater was thrilled and urged that it be quietly
circulated among evangelical Christians to discredit Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``G.W. wasn't excited; he was maybe a bit disgusted,'' recalled
Wead, who said that the article was duly disseminated among
Christian groups. ``He wasn't afraid to attack, but I never saw him
show any glee in taking people down.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Bush showed a talent for managing people in the
headquarters, reassuring them when they were upset and reproaching
them when they were not working hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the disciplinarian,'' remembered Andy Card, another key
aide. ``I'm blessed that I never got taken to the woodshed. But if
you were a disappointment to the campaign, he would let you know
that you were a disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Bush's most remarkable abilities, a particularly useful
one in politics, is making people think he likes them and approves
of what they are saying. He had a knack for melting into any group
he wanted. He could speak in salty language with campaign workers
one moment, and talk about Christ as his personal savior with
evangelicals the next.
</P>
<P>
   Wead recalled flying at night with Bush and a senator and
congressman on a private jet, returning from a campaign appearance.
They were relaxing in their seats, facing each other, and the
lawmakers were drinking Scotch and sodas and getting steadily more
talkative.
</P>
<P>
   ``So these guys were telling all these stories about their
girlfriends,'' said Wead, who was sitting beside Bush. ``And they
were talking about where they stashed their girlfriends and telling
stories about close moments with wives and journalists. They were
saying what they did with their girlfriends, and it got raunchier
the more they drank. And George W. was taking it all in and
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when they paused, he said, `I'm a lucky man to have
Laura.' And they sort of gulped and looked down at their whiskeys.
And one said, `Let's toast Laura.' And so they toasted Laura right
there and then in the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush gave the impression of not liking Washington much.
</P>
<P>
   The 1988 election ended in victory for the Bushes, of course,
but George W. immediately became impatient to return to Texas. He
worked with mounting frustration on the presidential transition _
and, aides say, helped kill the prospect that Craig Fuller, his
father's chief of staff, would become White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Bush thought that Fuller, among other sins, had been
disrespectful to the Bush family, not even returning calls. So
instead Bush pushed for John H. Sununu to get the job _ and Sununu
did. Likewise, Bush pushed his father to give the job of chairman
of the Republican National Committee to Atwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once his father won, and he settled in to this transition, he
was very unhappy,'' said Roland W. Betts, a college friend who in
early 1989 joined Bush and other investors in buying the Texas
Rangers baseball team. ``He did not want to be there. He was
looking for `what am I going to do next?' And that's just when the
Rangers came up.''
</P>
<P>
   So Bush returned to Texas to help run the Rangers, but he still
visited the White House periodically and became a trouble-shooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a good sense of what wasn't going right,'' said Alan K.
Simpson, an old family friend who was then a senator from Wyoming,
``and when things weren't going right, George W. would suddenly be
on the front porch.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, aides say that Bush became disenchanted with
Sununu and began plotting with them to oust him. In Bush's account,
he virtually fired Sununu, but that seems to be an exaggeration.
Instead, he took soundings and reported to his father _ and also
spoke bluntly to Sununu of the dissatisfaction. Sununu, instead of
resigning as expected, dug in his heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conversation that George had with John was when John was
already under fire,'' recalled Charles Black, a White House
official who himself played a leading role in the episode. ``George
didn't `fire' Sununu. It wasn't the result of that specific
conversation. It was a result of a whole bunch of things.''
</P>
<P>
   A stack of Bush administration documents, obtained through the
Freedom of Information Act, offers a window into Bush's interests
during his father's administration.
</P>
<P>
   The letters between George W. Bush and his father's White House
are strikingly mundane. They almost never mention the grand issues
of the day; nearly all have to do with paying back favors for old
family friends in an old-boy network.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas autograph collector named John W. Dorman, for example,
had written to Bush asking for help in getting the president's
signature. So Bush forwarded it to his father's secretary, with the
notation: ``Patti _ this guy has been loyal to all Bushes. Thanks,
GB.''
</P>
<P>
   The record shows that in each case, President Bush sent out the
autographs, personal notes and other favors, usually with a plug
along these lines: ``George, the Texas Rangers man, did indeed pass
along your letter.'' The result was that the younger Bush gained
chits that would be useful when he began his own political career.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Bush also backed particular appointments, invariably
citing loyalty as his reason. For example, Donald B. Ensenat, an
old Yale fraternity brother and former roommate of Bush's,
recommended Edith Brown Clement, known as Joy, for a federal
judgeship. Bush forwarded the recommendation to C. Boyden Gray, his
father's counsel, with the notation: ``Boyden _ Don Ensenat is a
very good man and good friend of all Bushes. Please give Joy any
consideration you can. Warmly, G.''
</P>
<P>
   Clement became a federal district judge.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4585 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-BIO-VII-4THTAKE-     08-28 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BIO-VII-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: district judge. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only item in the archive containing a policy suggestion from
Bush is a January 1992 letter to Samuel K. Skinner, who replaced
Sununu as chief of staff, about oil prices. ``We have trouble in
the oil states,'' Bush warned, ``because the president is viewed as
favoring cheap energy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Bush suggested that Skinner meet with
representatives of independent oil companies to soothe them and
that ``a mention in the State of the Union message would help.'' He
added: ``Perhaps, the big guy could renew his call for a cleaner
America and announce that -- percent of the government fleet will
be converted to use natural gas or fuel with farm product
additives.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, President Bush signed into law a bill providing
that some new cars in government fleets would use natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was far less involved in the 1992 campaign than he had been
in 1988. He did some public speaking and stayed in regular touch by
telephone with campaign officials, but he did not move to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our campaign obviously wasn't going well, our numbers weren't
good, so he, like all of us, expressed frustration,'' said Skinner.
``He was expressing these frustrations to me, but the phone wasn't
ringing off the hook. I guess he'd call once a month or so. And I'd
see him every month or six weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush seethed from a distance at the portrayal of his father in
the news media and at the way campaign officials blamed one
another, leaked secrets and generally ran an undisciplined effort.
Bush has seemed cool to Baker this year, and some attribute that to
resentment at Baker's slowness in leaving the State Department for
the White House in 1992 to help in President Bush's re-election
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bush may have learned even more from the failed 1992
campaign than from the successful 1988 one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw them jumping out the windows in 1992 looking for the
next campaign,'' Bush told reporters last month. ``And that
influenced me. Yeah, that influenced me. I worry that some may be
wanting to be involved in my campaign to enhance their consulting
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   One lesson Bush drew, friends say, is the importance of relying
on old friends in a campaign, even over people with more
experience. This year, Bush has surrounded himself with close
friends who are absolutely devoted to his career, and his leakproof
staff has the discipline and harmony of a chorus line.
</P>
<P>
   What Bush has never picked up, despite having a father in the
White House, is a fascination for the intricacies of foreign or
domestic policy. Marlin Fitzwater, President Bush's spokesman,
recalls that when they met during his father's White House years
they would chat about baseball, not government.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner puts it this way: ``He was certainly not immersing
himself deeply in policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some other presidential candidates, of course, have been even
more removed from politics and policy. Zachary Taylor had never
voted in a presidential election before the one he won in 1848, and
Dwight D. Eisenhower was so apolitical that he had to figure out
whether he was a Democrat or Republican in the months before he ran
for president in 1952. Bush was different in that he enjoyed the
horse race excitement of politics, but he was similarly bored by
policy debates.
</P>
<P>
   So while Bush gained an excellent political education under his
father, it was focused entirely on gaining power rather than using
it. He came across as a work in progress, relishing the theater of
politics, but leaving questions about what he would do with the
reins of government if he got hold of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
