<SLUG> BC-LOEWS-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOEWS' BOND RATING IS LOWERED BY S&AMP;P 
</HEADLINE>
   By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reacting to an announcement from Loews Cineplex Entertainment
that it might default on its debt, Standard &AMP; Poor's Ratings
Services on Monday lowered its rating of the movie theater
company's bonds to B from BB-.
</P>
<P>
   Loews, one of the country's largest movie exhibitors, with 2,967
screens in 385 locations, said on Friday that its second-quarter
earnings would be considerably lower than last year's and that it
was seeking ``alternative arrangements'' with its lenders to head
off a default.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, most of Loews' major competitors have either
filed for bankruptcy protection or acknowledged that they were in
serious trouble because of the rapid expansion of multiplexes.
</P>
<P>
   Loews executives declined to comment Monday. But in the
statement issued Friday, Lawrence J. Ruisi, the company's president
and chief executive, said revenues were down because of the
disappointing summer box office as well as the ``continued decay at
our older theaters that are experiencing competition from newer
megaplexes.'' Most Loews theaters are in major metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   Overall grosses on movies released since Memorial Day are about
4 percent less than in the same period last year _ $2.5 million,
compared with $2.7 million _ said Paul Dergarabedian, the president
of Exhibitor Relations, which tracks box-office performance.
Attendance for the year so far is down about 1.5 percent, but
revenues have increased by about 2 percent because of higher ticket
prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher P. Dixon, an analyst with PaineWebber, said the
industry was suffering because cinema chains built too many costly
theaters with stadium seating and other amenities. ``They cannot
blame it on the box office,'' he said. ``That's absolute
nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon said that there were now 37,000 movie screens in the
United States and Canada, but that the industry could only support
about 28,000. He and other analysts said that Loews and its
competitors had not moved swiftly enough to close older theaters
that were at a disadvantage when forced to compete with the newer
moviehouses.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Wilkinson, an analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's, said that
Loews had been more aggressive than other operators in shutting
down theaters. Chains are often saddled with long-term leases that
are not easy to break, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent filing with the Securities &AMP; Exchange Commission,
Lowes said it was committed to spending $361.9 million to build 34
theaters with 517 screens.
</P>
<P>
   Loews said it was seeking other sources of revenue in addition
to ticket and food sales. In May, for example, the company signed a
long-term advertising deal that it said was worth about $60
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 2001EDT &QL; 
