u i BC-LEBANON-ELECT-NYT     08-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION GAINS GROUND IN FIRST ROUND OF LEBANESE ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Opponents dealt sharp blows to the government
of President Emile Lahoud and Prime Minister Salim Hoss, results of
the first round of parliamentary elections showed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The voting, on Sunday, was for 63 seats in northern Lebanon, the
Christian heartland of Mt. Lebanon and the Shuf region, home to the
Druse, a Muslim offshoot. Of those, 33 appeared to have been won by
candidates either critical of the government or in some form of
alliance with Rafik Hariri, the multibillionaire builder who has
conducted a free-spending campaign to regain the prime minister's
office. The newspapers Monday morning, based on early results,
spoke of a ``stunning rout'' of the government.
</P>
<P>
   In elections next Sunday for the rest of the 128-seat
legislature, Hariri is fielding a slate of 18 candidates for the 19
seats that represent Beirut. There will also be elections for the
Bekaa region and southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy opposition vote does not immediately appear to
threaten the dominance of Lebanon by Syria, which has exercised
total power here for a decade, political experts said. Nearly all
the candidates have ties to Syria, though to varying degrees.
</P>
<P>
   But the results do present a problem for the new Syrian
president, Bashar Assad, who took office after his tough, wily
father, Hafez Assad, died in June.
</P>
<P>
   Lahoud, a former army commander installed by Syria as president
in 1998, detests Hariri and appears determined to thwart any
comeback attempt. But Hariri could amass a large enough bloc in
Parliament to demand the prime minister's office. And Syria may be
inclined to look favorably on him as the only figure who might
possibly help Lebanon out of its deepening economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the untested Assad may be forced to mediate or to choose
between Syria's fractious Lebanese surrogates. Over the last few
days Lebanese political leaders have been trooping to Damascus _ on
Monday it was Hoss' turn _ for consultations with Assad, apparently
in an effort by Syria to calm the situation. Hariri, Parliament
Speaker Nabih Berri and the army commander, Gen. Michel Sulieman,
among others, have already made the trip. The Hezbollah leader,
Sheik Hassan Nasrullah is on the schedule for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most closely watched races on Sunday, the powerful
interior minister, Michel Murr, managed to salvage nearly all of
his ticket in the face of a tough challenge from Nassib Lahoud, a
wealthy businessman. He is a former ambassador to the United States
and a cousin _ though a political opponent _ of President Lahoud.
</P>
<P>
   Murr had been criticized by opposition leaders _ particularly
the Druse chieftain, Walid Jumblatt _ for his dual role as a
candidate and the official directly in charge of the election.
</P>
<P>
   Murr's slate was for the Metn district, mostly in the Christian
mountains north and east of Beirut, with eight seats. As in other
districts, they are allocated by religion in this divided land,
four for Maronite Catholics, two for Greek Orthodox, one for a
Roman Catholic and one for an Armenian Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates aligned with Murr eventually won all but two of the
Maronite seats. But despite his legions of election workers decked
out in blue T-shirts bearing his name and his control of the
electoral machinery, it was a close call. The official announcement
of the results, scheduled for Monday morning, was delayed until
that night.
</P>
<P>
   One Maronite seat went to the dissident Lahoud. The other was
won by Pierre Gemeyal, the 30-year old son of former President Amin
Gemeyal who went into exile in Paris after leaving office in 1988
and only returned this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Jumblatt, warlord of the Druse militia in the war, was a major
winner, taking all eight seats in his own constituency in the Shuf
and most of the nine seats in the neighboring Aley-Baabda
constituency. He has allied himself strongly with Hariri and has
lately taken to harsh public attacks on the role of Syria and its
intelligence agencies here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
