<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PARIS-DESERT-EXHIBIT-     08-28 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-DESERT-EXHIBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMELESS MAGIC WITHIN THE DESERT'S SAND 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ With the arrival of photography in the mid-19th century,
the desert entered the European imagination. Endless sand dunes in
the Sahara became metaphors for the grandiosity of Nature, camel
trains and nomadic tribesmen evoked romance and mystery. Of course
the first desert photographers were not artists; as explorers and
scientists, they were merely bent on recording the unknown and
unseen. Yet their work passed one test of art: it made people
dream.
</P>
<P>
   It is no great leap, then, a century and a half later, to
commission 10 contemporary artists to travel into the desert and
record their reactions to it. True, in the meantime the desert has
become less of a secret, with expanses of sand now all too familiar
to both tourists and moviegoers. (The desert was surely the real
star of David Lean's film ``Lawrence of Arabia.'') But that is
where artists come in: they can prod the collective imagination by
finding fresh magic.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Desert,'' a show at the Cartier Foundation for
Contemporary Art in Paris through Nov. 5, they set out to do just
that. The exhibition is built around works made for the occasion as
well as existing works by five other living artists, but it also
provides context through a selection of remarkable photographs from
the 19th and early 20th centuries. The result is to turn the
familiar into a surprise, the unfamiliar into a discovery.
</P>
<P>
   This also happens to have become the Cartier Foundation's
speciality in organizing frequent thematic shows at its gallery
space in the stunning steel-and-glass building on the Boulevard
Raspail that was designed by Jean Nouvel in 1994. These have
included ``Like a Bird'' in 1996, ``Amours'' 1997, ``Being Nature''
in 1998 and ``A Real World'' in 1999, each devised to provide the
artist's take on the commonplace. With ``The Desert,'' which will
be presented at La Caixa Foundation in Barcelona early next year,
the foundation has gone further by virtually creating the show
through commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery's main lobby is dominated by three screening rooms.
One is given over to Bill Viola's 1979 film, ``Chott el-Djerid, a
Portrait in Light and Heat,'' in which the American video artist
juxtaposes wintry landscapes from North America with the mirages
and shimmering light of a dried-up salt lake in southern Tunisia.
Another shows ``Alice to Uluru, January '00,'' a commissioned work
by the Swiss artist Beat Streuli comprising 250 slides taken during
long drives through and flights over the Australian outback.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Depardon's film ``Deserts,'' also made for this show, is
a compilation of black-and-white photographs of mainly African
deserts (and their inhabitants), accompanied by atmospheric sounds
of children's voices, market cries, gunshots and wind. But the
Cartier Foundation also invited the Moroccan-born artist Titouan
Lamazou to travel to Timbuktu in Mali with 72 of Depardon's images
and to paint his own observations on the photographs. The results
add human warmth to the harshness of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   It is on the gallery's lower floor, though, that the
timelessness of the desert comes into focus through the mixed
display of old photographs and new works of art. Many of the
earliest desert photographs were taken in Egypt, where new
archaeological discoveries were drawing explorers and scientists.
Interestingly, in their photographs of the Sphinx and pyramids at
Giza, outside Cairo, Hippolyte Arnoux and J.P. Sebah made a point
of including camels and people in order to convey the massiveness
of the monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Soon photographers were venturing deeper into the deserts of
North Africa, revealing the majesty of the sand dunes, although
again frequently adding a human figure to show scale. Images taken
in desert communities, on the other hand, often reflected an
ethnographic interest in local customs and clothes. Gaetan Gatian
de Clerambault, for instance, took nearly 4,000 photographs of the
draped clothing of Moroccan women early in the 20th century. But he
also had an artist's eye: many of his images verge on the abstract.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Wilfred Thesiger, the British explorer, photographer and
writer (``Arabian Sands'') who is now 90, is in a sense a throwback
to the first desert photographers. Still in his 30s when he
discovered his ``vocation for the desert,'' as he put it, he has
dedicated his writing and photography to preserving the myths and
mysteries of the Arabian desert. In his images on display here,
there is no heat, only silence and solitude.
</P>
<P>
   Balthasar Burkhard, a Swiss photographer, found a new angle,
literally, by taking to the air earlier this year over the deserts
of Namibia in southern Africa, capturing the light and shadows of
boundless shifting sand dunes against the backdrop of arid
mountains. His stunning large-format photographs are echoed in
``Drift: 29 Days, 18 hours, 2 minutes,'' a 1999 film by Michael
Light, an American who has created a likeness of earthly deserts
using NASA images taken on the Moon.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Americans were invited to meditate on the deserts of
the United States for this exhibition. Lee Friedlander's
black-and-white photographs of entangled desert vegetation have the
abstraction of a Jackson Pollock painting. William Eggleston's
color photographs of the American Southwest, on the other hand,
remind one abruptly of what can happen when modern life penetrates
the desert: highways, gas stations, garbage. Walter De Maria's 1969
film ``Two Lines, Three Circles on the Desert'' puts Nature first:
it shows a man walking away from the camera in the Mojave Desert
until he disappears.
</P>
<P>
   The one artist who approached her commission with irreverence is
the Egyptian photographer Lara Baladi, who went into the Libyan
desert to create ``Om El Dounia'' (``Mother of the World''), a vast
mosaic of photographs with highly saturated colors. From afar the
work suggests sand dunes against a deep blue sky, but up close it
is alive with surrealist images: a desert with mermaids, a bizarre
picnic, an opium smoker, a sky where fish and clouds compete for
space.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly an exhibition with so many works from so many periods
can only aspire to the sensation of a journey through space and
time, one that starts with a concrete reality and ends up with
impressions and ideas. This show does that much. Reassuringly,
though, it does not pretend that this journey began in the mid-19th
century. The head of an ancient Egyptian mummy and an 18th-century
Iranian manuscript of the Koran in so-called dust writing are
timely reminders that the dead desert has always meant life, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
