<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTANEWPLANE0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First Delta 767-400to arrive in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Nancy Fonti
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Delta Air Lines will add a little more flash to its
fleet this week when it brings home its first Boeing 767-400, a new
model that will replace the airline's aging L-1011s.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 767-400 set to arrive in Atlanta from Seattle on
Wednesday marks the first delivery under a 21-plane order Delta
placed in 1997. Delta, the first airline to fly the new plane, will
get 11 more by the end of the year. It will take ownership of the
first plane today in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 12 months, 767-400s will replace the
Lockheed-built L-1011 on many high-volume domestic routes,
including Atlanta to Orlando, Miami, Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and
Tampa starting Oct. 1. By next year, the planes will fly to San
Francisco; Los Angeles; Honolulu; Maui, Hawaii; Salt Lake City;
West Palm Beach, Fla.; San Juan, Puerto Rico; Dallas-Fort Worth;
and New York-LaGuardia.
</P>
<P>
   The plane's design isn't new; the 767-400 is a stretched version
of the popular 767, an industry workhorse that began flying in
1982. In addition to a longer fuselage, the new model has wingtip
extensions, new landing gear, upgraded cockpit instruments and a
remodeled cabin interior based on Boeing's 777.
</P>
<P>
   Many travelers won't notice differences between aircraft models.
But any Delta frequent flier is familiar with the L-1011, said
Atlanta business travel consultant Chris McGinnis.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of like mom's old station wagon,'' McGinnis said.
``It's comfortable, but it's old. You'll miss it, but you're glad
you're getting a new car because the thing is ancient.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta is the last major airline to fly the L-1011. American
Trans Air, an Indianapolis-based airline, operates the plane on
scheduled and chartered flights.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's list prices values 21 767-400 at a total of $2.4
billion, but large airlines like Delta rarely pay published prices
for new aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The 767-400 is the third new model Delta has taken as part of
its 20-year agreement with Boeing, under which Delta buys only
planes built by the Seattle aerospace company.
</P>
<P>
   The other two are the 737-800 and the 777.
</P>
<P>
   When seeking a replacement for the L-1011, Delta considered the
A-330, a competing wide-body built by Boeing rival Airbus
Industrie. Boeing's announcement that it planned the new version of
the 767 helped it win the Delta contract.
</P>
<P>
   The first 767-400 was supposed to arrive in May, but an
engineers' strike at Boeing last winter pushed back the date.
</P>
<P>
   Now Delta will start retiring its last 18 L-1011s. First flown
by Eastern Airlines in 1973, the chunky L-1011 could seat more than
300 people. Lockheed nicknamed it Tristar because of its three
engines; some flight attendants called it Tritanic because it flew
at a slight nose-up angle and drink carts rolled downhill.
</P>
<P>
   Though not a financial success, the plane, which competed for
customers with the Douglas DC-10, was advanced for its time and
among the first aircraft equipped to land in complete fog, said Tom
Crawford, a program manager at Lockheed Martin Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed delivered the last of its 250 L-1011s in the early
1980s. Delta was the biggest customer and at one point owned 56,
including some it bought from Eastern when that carrier shut down
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ''With both Eastern and Delta hubbing in Atlanta, if you flew in
a wide-body from Atlanta in the '70s and '80s, there was a strong
chance you were on a L-1011,'' said George Hamlin, a senior vice
president at the Global Aviation Associates in Washington. ``This
is kind of a watershed event at Hartsfield.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't clear what will happen to all Delta's L-1011s, but one
will be donated to the Federal Aviation Association's Federal Air
Marshal program.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
