<HEADER>
A4595 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-QUINCYCARTER0829-     08-28 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-QUINCYCARTER0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia quarterback Carter finds there's always criticism
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. - It stung Georgia quarterback Quincy Carter like,
well, a Yellow Jacket. Or a Gator. Or a Volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   On page 121 of Sports Illustrated's college-football preview
issue, an opposing coach offered this scouting report on the
Bulldogs' third-year quarterback:
</P>
<P>
   ``Quincy's a beautiful athlete, but there's more to being great
than looking good. I don't see it in him. Every big game he's
played in, he's lost and looked bad. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Only four quarterbacks, including Heisman Trophy winners Ty
Detmer of Brigham Young and Charlie Ward of Florida State, have
thrown for more passing yards than Carter in their first two
college seasons. In only 22 regular-season games, Carter has thrown
for 5,197 yards, the third-highest total in Georgia history. He
needs only 1,138 yards to pass former three-year starter Mike Bobo.
</P>
<P>
   But as Carter begins his junior season Saturday against Georgia
Southern in Sanford Stadium, one glaring statistic continues to dog
him: He has lost all six games against Florida, Georgia Tech and
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've accepted that (as the way I'm measured), but I can't put
that much pressure on myself,'' said Carter, a former Parade
Magazine All-American from Southwest DeKalb High. ``I can't say,
'Quincy, you're not going to be successful unless you beat those
three teams.' I base success on wins and losses. But, at the same
time, it's a team effort. I'm not going to base it on whether I
beat Tech, Florida or Tennessee. I know my abilities. I believe in
myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm going to get what I deserve anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   After two seasons, Carter isn't getting much in terms of
respect. Even Carter admits that he is probably regarded as a
``third-tier quarterback,'' behind Purdue's Drew Brees, Nebraska's
Eric Crouch and Virginia Tech's Michael Vick.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll conducted by the Montgomery (Ala.) Advertiser during
last month's SEC Media Days in Birmingham, Carter was named the
``most overrated player'' in the SEC. Auburn quarterback Ben Leard,
who beat Georgia 38-21 in Athens last season, was named the
league's ``most underrated player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All summer, I've been hearing about Michael Vick and Drew
Brees,'' Carter said. ``Now, everybody is saying that I haven't
performed well against Florida and Tennessee and Tech. There's
always criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter contends that his performance the past two seasons has
been overlooked. In 1998, he was the first Georgia freshman to
start at quarterback since Johnny Rauch in 1945. He broke nearly
all of Eric Zeier's freshman passing records, and his 2,713 passing
yards last season were the most for a Bulldog sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one says anything about the yards I've passed for the last
couple of seasons,'' Carter said. ``That's just the way it goes.
I'm like a third-tier guy to everybody else right now. The only
thing I can do is to keep working hard. It shows on film what I do,
so I'll just let people talk, and I'll keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL Draft guru Joel Buchsbaum of Pro Football Weekly has watched
film of Carter and says that Carter needs to show drastic
improvement this season. Buchsbaum says Carter would not be a
first-round draft choice today but could become one if he improves
his decision-making and passing skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, he's a very good athlete with very good skills, but
he's still got a lot to learn about playing quarterback,''
Buchsbaum said. ``He's not as accurate throwing as you think he is,
and a lot of his reads aren't correct. He needs to show tremendous
improvement over the course of the season. He needs to improve his
judgment _ where to throw and when to throw _ and his passing
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchsbaum says some NFL teams might question Carter's ability to
play well in the games that matter most. In his six starts against
Florida, Georgia Tech and Tennessee, Carter has completed 51.5
percent of his passes while throwing for an average of 239.5 yards.
He has thrown five touchdowns and seven interceptions in those
games.
</P>
<P>
   In his other 16 starts at Georgia, Carter has completed 66.2
percent of his passes for 24 touchdowns and only eight
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he plays as well as he played last year,'' Georgia
coach Jim Donnan said. ``I'll be happy with that. He didn't have
the game against Florida like he did the year before, but I think
he played well throughout the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchsbaum rates Brees as the highest-rated passer available in
next year's NFL Draft. If Vick leaves Virginia Tech as a sophomore,
he could be the first player drafted. Carter's status is not
certain. He says he hasn't decided whether he would return to
Georgia for his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear that Carter could improve his draft projection
with a solid junior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things I want to accomplish,'' Carter said.
``I'm not going to base my decision on turning pro on whether we
win a national championship or whether we're a top team. I'm just
going to look at the whole picture.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, that picture includes criticism and doubters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to it,'' he said. ``When I was in high school, I was
always regarded as the quarterback behind (former Kentucky and
current Cleveland Browns star) Tim Couch. It always seems like
someone is saying that someone is better than me. If you look at
it, Drew Brees hasn't won a Big 10 title. He hasn't been to the
Rose Bowl. I'll get my credit when it's due.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
