<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4596 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-SPORTS-WEB0829-COX     08-28 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-WEB0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A weekend trip through the labyrinthine world of Internet sports
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Memo to: The office.
</P>
<P>
   Re: That assignment you gave me to watch sports on the Internet
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The latest: I'm trapped in cyberhell. It sounds like something
out of Twilight Zone, but it's true. There is a cartoon of a
ballplayer named Ron Jocker on my screen. His lips are moving, and
the audio track is saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the Mets. The biggest thing I don't like about New York
are the foreigners. How the hell did they get in this country,
anyway? I don't have the attention span to go out there and
concentrate much longer than 10 minutes. I am not a racist. I was
not raised that way. Baseball is just a game, and no matter what
happens my parents still love me.''
</P>
<P>
   And I can't get rid of it. Jocker keeps railing on, even though
the computer appears to have shut down. I'm stuck with a cartoon
maniac looming on my screen and coming out the speakers. This is a
computer greeting-card company's idea of a joke.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I know it wasn't part of the assignment. But following the
Braves pitch by pitch on the Internet wasn't that exciting. So I
decided to answer the e-mail that carried the subject line: Get
back at Atlanta's Bad Boy Pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, that Ron Jocker.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least something dramatic happened during my Internet
surf.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of two days and a long Saturday night, I
felt like I had been trapped in a time warp, back in the days when
news came over a ticker tape, line by line.
</P>
<P>
   Following baseball pitch by pitch, college football play by
play, Tiger Woods hole by hole. It lacked all of the emotion and
color one gets from TV, or by being there. The experiment revealed
this surprising revelation: the best thing to watch on the Internet
is a NASCAR race.
</P>
<P>
   On NASCAR.com, you get the race summary lap by lap, a graphic of
little cars supposedly running in true proximity among the top
four, a graphic of the track layout and a radar image showing how
far rain showers in the Midwest are from Bristol Motor Speedway. A
scoring and timing page gives each car's last-lap speed.
</P>
<P>
   What you don't get are the pit stops and the wrecks. On the Web,
a ``Race Alert'' dialogue box is as intense as it gets: ``Lap 395.
An incident involving Robert Pressley has brought out the 11th
caution in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   If you love statistics, following the pro golf tour is slightly
interesting. PGATour.com posts round-by-round, hole-by-hole scores
of tournaments, followed by a summary of key categories _ driving
accuracy, driving distance, putts per round, sand saves, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the numbers can leave one cold.
</P>
<P>
   I had expected to spend the weekend locked in my computer room
with Cynthia Cooper, Tiger Woods, Venus Williams, Ruben Mavarez,
Hristo Stoichkov and Albert the Great.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of them showed up.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt to follow Williams in the Pilot Pen finals against
Monica Seles got sidetracked by this revelation: www.WTA.com does
not connect to the Women's Tennis Association but rather to
Anything.com, a company that advises Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Some insider's info: type carefully. My typo _ Teenis.com _
brought me to My Teeny Tiny David Cassidy Appreciation Site. After
correcting my error, I was able to navigate to Tennis.com. Without
a match available, I felt obliged to work through the nine Anna
Kournikova Web pages and catch up on her development. The photos
testify that she surely has perfected the art of bending over to
tie her shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Had planned to follow Stoichkov and the Chicago Fire in the MSL
soccer match against Tampa Bay. No such luck. But www.mlssoccer did
offer one of the more interesting sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the latest news on drugs, players in trouble, manager
movement, injuries, scandals and a whole lot of other offbeat
features to keep you amused,'' it promised, but I was too timid to
click on Kickmyballs.com.
</P>
<P>
   My fascination with WNBA.com kept me from tuning into Albert the
Great's near-win in the Travers Stakes. I caught the Houston
Comets-New York Liberty championship game in progress. On the
cybercast, guest analyst Kym Hampton, retired Liberty center, was
available for Q&AMP;A.
</P>
<P>
   The interactive opportunity cluttered things up:
</P>
<P>
   MODERATOR: At 2:33 p.m. With 1:36 remaining in the half the
score is now 24-23 Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Megan from the Web: ``What do you recommend that New York works
on for the second half?
</P>
<P>
   Kym Hampton: ``Making more shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the game in Portuguese was as informative. ``Your
own photos from Houston with WNBA.cam'' offered still views from
either basket.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, over at www.ABCSports.com, Mavarez was pitching
Venezuela to the Little World Series title. Clicked on Myteam.com
to hear the gamecast. Instead, got an insult: ``You have an
outdated version of RealPlayer,'' the dialog box shouted.
``Download RealPlayer8 now, $29.99.''
</P>
<P>
   I always follow instructions. As the computer began the
46-minute downloading procedure, I escaped upstairs to watch the
Venezuelans win the game on TV. Returned to find the computer had
crashed with only 77 percent of the download complete. Scrapped the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Went to Fastball.com. To catch up on the Yankees-A's, already in
the top of the fourth, I clicked on the update and received 12
pages of play by play.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to watch the Kansas State-Iowa football opener. With
no audio available to me from the FANSonly.com site, I settled for
the play by play on www.K-Statesports.com. 2-8 K22 Allen 28 rush
middle (Davison). Just like reporters get in the press box, except
chronologically backwards, with the most recent play listed first.
</P>
<P>
   Another dialogue box popped onto the screen. ``Get out of debt.
Click here.'' How'd those people know I was online?
</P>
<P>
   Followed the game until K-State took a 17-0 lead (Beasley 4 pass
left to Morgan; touchdown (at) 0:19) just before halftime. The site
was packed with stats after the game, including drive charts, play
by play, notes and quotes.
</P>
<P>
   Clicked on over to Atlantabraves.com to see if they had rallied
against the Cardinals. They hadn't. Neither had my audio function.
Clicked on MLB radio, which allows access to every broadcast, and a
voice from inside the computer said, ``Sorry, but we did not
understand the URL you requested. Please check the URL and try
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a long day had become night. Dialed up NASCAR.com to
watch Rusty Wallace run away at Bristol. Neither Seminoles.com nor
BYUCougars.com offered play by play. Clicked on the audio broadcast
at the BYU site and got a message that said: ``Error No. 11. This
document is not a RealAudio document.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when I fell into the Ron Jockerzone.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: The Internet is interesting for cold numbers and
requires patience and a more agreeable computer than mine. I'll
take a TV and remote control, thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
