u a BC-VOUCHERS-MINORITIES-N     08-28 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOUCHERS-MINORITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS BLACKS DID BETTER BY CHANGING TO PRIVATE SCHOOL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Wis., Wash. D.C., N.Y., Ohio)  By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Black public school students who attended private schools on
scholarships that were similar to vouchers performed significantly
higher on standardized math and reading tests than similar students
who remained in public schools, a study released Monday says.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year study of students in three cities, by researchers
at Harvard University, Georgetown University and the University of
Wisconsin, found that the average performance of the black students
who switched to private school was 6 percentile points higher than
students who stayed in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which followed students in voucher programs aimed at
children from poor families in New York City, Washington and
Dayton, Ohio, found no significant overall gains among students in
other ethic groups who moved to private schools from public
schools. The greatest gains for black students were in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are expected to be cited by advocates of vouchers
for public school students during the current election season,
particularly as the two major presidential candidates stake out
opposing positions on school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican presidential
nominee, supports vouchers that poor families can use for
private-school tuition, saying it will force public schools to
improve. His Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, says
vouchers will drain needed resources from public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many previous studies of the effects of school vouchers,
students in the new study were randomly selected to receive the
privately financed scholarships and then compared with students who
applied for them but did not receive them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the students in the New York City and Washington
programs received vouchers paid for by Ted Forstmann and John
Walton, the businessmen and philanthropists who founded the
Children's Scholarship Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Paul E. Peterson, the Harvard researcher who was one of four
authors of the report and the principal investigator in each of the
three cities, said in an interview Monday that the study provided
evidence that private-school vouchers can help to achieve ``a
nontrivial closing of the gap'' in achievement between black
students and the rest of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Groups that opposed vouchers criticized the study, with some
noting that that among those who helped pay for it were several
conservative research groups and voucher advocates, including the
Thomas B. Fordham Foundation and the Milton and Rose D. Friedman
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The study's results raised questions about why blacks who moved
to private schools improved so much more than students from other
ethnic backgrounds. Additionally, in Washington, where the
improvement among black students was twice as great as in New York
City and one-third greater than in Dayton, the reading scores of
black students declined sharply in the first year that they
attended private school. Only after the second year did those
students record the gains that were the highest of any ethnic group
in any city over the entire two-year study.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson explained the anomaly by saying that some students
might have had difficulty in adjusting to private school during the
first year.
</P>
<P>
   And, Peterson said, when the researchers asked the parents of
all voucher recipients in New York City about the differences
between their children's private schools and their former public
schools, parents of black voucher recipients were more likely to
cite differences in discipline, specifically less fighting,
property destruction and racial conflict at the private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Other education experts raised questions about why some 20
percent of students dropped out of the study, either by returning
to public school after the first year or by receiving a voucher but
choosing not to attend private school.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson attributed those results to the fact that voucher
recipients typically had to contribute about half of the
private-school tuition, or received vouchers but could not find
space at a conveniently located private school. In any case, he
said, those results were accounted for in the researchers'
analysis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 2014EDT &QL; 
