<SLUG> BC-GORE-HEALTHCARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TAKES AIM AT PRESCRIPTION DRUG PRICING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Campaigning in a battleground state home to
many senior citizens, Vice President Al Gore said Monday that
prescription drug pricing that makes the same medication cheaper
for animals than for humans is especially harmful to the elderly
and should be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the ability to dictate the price,'' Gore said of the
nation's drug companies. ``But they know the market for cats and
dogs won't bear as high a price, so they have the power to dictate
a much lower price to the veterinarian's office.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was in Florida on the first stop of a week that will focus
on health care, specifically his proposal to extend prescription
drug benefits under the Medicare program to an estimated 40 million
people at a cost of &UR;  &LR; $250 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan would provide a prescription drug benefit with the
government paying half a patient's annual cost up to $5,000. The
plan, which would be funded by projected budget surplus funds, also
would cover catastrophic drug expenses over $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Before an audience of several dozen senior citizens on the
Florida State University campus, Gore described how his
mother-in-law and the family Labrador are prescribed the same
medication for different ailments, with the dog's monthly
prescription bill totaling far less.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said such disparities are disturbing at a time when many
senior citizens on fixed incomes are forced to either go without
other necessities or cut back on their medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is time to say to every senior in this country,
we have come to the point when we can improve Medicare by giving a
prescription drug benefit to every single senior in this country,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Coinciding with the start of Gore's health care week, the
Republican National Committee began airing $7 million in new
advertising critical of Gore's proposals, claiming the vice
president is ``pushing a big government plan that lets Washington
bureaucrats interfere with what your doctors prescribe.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican nominee, has not outlined
the specifics of his own proposal on health care, but has indicated
preference for letting seniors choose among a variety of private
plans, some of which may offer prescription drug benefits. He said
in Austin Monday that he'll provide more details next week.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett called Gore's proposal a
``one-size-fits-all, government-run drug plan,'' and compared it to
the failed 1993 attempt by the Clinton administration to establish
a national health care program.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what is fueling the ongoing focus on health care is data
showing voters rating it as an important issue in this year's
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the audience at FSU that he would work to improve
health care coverage for veterans, saying health care benefits and
retirement security are among his top campaign priorities. One of
the great hurdles, he said, is how high prescription drug costs
have risen since Medicare was created 35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Recounting his struggles to care for a handicapped adult son,
Arthur Flatt, 77, said he and his wife saved for their retirement
but soon found the costs of family health care overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we turn around, we get sick,'' said Flatt.
</P>
<P>
   Flatt, with his voice breaking, told Gore that getting a
reduction on prescription drug prices would allow him to pay for
home health care for his son, a one-time engineer who suffered a
brain aneurysm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're carrying a heavier burden than you should have to
carry,'' Gore said, embracing the man.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Dixie, 74, told Gore that it's ``really depressing''
seeing her friends forego their medicine to pay for food, a choice
Dixie said she also is sometimes forced to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can handle the pain, but there are a lot of people
who can't do it,'' Dixie said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, perspiring under the hot lights while he empathized in
turn with members of the audience, encouraged hesitant speakers
with ``I hear ya's'' and frequently intoned ``Bless you, God bless
you.''
</P>
<P>
   After campaigning in the Florida capital, the vice president
headed for a Monday night rally in Albuquerque, N.M. Other health
care-related events for Gore this week include a talk today in
Albuquerque on children's health coverage, and a rally later this
week in support of a patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
