<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STEEL-BANDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELEGATED TO THE SIDEWALK, STEEL DRUM BANDS WEATHER EXPOSURE TO
REHEARSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: name Stephan Gleich is CQ) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sleep did not come easily to Yuri Narinesingh the
last few days. He was used to a bed, not the ragged gray rug spread
out above a sidewalk in the Flatbush section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the dozens of steel oil drums lining the block
to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   They were sorted into groups, half a dozen or so each, and
lashed to metal frames that could be rolled up and down the block,
like coat racks. Each morning, Narinesingh counted the drums when
he woke up. One stolen here, another misplaced there could spell
disaster for his 75-member band, the Nu Tunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this for the sake of music, just music,'' said
Narinesingh, who had not shaved or showered for days while he was
guarding the drums.
</P>
<P>
   This week was supposed to cap a march to glory for the band. The
group is scheduled to compete Sept. 2 with 12 other steel drum
bands for thousands of dollars in prizes before Brooklyn's giant
West Indian American Carnival on Labor Day, which is expected to
draw more than 2 million people. The competition, called Panorama,
is one of the premier contests for pan music, a variant of calypso
played on converted oil drums.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nu Tunes, along with two other pan bands called the Pan
Rebels and the Metro Steel Orchestra, have found themselves
literally out on the street. On Aug. 16, they were forced from a
warehouse at 680 Parkside Ave. where they had stored their
instruments and rehearsed for several years. So the three bands
have been doing a bit of sidewalk improvising ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Through rainstorms and sweltering heat, they have kept their
drums on the pavement right outside the building, rehearsed there,
and even held round-the-clock vigils on the industrial block to
watch over the instruments. The thunderous rehearsals, which draw
hundreds of band members and residents, have also perked up the
ears of police officers, who have dropped by every night to keep an
eye on things.
</P>
<P>
   Local politicians said they were trying to find another space,
or help in negotiations with the landlord, but have come up
empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   The bands had never signed a lease or paid rent for the
warehouse, and the landlord, Klyn Properties, did not know the
bands were there, said Stephan Gleich, a lawyer representing Klyn.
Gleich said that several months ago, he heard there were bands in
the warehouse and asked the police to look into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 16, police officers went to the warehouse and arrested
Tony Joseph, the leader of the Metro Steel Orchestra, for
trespassing. The officers told the other bands to leave the
building.
</P>
<P>
   During the next two days, fire marshals and inspectors from the
Department of Buildings dropped by to look at the warehouse. They
cited a faulty roof and issued an order preventing anyone from
using the building. The bands and their equipment were out on the
pavement.
</P>
<P>
   This was no way for anyone to live, said Narinesingh, who
usually sleeps in his apartment in Bedford-Stuyvesant. Lounging on
a peeling vinyl couch on the sidewalk, he scratched at his beard.
The stench of urine wafted through the air. The musicians no longer
had use of the warehouse bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so embarrassing,'' Narinesingh said, a pair of
welder's goggles on his forehead, his T-shirt and khaki pants
covered in black grime. ``We're just simple people playing music,
taking part in our own culture. It's not a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The band members, who range from 6-year-old girls to 60-year-old
men, fear the humiliation that may come when music arrangers arrive
this week from Trinidad and Tobago and see them on the street. Two
of the bands have paid thousands of dollars to fly the arrangers
over to help pull together calypso favorites.
</P>
<P>
   But the show must go on, particularly since the Brooklyn
festival is one of the main showcases of the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed with what's happening,'' said Carlos
Lezama, president of the West Indian American Day Carnival
Association. ``But regardless of what the situation is, these
fellows will come out for Panorama. Practice or no practice, they
will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Panorama, which is performed in a lot behind the Brooklyn Museum
of Art, is one of the most renowned pan music competitions in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the bands battle it out, they march in a parade
called Jouvert (pronounced joo-VAY), ushering in the massive and
brightly costumed carnival that winds down Eastern Parkway on Labor
Day.
</P>
<P>
   Preparation for the pan competition begins early in the year,
culminating in frenetic rehearsals during the summer. Bands
throughout the city often use empty lots for that purpose,
converting them into what are called panyards. Before this summer,
the three bands on Parkside Avenue practiced both in and outside
the warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Edward Roberts, a lawyer representing two of the
bands, filed a request for a temporary injunction in U.S. District
Court in Brooklyn asking the landlord to let the bands back into
the warehouse until Labor Day. A hearing is scheduled for tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Dawad Philip, a manager for Pan Rebels, admitted the bands did
not have ``a legal leg to stand on in terms of tenant-landlord
relations.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the bands have been pushing forward with their
daily rehearsals, despite lack of sleep and occasional rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   The three bands rehearse from 9 p.m. until 2 a.m., when the
police end the session. Although there have been no complaints
about noise on the industrial block, some officials at Intermediate
School 2, across the street, have asked band members not to urinate
on the side of the school, Philip said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the headaches, the band members have tried to remain as
up-beat as their calypso standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live for the competition,'' Philip said. ``Will we be as
strong as previous years? That remains to be seen. But we believe
the gods are with us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 2017EDT &QL; 
