<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4614 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-CLINTON-BURUNDI-HNS &LR;      08-28 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BURUNDI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE BY CLINTON, MANDELA FAIL TO PRODUCE BURUNDI PEACE DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL HEDGES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARUSHA, Tanzania _ Persuasion by President Clinton and pressure
by former South African President Nelson Mandela failed Monday to
produce a peace deal that could have headed Burundi down the road
to end a bloody civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Several groups and the president of Burundi, Pierre Buyoya,
signed an agreement brokered by Mandela to share power between the
majority Hutus and the Tutsis, who seized power in the small
central African nation three years ago. But five small, influential
Tutsi militant groups refused, putting the accord's durability in
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a section of the leadership who do not care for the
slaughter of innocent people inside Burundi, who are still refusing
to sign,'' a visibly angry and exhausted Mandela said. ``That type
does not want peace. That type wants to drag out these negotiations
for eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, also clearly disappointed, urged the holdouts
in less emotional tones to have the ``courage and vision'' to sign
the agreement and move toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can walk away from this and fight some more. No matter how
long it takes, when it comes down to it you will still be dealing
with the same issues,'' Clinton told the holdouts. ``If you let
anyone else die, all you are doing is making it harder for somebody
else to make decisions you will have to make anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela said he would not support a cease-fire, a key demand of
the Tutsis, who have been battling Hutu insurgents in the nation of
5.7 million for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our trump card, this is our weapon to change things,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that if a realistic peace were signed by all
factions, the United States would urge a United Nations effort to
enforce the peace, participate in building a national army and
provide help in settling refugees and supporting the tens of
thousands of war orphans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to help your children to remember your history, but
you must not force them to relive your history,'' Clinton said.
``When all is said and done, only you can bring an end to the
bloodshed. No one can give you peace, you must choose it.''
</P>
<P>
   About 200,000 have been killed in Burundi's civil war, which is
part of a wider, regional clash between Tutsis, who have held power
since colonial days, and Hutus, who have sought to topple them. The
sometimes genocidal struggle has engulfed several countries in
central Africa, most tragically Rwanda where between 600,000 and 1
million Tutsis were massacred in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Tutsis and Hutus have been fighting in Burundi since 1993 when
Tutsi troops assassinated President Melchoir Ndadye, a Hutu,
shortly after his election. The Tutsi-controlled military seized
power in the nation of 5.7 million in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's persuasive tone was in stark counterpoint to Mandela's
disgust at what he repeatedly described as a betrayal by men
lacking ``honor and dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mandela, the effort to broker the deal, coming after 27
years spent in prison and four years as president of South Africa,
was a reluctant labor at a time he had hoped to withdraw from
public life, African experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal Mandela negotiated would have provided a framework for
the Tutsis and Hutus sharing government power and for building an
army whose ranks would have been half Hutu, half Tutsi.
</P>
<P>
   But even had the accord been signed by all parties, the most
important issues would not have been addressed. including who would
lead the country during a transition to a shared government, and
what would happen to the 11,000 prisoners that the Hutus and
Mandela call political prisoners but the Tutsis say are criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, said after
the partial signing ceremony, ``I think people are hopeful that
(the holdouts) will eventually sign the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger described the fluid nature of the day's events. ``When we
arrived here today we honestly couldn't have told you what would
have transpired,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a ``one-two punch'' of Clinton cajoling and Mandela
threatening brought 14 of 19 signatures to the document, Berger
said.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the two ``sticking points'' were details of a
cease-fire sought by Tutsis but which Mandela feared was a stalling
tactic and the question of who would run the country in a
transition to a shared government.
</P>
<P>
   After the signing ceremony, Mandela lost his balance and fell
forward. Several African leaders caught him and set him back on his
feet. The 81-year-old Mandela it waved off, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   On his arrival here earlier in the day, Clinton was greeted with
the wild enthusiasm he had encountered throughout his African
visit.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Tanzanians, including several hundred
school children in worn but clean matching uniforms, waved tree
branches and American flags and cheered for the first American
president to visit this country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, on a three-day trip to Africa, came to this small
resort in the shadow of Mount Kilimanjaro's snow capped peak at the
request of Mandela after spending two days in Nigeria, Africa's
most populous nation. But even before Clinton left Nigeria earlier
on Monday, aides sought to lower expectations for the visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to go to Arusha was made irrespective of whether
or not there was to be a signing. And there will be a further and
continuous effort to push the process forward in the direction of
progress and hopefully to an ultimate conclusion,'' Susan Rice, the
assistant secretary of state for African Affairs, said in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   While administration officials played down expectations, they
were blunt about the stakes involved, saying that the stability of
central Africa could be affected by the Burundian war.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
