<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ITALY-BASILICATA-3RDTAKE-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: probably right.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   Matera is 170 miles east of Naples on the A3 Autostrada to
Potenza, then Strada Statale 407. There are flights to Naples and
Bari, which is about 40 miles from Matera. Renting a car is
advisable; train service in Basilicata is very slow.
</P>
<P>
   Although the summer heat is not unbearable, April through June
and September through December are the most pleasant months to
visit.
</P>
<P>
   For information on Basilicata, contact the APT (tourist office)
in Matera, (39-0835) 331-983, or in Potenza, (39-0971) 411-839.
Carlo Levi's 1945 book ``Christ Stopped at Eboli'' (Noonday Press,
$13) remains a wonderful guide to the region.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect luxury hotels in Basilicata, although all of these
offer a telephone, TV and minibar.
</P>
<P>
   Grande Albergo, Corso XVIII Agosto 46, Potenza 85100, telephone
and fax (39-0971) 410-220, is Potenza's most modern hotel. The 70
rooms offer spectacular views of the valley below. A double with
bath, including breakfast, costs about $85, at the rate of 2,150
lire to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Hostel I Sassi, Via San Giovanni Vecchio 89, Matera 75100;
(39-0835) 331-009, fax (39-0835) 333-733. ``Hostel'' suggests bunk
beds and shared bathrooms, but there are no privations at this
delightful place built right into the sassi, with superlative
views. Our cool, white room, on two levels, had a large private
terrace and a funky bathroom carved out of the rock. The bar,
breakfast room and 14 other guest rooms are also in converted caves
(four rooms have air-conditioning). Doubles with bath are $65,
breakfast included.
</P>
<P>
   Albergo Italia, Via Ridola 5, Matera 75100; (39-0835) 333-561,
fax (39-0835) 330-087. This elegant, old-fashioned hotel in the old
city has nice views of the sassi. All rooms are air-conditioned and
some have antiques. Doubles are $85, with breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Due Pini, Piazzale Stazione, Melfi, 85025, (39-0972)
21031, fax (39-0972) 21608, is a simple 48-room hotel, offering
excellent value right downtown. Doubles with bath start at $50,
breakfast included.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel La Pergola, Via L. Lavista 27-31, Rionero in Vulture,
(39-0972) 721-179, fax (39-0972) 721-819, is well situated for
exploring Mount Vulture. This modest, comfortable hotel has 43
rooms and a large, cheery restaurant with a good local wine list.
Doubles with bath cost $55, including breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   Simple, rustic and based on the freshest of ingredients, the
delicious food of Basilicata is what the shepherds might have eaten
in Arcadia. Specialties include grilled meat and homemade sausages,
wild mushrooms and field greens, fresh sheep- and cow's-milk
cheeses, and distinctive wheat pastas like manate, cavatelli and
strascinati, shaped roughly like little caps or boats.
</P>
<P>
   Ristorante Due Torri, Via Due Torri 6-8, Potenza, (39-0971)
411-661, serves regional specialties in a nicely restored space in
a twin-towered Aragonese fortification in old Potenza. Dishes
include pureed fava beans with dark, winey-flavored sauteed chicory
and pepperoncino in sauce; homemade pastas; grilled pecorino, and
creamy sheep's milk ricotta with wild honey and nuts. Two-course
dinner for two, with local aglianico wine, costs about $45. Closed
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Le Botteghe, Piazza San Pietro Barisano 22, Matera, telephone
and fax (39-0835) 344-072, is in an elegant, restored cave in the
sassi. The fine regional menu begins with extensive antipasti, like
fresh little rounds of mozzarella, prosciutto and rocket, and local
hams. Scorze d'amelle pasta, like large orecchiette, are served
with cime di rapa (turnip greens). Grilled sausages are delicately
flavored with fennel. Two-course lunch for two with aglianico wine,
about $45. Closed Wednesday and Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   La Buca, Via San Pardo 95, Matera, (39-0835) 261-984, is a
simple place serving local specialties: baked veal shank with
onions, pasta and cicerchie, a type of bean that grows wild in the
area. Two courses for two with wine, about $40. Closed Sunday night
and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Vaddone, Contrada Santa Abruzzese, Melfi 85025, (39-0972) 24323,
is a family restaurant offering good local salami, cheese and
olives, grilled sausages and lamb, and local fruit. Two-course
dinner for two with wine, about $40. Closed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   What to See
</P>
<P>
   Because many sites are locked, you will need a guide to visit
the sassi of Matera and the chiese rupestri, or cave churches.
Freelance guides abound, but you're probably better off with one
from an agency. Itinera, (39-0835) 263-259, and Nuovi Amici dei
Sassi, (39-0835) 331-011, are among the reliable agencies for
guides. For other suggestions, call the tourist office, (39-0835)
331-983, or ask at your hotel for an English-speaking guide. A
reasonable price for a group of one to four is around $35 for a
two-hour tour.
</P>
<P>
   Museo Nazionale Domenico Ridola, Via Ridola 24, Matera 75100,
(39-0835) 310-058, has extensive prehistoric finds. There is a fine
collection of Lucanian and Magna Graecia red figure vases. Open
daily 9 a.m. to 7 p.m. Admission: about $2.40.
</P>
<P>
   Centro Carlo Levi, Piazzetta G. Pascoli, Matera, (39-0835)
314-235, exhibits a collection of paintings on local themes done by
Carlo Levi during his confinement in Basilicata. Open Monday to
Friday 9 a.m. to 1 p.m., and 4 to 5:30 p.m. Tuesday and Thursday.
Free.
</P>
<P>
   Casa Grotta di Vico Solitario, Piazza di San Pietro Caveoso,
Vicinato di Vico Solitario 11, Matera, (39-0835) 310-118. This
reconstruction shows how 20th-century villagers lived in their
caves. Open daily 10 a.m. to 2 p.m. and 3 to 6:30 p.m. Admission:
$1.
</P>
<P>
   Museo Nazionale del Melfese, Castello Normano-Svevo, Melfi
85025, (39-0972) 238-726, has stunning pre-Roman pottery, weapons
and jewelry of the Dauni and Lucanian peoples. Open daily 9 a.m. to
7 p.m., except Monday, when it opens at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Museo Archaeologico Nazionale, Piazza Umberto 1, Castello Pirro
da Balzo, Venosa, (39-0972) 36095, has tombstones, household
implements and other local Roman finds. Open daily 9 a.m. to 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeological Park and Benedictine Abbazia della SS Trinita in
Venosa is open 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. daily. A ticket for this, the Melfi
museum and the archaeological museum costs $2.40 at any of the
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Museo di Castel Lagopesole, Castello, Lagopesole, (39-0971)
86083, recently opened with an interesting collection from the
archaeological dig in the castle courtyard. Open 9:30 a.m. to 1
p.m. and 4 to 7 p.m. Closed Monday. Admission by donation or about
$1.40 each with a guide. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Museo Archaeologico Provinciale, Via Lazio 18, Potenza 85100,
(39-0971) 444-833, shows prehistoric, Italic and Greek relics. Open
Tuesday to Sunday 9 a.m. to 1 p.m., and 4 to 7 p.m. Tuesday and
Thursday. Free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
