<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4617 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-ITALY-SICILY-2     08-28 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ITALY-SICILY-2TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN COMFORTS, ANCIENT SITES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, September 3) 
 By CATHARINE REYNOLDS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring or autumn, Sicily heads my short list of holiday
destinations. It combines sun; good, plain food; natural beauty;
and enough history, art and architecture to leave me reeling. What
it doesn't promise is a selection of great hotels. Apart from a
handful of deluxe establishments in the larger cities and in
Taormina, Sicily's innkeepers have been getting a bad press since
Goethe bemoaned their shortcomings two centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   However, on a spring visit around the island, my husband, Ken,
and I saw old hotels being overhauled and old buildings morphing
into new hotels with admirable results. We weren't looking for
grandeur as much as comfort, charm and a sense of place, and in a
10-day stay we found three special hotels (outside the well-known
standards in Palermo and Taormina).
</P>
<P>
   Starting from Palermo, we circled the island clockwise. After
Taormina, we headed for Syracuse. This city, which to fifth-century
Greeks was New York to Athens' Washington, traces its origins
beyond history to myth, romantic myth at that. The comely nymph
Arethusa, pursued across Arcadia by the river god Alpheus, implored
Artemis, goddess of virginity, for protection. The goddess answered
her prayers, transforming Arethusa into a fountain, in which form
she fled to Sicily's eastern coast, settling on the island of
Ortygia, the heart of what became ancient Syracuse. Determined to
woo her, Alpheus channeled himself across the Ionian Sea, forever
to mix his waters with hers. Understandably then, a romantic spirit
imbues Syracuse, in spite of Athens' bloody defeat there in the
Peloponnesian War.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Hotel
</P>
<P>
   Not a half mile from Arethusa's supposed fountain stands the
58-room Grand Hotel. Its four-story bulk sits comfortably against
the backdrop of Ortygia's medieval fortifications.
</P>
<P>
   We admired the hotel's neo-Gothic stone details as we parked.
Slipping through the snazzy automatic glass doors, we were taken
aback by the interior _ a glossy revamp, about five years old, of
the pre-World War I hotel. As we signed the register, I admired the
flower arrangements. Examining them closely, I was disappointed to
discover they were artificial.
</P>
<P>
   Our second disappointment was the announcement that the elevator
was out of order. But the harbor view from our third-floor room
proved worth the climb on the polished white marble stairs: fishing
boats tied at our feet and the ghosts of Athenian triremes to
entertain my imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The airy room was eminently comfortable, with a firm bed; good
reading-in-bed lights; state-of-the-art telephone, unfortunately
without dataport (those can be found in rooms on the first floor);
and woodwork with whimsical post-Modernist eyebrows and loopholes.
The muted multicolored jacquard upholstery was soothing if
unmemorable. The bathroom was well fitted, though the shadowy
lighting left me wondering about my eyeliner. A convenient outlet
for my laptop required some jury-rigging, but the hotel's handyman
was as quick to sort out the problem as he had been to see that the
elevator was repaired.
</P>
<P>
   We had arrived at midday, just as the town was tying a
collective napkin around its neck, so we headed to the rooftop
dining room, hungry but with low expectations. The classic Italian
hotel service _ black tie, comic opera charm and all _ relaxed us
after the morning's Sicilian driving. The ethereal sea bass risotto
turned our smiles into grins of pampered satisfaction, a sensation
compounded by the sunlight tipping the waves in front of us.
</P>
<P>
   The following two days were packed with visits to Neapolis, the
Greek theater and the Latomia del Paradiso (an ancient quarry, now
overgrown), never leaving us time to use the hotel's inviting
private beach. On Ortygia we admired the cathedral, which
incorporates columns from the Temple of Athena, and the handsomely
installed Museum of Medieval and Modern Art, with Antonello da
Messina's beautiful, if highly restored ``Annunciation.''
</P>
<P>
   We were especially glad to be staying on tiny Ortygia itself
(where there are only two other hotels), able to roam the island's
byways into the evening, ogling the Baroque details of small
palazzi that are increasingly being restored as ravishing secondary
residences, and waltzing across the near-perfect, stagy Piazza del
Duomo by moonlight. Each time we left our room, the blinds closed
automatically, which we found slightly unnerving. But each time we
returned, we opened them with a press of a button, compounding the
theatrical impression Syracuse left on us.
</P>
<P>
   Eremo della Giubiliana
</P>
<P>
   This hotel was altogether different, situated deep in rolling
countryside south of Ragusa about an hour from Syracuse.
Approaching it along the Marina di Ragusa road and passing
well-tended farms outlined by dry-stone walls, my husband reminded
me that Sicily had been the breadbasket of the Roman Empire. Within
the electric gates of the property a bell tower rose over the
landscape-hugging whitewashed buildings.
</P>
<P>
   A charming young man welcomed us, and in impeccable English
sketched some of the estate's history as he deftly unloaded our
bags and carried them through the arched door into a beamed hall.
He explained that the buildings had started life in the 15th
century as a hermitage that in time was fortified to guard against
Barbary pirates raiding the nearby coast. The property was acquired
by the Nifosi family in the 18th century. Oriental rugs, sofas and
exuberant arrangements of field flowers warmed the austere
limestone walls and intaglio stone floors.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, the nine rooms and two suites, each with a high iron
bedstead, are small, as befits their former role as cells for the
community's friars, but the spacious tiled bathrooms, bright with
halogen pin spots, are positively sybaritic. In keeping with the
building, the handsome furnishings are spare, with only a few small
rugs on the stone tile floors and antique cupboards providing
hanging space _ a welcome contrast to the overupholstered clutter
of many hotel rooms. Simple wooden lamps provided good bedside
lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with instructions from the desk, we took off on a long
ramble around the countryside, accompanied by Pedro, the Eremo's
Maremmano sheepdog, who introduced us to the livestock. We paused
to take in the sweep of Mediterranean coast only a few miles from
the Nifosi family villa and wished it were warmer so we could use
the hotel's small, sandy beach. On our way back, we came upon a
lush vegetable patch, tended by a voluble gardener. In a Sicilian
buzz that bore no relation to my schoolgirl Italian, he described
how he sowed his organic rucola (arugula). We parted with more
smiles and nods than comprehension, but a conviction that dinner in
the vaulted basement dining room would be good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
