<HEADER>
A4618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-PRESCRIPTIONDRUG     08-28 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PRESCRIPTIONDRUGS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush to offer seniors discounted drug prescriptions
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With the rising cost of prescription drugs
becoming a key issue this year, Texas Gov. George W. Bush said he
will offer a comprehensive plan to reduce the cost of drugs for
senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the plan could be released in a few days, but Bush,
during a meeting at the governor's mansion with six reporters from
key battleground states, said his idea will include pooling seniors
into a consumer group that will get drug discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, speaking in the
parlor of the two-story mansion built in 1856, said his plan also
would include an option for seniors to make some sort of small
payments to get discounted drugs. Those too poor to make the
payments would be eligible to have them made by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Patented drugs also should be moved more quickly into the
generic market, Bush said. ``I think that is going to require
working with the industry,'' he said. ``I'm not for price controls.
I'm for continuing to encourage research and development. But the
idea of moving generics into the market is a good idea to keep
prices down.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare also needs to be changed, told reporters from Florida,
Pennsylvania, Missouri, Oregon, Georgia and Michigan, because the
program is hampered by more than 130,000 pages of regulations and a
failure to keep up with new medical technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicare has done a good job for seniors for a long time. But
the problem is that medicine has changed while Medicare as a
program itself has not changed,'' he said. ``I believe we ought to
say if you're happy with the current system, fine ... but give
seniors a variety of options from which to choose to tailor their
own program to meet their own needs ... including a prescription
drug benefit in all the programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Democrats released a television commercial Monday
that criticizes Bush's lack of details about his proposal to make
prescription drugs more affordable for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats claim millions of seniors would go without
prescription drug coverage under Bush, and those who do receive a
benefit would be forced to go through HMOs and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush approach is favored by big drug companies and leaves
millions with no help,'' according to the TV ad, set to start
airing across the country today.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming his opponent, Democratic presidential nominee Vice
President Al Gore, is trying to start a ``class war in America,''
Bush said he will ``not practice the politics that divide us.'' He
accused Gore of promising too much and leaving himself little room
to successfully govern.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that is important that you learn as governor
is how to accumulate and spend your political capital,'' Bush said.
``My point of view is that you can't try to be all things to all
people and then be effective when it comes time to spend political
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to set priorities, and my priorities are going
to be Social Security and Medicare, education, tax relief and
strengthening the military,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scoffing at Gore's suggestion that Bush does not believe the
military is the best in the world, Bush said that is not the issue.
``Will we still be the best 10 years from now?'' he said. Bush
argues that military morale is low and that it does not have the
resources it needs for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was in Tallahassee, not far from the mansion of Florida
Gov. Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Asked who has the better mansion, the Texas governor said he
hasn't spent much time in his younger brother's place, but ``ours
is more historic.'' Told that his brother has a pool, on a day when
the temperature in Austin was approaching 100, Bush said, ``really?
He has a pool? Then he got the better deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
