<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4619 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-ITALY-SICILY-2     08-28 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ITALY-SICILY-2NDTAKE-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: be good.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And it was: rustic bread to be dipped in olive oil pressed from
the fruit of the estate trees, ravioli filled with spicy eggplant,
grilled swordfish and beef, and irresistible blackberries. The
estate's own wine, a sturdy Il Frate Nero red, suited the fare, and
we climbed the stairs to fall asleep to the strains of ``Al di La''
rising from the wedding reception taking place in the courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, with advice from the art historian who also
manages the front desk, we scouted the enchanted towns of the
``Sicilian Highlands'': Noto, Ragusa and Modica. All were largely
constructed after the devastating earthquake of 1693 and reflect
the best of Baroque town planning. We wished we had allowed more
time for this less visited corner of Sicily and vowed to return.
Another time we will take advantage of the hotel's other offerings:
small-plane tours of the island and North Africa organized by the
Nifosi family, as well as antiquing and horseback expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   Foresteria Baglio della Luna
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we headed west to the ruins of Agrigento, the city
described by Henry Adams as ``Athens with improvements.'' What was
one of Magna Graecia's richest cities boasts a spectacular setting
along two ridges rising parallel to Sicily's south coast.
</P>
<P>
   The Baglio della Luna hotel, off the Porto Empedocle road, sits
at the west side of the Valley of the Temples, which, in an
unexplained historical misnomer, is not a valley but a ridge
overlooking the sea. Among the glorious fifth-century B.C. temples
are the nearly intact temple of Concord and the largest of all, the
sanctuary dedicated to Olympian Zeus.
</P>
<P>
   My goggle-eyed rapture with the temples created some traffic
risk, so my husband was relieved to reach the classical columns
that frame the gate of the Baglio della Luna safely. It opens into
a handsome courtyard centered on an ancient stone wellhead. Parts
of the Baglio date to the 13th century. Fortified in the 16th
century, it served as a manor house from the 18th century until
Ignazio Altieri converted it into a 24-room hotel five years ago.
Though the Baglio can't lay claim to a location as privileged as
the well-known Villa Athena Hotel alongside the Temple of Concord,
its decor is altogether fresher and, as we quickly realized, its
staff eager to please.
</P>
<P>
   Occasional antiques, cheerful Italian chintzes and rug-scattered
wooden floors define both public rooms and bedrooms. Altieri has
lovingly collected paintings and prints depicting Agrigento's
temples since the 18th- century Grand Tour put it on the map as
Sicily's most visited archaeological site. The bathroom adjoining
our small but cheery bedroom gleamed with white tile (and feebler
water pressure than my shower-maven husband prefers).
</P>
<P>
   After a hot day's temple crawling, I found a chaise longue in a
shaded area of the central courtyard ideal for sipping lemonade,
thumbing my Thucydides and dozing.
</P>
<P>
   The magic of the Baglio lies in being able to fling open the
shutters at sunrise to the panorama of the limestone temples
stretched across their ridge, softened by olive, almond and fruit
trees. In the background, modern white buildings rise with the
geometry of a Cubist painting, the contemporary town clinging to
Agrigento's ancient Acropolis. I revisited the image on a morning
wander under the pergolas and palms of the hotel's hillside garden.
</P>
<P>
   The dining room has the same view, rendered all the more
dramatic when the temples are lighted at night, like a golden
necklace strung across the landscape. The menu sounded worryingly
ambitious but proved very successful, with lightened versions of
Sicilian classics like eggplant caponata, wonderful fish and veal
and the ice-cream-based desserts for which the island is known.
</P>
<P>
   As with all three hotels, my only major quibble was breakfast.
Italians do not share Anglo-Saxon notions of how to start the day.
To please us, hotels up and down the boot of Italy lay out an
abundant breakfast buffet. But a sashay along the laden tables
reveals packaged crackers, cereals and jams. Even places that pride
themselves on homemade breads with lunch and dinner serve cardboard
croissants at breakfast. And hardest to swallow: juice fresh from
cartons, metallic-tasting when served in sight of orange groves in
this country of delicious blood oranges. Fortunately, more and more
hotels like the Baglio and the Grand propose some local
alternatives at their buffets: prosciutto and salamis along with
ripe fresh fruits. And Seattle can only hang its head once you've
started the day with Sicilian coffee.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest we were delighted to have found hotels that were
not only comfortable but, by reflecting the best of their
localities, also had significantly enhanced our understanding of
what the writer Mary Taylor Simeti so fittingly calls Persephone's
Island.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   Grand Hotel, via Mazzini 12 (on Ortygia), 96100 Syracuse;
(39-0931) 464600, fax (39-0931) 464611. Doubles from $163 including
breakfast, at 2,150 lire to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Eremo della Giubiliana, contrada Giubiliana (on the Marina di
Ragusa road, about five and a half miles from Ragusa), 97100
Ragusa; (39-0932) 669119, fax (39-0932) 623891. Doubles from $140
with breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Foresteria Baglio della Luna, contrada Maddalusa, Valle de'
Templi, 92100 Agrigento; (39-0922) 511061, fax (39-0922) 598802.
Doubles from $186 including breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
