<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT LINKS WITH BIG BOOKSELLERS TO CAPTURE E-BOOK MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stepping up the competition to set the standard for software to
read books and other documents on computer screens, Microsoft and
Adobe Systems both announced rival alliances intended to strengthen
their respective positions in the burgeoning market.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft announced a plan for Amazon.com to open an electronic
book store on its Web site that would distribute free copies of
Microsoft's Reader software. Amazon.com will make Microsoft's
format the site's ``preferred'' format for electronic books, said
Lyn Blake, general manager of bookselling at Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said the site would begin selling electronic books for a
variety of formats, including Adobe's, but Microsoft's format would
appear first when customers searched for a title in electronic
form. She said that Microsoft's software would probably also be
promoted elsewhere on the site as well. She said Amazon would begin
selling electronic books ``soon,'' but declined to specify.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Brass, vice president for technology development for
Microsoft, called the alliance with Amazon.com ``a great vote of
confidence in what is becoming a very competitive market.''
Amazon.com is the largest online bookstore with 23 million
customers, and its support will bolster adoption of Microsoft's
format over rivals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft makes no money from its Reader software but receives
an undisclosed ``single digit'' commission on the sale of
electronic books for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Microsoft started a similar cooperative
marketing venture with Barnesandnoble.com, the second-largest
online bookseller _ with about six million customers _ to coincide
with the release of the newest version of its Reader software.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had initially approached Amazon.com about
participating in the well-publicized release of its software, its
first version for use on personal computers as well as hand-held
devices. But Amazon.com decided to wait until the market
progressed, Blake said. Brass said more than 500,000 copies of its
new software had been downloaded in the three weeks since it became
available.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Adobe Systems, whose software for electronic
publishing and reading on-screen is currently the most widely used,
agreed to buy Glassbook, a smaller maker of software for reading on
screen. Terms of the transaction were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Glassbook also provides digital book distribution services to
publishers and others. Glassbook software is easier to read and to
use than Adobe's, and the two companies said they planned to
combine Glassbook technology in upgrades of Adobe's software. A
spokeswoman for Adobe said that customers had downloaded over 180
million copies of its free software for reading.
</P>
<P>
   The deal leaves three main rivals in the race to become the
dominant format the standards for electronic publishing: Microsoft,
Adobe and Gemstar. Gemstar's format is used on portable appliances,
like the Rocket e-Book, instead of a laptop or desktop computer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4621 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CRUISES-$ADV03     08-28 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRUISES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE SHIPS PRESSURED TO BE KINDER TO THE SEAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, September 3) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cruise ships were involved in 87 confirmed cases of illegal
discharges of oil, chemicals, garbage or plastic in U.S. waters
from 1993 through 1988, the General Accounting Office said in a
report to Congress in February. What's more, some cases involved
illegal discharges numbering in the hundreds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That report, together with several high-profile cases in which
cruise lines were fined for polluting waters in Alaska, the
Caribbean and elsewhere, did little to inspire public confidence in
industry statements that cruise lines were doing their best to
protect the environment.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet federal and state officials say that many ships have
improved waste management and other environmental procedures. The
GAO report concluded that 72 percent of those illegal cruise-ship
discharge cases in U.S. waters were accidental, and noted that
their number declined from 24 in 1994 to 9 in 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is persuaded by the GAO figures or by the cruise
industry's vows that it is committed to protecting the environment.
Many environmentalists say that the reason there appear to be so
few violations is that there is little enforcement and even less
monitoring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The cruise ship industry has to bring down violations to zero
before anybody should give them credit,'' said Dr. Russell Long,
executive director of the Bluewater Network, a San Francisco
organization concerned with protecting waters and ecosystems.
``Otherwise it's like a lawbreaker telling a judge that even though
he's committed a lot of serious crimes, he deserves praise because
he's working to do better.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But other environmentalists hail the recent turnabout by the
cruise industry. ``A lot has changed in the culture of cruise
lines,'' said Michael Conway, who coordinates cruise-ship
compliance for the Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation.
``They're working hard to comply and they've been very
responsive.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One area that almost everybody agrees needs improvement was at
least partly addressed in July when the Senate passed a bill
containing an amendment pushed by Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska,
banning the release of untreated black water (sewage) or hazardous
chemicals anywhere in Alaska's Inside Passage and tightening rules
for the release of treated black water and gray water (water from
sinks, showers and basins). The bill must still be approved by the
House. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even without the amendment, cruise lines operating in Alaska
agreed last winter not to discharge garbage, refuse and untreated
sewage in the Inside Passage, and not to discharge waste into
``doughnut holes,'' areas beyond the three-mile limit but within
the inside waters of Southeast Alaska. (The Murkowski amendment,
too, would prohibit ships from dumping waste water into doughnut
holes.) They have also agreed to have the Coast Guard monitor their
overboard discharges and send samples to an independent laboratory
to be tested. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In March the 15 members of the Florida-Caribbean Cruise
Association, which includes the leading ship lines, signed a
memorandum of understanding with the Florida Department of
Environmental Protection promising, among other things, to embrace
new technology in managing waste and designing environmentally
friendly ships. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While some critics view voluntary compliance as a stratagem for
fending off stricter regulation, Conway of the Alaskan
environmental office said that such agreements can avoid political
wrangling that might otherwise mean taking several years to get
rules enacted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reasons, cruise lines do seem to be embracing
environmental protections that go beyond the merely cosmetic,
ranging from having environmentalists aboard to ``zero discharge''
policies even where certain discharges are allowed. Some ships have
installed computerized systems and recorders to track hazardous and
chemical wastes and monitor smoke and water emissions. Most have
eliminated or cut down on plastic cups, straws, even individually
packed condiments. Crystal Cruises, which has extensive policies
for safeguarding the environment, uses recycled paper for printed
items and is experimenting with soy-based inks. Princess Cruises
said its policy to reduce the use of plastic has resulted in a
reduction of seven million pieces of plastic waste a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carnival, the world's biggest cruise line, has agreed to install
a monitoring device in its Carnival Triumph this month to collect
ocean data in the Caribbean and transmit them to the University of
Miami, whose scientists developed the device. Carnival is also
working with a Finnish company to develop a low-pollution diesel
engine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean's Radiance of the Seas, scheduled to sail in
Alaska, the Caribbean and Hawaii beginning next spring, will be
powered by gas and steam turbines that the line says will reduce
exhaust emissions by 80 to 90 percent. Holland America said that
all five ships on order for delivery through 2005 will be outfitted
with cleaner-burning propulsion technology estimated to reduce fuel
consumption, and thereby emissions, by as much as 40 tons a week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet whatever the cruise industry's progress in safeguarding the
environment, Conway said it is necessary to keep up the scrutiny to
prevent backsliding and to be sure that laws adequately protect the
environment and human health.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
