<HEADER>
A4625 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TROY-REBOUND-2TAKE     08-28 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TROY-REBOUND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPERATE IN 1995, A SMALL CITY'S FORTUNES REBOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE EATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ Just five years ago, this small city on the Hudson
River was literally broke.
</P>
<P>
   It had racked up millions of dollars of debts, but had scarcely
enough money in the bank to cover a week's bills. It could put only
two police cars out on the streets to patrol a city of 51,000
people. And city officials were scrambling to sell anything they
could lay their hands on, up to and including City Hall, which at
one point bore a sign reading ``For Sale by Owner.''
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed for the better in Troy _ and how.
</P>
<P>
   The city's budget was balanced last year, for the fourth year in
a row. There is finally enough money for improvements, like new
police stations and fire trucks. The city's extraordinary downtown
_ it looks like New York City might have in the 1870s _ has been
repaved and replanted. New businesses, once scared off by the
threat of municipal bankruptcy, have started moving in.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps most important to the people of Troy, their city is
no longer a national laughingstock, as it was in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now people look over here and say, `That place is doing all
right,''' said William Fagan, an insurance agent and head of the
area's industrial development authority.
</P>
<P>
   How that turnaround came is a tale of local grit, of citizens
who would not give up on their city and a new mayor who was brave
enough to raise taxes and make hard choices.
</P>
<P>
   But Troy also got a huge amount of help from the state, which in
the last four years has pumped about $20 million of direct aid into
the city and spent millions more on economic development projects.
</P>
<P>
   So Troy has been relying on the kindness of friends, like its
state senator, Joseph Bruno, who is the state Senate majority
leader. And in an odd way, it is relying on the kindness of
strangers: the taxpayers down in the booming southern tip of New
York who have helped fill the state's coffers so that there is
money available for Troy.
</P>
<P>
   Troy is not alone. Almost every small city in the state, from
Newburgh to Niagara Falls, has faced some of the same pressures
Troy has: loss of manufacturing jobs, loss of population and loss
of property values, which means loss of tax revenues. A handful,
including Utica, mismanaged themselves into a similar municipal
mess.
</P>
<P>
   And though their rebounds may not be as sharp as Troy's, many
cities have clearly been helped by an improving economy upstate and
assistance from the state.
</P>
<P>
   But they remain dependent, fiscally and economically, on the
financial success of once-scorned New York City, said Helen
Cregger, a vice president of Moody's Investors Service, which
evaluates credit ratings on municipal governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without those training wheels, they're not ready to do it
alone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox that has New York City and its environs, long
reviled upstate, helping to subsidize the urban north, is not lost
on H. Carl McCall, the state comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one state _ everyone's in this together,'' he said,
adding that the Legislature could improve matters by making state
aid for cities more predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, each city in New York has its own story. Situated on
the east bank of the Hudson River, north of Albany, Troy was a
center of transportation, especially after the Erie Canal opened in
1825.
</P>
<P>
   And it was an industrial center before and after the Civil War:
The Chamber of Commerce boasts that practically every horseshoe for
the Union Army was made in Troy. Later, in the 1920s, it became
known as Collar City, as more than 10,000 people sewed detachable
collars and cuffs for men's shirts.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, city fathers say, Troy was the 11th largest city
in the country, and the fourth richest.
</P>
<P>
   Even after motorcars and washing machines doomed the horseshoe
and collar businesses, Troy usually held its own. It has two
colleges _ Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute and Russell Sage
College for Women _ that boomed after World War II, and it is close
to the state government jobs in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   And well into the 1970s, Troy residents say, Troy remained a
shopping mecca. Young couples might buy their wedding rings at a
jeweler near Monument Square, then go up River Street to Nellick's
to buy their furniture, just as their parents and grandparents did.
But eventually, malls mushroomed and the suburbs beckoned, and the
quaint downtown became increasingly empty and abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   As far as city government, the trouble began in 1991, when the
state economy was in a recession and New York state cut aid to
cities. Aid to Troy fell by almost one-third. City revenues
dropped, while its expenses jumped, according to a scathing 1995
report by the independent Center for Governmental Research in
Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   But while some cities coped with similar problems, Troy _ where
bare-knuckle politics are a blood sport _ did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone can share in the blame,'' said Sen. Bruno, a
Republican. ``We were fighting more for turf than for the best
interests'' of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the government's financial health worsened, the
Democratic city council, which governed through a city manager, was
reluctant to raise taxes or cut expenses. Instead, it turned to
accounting gimmicks, like a complex bond issue that basically
mortgaged City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 bond issue, which was later condemned by McCall as
improper and bad for taxpayers, raised money to cover the deficit
and finance some grandiose building projects, like a recreation
center the city has never been able to afford to operate. It also
saddled Troy with enormous interest payments that ate up more than
20 percent of its budget.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, Troy was more than $50 million in debt; it couldn't
borrow any more. A new city council, led this time by Republicans,
fired 50 city employees, but it wasn't enough. Thus, the ``for
sale'' sign on City Hall, a structure much larger than the city
needed, and talk of selling the city's water system or filing for
bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The mood around town was dismal, said William Patrick Madden,
who runs a nonprofit housing program in the city and whose family
has been there for generations. The city's financial crisis ``just
broke people's spirits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that economic times were hard in other ways; in
the mid-1990s, he added, his staff spent half its time counseling
people who were about to default on their financial obligations.
(Today, that takes up just 3 percent of their time.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Mark Pattison was elected mayor of Troy, the first in
30 years. A rumpled and outspoken Democrat whose family settled in
Troy back in canal days and whose father served briefly in
Congress, Pattison had run group homes for the mentally handicapped
before he became a mayoral candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be the only politician who found that things were
exactly as bad as he said they were,'' Pattison now says. Every day
seemed to bring some new financial calamity, like the discovery
that although the city had more than 100 police officers, there
were only enough working police cars to put two on the street at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Pattison immediately raised property taxes in the city by 21
percent, and raised water charges by 38 percent. And 200 protesters
picketed City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Pattison also negotiated with bondholders to cut the amount of
debt the city owed, and embraced a state-imposed supervisory board
that had veto power over the city's financial decisions. In return,
a municipal assistance corporation, like the one that bailed out
New York City in the 1970s, helped Troy raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the city regained control of its finances.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pattison tried to keep up the spirits of town
residents. He decided to hang on to the bunker-like City Hall,
which was built in the early 1970s to replace an ornate structure
that burned in 1938. ``It would have been a death knell,'' he says.
``Selling your city hall, in a community with a lot of pride, does
not motivate people.''
</P>
<P>
   So he and his city learned to make do. (His office still
features its original ``space age'' white plastic and brown leather
furniture, and the brown and blue carpeting has seen better days.)
When the city could not afford new police cars, it bought 10 used
ones. When it could not replace things, it repainted them.
</P>
<P>
   And in a break with precedent, Pattison and Bruno managed to put
politics aside and work together to bring new development into
Troy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me,'' Bruno said, ``I had a lot of naysayers
approaching me and saying, ``Let 'em sink.'''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bruno helped Troy get about $4 million a year in state
aid for distressed cities. He had money appropriated to turn some
abandoned storefronts on the main square into a new arts center. He
provided $2 million to renovate the Rice Building, a fabulous
edifice designed by Calvert Vaux, to hold small high-technology
companies affiliated with Rensselaer Polytechnic. And he managed to
have more than 1,000 state workers stationed in Troy.
</P>
<P>
   All those office workers have been a lure for shopkeepers like
Gary Kiddney and Steven Fox, who last year moved their gift shop,
Mary Elizabeth, into downtown Troy from a nearby mall. ``We saw it
as a golden opportunity, even when everyone else saw it as a pit,''
Kiddney said.
</P>
<P>
   The gift shop's success has, in turn, inspired other store
owners, like John Waters, who just this week opened a new jewelry
store near the arts center. (Troy is sufficiently small that the
mayor performed the ribbon-cutting.) ``Five years ago, I wouldn't
have come here,'' Waters said, adding that he initially thought
about opening in a strip mall. ``But now there's a lot of foot
traffic here.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, however, are vacant storefronts, a reminder
of how far Troy still has to go before anyone can call it vibrant.
Nearby, a big block of buildings, supposed to house fledgling
businesses, has reverted to city ownership and is up for sale.
Carmella Mantello, who ran against Pattison in November and got 45
percent of the vote, said her supporters were worried about crime
and falling property values and rallied to her call for a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Troy's partisans argue, however, that their city's genuineness
and uniqueness are what will save it _ and are already attracting
people. Sure, there may not be a Starbucks, but there's Barb's
Coffee-Tyme, Open 24 Hours, and Famous Lunch, where $2.98 buys you
four small chili dogs, a can of soda, and conversation with a
waitress who knows everybody's name (and dental problems).
</P>
<P>
   Pattison remains both optimistic and cautious. ``We've had micro
successes _ tremendous victories _ but we still have macro
problems,'' he said. As a society, he added, ``We have to decide
whether we want small cities _ because they really depend on state
and federal support.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
