<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRKOOP0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drkoop.com gets new infusion of capital
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN - The venture capitalists who stepped in to save Austin's
drkoop.com Inc. have upped their investment to $27.5 million, which
they estimate gives the battered Internet health company another 18
months of life.
</P>
<P>
   The added capital completes the latest round of financing for
drkoop.com, which a week ago reported that it had run through its
cash and was relying on credit for operating capital. The
investors, who initially pledged $20 million, replaced the
company's management, are taking control of its board of directors
and received preferred shares in drkoop.com that are convertible to
common stock at 35 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The new management team says it is now ready to begin the
difficult work of resuscitating one of the Internet's best-known
dot-com flops.
</P>
<P>
   In just a few days on the job, executives have set a couple of
major goals: get control of the company's books, which have been
bleeding red ink; and expand the company's relationship with Shared
Medical Systems, which plans to distribute drkoop.com content to
computer systems in hospitals and doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, the new executives do not plan to
abandon drkoop.com's audience of about 700,000 consumers, despite
the stock market's recent backlash against consumer-oriented
Internet ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that was God's greatest gift six to nine months ago
is not man's greatest evil today,'' said Edward Cespedes, the
venture capitalist who has taken over as president of drkoop.com.
``This is a very lucrative audience that we serve. And quite
frankly, the content on drkoop is better than other content.''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts have warned that drkoop.com needs a new focus _ and
fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a magazine; they were a publication delivering on
the Web,'' said Eric Brown, who follows online health companie--
for Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``To just have another
go at it is not going to cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, investors gave drkoop.com stock a slight boost to $1.13
a share, up 13 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The group of firms investing in the company now includes Eco
Associates, the Austin venture fund that is pledging money to
distressed dot-coms. Two weeks ago, Eco took control of local
Internet retail site mall.com Inc. and promptly laid off half of
the staff. Scott Hyten, founding partner of Eco, will take a seat
on drkoop.com's revamped eight-person board of directors, which
will include six new members.
</P>
<P>
   The new management is still evaluating the company's expenses,
which might mean cutting back on the company's 130-person
workforce, Cespedes said. It expects to reduce costs to between $1
million and $1.3 million a month this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went through $100 million in nine months. That's
obviously what went wrong,'' Cespedes said. ``If we weren't going
to deliver on improved financial performance we wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, drkoop.com has laid off employees, cut back on
marketing and renegotiated costly agreements with Internet portals
America Online and Go.com, reducing its cash burn rate from $18.6
million in the first quarter to an estimated $6.5 million in cash
this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's too late at all,'' Hyten said. ``Drkoop
traditionally has bled cash profusely. They've now suddenly focused
on the fact that they can, in fact, break even and generate cash
short-term. That was something they didn't even try to do months
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyten said he is particularly hopeful about the company's plans
with Shared Medical, its biggest potential business-to-business
revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Drkoop.com) spent most of its efforts on creating the
consumer experience and not that much on the business-to-business,
so it's a huge move for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cespedes, new chief executive Richard Rosenblatt and new chief
financial officer Stephen Plutsky joined drkoop.com from Prime
Ventures, a firm they ran in Santa Monica, Calif. Prime has now put
up $6 million for drkoop.com and all three men have signed
three-year employment agreements, Cespedes said.
</P>
<P>
   Email: apark(at)statesman.com or 912-5933.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
