Internet ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that was God's greatest gift six to nine months ago
is not man's greatest evil today,'' said Edward Cespedes, the
venture capitalist who has taken over as president of drkoop.com.
``This is a very lucrative audience that we serve. And quite
frankly, the content on drkoop is better than other content.''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts have warned that drkoop.com needs a new focus _ and
fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a magazine; they were a publication delivering on
the Web,'' said Eric Brown, who follows online health companie--
for Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``To just have another
go at it is not going to cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, investors gave drkoop.com stock a slight boost to $1.13
a share, up 13 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The group of firms investing in the company now includes Eco
Associates, the Austin venture fund that is pledging money to
distressed dot-coms. Two weeks ago, Eco took control of local
Internet retail site mall.com Inc. and promptly laid off half of
the staff. Scott Hyten, founding partner of Eco, will take a seat
