<SLUG> BC-MITSUBISHI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITSUBISHI SHARES DROP AFTER POLICE RAID HEADQUARTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKI TANIKAWA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Shares of the Mitsubishi Motors Corp. tumbled on Monday,
as speculation mounted that the company's president would resign
after the Tokyo police raided its corporate headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mitsubishi Motors denied that the president,
Katsuhiko Kawasoe, would resign to take responsibility for a
scandal that erupted last week when the company admitted that it
had covered up customer complaints and auto defects for more than
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Still, shares of Mitsubishi fell more than 12 percent in trading
here _ its sharpest decline since March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, investigators from the Tokyo Metropolitan Police
searched the company's headquarters and factories, as well as homes
of executives. They retrieved piles of conference minutes, floppy
disks and other materials. It was the first such search since Japan
introduced its current law on automotive recalls in 1969. The
police had been expected to act on a complaint from the Ministry of
Transportation, which was due early next month, but they did not
wait.
</P>
<P>
   For 23 years, Mitsubishi Motors had hid the bulk of its
documents on customer complaints from the sight of the regulators
who routinely visited the company for on-site inspections. In 1992,
the auto maker incorporated the cover-up process into its computer
system, maintaining a dual set of records on customer complaints:
those to be reported to the authorities and those to be hidden.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on Monday, the company president, Kawasoe,
expressed his ``deepest apologies'' for the trouble his company
caused customers and other parties involved. ``I shall personally
assume full responsibility for doing everything necessary to regain
the trust and confidence of customers and all who have dealings
with the company,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The leading financial daily, Nihon Keizai Shimbun, reported
Monday that the chief executives of Mitsubishi Heavy Industries,
Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi and Mitsubishi Corp. had met with Kawasoe,
and that he had expressed his willingness to resign to take
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meeting was held so that Mitsubishi Motors could report
about the affair'' to Mitsubishi companies, said Wataru Ichikawa,
public relations manger at Mitsubishi Heavy Industries. He declined
to discuss the content of the talk.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Mitsubishi group companies were concerned
that the scandal might taint the Mitsubishi name and began to sense
a need for a measure such as the resignation of the company's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from serving as major stock holders, the leading
Mitsubishi companies carry a strong voice in the decision making of
other companies in the group.
</P>
</TEXT>
