<HEADER>
A4635 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-POWERTEL0829-COX     08-28 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERTEL0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Powertel to fill a gap in VoiceStream coverage
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - In agreeing to be purchased for $7.1 billion, Powertel
of West Point, Ga., will fill a critical gap for VoiceStream
Wireless and its soon-to-be corporate parent, Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement announced late Sunday _ worth $5.9 billion in
stock and $1.2 million in debt _ is meant to be completed as soon
as the German telecom giant consummates its $50 billion acquisition
of VoiceStream. Should that purchase be blocked by regulators,
VoiceStream is committed to buying Powertel with its own stock.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, intended to close next year, will replace
Powertel with the VoiceStream brand and give VoiceStream licenses
serving nearly 90 percent of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will compete effectively with the national
players,'' said Allen E. Smith, Powertel president and chief
executive officer on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite years of public disclaimers by both VoiceStream and
Powertel, the companies came to see a marriage of some kind as
virtually inevitable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone thought it was very logical that we try to do
a deal,'' Smith said. ``We were making our numbers. However, there
are a lot of investment dollars that are seeking a national and,
therefore, a global player. Telecom is going global.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Powertel launched service in 1996, phone use has become
increasingly common and users _ especially mobile professionals and
executives _ have come to demand that their service follow them
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The twist is _ this one deal will kick over two dominoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was clearly inevitable,'' said Richard Prentiss, analyst
at Raymond James. ``We saw wireless moving from local to regional
to national to international, and it really is playing out nicely
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, Powertel and VoiceStream will have licenses to offer
service to nearly 90 percent of the United States. Powertel's
12-state coverage includes some of the fastest-growing markets in
the country and has virtually no overlap with VoiceStream. But the
two companies do share the same technology, known as GSM, which is
also used by European carriers like Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   While Powertel has fewer customers, it is ahead of VoiceStream
in making its business profitable and in its penetration of its
markets.
</P>
<P>
   That equation has made Powertel a takeover target for months.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the stock closed at $81.06, down $5.56, after spiking
to close at $86.62 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts chalked up the difference between the stock price and
the potential payoff from Deutsche Telekom to doubt _ about how
long it will take to pass regulatory review, about whether the deal
will be stymied altogether.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Smith said every investor he had heard from was
pleased.
</P>
<P>
   But when official news about the deal was released, at least
some ostensible Powertel shareholders on Internet message boards
derided the company for selling itself too cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement now calls for each Powertel share to be traded for
2.6353 shares of Deutsche Telekom, a setup that values Powertel at
about $106 a share.
</P>
<P>
   But since Deutsche Telekom stock is trading near its 52-week
low, a rebound is possible or even likely.
</P>
<P>
   When Deutsche Telekom shares bounce back, the value of the deal
to Powertel shareholders will too, Prentiss said. ``If it gets to
even $50 a share, that is $131 a share for Powertel.''
</P>
<P>
   But then again, maybe Deutsche Telekom is overspending.
</P>
<P>
   Even adding Powertel's 727,000 subscribers, VoiceStream will
boast a mere 3.3 million subscribers compared with AT&AMP;T with 13
million, the planned SBC-BellSouth alliance with 17 million and
Verizon with 26 million.
</P>
<P>
   To catch up to the leaders will require billions of dollars of
investment in equipment and marketing. Moreover, VoiceStream still
doesn't have a complete national presence and will need to buy more
licenses _ or smaller wireless carriers _ in the Carolinas and
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are way behind,'' said Andrew Cole, head of the global
wireless practice at Renaissance Strategy. ``But they will have a
nationwide network, and GSM is a great technology.''
</P>
<P>
   In Powertel's favor is the logic of the newcomer. Companies like
BellSouth and Verizon, which incorporates the former AirTouch, have
been in business since the early 1980s and enjoy a far larger
customer base. But analysts say Powertel's aggressive marketing _
which has undercut other carriers' prices and introduced new
features _ has made it one of the leaders in scooping up new
wireless users.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates for that ``incremental market share'' range as high as
25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. wireless use has already surged past 80 million
subscribers, according to the Cellular Telecommunications Industry
Association. But industry analysts _ and the executives at Deutsche
Telekom _ believe that the wireless industry is morphing to a new
model, making the first wave of carriers vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   In the new wireless world, the devices will become conduits more
for data than voice.
</P>
<P>
   Users will commonly use them as electronic wallets to make
purchases, as communication modules sending and receiving e-mail,
as Internet connections linking to stocks, sports and news, and,
perhaps, as agents that link them to their home appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the spread of wireless phones for conversation, the
United States lags Europe by about a year, Cole said. ``The market
in the United States is still fairly immature.''
</P>
<P>
   As wireless changes toward data, carriers that do not have scale
will have trouble competing, Cole said. ``There will be four or
five major players in the U.S. They will be the fifth player for
some time.''
</P>
<P>
   But even that will take some rapid expansion. After the merger
with Powertel, VoiceStream will still lag not only Verizon,
BellSouth-SBC and AT&AMP;T, but also Alltel and Nextel.
</P>
<P>
   Still, deep pockets can make all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Walter, analyst with Robinson-Humphrey, said the company
will emerge ready to battle the big players. ``They're going to
have $5 billion from Deutsche Telekom to improve the network, and
Powertel has a lot of cash on their balance sheet,'' he said.
``They can compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom's acquisition of VoiceStream is far from
assured. The company faces congressional resistance, led by Sen.
Ernest Hollings (D-S.C.). That opposition focuses on the
still-majority stake held by the German government in Deutsche
Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream Chairman John Stanton said Monday that he believes
the deal will make the wireless markets more competitive by giving
added muscle to a smaller player. While acknowledging Hollings, he
said he is more worried about the members of Congress who hold key
leadership posts, like Trent Lott (R-Miss.).
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Hollings) is one member who has a strong view,'' Stanton
said. ``We are working with Sen. Lott and we are working with other
members, but we are not concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
