<HEADER>
A4637 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-1STLD-WR     08-28 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASTERT OFFERS KEY CONCESSIONS ON RAISING MINIMUM WAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Updates and expands throughout; now two takes and coded for
front page.)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT and LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Dennis Hastert on Monday offered key
concessions to Democrats on a plan to raise the federal minimum
wage, moving to end months of stalemate on a popular bill that
Republicans feared could damage them at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate earlier this year approved an increase in
the minimum wage by $1, to $6.15 an hour, with the increase coming
in 50-cent increments over two years in the House version and
smaller annual amounts over three years in the Senate bill. The
conflicting bills then stalled in the conference committee that was
supposed to reconcile them, raising fears among some Republicans
that they they were handing Democrats a potent campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Monday, Hastert sought to take that threat off the
table. He proposed that the committee would agree to the Democrats'
demands to spread the $1 increase over two years but continued to
insist that the compromise measure must include $76 billion in tax
cuts for small business over 10 years to help these companies pay
``the costs of this wage increase.''
</P>
<P>
   In another concession, Hastert proposed dropping pension
provisions and a repeal of the estate tax attached to the bill by
House Republicans and that Democrats had criticized as a giveaway
to wealthy Americans. Both of these provisions, however, have moved
through the Congress on separate tracks and now must be dealt with
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very clear that a vast majority of congressional
Democrats and Republicans would like to see a balanced approach
before we adjourn,'' said Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's proposal makes the minimum wage, in effect, the
opening issue among Democrats and Republicans in Congress when they
return next week from their late summer recess.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials expressed cautious optimism that the
Republican-controlled Congress and the Clinton administration could
strike a deal in the next month to raise the minimum wage for the
first time since 1996. Officials signaled that the Republican
insistence on the small business tax cuts would not be a deal
breaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``If at long last the Republicans are serious about dropping
many of their roadblocks to a $1 increase over two years, then
that's good news,'' Gene Sperling, head of the White House's
National Economic Council, said in an interview. ``There still
remain some obstacles, but the president stands ready to work in
good faith with Congress to get a bill he can sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's letter reflects his desire to position House
Republicans for the legislative endgame with Clinton, and to turn a
political liability into a virtue in time for the fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative for the minimum wage offer came from Hastert and
reflects how House Republicans feel more politically vulnerable on
the issue than their Senate counterparts. Hastert said that Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott shared his views, but only the speaker
signed the letter.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lott, John Czwartacki, said he had not seen
Hastert's letter but added, ``Senator Lott supports moving the
minimum wage increase as long as it's tied to small business tax
relief. Politics is the art of compromise.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that Hastert is seeking to secure his
legislative gains for the bruising fall elections, the speaker is
also paring back on the tax-cut proposals that he will press for,
cuts for married couples and retirement savings.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's offer comes just a few days after Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, the Republican nominee for president, found himself
defending his proposed tax cut, and admitting that he needed to do
a better job of promoting it.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats greeted Hastert's offer cautiously, and
seemed tempted to milk even more political mileage out his
political predicament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal that the speaker made was in the right
direction,'' said Rep. David Bonior of Michigan, the second-ranking
House Democrat and a sponsor with Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of
Massachusetts of the Democrats' original $1-over-two-years bill.
``It raises the question of whether 50 cents a year is enough or
whether we want to do 50 cents a year over three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are high on the tax relief side and low on the benefit to
minimum-wage workers,'' Bonior added, ``but it is my view that we
can work this out and we can get a bill by sometime next month.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonior noted that the current minimum wage, $5.15 an hour, has
lost purchasing power in the more than two years since since he and
Kennedy first asked Congress for the additional $1 increase.
</P>
<P>
   The $5.15 would have to rise by 24 cents to restore its 1998
purchasing power, according to an estimate furnished by Jared
Bernstein, a labor economist at the Economic Policy Institute. The
minimum wage reached its greatest purchasing power in 1968 when it
was worth the equivalent of $7.49 in 1999 dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hastert beat them to the punch, going public with the
Republican proposal, the Democrats had been discussing a revision
of their original bill, one that would increase the minimum wage by
more than $1.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's proposal of a $76 billion tax cut for small business
drew criticism from Bonior, who said that it was almost four times
greater than the $20 billion in tax relief that the Republicans had
sought in 1996, the last time Congress approved a minimum wage
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican proposal would also remove from minimum wage
coverage some workers now covered by the law, including some
``computer professionals'' and funeral home workers.
</P>
<P>
   ''After three years of foot-dragging, Republicans appear ready
to sign on to a wage increase for the lowest paid workers,''
Kennedy said in a statement. ``But their proposal is loaded with
poison pills and oversized tax breaks for the wealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some House Republicans, however, criticized Hastert for
compromising at all. ``I've never been in favor of bargaining on
the minimum wage,'' said Rep. John Shadegg, R-Ariz., who voted
against the wage increase in March. ``The package does not give
businesses anywhere near the relief they're going to need.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address on July 29, just before the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, Clinton appealed to
Republicans to break the impasse on the minimum wage increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Republican leaders really want to make their compassion
count, they ought to join me in getting back to business and
raising the minimum wage,'' Clinton said. ''I hope the majority
will join the Democrats to seize this moment, to stop the delays,
to work with me to help our working families.''
</P>
<P>
   An increase in the minimum wage, to $6.15 an hour, would affect
10.1 million workers who now earn between $5.15 an hour and $6.14,
and millions more who earn up to $6.70 an hour and would enjoy
raises to maintain their margin over the new minimum wage,
economists say.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the 10.1 million directly affected workers are
over age 20, often a family's principal earners, while one-third
are teen-agers. When Congress voted in 1996 to raise the minimum in
two annual steps, to $5.15 an hour on Sept. 1, 1997, from $4.25,
there was much concern that millions of low wage workers would lose
their jobs because they lacked enough skills to justify higher pay.
</P>
<P>
   But the increases came just as the economy began to boom, and
the unemployment rate, instead of rising, fell steadily. Now, the
concern over job loss is muted, the argument being that the strong
economy is raising the pay of low-skilled workers anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The modest proposal people are talking about _ $1 over two
years _ is pretty close to what would happen anyway in the
marketplace,'' said Kevin Murphy, a labor economist at the
University of Chicago, who had argued in 1996 that the proposed
increase in the minimum wage, to $5.15 an hour, would cost jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said the
Texas governor supported a $1-an-hour increase in the minimum wage
although he did not know if Bush supported the specific details in
the compromises being discussed by Hastert and the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush approves a dollar increase in the minimum wage
with flexibility for the states so that entry level workers are not
priced out of the market,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
