<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ART-700(2TAKES)-     08-28 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, IN ATTACK ON DRUG INDUSTRY, FOCUSES ON 2 COMPANIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Ore., Wash.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Vice President Al Gore Monday escalated his
attacks against the pharmaceutical industry, criticizing two drug
companies by name and calling for greater competition in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The drug industry has long been one of Gore's corporate
bogeymen, along with oil, tobacco and insurance. But in Monday's
speech to a forum of elderly people on the campus of Florida State
University, Gore expanded his criticism, saying he would veto any
legislation that would extend monopoly patents for prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore singled out for criticism the manufacturers of two
medications: the Schering-Plough Corp., which makes Claritin, and
the American Home Products Corp., the parent company of
Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories, which makes Lodine. In the case of
Claritin, he said the manufacturer spent more money on advertising
than on research. And in the case of Lodine, an arthritis medicine
prescribed for both people and pets, he said American Home Products
charged pharmacies more than veterinarians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for them making profits and having more research and
whatnot,'' Gore said. ``But I'm not going to stand by if they
behave in an unfair way.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's trip was Gore's second to Florida in less than a week,
underscoring the importance his campaign places on the state and
its 25 electoral votes. The governor here is Jeb Bush, the brother
of Gore's Republican rival, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, and Gore
was greeted by taunts from a larger-than-usual collection of Bush
supporters when he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic nominee's address kicked off a four-day,
four-state trip that Gore is devoting to health care policy, an
issue on which Gore feels he has an advantage over Bush. He also
plans to highlight his proposals for a patients' bill of rights,
expanded health care coverage for children, the solvency of
Medicare and investments in medical research at stops in New
Mexico, Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But the centerpiece of Gore's health care program is his
proposal for a voluntary Medicare benefit that would provide
prescription drug coverage for the elderly. About 13 million
Medicare beneficiaries have no drug coverage, while many others pay
expensive premiums through Medigap plans, Gore aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gore's plan, seniors with no coverage who have incomes of
135 percent of the poverty level or below, about $12,000 for an
individual and $14,000 for a couple, would have their drugs covered
without cost.
</P>
<P>
   Those with higher incomes would pay a premium, on a sliding
scale, and would be reimbursed half of the cost of their
prescriptions up to a total of $5,000. After Medicare recipients
paid $4,000 out of pocket for prescriptions, the government would
pay all remaining costs. The Gore campaign estimates the cost of
the proposal at $253 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is complicated, and Gore misstated some of the details
while explaining it to his audience Monday. But his larger points
were clear: He has a detailed plan, while Bush, does not; his plan
would be affordable within a balanced budget, while Bush, he says,
cannot afford a comprehensive plan because of the size of his
income tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has yet to propose a specific plan, but his aides say that
he would build on the proposal of a bipartisan congressional
commission that would seek to spur competition between public and
private plans for Medicare recipients, giving consumers a choice of
public and private plans, some of which would provide a drug
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has said he supports a sliding prescription drug
subsidy for the low-income elderly, but would leave the amounts to
be determined in negotiations with Congress. Gore said Monday that
``the insurance companies have said they will not offer such
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's focus on prescription drugs Monday coincided with the
release of a television advertisement on the topic by the
Democratic National Committee. Both the Bush campaign and the
Republican National Committee began broadcasting ads on
prescription drugs last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic ad, which will appear in eight states, charges
Bush with ``siding with the big drug companies.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Gore's main target Monday was the drug companies. He
described an industry that kept prices artificially high while its
patents remained in effect, forcing seniors to choose between
prescriptions and sometimes between prescriptions and food.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just wrong,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   He also accused Schering-Plough of spending more on advertising
than on research.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the Wall Street Journal, they spend more money
every year advertising Claritin and promoting Claritin than
Coca-Cola spends to advertise and promote Coca-Cola,'' Gore said.
``So if they're using these profits more for that than for research
and if a lot of the most valuable research is being paid for by the
taxpayers anyway, then I believe that we need more competition.''
</P>
<P>
   To force that competition, Gore said, he would veto all patent
extension legislation that would benefit drug companies.
Schering-Plough is seeking such an extension for Claritin, whose
patents begin to expire in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   William O'Donnell, a spokesman for Schering-Plough, said, ``The
pharmaceutical industry is responsible for breakthrough discoveries
that make invaluable contributions to the nation's health care
system. The real issue in the United States is the fact that a
significant portion of our population lacks prescription drug
coverage. Schering-Plough believes that all Americans should be
provided with access to drug coverage through private sector
mechanisms, without resorting to government price controls, which
history has proven simply do not work.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, denounced
Gore's proposals as a ``nationalized drug plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is similar to Hillary Clinton's attempt to nationalize
health care in 1993,'' Bartlett said. ``Al Gore is fully embracing
the old-style, government-knows-best approach that the American
people soundly rejected when Hillary Clinton tried it in 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also accused American Home Products, which markets the drug
Lodine, sets significantly lower prices for veterinarians than for
pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it costs $108 a month for a person, it costs $37.80 for
a dog,'' he said. A spokesman for American Home Products declined
to comment.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
