<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4646 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-SCANNERS0829-COX     08-28 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCANNERS0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bar codes give new Web link
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - In the beginning, magazines and newspapers ran stories
about the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Then they printed Web addresses along with their ads and
stories. Readers could carry the paper to their computers and peck
in the addresses to find more on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Now, media companies have begun their first mass tests of direct
print-to-Web connections using scanners and bar codes.
</P>
<P>
   Readers sitting at their computers can use special scanners to
swipe bar codes in magazine or newspaper ads or stories and jump
directly to related Web sites. Publishers hope the technology will
help them increase advertising revenue and satisfy increasingly
Internet-dependent, time-crunched subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, will enough readers and advertisers use it to
make it worthwhile?
</P>
<P>
   Both Forbes magazine and electronics retailer RadioShack have
just begun distributing more than 3 million hand-held scanners for
free.
</P>
<P>
   The scanners, called :Cue:C.A.T.s and resembling a computer
mouse, can be connected to computers, then swiped across special
bar codes to log on to related Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to create a shortcut between Web sites and printed
content. Readers no longer would have to wander through several Web
pages or type lengthy Internet addresses to reach specific pages
deep within a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies have proposed competing technologies for the
scanners. Charleston, S.C.-based GoCode, providing its technology
for free to 1,000 subscribers of The Post and Courier newspaper in
Charleston, uses a pen-shaped scanner that costs $75 to produce,
with a version planned later this year at a third the price.
</P>
<P>
   But the :Cue:C.A.T., a product made by Dallas-based
Digital:Convergence, is apparently the first that is cheap enough
to mass produce and distribute for free. The company is providing
them free to certain partner companies, which then are distributing
them to the public or subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Digital:Convergence declined to say how much the scanners cost
to manufacture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge, I think, is just getting it in people's hands
and getting them swiping,'' said Peter Eschbach, a spokesman for
Digital:Convergence.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to make money by licensing the technology to
media outlets and other companies. The media companies hope to
attract more advertisers and possibly charge more to run ads that
have the special bar codes of Digital:Convergence. (The scanners
also can jump to some Internet sites reading more traditional bar
codes found on groceries, CDs and other items.)
</P>
<P>
   RadioShack has begun distributing at least 2.5 million of the
scanners at more than 7,000 stores nationally. The electronics
retailer's 2001 catalogs include special bar codes that, when
scanned, connect directly to Internet pages where the products can
be purchased online.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' 850,000 subscribers began receiving free :Cue:C.A.T.'s
Friday in time for them to scan bar codes alongside ads and stories
in the magazine's Sept. 11 edition. A listing of ``Forbes
Favorite'' Web sites includes scannable bar codes that connect with
winning sites. The magazine plans to use bar codes in its future
editions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it gets people to Web sites they want to visit faster and
easier, then it is a success,'' said Ray Healey Jr., the magazine's
vice president of editorial information. ``One question will be how
many of them actually hook them (the scanners) up and start to zip
to advertising Web sites or editorial Web sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes isn't the only publication tying in with the scanning
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Wired magazine is distributing the scanners free to its more
than 400,000 subscribers starting late next month. The Dallas
Morning News is involved in plans to send out several hundred
thousand scanners free to homes in metro Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Other publications aren't giving away scanners but are including
ads and stories featuring special bar codes in upcoming editions.
Among the participants is Parade magazine, which will include
special bar codes in its Sept. 10 edition. Parade is inserted in
the Sunday editions of many U.S. newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with competing scanner technologies are hoping the
:Cue:C.A.T.'s mass distribution won't create an insurmountable
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola is part of one rival venture in the works. Digimarc,
another competitor, uses scannable marks that can be read by
certain Web cameras. The technology was incorporated in ads running
in recent editions of Wired magazine and Popular Mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   At GoCode in South Carolina, Marketing Vice President Prioleau
Alexander said his company won't follow Digital:Convergence's lead
and send scanners to people who haven't asked for them. ``We don't
want our hardware to end up in somebody's garbage can.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company has given scanners to about 1,000 people _
some selected by the company and others who requested it _ in the
Charleston area and plans to begin distributing scanners to another
4,000 people in Colorado Springs, Colo., where it has struck a deal
with a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   At The Post and Courier, which is using the GoCode technology,
executives are trying to craft a business plan to profit from the
device.
</P>
<P>
   So far the newspaper isn't charging advertisers more for using
the bar code, Assistant Publisher Larry Tarleton said. But he said
that might be an option in the future. Another is charging extra
for classified ads with the GoCode bar code, which is about the
size of George Washington's ponytail on a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper is also contemplating how to get the scanners into
the hands of more readers. Tarleton said options include charging
subscribers more to receive scanners or giving them away free for
subscribers who sign up for a year or more of service.
</P>
<P>
   But Tarleton said the new Web connection won't draw hordes of
new readers to his newspaper's printed page.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone is going to want to have the technology,'' he
said. ``A lot of people are not going to be interested in the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
