u a BC-PUMICE-MINE-NYT &LR;      08-28 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUMICE-MINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT REACHED TO CLOSE PUMICE MINE ON SACRED INDIAN PEAK 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ It's a long way from the catwalks of Paris to
the craggy forests of the San Francisco Peaks, but the two have
been linked for more than a decade by the demand for stonewashed
denim: new jeans made to look old by laundering them with pieces of
volcanic pumice.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the pumice came from a strip mine on Sugarloaf Mountain,
one of the Peaks, twelve miles northeast of here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were rated as the No. 1 supplier to the industry back in
the mid-1990s,'' said Ed Morgan, vice president of Arizona
Tufflite, the Phoenix company that owns the mine. Morgan estimated
sales by his company at $25 million to $30 million over the last 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pumice washed jeans went all over the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For just as many years, the Sierra Club and 13 American Indian
tribes have been trying to limit the company's mining, saying that
it damages the environment of the Peaks, which the Indians believe
are sacred ground.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, they succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   On a rocky outcrop overlooking Tufflite's 100-foot deep White
Vulcan Pumice mine, federal officials and the company signed an
agreement to close the 90-acre site within six months.
</P>
<P>
   That was welcome news for the Hopi tribe, which believes that
the Peaks are the home of kachina spirits who live part of the year
as clouds in the mountains, and bring rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people have believed these things for thousands of
years,'' said Wayne Taylor, chairman of the Hopi tribe.
</P>
<P>
   For the Navaho, the mountains are one of four borders to their
universe.
</P>
<P>
   Just as galling as the desecration of the land, Indian
representatives said, was the purpose for the mining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Further destruction of the countryside in this Sacred area
just so the fashion conscious can wear jeans which make them seem
to have spent time outside, is to us, ludicrous,'' wrote one tribal
leader to the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have to work to get that look,'' complained Andrew
Bessler, an organizer for the Sierra Club who runs the group's
`Save The Peaks' effort linking the Indian tribes with
environmentalists. ``Besides, stonewashing takes two years out of
the life of the jeans, and that's why the industry likes it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Tufflite applied for a permit to expand their operations in
1998, the Indian' and Sierra Club's public relations campaign
against the mine went into overdrive with concerts, demonstrations
at the mine site, and relentless pressuring of state, local, and
federal public officials.
</P>
<P>
   All thirteen tribes passed resolutions opposing the mine, as did
the city of Flagstaff and Coconino County, where it is located. Of
6,000 public comments received by the Forest Service on the
expansion project, only four favored it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased that this mine is being shut down and this long
controversy is ending. It's time to restore the Peaks to their
natural splendor,'' said Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt in a
statement released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the government will pay Tufflite $1 million
and drop a lawsuit that demanded $300,000 in unpaid royalties for
previous sales of the pumice. In return, the company will shut down
the mine, which has just four employees, but will be able to sell
extracted pumice for the next ten years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great victory,' says Bessler. ``It will protect a
key cultural and archeological site from the continued desecration
of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   To Morgan, the mine closure is just a relief.
</P>
<P>
   After all these years of fighting, we decided that the
government was going to make it harder and harder to do business,''
he said. ``We were paying our lawyers, plus paying our taxes which
paid the government's lawyers, and in the end it just didn't make
sense to keep going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also believes the best years of using pumice to stonewash
denim are behind Tufflite anyway. ``They've got new techniques now
that use enzymes that are biodegradable and cheaper. Our market was
declining,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Indian tribes, at least one tribal chairman saw some
significance in an unusual event that occurred in these
drought-stricken mountains just minutes after the closure agreement
was signed:
</P>
<P>
   It rained.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the spirits way of thanking us,'' said Taylor.
</P>
</TEXT>
