<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   By their own admission, the Dallas Cowboys broke summer camp
with no one who could replace Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys drafted three cornerbacks, hoping one or two might
become suitable replacements. Six days before the season opener,
the Cowboys made another move to strengthen the position.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Giants cornerback Phillippi Sparks signed with
the Cowboys on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Sparks on the 53-man roster, the Cowboys
released veteran linebacker Chris Bordano.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Ryan McNeil and fourth-round rookie Kareem Larrimore
will be the starting corners when the season opens Sunday at Texas
Stadium against Philadelphia. Sparks will play in nickel situations
and could replace Larrimore as a starter if the rookie has early
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, 31, played eight seasons with the Giants after being
drafted from Arizona State in 1992. After the 1999 season, he told
friends he would retire, and was not part of any team's roster in
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks intercepted 22 passes with the Giants, one last season. A
physical player, Sparks recorded at least 50 tackles in each of the
last five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have not been impressed with their cornerbacks after
Sanders moved to Washington and Kevin Smith retired. McNeil,
formerly with St. Louis and Cleveland, has been the most effective
newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore outplayed rookie teammates Dwayne Goodrich and Mario
Edwards in camp. Goodrich and Edwards have missed the last three
weeks with assorted injuries. Veteran Charlie Williams has not
played since having arthroscopic knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Email: rcantu(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
