</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ATTICA-SETTLEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL CHAPTER IN ATTICA UPRISING: SETTLEMENT DIVISION CAPS LONG
LEGAL BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story will be expanded) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ Declaring that the inmates who were beaten and
tortured during the 1971 Attica prison uprising were
``dehumanized'' and treated ``like garbage,'' a federal judge
divided up an $8 million settlement on Monday to compensate more
than 500 inmates and relatives for the abuse prisoners suffered at
the hands of the state police.
</P>
<P>
   The allotment of the landmark settlement caps one of the longest
and most ignominious chapters in American criminal justice history,
fleshing out a deal reached in January between New York State and
lawyers representing 1,281 former inmates.
</P>
<P>
   At more than 200 pages, the settlement filed on Monday reads
like a harrowing encyclopedia of personal anecdotes, incorporating
months of testimony from nearly 200 former inmates who stood before
U.S. District Judge Michael Telesca here and recounted how the
uprising and siege at the western New York prison left 43 people
dead, 80 wounded and countless more scarred psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   The awards, which range from $6,500 to $125,000 per former
inmate, were ``modest,'' according to Telesca's decision. And many
of the inmates and their lawyers, agreed, adding that no amount of
money could compensate them or resolve an episode that has become a
dubious symbol of prison life and state-sanctioned brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because it is history does not mean it is all in the
past,'' Telesca wrote. ``Indeed, Attica is the ghost that has never
stopped haunting its survivors _ both the inmates and the families
of the deceased guards and prison personnel. But at least the
settlement of this case provides the basis for the former inmates
to close the book on the past and to focus on the future.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the judge devoted the bulk of his decision to
short but powerful summaries of each inmate's experience.
</P>
<P>
   Frank B.B. Smith, for instance, was stripped naked, pelted with
hot and spent shell casings and threatened with castration, during
the uprising. He was awarded $125,000 _ the highest amount.
</P>
<P>
   For George ``Che'' Nieves, Attica was primarily a nightmare of
the mind. Like so many others, he was punched, beaten and forced to
crawl in the mud. But what still unsettles him is the memory of a
guard drawing a giant ``X'' on his back as if marking him as a
target in what one state prosecutor described as a ``turkey
shoot.'' He received $6,500 _ the lowest amount.
</P>
<P>
   For Josh Melville, Attica was simply the haunted place where his
father, Samuel, was fatally shot. So he traveled from Florida to
Rochester to introduce a forensic ballistic report and photos to
bolster his claim that his father was murdered. He was awarded
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   There was no celebration following Monday's settlement order.
Smith was the only former inmate who attended a news conference
organized by several of the former inmates' lawyers _ and that is
because he now works as a paralegal with Elizabeth Fink, the
principal lawyer, on prisoners' rights cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the money; money would not compensate if it was
$125 million,'' Smith said. ``I want everybody to concentrate,
everybody, on what happened at Attica and how we can prevent
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
