<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-SUIT-N     08-28 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET MUSIC COMPANY CEO DEFENDS COMPANY AS RESPECTING
COPYRIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The head of MP3.com, the internet music company, told
a federal judge in Manhattan Monday that he believed he was acting
legally when he created a Web-based database of thousands of
copyrighted record albums.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com is facing potentially hundreds of millions of dollars in
damages for copyright violations.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony from MP3.com's chief executive, Michael Robertson,
marked the first day of hearings in a trial pitting the San
Diego-based startup against Seagram Co.'s Universal Music Group,
the world's largest record company, after negotiations this weekend
failed to produce a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the case already has ruled that MP3.com infringed
Universal's copyrights, but the size of the damages in the case
will depend on whether the court determines the action was
``willful.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal and four other major record companies sued MP3.com in
January, but the other companies have since settled. In the
original suit, the companies asserted the MP3.com violated their
copyrights with the creation of the service called My.Mp3.com.
</P>
<P>
   The service created an ``online locker,'' permitting users to
store their music albums centrally on MP3.com's computers, then get
access to them through various digital devices, such as computers,
or portable music players.
</P>
<P>
   To make the service easy to use, MP3.com did not require users
to load their own music into the virtual lockers. Rather, a user
had merely to insert a copy of the music into the CD-ROM drive of a
computer, at which point, MP3.com would verify that the person had
possession of a CD, then the company would automatically put a copy
of the music into the person's virtual locker.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com amassed 65,000 albums to create the database from which
it drew its music.
</P>
<P>
   However, the lawsuit by the record companies asserted the
MP3.com had violated copyrights by creating the digital database of
albums to which they held the copyrights. In April, U.S. District
Judge Jed Rakoff ruled that MP3.com had infringed companies'
copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing months, MP3.com reached settlements with four of
the record companies, including Sony Music, Time Warner, EMI Group
and Bertelsmann. Details of the settlements were not made public,
but analysts estimated the company paid $20 million to each
company.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Scheier, an industry analyst with Forrester Research,
speculated that Universal has not yet settled for two possible
reasons: as the biggest record company it wants a larger
settlement; or because it has intentions to launch a competing
service with My.Mp3.com and does not want to license its music
content to MP3.com, a condition of the MP3.com's settlement with
the other record companies.
</P>
<P>
   Universal may not want to license music to ``MP3.com or more
generally to anybody they don't feel they can control or express a
lot of authority over about what kind of business models are going
to be used,'' Scheier said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Universal Music Group declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Universal is an investor in MusicBank, a company that has said
it plans to launch a virtual locker music business sometime in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's hearing, Robertson told the court he believed the
My.mp3.com service was respectful of the record companies'
copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing I had looked at suggested this was illegal use or a
copyright violation,'' he said, according to a report by the Dow
Jones news service.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing, which is scheduled to continue through Thursday,
will provide the basis for Rakoff to assess damages against
MP3.com. People close to the trial said that if the judge decides
the action was willful, MP3.com could face damage payments of
between $750 and $150,000 for each album infringed.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge finds the conduct not willful, the damages could
range from $750 to $30,000. People familiar with the case said that
MP3.com's database included roughly 10,000 albums with copyrights
owned by Universal.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com in May suspended the My.mp3.com service, which it said
had roughly 500,000 participants.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing comes as the music industry continues to fight on
other legal fronts, notably in its battle against Napster, a
popular service that permits individual users to exchange music
files online. It is a practice the music industry asserts amounts
the theft. The industry's case against Napster is being tried in
federal court in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
