<HEADER>
A4665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ABORTION-ART-N     08-28 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ABORTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEEMING VICTORY FOR ABORTION RIGHTS IN A MEXICAN STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Women's rights groups across Mexico celebrated a
victory Monday against resurgent efforts by conservative
politicians and church leaders who had sought to chip away at
already-limited rights to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The latest battle was fought in the central state of Guanajuato
where the legislature passed a bill this month that would have made
the state the only one in Mexico to extend the ban on abortions to
cases of rape.
</P>
<P>
   Word spread Monday that the governor would send the bill back to
the state congress for further study; the action amounts to a veto,
his aides said. The current legislature lacks enough votes to
overturn a veto. The governor, Ramon Martin Huerta, is to announce
the decision on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators of the conservative National Action Party narrowly
passed the measure, inciting furious protests across Mexico by
activists who worried that the measure would move Mexico a step
closer to making all abortions illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also provoked left-wing legislators in the local
government in the nation's capital to pass legislation that
expanded abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion laws differ from state to state in Mexico. But in all
31 states and the Federal District of Mexico City, abortion is
generally illegal except in cases of rape.
</P>
<P>
   Several other states also permit abortion when pregnancy puts
the mother's life at risk, when the fetus appears to suffer serious
malformations and when a woman has been artificially inseminated
without her knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   In the most liberal exception, women in the southern state of
Yucatan with at least three children can have legal abortions if
they are financially strapped.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the measure in Guanajuato say it was the most
alarming example of how the Roman Catholic Church and its
right-wing allies in the National Action Party, known as PAN, have
been politically energized by the election of Vicente Fox, a native
of that state and a Catholic; he becomes president on Mexico in
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day for all women in Mexico and a warning to
the PAN,'' said Veronica Cruz Sanchez, 29, who coordinated weeks of
protests that helped defeat the abortion measure. ``In just a few
months, they will hold the office of the presidency, and now it
should be clear that they cannot impose their will on the people.''
</P>
<P>
   While the overwhelming majority of Mexicans call themselves
Catholics, the intellectual and the middle class have historically
been guardedly secular in their politics. After the revolution at
the turn of the last century, the Mexican government passed some of
the toughest anti-church laws in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Religious schools were closed; foreign priests were deported;
church property was seized; and Mexican priests were prohibited
from voting or even wearing religious garb in public.
</P>
<P>
   Although the laws were not always strictly enforced, they served
to limit the Catholic Church's involvement in politics. Then in
1992, under the leadership of Mexican President Carlos Salinas, the
government amended the constitution to repeal those restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, said the church historian Martaelena Negrete, church
leaders have become increasingly outspoken and active.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks after Fox, a divorcee, was elected, a Catholic
newsletter, Nuevo Criterio, urged him to stand as a moral example
to the country and reconcile with his ex-wife or vow never to
remarry.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Cardinal Norberto Rivera condoned the actions of
two vandals who destroyed a drawing called La Patrona on display at
an exhibit in Guadalajara; it portrayed the Virgin of Guadalupe as
a naked blonde bombshell. Rivera called the drawing an insult to
Catholics and insisted that the church had to defend itself against
all forms of attack.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, formerly the governor of Guanajuato, has tried not to get
pulled into the political storm in his home state by restating
campaign pledges not to initiate any changes in the abortion laws
after he takes office, even though he opposes abortion. And, he
promised not to meddle in the decisions of state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   But those favoring looser restrictions on abortions called the
statements troubling doublespeak that emboldened the most
conservative sectors of the National Action Party. By refusing to
speak out for or against the proposals, they worry, conservative
forces within the PAN feel that they have tacit approval to
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the things that most worried us when Mr. Fox
was elected,'' said Susana Vidales, a spokeswoman for a
reproductive rights group called GIRE. ``Fox may have different
feelings than the ones expressed by the legislators in Guanajuato,
but we knew the most conservative sectors of his party would feel
that his triumph was theirs. And groups supported by the church
have been empowered.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the importance of the measure, a PAN legislator
who helped pass it said her party's ideology called for protecting
the lives of unborn children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that a woman who has been raped has suffered a
great trauma,'' said the legislator, Angelica Patricia Flores.
``What we are trying to prevent is that she suffer another one by
having an abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, newspapers have been filled with comments from
bishops and priests across the country in support of the measure.
In Mexico City on Sunday, as word began to leak that the governor
would not sign the measure, Rivera said during his homily: ``Even
in the case of a pregnancy that is the result of rape, we must ask
the woman to accept the mysterious designs of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Such comments have stirred furious reactions from women's rights
activists. And last week, the socially liberal mayor of Mexico City
signed legislation that legalized abortions in the capital in cases
where the mother's life was in danger and the fetus showed serious
malformations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely no one has indicated they are in favor of abortion,
much less as a family planning measure,'' said Mexico City Mayor
Rosario Robles of the Democratic Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fight is against death, against the deaths of thousands of
women,'' she said, referring to deaths resulting from abortions
performed by unlicensed and untrained practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   But Bishop Jose G. Martin Rabago, the bishop of Guanajuato's
industrial capital Leon, said in a recent interview: ``There has
been a new, clearer consciousness within the church that it has the
right to express itself. And so it has changed from a church that
was timid, even silent, to one that makes its opinions known.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
