<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4668 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-GOREPRESCRIPTIONS0829     08-28 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOREPRESCRIPTIONS0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore touts prescription drug plan as he campaigns in Florida
 &HT;    By Marcia Gelbart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ This week is health-care week for the Gore
campaign. And on Monday, returning to Florida's capital for the
second visit in six months, the vice president kicked it off with a
town-hall discussion of his plan for dealing with the high costs of
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida Gov. Jeb Bush wasn't about to concede the spotlight
on his home turf. So two hours before Air Force II touched down at
Tallahassee Regional Airport, Bush changed the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where has the vice president been on the issue of education?''
he asked, standing shoulder-to-shoulder with state regent Steve
Uhlfelder, a Democrat, and several Florida teachers, principals and
</P>
<P>
   other educators. Compare the education record of his brother,
the Texas governor, he urged, with 7 1/2 years of ``squandered
opportunities of Vice President Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   The George W. Bush camp hadn't planned a Florida campaign talk
on education this week. But that changed over the weekend, ``right
about when we found out the vice president was coming,'' Florida's
governor said.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential election is months away. Not even Labor Day has
passed. But the fight for Florida continues to heat up. There are
25 electoral votes at stake, nearly 10 percent of the total needed
to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is a state where I'm going to fight hard with
everything I've got right up to the night of the election. I'm not
taking a single state or single vote for granted, and I'm not
writing any state off,'' Gore said. ``I mean, there are probably a
few that are Republican, I'll have to admit, but Florida is not in
that category.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Gore is pinning his hopes on health care. Over the
weekend, Bush running-mate Dick Cheney conceded his team had no
detailed plan yet of how to pay for prescription drug benefits _ a
fact Gore revisited Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You deserve a detailed, adult, intelligent discussion,'' he
told 200 senior citizens who were bused from Tallahassee area
retirement communities to the forum at a Florida State University
building. ``When the other side gets around to proposing (one), you
can compare and contrast.''
</P>
<P>
   In an hour-long discussion, Gore praised the substantial
advancements in drug treatments in the past 20 years, but said the
problem now is how to make those treatments affordable, especially
for seniors on fixed incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed a voluntary prescription drug plan under
Medicare that would cover all drug costs for recipients with
incomes of about $12,000 a year. Medicare recipients making more
would have to cover half the cost of their drugs up to $5,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore believes that would help elderly patients such as
77-year-old Arthur Flatt. ``Every time we turn around, we get
sick,'' Flatt told Gore. With ailments including a bad heart, he
pays $225 a month for medications, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, unable to afford a full-time nurse, Flatt and his wife
also care for their 48-year-old son, George, who is 6-feet-2 and
severely disabled. With Gore's prescription drug plan, ``we'd have
more money to have somebody come in and help us, even one day a
week,'' Flatt said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Dixie, 74, told Gore that since she can't afford all the
medicine she needs, she takes some, but not others. No longer does
she get arthritis medicine. ``I think I can handle the pain,''
Dixie said, ``But there are a lot of people who can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also spoke from personal experience, talking about his
mother-in-law, who lives with his family. To treat her arthritis,
doctors prescribed a drug, lodine, that cost $108 a month, he said.
The same drug was prescribed for the family's 14-year-old black
Labrador at $38 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty bad when you have got to pretend to be a dog or
a cat to get a price break,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone at the town-hall style meeting was sold, though.
``It's one thing to say things; it's another to make them happen,''
said Karen Pinney, administrator at the Woodmont Assisted Living
Facility in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan would cost $253 billion over 10 years. ``We need to
give a lot of thought over the next 10 weeks as to what we want to
use the surplus for,'' Gore said, chiding the Bush plan for tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   He also slammed pharmaceutical companies for stifling
competition and therefore keeping drug costs high.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign responded by trying to tie Gore to the one man
he seeks distance from: President Clinton. ``Al Gore today is
proposing a nationalized drug plan that makes the federal
government the dispenser of drugs for seniors, similar to Hillary
Clinton's attempt to nationalize heath care in 1993,'' said Bush
spokesman Dan Bartlett in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee is also running television ads
touting the Bush prescription drug plan, which relies largely on
one proposed by a bipartisan congressional commission. Those ads
will run in nine states; Florida is not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with local Democratic candidates and supporters,
Gore left about 6 p.m. for the next stop on his four-day tour, in
New Mexico. His wife, Tipper, who came with him to Tallahassee,
will stay in Florida today, with campaign stops planned for
Jacksonville, Tampa and Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will probably visit Florida two or three more times before
Election Day, including the swing-voter-rich middle part of the
state between Tampa and Daytona Beach, said Sen. Ron Klein, D-Boca
Raton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're welcoming Vice President Gore back to the state,'' Gov.
Jeb Bush said before Gore's arrival Monday. ``And we're taking
Florida very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Email: marciagelbart(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
