A4671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OPTIONS-MARKETPLACE-N     08-28 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPTIONS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: STOCK OPTIONS COSTING COMPANIES MORE THAN ACCOUNTING
SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is one of the prettiest lies in corporate America.
Stock options dispensed to executives and workers are not accounted
for as an employee expense, even though they clearly are.
</P>
<P>
   So companies that reward their employees with stock options do
not include the costs of those programs in their overall expenses,
giving their earnings a boost.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the stock market rose, few investors seemed to care
that corporate earnings were overstated. But now with the stock
market mostly moving sideways, perhaps they will begin to notice
what option programs really cost them in the way of lower earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Pat McConnell, a senior managing director and head of the
accounting and tax group in equity research at Bear, Stearns, has
completed a comprehensive study examining how earnings at the
companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index would fare if
employee stock option grants were accounted for as an expense.
</P>
<P>
   Given that option mania has swept the country, it is not
surprising that McConnell finds that options had a bigger, and more
negative impact on corporate earnings last year than ever. Net
income at the S &AMP; P 500 companies, which totaled $51.68 a share in
1999, would have been 6 percent lower if options were accounted for
as an expense, she said. This compares with a 4 percent reduction
in 1998 and a 3 percent hit in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the jump is that last year was the first year in
which company financial statements reflected the full impact of
some stock option programs. The Financial Accounting Standards
Board requires companies to include in the footnotes to their
financial statements the effects of options granted in fiscal years
beginning after Dec. 15, 1994. Because many companies' plans allow
employees' options to vest in five years or less, last year was the
first in which the full effect of some of those plans appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Accounting rule makers recommend that companies charge the fair
value of options granted to employees as a compensation expense,
but they do not require it. If companies do not run the costs of
options through their profit and loss statements, they must
disclose in a footnote in their annual reports what net income and
per-share earnings would have been had the cost of stock options
been charged.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies choose the latter approach. In fact, McConnell
identified only two of the 500 companies in the S&AMP;P index that
account for options as a cost: Boeing and Winn-Dixie.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the larger the option grants, the bigger the cost to
a company's earnings. McConnell found four industry groups in the S
&AMP; P 500 whose earnings would have declined 10 percent or more in
each of the last three years if option grants were counted as an
expense. Companies in the business of health care services would
have shown a 38 percent decline in earnings last year; computer
networking concerns, 24 percent; commercial and consumer services
companies, 21 percent; and communications equipment makers, 19
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings at 122 companies _ almost one quarter of the stocks in
the index _ declined more than 10 percent last year when stock
options were accounted for as an expense. That compares with 79
companies showing such declines in 1998 and 61 companies in 1997,
McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   But earnings at 21 companies fell by more than half when
adjusted for stock options. These included McDermott International,
an oil services company; Yahoo, the Internet company; Autodesk, a
computer software designer; Polaroid; and Palm.
</P>
<P>
   Even more compelling, 12 companies that had an operating profit
in 1999 would have had an operating loss if stock options were
considered an expense. For instance, the $6 million in operating
income that Micron Technology made last year would have been an
operating loss of $120 million. Grant Jones, a Micron spokesman,
said, ``We treat options in accordance with generally accepted
accounting principles.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall effect of stock options on corporate earnings is
decidedly negative. According to McConnell's study, the S &AMP; P's
three-year compound annual earnings growth rate dwindles from 11
percent to 9 percent when options are considered a cost. And the
compound annual growth in operating income for the S &AMP; P slows from
a three-year rate of 12 percent to 10 percent when the favorable
accounting treatment for options is eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell expects the impact of options on earnings to continue
to grow in coming years. Will accounting rules ever change to
reflect the true cost of options?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in three to five years, if standard setters outside
the U.S. adopt a fair value approach for employee stock options,
then I think the U.S. will have to take another look at this,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she said she was relieved to find that the
overall impact of stock options on S &AMP; P earnings remained below 10
percent and that she believed that investors were fully aware of
the problem that stock option mania posed among technology
companies. Nevertheless, she added: ``I think it essential that
investors look at this information in making comparisons. If you
want to buy the best company in an industry, you have to take this
into consideration or you may be misled.''
</P>
<P>
   And investors need more information, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the footnote information allows you to dig in,'' she
said, ``it's not a substitute for doing the accounting correctly in
the financial statements themselves. In addition, this footnote is
only provided annually. Investors need this information more often
and sooner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 2124EDT &QL; 
