<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-RAMSEY0829-COX     08-28 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interview of Ramseys gets tense
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The first interview John and Patsy Ramsey have given
police in two years nearly crashed Monday during questioning from a
prosecutor their attorney called ``overzealous'' and ``obsessed.''
</P>
<P>
   The blowup occurred several hours into the interview with Patsy
Ramsey, when her attorney challenged several questions addressed to
her. The disagreement escalated until prosecutor Mike Kane
threatened to walk out, said Ramsey attorney Lin Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mike Kane is an overzealous, obsessed special
prosecutor who long ago lost objectivity,'' said Wood after the day
of talks at his downtown Atlanta office. He blasted Kane as intent
``on asking any question'' so he can carry on ``a fishing
expedition to find anything against this family.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kane nor Boulder, Colo., Police Chief Mark Beckner was
available for comment Monday evening. Kane, a consultant in the
case, is a Pennsylvania prosecutor hired to lead a grand jury probe
on the 1996 slaying of the Ramseys' daughter, 6-year-old beauty
queen JonBenet. The grand jury returned no indictment, but the
couple remains under suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys, who moved back to metro Atlanta from Boulder
afterJonBenet's death, are voluntarily participating in the talks
expected to wrap up today. In agreeing to the interviews, the
couple say they disregarded their attorney's advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here to prove our innocence,'' John Ramsey told
reporters. ``We're here to find the killer of our daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Monday morning session, in which Patsy Ramsey was
interviewed by Beckner, was congenial. Before heading to lunch, she
commented on the fairness of the questions, saying, ``I feel very
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the afternoon, Wood said, the two sides jousted over
several inquiries. Among other areas, Kane asked about the security
measures taken when the Ramseys' son returned to school after the
murder, and he questioned the activities of the JonBenet Ramsey
Foundation formed after the girl's death. Those questions, Wood
said, violated the vow made by Boulder police to focus on new
questions, not to rehash old ones.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting drew about 60 news personnel _ as well as some
remarks from those watching the media gather again for the nearly
4-year-old murder mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so stupid,'' said lawyer Suzanne Hashimi. ``Come on.''
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged, however, ``I keep up with this story like
everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
