<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-JOHNSON-GOP-CONGRESS-     08-28 1457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-GOP-CONGRESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLACK WOMAN AIMS TO KEEP LAZIO'S SEAT REPUBLICAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla.)   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAY SHORE, N.Y. _ It was, she says, divine inspiration that cast
her into a race that could make her the first black Republican
woman ever to serve in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think I am on a path that someone higher than me is
preparing me for,'' says Joan B. Johnson, 66, the elected town
clerk of Islip, who has mounted a campaign to win the Suffolk
County seat that Rep. Rick A. Lazio is giving up for his Senate
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   There was, of course, some earthly machination as well. Two of
Suffolk County's most powerful Republicans, the party leaders of
the county organization and the town of Islip, the largest
community, threw their support behind Johnson, a blunt-spoken
former social worker. She may lack the polish of a political pro,
party leaders reasoned, but she is a proven vote getter whose
moderate stances to the left of Lazio _ and perhaps her race and
sex _ will attract Democrats' votes in the 2nd Congressional
District, where Republicans hold only a slight edge in voter
registration.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, one of a few black Republican women running in the
country but the one political analysts say has the best shot, finds
herself in the semi-comfortable position of blazing a trail, maybe
two, lined with obstacles. She must win a primary on Sept. 12, and
confront the possibility that, as she and her supporters concede,
some people may not vote for her, simply because of her race and
sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people really thought they were going to get this
nod, mainly because here on Long Island you tend to have a
cookie-cutter type profile of what a congressperson should look
like,'' Johnson said, alluding to the Island's penchant for sending
young, white male lawyers to Washington. ``And it didn't look like
me. It's never female. And in that respect, that's the historic
piece of this. I would be the first Republican woman in either
Nassau or Suffolk Counties to ever run for Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who grew up in Florida when segregation was legal and
has lived in Islip for 38 years, said the racial aspect of her
potential achievement never occurred to her until a reporter for a
political journal raised the issue, shortly after she entered the
campaign in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Oh, my God.' First time I heard it. Never even
thought about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who teaches Bible study on Saturdays and dispenses
marriage licenses and other bureaucratic documents during the week,
now weathers the gale of a high-stakes congressional race, one
symbolically and tactically important for Republicans. Their
five-seat hold on the House is on the line, and they are loath to
surrender any seat, much less that of Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   So Johnson, town clerk since 1991, is surrounded by a staff she
hardly knows, with a state party operative serving as her campaign
manager and a Washington consultant, Tony Marsh, as campaign
strategist. Her eyes bulge at her fund-raising goal, $1.5 million,
88 times the most she ever raised for a town clerk campaign and a
far cry from what she has now, about $130,000.
</P>
<P>
   The open seat has brought out a bevy of contenders to a contest
that Congressional Quarterly, a leading political journal, rates a
tossup between the eventual Democratic and Republican nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has received the endorsement of the Republican and the
Conservative Party organizations, but faces a primary on both
lines. Her Republican challenger is Robert T. Walsh, a retired
banker from Deer Park who represents a Russian humanitarian
organization at the United Nations. Walsh also plans to run on the
Right to Life line, as he did in 1994 when he ran for governor.
(Johnson favors abortion rights with no restrictions, unlike Lazio,
who opposes both public financing for abortions and late-term
procedures.) Richard N. Thompson of West Islip is challenging her
on the Conservative line.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, pointing to Johnson's positions on abortion and gun
control as out of step with the district's electorate, said, ``I
think she is an extraordinarily weak candidate and has little
chance to beat the Democrats running.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his years as a banking executive and as a goodwill
ambassador at the United Nations stood above her qualifications
``or lack thereof'' as town clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a lawyer from West Islip who was a pitcher for the
Cleveland Indians and Montreal Expos in the 1980s, said he viewed
Johnson as too far to the left on a number of issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she was the best candidate chosen by the
Republicans,'' Thompson said. ``I didn't think she was a voice for
conservative values, so I felt compelled to run.''
</P>
<P>
   The opponent the primary winners will face is still
undetermined. Democrats are headed for a three-way primary, with
the victor almost guaranteed strong backing by the national party
in an effort both to embarrass Lazio by grabbing his seat and to
help win back the House. They are seeking to reclaim a seat held by
a Democrat, Thomas Downey, for 20 years before Lazio defeated him
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But among the biggest question marks looming is how voters will
take to Johnson's race and sex, in a district that has never sent a
woman to Congress and whose population of 580,000 is about 79
percent white, 9 percent black, 9 percent Hispanic and 2 percent
Asian.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have portrayed her candidacy as groundbreaking and
emblematic of the diversity and inclusiveness they seek. National
party officials gave her a brief but nonetheless valuable daytime
speaking role at the Republican National Convention this month. The
National Republican Congressional Committee, which conducted a poll
in early June that placed Johnson near the top of the potential
candidates in name recognition, is expected to send a hefty sum to
her campaign this fall.
</P>
<P>
   That said, even some of Johnson's supporters openly wonder
whether people will choose not to vote for her principally because
of her race. ``I'd like to say that won't happen, but realistically
it might,'' said State Senator Carl L. Marcellino of Syosset, who
said he was hopeful that ``people in the district will look beyond
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans privately worry about Johnson's age and lack of
political or legislative experience and rue the decision of Peter
McGowan, the powerful Islip town supervisor, to skip the race even
though he topped the list of six or seven contenders for the
party's backing. Johnson, who was not on the initial list, is most
often described as kindly, but lacking the fierce ambition that
could make waves in a local party striving for stability after
scandals and a succession of leaders.
</P>
<P>
   She scoffs at those who question her experience, saying the
administrative tasks of the town clerk's office and service on
numerous community organization boards adequately prepare anyone
for Congress. She cites the case of Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, a Long
Island Democrat, who won office in 1996 with no political
experience by running on a gun control platform rooted in the death
of her husband in the Long Island Rail Road shooting in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   As for strategy, she hammers an antitax message but also has
firmly hitched her fortune to Lazio, a popular figure in the
district. In remarks at a recent ``meet the candidates'' picnic,
Johnson scarcely mentioned herself for all her praise of Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Black Republicans have always tilted at political windmills,
said David Bositis, senior political analyst for the Joint Center
for Political and Economic Studies, a Washington-based organization
that studies African-American affairs. There is only one black
Republican now in Congress, J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, and there have
been only five this century, Bositis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face it, there is a lot of history between African-Americans
and the GOP,'' said Bositis, citing as an example the party's
advocacy during the 1960s and '70s of ``states' rights' and other
positions that blacks have seen as racially tinged appeals to white
Southerners. ``At least in the recent past, most of it is negative.
No amount of image making in the short term is going to change that
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson grows impatient with talk about one party being for one
race or another, a form of ``racial profiling,'' she says with a
laugh. If Democrats are perceived as more likely champions of
racial advancement, people need to go further back in history, she
says with mounting bitterness, rattling off names of Southern
Democrats with reputations for intolerance. ``I'll tell you who the
people were in power when my people were hanging from ropes in
trees. They were Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Her views are generally liberal. She is for not only abortion
rights, but also affirmative action, and _ as the godmother of a
17-year-old murder victim _ gun control, including registration.
She supports the death penalty, for the most heinous crimes like
serial killings, but she says her positions are not rigid and
shifted uncomfortably as she discussed the topic. ``These issues
don't come easy to me,'' she says. ``All life is precious.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson says she feels philosophically closer to Republicans
because of her goals to lower taxes and shrink government.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, however, Johnson senses victory in her web
of community connections, from her work at Head Start to children's
clubs to the town clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``See that robe?'' she says, motioning to a black gown hanging
in the campaign office here on East Main Street that once was the
place where she got her nails done. ``I've married 2,500 couples.
That's 5,000 people who personally know me because I've put them
together.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``I go to the Eagle Scout awards, and I was a member
of the Boy Scouts Council, and I was a vice president of the Girl
Scouts Council, so I do a lot of things locally. My weekends are
always filled with community things, the Fire Department, the
whatever, the church events.''
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Sanders, president of the Urban League of Long Island, a
nonpartisan group, said: ``She always has been an unsung hero in
our community. What Joan Johnson does represent is we've always had
progressive, articulate, dedicated African-Americans in our
community, and Joan Johnson is no stranger to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
