<DOCNO> NYT20000828.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-ARATON-NYT &LR;      08-28 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOLLOWING IN THE PATH OF A PIONEER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Daughter hailed mother on the cell phone, in Miami,
at the airport, with the flash that was no longer news.
</P>
<P>
   ``She already knew I won,'' said Allison Bradshaw, looking every
bit the 19-year-old whose family surprise was ruined.
</P>
<P>
   An anxious mother can only stand so much. The minute Valerie
Ziegenfuss landed, shuffling her national team of 14-and-under
players off the flight from Prague and through immigration, she
switched on the phone, and found the messages from the National
Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Two other U.S. Tennis Association coaches and Lynne Rolley, the
director of programs, had already reported Bradshaw's 6-4, 6-2
first-round takeout of France's Sarah Pitkowski in Bradshaw's Grand
Slam debut at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allison reached me at the baggage claim but we could only talk
for a couple of minutes because I had to check in for the flight
home to San Diego,'' Ziegenfuss said by phone, about to board.
``After we hung up, I started thinking that people in the press
might be asking her questions that she doesn't know the answer to.
I guess it's time I start filling her in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ziegenfuss never decorated the house with trophies, with photos,
with reminders that her daughter had any path to follow but her
own. She made a point of not regaling her with 30-year-old tales of
a very different time. Yet now that Bradshaw had an Open victory
under her belt, now that she was part of a tour that keeps
redefining itself, keeps growing, she ought to know how it all came
to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know more, considering my mom was involved,''
Bradshaw said. ``But more because everyone on the Tour should try
to learn about what Billie Jean King and the rest of them did.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows her mother was in Houston, with King and Rosie Casals
and the publisher Gladys Heldman, leaders of nine breakaway players
who in 1970 rebelled against the USTA and shunned a Tour stop in
Los Angeles. While the USTA was paying the women about one-tenth
what it gave the men, Heldman put up $5000 of her own money and the
players signed $1 contracts. They were banned by the USTA, told
they had committed career suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Ziegenfuss said, she would have to tell her daughter of
the anxious phone calls and the late-night fears and the
uncompromising faith in Heldman and King that ultimately pulled
them though.
</P>
<P>
   Four times in the top 10 in singles and No. 1-ranked in doubles,
Ziegenfuss lost to Rosie Casals that week in Houston and guessed
she made $300. For surviving one round after receiving a wild card
into the main draw, her daughter Monday guaranteed herself at least
a $19,000 Open haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I amazed by the prize money?'' Ziegenfuss said. ``Yes. But
I'm more amazed by the level of play. Not in my wildest dreams did
I ever hit a forehand like my daughter, and she's not one of the
top players.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Open slogged its way out of the starting gate, it began
with one potential response to Tigermania, to the kind of attention
golf gets, and that would be a women's final of Williams versus
Williams. For all of Pete Sampras' 13-Slam greatness and Andre
Agassi's inherent appeal, the men's game has stooped to a new
publicity campaign directed at those preoccupied with the
wrestlers, the rappers and other renowned reapers of the attention
the men don't command. ``New Balls, Please'' sounds more like an
excerpt from Bob Knight's autobiography than a sound marketing plan
for tennis.
</P>
<P>
   The transcendent superstar doesn't achieve the big television
rating by merely taking off his (or her) shirt. You either have a
compelling product, or you don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing from Venus and Serena is so far athletically
beyond anything we knew back then,'' Ziegenfuss said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw, who first beat her mother when she was 12 or 13, is 5
feet 10 inches, with reddish hair and an aggressive style. ``I
don't get nervous,'' she said, after proving it by ignoring the
noise pollution around Court 18, a bathroom dash by the 24-year-old
Pitkowski after Bradshaw had won 12 of 15 points to ice the first
set and an ensuing rain delay.
</P>
<P>
   After winning a Challenger event earlier this summer after
leaving Arizona State, she's come a long way without Virginia
Slims, and does not even consider herself a feminist. Here at the
Open, the one Grand Slam event that pays equal prize money, she
doesn't have to be.
</P>
<P>
   Ziegenfuss will be here Wednesday to tell her daughter more
about how this all came about. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
