<SLUG> BC-AMC-MMC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLIED MICRO CIRCUITS BUYS NETWORK CHIP DESIGNER FOR $4.5 BILLION
IN STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Applied Micro Circuits Corp., a San Diego-based
maker of chips for networking equipment, said Monday that it had
agreed to acquire MMC Networks Inc. in a stock swap valued at about
$4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   MMC Networks, which is based in Sunnyvale, Calif., designs chips
to speed the connections between fiber optic communications lines
and electrical circuits. The company contracts out the fabrication
of their chips.
</P>
<P>
   Both Applied Micro and MMC are large suppliers to network
equipment manufacturers like Nortel, Cisco and Lucent, and the
acquisition is part of Applied Micro's strategy to broaden its
product line.
</P>
<P>
   Applied Micro shares closed Monday at $183.81, down $4.75, in
Nasdaq trading, while MMC shares jumped $31.75, to close at $110.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts praised the acquisition as a logical strategic move,
but noted that the price was high for a small, little-known
company.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Motey, an analyst with CE Unterberg Towbin, said that
Applied Micro and its primary competitors, PMC-Sierra Inc. and the
Vitesse Semiconductor Corp., had all been bulking up through
acquisitions so that they could offer the network equipment
companies a complete catalog of chips. Companies like Nortel and
Cisco ``are no longer just looking for component suppliers, but
partners at the architectural level,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the chip suppliers,'' he said, ``are all trying to build a
war chest of components.''
</P>
<P>
   Although voice and data communications are increasingly
transmitted as optical signals carried over fiber optic cable,
those pulses of light must be translated back into electrical
current for the switches and routers that direct them across the
Internet to their ultimate destination. In acquiring MMC Networks,
Applied Micro gains a leading provider of network processors,
traffic management and switch fabric technologies, which are at the
core of a wide variety of switches and routers, including optical
networking, Web switching, subscriber management, broadband access
and other communications systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a new market emerging for intelligent optical
networking systems,'' said Dave Rickey, Applied Micro's president
and chief executive, in a statement. ``With this merger, we can
provide the most complete and powerful integrated circuit solutions
for this rapidly growing market.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Spreng, as president of MMC, which will become a subsidiary
of Applied Micro, will report directly to Rickey and join the
Applied board upon completion of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Peck, an analyst with SG Cowen, said this merger, as well
as some earlier deals, transformed Applied Micro from a niche
player to a powerhouse. ``With this deal, they've basically become
the dominant network component supplier,'' he said. ``They have the
highest performance across the broadest array of products.''
</P>
<P>
   But the deal is not without risk, Peck added. ``The bet they're
making is that huge customers like Cisco, Nortel and Lucent will
happily stop making these components internally, and use more
generic components,'' he said. ``If you believe in this strategy,
then the question is how much was it worth. There have been myriad
acquisitions of unheard-of companies at unheard-of valuations, but
it will be two or three years until we know if it was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Motey of CE Unterberg said he believed the deal would start
paying for itself soon. ``We're estimating an additional $140 to
$150 million in revenues in 2001, on top of the $500 million we
were estimating for AMCC,'' he said. ``With MMC, AMCC gets a
company with a proven track record, with 72 design wins and 42
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the largest in a recent string of networking
component acquisitions, including that of Quantum Effect Devices
Inc., which was bought last week by PMC-Sierra in a transaction
originally valued at $2.3 billion; that of the closely held SiTera
Inc., acquired in May by Vitesse for $750 million; and that of the
closely held Agere Inc., which Lucent bought in April for about
$504.5 million. Lucent has said it plans to spin off its unit that
makes chips and optical parts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
