<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND HIS OPPONENTS, ANOTHER TUG-OF-WAR DAY
</HEADLINE>
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Seeking to pull the campaign debate back onto
what he considers his turf, Gov. George W. Bush sharply attacked
Vice President Al Gore on education policy on Monday, asserting
that the Clinton Administration had complacently presided over ``a
national tragedy'' in the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But even as he tried to seize the offensive, Bush for the second
straight week found himself responding to criticisms from the Gore
campaign, which this time argued that he does not have a detailed
plan for creating a prescription drug benefit for the elderly. In a
sign that Gore's latest attack may have stung him a bit, Bush
announced in a news conference on Monday that he would spend part
of next week unveiling a proposal to have the government subsidize
prescription drug purchases by the low-income elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's press office also spent much of the day hammering at
Gore's proposal to create a prescription drug benefit under
Medicare, asserting that the plan would effectively raise taxes for
most seniors citizens and nationalize prescription drug policies,
``similar to Hillary Clinton's attempt to nationalize health care
in 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkably like Mrs. Clinton's plan,'' said Ari
Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign. ``It is a
government-run, one-size-fits-all plan. And just like her plan, the
Democrats thought it was popular and would put Republicans on the
defense. But once people look at the details, they will rebel
against it.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the discussion of health care, Bush intended to kick off
this week's tour through New England, Ohio, Kentucky and
Pennsylvania to promote his ideas for revamping the nation's public
schools. He had also planned to spend last week discussing
education, but was knocked off message when he spent a good chunk
of time defending his plan to cut income taxes across the board.
</P>
<P>
   The push and pull between the two campaigns to control the
debate on Monday placed in clear relief the issues they consider to
be the strongest for each of their candidates. Aides to Gore assert
that voters trust Democrats more on health care, and they believe
that the more Bush is forced to talk about it, the better the vice
president will perform in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue that is on Gore's territory,'' said an
advisor to the vice president. ``The Republicans just don't get it.
And they don't have a plan. So they fall back on tired old
rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign contends that the governor's focus on
improving education, particularly for poor and minority students,
underscores his commitment to ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President Gore offers more of the same,'' Bush said on
Monday. ``He will not end the status quo because he is the status
quo. He offers the failed ideas of the past. I offer new ideas,
ideas that are working and that can appeal both to Republicans and
Democrats to break the gridlock of education in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   At his event outside the governor's mansion here on Monday, Bush
surrounded himself with teachers and school administrators from
Kentucky, Ohio and Michigan _ all important swing states _ who have
helped form a group called Educators for Bush that could provide a
counterweight, albeit a mostly symbolic one, to the powerful
teachers unions that support Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Bush touted his plan for funneling federal money
to the parents of students in failing public schools so they could
attend other schools, public or private. He would also encourage
the growth of charter schools, require annual state reading tests
for students in grades 3 through 8, and reward districts that issue
report cards on their schools.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor devoted almost as much time to attacking Gore's
education policies as he did promoting his own. He asserted that
Gore's proposals would provide only ``the illusion'' of school
accountability. And he sharply criticized the Clinton
administration's record, citing seven and a half years of
``neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationwide, we are spending more on our public schools,'' he
said. ``But the achievement gap between rich and poor, minority and
non-minority, has remained the same or grown worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan focuses on increasing federal education spending by
$115 billion over 10 years for things like modernizing crumbling
schools, reducing class sizes and increasing teacher pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is proposing real reforms and resources to improve our
public schools, while Bush is pushing a voucher plan that would
drain money away from our public schools,'' said Doug Hattaway, a
spokesman for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   After Bush's education event on Monday, he was pressed on health
care issues by reporters. Asked if he would sign legislation based
on a bipartisan Senate plan, Bush offered a conditional yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can make it better,'' he said. ``One idea is to
make sure low-income seniors are better helped in paying for
prescription drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   After the news conference, Karen Hughes, Bush's press secretary,
said it was not necessary for Bush to explain details of a
prescription drug plan, because those details could be left to the
legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   She also blamed the Clinton administration for ``a litany of
squandered opportunities'' in failing to win bipartisan support for
a prescription drug plan. ``That's seven and a half years of
failure,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
