<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4695 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-LASSEN-$     08-28 1614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-LASSEN-$ADV03-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GEYSER FILLED PARK TO LET OFF SOME STEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 3)  
 (Editors: A 430-word information box appears at end of 2nd take.)  
 By GERALD HERTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Just my luck,'' I muttered, gazing at the unattended welcome
sign to Lassen Volcanic National Park in Northern California.
``STOP. Pay $10 here,'' it said. All I had was a $20 bill.
</P>
<P>
   The temptation was strong to ignore the demand. There was most
likely no ranger for miles around. But not wanting guilt to
jeopardize a good night's sleep, I placed the bill in an envelope,
attached a note asking for $10 change, and included my address. I
dropped it into the collection box, never expecting to see my $10
again. I had flown into Reno the night before, so there had been no
time to do much damage at the casino. Were my fortunes changing?
</P>
<P>
   The drive west from Reno that morning had covered 135 miles of
wide, green valleys crisscrossed with fast, churning rivers,
surrounded by low-lying pine-covered mountains. The landscape
became increasingly impressive as stately Lassen Peak rose 10,457
feet above the wooded landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Lassen Volcanic National Park, with its headquarters in Mineral,
Calif., is part of the Pacific Ring of Fire, the chain of volcanoes
along the rim of the Pacific Ocean that includes Mount Shasta in
California and Crater Lake National Park in Oregon. Lassen has
geologic features similar to Yellowstone's _ steam vents and
boiling mud pots _ though on a smaller scale. The peak itself is
one of the world's largest plug-dome volcanoes (a plug dome is
created when a volcano's expanding lava dome becomes so huge that
it plugs its own vent). Still considered potentially active, Lassen
Peak last erupted in 1914 and 1915. North of the mountain is what's
known as the Devastated Area, stripped of all vegetation by the
eruptions.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I reached the park entrance, I had completed 15 of
the 17 miles of Warner Valley Road, winding deep into the southern
end of the 106,000-acre park from the little town of Chester. My
compact rental car bounced and groaned along the rocky, rutted dirt
lane that crosses the final three miles to Drakesbad Guest Ranch,
the only lodging within the park.
</P>
<P>
   My visit last summer required getting on the waiting list two
years in advance just to try for reservations at one of only 19
spartan, rustic lodge rooms, cabins or more spacious bungalows. The
news had come in January, a year and a half later. Thanks to
cancellations, the five rooms our group had requested for a weekend
were confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   After a few more jarring moments, I finally spotted the
weathered wood structures of Drakesbad Guest Ranch, among the tall
evergreens at the end of the road since 1900.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Drakesbad,'' Billie Fiebiger said, greeting me
warmly as I stepped into the dining hall that doubles as the
registration office. With her husband, Ed, Billie runs the ranch
during the short June-to-October season. They both know the
mountains; Ed is from Garmisch, Germany's well-known ski resort,
and Billie is from Bern, Switzerland; they moved here many years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Though I wasn't scheduled to check in until later that
afternoon, Billie welcomed me to a free lunch of salads and
make-your-own sandwiches. The rest of my group, which consisted of
five families with various ties to our accounting firm in Orange
County, soon arrived in three separate vans from the day's various
starting points of nearby Redding, Chico and Red Bluff.
</P>
<P>
   We have been making these annual scenic outings together for
more than two decades. In the early years, the group consisted
mostly of myself and a few colleagues, who sought out rugged
backpacking adventures. Now, along with a client, we were joined by
four spouses and their seven children, ranging in age from 1 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   Before lunch was over, Billie had taken a genuine interest in
helping us with plans for the weekend. Our general idea was to hike
to nearby thermal areas that day, then drive over to the west side
of the park the next day to climb Lassen Peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The younger children can join our kids club, which runs from
11 a.m. to 3 p.m.,'' Billie suggested. The older children, she
added, could make the 2.3-mile round-trip hike to Devil's Kitchen
to see the smoking steam vents and bubbling mud pots. The hardiest
hikers could continue on to Terminal Geyser, with its spouting
20-foot high steam plume. Everyone seemed agreeable, so we decided
to quickly unpack.
</P>
<P>
   Our rooms were on the second floor of the separate lodge
building. They were small, with wood paneling, one or two beds and
half baths. The showers were down by the hot-springs pool, which we
would become well-acquainted with after our hike. There are no
locks on the rooms (although you can secure them from the inside
with a chain.).
</P>
<P>
   The lodge's first floor was a single large room with a stone
fireplace at one end, comfortably furnished with soft chairs and
couches. An array of T-shirts and supplies were sold on a
self-serve honor basis.
</P>
<P>
   Soon we were off to Devil's Kitchen. The trail wove across a
wide meadow and into thick pine woods. Before long, the kids were
holding their noses. The distinct rotten-egg smell of sulfur
permeated the air. Then there was an opening in the woods and we
came to a clearing of desolate beauty. Steam billowed from several
pink-yellow, mounded rock cauldrons near and far. The heat and
minerals in the steam inhibited plant growth near these fumaroles.
</P>
<P>
   A teen-age boy in our group reveled in ignoring the numerous
warning signs to stay well back of the steam vents. Even I leaned
in too close to view a boiling mud pot nearby. A large bubble burst
from the thick pool of ooze, spraying my hat with hot mud drops;
luckily, I was not burned, like others who have ignored warnings
posted there. Suitably impressed with the strange phenomenon, we
returned to the ranch for a soothing swim in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner was a delight. Our table of 16 was by far the largest of
a roomful of diners that totaled about 40, mostly families who
return year after year. The meal, prepared and served by the
friendly ranch staff, was surprisingly ambitious _ mahi-mahi in a
pineapple salsa, rice, mixed vegetables, salad and ice cream with
caramel sauce. Meals are included in the room price (the nearest
restaurant is back in Chester). Several moderately priced
California wines and rich German beers were available for an extra
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Later as we congregated around a campfire, the fixings for
s'mores appeared from the kitchen. Darkness fell. Soon the kids
were wide-eyed, cheeks sticky with marshmallows, listening to one
of their fathers start an eerie tale. They awoke often that night
to check under the bed for Big Foot.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning began with hearty breakfast choices of fruits,
juices, bagels and muffins, cereals and yogurt, topped off with a
hot cheese quiche served at the lodge's dining roomtable.
</P>
<P>
   Well fortified, the five men in our group plus 10-year-old
Monica and 16-year-old Tom grabbed the lunches we had ordered the
night before, and set out for Lassen Peak in one family's van.
Following Billie's advice, the others decided to seek adventures
closer to the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   We took a costly wrong turn, and by the time we returned to the
main road, Route 36, we had lost an hour. Finally, after two and a
half hours of driving, we approached the trail head to Lassen Peak.
</P>
<P>
   Starting up at 11:55, we were eager to reach the summit before
lunch. After a rapid start, the pace soon slowed, as the 8,500-foot
altitude and steep slope strewn with volcanic rock took their toll,
despite perfect weather.
</P>
<P>
   The gray mountain was still streaked with patches of snow and
there were intermittent trees on the lower reaches. We were passed
by an adventurer bearing skis, planning a more challenging descent.
</P>
<P>
   The steep two-and-a-half-mile trail is popular. For a while, I
hiked with a family from Ulm, Germany. I was dismayed to realize
that it had taken me and my companions 20 years to discover this
gem within our own state, only to find plenty of foreign visitors,
including travelers from England and France already enjoying
Lassen's splendor.
</P>
<P>
   Spectacular vistas greeted us at every turn as we moved up the
side of the mountain. The volcano is actually just a remnant on the
edge of huge Mount Tehama, which collapsed thousands of years ago,
forming the fascinating caldera defining the surrounding mountain
formations.
</P>
<P>
   Larry and Jeff, two colleagues and the fastest of our group,
reached the summit by 1:15 p.m., with the rest of us staggering
over the last boulders at 1:30. At 10,457 feet, we were all a
little lightheaded, but energized by our accomplishment. Mount
Shasta beckoned nobly in the distance to the northwest. We feasted
on our box lunch _ sandwiches, fruit and chips _ amid the grandeur
of this once and future mountain of molten power. Although it was
crowded, there was room to stretch out for a nap.
</P>
<P>
   The hike down was much faster. By 3 p.m. we were driving back to
Drakesbad, passing the Sulphur Works thermal area. After a quick
stop in Chester for root beer floats, we headed to the ranch for
showers and a swim in the lodge's pool. We found the stay-at-homes
looking as weary as us. Their day had included horseback rides,
canoeing on the small, peaceful Dream Lake, and a respectable hike
to Terminal Geyser.
</P>
<P>
   At dinner, we were rewarded with another delicious meal of prime
rib, steamed artichokes, mashed potatoes, salad and strawberry
cheesecake. Afterward, some still had energy for a round of
horseshoes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, seeking one last adventure, Larry, Jeff and I got up
at 6 and hiked a short mile from the ranch to Boiling Springs Lake,
one of dozens of fumaroles in the park. Approaching the rim, we
listened as the morning silence was broken by gurgling sounds. All
across the 300-yard diameter of the eerie lake, steam rose thickly
from the milky surface. The edge was ringed with bubbling mud pots.
</P>
<P>
   We hurried back to the ranch only to linger over a sumptuous
breakfast before leaving. Weeks later, as I thumbed through the
mail back home one day, I found an envelope from the National Park
Service. Inside was a $10 refund check.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION &QL; 
Getting There
</P>
<P>
   The closest major airport to Lassen Volcanic National Park is in
Reno, Nev., a three-hour drive via U.S. Route 395 and Highway 36.
Airline service is also available to Redding, Calif., about 50
miles to the west of Lassen's northern entrance on Highway 44, and
Chico, Calif., about 90 miles south of the southwest entrance on
Highways 36 and 89.
</P>
<P>
   Park information can be obtained from the Superintendent, Lassen
Volcanic National Park, Box 100, Mineral, Calif. 96063-0100; (530)
595-4444.
</P>
<P>
   The park is open year-round, but snow makes access difficult in
winter and spring.
Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   Drakesbad Guest Ranch, End of Warner Valley Road, Chester,
Calif. 96020, is 17 miles north of Chester. To contact the ranch,
messages may be left at (530) 529-1512.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations and information also can be obtained from
California Guest Services, 2150 Main Street, Suite 5, Red Bluff,
Calif. 96080.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch buildings, made of weathered wood, are located in the
secluded southeastern reaches of the park. It is the only lodging
in the park (which also has campsites) and is open from early June
through early October. Accommodations include 10 small, rustic
lodge rooms and cabins ($108 to $128 a person), 6 one-bedroom
bungalows plus a two-unit annex ($125 to $153 a person) and a
duplex ($133 a person). Rates include all meals. There are no
televisions or phones in the rooms but there is a phone in the main
lodge room.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants and year-round accommodations are available in the
towns of Mineral and Chester _ roughly an hour's drive away. The
Bidwell House, 1 Main Street, Box 1790, Chester, Calif. 96020,
(530) 258-3338, www.bidwellhouse.com, is an attractive 100-year-old
farmhouse, with a 10-year-old annex with the 14 rooms. Rates are
$85 to $190 with tax, including full breakfast. Sightseeing
</P>
<P>
   The main road winds 30 miles through the park, passing several
major sights. The crown jewel is Lassen Peak, a dormant volcano,
accessible by a 2.5-mile trail to the summit. Nearby is the Bumpass
Hell Thermal Area with boiling springs, mud pots and steam vents.
</P>
<P>
   North of Lassen Peak is the Devastated Area, stripped of all
vegetation by the 1914-15 eruptions. The more remote southern end
of the park, near Drakesbad, contains the Devil's Kitchen thermal
area, Terminal Geyser and Boiling Springs Lake. Trail rides are
available from the stables at Drakesbad. Prices range from $18 for
a 45-minute ride to $110 for an eight-hour ride, which includes a
bag lunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
