<HEADER>
A4699 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-AVANT-GARDE-FASHION-N     08-28 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVANT-GARDE-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO BE YOUNG, TALENTED AND MARGINALIZED IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Being a young designer in New York _ and the city
seems flush with new talent now _ hardly means that one will
survive to be an old designer in New York. The fashion business
here, especially, functions with a kind of Darwinian magnanimity.
Either you're good or you're gone.
</P>
<P>
   Talent alone doesn't ensure survival, as Isaac Mizrahi found
out. Nor is financial success the only measure of fashion
greatness. Can anyone really say that Ralph Lauren is a better
designer than Stephen Burrows?
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the designers who have risen in Mizrahi's wake
seem to possess neither his exciting talent nor his old-fashioned
skills of self-promotion. They are often shy, inarticulate, vague
to the point of appearing self-consciously cool, and even when they
become stars, as Miguel Adrover did this year, there is something
so reticent in their demeanor as to make one wonder if the very
notion of the designer as a personality isn't dead. ``I would like
to hide myself,'' Adrover said last Thursday in his new workroom on
the Bowery. ``But in the United States, that is impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in a way, the era of personality has ended. Ten or 15 years
ago, when designers like Donna Karan and Michael Kors were building
their businesses, and Todd Oldham, Marc Jacobs and Mizrahi were
emerging, it was assumed that they would seek the same
tried-and-true laurels. The cover of Vogue. The limousine lines of
store executives and editors stretching outside their shows. The
distinction, so American, of being hailed by their first names.
</P>
<P>
   In ways that fulfill the ideal of the self-made, individualistic
designer, they did aspire to those things. But it is also true that
in the last few years, as these designers have dropped out or taken
their companies public, or merged them into larger companies, the
story has shifted from personality and toward business. It is a
comment, if not on this change then on the way the industry is
responding, that for all the attention being paid to fashion, and
for all the names filling next month's show calendar in New York,
no single new designer has stood out. It isn't even clear that the
brightest star wants to. As Adrover said: ``I don't feel that
connected to the glamour of the fashion world. I hang out with my
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   There used to be cachet attached to young designers _ or poets
or musical artists _ whose work bubbled to the surface through some
underground channel of discontent or outrage. One thinks
immediately of Vivienne Westwood and her punk consort Malcolm
McLaren changing the name of their London shop five times to
reflect each new subtle wave of style. Or of Rudi Gernreich, who
was a rebel in his own way in California in the 1960s. Yet, because
of the speed with which change occurs, the underground doesn't mean
what it once did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder for something to remain underground now because
there's so much more information telling you where the underground
is,'' Julie Gilhart, a vice president of Barneys, said. Like a lot
of store buyers, Gilhart scans indie magazines like Dutch, I.D. and
Purple for the names of new designers. It was in one of those
magazines that she first came across the label United Bamboo, a
sportswear line designed in New York by Miho Aoki and Thuy Pham.
``Their clothes are adorable and very nicely made,'' she said.
``They're serious but also funny in that polished/unpolished way
that you see on girls in Japan.'' Barneys is carrying United Bamboo
for fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a true underground _ and the avant-garde has
never gained much lasting credibility here _ many young designers
who have something inventive to say find themselves struggling in
the margins. Among those who are worth watching are Alice Roi,
whose shapely suits and neck-tie blouses play up some of the
feminine cliches (secretarial glam, librarian frumpiness) that were
first explored by Susan Cianciolo; Sonja Rubin and Kip Chapelle,
who combine strict tailoring with fluid hand-knits that often defy
you to guess how they're made; and Bruce, which is designed by
Daphne Gutierrez and Nicole Noselli, and has consistently been in
the vanguard of a cerebral, slightly helter-skelter femininity.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, when a reporter phoned Noselli to make an
appointment, with the intention of including Bruce in an article
about designers preparing for the collections, her response said a
great deal about how her generation thinks. She said, ``Frankly,
you'd just be in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was endearing. The two Bruce designers were up to their
eyeballs in work, as they recalled last week in their Lower East
Side apartment, which is also their studio, and what, honestly, did
they need a reporter around for? How could they explain themselves,
the day-to-day struggle _ no money, but above all, no time _
without the whole thing sounding like some Andy Hardy tale? It
might be eye-opening _ but who needs it? ``People think that
because we're young designers we'll do anything,'' Noselli said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every day Greg Mills, a former president of Isaac
Mizrahi, who owns a showroom that represents Bruce and a dozen
other lines, including the men's wear label Richard Edwards, gets
calls from young designers looking for help. Lack of capital is
obviously a problem. So is striking a balance between artistic
integrity and commercial viability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just keeps getting harder,'' said Cianciolo, whose fall
production of only 400 pieces neither helps her bottom line nor
reflects her influence.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Mills suggested, the real problem may be an industry
that is increasingly dominated by a few brands. ``I recently got a
call from an owner of a men's store who told me he basically writes
three checks _ one each to LVMH, the Gucci group and Prada,'' Mills
said. ``That's unhealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, none of these designers want to create clothes
that are novel but don't sell. ``I sometimes feel as if I'm in a
race: we've got to win,'' Roi said. Her 15-month-old company, which
is being financed by her mother, produced about 1,200 pieces for
fall, and they are sold at Kirna Zabete and Fred Segal. ``We want
people to wear the clothes, not keep them so underground.''
</P>
<P>
   That is Adrover's aim, too. ``I still scratch through the
garbage, because that's my nature,'' he said. ``But I don't use the
word `avant-garde,' and I don't feel like a downtown designer,
either. It's about showing a different view.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the fashion business _ especially in New York _ is
nothing if not a prolonged search for the obvious. Two designers
who will not be on the runways this fall are Aoki and Pham of
United Bamboo, though not because they are shy or too cool but
rather because, for now, they think it's better to focus on
developing their business. Pham, who several years ago was part of
a maverick but short-lived design company called Bernadette Corp.,
said that after a while ``designers start to find that it's their
business, doing shows.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I would like to consider doing something like APC or
Polo, more of a lifestyle kind of business where the design doesn't
change every season.''
</P>
<P>
   Aoki, who happened to be wearing a red-striped little boy's
shirt from Ralph Lauren with one of her charming wraparound skirts,
looked at Pham doubtfully. ``That might get boring,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pham smiled slightly. ``I don't think so,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
