u s BC-OLY-DRUG-TEST-1STLD-W     08-28 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUG-TEST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL OLYMPIC COMMITTEE ANNOUNCES TEST FOR EPO 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS grafs 9-12 and three grafs at end with details)  
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The International Olympic Committee's
executive board announced Monday that it had approved plans to
carry out tests for the banned synthetic hormone known as EPO at
next month's Summer Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Anita DeFrantz, the board member from the United States, called
the approval ``a significant test.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a reminder to any cowardly athlete who doesn't have
confidence in himself or herself to compete without crutches or
stay home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The synthetic erythropoietin has been the performance-enhancing
drug of choice in cycling and other endurance sports for much of
the past decade, but the extent of the abuse was not clear until a
large cache of EPO was found in an official Tour de France car
driven by a Belgian employee of one of the competing teams in 1998.
After that, efforts accelerated to detect the substance, which was
initially developed to treat kidney transplant patients.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Schamasch, the IOC's medical director, said testing
would begin in Australia on Saturday and continue through the
Sydney Olympics, which begin Sept. 15 and conclude Oct. 1.
Schamasch said that a minimum of 300 random EPO tests would be
administered, but that the IOC hoped to administer at least a
hundred more than that.
</P>
<P>
   The new IOC-approved test requires both a blood sample and a
urine sample. For reasons of hygiene, Schamasch said, the tests
will be administered ``out of competition'' instead of at sports
sites, where conventional urine tests are traditionally
administered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to say which sports we are going to target,
but we will make sure we target the right sports,'' said Dr.
Jacques Rogge, the executive board member from Belgium, who is also
vice president of the IOC's medical commission.
</P>
<P>
   There has never been blood testing or out-of-competition testing
in any form at the Summer Games. The IOC modified the Olympic
charter last year to allow for blood testing, and athletes will
have to sign a form upon arrival in Sydney agreeing to submit to
it. Rogge said that any athlete who refuses, even on religious
grounds, will not be allowed to participate and any athlete who
refuses after competing will be disqualified retroactively.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very fine day for us,'' said Rogge, who indicated
that progress had also been made toward developing a test for human
growth hormone (hGH), an- other banned substance which is believed
to be widely used and remains undetect- able.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has been criticized internally (by Arne Ljunqvistof
Sweden) and exter- nally (by Richard Quick, the U.S. women's
Olympic swim team coach) for failing to direct enough funds into
human growth hormone testing research.
</P>
<P>
   ``With hGH, we are in the same phase as with EPO one month ago;
the problem is with validation,'' said Rogge, who made it clear
that it could take several months more.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as April, IOC officials considered it unlikely an
EPO test would be ready for Sydney, but with an acceler- ated
validation timetable and the com- bined efforts of French
researchers, who developed a urine test, and Australian
researchers, who developed a blood test, the test was approved.
</P>
<P>
   To test positive for EPO, an athlete must test positive in both
the blood and urine samples. The urine test developed by French
researchers, which could not be validated in time for use during
this year's Tour de France, can detect synthetic EPO injected in
the previous three days. The blood test developed by Australians,
which requires 12 milliliters of blood to be removed by syringe
from an athlete's arm, can detect EPO use up to 20 days after the
fact. But unlike the French test, it detects EPO by an indirect
method based on probabilities and young red blood cell
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the blood test's indirect nature, IOC officials were
not confident it alone could withstand legal challenges, but after
the medical commission approved the two-pronged test earlier this
month, the IOC's legal commission approved it on Sunday and
recommended approval to the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course there will still be legal challenges,'' Rogge said.
``But we expect that the scientific validation we have and legal
study we've done will convince every judge of our rights.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In another significant move Monday, the executive board cut the
number of candidate cities for the 2008 Summer Games to five from
10. The survivors are: Beijing; Osaka, Japan; Paris; Toronto; and,
in the least convincing fashion, Istanbul, Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The final vote is scheduled for next July 15, at the IOC meeting
in Moscow, one day before the full membership is scheduled to elect
a successor to the outgoing president, Juan Antonio Samaranch. But
for now and despite the vote-buying scandal involving the Salt Lake
City bid that shook the Olympic movement last year, the 80-year-old
Samaranch remains in charge. Monday's winnowing process was the
first phase of the new selection system that he lobbied belatedly
to put in place in order to reduce the chronic influence-peddling
that plagued the former process.
</P>
<P>
   IOC members who are not part of the small evaluation commission
are no longer permitted to visit bidding cities, and the
assessments of the 10 prospective hosts were made by a working
group on the basis of questionnaires filled out by the applicants
and with the help of outside experts in transport,
telecommunications and financial and legal affairs. In the next
phase, the evaluation commission will visit the five bid cities and
prepare detailed reports to present to the full membership.
</P>
<P>
   These five cities were eliminated from contention for 2008, in
descending order of quality as determined by the working group:
Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia; Seville, Spain; Bangkok, Thailand; Cairo,
Egypt, and Havana. Istanbul also did not meet the minimum
acceptable grade established by the working group, but the
executive board, essentially the board of directors, decided by a
majority vote to allow Istanbul to bid because its candidacy was
considered the strongest of the second tier.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing, Osaka, Paris and Toronto were all approved unanimously
by the board, which declined to establish a pecking order, although
Beijing, which lost by only two votes to Sydney in the bidding for
the 2000 Games, is considered the early favorite. China's human
rights record, considered a factor in Beijing's loss in 1993, is
again expected to be a major campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit that our human rights situation is not perfect, just
like in every country in the world,'' the executive board member He
Zhenliang of China said. ``You cannot say France has no problems.
You cannot say Japan or America have no problems. But what we
should do is let the Olympic Games be a means to help this country
improve its social environment, including human rights, and not use
this as an instrument to go against.''
</P>
<P>
   The human rights prob- lem is a problem that can only be solved
through mutual understand- ing and common efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the executive board has the power to further reduce the
field before next year's final vote, Fran- cois, the IOC's director
general, said that was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The EPO tests will be adminis- tered throughout Australia before
the Games as athletes participate in training camps, and in Sydney
_ primarily in the Olympic Village once the Games begin. A record
total of 3,200 drug tests, including 800 ``out of competition''
urine tests in an at- tempt to detect fast-clearing modern anabolic
steroids, are scheduled to be administered to the approximate- ly
10,400 competing athletes.
</P>
</TEXT>
