<HEADER>
A4706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DRUGS-AD-NYT &LR;      08-28 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP DRUG AD RATES LOW ON ACCURACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ark., Del., La., Mich., Mo., Ohio, Pa., Wash. Wis.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee began showing a new
commercial, ``Priority MD'' in nine states on Monday. Dealing with
prescription drugs, the commercial takes on the issue that has
grabbed center stage in the presidential campaign. The Democratic
National Committee plans to answer it, starting Tuesday, in the
same nine states _ Arkansas, Delaware, Louisiana, Michigan,
Missouri, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Washington and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Cold Harbor Films
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The commercial opens with a shot of prescription
drug bottles. Then Bush speaking in front of an American flag,
meeting with elderly people, shaking hands at an airport rally and
speaking from a podium. Vice President Al Gore is shown, looking
embarrassed, on television. Then, reinforcing the words of the
announcer, graphics declare: ``Interfere with doctors,'' ``The Gore
Prescription Plan: Bureaucrats Decide,'' and ``The Bush Rx Plan:
Seniors Choose.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial closes with a glimpse of Bush, campaigning in
shirt sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: Narrator: Under Clinton-Gore, prescription drug
prices have skyrocketed _ and nothing's been done. George Bush has
a plan: add a prescription drug benefit to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Bush: Every senior will have access to prescription drug
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Announcer: And Al Gore? Gore opposed bipartisan reform. He's
pushing a big-government plan that lets Washington bureaucrats
interfere with what your doctors prescribe. The Gore prescription
plan: bureaucrats decide. The Bush prescription plan: seniors
choose.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: On its central claim, zero. Bush does not have a
prescription drug plan. He has said he likes some elements of plans
proposed in Congress, but has not endorsed any. His running mate,
Dick Cheney, said on Sunday, ``We will shortly have a detailed
proposal to put forth.'' When the commercial accuses Gore of
favoring a plan that would let bureaucrats override doctors'
prescriptions, it is mistaken. The administration proposal would
involve hiring private industry managers, like those who administer
insurance plans today. The managers could establish lists of drugs
allowable under Medicare, but those limits could be overridden by
any doctor whose prescription identified a particular drug as
``medically necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   SCORE CARD: Political advertisements that are flat wrong in
essential elements are rare, and that failing may handicap their
effectiveness. But otherwise it is a classic ``contrast''
commercial that both advocates a policy and attacks the opponent's
approach. Extensive research has found this sort of political
advertisement more effective than either pure attack advertisements
or those that are only self-promotional.
</P>
<P>
   _ ADAM CLYMER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   (Other advertisements for Bush are available from The New York
Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com/politics.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
