<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRUCIAL CONCESSION MADE ON MINIMUM WAGE BILL
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert offered crucial concessions to
Democrats on a plan to raise the federal minimum wage, moving to
end months of stalemate on a popular bill that Republicans feared
could damage them at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate earlier this year approved an increase in
the minimum wage by $1, to $6.15 an hour, with the increase coming
in 50-cent increments during two years in the House version, and in
smaller annual amounts during three years in the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   BIG STOCK GAUGES APPROACH RECORDS
</P>
<P>
   Major stock market gauges crept close to records. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 60.21 points, or 0.5 percent, to 11,252.84.
The gain put the blue-chip index less than 30 points from its April
11 high of 11,287.08. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index also
neared a record, climbing 7.64 points, or 0.5 percent, to 1,514.09.
Its peak of 1,527.46 was set on March 24. The Nasdaq composite
index gained 27.91 points, or 0.7 percent, to 4,070.59.
</P>
<P>
   $4.5 BILLION DEAL FOR APPLIED MICRO
</P>
<P>
   Applied Micro Circuits, a chip maker for networking equipment,
has agreed to acquire MMC Networks, also a chip maker, in a stock
swap valued at about $4.5 billion. The deal is part of Applied
Micro's strategy to broaden its product line. Applied Micro shares
closed at $183.81, down $4.75, in Nasdaq trading, while MMC shares
jumped $31.75, to close at $110.
</P>
<P>
   FEN-PHEN SETTLEMENT IS APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge approved a national settlement that covers tens
of thousands of people who took fen-phen, the diet drug combination
that was sold by American Home Products. The settlement, which
American Home has said would cost up to $3.75 billion, offers
benefits depending on a person's injuries, ranging from refunds for
the cost of the drugs to cash payments of more than $1 million to
those who suffered the most.
</P>
<P>
   RATING ON LOEWS CINEPLEX LOWERED
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to an announcement from Loews Cineplex Entertainment
that it might default on its debt, Standard &AMP; Poor's lowered its
rating of the movie theater company's bonds to B from BB.
</P>
<P>
   SPENDING DOUBLES PACE OF INCOMES
</P>
<P>
   Personal spending rose in July at twice the pace of incomes as
consumers borrowed to make purchases and the savings rate fell to a
record low, government figures showed.
</P>
<P>
   RIVAL ALLIANCES IN E-BOOK SOFTWARE
</P>
<P>
   Stepping up the competition to define a standard format for
electronic publishing, Microsoft and Adobe Systems both announced
rival alliances intended to strengthen their respective positions
in the growing market.
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI SHARES FALL AFTER RAID
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Mitsubishi Motors tumbled, as speculation mounted that
its president would resign after the Tokyo police raided corporate
headquarters. A spokesman for Mitsubishi Motors denied that the
president, Katsuhiko Kawasoe, would resign to take responsibility
for a scandal that erupted last week when the company admitted that
it had covered up customer complaints and auto defects for more
than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   WACHOVIA ELIMINATING 1,800 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia, one of the nation's largest banks, plans to cut about
1,800 jobs _ or about 8 percent of its work force _ as part of a
revamping intended to reduce expenses by $100 million a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
