<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ENVIRONMENTALIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN ENVIRONMENTALIST IS FOUND GUILTY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY, Mexico _ A poor indigenous farmer was found guilty
Monday of drugs and weapons crimes and sentenced to nearly seven
years in prison, closing a case that led to outrage among
environmental groups around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The groups consider the farmer, Rudolfo Montiel Flores, 44, to
be a political prisoner, saying his only crime was to organize
protests against loggers who were cutting forests around his
village north of Acapulco.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, gunmen killed several members of a rural ecological
group led by Montiel. In May 1999, Montiel said that he was
detained and tortured by soldiers who forced him to sign statements
that confessed to marijuana cultivation and possession of illegal
arms.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the Mexican National Human Rights Commission said
that his rights had been violated, and that evidence against him
had been planted.
</P>
<P>
   Montiel was arrested and convicted with a friend, Teodoro
Cabrera Garcia, who was sentenced Monday to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the men pledged to appeal the sentences, issued by a
district judge in the state of Guerrero, and to help organize
protests to reignite interest in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Amnesty International in Mexico City said they would
urge President-elect Vicente Fox Quesada to dismiss the sentences
against the two men after he takes office in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
