<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, AUG. 29 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-SCI-NORTH-POLE-NYT (Moved on Friday, Aug. 18) AND
</P>
<P>
   BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT (Moved on Saturday, Aug 19)
</P>
<P>
   Two New York Times News Service articles sent on Thursday, Aug.
18 and on Saturday, Aug. 19 about the sighting of open water at the
North Pole misstated the normal conditions of the sea ice there. A
clear spot has probably opened at the pole before, scientists say,
because about 10 percent of the Arctic Ocean is clear of ice in a
typical summer.
</P>
<P>
   The reports also referred incompletely to the link between the
open water and global warming. The lack of ice at the pole is not
necessarily related to global warming. New studies of the polar
icepack and its recent changes are reported today in Science Times.
</P>
<P>
   BC-INSIDE-MAGAZINE-MEDIA-NYT (Moved on Sunday, Aug. 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Aug. 27
about Inside: The Business of Entertainment, Media and Technology,
a magazine to be started by Powerful Media and Standard Media
International, misstated the circulation breakdown of The Industry
Standard, whose back-office operations will produce and distribute
the new magazine. About 45 percent of the Industry Standard's
200,000 readers receive the magazine free. Not all of them do.
</P>
</TEXT>
