<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TECH-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLGY NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARDWARE
</P>
<P>
   INTEL RECALLS NEW CHIPS
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp. said Monday that it has recalled its fastest chip _
the 1.13 gigahertz Pentium III _ because the chip could cause
system errors when running certain programs at a particular
temperature and voltage. The problem is with certain circuits of
the chip that have been shown to malfunction in laboratory tests
running either a standard industry test called Sysmark2000 or a
particular Linux compiler, said Michael Sullivan, an Intel
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said it has received no reports from customers, but Dell
Computer and IBM have stopped shipping PCs with the processor.
Sullivan said few of the processors have been shipped to date, and
that a replacement should be ready within two months. He said the
recall would not affect Intel's financial results. Some analysts
agreed, saying the injury would be primarily to Intel's pride,
especially since its archrival, Advanced Micro Devices, began
shipping a 1.1 gigahertz version of its Athlon chip Monday.
</P>
<P>
   TELECOMMUNICATIONS
</P>
<P>
   SBC SELLS LEASE RIGHTS FOR 3,900 TOWERS
</P>
<P>
   SpectraSite Holdings, a company that builds, manages and leases
wireless-communications towers in major cities across the nation,
agreed to acquire the leasing rights for 3,900 towers from SBC
Communications for about $1.3 billion. SpectraSite, which is based
in Cary, N.C., will pay $983 million in cash and $325 million in
stock to manage the towers for 27 years. The company also agreed to
build about 800 new towers for SBC, of San Antonio, Texas, The
transaction indicates how large wireless carriers are seeking to
focus on expanding their customer base instead of managing the
growing number of towers that transmit wireless calls.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET PRICE CUT BY NETPLIANCE
</P>
<P>
   The maker of one of the industry's first Internet appliances _
small computers configured just for using the Web and e-mail _
Netpliance, has reduced the price of its i-opener device by $100,
to $299. The i-opener 2001 Membership Program includes a monitor,
separate keyboard and custom features such as a stock tracking
program and four e-mail accounts. Customers must also pay $21.95
monthly for Internet access through the company, which is based in
Austin, Texas. A few months ago, the company discontinued a $99
introductory price for the i-opener and raised its cost to $399.
Customers who already paid the higher price can get a $100 credit,
the company said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
