A4712 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MOMA-STRIKE-NYT &LR;      08-28 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MOMA-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMA AND UNION FINALLY MEET IN STRIKE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Museum of Modern Art and the union representing
its 250 administrative workers will hold negotiations next week in
what will be the first face-to-face talks between the two sides
since the union went out on strike four months ago, management and
union officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Batterman, the museum's chief negotiator, said in an
interview that he contacted a federal mediator last week to tell
her that the museum thought it was time for her to bring the two
sides together.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, negotiators for the two sides said that the
mediator, Kathleen Murray-Cannon, had repeatedly declined to bring
the two sides together because she did not think such a meeting
would result in meaningful progress.
</P>
<P>
   Maida Rosenstein, president of the union local representing the
strikers, said the museum requested the negotiations because of two
recent union successes in pressuring, even embarrassing, the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the union, Local 2110 of the United Auto Workers,
released a letter signed by 125 prominent artists that criticized
the museum for refusing to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which also asked the public to honor the picket line
in front of the museum, was signed by, among others, Robert
Rauschenberg, Barbara Kruger, Eric Fischl, Sol LeWitt, Steven
Spielberg, Martin Scorsese, Laurie Anderson, David Byrne, Bill T.
Jones and Susan Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   Batterman said: ``Of course the museum was troubled by the fact
that 125 artists signed such a letter. It is unfortunate that they
didn't have all the facts. The letter proceeded from a totally
fallacious assumption, namely that the museum was refusing to
negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   And last week, after intense lobbying by the union, the
Manhattan members of the City Council failed to give the museum
majority backing for the zoning variance it needs for its
renovation and expansion project estimated at more than $600
million.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the whole City Council votes against granting a
zoning variance when a majority of the delegation from the affected
borough fails to recommend such a variance.
</P>
<P>
   Batterman said neither the artists' letter nor the action by the
Manhattan council members caused the museum to ask for the talks.
Rather, he said, the museum asked to resume negotiations because he
thought it was wrong that no talks had been held for such a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosenstein insisted that the museum had repeatedly blocked
any resumption of talks.
</P>
<P>
   On April 28, the union, which represents librarians, assistant
curators, visitor assistants, bookstore workers and others began
its strike. About half of the 250 workers represented by the
bargaining unit have since returned to work.
</P>
<P>
   Since the strike began, workers have often shouted and banged
steel bars in front of the museum. The workers are demanding that
health benefits remain intact without any reductions and that all
newly hired administrative workers be required to join the union or
pay union dues. The union also wants management to agree to rehire
all workers who will be laid off during the renovation project,
which will entail closing large parts of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of labor leaders attending the New York State AFL-CIO
convention in Manhattan joined the strikers Monday afternoon to
picket in front of the museum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
