<SLUG> BC-PARK-THEME-LADN </SLUG>
 
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA FIRM PLANS THEME PARK IN CHINA  &HT;     (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a champagne toast marking the historic
occasion, the Landmark Entertainment Group signed a contract to
design a world-class theme park in China.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Christopher, Landmark's president and chief executive
officer, said Monday that the Yangtze Theme Park on more than 100
acres will be the ``most expensive theme park ever built in
China.''
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   A joint project with the Wuhan Yangtze Entertainment Development
Co. LTD, the entertainment complex will be built in Wuhan, in the
Hubie province of central China. Construction will begin in January
of next year and is scheduled to be completed in May 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very happy to sign this design contract with
Landmark,'' Mao Dong Sheng, chairman of Wuhan Yangtze
Entertainment, said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted the Yangtze Theme Park will set a new standard for
theme parks around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher said it took two years of negotiations to reach this
point. Landmark has also invested an undisclosed amount in the
theme park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think China is an incredible market in terms of future
growth,'' he said. ``We think we can build something that the
Chinese people can be proud of and support.''
</P>
<P>
   Landmark has designed and produced other attractions in China,
as well as in South Korea and the Philippines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Landmark Asia, which is based in Seoul, South Korea, oversees
our projects in Asia,'' Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Goddard, chairman of Landmark, said, ``This is the first
theme park in China that will combine the best of the East and West
to create a very unique attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   He said attractions at Yangtze Theme Park will include a roller
coaster, a high-tech simulator ride and a twin dragon Ferris wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Goddard said half of the park will feature Chinese-theme rides
and attractions, while the other half of the theme park will
feature attractions from the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This theme park will be to China what Disneyland meant to
Southern California when Disneyland opened in 1955,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1980, the company based in North Hollywood, Calif.,
has designed and built entertainment venues around the world,
including Terminator 2/3D for Universal Studios Florida, the
Venetian Hotel in Las Vegas and Star Trek: The Experience for
Paramount Parks.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-00 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
