u a BC-NY-ATTICA-SETTLEMENT-     08-28 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ATTICA-SETTLEMENT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL CHAPTER IN ATTICA UPRISING: SETTLEMENT CAPS LONG LEGAL
BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS for rewriting throughout. Adds optional 2nd take, 600 words) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ Declaring that inmates beaten in the 1971
Attica prison uprising were treated ``like garbage,'' a federal
judge divided up an $8 million settlement on Monday to compensate
more than 500 inmates and relatives for the abuse that the
prisoners suffered.
</P>
<P>
   The allotment of the landmark settlement caps one of the longest
and most ignominious chapters in U.S. criminal justice history,
fleshing out a deal reached in January between New York state and
lawyers representing 1,281 former inmates.
</P>
<P>
   At more than 200 pages, the settlement reads like a harrowing
encyclopedia of personal anecdotes, incorporating months of
testimony from nearly 200 former inmates who stood before U.S.
District Judge Michael Telesca and recounted the uprising and siege
at the prison in western New York that left 43 people dead, 80
wounded and countless more psychologically scarred.
</P>
<P>
   And now, after almost three decades of waiting and legal
maneuvering, the former inmates are scheduled to receive their
shares by October.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Telesca wrote in his decision, most of the awards _ from
$6,500 to $125,000 per former inmate _ were modest sums. Many of
the inmates and their lawyers agreed, adding that no amount of
money could compensate them or resolve an episode that has become a
symbol of prison life and state-sanctioned brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because it is history does not mean it is all in the
past,'' Telesca wrote. ``Indeed, Attica is the ghost that has never
stopped haunting its survivors _ both the inmates and the families
of the deceased guards and prison personnel. But at least the
settlement of this case provides the basis for the former inmates
to close the book on the past and to focus on the future.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the judge devoted the bulk of his decision to
short but powerful summaries of each inmate's experience.
</P>
<P>
   Frank B.B. Smith, for instance, was stripped naked, pelted with
hot and spent shell casings and threatened with castration during
the uprising. He was awarded $125,000, the highest amount.
</P>
<P>
   For George Nieves, Attica was primarily a nightmare of the mind.
Like so many others, he was punched, beaten and forced to crawl in
the mud. But what still unsettles him is the memory of a guard
drawing a giant target-like ``X'' on his back. He received $6,500,
the lowest amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really made me paranoid,'' Nieves said in a telephone
interview from Mount Vernon, N.Y., where he is social worker.
``Attica always continues.''
</P>
<P>
   For Josh Melville, Attica was simply the haunted place where his
father, Samuel, was fatally shot. So he traveled from Florida to
Rochester to introduce a forensic ballistic report and photographs
to bolster his claim that his father was murdered. He was awarded
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   And on it went, story after cathartic story, littered with
``brutal beatings and acts of torture'' and unlimited racial
epithets, Telesca wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Telesca approved 502 claims and divided the awards
into five categories based on the severity of the injuries: $6,500,
$10,000, $31,000 and $125,000 for the inmates, and $25,000 for the
relatives of the inmates who died during the uprising. More than
half fell into the $6,500 category; only 15 qualified for $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was understandable, perhaps, that there was no celebration
after Monday's settlement order. The case was a maddeningly slow
one, outlasting hundreds of inmates who have died since the
uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, in fact, was the only former inmate who attended a news
conference organized by lawyers for several of the former inmates _
and that is because he now works as a paralegal with Elizabeth
Fink, the principal lawyer, on prisoners' rights cases. ``It's not
about the money; money would not compensate if it was $125 million,
Smith said. ``I want everybody to concentrate, everybody, on what
happened at Attica and how we can prevent that.''  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &QL;
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The uprising began on Sept. 9, 1971, when inmates at the Attica
Correctional Facility, about 30 miles east of Buffalo, took several
guards hostage, seized control of parts of the prison and demanded
improvements in prison conditions. When negotiations stalled, Gov.
Nelson A. Rockefeller ordered the retaking of Prison Yard D and
authorized state troopers to storm the prison.
</P>
<P>
   The troopers used helicopters, dropped tear gas and fired
indiscriminately into a crowd of 1,281 prisoners. Then, after
regaining control, prison guards and law enforcement officials
forced inmates to crawl naked over broken glass and denied them
rudimentary medical care.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the five-day siege, 11 guards and 32 prisoners had
died.
</P>
<P>
   For years, though, all efforts to exact an official apology,
much less legal redress, achieved little. The widows of some guards
killed during the melee sued, with varied results. A class-action
suit against the state, filed on behalf of the 1,281 inmates,
languished for 18 years before going to a liability trial, and an
additional 5 to reach the damages phase.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Smith won a $4 million jury verdict in Buffalo, while
David Brosig, another inmate who had been in the D Yard, won
$75,000. But a federal appellate court reversed those verdicts last
year, saying that the trial judge, John T. Elfvin, had mishandled
the case. As a result, the case wound up with Telesca.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a deal materialized: the state agreed to set aside
$12 million, the biggest ever in a prisoners' rights case, with $8
million for the former inmates and $4 million for lawyers' fees. As
is routine in settlements, the defendants admitted neither
wrongdoing nor liability.
</P>
<P>
   To divide up the $8 million, Telesca asked the plaintiffs to
tell their stories in open court. From May to August, almost 200
did, in what turned out to be an emotional and often wrenching
experience, Fink said.
</P>
<P>
   One former inmate, Charles L. Williams, told the judge that the
beatings to his right leg were so severe that his leg had to be
amputated below the knee in 1998. He has suffered from
post-traumatic stress disorder, alcohol abuse and nightmares. He
was eventually awarded $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm leaving Attica here today, Your Honor,'' Hitchens said.
``I don't want to talk about it. I don't want to live it again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next few days, the plaintiffs will receive a letter from
the judge outlining his decision. But those who heard about their
fate on Monday through reporters said that while they were
disappointed, there was very little choice, this late in the
process. Many said that they did not know what they would do with
the money, other than pay some bills and debts.
</P>
<P>
   And while the money, presumably, will eventually be gone, the
memories will not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never going to go away,'' said George Alexander Shorts
Jr., a Brooklyn resident whose toes were broken during the
uprising. He was awarded $31,000. ``I had blocked a lot of things
out, but going before the judge, a lot of this stuff came back, and
a lot of it hurt. Thank God it's over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
