<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HARDAWAY-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDAWAY STILL WAITING FOR MIAMI TO SHOW HIM SOME RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAHAINA, Hawaii _ Tim Hardaway's knees are swollen, ice packs
wrapped around them. A grueling practice for the U.S. Olympic team
is over and the Miami point guard is hurting.
</P>
<P>
   If his body is sore, his ego is throbbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deserve a lot more respect than I'm getting,'' Hardaway
said.
</P>
<P>
   He has watched the Heat overhaul its roster this summer,
swinging deals for Eddie Jones and Anthony Mason from Charlotte and
Brian Grant from Portland.
</P>
<P>
   The trades, expected to be completed this week, will transform
Pat Riley's mechanical and methodical Eastern Conference team into
everybody's finals favorite _ a team capable of trading blows with
whomever emerges from the West.
</P>
<P>
   With three new starters to complement Alonzo Mourning, the Heat
has all the talent and improvisation to finally make sweet music on
the court. There is but one problem: they have no maestro. At least
not one under contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``And without that,'' Mourning said, ``you have a lot of noise
and nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, who turns 34 Friday, is an unrestricted free agent who
has seen almost every other significant player for the Heat be
compensated financially _ everyone except himself. He watched P.J.
Brown sign a $36 million contract and Mourning procure a $100
million deal several years ago. Even his backup, Anthony Carter,
has been re-signed by Miami.
</P>
<P>
   As Jones and Grant prepare to sign contracts in the neighborhood
of $90 million, Hardaway is seriously considering taking his
talents elsewhere to secure the last payday of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dead serious,'' Hardaway said. ``I'll go play for a
contending team like the Pacers. I'll go somewhere where they
appreciate me. Right now, I'm getting no love from the Miami
Heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway is the only player on the Olympic team not under
contract with his team. He is seeking a three-year deal worth about
$10 million a season. While those numbers may seem high for a
player who has physically broken down the last two postseasons, the
Heat's floor leader feels as if the organization owes him for his
loyalty as much as longevity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took less money to stay there,'' he said of the deal he
signed with Riley three years ago. ``He said he'd take care of me,
and it hasn't happened yet. I want to be there, but I've got to
look out for Tim Hardaway and Tim Hardaway's family.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley and Miami General Manager Randy Pfund are expected to fly
to Hawaii this week to meet with Hardaway and watch him scrimmage.
The Olympic team will play exhibition games Thursday against Canada
and Saturday against the U.S. Select Team.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Heat would like to sign Hardaway for one year, the
two sides will most likely arrive at some sort of compromise _
perhaps a two-year deal worth $8 million a season with a third-year
option. But if negotiations don't accelerate, Mourning has promised
to get further involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into this, he should have been signed,'' Mourning said.
``But it's like this: This is a cold, unpredictable business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Timmy's going to be taken care of because there's a
certain level of loyalty with our organization, unlike other
organizations that I won't necessarily name,'' Mourning added,
speaking not so inconspicuously of the Knicks and their dealings
with his friend, Patrick Ewing. ``We take care of our own, and I
know they're going to take care of Tim.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the last time the Heat eliminated the Knicks from the
playoffs, Hardaway had a huge series and became the primary reason
Miami advanced, scoring 38 points in Game 7 of the second-round
series.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are among several teams worried about Miami's
off-season acquisitions. New York is concerned enough that it has
made several overtures to other teams about unloading Ewing in
attempt to get younger and more versatile on the front line.
</P>
<P>
   But the fragile chemistry of incorporating three new starters
into the offense is something that may take a while.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway has already thought about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not on that team, so I'm not going to talk about the moves
they made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat has everything, it seems. Everything but the guy who
made the big shots for the franchise the last few years, the player
who made sure Mourning got the ball and the Heat had a chance at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke after the United States team practiced at the
Lahaina Civic Center, the stout point guard who bobs up and down
the court more than he runs these days could overhear an Olympic
teammate nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take you in Seattle,'' Gary Payton said. ``I'll move to
the two-spot if you want. I'll play shooting guard. I don't care.
To get Tim Hardaway, it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, not smiling, said, ``See, at least someone appreciates
me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
