<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ENJOY SUCCESS AT ROSE BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA has taken great pains, mostly in the weight
room, to shed the image of Gutty Little Bruins. And judging from
the biceps of Kenyon Coleman, Rodney Leisle and a number of other
linemen, it's clear they've succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Bruins shouldn't be so quick to discard the role _
particularly this season.
</P>
<P>
   They open the season Saturday with No.3-ranked Alabama and two
weeks later play No.6-ranked Michigan. Both games are at the Rose
Bowl, a place where the Bruins have played their gutty little
behinds off against some of the nation's best teams.
</P>
<P>
   In the last seven non-conference games at the Rose Bowl against
teams ranked higher, the Bruins are 4-3 but not far from being
undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   The three losses were to No.5 Michigan, 24-23, on a last-second
field goal in 1989; to No.8 and near-national champion Nebraska,
14-13, in 1993, and to No.3 Tennessee, 30-24, in 1997. In the loss
to Tennessee, the Bruins had the ball inside the Tennessee 22-yard
line twice in the final two minutes but couldn't score.
</P>
<P>
   The victories have come over Tennessee, Miami, BYU and Nebraska
_ all teams that have won national championships in the past 16
years.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo has no problem explaining this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're UCLA _ we still should have a pretty good program,'' he
said. ``We're not little sisters of the poor. Obviously, if we beat
Alabama (a 6-point favorite), it would be an upset. But we've got
good players, we've got a pretty good program here, and we should
be playing those kind of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least playing them in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   When UCLA goes on the road, it's another story. Since 1985, the
Bruins have one road victory over a non-conference opponent who was
ranked higher than they were _ the 66-3 rout of Texas three years
ago. They are 1-8 in that span and the scores have been just as
one-sided: an average of 39-17 and only one that's been closer than
two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance travel is the most-cited reason for the road woes.
The Bruins also have played in hostile environments _ Ann Arbor,
Lincoln, Norman, Knoxville, etc. _ and towns where college football
is the center of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, when many powerhouses come to Los Angeles, it's a
different environment for them. Few Alabama players have ever
ventured west of the Mississippi, and the trip here has been used
as a carrot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea how we're going to play, but I think the game
is going to be good for us,'' DuBose said. ``It helped us last year
in recruiting. When you can go into a home and tell a young man you
have the opportunity to go to the West Coast, it helps.''
</P>
<P>
   When Alabama players were dragging during spring or fall
practice, DuBose wasn't shy about getting his players to do a
little California dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA receivers coach Ron Caragher, a backup quarterback for the
Bruins in the late '80s, says he's seen teams with stars in their
eyes rather than X's and O's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football isn't the center of attention like it is a lot of
places, and maybe teams come out here and aren't as focused,''
Caragher said. ``I think the Rose Bowl might have something to do
with it, too. It's a place with a lot of history and a lot of these
schools have never been there before.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA strength and conditioning coach Mike Linn, like Caragher,
was on the sidelines in 1988 when the Bruins scored one of their
biggest victories. After getting pummeled in three previous
meetings against Nebraska, the fifth-ranked Bruins jumped on the
No.2 Cornhuskers, scoring 28 points in the first quarter and
building a 38-7 lead in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It removes the stigma that we couldn't beat Nebraska,'' UCLA
coach Terry Donahue said after the 41-28 victory, which would
catapult the Bruins into the No.1 spot in the nation that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I came to UCLA for _ to be part of games like
that,'' said Linn, a guard at UCLA from 1988 through '92.
``Obviously that was a real good team. We had Troy Aikman and
several other guys who are still playing in the NFL. But that team
believed it could win and really got up for that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our kids are the type who are excited to play the best
in the country, who want to prove that we're just as good as
anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletic director Pete Dalis doesn't think there's anything
special about the Bruins' success at home _ or their failures on
the road _ against the nation's best.
</P>
<P>
   What is important is how the Bruins play.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first year as athletic director in 1983, we were 0-3-1 and
had just lost a close game to (BYU),'' Dalis said. ``But I told
Terry Donahue after that game that `You've got a football team,'
and we ended up going to the Rose Bowl that year. You can tell a
lot by the way a team plays even though you may not win.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a tune Toledo is singing this week, too.
</P>
<P>
   He's called Alabama the best team the Bruins have played since
he came to UCLA in 1994 and that it's important for their
confidence to play well. He even called out to the fans to help
offset the 25,000 Alabama fans who are expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope we have as many people wearing blue as they do
wearing red,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gutty Little Bruins, it appears, are alive and well. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
