<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADDS CAIRO STOP TO TEST WATERS FOR MIDEAST PEACE &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  Editors: additional information in last graph  
 
 
By MICHAEL HEDGES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Ending a whirlwind journey in Africa that
stretched from the Niger Gulf to the Nile, President Clinton
planned a meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Tuesday to
discuss prospects of reviving the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the meeting, scheduled to last two to
four hours, was designed to get a reading from Mubarak about how he
and other Arab leaders feel about the prospects for a new round of
high-level meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The talks will be similar to the summit at Camp David, Md.,
between Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat that collapsed in July.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations broke down over the issues of Jerusalem, which
both sides claim as their capital, and the right of Palestinians to
return to their lands in what is now Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has planned a series of meetings with leaders close to
the Israeli-Palestinian conflict at next month's Millennium Summit
in New York. But Mubarak will be unable to attend.
</P>
<P>
   One U.S. official on the president's Africa trip, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said, ``Quite clearly there will be no
progress without Mubarak's backing, so it is important for the
president to have this meeting, and the timing worked out for
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, said he did
not expect any decisive action from the Mubarak meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hope will be furthered by this is the process by which
we can work with the Egyptians to try to get the parties closer
together,'' he said aboard Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   The Cairo stopover was added at the end of a three-day Africa
trip by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The president began the trip in Nigeria, where he had saluted
that nation's new democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the presidential party flew to Arusha, Tanzania, for peace
negotiations aimed at ending a civil war in the central African
nation of Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential trip continued with the stopover in Cairo,
where the president's plane was refueled. Clinton will make a brief
stop in Colombia Wednesday on his way home.
</P>
<P>
