<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSCH AND ALFONZO LEAD METS INTO 1ST-PLACE TIE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At Turner Field in Atlanta, the Braves were pitching
their No. 1 starter, Greg Maddux, against Cincinnati. At Shea
Stadium here, the Mets turned to their No. 5 entry, Glendon Rusch.
The Mets had a chance to move into a first-place tie with their
National League East rivals, but they would need Rusch to come up
big to get there.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Rusch has said, he has felt like a momentum
stopper. He has not pitched poorly, but he has not been sharp,
either. Monday night, as the Braves fell behind against the
Cincinnati Reds en route to a 6-3 loss, Rusch stayed tough for
seven innings and the Mets went on to beat the Houston Astros, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time since April 5 that the Mets have owned a
share of first place, and they have not been there by themselves
since Aug. 8, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Agbayani, who has been hot, singled off Brian Powell to
lead off the game for the Mets. On a hit-and-run play, Derek Bell,
who has been in a rut for three weeks, followed with a single. That
snapped a 0-for-21 stretch and made general manager Steve Phillips
look prophetic. Before the game, Phillips said Bell's lengthy
slumps did not worry him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the season's pattern holds true,'' Phillips said, ``we're
on the verge of an upswing. We've got him right where we want him
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo has been much more consistent, and he followed
Bell's single with a three-run blast over the fence in left-center
field. It was Alfonzo's 17th homer of the year, and it provided the
Mets with firepower in a game for which Mike Piazza was rested.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to tell in the early innings that Rusch would make
that 3-1 lead stand up and improve to 9-10. Rusch has found himself
in a self-proclaimed ``dead period'' in recent weeks, and his
performance has suffered. But he felt himself improving in his last
two starts, and he got an extra day of rest for this one.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch has run up high pitch counts in recent starts, which is
out of character for a control pitcher who does not walk or strike
out many hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Through four innings Monday night, he had thrown 82 pitches and
allowed three walks. With the Mets' bullpen thin, partly because of
soreness in John Franco's pectoral muscle, that was a bad sign. But
Rusch worked out of trouble at critical moments, before he began
conserving pitches.
</P>
<P>
   With two on and two outs in the second, Rusch walked Roger
Cedeno, who had homered leading off the game in his first
appearance at Shea since being traded last December. The bases were
loaded for Julio Lugo, but Rusch retired him on a fly to center,
using a curveball to do it.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, after another two-out walk to Cedeno, Rusch faced
Lugo with men on first and third. Lugo grounded to second, ending
the inning. At that point, Rusch had allowed a pair of bases-empty
home runs (the other was by Richard Hidalgo), but he had survived
the second and fourth innings, which began with extra-base hits.
</P>
<P>
   He settled in after that. Jeff Bagwell singled to lead off the
fifth, but Mike Bordick ranged well into left field to catch a
pop-up and Rusch got Moises Alou to ground into an inning-ending
double play. In the sixth, after Chris Truby's one-out double,
Rusch struck out Tim Bogar looking and retired pinch-hitter Lance
Berkman on a groundout off a first-pitch curve.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch's efficiency continued into his last inning, the seventh.
After finally retiring Cedeno, on a ground ball, Rusch retired Lugo
and Bagwell on fly balls, using only five pitches between the two
hitters. Rusch threw 117 pitches, 70 for strikes, and allowed two
runs on seven hits and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   While Rusch was not always sharp, Powell missed his spots
continually. Powell, a right-hander who beat the Mets earlier this
month for his first victory in the majors in two years, walked six
in five innings and threw more than half his pitches for balls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
