<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-TAXES-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING HIDDEN IN NEW YORK REPUBLICAN SENATE CANDIDATE'S INCOME TAX
RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After weeks of declining to release his tax returns,
Rep. Rick Lazio tried Monday to end the swirling speculation about
his finances.
</P>
<P>
   His aides provided limited access to 10 years of federal and
state returns, and a review of the long-sought documents found
little, at least at first glance. No arcane tax shelters,
tortuously reasoned exemptions, or offshore bank accounts on the
Isle of Man. No evidence of a scheme to take a high charitable
deduction for donating an old pair of chinos to the Central Islip
Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Lazio and his wife, Patricia, seem to have
relatively ordinary finances. They declared a 1999 adjusted gross
income of $150,400, largely from his congressional salary of
$126,740, with money also from her part-time work as a nurse, and
investments in the stock market and real estate. They gave $2,422
to charity.
</P>
<P>
   While such an income might be the envy of most Americans, it
would place Lazio among the poorest members of the Senate should he
be elected.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides seemed pleased to put the clamor about the tax
returns behind them, but the contents of the documents stirred only
more conjecture: if there's nothing there, why did he wait?
</P>
<P>
   Lazio pledged to release his tax returns soon after entering the
Senate race in May, but had not done so, raising suspicions about
whether he had the kind of financial problems that have tripped up
other politicians in New York in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of his Democratic opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton,
criticized the delay, asking whether he was hiding something. The
state Democratic Party even sent a young campaign worker dressed as
Uncle Sam to Lazio's campaign events to shout at him to disclose
his tax filings.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides said the delay stemmed from their need to review
the returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we would release them by the end of the summer, and we
did,'' said Dan McLagan, a spokesman for the Lazio campaign. ``The
only story here is Clinton's desperation in basing so much of her
campaign in attacking Rick on this issue. It shows the lack of
seriousness on her part, and I think calls her credibility into
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Lazio campaign said it wanted to clear up the
mystery, it did not exactly put the returns on the Internet. On
Monday, reporters _ but not the public _ were allowed to view the
returns at Lazio campaign headquarters near Grand Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters got as much time as they wanted and were permitted to
take notes, but the returns could not leave the room. Asked about
such restrictions, McLagan said other politicians, like Gov. George
Pataki, had used the same system. Many, including President and
Clinton, distribute copies.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign did not provide originals of the returns, and
they did not include the dates they were filed. Aides said Lazio
has always filed on time and had never sought extensions or filed
amended returns. He used an accountant, except in 1990, when it
appears he did his return himself.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's wife has proudly declared that she cleans her own house,
and there was nothing in the returns to disprove that. The Lazios
did not pay any taxes on salaries for household help or day care,
and McLagan said they had never used hired help to care for their
two young daughters. Other politicians in recent years have run
into trouble for not paying taxes on wages to domestic workers.
</P>
<P>
   As had already been apparent from the disclosure forms that he
files with Congress, the returns show that Lazio was smitten with
the stock market in recent years, often engaging in short-term
stock trades, though his lackluster results suggest he might have
been better off putting his money in a mutual fund that tracked the
market.
</P>
<P>
   One of his costliest trades was in the stock of Halliburton, the
oil services company whose chief executive then was Dick Cheney,
now the Republican vice presidential nominee. Lazio lost about
$5,000 trading Halliburton stock in 1998, when the stock was
sagging along with oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   The returns confirm the details provided earlier by the campaign
about one of Lazio's biggest successes in the market, his 1997
windfall from speculating in the stock of Quick &AMP; Reilly, a
brokerage firm. Those investments were the subject of an insider
trading inquiry by the Securities and Exchange Commission that
ended last week with the agency taking no action.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In 1999, the Clintons reported income of $416,039.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazios' adjusted gross income has hovered around $150,000 in
recent years, largely because of his congressional salary. Their
highest-earning year was 1997, when they declared $159,258 in
adjusted gross income.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, before he went to Washington in 1993, Lazio
was a county legislator and a lawyer, and his and his wife's
adjusted gross income was as low as $88,928 in 1992, according to
the returns.
</P>
<P>
   That year, the Lazios gave $1,397 to charity, or 1.6 percent of
their adjusted gross income. On average, Americans donate 2 percent
of their income to charity, and Lazio and his wife in recent years
have usually given between 1 and 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign did not release a list of charities that
received the money. Lazio did not use his state tax return to
contribute to the Breast Cancer Research Fund or three other
charities that are listed.
</P>
<P>
   For a few years in the early 1990s, Lazio owned three investment
properties on Long Island, but he sold two of them, leaving him
with a house on Fire Island that he rents out in the summer and
uses in the spring and fall. According to the returns, the Fire
Island house has often given the Lazios large deductions that have
helped them lower their taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton campaign has seemingly been deprived of an
angle to attack now that the returns have been disclosed, it
continued to try to stoke the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Lazio can't explain why it took three months to release
his taxes,'' said Howard Wolfson, a Clinton campaign spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
