<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA MUNI BONDS A PRICEY INVESTMENT  
 BY KATHLEEN PENDER 
</HEADLINE>
   c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ High-tech workers, parking places and affordable
housing aren't the only scarcities in California.
</P>
<P>
   There has also been an acute shortage of municipal bonds this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with cash from the booming economy, cities, counties and
the state haven't borrowed as much money _ by issuing bonds _ as
they have in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, demand for tax-free munis just keeps growing from
people with old money and new money, especially high-tech
millionaires looking for a safe place to stash some cash.
</P>
<P>
   The result: California muni bonds are trading at higher prices,
and lower yields, than they typically do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a classic supply-demand situation,'' says Kelly Mainelli,
senior fixed-income trader for Montgomery Asset Management.
``California munis are really expensive right now.''
</P>
<P>
   This is good news for people who invested in individual muni
bonds or muni-bond funds earlier this year. But people who buy now
may be paying top dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Year to date, mutual funds that invest exclusively in California
munis have beat all other types of muni-bond funds, and many stock
funds as well.
</P>
<P>
   For example, long-term California muni funds have provided a
total return _ interest payments plus gain in share price _ of 8.8
percent this year, rivaling the 9.3 percent return on technology
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Things could change if the state's municipal bond issuers go on
a borrowing binge.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, California municipal bond issuance is running
about 22 to 24 percent behind last year's pace, according to
various estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The booming economy accounts for only part of the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   Zane Mann of the California Municipal Bond Advisor says
``advance refundings'' have also dried up.
</P>
<P>
   When interest rates fall, municipal-bond issuers often replace
old, higher-rate bonds by issuing new ones at lower rates. It's
just like refinancing a home mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   However, unlike homeowners, cities can't always repay their old
bonds all at once. They have to do so over time. So they use the
proceeds from their new muni bond offering to buy Treasury bonds,
then use the income from their Treasury bonds to gradually repay
the old municipal bonds.
</P>
<P>
   This process, known as ``advance refunding'' inflates the supply
of muni bonds on the market and helps feed Californians' insatiable
appetite for tax-free investing.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, refundings accounted for as much as 50 percent of
new bond offerings in California, Mann says. But when interest
rates were up earlier this year, refundings weren't viable. Mann
estimates that a steep drop in refundings accounts for 75 percent
of this year's overall decline in municipal bond issuance.
</P>
<P>
   Most bond experts expect that supply will begin to grow later
this year.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the state is expected to issue $850 million in
general obligation bonds on Sept. 13, says Bernard Schroer, manager
of the Franklin California Tax-Free Income Fund. That's a bigger
bond issue than normal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the state and/or various counties will probably
issue $500 million in tobacco revenue bonds before year's end,
Schroer says. These bonds will be repaid by money the state
receives from tobacco-suit settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if interest rates continue to fall, refundings could
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Although supply will probably grow modestly this year and early
next, demand will remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   Californians always prefer muni bonds issued in California
because their interest is exempt from state as well as federal
taxes. Income from out-of-state munis is subject to state taxes.
(If investors sell municipal bonds or bond funds, from any state at
a profit, the gain is subject to capital gains tax.)
</P>
<P>
   Because California has so many high-income taxpayers, and state
income taxes are so high _ the top rate is 9.3 percent _ the demand
for municipal bonds is always stronger in California than in most
other states.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, California munis always trade at higher prices _
and lower yields _ than the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the yield on California munis is about 10 basis points
(0.1 percentage point) below the national average. Because of the
unusual supply constraints in California, the difference is now
about 25 basis points (0.25 percentage points) says Mainelli.
</P>
<P>
   As supply grows, that gap should shrink to more normal levels.
Whether that comes about because California yields rise, or
national yields fall, depends in part on interest rates in general.
</P>
<P>
   If interest rates continue to go down, as they have in recent
months, bond prices will rise and yields will fall across the
board. If interest rates turn around and head up, bond prices will
fall and yields will rise.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our outlook for the rest of the year is that the market will
probably be pretty stable,'' says Schroer. ``You will get more
supply, but on the other hand, there's nothing that would force
interest rates to go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainelli is a bit more cautious. ``We've been going up nonstop
for three months,'' he says. ``There might be more room ... but
it's time to take a breather.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at kpender(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
