<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLES SAY THEY NEED INCOME-TAX RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   By ARTHUR M. LOUIS  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; They call it the ``marriage penalty'' _ as if
marriage isn't penalty enough.
</P>
<P>
   It's a quirk in the federal tax schedules that forces many
married couples to pay more income tax than they would owe if they
were living in sin.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage penalty _ which has become an important
presidential campaign issue this year _ can cost a well-paid couple
more than $1,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be enough to keep people from getting married, but
some couples have acknowledged postponing their nuptials until Jan.
1 to avoid the marriage penalty for another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ought to just repeal it,'' says Larry Rabun, senior
partner and national director of estate, gift and trust services
with Deloitte &AMP; Touche in Washington, D.C. ``It's a dumb provision
and doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The marriage penalty has been around for decades.
</P>
<P>
   It became a campaign issue this year because the federal
government _ inundated with tax revenues from the booming economy _
anticipates trillions of dollars in budget surpluses during the
years just ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans in Congress, steeped in family values and also
mindful that the marriage penalty applies most harshly to
upper-income families _ the GOP's natural constituency _ passed a
bill last month that would have virtually eliminated it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill _ which would have increased the standard deduction for
all married couples and lowered the tax brackets for many _ would
have cut federal revenues by an estimated $292 billion over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, no great friend of the well-to-do _ Hollywood
campaign contributors excepted _ vetoed the measure, saying it
would cause too great a drain on the Treasury and benefit people
who didn't really need it.
</P>
<P>
   What Clinton did was either statesmanlike or fundamentally
misguided, depending on which political wing you occupy.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Aaron of the Brookings Institution, a liberal think tank
in Washington, says ``cutting taxes by a large amount now'' would
be a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Better to wait until the expected surpluses actually
materialize, he reasons. Otherwise, ``we could be putting
government back into the deficit situation we spent two decades
clawing our way out of.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Slivinski, a fiscal policy analyst with the libertarian
Cato Institute, also in Washington, counters that the government
should simply spend less.
</P>
<P>
   ``To ask whether the government can afford tax cuts
automatically assumes it's the government's money to begin with,''
Slivinski observes. ``The only reason they might not be able to
afford it is if they commit to spending more money than they
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore _ who is, of course,
blissfully married _ has proposed a modest marriage-penalty reform
of his own. True to Democratic tradition, it stresses benefits for
less-affluent taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   He favors raising the standard deduction for married couples _
which would mainly help people who don't own houses. Mortgage
interest payments usually are large enough to cause taxpayers to
itemize deductions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also wants to make more lower-income married couples
eligible for the earned-income credit.
</P>
<P>
   His Republican opponent, George W. Bush, has proposed a
substitute GOP plan in the wake of Clinton's veto. True to
Republican tradition, it would be most helpful to taxpayers with
above-average incomes.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan would restore a tax rule that was in effect during
part of the Reagan administration. It would give each married
couple an extra tax deduction equal to 10 percent of the salary of
the spouse who earns the least.
</P>
<P>
   The deduction would be capped at $3,000, which means that its
fullest benefits would be enjoyed by households in which each
spouse earns at least $30,000 _ that is, households with incomes of
$60,000 and higher.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Feenberg, a research associate with the National Bureau
of Economic Research in Cambridge, Mass., says the marriage penalty
developed because of a fundamental change in the tax tables during
the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Congress made the tables more favorable to single individuals,
who had complained that, by and large, the old tables forced them
to pay more than married couples with comparable incomes.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; More Working Women
</P>
<P>
   The new tables shifted the balance too far, but this wasn't
generally recognized as a problem until well into the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the marriage penalty has little or no impact on
households in which the spouses file joint returns and have widely
different incomes. In fact, they pay less than they would if they
were single.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1970s, it was rare for husband and wife to earn
nearly the same amount of money, and many wives earned nothing at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it has become common for spouses to earn roughly the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Under the present setup, if a couple earn a total of $100,000
this year, they won't get hit by the marriage penalty if one of the
spouses earns more than $77,000. At that point, the current
tax-rate schedules reach equilibrium for married and single people.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if each spouse earns $50,000, the marriage
penalty _ assuming the couple are childless and claim the $7,350
standard deduction _ would amount to $1,530.50.
</P>
<P>
   Filing jointly as a married couple, they would pay a tax of
$18,673.50. If they were single, they each would pay a tax of
$8,571.50, for a total of just $17,143.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; A Closer Look
</P>
<P>
   A glance at the tax schedules shows how such quirks arise.
</P>
<P>
   A married couple filing a joint return for 2000 will have to pay
a tax of 15 percent on the first $43,850 of taxable income. Above
that, they enter the 28 percent bracket.
</P>
<P>
   If the tax schedule for a single individual were perfectly
aligned with the schedule for a married couple, then the single
individual would cross into the 28 percent bracket when taxable
income exceeded $21,925, or half of $43,850.
</P>
<P>
   But, in fact, single people don't reach the 28 percent bracket
until their incomes exceed $26,250.
</P>
<P>
   Single people also get a break on the standard deduction. The
standard deduction for a married couple is $7,350, while for a
single person it is $4,400 _ substantially more than half the
married couple's deduction. Feenberg says it is impossible to
devise a rate schedule that would tax married couples and single
people equally, that would ensure that any two married couples with
the same income would pay the same tax, and that would be
progressive _ imposing higher percentage rates on people with
higher incomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All seem like very reasonable principles to uphold,'' Feenberg
observes, ``but no tax system can obey all three. You have to
violate one or more.''
</P>
<P>
   So the balance of favoritism can be expected to swing forever
between the married and unmarried, the rich and not-so-rich,
households with two wage earners and households with trophy spouses
_ depending on how many votes each group commands, how loudly they
voice their views and how the party in power feels about them.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Holding Pattern
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect changes in the marriage penalty soon, Rabun warns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of anything passing between now and the election
are probably slim and none,'' he says. And after the election,
``the lame-duck Congress is unlikely to pass any major legislation
that won't get vetoed.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens next year will hinge on the makeup of Congress and
which party occupies the White House.
</P>
<P>
   If the same party controls both houses and the presidency, there
probably will be some sort of marriage-penalty reform. If the
leadership is split, then the stalemate seems likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Arthur M. Louis at alouis(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
