<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 APPLE NAMES EMPLOYEE IN TRADE-SECRETS LAWSUIT  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Apple Computer has apparently fingered one of
its own as the source of several recent leaks about products it
hadn't announced.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued yesterday, the company said it had added
the name of Juan Gutierrez, ``an individual employed by Apple,'' to
a previously filed lawsuit alleging unauthorized disclosure of
trade secrets.
</P>
<P>
   In the original complaint, filed Aug. 1 in Superior Court in
Santa Clara County, the Cupertino, Calif., computer-maker had
charged up to 25 ``John Does'' with posting pictures on the Web of
a new dual-processor Mac model and a new mouse before Apple
unveiled the products on July 19.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, Apple said it had identified Gutierrez through
subpoenas issued as a result of its suit. On Aug. 3, Santa Clara
County Superior Court Judge Gregory Ward signed an order allowing
Apple to subpoena records from Yahoo relating to an individual
known online as ``worker bee.'' The pictures in question were
posted on a site maintained by a user of that name in Yahoo's
GeoCities Web community.
</P>
<P>
   Apple spokeswoman Lynn Fox declined to say what job Gutierrez
had held at Apple. Asked if he was still employed by the company,
she laughed and said, ``No comment.'' Gutierrez did not reply to a
voice-mail message left for him at Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said Apple would continue to seek the identities of ``Does 2
through 25.'' In its statement, the company said, ``The protection
of Apple trade secrets is incredibly important to our success. We
intend to vigorously pursue legal actions that ensure the
confidentiality of our intellectual property is not compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
