<SLUG> BC-MEDIAVISION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CEO PLEADS GUILTY IN TECH FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID LAZARUS  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In one of the largest securities fraud cases in
Silicon Valley history, the former chief executive of a Fremont,
Calif., technology company has pleaded guilty to bilking investors
out of millions of dollars, the U.S. attorney's office said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Jain of Berkeley, Calif., admits that he and other
executives at Media Vision Technology defrauded investors by
creating bogus inventory and hiding millions of dollars in product
returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was certainly one of the dirtiest cases I was ever
involved in,'' said Steve Sidener, a San Francisco lawyer who had
sued Media Vision for more than $30 million on behalf of investors.
``I'm just shocked that it's taken this long to get to this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Jain had been indicted by a federal grand jury in September 1998
on charges of wire, mail and bank fraud, as well as giving false
statements to stock-market regulators. He pleaded guilty to only
two counts of wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Media Vision, a maker of multimedia products, went belly up in
1994 after allegedly falsifying records to inflate its financial
performance. Charges are still pending against the company's former
chief financial officer, Steven Allan.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty plea comes after a setback last week for the U.S.
attorney's office, which has pledged to crack down on white-collar
crime in the tech industry. On Friday, a federal appeals court
tossed out the convictions of two former executives at California
Micro Devices, the office's first major securities fraud case in
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Media Vision case, first brought to light by The Chronicle,
illustrates the darker side of Silicon Valley, where cases of fraud
and stock manipulation largely have been overlooked by the media
and law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Media Vision case sends a terrific message that the
Department of Justice is going to get tougher on these types of
cases,'' said Joe Cotchett, a Burlingame lawyer specializing in
securities-related litigation.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said Media Vision represents only the tip of the
stock-fraud iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely clear to me that stock fraud and manipulation
has not slowed down,'' Cotchett said. ``Over the past few years,
we've seen a dramatic increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Jain will cooperate with the government in its case against
Allan, said Deborah Husnik, a spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Jain could not be reached for comment. But his Sacramento
lawyer, Richard Pachter, said Jain finally decided it was time to
get on with his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Jain has accepted responsibility for his part in what went
on,'' he said. ``He wants to put this behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jain faces a maximum sentence of 10 years in prison, a $500,000
fine and compensating victims of the fraud. Sentencing is scheduled
for Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. attorney's office, Media Vision's senior
executives, after discovering an approximately $6 million shortfall
in 1993 sales, attempted to pressure the firm's business partners
to claim they held millions of dollars in nonexistent inventory.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, a company in India falsely claimed to have purchased $6
million worth of Media Vision's goods, and the sale was
subsequently entered into Media Vision's books.
</P>
<P>
   Jain also admitted that he had provided deliberately inaccurate
information to investors when he and Allan discussed Media Vision's
1993 financial results in a conference call with stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office said the pair had reported revenue of
$241 million and profit of $20 million, even though they knew the
bogus sale accounted for about a third of Media Vision's purported
income.
</P>
<P>
   They also allegedly hid about $10 million in returned products.
</P>
<P>
   Media Vision's stock was trading at $42.50 at the time the
contrived results were reported on Feb. 17, 1994. A month later,
the company said it would report a loss for the first quarter,
causing the firm's stock to plunge to $11.
</P>
<P>
   By May 17, 1994, Media Vision's share price was down to $2.75
after the company revealed that it actually lost almost $100
million in 1993. Bankruptcy followed not long after.
</P>
<P>
   Jain's plea agreement, supplied by his lawyer, suggests that he
sees Allan as the prime mover behind Media Vision's financial
deceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allan informed me that it was essential that we find someone
to confirm the nonexistent inventory to the auditors, and Allan
would reverse the entries in a few weeks,'' Jain told the U.S.
attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Allan nor his lawyer could be reached for comment.
Allan's trial is scheduled to open on Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Three former Media Vision employees already have pleaded guilty
to charges related to the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Former company controller Robert Williams pleaded guilty to one
count of providing false information to the FBI, while former Chief
Operating Officer Russell Faust and former sales director Michael
Humphress pleaded guilty to federal mail fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   The sentencing of the three has been postponed until the cases
against Jain and Allan are resolved. A related investigation by the
Securities and Exchange Commission is also on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that it was not just Steve Allan,'' said
Sidener, the lawyer who had sued Media Vision on behalf of
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see this as the result of one man's conduct,'' he
said. ``It was a group collaboration.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
