<SLUG> BC-PUC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC BELL'S BUSY SIGNAL ADS INTRUSIVE, PUC GROUP SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD WALLACK  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ No one likes to hear the brash, buzzing sound of
a busy signal, unless the alternative is something worse: an ad.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the consumer watchdog arm of the California Public
Utilities Commission filed a formal protest against Pacific Bell
for forcing customers to listen to a recorded sales pitch whenever
the person they are calling is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   For ``only 95 cents,'' the announcement says, Pacific Bell will
automatically keep redialing the number for the next half hour
until a connection is made.
</P>
<P>
   In the complaint, the Office of Ratepayer Advocates accuses Pac
Bell of intruding on customers' privacy, violating its pledge to
avoid telemarketing to customers with unlisted phone numbers and
increasing the price of the service by 20 cents without permission.
</P>
<P>
   The ORA complaint also asks the state PUC to order Pac Bell to
immediately halt the ads, roll back the price to 75 cents, give
refunds to customers who paid more than that and make
``restitution'' to customers with unlisted phone numbers who were
forced to listen to the announcements.
</P>
<P>
   Some customers have also complained about the ads, which started
in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was outraged,'' said Joe Stevens, a San Francisco Web
developer. ``I pay for this line and I get phone spam?''
</P>
<P>
   But Pac Bell spokesman John Britton said the complaints are
unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   First, Britton said, the message shouldn't be confused with an
unsolicited sales call. ``You only hear (the message) if you make a
phone call and the line is busy,'' Britton said. ``If you don't
like it, you just hang up.''
</P>
<P>
   Britton also said the message is actually helpful for many
customers who weren't aware of the feature. And several phone
companies in other states use similar announcements to tout the
service, Britton said.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Pac Bell said it jumped through all the regulatory
hurdles before raising its price in July. Pacific Bell filed a
notice with the PUC on May 3, indicating it planned to raise the
price for three services, including repeat dialing, three-way
calling and star-69 (which calls back the number of the last
incoming call), to 95 cents. Pac Bell said it actually has
permission to raise the price to $1.42.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, no one protested the plans, so the PUC signed off
on it as it normally does with noncontroversial changes. (The ORA
belatedly protested last week.)
</P>
<P>
   Britton also said Pac Bell warned customers about the recorded
message in an insert in customers' phone bills in April, though ORA
gripes that the notice didn't say the price was being increased and
omitted other details.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the complaints demonstrate that some customers are
particularly sensitive to being forced to listen to anything
resembling an ad when making a call.
</P>
<P>
   As The Chronicle reported in May, several AT&AMP;T customers were
annoyed after the long-distance giant forced them to listen to ads
touting sweepstakes and other promotions before connecting their
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, the Pac Bell customer, said he initially complained
about the recorded messages to Pac Bell, who told him they were
actually ``service availability announcements'' _ not ads. Stevens
called it ``semantic bull_.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
