<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE GROWS ON CORZINE TO RELEASE TAX RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton may have succeeded in
pressuring Rep. Rick Lazio to disclose his tax returns, but the
episode could prove embarrassing to her fellow Democrat running for
the Senate: Jon Corzine of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, Corzine was the only Senate candidate on either
side of the Hudson who had yet to release his tax returns, and his
Republican opponent, Rep. Robert Franks, quickly seized the
opportunity created by Lazio's reversal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton has been an outspoken advocate for full financial
disclosure, and hopefully she will be able to convince her
Democratic colleague, Jon Corzine, to follow her lead,'' Franks
said in a statement Monday afternoon. ``So far, no one in this
state has had much luck in getting Mr. Corzine to tell us where his
money comes from.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has released abbreviated abstracts of his earnings and
taxes paid in three recent years. But he has refused to release his
returns, saying that doing so would violate a confidentiality
agreement he signed with Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., the investment bank
he headed until his retirement last year. But Corzine is coming
under increasing pressure from both the local and national news
media to relent. And in a July poll by the Gannett New Jersey
Newspaper Group, 72 percent of respondents said Senate candidates
should disclose the sources of their income, and 64 percent said
Senate candidates should release their tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a choice here,'' Franks' campaign manager, Charlie
Smith, said of Corzine. ``He can either run for the United States
Senate and try to earn the trust of the voters, or he can remain a
businessman and continue to have secret business dealings. He's
chosen to run for the U.S. Senate. There's an obligation to be
forthcoming with the residents he hopes to represent. You can't
have it both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's spokesman, Tom Shea, said the candidate intended to
place his assets in a blind trust if he was elected, rather than
violate the confidentiality agreement, which Corzine considers a
binding contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's released everything he can, and everything that's
required of him by the Senate Ethics Committee,'' Shea said. ``But
he's kept his word on that contract, and he'll keep his word to the
voters of New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks, who remains less known and is looking for publicity, has
invoked Clinton's name often recently, but not in such a positive
light. In July, he sent out fund-raising appeals saying Clinton was
one of the liberals ``New Jersey can't afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Her spokesman, Howard Wolfson, dismissed Franks' appeal as a
campaign stunt. ``Where was Bob Franks when Rick Lazio was delaying
releasing his tax returns for three months?'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
