<HEADER>
A4877 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     08-28 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS NEED TO MAP A COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Five months into the franchise's worst season
in more than a decade, Texas Rangers' management remains strangely
uncertain about what direction it will take in reconstructing the
ballclub this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Three words for you, Doug Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   Win or else.
</P>
<P>
   Leave that other trash reeking in the cow pasture, where it
belongs.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries we understand. Mistakes in judgment we may forgive, for
a while. But indecision on philosophy at this stage of the game
won't be tolerated, not here and, it's my guess, not in Tom Hicks'
office either.
</P>
<P>
   Not for long anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the philosophy of the team and what's the goal of our
organization?'' manager Johnny Oates asked before Monday night's
series opener against the Cleveland Indians at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The scary part is that with just 32 games to go in this
miserable dead-end season, only the second half of his question was
actually rhetorical. The goal, Oates said, is still to win the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The map on how they'll get there, however, is suddenly very
muddled. Will Melvin continue to stick with the youth plan he
implemented last winter, or will he spend heavily on the free-agent
market to plug the obvious holes?
</P>
<P>
   Or both?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get through September before we make that
decision,'' Melvin said. ``I thought we did our major
reconstruction last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody keeps wanting us to be where the White Sox and the
A's are, but they're two years ahead of us with younger players. We
go three months and already people are losing patience.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a fairly accurate assessment and one Melvin should keep
in mind. This is not a patient town when it comes to bad baseball,
especially from a team that won three division titles in four years
but faded with barely a whimper in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   No, we're not very tolerant of night after night of shoddy
defense, poor starting pitching, an underachieving bullpen and a
lineup of banjo hitters.
</P>
<P>
   We're spoiled. So sue us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem in baseball is that people overreact all the
time,'' Melvin said. ``A week ago Doug Davis was going to be our
left-handed reliever. Two starts later he's set in our rotation.
Brian Sikorski pitches a good game and he's one of our starters
next year. He comes back with a bad game and he's out of the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things change from week to week, from one start to another.
That's why I'd like to continue our evaluations through the end of
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a reasonable request, but these aren't reasonable
times. Personally, I don't need another 30 days to figure out what
this team needs, and for the first time in memory, the list of
necessities doesn't have starting pitching at the top.
</P>
<P>
   So in the interest of saving time and for a mere 50 cents
investment, here's what you should do, Doug:
</P>
<P>
   Add a ``monster'' bat to the lineup, preferably an outfielder
who won't mind DH-ing most of the time. Suggestions: Juan Gonzalez,
Manny Ramirez, Ellis Burks. They can all be free agents at the end
of the year. Sign one. Heck, sign two if you can. It's only money.
</P>
<P>
   Find a second baseman who can play defense and run, someone who
can turn a double play once in a while and has a little range. If
we've learned anything this season, it's that you can't get by with
utility infielders playing full time.
</P>
<P>
   Sign or trade for a stop-gap third baseman _ preferably one with
some power _
</P>
<P>
   while Mike Lamb goes back to Triple A and learns two things: How
to make accurate throws to first and how to drive in an occasional
run. It wouldn't hurt if he hit the ball out of the park once in a
while, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sign or trade for a closer. If it's definitely not going to be
John Wetteland, how about auditioning one of the younger guys in
September? What have you got to lose?
</P>
<P>
   ]Finally, sign one veteran starting pitcher. After missing on
Mark Clark and Darren Oliver, you're due to hit on one of those
reclamation projects you love so much.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, unless major changes are made defensively, you're not
going to be able to lure any big-name free-agent pitchers to
Arlington. Who would want to pitch in a hitter's park in front of
the gloves that are out there now?
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a legitimate chance to play with the Yankees, the
Clevelands, the Seattles of the world, we need some more work,''
Oates understated. ``Can we be competitive with minor changes?
Yeah. We can have a decent ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we have a ballclub like the one we had last year? That's
going to take awhile. You're not going to do it over the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad news, guys. A winter may be all you have. Guaranteed
contracts are nice because they provide some financial security.
But as Oates himself has often pointed out, they don't guarantee
him a seat in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with trying to be the next White Sox, or A's, is
that there's no guarantee that the Rangers' young players will be
as good as theirs. Do the Rangers have another Paul Konerko?
Magglio Ordonez? Carlos Lee? Mike Sirotka? Ben Grieve? Miguel
Tejada? Eric Chavez? Tim Hudson?
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that Ricky Ledee, Gabe Kapler and Mike Lamb can be
productive players with a good surrounding cast,'' Melvin said.
``Once we felt the injuries weren't going to allow us to contend,
we tried to strip it to a point where we could at least build from
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But are those players good enough to build with or around?
</P>
<P>
   Kapler has made progress but there's still reason to wonder if
he'll develop into the 35-homer, 100-RBI center fielder the Rangers
hope he will be.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb has almost as many errors (26) as he does RBI (39). Ledee
is still an enigma and it's difficult to predict what Ruben Mateo
can produce next season, even if he can stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need some growth from the people that we have,'' Oates
said. ``Right now, we're asking a lot. We're asking some of our
younger guys to carry a load.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the young guys ``are'' a load.
</P>
<P>
   We know where the Rangers have been. We know where they are now
and why.
</P>
<P>
   The crazy thing is that with only a month left in the season,
they still don't seem to know what to do about it. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
