<SLUG> BC-NJ-TROOPERS-CASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE GRANTS DELAY ON NEW EVIDENCE IN NEW JERSEY TROOPER TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Prosecutors investigating the 1998 police
shooting at the center of New Jersey's racial profiling scandal
were granted two more months by a judge on Monday to examine new
eyewitness testimony and determine how it may alter their case.
</P>
<P>
   The state troopers involved in the shooting, James Kenna and
John Hogan, are awaiting trial on attempted murder charges for
firing 11 shots at a van during a traffic stop on the New Jersey
Turnpike in April 1998 and wounding two black men and one Hispanic
man, all unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   The case was thrown into turmoil this month when two new
eyewitnesses came forward and gave statements that reportedly
corroborated some elements of the troopers' version of the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers have argued that the troopers fired in
self-defense, and they filed motions asking that the charges be
dropped. A hearing on the new evidence had been scheduled for
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A special deputy attorney general, James J. Gerrow, asked
Superior Court Judge Andrew J. Smithson on Monday for two more
months to respond to the defense's motion to dismiss, saying that
the new evidence had forced prosecutors to reconsider their
approach to the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more time to continue our investigation and also to
really evaluate what our response is going to be,'' Gerrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Smithson granted a delay until Oct. 26, and is expected to
decide whether to dismiss the charges at a hearing scheduled for
Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Gerrow has refused to discuss what the evidence is or how it may
affect the case against the two troopers.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting sparked a political uproar from civil rights
activists, who had complained for years that troopers were singling
out black and Hispanic drivers for traffic stops. After an
investigation by the New Jersey Attorney General's Office and the
federal Justice Department, the state signed a consent decree in
which it agreed to stop the practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
