r s BC-BKN-RIDER-LADN     08-28 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RIDER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HOPE GETTING RIDER IS RIGHT MOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO _ Only Isaiah Rider knows what secrets of life are
stored in Aruba, St. Thomas, Antigua and Trinidad. Only he knows
what, if anything, a brief banishment from the NBA, and a long
vacation in the tropics, taught Rider about himself.
</P>
<P>
   Only Rider knows for sure whether the months of reflection will
help him end a seven-year string of late arrivals, occasional
arrests and repeated suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday afternoon, as Rider accepted his fourth new lease on
NBA life, he said all the right things, made all the reassuring
vows and sounded genuinely grateful to be a Los Angeles Laker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know all the chips are against me,'' Rider said at an
afternoon news conference, ``but I just want to come in and play
hard. And it will be easy to get in and fit in really comfortably
with the players that we have here. So my main thing is just
bettering myself. And I prayed and wished for a lot of things, and
my dreams came true ultimately.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the 29-year-old Rider, equally talented and
troubled, found his market value diminished and found a willing
employer in the Lakers, who obtained him for a low-risk, one-year
contract for $736,000.
</P>
<P>
   After being waived by the Atlanta Hawks in mid-March, after
prior blowouts with Portland and Minnesota, Rider knows this could
be his last chance to save what remains of a promising career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows the situation, so it's up to me to respond and
to come out, not really on top, but just come out as a good person
and end my career with credibility, on a positive note,'' Rider
said.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted his troubles have all been of his own making but
said that during his extended offseason, ``I think I've matured.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Rider nor general manager Mitch Kupchak addressed
Rider's run-ins with the law _ including an arrest for marijuana
possession _ or his penchant for verbally assaulting fans. But both
seemed certain Rider could solve his vexing habit of tardy
arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   And Kupchak said Rider, unlike one-time Laker Dennis Rodman,
would be held to the same rules as everyone else but said there are
no if-then scenarios that would prompt Rider's early termination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone's aware of what's at stake,'' Kupchak said,
``and to sit down and talk about cutting somebody if they're late
once or twice, that doesn't have to be discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the Lakers know what they'll get on the court:
a tough, athletic swingman capable of scoring 20 points when needed
and who, at his best, ranks among the top 15 shooting guards in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Rider can easily make up the 16 points per game they'll lose
once Glen Rice departs, and he's younger and more dynamic. Unlike
Rice, Rider can create his own shot and get to the hoop with
regularity, and for his career is a 36 percent 3-point shooter.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of that matters if he's suspended, pouting or
perpetually late, which is why even the Lakers admit this is a
risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's not a risky move,'' Rider said. ``Obviously, to the
public it will be. ... But everyone has their opinions, and I have
my beliefs and I have my strengths. And my head is on straight, so
therefore, I don't think it's a risky move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy, I'm confident and I'm not reluctant to be in
this situation. I really look forward to it. It's a lot of pressure
on me, but I look forward to that pressure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
