<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GET DOWN TO BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A sense of urgency returned to UCLA practice
Monday as preparations began for Saturday's season opener against
No. 3 Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   It beat a sense of helplessness, the feeling that a number of
Bruins, those caught in the handicapped parking scandal,
experienced at the start of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no distractions this year,'' said linebacker Ryan
Nece, one of the 11 Bruins who were suspended for at least two
games last season. ``We can really concentrate on football.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very frustrating to come to practice, work hard and
then I had to be in the stands. It's something I'll never forget
and something I never want to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo said he already senses better chemistry
this season, something that was largely impacted by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some seniors who had some problems and they had a hard
time leading the football team and then we had some underclassmen
who didn't want to follow them,'' Toledo said. ``That's behind us
now.''
</P>
<P>
   A sign that the Bruins have moved on came over the weekend when
the team voted guard Oscar Cabrera, one of the placard possessors,
a game captain for the Alabama game along with defensive end Kenyon
Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKS LIKE A MILON: The Bruins won't see a more dynamic player
this season than Bama flanker Freddie Milons. The 5-foot-7,
191-pound junior will return punts and kickoffs and might also line
up at running back, quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   He set a school record with 65 receptions last year, and he was
the MVP of the SEC championship game, in which he scored on a
spectacular 77-yard run against Florida.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA will try to punt the ball away from him and kick the ball
out of the end zone, but ``we can't do much about him offensively
except tackle him when he gets the ball,'' Toledo said. ``They're
going to get him the football. He's going to make some plays. We've
just got to find him and tackle him.''
</P>
<P>
   CRIMSON TIDE OR RED WAVE: At least 20,000 Alabama fans are
expected for the game, which could draw close to 80,000. Alabama's
ticket allotment of 15,000 is long gone
</P>
<P>
   WAR BABIES: Alabama's last trip to Pasadena was in 1946 when it
beat USC in the Rose Bowl to cap a 10-0 season. It was the last
time a non-Pac 10 or Big Ten team has played in the Rose Bowl game.
Two members of that team, Harry Gilmer and Vaughn Mancha, will
accompany the Crimson Tide on their flight here Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
