<SLUG> BC-US-OPEN-STATUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATUE FOR ARTHUR ASHE CREATES CONFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the nude 14-foot bronze statue in front of the
Arthur Ashe Commemorative Garden was unveiled Monday night, some in
the crowd were confused over its meaning, while others remarked of
its power.
</P>
<P>
   The imposing figure, sculptured by Eric Fischl, was designed to
commemorate Arthur Ashe's legacy but not his likeness; this was the
root of the confusion. It is a rough statue of a man serving,
holding the grip of only a tennis racket, the end torn off to
depict a baton to be passed from generation to generation. The
stocky, intentionally out of proportion statue, which also depicted
genitals in an abstract form, emerged from a base in a way intended
to portray growth.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Levering, the president of the U.S. Tennis Association,
prefaced the unveiling by saying that this statue, like Ashe, was
provocative as well as elegant. She said, ``It is meant to
represent all people from all races and backgrounds, Arthur's full
range of impact.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, some spectators at the unveiling were shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is disappointing to see,'' said Bee Atwell, 56, from
Brooklyn. ``There's not even a tennis racket in his hand. It's not
very relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Emily Moore, the executive director of the Alliance Junior
Tennis League in Roosevelt, N.Y., kept interrupting the ceremony by
yelling out that the statue should be clothed or carrying books or
children. ``Kids will see that, and what will they think?'' Moore
said. ``Arthur Ashe stood for more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati Moves On, Calmly
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Capriati tried to serve Monday as the wind whipped
around the darkened Louis Armstrong Stadium during the drizzly
first day at the U.S. Open. Planes roared, thunder boomed and the
public address system crackled like gunfire, its startling blasts
causing a delay minutes before the rain began pouring down.
</P>
<P>
   But the 24-year-old Capriati was calm, easing jitters about
playing the first match on the first day, and held a 6-4, 1-0 lead
over Emmanuelle Gagliardi.
</P>
<P>
   Play resumed after about 90 minutes, and Capriati took little
time to dispatch the 82nd-ranked Gagliardi, 6-4, 6-0. Afterward,
the 15th-seeded Capriati was all sunny smiles and waves to the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel totally different coming into this,'' she said. ``I
have no issues I want to discuss or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati's self-aware smiles were a contrast to the tears that
marked her final appearance at last year's Open. After falling to
Monica Seles, 6-4, 6-3, in the fourth round, a composed Capriati
recited a statement discussing her personal problems as a
teen-ager. But she crumbled under questioning and left the room in
tears.
</P>
<P>
   This year things are different. Seeded for the first time since
1993, and more confident, Capriati said she likes the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've established my presence for good, you know, hopefully,''
she said. ``I like it better like this.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sophia Hollander
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
