<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS VICTORY RAISES QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine being told a week ago that USC's star quarterback would
throw for less than 100 yards, the go-to receiver would catch two
passes and the offense would score one touchdown against Penn
State.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-point margin of victory? Sounds about right, except
conventional wisdom would have said the Nittany Lions were the
winning team.
</P>
<P>
   That's how utterly strange USC's season-opening victory over
Penn State turned out to be. The Trojans were sloppy offensively,
not to mention predictable, but they also registered the most
impressive victory of the Paul Hackett era.
</P>
<P>
   Players are already talking about winning the national
championship, which sounds downright wacky. But so does destroying
Penn State without a top-flight offensive performance.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, this is no vintage Penn State team, but USC still
manhandled a respectable group. The way the Trojans did it,
however, makes it extremely difficult to predict what it means for
the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew last year, or hopefully realized, that the
season-opening 55-point drubbing of Hawaii was no barometer of the
Trojans' talent or success.
</P>
<P>
   But this is different. Penn State can't be that bad, can they?
</P>
<P>
   No matter, some things were easy to spot Sunday as major signs
of improvement. The running game is vastly different, as is
Hackett's dedication to run the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan McCullough gained 128 yards in 29 carries, but more
importantly, Hackett was determined to keep taking time off the
clock by running.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, Sultan got the tough, hard yards,'' Hackett said.
``We couldn't do that last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A would be last season's Notre Dame game. USC blew a
21-point halftime lead, and afterward, there were complaints within
the program that the Trojans passed too much in the second half and
allowed the Irish back in the game. No such problem this year.
</P>
<P>
   The unity that was so apparent during training camp at UC Irvine
also showed at Giants Stadium. With a 23-3 lead, USC didn't lose
focus in the locker room, as the Trojans did twice last season
while blowing 21-point leads to Notre Dame and Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we came in the locker rooms thinking we had won
those games,'' defensive tackle Ennis Davis said. ``So this year,
we came in and kept it calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Added linebacker Zeke Moreno: ``There was no talking. We decided
not to talk, just do what you have to do. It was pretty quiet in
here.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to work, because the Trojans never came close to
squandering the lead.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if anyone was the most valuable player of the game,
it might have been wide receiver Marcell Allmond. In the second
half, he recovered McCullough's fumble inside the USC 25-yard line.
Later, he recovered Mike MacGillivray's blocked punt in the end
zone, preventing Penn State from getting an early touchdown that
might have completely changed the game's momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, those type of plays seemed to go against USC in the
clutch.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens when Palmer gets his rhythm back, and Kelly gets
the touches he deserves? How far can the Trojans go, with their
experienced defense expected to be tough against any opponent?
</P>
<P>
   We won't really know until the Colorado game Sept. 9. USC will
be favored in that contest, but how the Trojans bounce back from a
victory that rejuvenated the program will tell a lot about this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we haven't answered all the questions that people
have, but we made a statement that we're here to play,'' offensive
lineman Faaesea Mailo said.
</P>
<P>
   What's really scary is that the passing game might never be
worse this season. Then again, will the special teams and defense
score touchdowns in many more games?
</P>
<P>
   If a game can raise as many questions as answers, the Kickoff
Classic did it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
